<SLUG> BC---COMPUTERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PC EXPO SHOWCASES WEARABLE HARDWARE  &HT;     BY CAROLYN SAID
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
New York _ The blue suits, the white shirts, the red ties _ they're
history.
<P>
   The new de rigueur uniform, according to IBM Corp., is a
wearable computer.
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue, generally not known for setting fashion trends,
attracted a stream of PC Expo showgoers to a corner of its huge
booth, where it showed a prototype of a wearable PC.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, IBM miniaturized one of its ThinkPad notebook
computers to the size of a VHS cassette so it would fit in a pocket
(a large one) or fanny pack. Instead of a keyboard, it came with a
curved mouse that nestled in the user's hand (there's also the
option of voice control); and instead of a screen, there was a
headset that floated a minidisplay in front of the user's eyes. An
earpiece provided sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the future,'' said Peter del Rio, one of the visitors
to the booth. Del Rio, who had skated over to the Javits Convention
Center from his Chelsea office, said he would like to equip
salespeople for his customized clothing company with wearable PCs.
The company, ic3D, will open a store in Times Square next year and
counters in Bloomingdale's this fall. ``It's the cyborg look; we'd
like our salespeople to be modeling the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, del Rio faulted IBM's prototype for being cumbersome.
``I'd like to design something cooler,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has been testing the waters with corporate clients for the
system, which would be for mobile workers who need to keep their
hands free _ customs agents, ship inspectors, telephone line repair
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could even retrofit a Web cam into a hard hat so they
could capture video of a problem area,'' said George Tatomyr, an
executive with IBM's Wearable Solutions division. He added that
with wireless connectivity, someone wearing the system could access
a database to help in troubleshooting problems up an 80-foot pole
or down a manhole.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial versions should be available early next year from IBM
partner Xybernaut, according to Tatomyr, priced from $4,000 to
$7,000. He said a consumer version is likely to be a couple of
years away.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is showing the system in a TV commercial that depicts a man
in a Venice, Italy, plaza surrounded by pigeons that think he's
talking to them instead of his wearable PC.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies at PC Expo had looked deep into the future and
saw _ a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   HeyAnita, from a Los Angeles company of the same name, is a
``voice portal'' _ the same designation as recent media darling
TellMe. Consumers call its toll-free number and can orally request
information such as stock quotes, weather, traffic, news and
horoscopes. It will launch nationwide in September. Versions for
Korea, Japan and China are also coming this year. The consumer
version will be partially supported by ads; overseas it will also
be subsidized by phone companies that hope customers will run up
their cell-phone bills calling it. The company hopes to license
HeyAnita to Internet sites like Yahoo and Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like radio on command,'' said Victor Sim, co-founder and
chief strategy officer of the company. The five founders named it
after a waitress in their favorite Los Angeles diner; she has since
moved on to seek fame in Hollywood and doesn't yet know that she's
soon to be renowned on the phone, Sim said.
</P>
<P>
   Another telephone solution is ShopTalk. As the name promises,
it's like an uber-800 number for shopping. More than 50 companies
like Jiffy Lube, Pizza Hut and Crate &AMP; Barrel offer their wares
through the service, which gives them a chance to make special
offers to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Why, when so much of the high-tech industry is focused on making
whiz-bang gadgetry, are companies betting on a century-old
technology?
</P>
<P>
   Simple, said Sim. ``Worldwide, PC penetration is only 10
percent. We want to go after the other 90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
