<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTWIRE--TICKETS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTUP WANTS TO TAKE ON PRICELINE.COM  &HT;     BY CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco startup code-named Purple Demon has
been quietly gearing up to challenge Priceline.com in the business
of selling off the airline seats that go unfilled every day.
<P>
   With six major airlines as founding investors, Purple Demon
plans to launch in the fall as Hotwire. The company has $75 million
in investments, with minority stakes held by American Airlines,
United Airlines, Continental Airlines, US Airways, Northwest
Airlines and America West.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Priceline.com fell $3.38 to $36.81 Thursday. Despite
the drop, a Priceline.com spokesman insisted that the planned
company is not a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a competitor to Priceline's name-your-price
model,'' said Priceline spokesman Brian Ek. ``This will have zero
effect on our business.'' Priceline.com's expectation of achieving
profitability by 2001 will not be affected, Ek said.
</P>
<P>
   With both services, the buyer agrees to buy tickets at a certain
price, with no choice regarding airline or route.
</P>
<P>
   But there are differences between the two companies' systems:
Customers of Priceline.com decide how much they are willing to pay,
then wait an hour to find out whether any of the site's airlines
will sell a seat at that price. Hotwire plans to provide a
predetermined discount price for the chosen day and destination.
</P>
<P>
   Hotwire's idea eliminates one problem that has kept some buyers
away from Priceline.com: With Hotwire, buyers don't agree to accept
the flight until they view the price and route; Priceline.com
customers must agree in advance to buy whatever the service comes
up with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the Purple Demon project will be similar to
Priceline with less restrictions,'' said Aram Fuchs, chief
executive of Fertilemind.com, a group of New York City Internet
analysts. ``That doesn't seem to be an idea to base an entire
business on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Priceline can simply adjust. If they do that, the Purple Demon
wouldn't be so demonic,'' Fuchs added.
</P>
<P>
   However, having six large airlines as founding partners could
give Hotwire an edge in obtaining more and better seats to sell,
Fuchs said. Priceline also has investments from airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Orbitz, another company with airline investments that plans to
sell tickets online, is being investigated by the Justice
Department for possibly being anticompetitive, even though the site
hasn't launched. But Hotwire chief executive Karl Peterson said
although the airlines' combined investment is significant, he's
confident that his venture does not undermine competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike other industry consortiums, there is no governance from
our airline supplier partners. We are independently managed,''
Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hotwire's majority investor is Texas Pacific Group, a private
investment company with which Peterson was formerly a partner.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
