<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS JUMP BACK INTO FIRST PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ These are the facts and go figure: The Mariners won
again Thursday afternoon, using a combination of pitching and
power, defense and execution.
</P>
<P>
   They beat Anaheim, 7-2, at Safeco Field, taking their eighth
consecutive series, a franchise first.
</P>
<P>
   They jumped back into first place in the AL West, improving to
45-31, the second-best record in the American League, third-best in
the majors behind the White Sox and Braves. In contrast,
Cincinnati, home of the dearly departed but not sorely missed, is
37-40.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners begin a seven-game road trip in Texas Friday night
after breezing through an 8-2 homestand, running their Safeco
record to 28-12, best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this ballpark,'' Mariners manager Lou Piniella said.
``It's really made a big difference in our pitching. Our young
pitching has really developed here.''
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud stroked two home runs while starter Gil Meche and
three relievers stifled the Angels in front of 44,387 fans. Stan
Javier and new catcher Robert Machado also homered for the
Mariners, adding insurance blows in the seventh and eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   If it all sounds straightforward, that's because it is _ the
Mariners are business-like in their approach, ruthlessly and
methodically mowing down their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Piniella prefers to proceed with caution, the bandwagon
is picking up the pace and now includes the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're solid,'' said Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn. ``They
have a chance to be one of the best teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Darin Erstad added:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no holes, none, zero. They're going to have their
hands in it (the pennant race). There's no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a player who is batting .373 after banging out three
singles, nonetheless recognizing a potential powerhouse. They used
to mock the M's and now they marvel instead.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the developments Thursday, however infrequent in
the past, have turned routine. The foundation is fundamental
baseball, always stressed but rarely seen in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team won't get beat making mistakes,'' said Stan Javier,
a utility man who lit up the Angels with a home run in the seventh
inning. ``We have very smart players. Doing little things ... it's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   A lack of defense could have led to a different outcome. But the
Mariners have an abundance.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the tone, Mike Cameron raced in to catch a short fly
ball to right-center. Erstad tagged up at third and tried to score.
Cameron gathered himself and threw a strike to Machado, who tagged
the sliding Erstad, resulting in a double play to end the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud cleanly fielded three basic grounders before making the
play of the game, snagging a one-hop bolt off Vaughn's bat. The
first baseman turned it into a double play that ended the seventh,
avoiding the unpleasant alternative: extra bases for Vaughn and a
serious rally by the Angels, who trailed 4-2 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gold down there,'' Vaughn said. ``He saves a lot of
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Olerud: ``I didn't have time to try to get it on a big hop.
That's a reaction play. Mo's a dangerous hitter. To get out of an
inning like that ...''
</P>
<P>
   Was huge, just like Olerud's performance. The 31-year-old is an
appropriate example of what the Mariners are all about these days:
understated elegance. His swing is Fred Couples smooth, and
Thursday he generated the same kind of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can juice the ball when he has to,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Olerud deposited Kent Bottenfield's waist-high
fastball into the right-field seats for a 2-1 lead. In the sixth,
he ripped a two-run shot off Mark Petkovsek, sending another
fastball over the Mariners' logo in right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some pitches to hit and hit 'em well,'' said Olerud, who
had a .316 batting average and nine RBIs during the homestand. ``I
want to keep that going.''
</P>
<P>
   The other elements of the victory also were predictable:
Supposedly slumping Edgar Martinez delivered a run-scoring single
in the first inning, and Jose Mesa continued his revival from
barely breathing to suddenly flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   The same reliever who gave up nine runs in one inning a month
ago in Tampa Bay struck out three Angels. One was the baffled
Bengie Molina, who fanned on a pitch that hit the dirt 2 feet in
front of home plate. Another was Erstad, flailing at the last pitch
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've ever seen him throw the baseball,''
Erstad said. ``It was pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   As are the M's, now hoping for the same kind of results on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
