A9060 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ENERGY--RATES-SFCHRON     06-30 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY--RATES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER-GRID OPERATOR CUTS ELECTRICITY PRICE CAP  &HT;     BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a move to lower wholesale prices for electricity, the California
Independent System Operator said Thursday that it has slashed the
maximum price it will pay for power to $500 per megawatt hour from
$750.
<P>
   The Independent System Operator _ made up of utility officials,
power generators, and commercial and industrial power users _
operates much of the state's electricity grid. Its decision to cut
the wholesale cap comes two weeks after a heat wave caused
blackouts and pushed wholesale prices for electricity up to the
limit in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Most residential consumers in the Bay Area will see no immediate
difference in their monthly electricity bill as a result of
yesterday's decision. However, the lower maximum bid price could
mean lower bills in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for electricity consumers in most of California were
frozen to artificially high rates as part of a deal for
deregulation in order to allow utility companies to pay off debts.
Now, a potentially smaller portion of a consumer's utility bill
will go toward paying actual electricity costs. That leaves a
larger portion to go toward paying the debt. The debt was scheduled
to be repaid by 2002, but with a lower price cap it may be paid off
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent System Operator acknowledged that the price cap
may make it difficult for the state to get all the power it needs
the next time electricity demand is extremely high. That's because
the low price cap may discourage companies from building new power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The new price cap, which was passed 16 to 4 with four
abstentions and will be effective July 1 through October 15, is a
compromise. Many consumers and businesses wanted a cap of $250 per
megawatt to keep prices low. An earlier motion to cut the cap to
$250 was proposed by Southern California Edison, an investor-owned
utility, and failed after a 12-to-12 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Some electricity generators, however, wanted all caps lifted,
arguing higher profits will be an incentive to build more
generating plants.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine Corp., a San Jose constructor of power plants, said the
decision won't affect its plans to provide power sources in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our backyard and we're going to keep building
plants,'' said Calpine Chairman Pete Cartwright. ``But it's no way
to encourage people to come in and build power plants in
California, and what we need is more power plants _ very, very
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent System Operator board member Barbara Barkovich said
the board made the decision in spite of some pressing concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the votes show that there are real concerns about all
these issues,'' said Barkovich, who is also an energy analyst.
``It's a judgment call for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the price cap for electricity in the
state has been argued over and adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, prices for electricity soared as high as
$9,999 per megawatt hour. That translates into $9.99 per kilowatt
hour, compared with a more typical price of 3 to 5 cents. There
were not enough generators to produce electricity in the state, and
the lack of competition opened the door to price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   A price cap in a competitive market is generally seen as a
temporary means of addressing market design flaws or other
problems. During the summer of 1998, the Independent System
Operator imposed a cap of $250 per megawatt hour, which it later
lifted to $750.
</P>
<P>
   During the week of June 12, the cost for electricity for all
users in California was more than $850 million &LR;   &LR; _ three times the
most expensive week for electricity last year _ a red light went up
again. Utility officials and consumer groups said the astronomical
prices signal that the market is not functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at yamanouchi(at)sfgat.com
</P>
