r f BC-COSTUME--PARK-SFCHRON     06-30 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTUME--PARK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING IN A COSTUME ISN'T ALL YABBA-DABBA-DOO  &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
I gazed into the mirror and a 7-foot-tall Yogi Bear stared back.
<P>
   ``Ready?'' asked Rod Edora, who runs the costume department at
Paramount's Great America theme park in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering that costumed characters must never, ever speak, I
awkwardly nodded Yogi's huge, heavy head, which was clamped firmly
to my own and fixed in place via a strap around my chest.
</P>
<P>
   I struggled to see out of the small holes hidden in Yogi's nose
and mouth. My breathing sounded like I was in a deep-sea diving
rig. Sweat was already cascading down my face.
</P>
<P>
   Cautiously, I shuffled in my furry Yogi boots toward the door,
dipping to get through doorways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you go outside,'' Edora said, ``you are onstage. You have
to stay in character, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded once more, bent to get through the doorway and stepped
into the sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   From this point on, I would be Yogi Bear.
</P>
<P>
   The performers inside the costumes are the unsung heroes of the
theme-park world. Wandering the grounds in oven-hot outfits
weighing as much as 30 pounds, they fill in the gaps between
scream-inducing attractions and often create the most memorable
experiences for younger visitors.
</P>
<P>
   What most people probably don't &LR;   &LR; know, though, is that almost
all the costumes at Great America are inhabited by kids themselves,
usually 16- or 17-year-olds enjoying what is arguably one of the
niftier summer jobs in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like one of the funnest jobs you can ever have,'' said
Monique Rutherford, 17, a student at the School of the Arts in San
Francisco who frequently appears as Cindy Bear, Yogi's girlfriend
in Jellystone Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring your own personality to it,'' she said. ``Normally,
I'm, like, quiet. But when I'm Cindy, I'm like the bomb. You like
walk and shake your little Cindy butt.''
</P>
<P>
   This level of, like, commitment is shared by most other young
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Bedrock Bonding
</P>
<P>
   Greg Larsen, a 16-year-old student at James Logan High School in
Union City, adopted a serious expression as he inspected the
costume for Fred Flintstone's pal Barney Rubble in the backstage
wardrobe room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I connect with Barney,'' he said. ``You try and be the
costume. I'm no longer Greg. I'm Barney Rubble from the town of
Bedrock. I have a wife named Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   And Justin Chapman, 19, who has just finished a drama program at
Delta College in Stockton, sees his role as Scooby-Doo in one of
Great America's stage shows as a steppingstone toward a career as
an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make your actions so much bigger to get across to
the audience,'' he said. ``I think a lot more now about what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   To underline this point, Chapman talked about how he prepared
for his part as an 8-foot-tall crime-fighting dog. He said he did
considerable research on the Internet, as well as pore over
background briefings from the character's creator, animation
heavyweight Hanna-Barbera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet you didn't know that Shaggy's real name is Nashville
Rogers,'' Chapman said of Scooby's human sidekick. ``That's not in
the cartoon. That's just something Hanna-Barbera made up for the
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen chimed in that his own research revealed that Fred
Flintstone's ``Yabba-dabba-doo'' yell actually was inspired by an
ad for Brylcreem hair lotion (``A little dab'll do ya'').
</P>
<P>
   Great America officials say such extracurricular study is
encouraged among performers. It complements the training _ basic
movements, do's and don'ts _ provided by park staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know about your character, the better you're
going to do,'' said Edora, the costume manager. ``We like to see a
lot of job-related research.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, he admitted, ``job-related research'' means
sitting around watching lots of cartoons _ something all the young
performers agreed was a pretty cool way to spend one's summer
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed that, at a starting salary of $6.50 an hour,
this isn't a job you do for the money. ``We could get paid less and
we'd still do it,'' said Christina Gaines, 15, who often appears as
Boo-Boo, Yogi Bear's partner in pic-a-nic basket theft.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; First Rule _ Be Animated
</P>
<P>
   Keith Clausen, Great America's entertainment operations manager,
said the park holds auditions for performers each fall. Usually, he
said, about 500 people will try out for just 35 or so openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tight,'' Clausen said. ``It's very competitive. What
we want is that spontaneity, an ability to take risks, to take
command. We want an ability to be with a guest and make them feel
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clausen should know. In a former job at Universal Studios in Los
Angeles, he played the Mummy and the Wolfman, among other
characters, and has even been known to don the Scooby-Doo costume
in a pinch _ making him, at 50, probably the oldest person ever to
appear as a Great America character.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no words to describe the really cool feeling you
get,'' Clausen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cool wasn't how I felt as I made my way toward the park's
KidZville area, trailing my ``escort,'' Kaleena Zanders, 18, who
would serve as my eyes and ears when interacting with crowds. (All
characters are accompanied by an escort. It's too easy to become
disoriented otherwise.)
</P>
<P>
   Beneath my costume I wore a T-shirt, shorts, socks and a
headband, and still I was broiling before I stepped through the
gate and into KidZville. Outside, the temperature was in the
mid-80s. Inside my outfit, it must have been near 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Yogi!'' I heard a kid shout from somewhere, and Zanders
steered me in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't remember how Yogi Bear was supposed to walk. The
brief orientation I'd been given hadn't covered this point.
</P>
<P>
   Improvising, I quickly came up with a who's-the-man sort of
strut _ as if Yogi had starred in ``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   A Fleeting Embrace
</P>
<P>
   Through my tiny view holes I made out a pair of small girls
coming at me like little missiles. ``Yogi!'' one cried, slamming
into my padded belly. I bent down as best as my costume allowed and
gave her a loose hug.
</P>
<P>
   The other girl followed suit, and again I hugged back.
</P>
<P>
   This was a strange experience. Reconstructed by years of
political correctness, I had grown accustomed to a few simple
rules, one of which being that you don't ever touch children you
don't know, let alone give them a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here I was exhibiting behavior that, under virtually any
other circumstance, would have landed me in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hug is OK,'' Edora had told me earlier. ``But you want to
keep it simple. You don't want to move up and down the back of the
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcompensating, I kept my hugs relatively brief, favoring
instead a friendly pat on the back or a ruffling of hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yogi, over here!''
</P>
<P>
   A parent wanted me to pose with her kids. I waved and
instinctively smiled, forgetting, as I would again and again, that
my face was hidden beneath a big grinning bear mask.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Liberation, Feet First
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's something immensely liberating about being in
costume. I'm not the sort of person, for example, who dances about
in public.
</P>
<P>
   But with the park's loudspeakers playing an endless stream of
light, chirpy tunes, I soon found myself filling the brief moments
between encounters with little impromptu jigs and shuffles _ a Yogi
Bear who was either profoundly happy or heavily medicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Yogi!''
</P>
<P>
   I waved in the approximate direction of the voice. I couldn't
see a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Zanders confined my walkabout to KidZville. This was undoubtedly
deliberate. I'd been warned by other performers that things can get
a little hairy in other parts of the 100-acre park, particularly
when rowdy teens decide to have a little fun with Scooby or Yogi.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be around teenagers a lot,'' said Larsen,
who connected so intensely with Barney Rubble. ``They're the ones
who cause trouble. You get hit a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Being bopped on the head is most common, with the blow
resonating through your vertebrae. Occasionally a kid might try and
pull your head off, which is why most costumes include chest
straps.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the more intangible hazards. The performers spend
a great deal of time perfecting their characters. They agonize if
the illusion is broken.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Carson, a student at Stagg High School in Stockton,
takes enormous pride in her depiction of Fred Flintstone. When
teens try and mess with her _ not knowing that inside the burly
caveman costume is a 16-year-old girl _ she has learned to defuse
the situation with some hip-hop pantomime intended to put Fred on
the same wavelength as his antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   Illusions Shattered
</P>
<P>
   But Carson still hasn't figured out how to deal with parents who
refuse to join in the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once had a little girl play with me,'' she recalled, ``and
she said to her mom, `Is he real?' And she said, `No, it's just
someone in a costume.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carson's expression turned somber. ``That really hurt,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Strutting and dancing and waving and smiling (mask or no mask),
I faced no such dilemmas in the half-hour I made my rounds _ the
usual time that a performer remains in costume before returning
backstage for a break.
</P>
<P>
   But as Zanders led me back to the gate, I could feel my energy
and enthusiasm rapidly waning. It's hard work being Yogi Bear. I
couldn't imagine doing it five or six times a day like the pros.
</P>
<P>
   It was with more than a little relief when I finally hauled
myself into the wardrobe room and peeled myself out of the furry
outfit, which, like most other Great America costumes, would head
off for a daily cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Clausen, the entertainment manager, knew exactly what kind of
shape I'd be in. He handed me a towel and a bottle of water. I
chugged it down in a single gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Then I hung out with the other performers, swapping war stories.
I'd paid my dues.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(at)sfgate.com
</P>
