<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE M'S HORSES, NO WISHES NECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A closed-door meeting with all sorts of Mariner
front-office people after Thursday's 7-2 win over the Angels made
Lou Piniella late for the postgame buffet.
</P>
<P>
   These are busy times in Marinerville. The team is rolling,
having reeled off an 8-2 homestand with dizzying pitching and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, before the team headed off to Texas, Pat Gillick, Lee
Pelekoudas and Roger Jongewaard piled into Piniella's office to
talk some things over, calling in pitching coach Bryan Price for a
few words, too.
</P>
<P>
   Could a trade be on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   As if the poker-faced Gillick is going to give anything away.
</P>
<P>
   While no word of a deal came down, Piniella was at least direct
about the catbird seat in which the Mariners sit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are so flush with pitching that one can almost
imagine the jealousy and covetousness in places like Cleveland, New
York and Boston, where they are dying for live arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what. We're one of the few teams that you can
say that about right now,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with Freddy Garcia needing at least one more minor
league rehab start and Brett Tomko still on a seesaw as to where he
fits into the rotation, the Mariners will have some adjustments to
make soon in their well-stocked pen.
</P>
<P>
   Now that starters Gil Meche, Paul Abbott, Jamie Moyer, Aaron
Sele and John Halama are going six or more innings, the strain on
middle relievers has diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Rodriguez, Tomko and Robert Ramsay are finding it hard
to get work with Jose Paniagua, Arthur Rhodes, Jose Mesa and
Kazuhiro Sakaski locked in. The late innings have been clockwork,
not fireworks as in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Rhodes extended his shutout streak to 13 innings.
Paniagua got the win, knocking his June ERA down to .074.
</P>
<P>
   And, Mesa _ who fans and talk show hosts said might as well be
cut after that nightmarish loss to Tampa Bay _ was again
overwhelming in relief, striking out three of the five batters he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa has benefited from four days of intense instruction from
Price, who moved Mesa to the right side of the rubber, making the
ball harder for the batters to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Price has encouraged Mesa to use the four-pitch arsenal he
developed as a starter. He is mixing speeds and angles.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who watched Angels batters fooled by some big
breaking curveballs during the final two games of the homestand, it
is hard to imagine the new Mesa is the same pitcher that had some
people thinking it would be better for the Mariners to eat his $3
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the Mariners' catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a bullpen like this since Cincinnati,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit like this at the end of '95, but I haven't
had this many options since Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting over a pile of spaghetti laced with some shrimp and a
thin little strip steak, Piniella wasn't going to get on the plane
hungry. Nor was the skipper shy about putting the Mariners' most
pressing needs on the table.
</P>
<P>
   If the team is stocked with arms, it is missing a key ingredient
for countering pitching moves by opponents and helping run
production, Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost a left-handed bat in our catcher with (Tommy)
Lampkin out (for the season with ligament damage to his elbow.) If
we can add one, we're going to try and do it,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Accentuating the mood for player movement was the news that the
Yankees traded outfielder Ricky Ledee to Cleveland for David
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, we have been told, have been working the phones
the last few weeks, looking for infield help and left-handed bats.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, it seems as if it's going to be the Mariners
getting the calls, not making them.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the envious position of inviting suitors to make
them an offer _ a rare thing considering this was a team that once
sent away Jason Varitek and Derek Lowe in one foolish deal, just
because no one worked hard enough to stockpile the kind of goods
other teams would come crying for.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the turn of events in Marinerville:
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hart (Cleveland general manager) called here and said
they knew we were interested in a left-handed bat but they said
they were pretty far down the road with one team already,'' said
Jongwaard, vice president of baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they were all the way down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, while the Mariners may not have had a lot of time
to ponder this deal, they are being offered good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   They are the ones who are in a position to barter from strength,
not weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the paucity of left-handed bats in the Mariner line-up
was hard to distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   That's because John Olerud and Stan Javier both rapped homers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Olerud had two. Raul Ibanez stroked a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``See what left-handed hitting does?'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   If the skipper gets his wish, we might see what more left-handed
hitting does, if the M's get the right call.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
