<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     06-30 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCATHING REPORT OF AMAZON IS A MUST-READ FOR STOCK OWNERS 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's blistering report on Amazon.com by Lehman Bros.
convertible bond analyst Ravi Suria is a must-read for anyone
owning stock or bonds in any dot-com company.
</P>
<P>
   But unless you're a Lehman client or a reporter, it's not easy
to get your hands on the full report, which is even more damning
than snippets you might have read.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site  &LR; www.multexinvestor.com  &LR; will begin selling it
Monday for at least $75. But it probably won't be offered on
 &LR; www.amazon.com &LR; . So it's worth quoting from at some length here.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-page missive is unlike anything you'll see from a stock
analyst. That's because research is becoming a key sales tool for
Wall Street investment banks, and most firms are squeamish about
publishing anything that might jeopardize a stock-underwriting deal
from an existing or potential client.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Lehman Bros. also underwrites bonds, and why Suria was
allowed to take Amazon apart limb by limb is a mystery. Suria says
he's stopped talking to the press ``for political reasons.''
(Lehman's equity analyst has a buy rating on Amazon stock and is
none too happy about her colleague's June 22 report on its bonds.)
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's stock fell from $46.06 the day before the report was
released to $33.88 the day after. It has since rebounded to $37.13,
thanks to a herd of Wall Street bulls who rushed to Amazon's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what's in the report had previously been reported in
bits and pieces. What makes it powerful is the way Suria builds his
case, using numbers, charts and caustic wording.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the company will run out of cash within the
next four quarters, unless it manages to pull another financing
rabbit out of its rather magical hat,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The report is nominally about Amazon's two huge convertible bond
issues. Convertibles are bonds that can be swapped for stock at a
presetrate. But it's really a critique on Amazon's fundamental
business plan.
</P>
<P>
   While stock analysts generally focus on the income statement,
Suria concentrates on cash flow, a complicated analysis that most
investors ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the fourth quarter of last year, Amazon evolved from a
virtual business to a real-world retailer,'' he writes. ``While the
operational characteristics of Amazon are not that different from
an online retailer, they are a lot more distressed than even
mediocre real-world retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``fundamental problem,'' he continues, ``lies in the fact
that Amazon does not generate positive net cash flow per unit of
product it sells.''
</P>
<P>
   He lays part of the blame on Amazon's poor inventory management.
Amazon's inventory turnover _ how many times a firm's inventory is
sold and replaced during a period _ has steadily declined,
``clearly reflecting an inability to effectively manage sales
growth.'' He says that from 1998 to 1999, sales grew 170 percent,
while inventory grew 650 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the company moves into toys and electronics, ``managing
inventory is going to become more difficult,'' he writes. ``We
believe that the upcoming holiday season is going to be a
significant operating and logistics challenge for the company and
could largely determine the credit outcome for debt holders.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has been able to finance its negative operating cash flow
by borrowing money _ tons of it. Its $2 billion in long-term debt
accounts for an astronomical 99 percent of its total
capitalization, compared with43 percent for Barnes &AMP; Noble and 28
percent for Borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1997 through the latest quarter, the company has received
$2.8 billion in funding, while its revenues have been $2.9 billion
_ a whopping 95 cents for every dollar of merchandise sold,'' Suria
points out.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Amazon starts generating positive cash flow, it will have
to raise more capital. And that won't be as easy as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Given its high debt load and dearth of tangible assets, Suria
doesn't see bank loans, high-yield (junk) bonds or more convertible
bonds as a likely option.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon could sell more shares, ``but given that the stock is
down more than 55 percent from its highs, it is likely to be
difficult,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A strategic investor could come to the rescue, such as ``Prince
Alwaleed, who loves to make cash infusions into cash-starved
world-class brands,'' he writes. Or, Amazon could sell private
equity to a buyout fund, a portal company or a real-world retailer.
But such an investment would take a backseat to $2 billion in debt,
``which might be a sticky point.''
</P>
<P>
   Less obvious sources of financing: Amazon could use its stock to
acquire a company with a cash horde (it's done so before). And then
there are Amazon employees, who could help out by exercising stock
options. (That raises money because employees have to buy stock
from the company before they can sell it.)
</P>
<P>
   However, Suria points out that ``from a credit perspective, it
certainly is not good for a company to depend upon cash from
employee option grants for its funding needs.''
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion: ``At the end of the first quarter, the company
had approximately $1 billion (in cash). Going into what is arguably
its most challenging holiday season, we believe that the
combination of negative cash flow, poor working capital management
and high debt load in a hyper competitive environment will put the
company under extremely high risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that the risk in the credit is priced into
the convertible bonds and therefore recommend that investors avoid
the securities.''
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON'S RESPONSE: Amazon has criticized Suria for not
consulting the company before writing the report. His response:
``Anything I need to know is in the company's (SEC) filings.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Stone, Amazon's director of investor relations, says the
report is ``a point of view that is based upon a historical
analysis rather than taking into consideration where the company
and many other folks think the business is going.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, he says Amazon will be ``strongly growing sales on a
year-over-year basis while also driving operational improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicts the company's pro-forma operating margin (operating
loss as a percent of sales) will shrink from 26 percent at the end
of December to 17 percent at the end of March to ``single-digits''
by year end.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those improvements, he thinks the company will turn
cash-flow positive by December and will end the year with $1
billion in cash. That would obviate the need for additional
financing, although he says the company won't rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   Stone disputes Suria's criticism of Amazon's inventory
management. ``In periods going forward, we would expect that we
would turn our inventory faster than has been in the case in the
physical world. We have warehouses that (allow us to) ship directly
to customers, so we don't have to deploy merchandise from
warehouses to retail stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon says it will increase sales by expanding products,
services and customers here and abroad and enhancing its
relationship with existing customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the expense side, we will improve the way we operate our
distribution network,'' rather than building new distribution
facilities, like it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   A BULL'S OPINION: Henry Blodget, an Internet analyst with
Merrill Lynch, believes that Amazon can turn itself around this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first five years, Amazon emphasized growth and
customer service at any cost. In 1999, it built 10 times as much
distribution capacity as it had the prior year. When you're
building that quickly, it's extremely difficult to run efficiently.
At the end of last year, it was as inefficient as it will ever
be.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Amazon will emphasize efficiency over growth.
</P>
<P>
   Blodget believes the company can achieve positive cash flow by
year end, although it will go negative again early next year when
it pays off its Christmas bills. (Amazon demands payment upfront,
via credit card, from its customers, but it can stretch out its own
payments to suppliers.)
</P>
<P>
   He believes Amazon now ``is where AOL was in 1996. There was
tremendous controversy. Lots of smart people were convinced (AOL)
would never make money.'' And yet thanks to strong management, it
maintained its leadership position in an enormous market. ` &UR; ` &LR; Those
situations, if they work out, make for goods stocks. But they don't
always work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Blodget thinks Amazon will work out, ultimately. ``If you're a
long-term investor, go ahead and buy now. But it's not going to be
a heroic stock in the near term.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
