<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9067 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-30 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR DODGERS TO GET ON WITH IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With 6:11 showing on the Dodger Stadium clock
Thursday evening, Darren Dreifort rocked into his distinctly
uncomplicated windup and delivered a fastball low and away to the
San Diego Padres' Eric Owens - and the 2000 baseball season was
under way.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it felt, anyway. Like a second Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' longest losing streak of the season had ended with
back-to-back, last-at-bat victories the past two nights. The
Dodgers had waived Orel Hershiser two days earlier, and cleared the
sentimental mist from their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier Thursday, baseball eased or eliminated most of the
suspensions stemming from the Dodgers' fight with Wrigley Field
fans - and lifted the wintry cloud that has hung over the team for
more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   It is springtime once again for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the city to wake up with its Lakers hangover
and ask, ``Hey, are the Dodgers are still in the race?'' Yes, they
are, and now they can turn their full attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Paul Beeston, baseball's president and chief
operating officer, was a repudiation of vice president for on-field
operations Frank Robinson's May 24 decision and a clear-cut victory
for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of 19 suspensions eliminated. Combined player suspensions
reduced from 60 days to 24. All of which said the Dodgers were
right to argue that there weren't 19 guys committing mayhem on the
skulls of Chicago Cubs fans that May 16 night.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers didn't get everything they sought on appeal. They
still must pay the original fines. They still can't choose the
games the suspended players will miss. They still lose Gary
Sheffield for five games; that's the one they'd like to have back.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office didn't back down from its message,
that players should stay out of the stands, even if somebody
pinched a $20 cap.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the commissioner's office realized that it, in
turn, should stay out of the pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   With the easing of the suspensions, it's up to the players to
win or lose the National League West, no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson announced the original penalties, I wrote that the
Dodgers could turn their outrage into a rallying cry, that this
could be the misfortune that brings the team together. A couple of
readers asked if I had some other set of Dodgers in mind, a corps
with the (begin ital)esprit(end ital) to rally around.
</P>
<P>
   Touche! Between that day and Thursday, the Dodgers went 15-18,
dropped from second to third in the division, and slipped from 2 to
4 games. They didn't rally. They wallowed.
</P>
<P>
   Now they can move on.
</P>
<P>
   A further appeal on the players' behalf by their union is
scheduled. The Dodgers should not encourage it.
</P>
<P>
   They should count their blessings and their legal victory. In
the language of Wrigley Field: Dodgers win! Dodgers win!
</P>
<P>
   Nice way to start a season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
