<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IMF TO CONSIDER CHANGES IN CONDITIONS PUT ON LOANS
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, which has ordered developing
nations to enact wrenching reforms as the price for emergency aid
in recent years, is likely to curtail the demands it makes of
clients who borrow money in the future, a senior fund official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Streamlining the conditions the IMF imposes on borrowers is one
of the changes Horst Koehler, the new managing director, is
weighing as a panel he set up to study the agency's role finishes a
draft report.
</P>
<P>
   SEPSIS DRUG LIFTS ELI LILLY SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly said that advanced trials of a drug it is developing
to treat the bacterial infection sepsis had met its goals for
lowering death rates. Zovant, if eventually approved, would be the
first drug to treat complications of the disease, which kills 1,400
people a day worldwide. Lilly said it expected to submit an
application to the Food and Drug Administration for approval by the
first quarter of 2001. Shares of Lilly soared $15.125, to $102.25.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT WARNINGS PULL DOWN STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell broadly as several prominent companies,
including Ericsson, Unisys and Goodyear Tire, warned of
lower-than-expected profits. The Nasdaq composite index slid 63.11
points, or 1.6 percent, to 3,877.23. The Dow Jones industrial
average slumped 129.75 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,398.04. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 12.43 points, or 0.9
percent, to 1,442.39.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES' PLANS HURT PRICELINE
</P>
<P>
   Stock Shares in Priceline.com dropped 8.4 percent after a report
that six major airlines _ America West Airlines, American Airlines,
Continental Airlines, Northwest Airlines, United Airlines and US
Airways _ plan to invest in a competing Web site for customers
looking for discounts on plane tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-QUARTER GDP REVISED UP
</P>
<P>
   Gross domestic product, the broadest measure of economic
activity, grew at an annual rate of 5.5 percent in the first
quarter instead of the 5.4 percent estimated a month ago, the
Commerce Department said, raising the prospect of more
interest-rate increases this year.
</P>
<P>
   DRUCKENMILLER TO REJOIN DUQUESNE
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Druckenmiller, who quit Soros Fund Management in April
and also told investors in his Duquesne Capital Management fund
group that he was taking a break, is now telling Duquesne investors
that he will return in September, according to investors in the
firm. Duquesne, based in Pittsburgh, has about $2 billion in assets
from clients that include Bowdoin College, Druckenmiller's alma
mater in Maine; Berea College in Kentucky; and Denison University
in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   NOMINEE FOR COMMERCE SECRETARY
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton nominated a former congressman, Norman Mineta,
as secretary of commerce for the rest of his presidency. Mineta
would become the first Asian-American to hold a Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   FORD IN EXCLUSIVE TALKS FOR DAEWOO
</P>
<P>
   Ford won exclusive rights to negotiate the purchase of Daewoo
Motor of South Korea with a $6.9 billion offer that would be Ford's
largest foreign acquisition and could significantly strengthen its
operations in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PROPOSES CHANGES IN SUBSIDIES
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration introduced a sweeping proposal at the
World Trade Organization to change the way governments subsidize
farmers, challenging the European Union's extensive agricultural
subsidies.
</P>
</TEXT>
