<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-WILDFIRE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
200,000-ACRE HANFORD WILDFIRE UNDER CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CANDY HATCHER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. _ Southeastern Washington, charbroiled and
stinky after walls of fire hip-hopped through about 200,000 acres
in two days, began to clean up Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By dusk, firefighters had the Two Fork fire, America's
fastest-growing wildfire in the past decade, under control. The
blaze, fueled by dry sagebrush and shifting winds, burned thousands
of acres in and around the Hanford Nuclear Reservation, including
three old radioactive waste sites.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, it destroyed 36 buildings, most of them homes
near Benton City. It sent one resident to Harborview Medical Center
in Seattle with burns over one-fourth of his body, and 10 others to
hospitals to treat smoke inhalation. It blanketed communities many
miles away with a lingering, acrid odor.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials said they detected no radiation
releases from Hanford, although further tests were planned.
</P>
<P>
   About 900 firefighters, including more than 50 from the
Seattle-Tacoma area, helped fight the fire, which Washington's
emergency response team called ``the top fire priority in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven thousand people had fled Benton City, Horn Rapids and West
Richland on Wednesday. On Thursday, as they returned home, in some
cases to rubble, they described the fireballs, 30 to 40 feet high,
that had barreled toward them at 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were goners,'' said Marty Peck, 43, who left with
his daughter, Kristin, just before one of their two mobile homes
near Benton City was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The family had watched the flames come down nearby Rattlesnake
Mountain, a wall of fire that nothing could stop. Kristin Peck, 17,
had time only to grab a blanket and an album of photographs of her
mother, who died when Kristin was 3.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, all that remained of the mobile home where
she lives with her grandmother was blackened rubble. But 30 feet
away, her father's mobile home was fine.
</P>
<P>
   The fire razed their barn and destroyed the well and one car,
but it left a car in the same driveway unscathed except for a
melted tail light.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, even as officials declared 40 percent of the fire
contained, flames glowed like bright orange snakes and sent gray
smoke billowing upward. The fire blackened hills and fields for
miles around Hanford, scorching land in some cases to the banks of
the Columbia and Yakima rivers.
</P>
<P>
   At one farm, several horses trotted in a green pasture
surrounded by blackened earth. A white barn still stood, but other
buildings on the property were reduced to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   At another farm, a circular field of crops was split in half _
lush and green on one side, black and burnt on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, smoke from the fires hung in a gray haze above
the rural area, some of it more than 20 miles from the center of
the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH SPARKED FIRE
</P>
<P>
   The fire began Tuesday with a car crash in dry grass near the
west gate to Hanford.
</P>
<P>
   A car left the road, then veered back onto pavement and slammed
head-on into a tractor-trailer rig. The car's driver died; the
truck driver was injured. The fire, fanned by stiff winds, exploded
Wednesday afternoon as temperatures pushed 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze doubled in size, jumped the Yakima River near the
Wanawish Dam, threatened homes in West Richland and consumed some
outside Benton City. Companies along the northern edge of Richland
sent their employees home.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-third of the sagebrush plain that makes up the
560-square-mile Hanford reservation was scorched. Hanford,
established to help build the atomic bomb during World War II,
contains the nation's largest volume of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke declared a state of emergency in Benton County,
activating the National Guard to help with evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   COMMAND CENTER
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of people drove from the burning area, hundreds of
others, professionals and volunteers whose job was to quench the
flames, headed toward the smoky desert in 90-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them arrived before dawn Thursday, trudging into a
dense, gray hell with their specialized coats and bunker pants,
leather gloves, thermal boots and helmets.
</P>
<P>
   They worked in shifts, 600 fighting fire and 300 resting.
Helicopters and tankers dropped flame retardant on the fire.
</P>
<P>
   While firefighters worked the front lines Thursday afternoon,
about three dozen emergency workers monitored the fire lines at the
state Emergency Response Center at Camp Murray in Tacoma, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Things had slowed a bit around dinner time in the large room
with a dozen pods of desks, computers and fax machines. The workers
caught their breath between crises in the room lined with maps and
bulletin boards. They had nine clocks set in different time zones,
and 16 televisions and three giant screens tuned to the news and
fire line maps.
</P>
<P>
   Each pod of desks had its own focus, from the National Guard to
the state social services to the media.
</P>
<P>
   At the cluster responsible for coordinating firefighting
resources, Trooper John Farrow of the State Patrol fire prevention
bureau and his colleagues coordinated which resources went where.
Sometimes, he said, especially in the first hours of a fire, that
requires balancing the needs of firefighters demanding help with
fire departments spent beyond their resources.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Farrow's 18-hour workday Wednesday, fire had torn
through about 100,000 acres and the emotions of those calling
Farrow for help had worn raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen that often, but (Wednesday) night it
happened,'' Farrow said. ``It's not a pleasant thing to deal with
folks who are desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   `HOLD YOUR BREATH'
</P>
<P>
   In much of the Tri-City area, people were looking forward to the
holiday weekend. Nearly 6,000 Jehovah's Witnesses came to town for
a convention, filling hotels in Kennewick. The Tri-Cities Visitor &AMP;
Convention Bureau was busy trying to find hotel rooms for reporters
covering the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cups runneth over,'' said one bureau worker who cited the
soccer tournaments and horse shows and Jehovah's Witness convention
that would keep the community hopping through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The River of Fire Festival, slated for July 4 in Kennewick, is
still scheduled. Ditto, luckily, for Benton City's Eighth Annual
Blues Festival July 7. The festival, appropriately, is featuring
barbecue and blues.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Brodzinski, owner of the Seth Ryan Winery hosting the
festival, said this week's fire wasn't the first time her family
has had to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, who lives on the back side of the winery along Highway
224, called Wednesday night, asking what he should pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sagebrush,'' Brodzinski said, ``it's a very serious
thing. You do kind of hold your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Angela Galloway, Hector Castro and The Associated
Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
