<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-CORRECTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPICS: A TALE OF THE TAPE
</HEADLINE>
 IN FOURTH GRAPH TO 9 1/2-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dick Ebersol should have been drooling
uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, as the chief of NBC Sports was beamed via satellite
to all the network affiliates Wednesday to give a progress report
on the upcoming coverage of the 2000 Sydney Olympics, he subtly
slipped in a few interesting facts that, when closer examined,
should have a chilling effect on the future coverage of live
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Due to the advertising sales and contributions from the
affiliates, ``we will eke out a small profit,'' Ebersol said,
mentioning that the $705 million in rights fees the network had to
put up for this event would probably be offset by $900 million in
sponsors contributions.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, there's going to be fewer advertising minutes per
hour during the 84 hours of prime time - just 9 minutes as opposed
to the 9 1/2 that they did in Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, they project more viewers for these Aussie games
than watched four years ago - 215 million, this after Atlanta set a
record with 206 million, he figured they'd actually lose about $70
million on the proposition.
</P>
<P>
   And, he repeated for those hard of hearing, it'll all be on tape
- 441 hours, divided up between the network and its two cable
channels.
</P>
<P>
   All of which only reinforces the foundation of his grand scheme.
No matter how much anyone screams for a live Olympics, it doesn't
make business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago, we made the decision for all videotape,''
Ebersol repeated, despite the fact some media outlets still believe
he'll change his mind sometime before the Sept. 15 opening
ceremonies. ``The first three days of the Olympics, we've made a
commitment to telling viewers that it's all on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Rub it in, more like.
</P>
<P>
   We've already been over the fact that a prime-time event in
Australia will pretty much be a prime-time event on the West Coast
(which is 18 hours behind). That means West Coast newspapers will
have a fair amount of same-day results of major events in the next
day's edition. But NBC will show them about 24 hours after they
happen.
</P>
<P>
   And most of those NBC events, Ebersol disclosed, will be the
``family coverage,'' or individual-type sports that fall into the
``Up Close and Personal'' category, such as swimming, gymnastics
and track and field. The cable outlets - MSNBC and CNBC - will be
the dumping ground for team sports and boxing.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're hard up enough to actually want to know results as
they happen, Ebersol said that the network's Web site -
nbcolympics.com - will take care of that.
</P>
<P>
   Which, again, is great news for anyone who doesn't have cable
TV, let alone a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Apologist: All it took for Lakers center Shaquille
O'Neal to get back into the good graces of his fellow striking
Screen Actors Guild members was to issue a nice statement of
support following all the guff he took for his participation in the
gratuitous Disneyland commercial after the Lakers won the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through two work stoppages in my career, and I know
how very difficult they are to union members and their families,''
O'Neal's statement read, making no mention of how agent Leonard
Armato has been trying to spin the appearance as a public service
announcement. ``As a SAG and AFTRA member, I fully support the
strike and hope that negotiations can resume in the very near
future so both sides can get back to business as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A SAG spokesman told the Hollywood Reporter that O'Neal wouldn't
face disciplinary actions, but SAG joint strike committee chairman
Todd Amorde was quoted as saying: ``I have a real issue with
Disney, with Nike and all these other corporations making a cynical
grab to exploit young athletes and performers during their moment
of glory and use them to bust our unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's bite: Notice how no one in the TNT studio would follow
up when Charles Barkley tore into the Clippers after they picked
high schooler Darius Miles during Wednesday's NBA draft coverage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Clippers are a good environment for the
Miles kid,'' said Barkley, who wasn't in the studio but at his home
doing remote analysis. ``They are a terrible organization ... I
hope he gets out of there. They should've re-signed their two free
agents (Derek Anderson and Maurice Taylor).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clippers are one of the problems in sports. People think
you have to win to make money, and the Clippers are a perfect
example of a team that lets all of their good players go every year
and just keeps giving the fans a bad product. People assume that
every organization is trying to win, and there's just no excuse for
what the Clippers have been doing the last 10 to 15 years, letting
all their good players go.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the gang in Minnesota, anchor Ernie Johnson and analysts
Rick Majerus, John Thompson and Kenny Smith were as responsive as a
snow plow.
</P>
<P>
   At least Thompson has an excuse - he's been mentioned as a
possible new Clippers coach. In fact, after the team traded for
Orlando's Corey Maggette, Derek Strong and Keyon Dooling, Thompson
said: ``It may be time to go back for another interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Might as well. Your TV work has shown an astonishing display of
mediocrity since you left Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   More interoffice bashing: It was crazy enough for the Atlanta
Braves to order that TBS broadcasters Skip Caray, Pete Van Wieren,
Don Sutton and Joe Simpson be left off the charter after they
exposed the shortening of the catcher's box at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   You know that they all work for the same company, right? Imagine
the Fox-owed Dodgers punishing Fox Sports Net play-by-play legend
Vin Scully by making him fly commercial after he questions another
one of Davey Johnson's suspect managerial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But then, CNN sports anchor Vince Cellini, another Time-Warner
employee under Ted Turner's fiefdom, throws in his opinion on
Tuesday's ``Sports Night'' after the broadcasters were reinstated:
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta get a timeout. I mean, kicking the Braves announcers
off Monday's chartered flight to Montreal is beyond absurd. I never
thought the acerbic Skip Caray could ever be a sympathetic figure,
but Braves president Stan Kasten made it happen. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing the Braves needed was another public relations
gaffe - but old Stan served one up. ... Is that how you treat
longtime employees? How petty. How small. And this announcer
doesn't care how this flies with Stan.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Cellini and the points over Kasten in the company picnic's
water balloon toss competition.
</P>
<P>
   The last word: Said Skip on the TBS telecast as John Rocker
walked off the mound after throwing a shutout inning against the
Mets on Thursday night and went straight to the dugout: ``Not a
word, my friend ... way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -The sight of 1150-AM's Arnie Spanier hosing down cars in Studio
City on Thursday, making good on a promise to wash everyone's
vehicle in L.A. if the Lakers won the NBA championship. It may not
be the most original sports-talk radio promotion, but at least this
does the city good while wasting some of Northern California's
water at the same time. Spanier took it upon himself to even steam
clean a few engines - using only his own breath.
</P>
<P>
   -The extended piece - 14 minutes, in fact - that Fox Sports
Net's National Sports Report did on Atlanta Braves pitcher John
Rocker during Wednesday night's ``Open Mike'' segment. Credit FSN
producer Sean Pamphilon with doing a masterful job editing the
various opinions from national journalists, clergymen, an AIDS
activist and kids who live in Macon, Ga. - Rocker's home town. It
was then followed up by some interesting commentary by anchor Keith
Olbermann, who questioned the media's role in how to cover this
``story,'' including whether Fox Sports Net was justified in doing
this piece considering it could be construed as promotion for its
airing Thursday night's Braves-Mets game (plus Saturday's game on
the network to nearly half the country).
</P>
<P>
   -Fox and NBC told baseball there'd be no walk-off victory after
the networks were informed it'd be in their best interest to pay
triple the rights fees if they wanted to keep promoting their
product on an annual basis. If Fox has to pay $345 million a year
(instead of $115 million) and NBC is supposed to kick in $240
million (over their current $80 million), guess who's gonna be
footing that bill?
</P>
<P>
   -Marv Albert, on TNT's coverage of Wimbledon, talking about
ex-UCLA star Justin Gimelstob on Wednesday's telecast: ``Recruiters
made certain to keep Justin away from Bill Walton before the
decision was made to attend UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -First Anna Kournikova, now Dennis Miller on the cover of Sports
Illustrated. Next, a follow-up on the controversy surrounding how
Derek Jeter was No. 2 behind George Clooney on People magazine's
list of the most eligible bachelors in the country.
</P>
<P>
   -Sport magazine will suspend publication following its August
issue, citing a huge loss in advertising revenue, according to
Peterson Publications.
</P>
<P>
   -We now understand why Jason Kapono reconsidered applying for
the NBA draft - had he been picked, UCLA basketball coach Steve
Lavin would have been right there (after leaving the Jermoe Moiso
press gathering) to be his media spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   -Chick Hearn's summer vacation - doing more Sparks games for
KCAL Channel 9. Why not take a break? Starting with Saturday's
broadcast (5 p.m.), he'll be on three of the next four Saturdays.
Did you know: He actually did play-by-play on the Sparks' TV game
Sunday, June 18 - the day before the Lakers' clinched the NBA
title?
</P>
<P>
   -Reader contribution of the week: When ESPN2 aired a delayed
broadcast of Sunday's CART race from Portland, it continued to run
its sports ticker at the bottom of the screen. Which, a half-hour
into the race, revealed the winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
