u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-30 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROCKER SAYS MOVE AHEAD; HE'S RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bearbaiting having been abolished and pigsticking
being currently out of fashion, the public still needs spectacles,
preferably vulgar and ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the spectacle comes in the form of a troubled boxer
named Mike Tyson threatening to eat other people's children, and
sometimes it comes in the tattooed form of Dennis Rodman, saying
anything and wearing anything to get attention.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night the spectacle was the return of John Rocker to
Shea Stadium for the first time since he made his crude comments
about the citizens of New York and particularly the diverse riders
of the No. 7 elevated train that runs from Manhattan to the borough
of Queens in all its zestful ethnic glory. He pitched a scoreless
eighth inning as the Braves beat the Mets once again, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's remarks escalated like some new strain of virus let
loose outside the laboratory of his own mind. But then again, the
news media gave Rocker's remarks the ultimate breeding dish, and
the populace provided the heat.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of blame to go around for the foolish tableau
that had Rocker make a feint toward taking the IRT to the ballpark
until wiser heads prevailed. There was more blame for the dolts who
sent notices of Battery Night for this first visit by the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Stengel used to say that every day in baseball you see
something you never saw before (a pretty strong statement for a man
who managed until he was 75), but it is quite possible nobody had
ever seen a player's mixture of mea culpa and nolo contendere
beamed from a message board.
</P>
<P>
   The Romans, who put men in the ring with bulls, or any other
combination with potential for gore and titillation, would have
been perplexed by the sight of Rocker, looming larger than life
high above the stands, reading a quirky prepared statement he
claimed to have written, and probably did.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said he was ``happy to be back in New York, believe it or
not,'' and he referred with proper irony to ``my presumed hatred
for the people of New York'' and he said he was sorry for the
disruption to all, and he noted that he had apologized several
times already, but he added, ``Many people perceived these comments
to be malicious, and for this again I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded by saying, ``I am not the evil person that has been
portrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   The early arrivals razzed Rocker, but almost reflexively, which
may be a good sign that the fans are not up to perpetual menace.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sports Illustrated enterprisingly sent down a reporter to
see what manner of chap had come up with a huge case of rabbit ears
during the playoffs, Rocker has been pursued by the furies,
including the occasional scolding from his absolutely perfect
little corner of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's ugly remarks about gays, people on welfare, people who
speak foreign languages and others different from him _ and the
righteousness and the outrage have a cost. Seven hundred police
officers who could have been out righting wrongs (or giving tickets
for parking at broken meters) were deployed Thursday, including
phalanxes at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is coming! Rocker is coming!
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is no fool. Some people think this was his Rodmanesque
way of creating a second career as a professional wrestler, which
seems unlikely, but he may surely have been messing with New York's
mind by threatening to ride the No. 7 train, which his team and
baseball was not about to permit. To this particular ploy, Rocker
is entitled to say, ``Gotcha.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he is guilty of starting this madness, by shooting off
his mouth with vile comments that didn't come from nowhere. Has he
learned a lesson? The process seems to have wiped the smirk off
Rocker's mouth, finally.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night police officers were crouching in the front row,
there was a temporary roof and partition around the Braves'
bullpen, and the announced crowd of 46,998 waited to boo Rocker.
The joint was not exactly bristling with the malice that seethes in
New York ballparks during the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   There was room for a few sportsmanlike cheers for the recovering
cancer patient, Andres Galarraga, but the crowd seemed drained by
the eighth inning, until Rocker made his trademark sprint to the
mound. The crowd chanted a few nasty names, but he got three
straight outs and then walked tall to the dugout as a few officers
stood guard. Afterward, he said, ``I'm going to quit while I'm
ahead and not talk, and he did not, while a security guard shooed
reporters away.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for trouble will stay around all weekend, but
maybe outright brutality has been averted at the cost of massive
police overtime. There's got to be a better way to react to a few
dumb remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
