</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUALITY START BY PETTITTE HELPS YANKS STOP A SLIDE
</HEADLINE>
  By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Though the pursuit of a slugging outfielder might have
captivated those who follow trade speculation and might have hung
over the New York Yankees for the last two weeks, it was the woeful
state of the club's pitching that was at the root of the Yankees'
unseemly six-week struggle since May 11, when they were 13 games
over .500.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday night's game against the Detroit Tigers at
Comerica Park, in the wake of a trade that sent David Justice to
the Yankees from Cleveland, the talk was not of how to shore up the
Yankees offense but of just how dramatic the misery of the pitching
staff had been.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone spoke confidently of the notion that all the staff
needed was to get several quality starts in a row to stop its slide
and re-establish the equilibrium of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night Andy Pettitte, pitching on three days' rest
because the scheduled starter, Ramiro Mendoza, was placed on the
disabled list on Wednesday, stood firm. He said he relished the
opportunity to bolster the staff with this start, but even he had
not counted on such success. He was aiming for seven strong
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently emboldened by the Yankees' eight-run fourth inning,
and pitching aggressively, Pettitte outdid his expectations in
beating Detroit, 8-0, Thursday night. He allowed six hits in
handing the Tigers (32-43) their 10th shutout loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   One night after the Tigers pounded the rookie Ben Ford and the
reliever Allen Watson in a 13-6 demolition of the Yankees, Detroit
succumbed to the first complete game by a Yankees pitcher since the
last time Pettitte (8-4) notched one, on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to be able to give us a good start,'' said
Pettitte, who has one other complete-game shutout in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that all of our problems would go away with a good
pitching performance. Trade or no trade, we win here because we
pitch well. That's the way we've won for four years. Runs are nice,
but good pitching shuts down good offense. I was determined to put
together a good start. It was nice to get something going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (38-35) can exhale a bit with this victory. It was
their first triumph in the Tigers' new stadium after five straight
losses, and it kept them three games behind first-place Toronto in
the American League East as they head to Florida for a three-game
series against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley is expected to start Friday night and the healing
Orlando Hernandez and Roger Clemens should go on Saturday and on
Sunday. But it was up to Pettitte Thursday night to put a halt to a
stretch in which the rotation was being held together by bandages,
fill-ins and awestruck rookies. Pettitte had been mediocre (1-2,
4.84 earned run average) in the six previous times he had pitched
on short rest, and he had not done it since 1997. But the
left-hander allowed just two hits through the first three innings
before his teammates unleashed a furious assault.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees sent 13 batters to the plate in the fourth inning.
The rally began with Paul O'Neill's single off Dave Mlicki. There
were eight hits in the inning, one a triple to the center-field
wall by Bernie Williams on which center fielder Juan Encarnacion
seemed to have no clue which way to break before watching the ball
sail over his head.
</P>
<P>
   And there were three sacrifice flies in the inning, a feat that
happened one other time, in 1962. It was possible because Jose
Vizcaino's drive to left field with one out briefly nestled in
Bobby Higginson's glove, only to drop out. Vizcaino went to first
base on the error, Scott Brosius scored the fourth run of the
inning, and the play was ruled a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Four more runs followed, the last one on Williams' sacrifice fly
off reliever Nelson Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Such offensive theatrics, even with the acquisition of Justice,
manager Joe Torre said, would not have as much impact on the
Yankees as the revival of the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``David or Goliath couldn't help us if we don't pitch,'' Torre
said. ``It tells us what we should know already _ all it takes is
someone going on the mound and shutting them down. After that, we
know how to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
