<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 A burst of pyrotechnic punditry  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marketplace musings for an extended Independence Day weekend:
</P>
<P>
   The WorldCom-Sprint merger's obit will say it succumbed to
trustbusting zeal, but its demise was more due to bad luck, bad
timing and bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it passingly curious that the more ``lite'' and ``lo-fat''
comestibles America's food processors bring to market, the more
obesity becomes a problem in this country?
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that because everyone has come to have a cell
phone, including scientific researchers, you don't hear nearly as
much anymore about cell phones causing brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ben &AMP; Jerry decision to sell its touchy-feely ice cream
empire to Unilever proves nothing else, it proves that everybody
has a price.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the overrated things in the world, April in Kansas City
has to be right up near the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   The way scientists keep reversing long-accepted theories, it
won't be surprising if someday somebody purports to discover that
smoking /{prevents/} lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the commercials on television are more interesting than
the programs they help sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   You know there's still some sanity left in America when ABC's
Earth Day television special with Leonardo DiCaprio does a ratings
pratfall.
</P>
<P>
   Wake me when Kansas City gets a big-league hockey franchise.
</P>
<P>
   You're getting old if you can remember when nearly all adult
male golfers wore slacks rather than shorts while playing in the
warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   One of the iron laws of nature is that human intellectual
development is inversely related to how much humans think they
know, because the dumbest people are almost always those who think
they know everything.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sad day for anyone in the Kansas City area born before
1940 when KFEZ dropped its ``Music of Your Life'' format.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to fight obesity is to pass a federal law
prohibiting restaurants from serving gut-busting portions of
everything on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to David Stockman?
</P>
<P>
   Do older men with bushy eyebrows appreciate how grotesque they
look?
</P>
<P>
   If GOP congressional candidate Greg Musil thinks the evolution
vs. creationism controversy in Kansas is a vote-getter, perhaps
primary opponents Phill Kline and Gary Morsch can counter by
pledging to resolve Johnson County's vehicle registration mess.
</P>
<P>
   Are all those people yakking on cell phones compulsive talkers,
or are they scintillating conversationalists with loads of
worthwhile things to say?
</P>
<P>
   People who contend that current levels of taxation are
reasonable either don't pay taxes or have more money than they can
handle wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Why should taxpayers have to help underwrite the risks taken by
often affluent people who insist on maintaining beach homes in
areas at risk for storms and coastal erosion?
</P>
<P>
   How many people complaining about high gasoline prices wouldn't
think twice about dropping $50 at a casino as part of an evening's
entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   Sprint employees should understand that any sense of relief they
are enjoying about now will last only as long as it takes another
suitor to emerge from the wings, which shouldn't be long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9089 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-PRECIOUS-KAN &LR;      06-30 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRECIOUS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Enesco calls off bid to buy all licensing rights for Precious
Moments  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enesco Group Inc., the primary marketer of Precious Moments
products, has called off a deal to pay Precious Moments Inc. as
much as $175 million for all license rights to the inspirational
art.
</P>
<P>
   Precious Moments products, best known for the figurines of
tear-eyed children, rank among the most popular collectibles in the
world. The Precious Moments line was created by artist Sam Butcher.
Precious Moments also operates the Precious Moments Chapel Center
in Carthage, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Enesco has had the primary licensing rights to the art for about
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of the deal came three days after Enesco's
president and chief executive, Jeffrey Hutsell, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which was trading at 30 two years ago, has
lost about 56 percent of its value this year. It closed Thursday at
4, up .
</P>
<P>
   Donna Conklin, an Enesco spokeswoman, said that while she
understood other companies, including Hallmark Cards Inc., had
expressed interest in buying the licensing rights to the line,
Precious Moments Inc. had pledged to continue its relationship with
Enesco. Hallmark is among the primary retailers of the Precious
Moments line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two companies could not come to terms on the deal, but we
are going to move forward with business as usual,'' Conklin said.
</P>
<P>
   M. Allan VanDenBerg Jr., who in April was named president and
chief executive of Precious Moments by Samuel J. Butcher Inc., said
the decision to cancel the deal ``was not based upon the strength
of the brand.'' He said there were other considerations within
Enesco.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that other companies had expressed interest in
buying the licensing rights but said Precious Moments had committed
to remain with Enesco.
</P>
<P>
   It was Eugene Freedman, founder of Enesco, who had persuaded
Butcher to expand his line of inspirational cards into other
products more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   VanDenBerg declined to identify the companies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Hallmark declined to say whether the company
was a suitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a surprise that our name is out there, but we simply
don't talk about those kinds of plans until we do them,'' said
Julie O'Dell of Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   VanDenBerg said cancellation of the deal would have no effect on
plans to expand the Carthage center, where Butcher and his family
have built attractions that include galleries, gift shops, a
museum, a music and water fountain show, Victorian wedding
facilities and the original Precious Moments Chapel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
