<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCORM-KAN </SLUG>
  
 McCormick agrees to additional $1 million civil penalty  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCormick Distilling Co. has agreed to a $1 million civil
penalty, on top of $1 million in restitution it already has paid,
to settle charges stemming from its participation in a scheme to
smuggle liquor to Eastern Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The payment, along with McCormick's earlier agreement to suspend
operations for seven days beginning Saturday, is part of a
settlement that resolves alleged violations of the Federal Alcohol
Administration Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most substantial case, in terms of the
breadth of the penalty, that we have handled in the last 20
years,'' said Jeff Cohen, assistant chief counsel with the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the lead investigative agency in
the case. ``We consider this to have been very serious
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement ends the agency's investigation of the
144-year-old company based in Weston. It is the oldest continuously
active distillery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In April, McCormick pleaded guilty in Newark, N.J., to a
misdemeanor charge of falsifying liquor export documents to avoid
paying excise taxes overseas. Federal authorities said the liquor,
disguised as industrial alcohol, was sold by Russian mobsters on
the black market as beverage alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, McCormick paid $1 million to the Ukrainian
government to compensate it for excise taxes it was unable to
collect as a result of the smuggling scheme. The company also
agreed to pay a $10,250 criminal fine to the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick officials were said to be attending a board meeting
Thursday and could not be reached for comment. An attorney for the
company, Christopher Lee Milner of Dallas, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCormick is now in the clear, the two-year probe into
the smuggling scheme continues. Federal authorities are focusing on
mob influence at New York shipping harbors and other, so far
unnamed distilleries. In May, the investigation resulted in the
arrests of seven persons on money laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, all natives of former Soviet republics and most
now living in Brooklyn, N.Y., reportedly have ties to Russian
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that undercover agents approached
the suspects, pretending to be acting on behalf of big drug
traffickers in Florida and South America whose operations
``generated a lot of cash,'' in the words of the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The agents gave cash to several of the suspects during more than
20 secretly recorded meetings at different hotel rooms. The
suspects allegedly returned the cash to the agents, less a 25
percent commission or checks payable to dummy companies formed by
the agents.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mosley, director of industrial operations in the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms' Kansas City field division, said
he couldn't comment on the ties between the suspects and McCormick,
``other than that product manufactured and sold by McCormick was
going into the hands of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City field division led the investigation of
McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said McCormick has cooperated in the investigation, which
also involves the FBI, the Internal Revenue Service and the Customs
Service. The extent of McCormick's participation in the smuggling
scheme remains unclear _ company officials have not returned
repeated phone calls from /{The Kansas City Star/} over the last
two months _ but court documents filed in New Jersey said a key
official ``within substantial authority'' at McCormick was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. attorney (in Newark) made the decision not to
prosecute any higher-ups at the company,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed by federal prosecutors alleged that from April
1995 to December 1997, McCormick improperly identified alcoholic
beverages shipped to Russia and Ukraine as industrial products,
using descriptive labels such as ``Cleaning,'' ``Cleansol'' and
``Rainbow Cleaning Solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reportedly added food coloring to the alcohol to
make it look like paint solvent, windshield washer fluid and other
industrial products. Once the alcohol was in Russia and Ukraine,
members of the Russian mob were said to have removed the food
coloring and sold the liquor on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said McCormick will pay off the $1 million civil penalty
in installments as part of an agreed-to payment schedule. He said
the company will be barred from importing, selling or producing
distilled spirits during the seven-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, as a privately owned company, does not disclose
revenue figures, so the effect of the shutdown on its finances is
unclear. A group of investors bought the company from Midwest Grain
Products Inc. of Atchison, Kan., in January 1993 for about $2
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
