<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9091 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-LAZAR-KAN &LR;      06-30 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZAR-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Commission to hold hearing on Station's $500,000 bonus payment  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Missouri Gaming Commission will hold a public hearing in
August to learn what happened to $500,000 that Station Casinos Inc.
paid a St. Louis lawyer more than four years ago when the company
was seeking a license to operate in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   That money was part of $870,000 that federal prosecutors said
attorney Michael Lazaroff either misappropriated over several years
or failed to report to his partners as law firm income.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Lazaroff pleaded guilty to multiple charges
of financial fraud and federal election fraud in connection with
that money. Those charges made no allegations of wrongdoing by
Station, which is based in Las Vegas and runs the largest Kansas
City area casino.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in St. Louis said
Thursday that no further indictments or charges were expected in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea agreement, however, Lazaroff agreed to
cooperate in the continuing investigation by the Gaming Commission.
He could be called as a witness at the scheduled Aug. 30 hearing at
the Westin Crown Center hotel.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the case said it was clear the commission
had substantial concerns and that testimony presented at the
hearing was likely to have ``important'' consequences for Station.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Fisher, executive director of the gaming commission, said
Thursday, ``We want to try to determine as best we can what the
facts are regarding the payment of $500,000 to Mike Lazaroff by
Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring witnesses in and ask them questions about how
Mr. Lazaroff was involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher would not discuss the names of potential witnesses but
said some might have to be subpoenaed to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff's St. Louis lawyer could not be reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While publicly traded Station denies wrongdoing, it acknowledged
Wednesday in a public statement required by the federal Securities
and Exchange Commission that continuing scrutiny of ``certain bonus
payments'' it made to Lazaroff ``could lead to further proceedings
against the company or its executives, which could result in fines
and other penalties against them (or) restrict their ability to
hold gaming licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a similar statement in March in its annual
report to the SEC. But that statement three months ago did not
specifically warn that any company executives' Missouri licenses
might hang in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials will not discuss particulars of the
Lazaroff case. But in the past the scheduling of such extraordinary
hearings has cost casino executives their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   When it was disclosed that Boyd Gaming Inc., which operated the
now-closed Sam's Town Casino in Kansas City, indirectly had paid
legal fees to the speaker of the Missouri House _ and that there
may have been a cover-up _ the riverboat's 1995 opening was
threatened until company President Charles L. Ruthe stepped aside.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, three top executives of Hilton Hotels Corp. had to
resign over questionable company payments to associates of a former
Kansas City Port Authority official before the commission would
license its Flamingo casino.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing controversy forced Hilton in 1998 to agree to sell
the Flamingo and surrender its Missouri gaming license.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lazaroff situation, the bonus or ``success fee'' payments
came to light late last year during the commission's routine audit
of Station's books as part of the company's proposed $22.5 million
purchase of the Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   Questions over the Lazaroff payments scuttled the Flamingo's
sale to Station and later triggered the investigation of Lazaroff
by the U.S. attorney in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has never made a public allegation or comment
regarding the bonus payments. But casino regulators held off
approving the $22.5 million Flamingo sale for three months, until
the purchase contract expired and the deal collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   That delay was considered unusual because Station already was
licensed to operate four other Missouri casinos and several in
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of his law firm partnership agreement, Lazaroff was
entitled to keep only about $9,100 of the $500,000 bonus. In
federal criminal court documents Lazaroff acknowledged he had
deposited the money into his own bank account for unspecified
``personal purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, questions have been raised about whether any
of the money paid to Lazaroff was used to improperly influence any
public officials.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lazaroff case became public in December, Scott M.
Nielson, Station's general counsel, said the company had done
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The payments were all in the ordinary course of business,''
Nielson said. He could not be reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement issued late Wednesday, Station said,
``Based on the company's own internal review, the company is
unaware of any improprieties on its part'' and is ``cooperating
fully'' in all investigations.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed in the criminal case against
Lazaroff, the lawyer received five bonus payments from Station,
ranging from $50,000 to $150,000, between June 1994 and June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say the payment of success fees by satisfied clients is
a common practice at the conclusion of a legal matter.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Lazaroff pleaded guilty to one count of
soliciting illegal contributions to the 2000 Democratic
presidential primary campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and former
U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted to two counts of defrauding his law partners
and clients through falsified expense account billings and other
records, and by pocketing the $500,000 bonus from Station.
</P>
<P>
   Station's stock closed Thursday at 26, down 1. But gaming stock
analysts appeared unfazed by the news. Jeffrey B. Logsdon at WR
Hambrecht &AMP; Co. initiated Station coverage on Thursday with a
``strong buy'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Ader of Bear Stearns reiterated his company's buy
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Station's stock went down a point in a market that was down
150,'' said Harry Curtis, of BancBoston Robertson Stephens, who
also recommends a buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read it as the Gaming Commission fulfilling its obligation
to be satisfied that there was no wrongdoing by any gaming
operators,'' Curtis said of the August hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
