<SLUG> BC-VICT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC COUPLE ARE DRIVING FORCE BEHIND CROSS-COUNTRY MOTORCYCLE RELAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're going to buy a Victory motorcycle, then it only seems
right that you should take a ride on the old Victory Highway.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the morning sun sparkling off his blue V92C on
Thursday, Spike Durkin of De Soto and about 20 other Victory owners
from Texas, Minnesota, Iowa, Virginia, North Dakota and elsewhere
pulled out of the Victory Junction Restaurant in Kansas City, Kan.,
to begin the sixth leg of the cross-country Victory Highway relay.
</P>
<P>
   Brand-new motorcycles on a worn and forgotten highway, which
generally follows U.S. 40, seemed a perfect match to the group of
bikers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great old highway and a great new American bike,''
Durkin said. The first Victory rolled out of the company's Spirit
Lake, Iowa, finishing plant just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The relay was organized by Durkin, known better to co-workers at
Sprint ION as Raymond Durkin. Riders left June 23 from Victory,
N.Y., and will end July 4 in San Francisco. (Victory, N.Y., isn't
on the Victory Highway, but it seemed to fit.) Riders meet the
relay team at restaurants, Victory dealerships and cities along the
way of the 11-leg journey.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Durkin said, he is looking forward to sharing
the road with another Victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot in common,'' Durkin said of the relay members.
``What we have in common is that we're all early adopters, we're
chance-takers.''
</P>
<P>
   Each morning the group passes a baton and a souvenir bag from
team to team. By the time the baton _ custom-made by Victory
machinists _ makes it to San Francisco, it will have passed through
the hands of guys called Spike, Roadkill and Sparky Bill, and
through the paws of Blaze, a Pomeranian dog that rode in a knapsack
with a special safety chain.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the bag reached Kansas City, there were notes from
riders and machinists at the two Victory factories and company
keepsakes. The Kansas City group added a Victory Highway Map from
the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after the first Victory motorcycle was produced, a
handful of people, including Durkin, began swapping stories in
Internet chat rooms about custom-made parts, paint detail and
motorcycle rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turning out to be a tight-knit little community,'' Durkin
said. ``We've been talking to each other for so long. We all wanted
to meet each other.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of brainstorming, the Victory Highway was the
natural choice for that meeting. Durkin and his wife, Trish,
discovered a small Kansas City, Kan., restaurant called the Victory
Junction Restaurant that would become the focal point for the
relay. But it was the menu that really piqued their curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It told about the Victory Highway and we said, what about a
Victory ride on the Victory Highway?'' Trish Durkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The group of bikers has been researching the historic highway
ever since. They pooled their money to buy historic maps and
information on the road. If they have anything to say about it, the
roadway won't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people out there talking about this old
road they've never seen,'' Trish Durkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Several also set out to see it for themselves before the trip
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some towns have died off, but there's still roads there. Back
in the old days it was the way to get through Kansas City,'' she
said. ``You see old gas stations, you see the markets that survived
and the churches with no houses around them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the maps, the highway was built in the 1920s and
honors World War I veterans. The highway has long since been
forgotten, but it is said to be one of the first paved roads to
stretch from coast to coast. Dated maps provide detailed
descriptions for points of interest along the way, including the
Victory Junction Restaurant. The road generally follows U.S. 40,
with a few exceptions, but the bikers reported that only a few
scattered signs remain.
</P>
<P>
   The group's energy has stirred a curious eye from the motorcycle
maker's parent company, Polaris Industries in Medina, Minn. The
$1.3 billion company is known for its snowmobiles, all-terrain
vehicles and personal watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Laskin, Victory product manager, thinks the riders' pride
and energy comes from buying an American product.
</P>
<P>
   The company donated T-shirts and other keepsakes but has watched
from the wayside as club members organize and carry out the
cross-country tour.
</P>
<P>
   Laskin would not release the company's sales figures, but said
that more than 3,000 motorcycles had been produced since fall 1999.
The company's nearest rivals are Japanese manufacturers and
Harley-Davidson, which has a plant in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the first American mass-production motorcycle to enter
the market in over 50 years,'' Laskin said. ``There's an obvious
pride of owning a Victory motorcycle.''
</P>
<P>
   If industry leaders are curious about the company's future,
Laskin said they need only look at the tattoos on the riders' arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only a few motorcycle brands that can make that
claim,'' he said. ``That's brand loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   As the club has grown from five to 520 members, the Durkins are
hoping the company and its popularity will grow just as the
Harley-Davidson empire has for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kinship we feel with the Victory group is the same kinship
the Harley riders must feel,'' Trish Durkin said. ``There's
something to be said about buying an American-made motorcycle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 0106EDT &QL; 
