<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-SUSPENSIO     06-30 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-SUSPENSIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWELVE DODGERS SUSPENSIONS OVERTURNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers' confidence in the appeals process was
rewarded Thursday when it was announced the suspensions of 11
players and third-base coach Glenn Hoffman were overturned by Paul
Beeston, chief operating officer of the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   However, keeping the Dodgers from complete elation were the
suspensions that were upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Chad Kreuter's eight-game suspension and the five-game
suspensions of Gary Sheffield, F.P. Santangelo and Carlos Perez
remain intact, as did their $5,000 fines. Right-hander Mike Fetters
had his suspensions reduced from four games to one and was fined,
but the issue is not over.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter was slated to serve his suspension beginning with
Thursday's game against San Diego, but his suspension was
immediately appealed. Representatives of the players association
are expected to meet today and file appeals on the four other
suspended players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happier,'' Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob
Daly said. ``I don't think this will have any major effect at all
on the pennant race. I think last time it could have had a major
effect. In that regard, if you want to call that a victory, then
call that a victory. Now, I think it will have a slight effect but
not a major effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The original suspensions, handed down eight days after the May
16 fight with fans at Chicago's Wrigley Field, totaled 89 games and
$77,000. Each of the fines remained intact, but the number of games
lost were cut to 45. Players were originally suspended by Frank
Robinson, vice president of on-field operations for baseball, for
60 games. After hearing appeals last week in Houston, Beeston
trimmed that to 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were most upset about Sheffield's suspension,
especially since the All-Star left fielder gave what insiders
termed an emotional speech to Beeston at the appeals hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my teammates were in danger, and I was trying to get
them out of danger,'' Sheffield said. ``If the same thing happened,
I'd do it all over again. I wouldn't change a thing. If you don't
have anything to do with it, the first thing you do is protect your
teammates, make sure nobody gets hurt. When you do that, and get
punished for it, I don't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeston also set up the schedule to serve the suspensions.
Kreuter was to be followed by Sheffield (July 8), Perez (July 16),
Santangelo (July 21) and Fetters (July 22), though that's on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Sheff for even one game, it's tough,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``Like I said, he's my best player. ... I don't
like to lose any of them, but I hate for him to be out.''
</P>
<P>
   MLB spokesman Richard Levin was asked what the decision meant to
Robinson's power and how much confidence people will have in
Robinson in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's open to your interpretation,'' Levin said. ``Paul's
role is a sort of an appeals court. After talkin to the players in
Houston, the decision was the punishment should be reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Orza, associate general counsel of the players association,
said appealing each of the remaining suspensions wasn't a given.
However, Kreuter's appeal will be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that Paul saw the light in overturning the
suspensions of the 11 players, but I'm unhappy the light went off
when it came to the other five players,'' Orza said. ``Frank
originally suspended each player that went in the stands three
games, and the players that got three games had their suspensions
cut. Chad's suspension and the remaining suspensions should be cut
by three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Who hears the next set of appeals must be decided. Usually, it
would fall under commissioner Bud Selig, but the players
association is likely to ask for an independent arbitrator. If
they're not given one, a grievance could be filed to take it to an
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the players originally given three-game suspensions had
it wiped out, including reliever Alan Mills, since traded to
Baltimore. Also escaping game punishment were Terry Adams, Darren
Dreifort, Eric Gagne, Onan Masaoka, Antonio Osuna, Chan Ho Park,
Geronimo Berroa, Shawn Green, Todd Hundley and Eric Karros. Each
were fined $3,000, which was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I saw the tape, the more I thought everyone was
acting in a manner to get the situation under control,'' Green
said. ``We're in a lot better shape, but when you lose Sheff for
five games, not to mention the other guys, it's still something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
