<SLUG> BC-BABY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN NEWBORNS CAN BE TESTED FOR HEARING LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID KLEPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley Gorrell gently placed the sensor against 3-day-old
Calyssa's forehead. Minutes later, the test Gorrell has performed
reveals nothing amiss with Calyssa's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is obvious in Gorrell's smile. Deaf since
adolescence, Gorrell knows full well the hurdles posed by hearing
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Gorrell volunteers at Research Medical Center, where she tests
infants for hearing loss. She performed her first test Thursday,
using high-tech equipment to evaluate an infant's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The tests done by Gorrell and other volunteers will become
especially relevant Jan. 1, 2002, when Missouri will begin
requiring hearing loss tests for all newborns. Kansas will require
the tests beginning Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The tests alert parents and physicians to early hearing loss and
allow them extra time to prepare for the challenges of raising deaf
children. Detecting hearing loss in newborns is vital if parents
are to prepare for the linguistic and social obstacles that lie
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's good to find out early,'' Gorrell said.
``If they are deaf, it's very important to get an early start.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorrell lives in Olathe, where for years she was a teaching
aide. When she retired, she looked for something to keep her
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering to help with the medical center's newborn hearing
tests was an easy call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an ad in the paper, and I thought it sounded very
interesting. I like doing things worthwhile,'' Gorrell said. ``But
I didn't know if they'd let a deaf person do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorrell, as it turned out, was perfect for the job. Because her
patients are notoriously bad at following instructions, the test
relies on brain wave analysis. A good bedside manner, warm hands
and computer skills are all that's required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies don't talk,'' she said. ``So I do just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorrell learned how to administer the screening with several
other volunteers. She mastered the computer skills. She learned how
to attach the adhesive sensors that monitor the baby's brain
activity.
</P>
<P>
   During the test, clicking noises are produced in a headset
secured over the infant's ears. A nearby computer uses the sensors
to analyze the infant's brain waves. Differences in brain waves
indicate whether the infant heard the noise. The test is painless _
Calyssa slept through the event _ and usually takes less than 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started as a doctor, 31 years ago, plugging a baby into
a computer was science fiction,'' said Dan Bender, supervising
physician for audiology at Health Midwest, which operates Research
and other area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The test is sensitive enough to detect even slight hearing loss.
That, and its ability to test patients who can't yet talk, makes it
a powerful diagnostic tool, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crucial to catch hearing loss early,'' he said. ``If you
don't, it will affect their reading ability, their linguistic
skills _ just about every stage of development.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as six of every 1,000 children are born with significant
hearing loss. Causes include heredity, prenatal infection,
premature birth and side effects from prenatal medication.
</P>
<P>
   If hearing problems are caught in time, Bender said, parents,
teachers and physicians can prepare children to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gorrell is quick to point out that deafness hasn't kept her
from helping others who might share her silent world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deafness is not really a handicap,'' she said. ``I wanted to
do this, and here I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
