<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY BREAKS DECADES OF SILENCE FOR DEAF MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARTELLARO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His wife's lips quivered. His mother dabbed with a tissue at the
corner of her eye. And for the first time in his 30 years, Jason
Curry lowered his voice.
</P>
<P>
   It took him a few moments to figure out how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Deaf since birth, Curry never could tell how loud his voice was.
Not until Thursday, when a microprocessor turned him into a hearing
person for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The processor transmits digital simulations of sound through a
surgically implanted electrode, called a cochlear implant, to
stimulate nerve endings in the inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, of Kansas City, had the electrode implanted weeks ago. On
Thursday, after waiting for the standard swelling and inflammation
to heal, Curry, his wife and parents and about a dozen more family
members and friends gathered to see it turned on for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   They waited for about 45 agonizing minutes while Barbara
Luikart, supervisor of clinical services at the Midwest Ear
Institute at Trinity Lutheran Hospital, painstakingly programmed
and adjusted his processor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to realize that this is going to be quite
overwhelming,'' Luikart said, moments before turning on the
implant, as Curry's wife, Missy, translated into sign language.
``Just try to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch was flipped. Luikart's was the first voice he heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you hear my voice right now?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hear,'' he responded _ followed immediately by a wince,
a shake of his head and an embarrassed smile. Like that of many
deaf persons, Curry's speaking voice is loud.
</P>
<P>
   While Luikart showed Curry how to adjust the volume control on
the processor, family members took turns greeting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Jason,'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Jason, this is Mom,'' said his mother, Emma Curry of
Sedalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Jason,'' said his brother David Curry of Springfield.
``Now you know how damn loud you are all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brother Douglas Curry of Lee's Summit added, ``Welcome to my
wonderful voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jason told them all, ``I can't believe you have all put
up with my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Curry could hear the words, all of the statements were
still translated into sign language. While the processor worked,
sending the sounds directly to Curry's brain, they ran into a major
roadblock once they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He still has to train his brain to understand them. That will
take a long time and a lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Getting the message  &LR; tx:Jason Curry was born deaf July 22,
1969. His mother realized it when he was 11 months old. She banged
some pans together just behind his head, and he did not react.
</P>
<P>
   Many deaf children and their parents immerse themselves in deaf
culture, learning American Sign Language and attending schools for
the deaf. The Curry family chose a different path.
</P>
<P>
   Jason started speech therapy at 13 months of age. When he was 4,
he and his family learned Signing Exact English, a different
language from American Sign Language and one that Jason said more
closely approximates spoken English.
</P>
<P>
   Jason was enrolled in public schools, and his mother went to
school every week to conduct sign language classes for the students
so they could interact with Jason.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first deaf student to attend Central Missouri State
University, where he earned a bachelor's degree in business
administration. He was invited to join the Sigma Nu fraternity and
was the first deaf member in the organization's history nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   He met Missy, who has normal hearing, while he was attending
CMSU and she was at the University of Missouri-Kansas City. He now
works as a financial analyst for the U.S. General Services
Administration while trying to build his sideline as a motivational
speaker into a full-time career.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as a deaf-since-birth 30-year-old, Jason Curry is once
again a pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Luetje, Jason's surgeon and a leader in the field of
cochlear implants, said the procedure usually has its best results
with other types of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Children younger than 5, whose brains are still developing
language ability, can have ``spectacular'' successes with the
implants as their brains become hard-wired to the simulated sounds
they hear, Luetje said. And older people who had normal hearing but
lost it through accident or illness can learn over time to adjust
the auditory centers of their brains to react to the new sounds
produced by the implant.
</P>
<P>
   But patients like Curry don't have the still-developing brains
of children or the auditory frame of reference of those who used to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   They face a long, hard road as they try to learn so many things
the hearing take for granted _ to tell a knock on a door from a
footstep on the floor, never mind the hundreds of thousands of
minute variations that make up human speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to try it, and I don't want to deny anybody the
possibility of improvement in their quality of life,'' Luetje said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every patient hopes deep down that they will be able to
understand the spoken word. And I don't know that he won't be able
to do that. But based on past experience, I have doubts that will
become a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry said he wanted to make the attempt because, although he
was born deaf, ``I'm psychologically and culturally a hearing
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision from my heart to do this, because I wanted
to sit in the back yard and listen to the birds chirping and frogs
ribbiting. One of the things I've always wanted to do was drive
across an old bridge that makes a creaking noise,'' he said. ``I am
a motivational speaker, and my goal is to do this full time at some
point, because I want to get my message across to people and make
an impact on them in a positive way, and to move my life forward in
a positive way.''  &LR; brk:A new sensation  &LR; tx:``I feel it in my head,
not in my ears,'' Curry told Luikart.
</P>
<P>
   She said that was normal. Patients are often surprised when
their new hearing produces no real sensation within the ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing like what I thought,'' Curry said. But he had
known that would be the case. ``There's a part of my brain that
processes information that has been asleep for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Luikart said people who used to hear normally, then get cochlear
implants, often say the new sound has an electronic, synthesized
quality to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their brains quickly adapt to the new sound,'' Luikart said.
``It's all they know, so it becomes their `normal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Curry vowed to ``break all the (learning) curves for people who
were born deaf,'' and Luikart wasn't inclined to doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most motivated people I've ever met in my
whole life,'' she said. ``If anybody is going to do it, he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry, meanwhile, just kept marveling at the wonder of sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed it was going to be like this,'' he said.
``It's mind-boggling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
