<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE COMMISSIONER DENIES ANY WRONGDOING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ A day after his hasty resignation, Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush denied any wrongdoing, even as a
state criminal probe widened to include one of his former top
aides.
<P>
   Former Deputy Commissioner George Grays, who Thursday became the
first person named in the attorney general's criminal
investigation, was allegedly part of a kickback scheme that
funneled money into his own pocket, sources told The Chronicle
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Attorney General Bill Lockyer's office went to
court to force the Department of Insurance to comply with subpoenas
demanding six years of documents dealing with four foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush submitted his resignation Wednesday, avoiding almost
certain impeachment and Thursday's scheduled testimony before the
Legislature. But his resignation _ which is effective July 10 _
does not shield him from criminal and civil probes.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush said he left to ``clear the cloud hanging over the
department,'' not because of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political world up here, and politics is always part
of it,'' Quackenbush told the Northern California News Satellite
service. ``But it's the world we live in. The situation called on
me to move on and the department to get back to being
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislators were investigating Quackenbush's decision to let a
half-dozen insurers avoid up to $3 billion in fines for mishandling
Northridge earthquake claims by giving about $12 million to
nonprofit foundations he created.
</P>
<P>
   One of the foundations, the California Research and Assistance
Fund, was supposed to spend the money to help consumers with
earthquake claims and finance quake-damage research.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, much of the money went to public-service television ads
highlighting Quackenbush and to groups with no connection to quake
issues but direct links to people in the state Insurance
Department. The Legislature is preparing a final report and will
turn its information over to the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer's office has named Grays, who resigned last April, as
the man who ran the fund from inside the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have obtained materials showing check payments to Mr. Grays
that raise very serious questions,'' said Sandy Michioku, a
spokeswoman for Lockyer.
</P>
<P>
   Sources told The Chronicle that Grays and B.T. Thompson,
director of the Skillz Athletic Foundation, allegedly conducted a
kickback scheme, channeling money from the fund into their own
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Skillz _ a football camp in Sacramento that two of Quackenbush's
children attended _ received $263,000 from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Grays then received nine $10,000 checks from Skillz, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Thompson acquired an ATM card for the account the
fund's money was in and began withdrawing $300 every day, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grays' attorney did not return phone calls Thursday. On Monday,
Grays took the Fifth Amendment when he was questioned by the
Assembly Insurance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, Lockyer went to court Thursday to
force the Department of Insurance to turn over documents relating
to four foundations, including CRAF, a title insurance fund and a
foundation for holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena requested 71 categories of documents dating back to
Jan. 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After being served with the subpoena, senior officials in the
department failed to respond, return phone calls or establish an
agreement under which the materials would be turned over.
</P>
<P>
   More than two weeks late, the department sent 700 pages,
something the attorney general's office described as ``a grossly
inadequate response.''
</P>
<P>
   No court date has been set for a hearing. A spokesman for the
department said every effort was being made to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's legal staff has worked arduously to comply
with the 71-part subpoena and if further information is needed, the
department will continue to cooperate fully,'' said Scott Edelen, a
spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, interviewed in his office dressed in khakis and a
golf shirt, said he thinks victims of the Northridge quake got a
fair deal from his department.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than $15 billion was paid out to the victims of the
Northridge earthquake over the years,'' he said. ``We got another
$78 million over that. There are only a handful of claims left out
there, and most of them are tied up in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush said there are ``misperceptions'' about the
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature investigated something that seemed unusual to
them,'' he said. ``Some of those perceptions came out of heavy
inaccuracies, but I didn't think California should have to go
through more of such a long process.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush also addressed one of the hot questions in
Sacramento Thursday _ whether the insurance commissioner should
remain an elected post or revert to being appointed by the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be an appointed position,'' he said. ``I
think having someone who isn't involved in politics is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters made the insurance commissioner's post an elected
position in 1988 when they approved Proposition 103.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the legislators who were part of the committee
investigating Quackenbush agreed Thursday, saying the mix of
regulator and politician is a poisonous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are subject to constant demands for prodigious
fund-raising,'' said Republican Assemblyman Tom McClintock of
Northridge. ``They are subject to many political considerations
that are very dangerous when combined with the responsibility to
impartially enforce the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Jack Scott, D-Altadena, said he is not convinced
the voters should be taken out of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Voters) decided in Proposition 103 that they wanted it an
elected office,'' he said. ``I doubt seriously that they will want
to take away that right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
