A9099 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-INSURANCE-SETTLEMENTS     06-30 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-SETTLEMENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IN THE WAKE OF QUACKENBUSH RESIGNATION, SETTLEMENTS POSSIBLE  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The downfall of Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush raises
the possibility that tens of thousands of Northridge earthquake
victims who were cheated out of property-damage settlements might
get some of the money after all.
</P>
<P>
   Such an outcome is by no means certain. Thorny legal issues are
involved, such as the validity of contracts between the Insurance
Department and the insurance companies and application of the
statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned his elected office Wednesday to avoid
testifying under oath before the Assembly Insurance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings before the committee previously had disclosed that
Quackenbush allowed insurance companies to avoid as much as $3.7
billion in Northridge-related fines by paying a relatively trifling
$12 million into nonprofit foundations he created. The companies
faced the fines for allegedly mishandling policyholder claims in
the wake of the January 1994 quake.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Scott, D-Pasadena, chairman of the Assembly Insurance
Committee, said a bill before the committee would require the
Quackenbush-created foundations to distribute $6 million in unspent
funds to the earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said the Assembly also is looking at ways to force the
companies to pay the fines they avoided and any rightful claims
they withheld. But he said this could prove difficult or
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contracts are contracts,'' he observed, ``and it was a
contract duly signed by the state of California in the person of
Chuck Quackenbush and the insurance industry. So I'm not sure you
can un-ring that bell, but I know that if it is possible, we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott also advised Northridge quake victims who think they were
cheated to file private lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   One potential stumbling block, however, is the statute of
limitations that applies to insurance claims. Policyholders can sue
their insurance companies for dealings in bad faith or breach of
contract, but only within limited time periods.
</P>
<P>
   The statute of limitations for bad faith expires after two
years, while the statute for breach of contract expires after four
years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of INSURE30 (100056 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although the Northridge quake happened more than six years ago,
there may be time in some cases, said San Francisco attorney Ray
Bourhis, who specializes in consumer cases against insurance
companies. He pointed out that the two- and four-year periods
generally begin only after the victim becomes aware of the
victimization.
</P>
<P>
   Bourhis also held out hope that the settlements between the
companies and Quackenbush can be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Can the new insurance commissioner reopen an
inquiry into company violations?'' he said. ``You may very well be
able to do that by making a motion in court to set aside the
agreements, on the basis that they were obtained by a conspiracy
between the Insurance Department and the companies. I predict that
the agreements will be set aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sirola, a spokesman for State Farm, the largest homeowners
insurance vendor in California and a party to the settlements, said
his company's lawyers have pondered that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the authority and power of the commissioner, our people
seem to think there's nothing that says he can't reopen the
settlements, but they're just not sure,'' Sirola said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Lynda Gledhill contributed to this
report.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of INSURE30 (100056 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
