<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-MEXICO-PRI-SFCHRON &LR;      06-30 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VOTE-BUYING CLAIMS TARNISH END OF RACE  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO JUXTLAHUACA, Mexico _ When Oaxaca state Gov. Jose Murat
came to this mountain town recently to give some well-timed aid to
poor local farmers, he was greeted with lots of smiles.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1,377 people who got an average of $72 each, the money
came at just the right moment _ the start of the rainy season _ to
help with planting corn, beans and wheat on their tiny farms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that Sunday's federal elections were only
two weeks away was lost on no one.
</P>
<P>
   As Murat's Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) fights
desperately to keep its 71-year hold on the presidency and to
regain control of Congress, it appears to be spending unprecedented
amounts on anti-poverty programs and outright giveaways to gain
votes from the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The handouts range from bicycles to tin roofs, and they often
come with not-so-subtle hints that the recipients should vote for
the PRI. Together with instances of PRI coercion, these practices
have begun to tarnish the credibility of an election campaign that
had been billed as the fairest in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Is the PRI engaging in vote-buying on a vast scale, as critics
say? If so, a victory by PRI candidate Francisco Labastida _ who is
running almost in a dead heat with PAN candidate Vicente Fox _ may
be challenged as fraudulent, plunging Mexico into an extended
period of post-election turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Or is the PRI legitimately enjoying the powers of incumbency,
using the few legal loopholes left in an electoral system that even
PRI opponents admit has been transformed by recent reforms from a
notoriously corrupt one to a process protected by a host of
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with dozens of peasants, Indian leaders, government
officials and election observers suggest that the questions must be
viewed in light of Mexico's poverty and cultural beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, among the country's Indian groups, which comprise
10 percent of the country's 97 million population and most of its
extreme poor, government aid is viewed as conferring a moral
obligation on the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think that if they are given something, they're in
debt to the person who gave it to us,'' said Olga Quiroz, a Mixtec
Indian near Santiago Juxtlahuaca who received a no-collateral
government loan and also gets other aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's so hard for many of the people around here to
vote against the PRI. We can't just pocket (the aid) and go vote
for the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Doling out money, food and other goods is not strictly illegal.
But it is unlawful to tie the handouts to votes. It's also
off-limits for public officials to use their position or government
resources to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Raul de los Santos, who directs a statewide voter-education
campaign, says election ``fairness'' is not necessarily a legal
matter: ``There are deep cultural reasons why rural people in
Oaxaca and elsewhere are susceptible to practices that aren't
necessarily illegal but that do distort the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   In Santiago Juxtlahuaca town hall, where the PRI holds sway,
Vice Mayor Francisco Beristain smiled as he said his party expects
to win the region Sunday despite growing support for opposition
parties. ``The loans definitely help us with people, as well as all
the other programs that we give. The people see that their
interests are guaranteed by the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, government social programs give badly needed aid to huge
numbers of poor people. The two largest such programs are Progresa,
which gives money to about 2.6 million poor  &LR; rural women who agree
to keep their children in school and take them to regular medical
checkups, and Procampo, which assists 2.9 million farmers with
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   But election observers and opposition parties say the PRI's
campaign is pushing _ or outright exceeding _ the boundaries of
what's legal. Among the examples they cite are:
</P>
<P>
   -- Since April 1, President Ernesto Zedillo has sped up the pace
of public works programs, inaugurating projects around the country
worth an estimated $435 million. Zedillo ignored a call from the
independent, highly respected Federal Election Institute, which is
overseeing the voting, to cancel advertising of government programs
in the final weeks before the election. Every day during the
campaign (which ended Wednesday), leading television and radio
programs were punctuated by ads from the presidency and federal
Cabinet agencies touting the successes of government programs. The
ads often ran back-to-back with ads for &LR;   &LR; those of PRI candidates.
Major newspapers and newsmagazines were full of similar, full-page
displays.
</P>
<P>
   -- In recent weeks, Yucatan state Gov. Victor Cervera traveled
to remote rural villages to personally deliver thousands of washing
machines, water pumps, fumigators, tin roofs, machetes, rolls of
barbed wire, bicycles _ all stamped with the emblem of his
government _ to PRI supporters.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Tabasco state, officials appeared suddenly with disaster
relief, which had been delayed since floods in October, and paid
homeowners who support the PRI $600 each while paying opposition
backers $200.
</P>
<P>
   -- Welfare mothers and corn farmers in 13 states have reported
being told by officials that their cash payments will be cut off
unless they pledge to vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   -- Workers at the national oil monopoly Pemex have complained
that  &LR; said their bosses threatened to fire them unless they
campaign for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   -- The nation's private media recently reverted to their
traditional pro-PRI bias. A Federal Election Institute survey
released Monday said that this month, Fox received 70 percent of
all coverage with a negative spin, compared to 30 percent earlier.
Meanwhile, the PRI's share of negative coverage dropped from 60
percent early last month to just 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, a congressional commission to review charges of
illegal campaign activity had received 144 complaints of
vote-buying and coercion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign appears to be marred by a growing and disturbing
amount of corruption, coercion and vote-buying,'' said Silvia
Alonso, president of Civic Alliance, an election watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   But the extent of illegal activity may be in the eye of the
beholder.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all observers agree that this year's election appears
likely to be Mexico's fairest ever. The system is much more
fraud-proof and equitable than during the infamous 1988 vote, when
Interior Ministry officials were widely believed to have used a
suspicious, election-night computer crash to give victory to PRI
candidate Carlos Salinas. Before the crash, Salinas had been
trailing leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who is running for
president again this year but is lagging in third place in opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, because of reforms enacted in 1997, Mexico's election
system is in some ways one of the fairest in the developing world,
election observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Mexico has spent billions of dollars to compile a reliable
list of eligible voters, issue 60 million photographic voting
credentials, train nearly 800,000 civilian poll watchers and
provide safeguards that include transparent ballot boxes and
curtained voting booths.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Federal Election Institute has been removed from Interior
Ministry control and converted into a nonpartisan, highly
professional body that is praised by all candidates as well as
Mexican and foreign observers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nearly $400 million in public campaign financing has been
provided to the major parties. This step has gone a long way toward
reducing the PRI's traditionally overwhelming edge in campaign
spending. The five-party coalition backing Cardenas, for example,
was given $109 million _ allowing Cardenas to blanket the airwaves
with advertisements, even in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   -- Opposition parties reported last week that their
representatives would observe balloting at all 113,000 polling
places.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these efforts, many opposition leaders and activists
remain deeply suspicious of the PRI, even when they can't put their
finger on evidence.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, for example, an official from Civic Alliance,
Mexico's main independent observer organization, took a Chronicle
reporter and photographer on a 12-hour tour of the enormous, dusty
slums stretching east of Mexico City _ a trip, he promised, that
would display many cases of coercion and vote-buying.
</P>
<P>
   Although plenty of hearsay accounts of such practices were
relayed by people interviewed in their homes and on the street, and
although several residents expressed fear of discussing their
experiences with government aid administrators, no direct proof was
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Woldenberg, head of the Federal Election Institute, has
said that reports of vote-buying are exaggerated and that even if
somebody bought 400,000 votes _ ``a deliriously high figure'' _ it
would represent only about 1 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   One percent may not seem like much, but it could be enough to
throw the election to Labastida in his neck-and-neck race with Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox warned earlier this month that he may not accept a Labastida
victory if the margin is less than 10 percentage points, prompting
Labastida to retort: ``Those who are predicting fraud beforehand
are doing so merely to cover up their own defeat in free
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox has since backed off from the warning, he is still
threatening to lead a campaign of civic resistance if he loses by
fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
