r a BC-GUNS-COURT-SFCHRON &LR;      06-30 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-COURT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT WEAPON BAN IS UPHELD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court upheld the state's
1989 assault-weapons ban Thursday, a stinging defeat for the gun
industry that could lead to the prohibition of nearly 200 types of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   By a 6-to-1 vote, the high court said the law, which bans more
than 60 types of semiautomatic assault weapons, does not violate
the constitutional rights of gun owners. Justice Joyce Kennard
filed the sole dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 law, known as the Roberti-Roos Assault Weapons Control
Act, was the nation's first ban on assault weapons and served as
the model for regulations in other cities and states as well as a
federal ban in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gov. Gray Davis signed an amendment to the law
banning so-called ``copycat weapons,'' firearms designed with
slight modifications to skirt the original law. The addition made
the law the nation's most comprehensive gun regulation.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Bill Lockyer called Thursday's decision
``a major victory for gun safety and public safety in California.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling, he said, at least 120 types of
weapons, known as AR-15 or AK ``series'' weapons, will be added to
the list of banned firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge setback for the gun industry,'' said Luis Tolley,
western director of the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence, which
filed a brief supporting the law on behalf of the California Police
Chiefs Association cq  &LR; and several other law enforcement groups.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 1989 law and its 1999 amendment ``work very
effectively together to really close down loopholes to try to get
around the language.'' The amendment outlaws guns if they have
certain features, such as a detachable magazine and a pistol grip.
</P>
<P>
   Tolley said that a gunmaker could remove the offending feature
to get around the 1999 law, but the gun would still be subject to
the ban if it had been on the 1989 list.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Michel, one of the lawyers for the plaintiffs challenging
the law _ a group of taxpayers, gun collectors as well as gunmaker
Colt Industries _ said they might appeal the decision to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, he said, may create consumer uncertainty over which
weapons are legal and which ones are not. Further, it may not be
clear whether a weapon is covered by the 1989 ban or the 1999
amendment. ``There's already a tremendous amount of confusion among
police, lawyers and judges over what is or what is not an assault
weapon,'' Michel said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 law was passed by the Legislature after a crazed gunman
armed with an assault rifle sprayed a Stockton schoolyard with
bullets, killing five children and wounding 30 others.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the banned weapons, the law allows the state
attorney general to add to the list by getting the approval of a
Superior Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   The law was challenged after former state Attorney General Dan
Lungren attempted to add the Colt Sporter to the list.
</P>
<P>
   The gun manufacturer Colt Industries sued to overturn the law,
but a trial judge threw out the suit. In a dramatic move, a state
appeals court in 1998 struck down the law, ruling that it was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court in Sacramento said that the law violated the
equal protection laws because it arbitrarily singled out those gun
owners who owned a firearm that was on the list.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the state Supreme Court said states have broad
powers in regulating the gun industry. They rejected the argument
that gun owners are protected by a fundamental state constitutional
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If plaintiffs are implying that a right to bear arms is one of
the rights recognized in the California Constitution's declaration
of rights, they are simply wrong,'' wrote Justice Janice Rogers
Brown in the court opinion. ``No mention is made in it of a right
to bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   She also dismissed the notion that the 1989 ban by singling out
some gun owners and not others violates their to equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature here was under no illusion that the AWCA would
rid the streets of assault weapons in one fell swoop,'' she said.
``The step-by-step approach adopted here _ the list plus the add-on
provision _ does not violate principles of equal protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also rejected the argument that the law violated the
separation of powers requirement of the constitution by giving a
judge the final say on what firearms can be added to the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
