<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-MINETA-COMMERCE-SFCHR     06-30 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINETA-COMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NAMES MINETA TO COMMERCE POST, FIRST ASIAN AMERICAN
IN  JOB
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton named former California Rep. Norm
Mineta as his choice for secretary of commerce Thursday, making him
the first Asian American ever nominated for a Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta, a senior vice president at the Lockheed Martin Corp.,
called his appointment a triumph of the American dream, and
shrugged off concern that he is stepping in at the twilight of the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might say that the months remaining in this
administration are not a lot of time to make a difference in the
life our our nation, but I disagree,'' said Mineta, who passed up a
chance to become secretary of transportation in 1992. ``Six months
is a virtual eternity in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a century ago, Mineta was forced from his San Jose home
and, along with 120,000 other Japanese Americans, imprisoned in an
internment camp at the order of President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
Thursday, he stood in the Oval Office as the current president
called him a ``strong leader'' and a ``highly skilled negotiator''
who will ``play a critical role in keeping our economic strategy on
track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm Mineta's family story tells a lot about the promise of
the America dream,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the Senate, Mineta would succeed William Daley _
leaving to become chair of Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign _ as head of the 63,000-person department responsible for
tasks ranging from the promotion of American business abroad to
overseeing the census and the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be another first for Mineta. As mayor of San Jose
in the early 1970s, he was the first Asian American to head a big
city, and, as chairman of the House Transportation and Public Works
Committee, the first Asian American to run a major congressional
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by his family and former staff members, Mineta told
Clinton: ``The substance of your actions today must never be
underestimated or forgotten. Mr. President, you have the eternal
gratitude of not just Japanese Americans or Asian-Pacific
Americans, but, I believe, every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian Americans, who make up an estimated 5 percent of the
nation's population, have few representatives at the highest levels
of government. Washington Gov. Gary Locke, elected in 1996, is the
first governor of Chinese American descent. In Congress, only three
of the 435 House members are of Asian descent. Hawaii is the only
state with an Asian American senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nomination sends a signal to the country that Asian
Americans are a significant part of American society,'' said John
Tateishi, executive director of the Japanese American Citizens
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mineta's nomination has a really profound effect on the
perception of others. And for us, it tells us that we've ...
finally reached a point where we have a foot in mainstream
America.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also help repair relations between Democrats and Asian
Americans, some of whom have felt wrongly accused for the Democrats
fund-raising antics in 1996, which included illegal contributions
from foreign sources.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional staffers predicted a quick
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is well known and well respected on Capitol Hill and in the
Senate, and it bodes well for a speedy (confirmation) process,''
said John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he sees any obstacle in the Senate, where many Clinton
nominations have languished, Czwartacki said: ``Not one.''
</P>
<P>
   One GOP staff member said, ``It would be monumentally stupid to
stand in the way of the first Asian American Cabinet secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley has said he will leave his post on July 15. Administration
officials are hopeful they can secure Mineta's confirmation before
the Senate's August recess. If not, they are holding open the
possibility of a ``recess appointment'' that would temporarily
install Mineta in the post without Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta left Congress in the middle of his 10th term to accept a
job working on transportation issues for Lockheed Martin, the
nation's largest defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions were raised Thursday about how he would handle
matters regarding Lockheed at the Commerce Department. A White
House spokesman said Mineta would adhere to any relevant ethics
rules.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MINETA30 (107059 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In Congress, Mineta spent years garnering funds for freeway and
transit projects. But he is probably best remembered for his
efforts to secure reparation payments for the tens of thousands of
Japanese Americans who, like himself, were forced into internment
camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   When he left Congress in 1995, he was criticized by some public
interest groups for walking away in mid-term. His colleagues
withheld public criticism, even when his congressional seat was
taken over by Republican Tom Campbell in a special election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm thought he had left politics for good in 1995 when he
left Congress to work for Lockheed Martin,'' Clinton said Thursday,
``but politics and public service have a way of calling the best
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta has been courted by the Clinton administration before. He
was the president's top choice for secretary of transportation in
1992, but turned down the job so he could take over as chair of the
House Transportation Committee. He was also mentioned for Cabinet
posts at the start of Clinton's second term.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials contacted him within days of Daley's
announcement that he would leave the Commerce Department, sources
said. Mineta has a strong relationship with Gore, and many regard
him as a likely candidate for a Cabinet post if Gore wins the
presidency in November.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Mineta will ``play a crucial role in keeping our
economic strategy on track, opening trade around the world,
investing in our people, promoting high technology (and) bridging
the digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta did not discuss his possible agenda at the Commerce
Department, saying only that ``there is no more important task than
to further advance the policies that have brought us to this
triumph of economic performance and prosperity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
