<SLUG> BC-NY-WENDYS-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 INDICTED ON CHARGES OF MURDER AT WENDY'S
</HEADLINE>
  By EUN LEE KOH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two men charged in the execution-style slayings of
five workers at a Wendy's restaurant have been indicted by a grand
jury on multiple counts of first- and second-degree murder,
District Attorney Richard Brown of Queens announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he had not decided whether to seek the death penalty
for the men, John B. Taylor, 36, and Craig Godineaux, 30, and would
need to do a ``thorough and painstaking'' review of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a great deal of work to do before reaching that
decision,'' said Brown, who has 120 days from the arraignment,
scheduled for July 27, to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Godineaux have been charged with 50 counts of first-
and second-degree murder, attempted murder, robbery and weapons
possessions in the May 24 killings at the restaurant, on Main
Street in Flushing. The victims were bound and gagged, their heads
covered with plastic bags, then were marched into a freezer room
and shot one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Nazario, Anita C. Smith, Jean Dumel Auguste, Jeremy Mele
and Ibadat Ali were killed. Two other workers _ Jaquione Johnson
and Patrick Castro _ were critically injured but have since been
released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also was charged with tampering with evidence. Brown said
that Taylor took the keys to the restaurant and that he removed a
videotape from a surveillance camera there.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who have been held without bail since their arrest in
late May, have admitted to the murders in videotaped confessions,
in which they outlined plans to rob the restaurant and kill the
workers to eliminate witnesses, according to Gregory L. Lasak, the
lead prosecutor in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The confessions also include details of how the slayings were
carried out and how $2,400 in cash was stolen from the restaurant,
Lasak said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the survivors of the shootings has
identified the two suspects as the assailants, the authorities have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who had worked at the Wendy's before being fired in
October, tried to rob five fast-food restaurants last year, and had
been a fugitive since November for jumping bail, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Godineaux, who had worked as a security guard in a clothing
store, served three prison terms in the last decade for robbery and
drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has sought the death penalty in three cases since New
York's death penalty law was reinstated in 1995, according to Mary
de Bourbon, a spokeswoman for his office.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Brown sought the death penalty for James Allen
Gordon, who was convicted of murdering three women and seriously
injuring two others. Also that year, Brown sought the death penalty
for George Davis Bell, who was convicted of murdering an off-duty
police officer and the owner of a check cashing store.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Brown sought the death penalty for Steven Smelefsky,
who pleaded guilty to killing two people in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   All three received life in prison without parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
