<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     06-30 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
  
 SOX FLEX MIGHT, LEAVE ORIOLES IN THEIR WAKE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Some big bang back in their bats and Tim Wakefield's
flutterballs skipping and dipping like stones skimmed across the
Charles, the bedraggled Red Sox finally showed some life Thursday
in a 12-4 trouncing of the Orioles at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Daubach, his socks on display for a change of luck, belted
two homers and drove in six runs, leading a 16-hit barrage that
brought the Sox only their 13th win in their last 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   On a night that began with Pedro Martinez being placed on the
disabled list, the Sox saw Wakefield pitch into the seventh inning
with a shutout before yielding a three-run bomb to Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   For a club that has done little right over the better part of
six weeks, it was a return to their early-May days of shake,
rattle, and roll, when they were once 12 games over .500. The win
put them two over the break-even mark (38-36) and sent them off for
a Chicago-Minnesota trip with their self-esteem slightly restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahh . . . that was big for us,'' said manager Jimy Williams,
his club snapping a five-game losing streak. ``For (Wakefield) to
pitch like that, that was the key _ a big lift for us. It was big
for him, and the rest of our (pitching) staff _ the whole club.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield was on the plate all night, scattering seven hits
through six innings, only twice allowing runners to reach scoring
position. He didn't give up a walk. Only twice did Orioles hitters
work him to three balls. Making only his fourth start of the
season, it was an outing reminiscent of Wakefield's masterful
(never to be repeated?) 16-8 season here in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen needs a rest, big time,'' said Wakefield, who
provided the perfect respite for some of the tired-going-on-dead
arms among the relief corps. ``I've been out there. I know how
taxing it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sox' bats gave Wakefield plenty of comfort to go
out and go right at the Baltimore hitters. Daubach slammed the
first of his home runs in the second, a three-run shot off starter
Scott Erickson that sailed into the screen in left-center. Scott
Hatteberg belted a three-run blast of his own in the fifth inning,
helping to build a 7-0 lead, and Daubach added his solo blast in
the sixth to make it 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   A slight adjustment in his batting stride, as well as a fashion
statement that saw him show his red-white-and-blue socks,
contributed to Daubach's change of fortune at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since Double A ball have I done that,'' said Daubach,
referring to the hauled-up hose. ``I'm pretty sure they'll be up
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach drove in his fifth and sixth runs with an infield roller
in the eighth that went for a double. The night before, following
an 11-inning loss to the Orioles, the Sox locker room was full of
guys who said their luck had to change. One sure sign of fortune
taking a turn is a grounder back up the middle that first ricochets
off the pitcher, then eludes the second baseman and rolls to the
outfield for a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Sang Lee, the Korean reliever called up to fill Martinez's
roster spot, took over after Wakefield faltered in the eighth (a
walk, double, and Belle's blast). The lefthander gave up a Jeff
Conine pinch-hit homer, but otherwise pitched well (12 pitches, 7
strikes). John Wasdin closed it out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big win for us,'' said Williams. ``It really was.''
</P>
<P>
   With Martinez out of the rotation, and no starter yet named for
Saturday's game in Chicago (look for another call to the minors),
Wakefield likely can figure on living the starter's life for at
least a little while longer. He'll likely start Tuesday in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a heck of a game,'' said Williams. ``We will savor
the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Licking their wounds for a month-plus, the Sox finally had a
moment to lick their chops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not half the season is over,'' said Daubach. ``We get some
people back, get healthy . . . ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
