To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Undated) _ Special Report: For ages, nations
have dreamed of building invulnerable shields to protect themselves
from hostile forces. Now the Clinton administration and its
military advisers are trying again, this time with a limited
antimissile weapon they think will go a long way toward immunizing
the United States against attack at least from missiles launched by
adversaries like North Korea, Iran and Iraq. Officials at the
Pentagon and experts outside the government say this defense
technology has reached a new level of maturity, and they argue that
the combination of miniaturized electronics and high-speed rockets
can produce an agile, light-weight weapon that can find and ram an
incoming bomb at supersonic speed. But critics are skeptical. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-WOMEN (Mexico City) _ The macho, conservative world of
Mexican politics has finally begun to show off its more feminine
side as political parties battle as never before to win the votes
of women. Male strippers were hired to perform at one campaign
rally. Television ads raised questions about candidates'
relationships with their former wives, a subject long considered
taboo for public discussion. And the high-profile roles of
political wives and daughters this year in Mexico has signaled a
new opening for women's issues in government. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-JEWS (Hamadan) _ This is where Esther, the Jewish queen of
Persia, is reputed to be buried, a town once a center of Jewish
life. Now there are 35 Jews left. Here, as elsewhere in Iran, a
once-thriving community is worried. A verdict is expected Saturday
in the spy trial of 13 Jews in the Iranian city of Shiraz and,
according to Jewish leaders, the case has made life so unsettled
that up to half of the remaining Iranan Jews will emigrate in the
next year or so. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Havana) _ Despite triumphal headlines, Cubans were
quickly reminded that Elian Gonzalez's return was just the
beginning of renewed efforts by Cuban officials who want to see an
end to a U.S. trade embargo. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-RIGHTS (Undated) _ A day after the Supreme Court
effectively struck down bans on a medical procedure its opponents
call ``partial birth abortion.'' lawmakers and other supporters of
the bans say they are already planning a new generation of laws
that they hope will withstand further legal challenges. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION-DOCTORS (Undated) _ Doctors who do abortions as
part of their regular medical practice said Thursday that they were
greatly relieved by the decision of the Supreme Court that the
government cannot prohibit doctors from performing a procedure that
opponents call partial-birth abortion. They said that laws
attempting to ban the procedure were so vague that doctors
performing most any abortion could be prosecuted under them. By
Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-LOBBY (Washington) _ After dominating the U.S. policy
debate over Cuba for nearly two decades, Cuban-American advocates
of a hard-line stance toward Havana find themselves on the
defensive, increasingly estranged from other Americans, according
to supporters and critics. As a result, the Cuban American National
Foundation, the preeminent exile lobby, is reorganizing its
leadership to include younger faces and today appointed a non-Cuban
former State Department expert on Cuba to head its Washington
office. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENRON (Dallas) _ Enron, the Texas energy company, is George
W. Bush's biggest political benefactor, having donated $550,000 to
his campaigns. Bush, in turn, has gone to bat for the company in
Texas and Washington, where it has a growing list of legislative
interests. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AIRCRAFT (Lod, Israel) _ In the past 15 years, Israel
Aircraft Industries, a military contractor, has been built from
bankruptcy into an export-driven powerhouse. A major contract it
signed with China to convert an Ilyushin into a modern radar plane
showcased the company's strengths. But if the Pentagon has its way,
the converted Ilyushin will never get to China. By William A. Orme
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-COSTS (Undated) _ A politically potent coalition of 69
health plans, several large employers, unions and consumer
advocates is beginning a broad campaign to slow the surge in
spending on prescription drugs. They hope to counter drug makers'
huge marketing and advertising campaigns directed at doctors and
consumers. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURES-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ The futures markets want to
trade ``single-stock futures,'' which in economic terms are
virtually identical to stocks. This week the House and Senate
Agriculture Committees unanimously approved bills to allow such
trading even though many regulatory issues remain unsettled. Once
they become legal, you will be able to buy single-stock futures by
putting up pennies on the dollar, in sharp contrast to the stock
market, where you have to put up half the purchase price. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
