<HEADLINE>
FALK TALKS OF NEW FUTURE WITH CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Go ahead. Rubs your eyes. Clean your ears.
</P>
<P>
   Three young first round NBA picks - Darius Miles, Keyon Dooling
and Quentin Richardson - sat in the Staples Center Thursday
afternoon, happy to be the future of the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   And afterward Clipper adversary David Falk, the agent for Miles
and Richardson, talked about a new future between himself and the
Clipper organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who always believes that you learn from your
experiences,'' Falk said. ``I hope we all learned something and
perhaps we can turn the page. It's a very positive day for the
Clippers.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk was at the Staples Center as the Clippers introduced their
three first round acquisitions: the third picks Miles, an
18-year-old high schooler; the 10th pick Dooling, a 20-year-old
point guard out of Missouri; and, the 18th pick Richardson, a
20-year-old swingman out of DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Falk in the same room at such an event, let alone talking
of working with the Clippers didn't seem likely last February.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a deal to send free agent forward Maurice Taylor to
the New York Knicks fell through. Falk blamed the Clippers. The
Clippers blamed Vancouver, a third team in the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Taylor situation is unfortunate,'' Falk said.
</P>
<P>
   Falk described the relationship the two sides as
``cantankerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The detente between the two sides appears mutual. Clipper vice
president of basketball operations Elgin Baylor said he is looking
past the Taylor situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the past,'' Baylor said. ``This is the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor added, ``The players weren't drafted because David
represents them. The players were drafted because they are talented
players. Dave and I have a good relationship. We've always had a
good relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The players want to be together and on the Clippers. They spent
the new conference laughing and joking in front of the Los Angeles
media.
</P>
<P>
   Miles, who had never been to Los Angeles before, said that
Falk's past relationship with the Clippers hasn't impacted his
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy...and (Falk) wants us to be happy because we're
his client,'' Miles said. ``I would love to rebuilt...it's shows
how strong I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk said a key in the rebuilding process is the selection of a
coach. Falk lobbied for John Lucas, Falk's first client and a
number one draft pick in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tremendous energy,'' Falk said. ``I think he is very
close to Odom as well. I think as a former player and a number one
pick in the draft and a thinking man's point guard I think he will
be an outstanding coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said that he has received and expects to receive more
interest in the coaching opening since the Clipper moves. But he
stopped short of saying that he is restarting the selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   The top candidates so far are Lucas and Clipper assistant coach
Dennis Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Without a new coach, Falk said that both Miles and Richardson
will play summer league in Chicago and not with the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   As Falk left he came over the Baylor and the two shook hands and
the two appeared ready to work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really fond of Elgin and I hope the Donald Sterling seizes
the opportunity Elgin has created to make this a positive change,''
Falk said. ``Only time will tell but this is a very strong first
step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
