<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HIV-MOM-LADN     06-30 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-MOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIV PARENTS TRY TO COPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SYLVIA L.OLIANDE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Keeping up with children is difficult enough,
but for the 62,000 parents who are HIV-positive, managing the
illness on top of that can bring a whole new set of difficulties,
according to a study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Susan Gutierrez, 37, an HIV-positive mom being treated at
UCLA, where the study was done. Gutierrez said distractions that
come with her two young daughters sometimes mean going the whole
day forgetting to take the handful of medicines she needs to stay
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see my pills when I'm washing the dishes and figure I'll
take them when I finish, but I don't finish them before I have to
run after (her older daughter) or change the baby,'' the Glendale
resident said. ``By the time I'm in bed, I remember, but I'm so
tired I don't get up to take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing out on medication is one of the many problems that hit
HIV-positive Americans who have children under age 18, according to
the UCLA and Rand Institute study being published in the American
Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 120,000 children have parents infected with the
virus, and the challenges of dealing with the disease, let alone
making ends meet when facing expensive but critical medical
treatments, are among the many faced by this forgotten corner of
the AIDS population, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen percent of parents surveyed who had sought treatment
for HIV stalled their own health care, primarily so they could
afford necessities for their children, said Dr. Mark A. Schuster, a
Rand researcher and UCLA pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   The consequence of putting off treatment, he said, is simply
that those parents might not live as long as they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are medications that can prolong their lives, but they
need to be taken regularly, and if they're not able to do that, it
could compromise their health,'' Schuster said. ``Lots of these
parents will live to see their children and their grandchildren,
but they need to take care of their health.''
</P>
<P>
   This first national study on families surveyed 2,864 adults
across the country who are undergoing treatment for HIV. It found
that 28 percent of those infected by the AIDS virus have children
under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Women were more likely than men to have children _ 60 percent of
the women vs. 18 percent of the men.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez contracted the virus more than five years ago, the
consequence of a 13-year heroin addiction. She learned she was
HIV-positive in October 1995, while undergoing treatment to get
clean.
</P>
<P>
   She said the first thing she did was pray to be able to have a
healthy child with her then-boyfriend Cesar, also 37, whom she
married last year. She has an 18-year-old daughter from a previous
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Rand-UCLA study found that, like Gutierrez, 12 percent of
women surveyed conceived and bore their children after a diagnosis.
But only 14 percent of those children tested positive for the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watch of UCLA's Clinical AIDS Research and Education
Center, daughter Ryanna was born in August 1997. The little girl is
HIV-negative. Soon after, the couple decided to have another child
and Rebecca was born six months ago _ also negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I had a healthy baby, I talked to the doctors and nurses
and wanted to get pregnant again,'' Gutierrez said. ``I don't know
what's going to happen to me. I didn't want to go out of this world
leaving my husband and (Ryanna) alone. I wanted to have a whole,
little family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rand-UCLA study showed that 76 percent of women and only 34
percent of men reported caring for their children, a disparity that
did not surprise the doctor. Schuster said these were likely men
who would not have been raising their children regardless of their
HIV status.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also found that 45 percent of those infected parents
showed symptoms of psychiatric disorders, 5 percent said they were
heavy drinkers and 10 percent required drug or alcohol treatment in
the previous six months. And like Gutierrez, 10 percent had a
history of drug dependency.
</P>
<P>
   But financial hardships were the primary concern reflected by
the 13 percent who did without medical care to afford necessities.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez, who does not have full-blown AIDS, worked until she
was laid off two weeks ago from her secretarial job, so the family
will have to adjust to living on Cesar's wages. She said she hasn't
considered what to do if they suddenly found themselves with
financial problems, adding they'd probably turn to their families.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster said 20 percent of those surveyed reported no close
friends and 16 percent said they saw family members once a month or
less. Sixty-seven percent of the parents had enrolled in at least
one government welfare program.
</P>
<P>
   The study recommends that any social or governmental planning to
deal with the epidemic in the future will have to consider the
impact on children of having parents with a chronic and potentially
fatal condition.
</P>
<P>
   An issue that needs to be looked into, Schuster said, is
discrimination. Often parents have to hide the fact they have the
virus and so aren't comfortable reaching out to friends or
families.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster said the most hopeful message of the survey is that
people are getting help, having families and are thought to be
living longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago, we would have been talking about these children
as orphans, losing their parents while they are still quite
young,'' he said. ``Now there are going to be children who are
orphans but many will grow up with their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
