<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO-DRLAURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUIOD OPENS 6TH SOUND STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you build it, they will come.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art Studios owners Robert Papazian and James Hirsch showed
their newest sound stage, Stage 6, built specifically for Dr. Laura
Schlessinger's talk show for Paramount Domestic Television.
</P>
<P>
   Taping for the daytime talk show is expected to begin next
month, said Daniel Tibbets, vice president of development for the
Canoga Park studio located in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The 15,000-square-foot sound stage, rated for an audience, took
eight months to build on 12 acres that used to be part of the
company's parking lot, Hirsch said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like this west of the 405 freeway,'' said
Hirsh, who is also one of the producers of ``Nash Bridges'' for
CBS. ``If a production company needs an audience-rated facility,
they have to drive to Paramount or CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Stage 6 was built for just under $4 million and can accommodate
an audience of 300 for each show, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new sound stage will help bring attention and high-wage jobs
to the west San Fernando Valley, predicted City Councilwoman Laura
Chick, whose 3rd District includes the studio site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts us on the map by making us a larger player in the
television and film production business,'' said Chick. ``It also
means a lot of good jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio, which employs 400 people, now has six sound stages
with wood floors, elephant doors, production facilities and a
full-service commissary, which can cater to all production needs
from prop food to production meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new sound stage is just the beginning for the studio, with
the ultimate goal being the establishment of a campus of creativity
in the West San Fernando Valley,'' said Hirsch. ``We want to make
Ray-Art an alternative to the major studios.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also has been laid for a seventh sound stage,
said Papazian.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art Studios is also a full-service production facility where
producers can create television shows, feature films and new media
productions from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian/Hirsch Entertainment purchased the 11-acre property on
Variel Avenue almost three years ago and has spent about $18
million upgrading and expanding the former Redken Laboratories
site.
</P>
<P>
   Spelling Entertainment occupies five of the sound stages to
shoot the WB television series ``Charmed.'' Other tenants have
included Warner Bros., Fox, MGM, NBC and Disney.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
