r f BC-FHS-HMO-LADN     06-30 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FHS-HMO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION HEALTH SYSTEMS TO CUT BACK MEDICARE COVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Foundation Health Systems Inc. said it will end
its Medicare-plus-Choice HMO coverage of 19,000 members in six
states, blaming the federal government's policies on
reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Haines, a spokeswoman with FHS, said Thursday a 2 &UR;  &LR; percent
reimbursement cap in these markets didn't cover the ever-increasing
costs of the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Dec. 31, Foundation Health members in 36 counties in
Arizona, California, Connecticut, Florida, New York and
Pennsylvania will no longer get coverage under the
Medicare-plus-Choice HMO product.
</P>
<P>
   In California, FHS subsidiary Health Net will cease offering its
Medicare HMO product in Fresno and Sonoma counties, affecting 3,200
Medicare enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both areas, we didn't have a lot of market share, which
makes it tougher from a negotiating standpoint with our
providers,'' Haines said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sonoma County, for example, for every $120 Health Net spends
treating a patient, the government reimburses the company $100, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Health Net will continue to provide Medicare coverage
in 20 California counties, including Los Angeles, Ventura, San
Bernardino and Riverside counties.
</P>
<P>
   FHS also announced that it would significantly reduce pharmacy
and other benefits in the majority of the 36 counties nationwide
where it will continue to offer a Medicare-plus-Choice product next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company was expected to increase supplemental
premiums in many of these counties, which could lead to further
attrition in its Medicare-plus-Choice program.
</P>
<P>
   Haines said the subsidiaries are contacting all affected
enrollees, physicians and employer groups, notifying them of these
decisions and informing them of other Medicare options for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   All of the health plans will work closely with their members to
ensure a smooth transition to another Medicare HMO or back to
traditional Medicare, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress passed the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, which
revised the way Medicare was funded, FHS health plans offering
Medicare HMO products have left 64 counties, affecting 38,000
enrollees nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Effective Jan. 1, FHS will have ceased offering its HMO product
in 82 counties, affecting 57,000 Medicare enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Woodland Hills-based Foundation Health Systems closed
up 0.31 cents to $14.31 on volume of 701,100 shares traded on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
