A9133 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DALAI-SHRINE-1stLd-LA     06-30 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAI-SHRINE-1stLd-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALAI OFFERS BLESSINGS FOR PEACE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Clarifies lede: first of its kind built...) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONNA HUFFAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ The Dalai Lama blessed a Tibetan-Buddhist
shrine at Forest Lawn Memorial Park on Thursday that is the first
of its kind built in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then, since even a Tibetan-Buddhist shrine blessing wouldn't be
complete in Los Angeles without a Hollywood celebrity, the Dalai
Lama appeared onstage with Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The exiled Tibetan leader spoke to more than 900 people gathered
at Forest Lawn's Hall of the Crucifixion-Resurrection in a
question-and-answer session hosted by the actress, an outspoken
advocate for the Tibetan cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``When affection is there, caring is there,'' the Dalai Lama
told the capacity crowd as he advised them to use their
intelligence positively, live holistically and open themselves to a
more positive existence. ``Automatically our minds become more
widened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barefoot and wearing a feather boa, the star of ``Basic
Instinct'' and ``Casino'' wondered beforehand how she would
introduce the religious leader, the 14th Dalai Lama, referring to
him as ``Mr. Please, please, please let me back into China'' and
``the hardest working man in spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old actress, who with her husband, Phil Bronstein,
recently adopted a baby boy, said one of the things gleaned from
Buddhism is empathy for one another and the complete freedom to
love another human being whom you have never met before.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama blessed the Shi-tro Mandala, which is being built
at Forest Lawn, in a private ceremony. The first three-dimensional
mandala to be created in the United States, it is one of only a few
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The intricately carved and brightly colored work by artist Pema
Namdol Thaye is dedicated to universal peace. Expected to be
completed in three months, it will be available for exhibition in
museums and other venues throughout the United States before it's
permanently installed at the Chagdud Gonpa center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Maxwell, executive director and co-founder of the local We
Care For Youth group, has been involved with the mandala since the
project began and helped bring it to Forest Lawn. At the
question-and-answer session, she praised the attendance of a group
of 22 teens from Camp Scott of the Los Angeles County Probation
Department, saying they would benefit from the Dalai Lama's
Buddhist teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you turn kids' minds to peace, they go there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the teens asked the Dalai Lama how she can keep herself
out of trouble when trouble is often brought to her.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing laughter, he told her, ``Life is not easy,'' then
suggested she take note of Jesus and other teachers of peace. After
encouraging the girl to build her self-confidence and fight life's
challenges with wisdom, knowledge and determination, he summoned
her to the dais. As she wiped away tears, they exchanged hugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, born in 1935 when Tibet was an independent
country, assumed leadership when he was 16, after the Communist
Chinese invaded Tibet. Nine years later, he was forced into exile
in India and his return has become an international cause.
</P>
<P>
   His teachings are revered by followers around the world. San
Diego residents Sara and David Hamilton have practiced Buddhism for
a few years and have seen the Dalai Lama several times. They
brought their 9-month-old daughter, Lila, on Thursday, saying it is
important to show support for his teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddhism is a really good place to put your mind. I love the
discussions, even if you can't hear everything because you're
running around after a baby,'' Sara Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
