<HEADLINE>
COSTLY LOSS FOR AVENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All the success enjoyed by Todd Marinovich the
past few weeks was bound to be balanced out at some point, and
Thursday night brought a devastating dose of adversity to the
Avengers and their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Marinovich sprained his foot in the second quarter and committed
two crucial errors near his own goal line as the Avengers had their
Arena Football playoff hopes all but destroyed by a 64-52 loss to
the Milwaukee Mustangs before 10,991 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Marinovich, the Arena League's player of the week after a
10-touchdown performance against Houston Friday, completed 22 of 34
attempts for 317 yards and seven touchdowns. But a lack of
protection from his offensive line left Marinovich under pressure
for much of the game and contributed to the two game-turning plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers trailed by five with less than a minute remaining
and had the ball at their own 10, but Marinovich couldn't handle
the snap from center Brett Clark. Milwaukee's Lincoln Coleman
recovered the fumble, and quarterback Kevin McDougal scored on a
9-yard draw to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to hear me blame Todd for anything,''
Avengers coach Stan Brock said. ``This is a team game, and Todd did
a great job out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The other crucial play came midway through the second quarter,
when fullback Brian Easter missed a block and Marinovich was sacked
near his own goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Avengers lineman Rob Stanavitch recovered the ball in his own
end zone for a safety, and the Mustangs scored on the ensuing drive
to take a 29-14 lead that the Avengers could not overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurts, there's no doubt,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers, who had big efforts from receivers Chris Jackson
(11 catches, 150 yards) and Travis Hannah (six catches, 121 yards)
fell to 3-9. Even though 12 of the Arena League's 17 teams make the
playoffs, this game was considered a must-win for the Avengers,
since they host division-leading San Jose next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loser of this game is toast,'' Milwaukee coach Rick
Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee improved to 4-7 and improved its playoff situation
significantly, thanks in large part to McDougal, the former Notre
Dame option quarterback who completed 22 of 34 attempts for 315
yards and eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal's 40-yard touchdown pass to Lamart Cooper with 5:18
remaining in the fourth quarter put the Mustangs up 57-45 and
appeared to seal the game. However, five minutes is plenty of time
to mount a rally in arena football and the Avengers nearly did it.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:24 remaining, Marinovich and Hannah connected on a
22-yard scoring pass. The Avengers forced the Mustangs to try a
57-yard field on their next possession, and the Avengers returned
the ball to their own 10 with 52 seconds to score a winning
touchdown, but the fumble ended any comeback hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
