<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COTTON-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL TEAMS INTERESTED IN COTTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Schea Cotton remains a basketball player looking
for a place to play.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing with the surprise of not being selected in the NBA
draft, the well-traveled former Long Beach City College star has
received interest from a number of teams.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the draft concluded, Cotton's agent Steve Kauffman
said he received a call from the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman has also heard from the Minnesota Timberwolves and
Miami Heat. Kauffman said that Cotton, who left Alabama after his
sophomore season, has might have a better chance of finding a team
he can make as a free agent
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him this last night that sometimes when you are drafted
mid late second round, you might round up with a team you don't
have a chance of sticking with,'' said Kauffman on Thursday. ``If
he winds up going to a team (as a free agent) he is arguably better
off than being picked randomly in the mid to late second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton averaged 15.5 points per game last season at Alabama. The
6-foot-6, 215-pound Cotton began the season playing shooting guard
but was moved out of position to power forward during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said the move hurt Cotton's numbers at school and his
status heading into the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Kauffman said Cotton was able to show one-on-one
ability in workouts and they expected a mid-second round selection
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a surprise,'' Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton played the 1998-99 season at Long Beach City College,
averaging 25.8 point per game and leading LBCC to a 33-3 record. He
was named a JUCO All-America.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton has been a heralded player since the eighth grade when he
was featured on the cover of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But his path to the 2000 NBA Draft has been winding.
</P>
<P>
   He won a CIF championship at Mater Dei in his sophomore season.
But his high school career included a stop at St. John Bosco, then
Mater Dei and then back to St. John Bosco.
</P>
<P>
   He signed letters on intent to play at Long Beach State, UCLA,
and N.C. STate but never played at any of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a really nice kid,'' Kauffman said. ``Some people think
of the bouncing around but he's a really nice kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
