<HEADER>
A9178 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-`NEST'-NUKE-SLEUTHS-I     06-30 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`NEST'-NUKE-SLEUTHS-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEST': AMERICA'S LITTLE-KNOWN NUCLEAR BOMB SQUAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BRIAN KNOWLTON  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Nuclear Emergency Search Team _ the Energy
Department unit likened to a nuclear bomb squad that kept sensitive
information on the two computer disks that disappeared recently at
Los Alamos _ is a highly secretive outfit little-known to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   NEST, as it is called, was formed to allow a speedy response to
any credible report that a terrorist group might have planted a
nuclear device somewhere on U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   Its mission was given particular urgency, and its budget
considerably increased, in the aftermath of the Feb. 26, 1993,
terrorist attack on the twin towers of the World Trade Center in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   While that truck-bombing, using simple chemical explosives,
claimed six lives, a similar attack using even a small nuclear
device could have felled the towers and devastated the southern tip
of densely populated Manhattan Island, killing scores of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has thus built the capacity to fly a search and
response team of nuclear scientists and engineers, radiation
technicians and communications specialists to any spot in the
United States at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   NEST, at a remote corner of Nellis Air Force Base in a vast
installation in the desolate reaches of southern Nevada, keeps a
cargo plane ready on the tarmac, loaded with vans, generators,
communications equipment and highly sophisticated detection
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Its staff comprises volunteers from Nellis and also from the
national nuclear laboratories of Los Alamos and Sandia in New
Mexico and Lawrence Livermore in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Some are experts in nuclear-bomb-making, others in the
dismantling of nuclear devices. Their identities are kept secret,
as are those of Energy Department briefers on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The department, which oversees the team, will reveal little
about how it does its work, in order not to provide unwitting
assistance to terrorists. Only rough outlines are known.
</P>
<P>
   One of the secrets most closely held about the group's work is
how it would disarm or neutralize a terrorist nuclear device. That
information was contained on the missing hard drives in the Los
Alamos lab.
</P>
<P>
   Such information might be useful to a terrorist group, allowing
it to booby-trap a nuclear device. But espionage at a level that
could penetrate America's most closely guarded laboratories would
seem far beyond the capacity of almost any terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   However, the disks also included data on U.S., Russian, French
and Chinese nuclear systems, useful to bomb-disarmers if a device
was based on such technology. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
