<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-IN-CUBA-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH OR WITHOUT CASTRO, CUBA'S AN EXOTIC INVESTMENT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Financial Editors)   (This 525-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JUDITH REHAK  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Could investing in Cuba become a reality in the near
future?
</P>
<P>
   For years, investors with a taste for exotic plays have had
their eye on the Caribbean island, in hopes that an easing of the
38-year U.S. trade embargo would provide a windfall.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that hope has proved futile, but change may be in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The granting of permanent normal trading status to China by the
U.S. House of Representatives and the easing of trade sanctions on
North Korea makes American policy toward Cuba look outdated, say
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is growing from U.S. companies that want to export
everything from food to pharmaceuticals to the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   So how to take advantage of a possible easing in U.S. policy?
The Herzfeld Caribbean Basin Fund, run by Thomas J. Herzfeld
Advisors Inc., a Miami-based specialist in closed-end funds, is one
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, introduced in 1993, was originally called The First
Cuba Fund, but Thomas Herzfeld, the portfolio manager, said that
when it became clear that the embargo would not be lifted, it took
its present name with a mandate to invest in the region. It still
carries its original ticker symbol of CUBA.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cuba has no public companies, the fund invests in American
and international companies that stand to benefit from better
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The companies must be able to do well, even with no change in
Cuba, but if there is, they would have a ``Cuba kicker'' Herzfeld
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he owns Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. and Seaboard
Corp., which has an extensive commercial shipping network in the
region. The portfolio also includes Empresas ICA SA, the Mexican
construction company, and Puerto Rican Cement Co., likely
participants in rebuilding the country's crumbling infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean Basin Fund is listed on the Nasdaq Small Cap
Market, and traded at about $5 on Thursday, at about a 1.5 percent
discount to the value of the fund's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Herzfeld also has a new offering, The Cuba Fund, which would
invest directly in the country. It had been in registration, but
was ``on hold,'' he explained. ``We have to file an amended
registration to bring it back to life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors with a heartier appetite for risk may want to consider
a single play on Cuba's flourishing tourism industry. Leisure
Canada Inc. has a joint venture with the Castro government to build
four luxury tourist complexes.
</P>
<P>
   While the projects sound promising, Leisure Canada's shares,
which trade on the Canadian New Ventures Exchange, a merger of the
Vancouver and Alberta Stock Exchanges, have tumbled from 22.25
Canadian dollars ($15.10) last July to trade at 1.55 dollars on
last Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FOR MORE INFORMATION: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLOBAL INVESTING. Telephone: 1-800-388-4237. $147 for a one-year
subscription in the U.S.; $175 outside the U.S., or via the
Internet for $99 a year. Web site: www.global-investing.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HERZFELD CARIBBEAN BASIN FUND. Telephone: 1-305-271-1900. Web site:
www.herzfeld.com Ticker symbol: CUBA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEISURE CANADA INC. Web site: www.leisurecanada.com &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
