<HEADER>
A9193 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`ORACLEGATES'-SCANDAL     06-30 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`ORACLEGATES'-SCANDAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY BYTES: ORACLE ADMITS HIRING DETECTIVES TO `TARNISH'
MICROSOFT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 1,000-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The U.S. software giant Oracle made the
sensational admission Wednesday that it had hired a firm of private
detectives to discredit its arch-rival Microsoft and undermine its
efforts to fend off the government's antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after a flurry of office break-ins,
computer laptop thefts, and attempts to buy off janitorial staff at
consultancy firms associated with Bill Gates' company.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be a hastily orchestrated piece of damage
control, Oracle admitted it had hired Investigation Group
International to try to establish links between Microsoft and a
number of supposedly independent consultancy firms, which had
testified on its behalf in court. It insisted, however, that it had
not sanctioned any illegal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said it had ordered the investigation into two groups,
the Independent Institute and the National Taxpayers Union, because
it suspected they were not as impartial as they claimed. Evidence
of their financial links to Microsoft subsequently appeared in The
Wall Street Journal and other newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact their work was funded by Microsoft for the express
purpose of influencing public opinion...'' an Oracle company
statement alleged. ``Left undisclosed, these Microsoft front groups
could have improperly influenced the outcome of one of the most
important cases in U.S. history,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Oracle statement made no mention of a third group,
the Association for Competitive Technology, which recently reported
a woman investigator trying to obtain its trash by offering cash to
its office cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   It also made no mention of a series of laptop thefts reported at
yet another group, Citizens for a Sound Economy, whose links to
Microsoft were subsequently written up in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent Institute has also complained of laptops going
missing. Microsoft suffered a break-in at its Washington office
earlier this month, although it has yet to determine if any
important effects or documents were taken.
</P>
<P>
   The Oracle statement said it did not stipulate how IGI should go
about its investigations. ``We did, however, insist that whatever
methods IGI employed, those methods must be legal. IGI repeatedly
assured us that all their activities were in fact 100 percent
legal.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. business press, ever sensitive to the bitter rivalry
between Microsoft founder Bill Gates and Oracle's chief executive,
Larry Ellison, are delighting in what they are already describing
as a Watergate-style scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Microsoft antitrust suit, Ellison has taken the
moral high ground, describing Gates as a ``convicted monopolist''
and arguing for an aggressive company break-up to stem his power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when someone breaks the law, he should be punished,''
Ellison told The Independent in an interview in January. Now,
however, the pressure is on for Ellison to demonstrate that he did
not stray from the high ground himself.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the private investigation affair, The Wall Street
Journal reported Wednesday that Oracle had hired a Washington
public-relations firm, Chlopak, Leonard, Schechter and Associates,
to circulate damaging stories about Microsoft in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dramatic proof that Microsoft's competitors have been
funding and orchestrating a massive PR and lobbying campaign in an
effort to tarnish Microsoft's image and invite government
intervention in an industry that has been very competitive and
serving consumers very well,'' a Microsoft spokesman said. ``We
think it's a very sad day and a huge embarrassment for Oracle and
all its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode that first put the spotlight on IGI occurred on June
1, when a team of cleaners at the Washington offices of the
Association for Competitive Technology was approached by a woman
asking if she could buy their trash.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying herself as Blanca Lopez and speaking Spanish to the
Latino cleaning crew, she said she was investigating a criminal
case and wanted the trash moved to the adjacent offices of a firm
called Upstream Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaners turned down her offer, and rebuffed her again five
days later when she came back with $1,200 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Upstream Technologies, which only began leasing the office space
last month, has since shut up shop and appears to have been a
phantom organization. The person whose name appeared on the lease
application, Robert Walters, has been identified in the past as an
IGI investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Zuck, the Association for Competitive Technology's
president, was quoted Wednesday describing the trash episode as
``despicable'' and said he was contemplating legal action for
violation of his employees' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope to get a letter of apology from Larry Ellison and
an explanation of how, in a climate over so much concern over the
issue of privacy, he could think this is an acceptable business
practice,'' he told The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not dumpster-diving in offices outside the building,
this is bribery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Oracle refusing to acknowledge any link with the episode,
Ellison now faces the famous Watergate question: what did he know,
and when did he know it?
</P>
<P>
   IGI, a well-known investigation firm which worked for the White
House during the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit against U.S.
President Bill Clinton, said Wednesday that it did not want to
comment on the Microsoft/Oracle matter.
</P>
<P>
   Press reports, however, suggested a variety of potential
embarrassments for the company, including the revelation that it
accepted work from Microsoft on a software counterfeiting case
earlier this year while under contract to Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   News reports have also focused attention on the string of recent
break-ins and laptop thefts, although nobody has yet furnished
evidence that they are more than a bizarre coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   The least suspicious is the Microsoft break-in, which was one of
a number of burglaries committed in the same part of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The consultancy firms that have lost laptops, only to see
confidential files contained in them appear in the newspapers, are
straining themselves not to jump to conclusions. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
