<HEADLINE>
BORED TV NETWORKS SWITCH OFF BLANKET ELECTION COVERAGE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. electorate is treating the Gore-Bush
presidential contest as one colossal yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits forecast that the turnout in November could be the
lowest on record. The television networks are scaling down their
campaign coverage, and most have decided to leave gavel-to-gavel
coverage of the nominating conventions in July and August to the
specialist cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   But news is gradually seeping out that Al Gore and George W
Bush, two bland offspring of famous political families, will not
have the publicity field entirely to themselves this summer, not
during their setpiece conventions, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on an idea from Arianna Huffington, the glamorous and
sharp-tongued columnist formerly married to the millionaire and
failed senatorial candidate, Michael Huffington, an alliance of
groups is organizing two alternative conventions to shadow the
official ones, day by day and hour by hour.
</P>
<P>
   These shadow conventions promise to be more fun, and probably
more glitzy, than the official ones, which could well displease the
many commercial sponsors of the Gore and Bush extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, for instance, the band will strike up, the
strobe lights flash, and on to the stage will stride John McCain
with his hearty wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good evening and welcome,'' he will shout to ecstatic cheers,
before lambasting the corruption of a political system that
railroaded through its favorite sons before half the electorate had
had a chance to choose.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Democrats can expect Warren Beatty to reprise
his Bulworth act from the film of that name, unleashing a torrent
of invective about the real state of the nation and the cynicism of
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   They will also be treated to tub-thumping equality rhetoric from
Jesse Jackson, and maybe a touch of insurrectionist argument from
Ralph Nader, devoted advocate of ordinary people and newly crowned
nominee of the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a technique used at recent party conventions, when
``real'' people are recruited to praise the nominee, both shadow
events will hear from ordinary citizens who say they have been
victimized during the past eight years of the Clinton presidency.
There will be entertainment, with contributions from such household
names in U.S. television satire as Bill Maher and Al Franken.
</P>
<P>
   Participants are also likely to be treated to Huffington's
biting satire and newfound social conscience. She could read choice
excerpts from her diary, written as though from the White House
Lincoln bedroom, or from her new book _ her rich woman's epiphany
about the wealth gap and poverty in America. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
