<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIANIZED-LEBANON-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON'S INCESTUOUS RELATIONSHIP WITH `SISTER SYRIA'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 1,000-word separate-buy article by Robert Fisk _
``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the Year'' _ is from
THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIRUT _ The Independent on Sunday didn't make it onto the
newsstands here in Beirut the weekend before last. Nor did Business
Week. Nor did the Economist. Or Newsweek. Or Time magazine. Or Le
Figaro. Or Le Monde...
</P>
<P>
   There was, it seemed, a little problem with the coverage of a
recent Middle East event: the death of President Hafez el-Assad of
Syria, whose memory was not always treated in the international
press with quite the respect it deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent's sin, it seems, was to have recorded the
genuine grief of Syria's citizens while noting the lack of black
flags in the ancient city of Hama where a 1982 fundamentalist
insurrection was bloodily repressed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Lebanese can read anything they want on the Internet,
the Surete Generale felt it necessary to explain the reason for its
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were well aware that articles could be read on
the Internet, the Surete said. But refusing permission for
offending publications to go on sale was a way of expressing the
government's ``moral disapproval.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities, an official statement added, had a duty to
counter comments which were disrespectful of the head of state or
``the head of state of a neighboring country.'' In other words,
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of conjecture as to whether the Syrians are as
frightened of criticism as the Lebanese are on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's government ministers have long accepted that foreign
journalists won't show the same respect as such giants of
journalism as Al Baath or the Syria Times. And Syria's new
heir-president, Bashar el-Assad, is fascinated by computers and the
Internet _ indeed, he was himself brought online by a Lebanese
communications expert.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, the problem has nothing to do with the press.
It's about the relationship between Lebanon and ``Sister Syria,''
the presence of some 21,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon and the cozy
way in which Damascus and Beirut become ever closer.
</P>
<P>
   Take the telephone. Syria's international code is 0096311. But
in Beirut, I have only to dial 02 for Damascus. When I'm in
Damascus, I dial Beirut not through the international code 009611
but just 061. Overnight, the two capitals became just local calls
apart.
</P>
<P>
   True, Syria has not annexed Lebanon, as its critics would have
the world believe. The Syrians have not introduced their currency
to Beirut and the Lebanese _ not the Syrian _ flag flies over
government ministries.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Boulevard du President Hafez el-Assad near the
airport, there are plenty of highways dedicated to Lebanese
presidents and prime ministers. In Beirut, even the lunatic General
Michel Aoun _ who thought he was General de Gaulle when he launched
a war against the Syrians in 1989 but then ran like Petain for the
French ambassador's residence the moment the Syrians bombed him in
1990 _ can find his rantings printed in the Beirut press.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a certain amount of hypocrisy uttered about the
Syrians. I often hear the Lebanese complaining that their sons
cannot find jobs because of the presence of 400,000 Syrian guest
workers (or a million if you believe some) in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the Syrians can be found cleaning streets, selling bread,
washing houses _ menial jobs which the Lebanese have always refused
to do. If the Syrians weren't here, I suspect an army of Filipinos
would be forthcoming. There's already reported to be a legion of
240,000 Sri Lankan housemaids in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the cry from the Christian Maronites that with the
Israelis in retreat, it's time the Syrian forces also left Lebanon
_ a demand which conveniently forgets that it was the Maronites who
demanded the Syrian presence in the first place, and that the
mainstream Christian community never lifted a finger to oppose the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians, of course, remember 1982 and the Maronite
government installed by the Israelis _ Syria's troops and guns and
tanks are here to ensure that Lebanon does not again fall under the
sway of Syria's enemies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Lebanese and Syrian intelligence services work
closely together. There has even been a joint passing-out parade of
Syrian and Lebanese cadets.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not quite that simple. The treaty of brotherhood and
cooperation between Beirut and Damascus provides for Syria's
protection of her tiny neighbor in the event of ``Zionist
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is that, while Syria may have saved Lebanon
from an Arafat-style capitulation to Israel, it clearly cannot
defend Lebanon from Israeli military attack. The Israeli air force
has eight times bombed Lebanon's power stations with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, needless to say, the Syrians tell you how grateful
the Lebanese should be, how many sacrifices Syria has made for
Lebanon _ a view not exactly reciprocated in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese, I suspect, have never gotten over the fact that
the Syrians _ who were cruelly regarded before the civil war as
backward and uneducated _ had to enter Lebanon when the
sophisticated, over-educated Lebanese tore themselves apart in
bloody internecine war.
</P>
<P>
   They forget, too, that an estimated 36 percent of the millions
of dollars invested in Beirut's banks is Syrian money.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it all goes back to the one-armed General Henri
Gouraud who carved ``Greater Lebanon'' out of Syria after the
1914-18 war. Before that, Beirut was a Syrian port.
</P>
<P>
   If you go up to the northern Lebanese city of Tripoli today,
you'll find thousands of families with relatives living in the
central Syrian cities of Hama and Homs, a reminder that back in the
aftermath of the First World War, most of the population of Lebanon
wanted to remain unified under the old Ottoman-style ``vilayet'' of
Damascus. Only the Maronites and the French demanded a new state.
</P>
<P>
   In the north of Ireland, another frontier was being drawn about
the same time. And around the new state of Yugoslavia. Thus did the
power and authority of the old mapmakers help to doom future
generations. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this insightful 1,000-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
