A9211 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ECONOMIST-ADVISORY &LR;      06-30 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIST-ADVISORY </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 1 July 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD SCIENCE, EVIL MEN: GENOME TRIUMPH CALLS FOR CAUTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENOME-CHEERS'N'FEARS-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Alice's adventures in Wonderland takes the form of a
race. When it is over, she asks who has won. ``Everybody has won,''
the judge, a dodo, replies, ``and all must have prizes.'' The race
to sequence the human genome _ or, rather, to claim the credit for
sequencing it _ is now over. So the White House's dodo-in-chief,
Bill Clinton, has duly awarded prizes to everybody. But let's not
forget that this particular race was not to the finish-line, but to
the starting-line. Knowing the sequence is really just the
beginning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 optional trims, totaling 325; 1,275 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZIMBOBAWAY: ZANU, FOR YOUR SAKE _ AND ZIMBABWE'S _ DUMP MUGABE
NOW &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAKE-UP-ZIMBABWE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His strategy for winning last weekend's parliamentary election
in Zimbabwe was worse than a crime. It was a mistake. Ready to
wreck the country in order to hold on to power, Zimbabwe's
president, Robert Mugabe, ruthlessly tried to refight the
liberation war, encouraged brutal intimidation of the opposition,
played the race card against whites, and promised to seize their
land and give it to landless blacks. Mugabe believes his right to
rule is absolute; Zimbabwe's voters beg to differ. For their sake,
his party, ZANU, could do itself and Zimbabwe a favor by dumping
Mugabe now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONCE AGAIN (YAWN), TWO SENTENCES SUM UP JAPAN'S ELECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUTLESS-JAPAN-LDP-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It used to be said that every foreign article about Japanese
general elections began with the same two sentences, adjusted for
the odd change of dramatis personae: The Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP) would again form the government. And there would be no change
of policies. After the poll on June 25, the same can be said again.
But there is a difference: once, this saying was a compliment
(don't meddle with success). Now, it's a sign of despair (while
Japan's society is changing, its political system remains
paralyzed). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-COMMERCE `NIRVANA' GETS A NEEDED REALITY CHECK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOT.COMS-DOT.BOMBS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Markets notoriously overshoot, in both directions. So, it seems,
can dot.com obsessions. For much of the past three years, shares in
Internet firms have climbed stratospherically, regardless of
whether they were making any profits or even any sales. The future
promised land, it was felt, was all that mattered. But now the
price of Amazon.com and other dot.com shares have tumbled, forcing
a rethink of ``real'' offline firms vs. ``virtual'' online ones.
The truth is, business bosses can behave badly, and companies can
make losses, whether in the new or the old economies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED, WHITE AND GREEN: TEAMSTERS AND TURTLES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREEN-PARTYANIMALS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER, COLO. _ Thank God for Greens. Amid the general po-faced
seriousness of American politics, here is a party that doesn't dare
to be dull. One pony-tailed wannabe presidential candidate from
Tennessee says that he hasn't smoked pot with Al Gore for a long
time. Another, named Jello Biafra, wants a maximum wage _ around
$200,000, he thought, should suffice _ and the abolition of both
the CIA and sports-utility vehicles (SUVs). And delegates in formal
evening wear carried placards saying ``Billionaires for Bush and
Gore. We bought the election so you don't have to.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW WILL NEXT PRESIDENT IMPACT SUPREME COURT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSHGORE-SUPREMECOURT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The nine justices of the U.S. Supreme Court are
famously shy of the limelight, preferring to announce their most
politically contentious decisions on the very last day of their
nine-month term and then go off on vacation, leaving a swirl of
controversy behind them. They did it again on June 28, in four
split rulings, capping a term littered with attention-grabbing
cases. It coincided with a presidential election year. Inevitably,
this has raised the question: how much impact can the next
president have on the direction of the Supreme Court? A lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALAS, POLITICIANS CAN'T PRESS THE FLESH IN CYBERSPACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOT.COM-DEMOCRACY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Politics has few rules, especially in an election
year. But here is one: it generally lags commerce. In the late 19th
century, party bosses paid the ultimate compliment to the brand-new
system of industrial mass-production by inventing ``machine
politics.'' Now that commercial America is in love with the
Internet, when will that, too, turn politics upside down? Is a
handshake still more potent than a Web page? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary and Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (300 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EPIC `BATTLE FOR ELIAN' ENDS. NOW, ABOUT THAT EMBARGO... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN-EMBARGO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Fidel Castro might have won his epic Battle for Elian,
the six-year-old boy shipwrecked off Florida last November, who
finally returned to Cuba with his father on June 28. But his hopes
that his victory would prompt bigger changes in American policy
towards Cuba _ particularly the trade embargo imposed in 1960 _
seem premature. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NERVOUS NAIL-BITING GRIPS MEXICAN VOTERS, MARKETS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO-JITTERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The last four presidential terms have ended in
economic turbulence, but this time it is going to be different. So
Mexican officials have sworn and, until recently, investors had
believed them. But a bout of nerves that began last month seems to
be worsening. This week the peso fell, briefly, to its lowest point
since February 1999. It is not just political uncertainty over this
weekend's election that is to blame. Investors are also worried
about the effect on Mexico of a hard landing in the United States,
which takes 90 percent of its exports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Mexico's Election, Sunday, JULY 2) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUEL-CELL-POWERED CARS ARE ROLLING ALONG &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUEL-CELL-AUTOS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It looks increasingly likely that the eventual
replacement for the internal-combustion engine in motor vehicles
will be the fuel cell. This is a device that reacts hydrogen and
oxygen together to release electrical energy. Environmentalists
like it, because its exhaust is water. And, after some initial
hesitation, the world's car makers are now investing heavily in
turning it into a practical reality. The latest prototype comes
from General Motors, which hopes to get its first fuel-cell-powered
car into the showrooms by 2004. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `I'M SORRY, WE'RE UNABLE TO CONNECT YOUR MERGER. PLEASE DON'T
TRY AGAIN' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORLDCOM-DISCONNECT-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Live by the sword, die by the sword. In less than two
decades, Bernie Ebbers made his way from small-time motels to
big-time telecoms, eventually controlling a third of America's
long-distance calling and nearly as much of its Internet traffic
through his empire, Worldcom. Last year he crowned his run with a
deal that was then the biggest in history: a $115 billion bid for
Sprint, America's third-largest long-distance carrier and perhaps
its best wireless firm. But on June 27, the streak ended: Sprint
was one acquisition too many. Both America's Department of Justice
and the European Union's regulatory authorities moved to block the
deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Story can stand alone in 700 words; 1,050 uncut) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
