<P>
   &UR; DOT.COMS-DOT.BOMBS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Markets notoriously overshoot, in both directions. So, it seems,
can dot.com obsessions. For much of the past three years, shares in
Internet firms have climbed stratospherically, regardless of
whether they were making any profits or even any sales. The future
promised land, it was felt, was all that mattered. But now the
price of Amazon.com and other dot.com shares have tumbled, forcing
a rethink of ``real'' offline firms vs. ``virtual'' online ones.
The truth is, business bosses can behave badly, and companies can
make losses, whether in the new or the old economies. &QL;
</P>
