A9214 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-WAKE-UP-ZIMBABWE-ECON     06-30 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAKE-UP-ZIMBABWE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBOBAWAY: ZANU, FOR YOUR SAKE _ AND ZIMBABWE'S _ DUMP MUGABE
NOW  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 725-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   His strategy for winning last weekend's parliamentary election
in Zimbabwe was worse than a crime, it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to wreck the country in order to hold on to power,
Zimbabwe's president, Robert Mugabe, tried to refight the
liberation war, encouraged brutal intimidation of the opposition,
played the race card against whites, and promised to seize their
land and give it to landless blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Like his predecessor, Ian Smith, who believed that white rule in
Zimbabwe would last a thousand years, Mugabe believes his right to
rule is absolute. Zimbabwe's voters beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he now has the sense to listen to them, the damage
Mugabe has done in recent months will take years to repair. And the
nightmare may not be over yet.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an opposition victory, Mugabe had claimed, could
be entertained only in dreamland. Yet the dream almost came true.
</P>
<P>
   Roused from years of political apathy and determined to stand up
to Mugabe's thugs, Zimbabweans turned out in their greatest numbers
since independence and, for once, the majority did not vote for the
ruling ZANU-PF party.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the main opposition party, the Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC), defied Mugabe's racism by electing four
white MPs. Several ministers, close cronies of the president, lost
their seats. Crucially, Mugabe has lost the two-thirds majority in
parliament that he needs to change the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In time, this election may be seen as having broken the back of
Mugabe's increasingly autocratic one-party state. But it has also
created an explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   The election showed up the natural divisions Mugabe has
exacerbated: the disaffected towns were mostly for the MDC, the
rural areas for ZANU; the minority Ndebele parts of the country
voted solidly for the opposition, the majority Shona areas stayed
loyal to the government.
</P>
<P>
   But for the intimidation in rural areas, the opposition might
have won a majority of seats. Yet the MDC leader, Morgan
Tsvangirai, has behaved with statesmanlike restraint, so far.
</P>
<P>
   He has accepted an unfree, unfair election because it has given
him and his supporters a moral victory. He has yet to say whether
he would join a national-unity government, if asked. Mugabe has yet
to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe badly needs a change of direction. The economy is in
ruins; it is expected to shrink by about 5 percent this year. The
country may not be able to feed itself. There is not enough foreign
exchange to buy fuel and electricity. Inflation may soon rise to
nearly 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Devaluation is an essential part of any recovery strategy. But
that means that a country already feeling impoverished by bad,
corrupt government is about to get poorer. Under such conditions,
one more stupid move by Mugabe could bring violent upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are now on the president. In order to prevent economic
collapse, he needs emergency loans. But to obtain those he must win
back the trust of the donors.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of national reconciliation, but such words have been
cheapened by his own recent actions. The president has ten
parliamentary seats to appoint. He could offer one to Tsvangirai,
who failed to win his seat in the open election, and give others to
national representatives instead of ZANU party hacks.
</P>
<P>
   His government says it will push ahead with land acquisitions.
That will be fine, so long as the change of farm ownership benefits
the poor and landless, not the rich and well-connected, and so long
as Mugabe follows the law instead of encouraging violent
occupations. And he should let the police and courts pursue those
who used violence and intimidation during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's own eyes are on the presidential election in 2002, and
so are those of his supporters and rivals within ZANU. The party is
no slavish monolith. There have been two attempts to unseat Mugabe
in the past year. He held on by promising a huge election victory
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Now that so many voters have deserted him, Mugabe may yet change
his policies in the hope of facing a more contented and united
country in two years' time. But that is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ZANU could do itself and Zimbabwe a favor by dumping Mugabe
now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
