<HEADER>
A9215 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GUTLESS-JAPAN-LDP-ECO     06-30 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUTLESS-JAPAN-LDP-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN (YAWN), TWO SENTENCES SUM UP JAPAN'S ELECTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It used to be said that every foreign article about Japanese
general elections began with the same two sentences, adjusted for
the odd change of dramatis personae: The Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP) would again form the government. And there would be no change
of policies.
</P>
<P>
   After the poll on June 25, the same can be said again. But there
is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Once, this saying was a compliment; it was best not to meddle
with success. Now, it is a sign of despair; there is scant prospect
of an end to Japan's failure.
</P>
<P>
   Failure? Isn't that a little strong? Despite a decade-long
slowdown and then recession, which followed the collapse of the
country's stock market in 1990-91, Japan remains the world's
second-largest economy. Its unemployment rate, when measured in
comparable ways, is higher than in America but lower than in
France. Japanese people remain comfortably off.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some disturbing signs of social
deterioration, Europeans and Americans can still find much to envy
there. And the best Japanese companies remain world-class,
producing brilliant new gadgets or reliable cars with typical
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Japan is suffering from failure, nonetheless. The failure is
that, ten years after the lean times began, no government has
introduced the sort of broad reforms that are needed to take the
economy out of intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some changes, to be sure: more competition in
finance, more, thanks to deregulation, in sectors such as retailing
and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But, by and large, every government since the troubles began has
followed a policy of wait and hope: of postponing painful reforms
in the hope that the economy will revive of its own accord. That is
the policy that the re-elected, LDP-led coalition is expected to
leave unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that fortune will smile upon Japan. The economy
has been recovering for the past few months, with a bit of extra
consumer spending and some more corporate investment.
</P>
<P>
   If that were to carry on for another year or two, consumers
might gain enough confidence to run down their savings and spend
even more, and the government might be able to trim back its huge
budget deficit, now approaching 10 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   The room, and the political backing, might emerge for a genuine
clear-out of dead wood in the banking and life-insurance
industries, for wider competition in telecoms, and for other
much-needed deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past five years, however, economic revivals have
been brought rudely to a halt. In 1995 the Kobe earthquake
destroyed lives and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997 came the East Asian financial crisis, amplified by
Russia's debt default in mid-1998: the crisis walloped Japanese
exports, as well as adding to the already large pile of bad loans
at Japan's banks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these shocks was Japan's fault. Nor, if it comes,
will the next one probably be: it is likelier to arise from a slump
in America, or a political crisis of some sort in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's fault is one of negligence: that by shrinking from
implementing proper reform, successive governments have left Japan
terribly vulnerable to another shock.
</P>
<P>
   If one comes, Japan's fiscal tanks will be empty; public-sector
debts already exceed 120 percent of GDP, and loom even larger once
the government's full liabilities are totted up.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, much of the Yen110 trillion ($1 trillion or so) in
fiscal-stimulus packages in the past decade has been frittered away
on unproductive projects, which have shovelled public money into
the grateful hands of one of the LDP's main backers, the
construction industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the main banks have in effect been nationalized. And
the public bailouts continue, this time with a rescue of a bankrupt
retailer, Sogo.
</P>
<P>
   What Japan needs is a vigorous clean-out of the banks' loan
books and their managements; the liberalization of farm trade;
deregulation and proper antitrust enforcement in telecoms and a
myriad other sectors.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no current prospect of this, or anything like it,
happening. Wait and hope. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
