<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL-CELL-AUTOS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL-CELL-POWERED CARS ARE ROLLING ALONG  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 400-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It looks increasingly likely that the eventual
replacement for the internal-combustion engine in motor vehicles
will be the fuel cell.
</P>
<P>
   This is a device that reacts hydrogen and oxygen together to
release electrical energy. Environmentalists like it, because its
exhaust is water. And, after some initial hesitation, the world's
car makers are now investing heavily in turning it into a practical
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The latest prototype comes from General Motors. The archly named
HydroGen1 is a third of the size of the company's previous version,
yet it produces about 60 percent more power _ 80 kilowatts, the
equivalent of an average 1,600cc engine _ and GM's researchers
estimate its thermal efficiency at somewhere between 53 percent and
67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, up to two-thirds of the energy in HydroGen1's
fuel is ultimately channelled to the vehicle's wheels. That is
nearly four times more than the best gas-engined vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The car maker claims to have achieved several other significant
breakthroughs with HydroGen1.
</P>
<P>
   It can operate at temperatures as cold as -40degreesC. Even in
such conditions, it takes less than 30 seconds to boost itself into
operation, compared with five minutes or more for existing fuel
cells.
</P>
<P>
   But it is its compactness that really makes it look a plausible
predecessor to a production version.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel cell and hydrogen-storage system in the previous
prototype took up not only the engine compartment of an Opel
Zafira, but the vehicle's trunk and half the rear seat as well.
</P>
<P>
   HydroGen1 squeezes most of its hardware under the hood, while
raising the floor of the trunk by a modest 10cm (2.5 inches) and
the rear seat by 4cm. And the fuel tank, which holds enough
hydrogen to drive the car some 600km (400 miles), is the same size
as an ordinary gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   This environmental (and, potentially, commercial) paragon is not
the result of some startling breakthrough. It is, rather, the sum
of a lot of humdrum engineering refinements.
</P>
<P>
   These include simpler pipework, miniaturized electronics and a
better understanding of the ``envelope'' of operating conditions
that a commercially available vehicle must be able to tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   The previous prototype was found to be overdesigned. By paring
things back to match capabilities to requirements, a smaller,
cheaper fuel cell becomes possible.
</P>
<P>
   If it can keep up this process of continuous improvement, GM
hopes to get its first fuel-cell-powered car into the showrooms by
2004. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
