<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 08:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV02-COX     06-30 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S LEGACY: A SPOTLIGHT ON GOOD, BAD, UGLY OF CUBA POLITICS
 &HT;    With US-CUBA-$ADV02.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was a made-for-television story: a cute little boy
survives a nightmare-at-sea, only to come ashore into a maelstrom
of battling sound bites, dueling legal teams, shouting protestors,
an aging but forceful dictator, defiant mayors, crying
grandmothers, a warm-hearted nun and a shocking pre-dawn raid.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez's story grabbed the imaginations of millions
around the world. Propelled by an avalanche of televised images, it
grew from the story of an improbable, 6-year-old shipwreck survivor
into a fiery international debate that summed up 40 years of bitter
Cuban exile politics.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally went home to Cuba on Wednesday, the television
networks broke into regular programming and broadcast live pictures
of the motorcade and the jet's taxi and take-off, as if Elian were
a major world figure.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, he was.
</P>
<P>
   Observers disagree over the long-term legacy of Elian's case.
But most agree that the images will linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a story dominated by visuals,'' said Dario Moreno, a
Cuban-American professor of political science at Miami's Florida
International University. ``In a way, there are a lot of
similarities to the O.J. Simpson case. It was a tremendously
dramatic story that captured the interest of a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But many believe more than the images will linger.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the furious reaction to his story, the impish little
boy is being credited _ partly _ with helping open a crack in the
four-decades-old U.S. embargo against Cuba. Congressional leaders
reached a deal to allow the sale of food and medicine to Cuba just
a day before Elian went home, although the measure has yet to win
final passage.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Elian made the American public more aware than
ever of their country's tortured relationship with Fidel Castro's
communist Cuba. Before Elian, mainstream America knew little about
Cuba. But with the case grabbing headlines and heartstrings, many
Americans were shocked that a father's blood ties to his son might
be sacrificed for politics.
</P>
<P>
   Their questions raised the most serious challenge ever to the
power of a small but determined band of Cuban-American lobbyists
who for decades have held great influence over U.S. policy toward
the Caribbean island sitting just 90 miles off Florida's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showing that two-thirds of Americans wanted Elian to go
home to Cuba also served as a wake-up call for many of South
Florida's 800,000 Cuban-Americans. After 40 years of exile, they
were accustomed to having their way on the Cuba issue in the
national political arena.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the American public was rejecting the heart of their
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't understand us,'' added Josefina Inlimo(CQ),
50, a Cuban-American housewife who fought back tears outside the
home Elian shared with his Miami relatives on the day the boy
returned to Cuba. ``Before Elian, I was proud to be an American.
Now I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Elian's legacy is one of confusion, heartbreak and
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the true believers, the reaction is retrenchment,'' said
Damian Fernandez, another Cuban-American academic and author of the
book, Cuba and the Politics of Passion. ``Others feel frustration.
A third group feels apathy and withdrawal, that they don't want to
play the game of politics anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fernandez and Moreno feel the Cuban-American leadership
stumbled badly in their handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their error was to say that it was an issue of communism
versus democracy, while the rest of the world saw it as a
father-son issue,'' Fernandez said. ``Now, they've not only lost
Elian, but they've also lost the public relations battle. Their
image is tarnished in the eyes of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Vazquez, a spokesman for the Cuban-American National
Foundation, the most powerful exile lobbying group, dismissed the
criticism, saying the case was a tragedy that will only re-double
the determination of Castro's foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation's obituary has been written so many times and
it's the furthest thing from the truth,'' he said. ``The Elian saga
is a tremendous tragedy, but the mission of the foundation remains
the same: to bring freedom and democracy to the Cuban people.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno agrees that the community suffered losses, but questions
the long-term impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the attention the case got, the political impact was
really minor,'' he said. ``The pressure to loosen the embargo had
been getting stronger every year. And nothing earth-shaking has
happened. We still really haven't seen how it will play out
politically.''
</P>
<P>
   One interesting impact of the case has been its effect on young
Cuban-Americans. Many observers had believed the younger generation
was more moderate than their parents were, and would inevitably
soften the hard line against Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian shattered that notion,'' Fernandez said. ``Polls
consistently showed that 90 percent of Cuban-Americans wanted Elian
to stay here, regardless of age. I think Elian embodied something
about the Cuban experience that became a cause for them to define
what it means to be Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Elian case will have a lasting impact on U.S.-Cuba
relations in the long-term remains to be seen. But some longtime
Cuba watchers say the case has already triggered important changes.
</P>
<P>
   John Kavulich(CQ) of the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council
believes the Cuban and American governments took an important step
in their handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, whenever there has been a problem with one facet
of the relationship, all the other facets shut down until the
problem was resolved,'' he said. ``In this case we saw a real
effort by both governments to isolate the Elian problem while they
continued to make progress on other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavulich also credits the boy's saga with educating the American
public about Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a necessity for the media to present the context in
which the Elian issue was being debated,'' he said. ``The stories
were substantive and went into areas of Cuban life that were not
discussed before. They also provided a picture that many people
were uncomfortable with, of shouting and threats and the separation
of a parent and child.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, those images will stick with many Americans for years
to come: Cuban-American politicians angrily defying the federal
government; protestors burning American flags in the streets of
Miami and the controversial video made by Elian's Miami relatives
showing the boy lecturing his papa.
</P>
<P>
   Also disturbing was the infamous news photo of a gun-wielding
federal agent reaching out for a terrified Elian.
</P>
<P>
   But the unkindest blow for many Cuban-Americans is in the fact
that Fidel Castro comes out once again looking like the victor,
having somehow turned the tables on the exiles and won the public
relations battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro is clearly the big winner, while in many ways, Elian
has left this community shipwrecked,'' Fernandez said. ``It's left
us without a sense of direction. Unfortunately, I don't see any
institutional effort at change. The community is in shock. I'm not
sure what lessons have been learned, and by whom.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams'' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
