<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-DOME-$ADV01-C     06-30 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOME-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANNING BRITAIN'S MILLENNIUM DOME: Expensive attraction's slow
start confuses some, angers others
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, England _ Emerging from the Body Zone on a recent
afternoon, David Owens said he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right then, that's it,'' fumed Owens, whose annoyance was
stimulating a powerful desire for a cigarette. ``I'm embarrassed as
an Englishman, as a European and as a human being. They spent
untold millions on this and at the end of the day it's money down
the pipe, isn't it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Body Zone is perhaps the best known of the 14 themed sectors
in the Millennium Dome, the US$1.2 billion attraction intended to
make an important statement about modern Britain at the dawn of the
new century.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the midpoint of the Dome's troubled life, the
statement being delivered is not exactly what its backers had in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who paid about US$100 for a family ticket, waited 30
minutes with his wife and twin 5-year-olds to enter the colossal
peach-colored, androgynous body. The journey began with a view of a
giant naval _ pierced stylishly with a huge ring _ continued with a
ride up an arm past the thunderous pounding of a giant heart, a
talking brain, a Volkswagen-sized eyeball and then down the stairs
and out the leg.
</P>
<P>
   After finally lighting up and taking a thoughtful puff, the best
thing Owens could say about the experience was that it was brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, five minutes?'' he asked his speechless wife. ``I can
withstand anything for five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Britain must withstand six months more of the misery
generated by the ill-fated Dome since its inauguration on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Dome quietly welcomed its 3 millionth visitor.
That's the good news. The bad news is that the attraction's
managers last year projected that the Dome would have 12 million
visitors for the year that is now half over.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing opening in January the projections were
slashed to 7 million _ a figure that may still be elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Slow ticket sales have had the predictable effect on the bottom
line. Losses are reported in the British media to be already more
than US$150 million. In May, the government had to come up with a
nearly US$50 million emergency cash injection to keep the doors
open. The government intends to sell the Dome in July to a private
bidder. At the end of the year, it is to be reconfigured into some
other use.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun, Britain's largest selling tabloid, reported earlier
this week that the Dome would run out of money in September and
close four months early _ an assertion that the Dome's management
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the most recent group of managers, headed by
EuroDisney veteran Pierre-Yves Gerbeau, acknowledges that the
earlier attendance estimates were wildly optimistic and that the
Dome has been slow to work its way into the public's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Gerbeau, a Frenchman who speaks with an American accent, blames
much of the problem on the British press, which has been gleefully
merciless in its attacks on the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gerbeau used an appearance at Parliament to appeal
for less vitriolic coverage. ``Why don't you stand behind us for a
change and let us prove ourselves to the general public,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome's new advertising campaign urges the public to ignore
the press. A new television spot casts Dome critics as sheep and
ends with the line, ``You've got a mind of your own _ take it to
the Millennium Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, people seem to be taking their minds elsewhere. In a
nagging coincidence, the new and much acclaimed Tate Modern museum
also marked a milestone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Open just seven weeks a few miles up the River Thames, the Tate
welcomed its millionth visitor and is on a pace to become London's
surprise top attraction for the year.
</P>
<P>
   This can be explained by two important factors: the Tate is free
and in central London. A ticket to the Dome is more than US$30 and
the structure is set in a car-free zone on former industrial land
about 15 miles east of London.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, many observers believe the Tate provides the smart
and funky experience promised but not delivered by the Dome.
Stephen Bayley, who resigned as creative director of the Dome
before its opening, believes that the Tate has been well-received
because it appeals to the public's intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People so wanted something intelligent, smart and optimistic
and now it seems as though it is Tate Modern that has supplied
that,'' Bayley said. ``The Tate does not characterize the British
public as drooling morons, whereas the Dome insults with
patronizing rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dome is a national disgrace, a catastrophically expensive
lesson and we should all be ashamed. The dimwits responsible should
be publicly stoned.''
</P>
<P>
   While there have been a number of resignations, no one has been
stoned _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   Dome designers say they meant to appeal to the masses and are
dismissive of complaints that they dumbed down the exhibits. ``We
have been accused of having low standards and pandering to the
lowest common denominator, but I don't apologize for that at all,''
Ben Evans, one of the Dome's four content editors, said in a recent
BBC radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be family-orientated and to be inclusive, not
exclusive, and ensure that as many people as possible could come
and enjoy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14 zones within the huge Teflon-roofed structure _ which is
twice the size of the Georgia Dome _ were intended to illustrate
human life, work and play as well as the social and environmental
challenges of the 21st century. Unlike Disney's Epcot Center, the
exhibits are not rides but rather strolls, climbs or meanderings
through the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Body Zone, the Dome offers such attractions
as the Journey Zone, which chronicles the history of
transportation; the Money Zone, which invites visitors to spend
vast sums and watch the inflationary effects of their extravagance;
and the Faith Zone, which represents various forms of religious
worship.
</P>
<P>
   Some zones may seem peculiar at best to a visitor. Living
Island, which faithfully replicates the Spartan pleasures of a
British beach, offers a fine collection of what can be best
described as washed up garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Other sectors are more successful. The Play Zone has a variety
of entertaining family games, and the Self Portrait Zone, with its
thousands of photographs contributed by ordinary and famous
Britons, makes a fine national time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome also seems to fare better with conventional
entertainment. Each day, the Millennium Show provides a stunning
extravaganza of dance, acrobatics and high-wire theatrics in the
Dome's cavernous central arena.
</P>
<P>
   Impressively, the Dome also offers the largest McDonald's
restaurant in the world _ an odd feature in an attraction intended
to celebrate modern Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Dome's standing as favorite target for the city's
journalists, comedians and artsy class, it nevertheless does seem
to please many of its visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Keene, who also exited the Body Zone on a recent
afternoon, said she was impressed. ``I'm quite weary with all the
comments in the press,'' she said. ``I think this is a bright and
cheerful place, and many of the exhibits are brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dome's managers constantly remind everyone that
their studies show that people who actually see the Dome enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Gerbeau, the Dome's chief executive, believes he will achieve
the revised target of 7 million visitors, which would place it
among Europe's most popular attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any standards, the Dome is clearly an overwhelming success
both in terms of visitor numbers and the positive feedback from
those who visit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, many visitors may share the reaction of French
President Jacques Chirac, who had only one question after seeing a
model of the Dome in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's it for?'' asked a puzzled Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   The answer still isn't completely clear.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http//:london.millennium-dome-uk.com
</P>
<P>
   http//:www.londontown.com
</P>
<P>
   http//:www.tate.org.uk
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV02-COX     06-30 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S LEGACY: A SPOTLIGHT ON GOOD, BAD, UGLY OF CUBA POLITICS
 &HT;    With US-CUBA-$ADV02.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was a made-for-television story: a cute little boy
survives a nightmare-at-sea, only to come ashore into a maelstrom
of battling sound bites, dueling legal teams, shouting protestors,
an aging but forceful dictator, defiant mayors, crying
grandmothers, a warm-hearted nun and a shocking pre-dawn raid.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez's story grabbed the imaginations of millions
around the world. Propelled by an avalanche of televised images, it
grew from the story of an improbable, 6-year-old shipwreck survivor
into a fiery international debate that summed up 40 years of bitter
Cuban exile politics.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally went home to Cuba on Wednesday, the television
networks broke into regular programming and broadcast live pictures
of the motorcade and the jet's taxi and take-off, as if Elian were
a major world figure.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, he was.
</P>
<P>
   Observers disagree over the long-term legacy of Elian's case.
But most agree that the images will linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a story dominated by visuals,'' said Dario Moreno, a
Cuban-American professor of political science at Miami's Florida
International University. ``In a way, there are a lot of
similarities to the O.J. Simpson case. It was a tremendously
dramatic story that captured the interest of a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But many believe more than the images will linger.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the furious reaction to his story, the impish little
boy is being credited _ partly _ with helping open a crack in the
four-decades-old U.S. embargo against Cuba. Congressional leaders
reached a deal to allow the sale of food and medicine to Cuba just
a day before Elian went home, although the measure has yet to win
final passage.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Elian made the American public more aware than
ever of their country's tortured relationship with Fidel Castro's
communist Cuba. Before Elian, mainstream America knew little about
Cuba. But with the case grabbing headlines and heartstrings, many
Americans were shocked that a father's blood ties to his son might
be sacrificed for politics.
</P>
<P>
   Their questions raised the most serious challenge ever to the
power of a small but determined band of Cuban-American lobbyists
who for decades have held great influence over U.S. policy toward
the Caribbean island sitting just 90 miles off Florida's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showing that two-thirds of Americans wanted Elian to go
home to Cuba also served as a wake-up call for many of South
Florida's 800,000 Cuban-Americans. After 40 years of exile, they
were accustomed to having their way on the Cuba issue in the
national political arena.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the American public was rejecting the heart of their
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't understand us,'' added Josefina Inlimo(CQ),
50, a Cuban-American housewife who fought back tears outside the
home Elian shared with his Miami relatives on the day the boy
returned to Cuba. ``Before Elian, I was proud to be an American.
Now I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Elian's legacy is one of confusion, heartbreak and
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the true believers, the reaction is retrenchment,'' said
Damian Fernandez, another Cuban-American academic and author of the
book, Cuba and the Politics of Passion. ``Others feel frustration.
A third group feels apathy and withdrawal, that they don't want to
play the game of politics anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fernandez and Moreno feel the Cuban-American leadership
stumbled badly in their handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their error was to say that it was an issue of communism
versus democracy, while the rest of the world saw it as a
father-son issue,'' Fernandez said. ``Now, they've not only lost
Elian, but they've also lost the public relations battle. Their
image is tarnished in the eyes of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Vazquez, a spokesman for the Cuban-American National
Foundation, the most powerful exile lobbying group, dismissed the
criticism, saying the case was a tragedy that will only re-double
the determination of Castro's foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation's obituary has been written so many times and
it's the furthest thing from the truth,'' he said. ``The Elian saga
is a tremendous tragedy, but the mission of the foundation remains
the same: to bring freedom and democracy to the Cuban people.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno agrees that the community suffered losses, but questions
the long-term impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the attention the case got, the political impact was
really minor,'' he said. ``The pressure to loosen the embargo had
been getting stronger every year. And nothing earth-shaking has
happened. We still really haven't seen how it will play out
politically.''
</P>
<P>
   One interesting impact of the case has been its effect on young
Cuban-Americans. Many observers had believed the younger generation
was more moderate than their parents were, and would inevitably
soften the hard line against Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian shattered that notion,'' Fernandez said. ``Polls
consistently showed that 90 percent of Cuban-Americans wanted Elian
to stay here, regardless of age. I think Elian embodied something
about the Cuban experience that became a cause for them to define
what it means to be Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Elian case will have a lasting impact on U.S.-Cuba
relations in the long-term remains to be seen. But some longtime
Cuba watchers say the case has already triggered important changes.
</P>
<P>
   John Kavulich(CQ) of the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council
believes the Cuban and American governments took an important step
in their handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, whenever there has been a problem with one facet
of the relationship, all the other facets shut down until the
problem was resolved,'' he said. ``In this case we saw a real
effort by both governments to isolate the Elian problem while they
continued to make progress on other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavulich also credits the boy's saga with educating the American
public about Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a necessity for the media to present the context in
which the Elian issue was being debated,'' he said. ``The stories
were substantive and went into areas of Cuban life that were not
discussed before. They also provided a picture that many people
were uncomfortable with, of shouting and threats and the separation
of a parent and child.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, those images will stick with many Americans for years
to come: Cuban-American politicians angrily defying the federal
government; protestors burning American flags in the streets of
Miami and the controversial video made by Elian's Miami relatives
showing the boy lecturing his papa.
</P>
<P>
   Also disturbing was the infamous news photo of a gun-wielding
federal agent reaching out for a terrified Elian.
</P>
<P>
   But the unkindest blow for many Cuban-Americans is in the fact
that Fidel Castro comes out once again looking like the victor,
having somehow turned the tables on the exiles and won the public
relations battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro is clearly the big winner, while in many ways, Elian
has left this community shipwrecked,'' Fernandez said. ``It's left
us without a sense of direction. Unfortunately, I don't see any
institutional effort at change. The community is in shock. I'm not
sure what lessons have been learned, and by whom.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams'' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
