<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ Arms outreached in eagerness,
thousands of peasants, Indians and blue-collar workers lunged for
the sandwiches, potato chips and soft-drinks tossed in plastic bags
from open trucks. They weren't victims of a flood, hurricane or
earthquake. They were voters hauled in from all over Mexico by the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, to attend a rally
in Mexico City's colonial Zocalo plaza. If voters are the quarry,
Mexico's ruling party is the expert hunter in a country where new
election laws are trapped by old political traditions. The election
is Sunday. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-PROBLE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Attorney
General Bill Lockyer is investigating whether a former Insurance
Department official received kickbacks funneled through a football
camp that Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush's children had attended.
Lockyer's office is investigating allegations that former
department official George Grays pocketed up to $90,000 from the
Skillz Athletics Foundation, sources said. Skillz, in turn, had
been given $263,000 by a foundation Grays created with fines levied
against insurance companies, documents and testimony show. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   FACTORY-KILLINGS (Hayward, Calif.) _ In an ironic twist, the
most damaging piece of evidence against a sausage maker facing
triple homicide charges may have been created by the defendant
himself. Stuart Alexander, 39, charged with gunning down three
government meat inspectors at his factory, turned on the store's
surveillance cameras shortly before the shooting rampage, according
to court records. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTAGE-ARCHBISHOP (San Antonio) _ San Antonio Archbishop
Patrick Flores wants the man who held him hostage for nine hours to
get psychological help. The archbishop said he wasn't in a position
to recommend whether Nelson Antonio Escolero, the man charged in
the hostage taking, should face criminal charges. By JOE HOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTAGE-SNIPER (San Antonio) _ A police sniper was positioned to
take action if negotiators failed to persuade a hostage-taker to
put down his weapon and release Archbishop Patrick Flores, police
officials said. By BILL HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTTED-OWN (San Francisco) _ The northern spotted owl, poster
bird for the campaign against logging in national forests, is
thriving just north of San Francisco in Marin County. National Park
Service biologists have found 50 pairs nesting on public land in
the county, including the Golden Gate National Recreation Area,
Muir Woods National Monument and Point Reyes National Seashore. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (San Francisco) _ In a resounding victory for gun
control advocates, the state Supreme Court has upheld California's
1989 ban on military-style assault weapons, the first law of its
kind in the nation. The high court ruled 6-1 that the law did not
discriminate unconstitutionally by outlawing some weapons while
allowing others, arguably just as dangerous. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-FUNERAL (Houston) _ In life, Gary Graham was known as a
convicted murderer. In death, he was hailed as a martyr. About
2,000 mourners turned out Thursday for the funeral of 36-year-old
Graham, who preferred to go by the African name Shaka Sankofa. He
was executed last week for the 1981 killing of Bobby Lambert. By
AMY DORSETT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The Justice Department has
defended its approval of Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the San
Francisco Chronicle, but turned down a federal judge's invitation
to take part in an antitrust case over the deal, apparently
removing the last obstacle to a ruling by U.S. District Judge
Vaughn Walker. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-STORM (Undated) _ It wasn't long after the money
shot of that minuscule fishing boat meeting that obscenely large
wave (in a sure prelude to the Universal Studios knock-off ride)
that I knew it was OK to throw ``The Perfect Storm'' back in. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BULLWINKLE (Undated) _ Robert De Niro plays Fearless
Leader, alongside Rene Russo and Jason Alexander as Boris and
Natasha in the mixed cartoon-live-action ``The Adventures of Rocky
and Bullwinkle'' _ known in precocious children's circles as
``Mommy, Who Framed These People?'' Universal's update of the
40-year-old ``Bullwinkle Show'' is an insulting thing to ask a kid
to slog through. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BOURGEOISIE (Undated) _ Luis Buuel was as old as the
20th century when he made ``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie''
in 1972. Time was his twin, a sibling that he learned to bend
violently to his satirical, anti-realist will. Their rapport only
deepened as Buuel aged, and ``The Discreet Charm of the
Bourgeoisie'' is the tidy manifestation of those years. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-MUSICIANS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Fuel costs affect musicians
nationwide, especially those who provide their own travel and pay
their own expenses. ``I'm feeling the pinch of the increase
everywhere,'' says Chris Shaw, a solo artist based in Albany.
``It's reflected in my airline tickets, then when I get off of the
plane, it hits again at the gas pump with a rental car.'' By MIKE
HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-WORKPLACE (San Antonio) _ The unlikely partners of
business and nature marry beautifully at Ultramar Diamond Shamrock
Corp. headquarters in northwest San Antonio. The corporate campus
for more than 900 workers sits on 54 hilly acres where green
predominates _ a sharp contrast to typical corporate gray asphalt
and concrete. By TRACY HOBSON LEHMANN.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK-LIGHTING (Undated) _ Track lighting is one of the most
versatile forms of artificial lighting available. It can be used as
task or accent lighting, from showing off works of art to simply
creating a mood. For flexibility, it can be mounted just about
anywhere and cut or pieced to any length. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Larry Ellison and I have almost
nothing in common. I don't have a jillion bucks, a Gulfstream G-5
jet or a mansion constructed Japanese-style with no nails. But
there is one big thing the flamboyant CEO of Oracle Corp. and I do
have in common. I have gone through other people's trash, as a
``public service,'' to use Ellison's words. It's a basic
reportorial technique, but not one taught at the Columbia
Journalism School. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
