</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BOURGEOISIE (Undated) _ Luis Buuel was as old as the
20th century when he made ``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie''
in 1972. Time was his twin, a sibling that he learned to bend
violently to his satirical, anti-realist will. Their rapport only
deepened as Buuel aged, and ``The Discreet Charm of the
Bourgeoisie'' is the tidy manifestation of those years. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-MUSICIANS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Fuel costs affect musicians
nationwide, especially those who provide their own travel and pay
their own expenses. ``I'm feeling the pinch of the increase
everywhere,'' says Chris Shaw, a solo artist based in Albany.
``It's reflected in my airline tickets, then when I get off of the
plane, it hits again at the gas pump with a rental car.'' By MIKE
HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-WORKPLACE (San Antonio) _ The unlikely partners of
business and nature marry beautifully at Ultramar Diamond Shamrock
Corp. headquarters in northwest San Antonio. The corporate campus
for more than 900 workers sits on 54 hilly acres where green
predominates _ a sharp contrast to typical corporate gray asphalt
and concrete. By TRACY HOBSON LEHMANN.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK-LIGHTING (Undated) _ Track lighting is one of the most
versatile forms of artificial lighting available. It can be used as
task or accent lighting, from showing off works of art to simply
creating a mood. For flexibility, it can be mounted just about
anywhere and cut or pieced to any length. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Larry Ellison and I have almost
nothing in common. I don't have a jillion bucks, a Gulfstream G-5
jet or a mansion constructed Japanese-style with no nails. But
there is one big thing the flamboyant CEO of Oracle Corp. and I do
have in common. I have gone through other people's trash, as a
``public service,'' to use Ellison's words. It's a basic
reportorial technique, but not one taught at the Columbia
Journalism School. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
