<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ While the two leading candidates
in Mexico's upcoming presidential election represent opposite views
of where Mexico's political system will go and have vastly
different personalities, they are remarkably close on the issues.
By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S. (Chicago) _ To an unprecedented degree, the
Mexican election has come north of the border, to the United
States. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MCDONALDS (Millau) _ The trial of the left-wing militant
Jose Bove, accused of criminal damage to a McDonald's, opened here
Friday in a carnival atmosphere as thousands of anti-globalization
protesters crammed into this southern French market town. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to approve
a spending bill that includes funds to help fight the drug war in
Colombia and for peacekeeping in Kosovo before it adjourns for the
Fourth of July holiday. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BOAT (Jakarta) _ They fled in terror, many of them
women and children, after 200 fellow villagers were killed in
Christian-Muslim violence in the Spice Islands. Now, with no trace
of their sunken ferry, it seems that 500 refugees are dead. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ North and South Korea signed a deal to
reunite aging family members separated by the Korean War half a
century ago and to return dozens of North Korean spies held in the
South. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-POLITICS (Kampala) _ President Yoweri Museveni has won
his referendum on maintaining a ``no party'' system, but the
ultra-low voter turnout has prompted both sides to claim victory.
By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
