<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BULLWINKLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `ROCKY AND BULLWINKLE': NO FUN INTENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' Universal's update
of the 40-year-old ``Bullwinkle Show,'' is an insulting thing to
ask a kid to slog through.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes are the same desperate cops to coolness that the
Muppets have been choking on for years. The biggest gags are in the
dead-on, but largely dead, casting, and thankfully will leave the
young unsullied.
</P>
<P>
   The original series co-opted a benign entertainment format to
throw political daggers at the Cold War. The movie is a dim conceit
in search of a fast-food tie-in; it doesn't even work as passable
kitsch, and Rene Russo and Jason Alexander (as Natasha and Boris)
are too mechanical for even midlevel camp. Anyone thinking that
bringing the two famously bumbling Russian spies into the flesh was
a brilliant idea must have missed Sally Kellerman and Dave Thomas
in ``Boris and Natasha'' (1992). Nonetheless, they have done it
anyway with ``Rocky and Bullwinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with a teen-age FBI agent (Piper Perabo, a plucky
girl who seems in over her head anyway), the obtuse moose and
flying squirrel remain cartoon relics left to fend for themselves
and foil Boris, Natasha and Robert De Niro's bottomlessly scary
Fearless Leader. The trio still wants to obliterate Rocky and
Bullwinkle and take over the world, only to find it has changed
over 35 years, which means they are hatching their plan even more
slowly than they did in the cartoon series.
</P>
<P>
   And die-hards should be relieved to know that they also are
still punishing in their stupidity. In fact, inside and out, idiocy
rules ``Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' a movie too dumb to realize that
the senselessness is viral. The deadly puns move faster than the
story by playwright Kenneth Lonergan, and the hipness quotient
ropes in Nickelodeon sketch comics Kennan and Kel, as well as good
names like Janeane Garofalo, Whoopi Goldberg, Billy Crystal, John
Goodman, Carl Reiner, David Alan Grier and a triple dose of a
craggy Jonathan Winters.
</P>
<P>
   There are Crips and Bloods who come out of drive-bys less
scathed. Some (Crystal, Reiner) seem coerced, others (Garofalo,
Goodman) look bored, and Goldberg actually spends half her stint
dozing off.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Des McAnuff, it's less ``Roger Rabbit'' and more the
``Rabbit'' imitation of ``Cool World.'' The whole thing looks and
feels like the cheap, plotless satire ``Austin Powers'' somehow
avoided though sheer self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   In what I imagine was meant as a poignant gag, Rocky and
Bullwinkle are still despondent over their life in reruns, smarting
perhaps over the dominance of ``The Simpsons'' and the lack of
Cartoon Network support. But they are not vengeful, they are mopey.
The film is clinically depressed, too. And it doesn't take long for
the self-pity to grow contagious then mutate into audience
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, my date with ``The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' was a kidless one. There was no one to snicker when
Bullwinkle talks to a wall or cheer when the Boris, Natasha and
Fearless get their big kiss-off. Yet, when Russo confesses to
Alexander, ``Let's face it darlink, we suck,'' is there a child
alive who would sit there unarmed with a comeback? Is there a kid
who would prefer to be at the movie than in line for Harry Potter
4?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
