<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BOURGEOIS     06-30 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BOURGEOISIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE EXTANT CHARMS OF `DISCREET' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luis Buuel was as old as the 20th century when he made ``The
Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie'' in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   His alignment with the 20th century took on a cosmic, psychic
dimension. Time was his twin, a sibling that he learned to bend
violently to his satirical, anti-realist will. Their rapport only
deepened as Buuel aged, and ``The Discreet Charm of the
Bourgeoisie'' is the tidy manifestation of those years.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of Buuel's hundredth birthday (he died in 1983), Rialto
Pictures has re-released the film in a refurbished print with new
subtitles that better preserve the verbal wit often overshadowed by
the visual glee. Six upper-class diners in search of the perfect,
undisturbed meal never get a decent meal as, with sublime
ridiculousness, food is snatched from their mouths whenever
possible. The film plays as the cheekier, more blithe converse of
``The Exterminating Angel,'' in which a group of dinner guests is
trapped at a meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discreet Charm'' is more repast interruptus, with the three
men and three women being denied food over an indefinite or
infinite period. Time is banished here, as politics intrude, death
knocks, circumstances are misperceived and dreams are tethered to
dreams within dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a reaction against bourgeois living and bourgeois
filmmaking. And this film is funny where something like ``Belle Du
Jour'' or ``The Milky Way'' was contentedly dour in its gimmicks.
Buuel let the anger go, the embers of his cynicism having cooled
into room-temperature mockery.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Rey plays the French ambassador from the South American
principality of Miranda. He is a Casanova, engaged in indiscretions
with one of the other men's wives (Delphine Seyrig). The men
(Jean-Pierre Cassel and Paul Frankuer are the other two) are covert
partners in a hot coke-smuggling operation. The women (Seyrig,
Bulle Ogier and the ever-striking Stephane Audran), meanwhile, are
ladies-who-lunch types. They sit around in restaurants and cafes on
the verge of being appalled. They live in contempt of a service
industry that couldn't possibly conceive of the subtler pleasures
lurking in society's upper echelons, but they're hardly
contemptible themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Buuel is careful _ no, carefree _ not to typify the principals.
Sure they show glimmers of disaffection. Ennui is a four-letter
word, and Buuel is far from pulling strings on automatons. These
characters have always lived like this and they love it.
</P>
<P>
   The film's discreet charm is Buuel's finesse. The six characters
always look simultaneously pleased with themselves and completely
confounded. With each thwarted meal comes a look of astonishment as
if letting the actors know that something absurd was about to
happen had slipped Buuel's mind. If there's a granddaddy of breezy
situationalism, it's probably Buuel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-STORM-HNS     06-30 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-STORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE IMPERFECT `STORM' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't long after the money shot of that minuscule fishing
boat meeting that obscenely large wave that I knew it was OK to
throw ``The Perfect Storm'' back in.
</P>
<P>
   The boat's name is Andrea Gail, and she has barely survived an
exciting thrashing, her six-man crew holding on for dear life. But
there's Mark Wahlberg, separated from the ship, bobbing in the
monstrous digi-waves of the Atlantic, offering this psychic
assurance to his ladylove who sits forlorn thousands of miles away
in a bar watching the news hoping he'll return home: ``There's only
love, Christina. There's only love.''
</P>
<P>
   That's merely the climax of the misty-eyed audio missive
delivered to the audience, who serves as Christina's (tittering)
stand-in. Inexplicably, the filmmakers have chosen to superimpose
Diane Lane, our Christina, over the calming tempest, next to
Wahlberg's plaintive face. It's a moment so savagely Marky Mark
that it's a wonder no one thought to have the Funky Bunch
hydroplaned in. It's also a betrayal of a guy who has worked his
abs off to become a persuasive actor.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, ``The Perfect Storm,'' an enthralling special-effects tour
de force with a lover's nook. Rare is that summer blockbuster with
the nerve to sport a wife-beater while whispering sweet nothings
like Mike Tyson. Adapted from Sebastian Junger's best-selling
account of a true meteorological anomaly and directed by the
reliable action-flick sophisticate Wolfgang Petersen, ``The Perfect
Storm'' knows you've come for brutal oceanic action but also thinks
you demand to see ``Titanic.'' Of course: titanic weather, titanic
death, titanic sea-faring facial hair growth!
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the romance in this,'' our beloved Christina tells
Wahlberg's Bobby as he heads back out to sea. Neither do we.
</P>
<P>
   The film, written by William Dale Wittliff, has visions of
Ahab-like passion to conquer turbulent waters and conquer the
marine life. Let's face it though, the boys, with their blue
collars and land-locked responsibilities, are in it for the money.
After receiving far less pay from his haul of swordfish than he
expected, captain Billy Tyne (George Clooney) mounts a small
Gloucester, Mass., crew to hit the Atlantic for what is played as
the old One Last Score. In the meantime, a nor'easter has taken a
great deal of steroids and become Mother Nature's bastard child, a
storm unprecedented in its scale.
</P>
<P>
   On land, each of the women, exercising her intuitive rapport
with the weather, has a terrible feeling about this trip. They show
up at the dock with their extra-strength goodbyes belying the wan,
worried morning sickness on their faces. It's the sensitive,
instinct-driven equivalent of the way cups of water would ripple
before T-Rex struck in ``Jurassic Park.'' Only, you feel nagged.
</P>
<P>
   Excepting the nice touch of the grime beneath the actors
fingernails, the film is more interested in the sacrificial heroism
of the mission than the grit of the job. Read: They're in it for
the effects.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the industrial light and magic arrives with a storm
monstrous in its scope, ominous and loud enough to leave you in
appropriate awe. Petersen is of the
more-bang-for-your-bargain-matinee-buck school of efficiency,
deftly moving almost rhythmically between the plight of the Andrea
Gail, the Coast Guard rescue of Cherry Jones and Karen Allen from a
yacht and the women gathered in Bobby's mother's bar watching the
Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Andrea Gail's rogue skipper, Billy. Well, call him
Clooney. Clooney's stern drive is classy, straightforward and
inwardly heroic. He's not asked to do anything more grandiose than
keep a flinty, altruistic gaze fixed on the computer-generated
waves. The remaining five guys in this six-pack of manly types
(John C. Reilly, William Fichtner, Allen Payne) are drawn straight
from the ``Poseidon Adventure'' course on how antagonistic
personality types in an enclosed space generate tension, chaos,
healing.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years before, Petersen did this with unfurling,
nightmarish precision over the 210-minute run time of ``Das Boot.''
It's still his finest hour as a technician of the kinetic and the
unknown. His best film since, ``In the Line of Fire,'' used a
similar MO to make a Hollywood cat-and-mouse thriller something
more visceral than it should have been. ``The Perfect Storm'' is
``Das Boot's'' thrill-seeking teen-age American cousin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
