<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-GAS-MUSICIANS-HNS &LR;      06-30 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-MUSICIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RISING GAS PRICES LEAVE ROVING MUSICIANS PLAYING THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Kevin McKrell, like most motorists, is feeling
the pocket-pinching prices of gasoline. Yet the pinch has a tighter
grip on McKrell, because the musician and his band, the McKrells,
travel in a 30-foot motor home that averages 10 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The McKrells normally tour a major portion of the United States
and Canada during the summer. However, McKrell decided to limit
this summer's itinerary to shows within 500 miles of Albany. Rising
gas prices, coupled with a steep entrance fee into Canada for an
American band, prompted him to cancel the Canadian leg of the
band's tour.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel costs affect musicians nationwide, especially those who
provide their own travel and pay their own expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling the pinch of the increase everywhere,'' says Chris
Shaw, a solo artist who normally performs in the Adirondacks of
upstate New York during the summer. ``It's reflected in my airline
tickets, then when I get off of the plane, it hits again at the gas
pump with a rental car.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists call that scenario trickle-down economics, a
situation where an increase in the price of one good will cause
increased prices for many others. Shaw calls it ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   McKrell concurs: ``The profit margin for doing shows is small
enough.'' An excursion to Boston or Philadelphia for a low-paying
gig just isn't worth it, says McKrell, because of fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gamsjager of the Lustre Kings is affected, but he knows
that paying more at the pump is unavoidable. ``We travel 45,000
miles a year just touring,'' Gamsjager says. ``Clubs won't pay a
certain amount more because gas prices are up. You just have to put
your head down and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices hurt audiences as well as performers, which the
artists also have considered. ``Are the people that were going to
vacation in the Adirondacks coming from Pennsylvania now going to
find a closer place?'' asks Shaw, worrying about the turnout he may
receive when he plays Blue Mountain Lake in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Many artists will be swallowing the higher costs of fuel. Most
will keep what McKrell calls the ``Pearl Jam attitude,'' of trying
to keep prices at a reasonable level so that the fans are not
punished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GREEN-WORKPLACE-HNS &LR;      06-30 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-WORKPLACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMPANY PLANTS ITS HEADQUARTERS IN A PARK-LIKE SETTING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TRACY HOBSON LEHMANN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ What do you get when you combine corporate culture
and wildlife?
</P>
<P>
   This is no riddle. It is reality.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely partners of business and nature marry beautifully
at the Ultramar Diamond Shamrock Corp. (UDS) headquarters in
northwest San Antonio. The corporate campus sits on 54 hilly acres
that were once home to cattle and assorted wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 950 employees work at the site, where green predominates
_ a sharp contrast to typical corporate gray asphalt and concrete.
Wildflowers bloom in medians that look more like meadows than part
of the thoroughfare that funnels automobiles into the parking
garage. Around the visitor parking lot, butterflies float among the
flowers and birds chirp welcoming notes to guests. Shrubs, trees
and flowers native to South Texas provide ample cover for wildlife,
allowing the critters to coexist comfortably with people.
</P>
<P>
   The idyllic setting at UDS reflects the comfortable, laid-back
culture of the petroleum and petrochemicals corporation, says
spokeswoman Tara Ford. The khaki- and polo-clad employees not only
look out over the tree-covered vistas from their cubicles, but they
also enjoy the landscape up close. Paths meander through the trees,
leading workers into the wild for a respite from computers and
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving the natural setting was a goal of former UDS chairman
and chief executive Roger Hemminghaus, says facilities manager
Randy Mellinger. He and Ford were part of an employee committee
that devised a wish list for the new headquarters, completed in
late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says they wanted a building that had a resort look. The
resulting two-story structure, built from limestone quarried
nearby, suits its setting well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building was kept low so you could view the natural
surroundings,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And what a view it is.
</P>
<P>
   Ample windows expose the expanse of green. From the employee
cafeteria, the view includes a mesmerizing fountain and a
stream-fed pond that attracts an array of birds. Bright green
prairie buffalo grass bends in the breeze, its soft texture
reminiscent of a favorite blanket stretched out under the sun.
Beyond, trees envelop the open area, creating a sense of mystery
about the wild world that cohabitates with the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Employees, developers and builders worked to preserve the trees
at the site, Mellinger says. Every tree of more than 4 inches in
diameter was plotted on a map, and the building was sited to save
as many of them as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It is a conservation theme that shaped the landscape around the
building and earned UDS the 2000 Naturalist Preservation Award from
the Texas Master Naturalist group. The corporation was selected
``for preserving the area around the headquarters and choosing to
keep it in a natural state and for including a large variety of
native plants in the landscape design,'' says Master Naturalist
President Thea Platz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept intact pretty much everything that was native,''
Mellinger says. Native species such as lantana, autumn sage and
cenizo were used in plantings around the building.
</P>
<P>
   In wild areas, obvious natives such as live oaks, agarita,
prickly pear and mountain laurels grow alongside lesser-known
specimens common in the wild: senna, cassia, elbow bush and
escarpment cherry.
</P>
<P>
   The native plants, Platz points out, provide food and shelter
for mammals, birds and butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   At UDS, the wildlife seems appreciative. A rock squirrel
scampers along a retaining wall, stopping to survey passersby and
seek out morsels from the ground. The same retaining wall was
natural enough for a fox to have a litter of pups among the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Possums, raccoons, ringtail cats and deer all are among the
animals that browse the UDS grounds and an adjoining 93 acres of
undeveloped land owned by the corporation. And, unlike many
neighborhoods that find their landscapes a buffet for wildlife, the
UDS fauna rarely disturb the flora.
</P>
<P>
   The animals ``don't have to decimate to survive. Natives need
natives; they recognize food sources that are inherent,'' Platz
says. ``This is an awesome example of what can be done with
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Preserving native plants, particularly smaller trees that
provide cover, enables wildlife to survive as humans move into
animal territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's sorely lacking in traditional landscapes is the
understory,'' she explains. ``You have canopy, and you have turf.
But you don't have shelter and food sources.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage understory trees such as redbuds and mountain
laurels, UDS elected to remove cedar trees. Though Platz contests
the popular theory that removing cedars _ really Ashe junipers _
saves water, she agrees that it is best to remove the familiar
evergreens. ``Oaks and cedars use the same amount of water, but
cedars form mottes so the water can't get into the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews cut cedar by hand so they wouldn't disturb other plants
and shredded the trees into mulch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to aesthetic and wildlife benefits, UDS also sees
payback in maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas many office complexes buzz with the cacophony of mowers
and blowers at least once a week, mowing is kept to a minimum at
UDS, says Brad Hold of Precision Lawn Maintenance. The grass is cut
three or four times a year, which also curtails watering.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were cutting this grass every week, it would cost about
$10,000 a month,'' he says. UDS spends about $3,500 a month on
grounds maintenance. About 30 acres of the developed area is
watered with a carefully programmed automatic irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
   Though individual homeowners don't share such a large-scale
landscape budget, they can take lessons from the corporate
experience and enjoy similar benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have noxious animals no matter what you do,''
Platz says. ``What you won't have is songbirds and butterflies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TRACK-LIGHTING-HNS &LR;      06-30 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACK-LIGHTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRACK LIGHTING: BRIGHT IDEA FOR SHOWCASING ART 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Track lighting is one of the most versatile forms of artificial
lighting available.
</P>
<P>
   It can be used as task or accent lighting, from showing off
works of art to simply creating a mood.
</P>
<P>
   For flexibility, it can be mounted just about anywhere and cut
or pieced to any length.
</P>
<P>
   This type of lighting is not difficult to install. A good place
to start is with an existing light fixture in the ceiling. From
there, you can branch out in any direction to focus the individual
lights on the areas or objects you wish to illuminate.
</P>
<P>
   Newer designs in track lighting originate from a ceiling outlet
with a suspended track, giving the effect of a contemporary
chandelier.
</P>
<P>
   There are several do-it-yourself track lighting systems on sale
at lighting stores and in most home centers.
</P>
<P>
   The track is secured to the ceiling and individual lamps or
lighting heads are snapped into place and rotated to any direction.
</P>
<P>
   Finishes include black or white, polished, matte or brushed
brass, chrome or graphite.
</P>
<P>
   Before you purchase a system, decide where you are going to
place the track and what you plan to highlight. Research the light
spread, so you don't end up with too little or too much light.
</P>
<P>
   A small light can throw off as much light as a large fixture.
Compact, low-voltage halogen bulbs provide a bright white light,
and reflector bulbs focus light.
</P>
<P>
   A dimmer switch controls the intensity of the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Track lights come in a variety of shapes. Decide what will look
best with the scale and style of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Never try to mix brands or modify fixtures. Tracks are usually
sold in two-foot increments and connectors should be used with runs
of more than 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Track lighting was the brainchild of lighting designer Edison
Avery Price. His work can be seen in hundreds of museums around the
world, including the lobby of the Seagram Building in Manhattan,
the Museum of Modern Art, the Whitney Museum and the Louvre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAND OF CYBERTRASH AND E-ESPIONAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Larry Ellison and I have almost nothing in
common. I don't have a jillion bucks, a Gulfstream G-5 jet or a
mansion constructed Japanese-style with no nails. My sailboats were
just dinghies and I never took them out in gales. I only wage war
with Bill Gates when I try to use a Windows PC at work, and I
always lose.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one big thing the flamboyant chief executive of
Oracle Corp. and I do have in common. I have gone through other
people's trash, and as a ``public service,'' to use Ellison's
words. It's a basic reportorial technique, but not one taught at
the Columbia Journalism School.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been keeping up, the best trash news lately has
been in the Wall Street Journal, not ``Inside Edition'' or Talk
magazine. Ellison admitted that Oracle hired private investigators
to sift through the trash of groups that supported rival Microsoft
in its antitrust struggles with the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence was there among the orange peels and stained
Styrofoam cups. Oracle's dicks discovered that several of those
``independent'' groups were funded by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Silicon Valley is in a gleeful uproar trying to decide
who's sleazier, Ellison for hacking into other people's crumpled
paper, or Gates for secretly paying for supporters.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I'm concerned, they're both high-living lowlifes, but
then I'm prejudiced. They can afford to pay applauding economic
institutes and trash-sniffing detectives. When I did my Dumpster
diving I had to do it myself, and it was much less elegant than
that Silicon Valley saying about ``garbage in, garbage out.''
</P>
<P>
   In garbage, outing garbage. It's literally the dirtiest of dirty
tricks.
</P>
<P>
   I do mean garbage. Long ago I was an anonymous restaurant
reviewer, and went in a fancy restaurant's Dumpster to determine
exactly what kind of canned and frozen gunk the local celebrity
chef was putting on a plate and selling for the equivalent of one
of his busboy's daily take-home pay.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ellison and his detective agency, I can claim that
technically I didn't break the law. In their case, the paperwork
that companies throw away isn't private because it's been thrown
away.
</P>
<P>
   Dumpsters are trickier than wastebaskets. Read the signs on the
sides. Throwing things in Dumpsters without permission (Dumpster
abuse, as it's commonly called) is a crime. But everything I put in
the Dumpster I took out _ namely, me.
</P>
<P>
   I also took out some confidential culinary information, like the
chef's love of such indelicacies as frozen fish, factory-made
stocks and canned bearnaise sauce. Yes, there is such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   My excuse? The public had a right to know what they were putting
in their mouths at $25 a pop. I knew the food was bad, but I wanted
to see the labels on the cans for myself. Restaurant reviewing _
it's a tough job, but somebody has to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's excuse? The public has a right to know that an outfit
in Oakland, Calif., called the Independent Institute, which has
criticized the government's antitrust suit against Microsoft, also
took $153,000 from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The more information members of the public have, the better they
can judge for themselves whether they like canned bearnaise sauce
or believe the Independent Institute's ``Open Letter on Antitrust
Protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd rather spoon down a whole can of bad bearnaise
than read any more pap about Microsoft as a powerful engine of
innovation behind the single greatest economic revolution since the
dawn of the industrial age.
</P>
<P>
   It's much more entertaining to read about a billionaire going
through another billionaire's garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the possibilities for the vast landfill of TV. ``And
now, here's Regis Dustbin, the host of ``Who Wants to Be a
Billionaire's Garbologist?''
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to get caught going through anyone's garbage.
That's what I used to think.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to be called ``Nixonian,'' as Ellison has. That's
what I used to think, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm not so sure. I went into that restaurant's Dumpster with
great trepidation, and not only at the thought of wading through E.
coli and possibly getting tetanus from the lid of an
industrial-size can of petits pois.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different time and a different place. In a Southern
city 15 years ago, a gentleman simply didn't climb into another
gentleman's garbage unless very, very drunk or in a Tennessee
Williams play. Well, I did.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have the sight of reporters eagerly asking Ellison if
he's been going through Gates' garbage, and Ellison proudly saying
that it was a public service, and he'd be happy to ship all his
garbage to Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage out? Garbage in.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV0     06-30 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STAY THE COURSE VERSUS PASSION FOR CHANGE AS MEXICANS VOTE
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A few hours south of here, Angel Mina proudly
recites the history of Emiliano Zapata, the Mexican revolutionary
who helped overthrow a dictatorship and usher in a new era for this
country 90 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, Mina said, precisely because he is passionate
about Zapata, he will vote against the political party that emerged
from the revolutionary's cause for land and liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for change,'' the guide at the Zapata Museum in
Morelos state said firmly, repeating a slogan of opposition
presidential candidate Vicente Fox Quesada. ``Enough of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Mexico _ the world's fifth biggest oil producer, but
where half the population lives in poverty _ similar calls for
change are making Sunday's historic general election the most
competitive and bitterly fought in modern history. More than 58
million people are eligible to vote for a new Congress, dozens of
local leaders and president.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the
PRI, has controlled this country's presidency for 71 years _ the
longest reign of any party in the world. The party is still
indisputably powerful, but its candidate, Francisco Labastida
Ochoa, is on the defensive against a surge by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has invested about $1.7 billion in public money since
1998 in election reforms, and balloting is supposed to be the
cleanest ever. The campaign has been clouded, however, by scores of
allegations of vote buying and coercion by PRI operatives.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the election, the PRI governor of Yucatan
presented poor residents of his state with cut-rate washing
machines, water tanks, cement floors inscribed with his name and
machetes. He argued he wasn't buying votes because votes are
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Women enrolled in the federal welfare program Progresa in a
number of states have reported pressure at meetings to vote for the
PRI or lose benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is impunity in this area,'' admitted Jaime Cardenas, one
of Mexico's nine counselors at the independent Federal Elections
Institute. He also said there were sporadic reports of attempts to
take people's credentials to prevent them from voting, or party
officials trying to discourage independent citizens from serving as
poll supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter is in Mexico to observe the
elections along with more than 800 other foreigners. In a
pre-election report, the Atlanta-based Carter Center said Mexico
has made ``great strides'' toward ensuring a fair election, but
that ``serious charges of the abuse of government resources have
been made; not all of them have been investigated or pursued as
vigorously as we believe they should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear of reprisal for denouncing coercion still reigns in many
remote areas, said political analyst Jose Antonio Crespo.
</P>
<P>
   A Mixe Indian in Oaxaca state has asked authorities to
investigate the death of his brother, who he claims was killed in
police custody after criticizing a local PRI candidate during a
public meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you speak up in isolated areas, you are not protected,''
Crespo said.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of this tense backdrop, the election is still
considered the fairest and tightest in history.
</P>
<P>
   Media coverage during the campaign, once again, grew
increasingly biased toward the PRI, according to election
officials. But new laws gave top candidates almost equal public
funding and the right to buy radio and television time for ads.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion surveys suggest that Labastida is locked in a dead heat
with Fox, a tall, cowboy-booted rancher and former Coca-Cola
executive who has mounted the toughest campaign ever of any
opposition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This July 2, rain, thunder or lightning, you have a date with
history. Don't let it go by,'' Fox, a former governor of Guanajuato
state, told Mexicans in a final television ad. A high turn-out
among urban and young voters is critical for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox's party, the National Action Party, or PAN, is
conservative, Fox has promised to lead a plural ``transition'' from
one-party rule. To win, Fox must attract votes from leftist
candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, who polls suggest trails
in third place. Cardenas, who has labeled Fox a right-wing
reactionary, refused to drop out of the race to unite the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's advantage is among government workers who belong to
PRI-affiliated organizations and people who live in rural
provinces. Labastida, whose slogan is ``change with a purpose,''
has criss-crossed the country to shore up that traditional support.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointment with the PRI is undeniably strong. Although the
economy has recovered to some degree, Mexicans were devastated by a
December 1994 peso crash that cut their purchasing power in half.
</P>
<P>
   They have seen manufacturing for export in their country
flourish, making Mexico in 1998 the United States' second largest
trading partner. Yet Mexico has one of the worst gaps in wages
between rich and poor of any Latin American country.
</P>
<P>
   The average education level is only seven years, less than in
communist Cuba. And revelations of drug-trafficking ties and
corrupt acts by high-ranking PRI officials in recent years have
disgusted Mexicans and strained relations with United States.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has pledged to attack corruption with vigor and pay
more attention to poverty. The three-time cabinet member and former
Sinaloa state governor has promised to help families by cutting
prices for cooking oil, and offering more subsidies to farmers and
poor schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of belt-tightening is over,'' Labastida said in a
final speech. ``The years to come are years when salaries will grow
annually above inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in remote areas, where the PRI has always won, voters
are considering alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear that people are saying, 'No more PRI,''' said Juana
Soto, 58, who lives in Sierra de Nanchital, a remote municipality
dotted with oil wells in eastern Veracruz state.
</P>
<P>
   Residents here say they've been waiting for decades for
authorities to build a decent road into their farming town, but
promises have gone unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no life here,'' Soto said. ``I have 10 children and
only two live here now. Seven of them are in North Carolina
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Soto isn't sure who she'll vote for, but it won't be the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad Hernandez, 40, a local shopkeeper, is for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the moment many of us have decided we need a change,''
he said. ``We're willing to take a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Morelos state town of Tetelcingo, Felix Balon supports
Labastida. He belongs to a PRI farmers' group, and while he isn't
fully happy with the party he credits it with giving him federal
government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Labastida was agricultural secretary we got a well for
about 100 farmers. We got several concrete posts for a fence,'' the
54-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   Balon's younger brother, Antonio, 45, said, ``I'm a PRI member.
But what good does it do me when harvest time comes around and they
don't make sure prices are decent for my crops?''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Balon didn't rule out voting for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Antonia Ramirez of Anenecuilco _ where Zapata was born _ said
she's for Fox and her sister for Labastida. .
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox wants to help people who have to go to the United States
to work,'' said Ramirez, who usually is in Denver working as a
hotel maid. ``But my sister works at Social Security (Mexico's
federal health system) and she says she's been told that if Fox
wins he will get rid of all the unions and privatize government
agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, home to more than 10 percent of the electorate,
illiterate Otomi Indian street vender Josefina _ she wouldn't give
her last name _ will vote for Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   After Cardenas became mayor of Mexico City in 1997, Josefina
said, she started keeping more of the $5 to $10 a day she earns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Cardenas I had to pay $1 or $2 to someone (from the
PRI) so I could sell things here,'' the 37-year-old mother of eight
said. ``Now I don't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fernando Rodriguez, 23, who washes parked cars for a living,
said, ``Fox seems like an honest person. Let's see if he'll keep
his promises and not steal like the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   In the highly populated state of Mexico, home to 13 percent of
the country's electorate, university student and PRI militant
Claudia Gonzalez said people should be grateful to the party.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the federal government invested heavily in public
works in Chalco, a former slum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do your schools come from?'' she said. ``From the
government. And remember, that government is a PRI government.
Where does your water come from? From the government. And remember,
that government is a PRI government.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, Elvia Herrera, 65, displayed a Fox sign on her
front window. She lives near an area that was flooded with sewage
recently when neglected pipes burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is a Mafia,'' she said, beginning to cry. ``I've had
it with these thieves. I worked all my life to build this house _
as a nanny, a cook, a cleaning lady, a secretary. And from one day
to the next those people build huge houses for themselves after
they get into office.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Luis Miguel Rionda, a University of Guanajuato political
analyst, said Mexicans have traditionally been cautious voters who
looked for change within the ruling party and took their cues from
unions or neighborhood associations.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mexico becomes more urban and opposition parties gain
ground in state houses and Congress, he said, voters are making
more individual choices. Plus, he said, ``none of the PRI's last
four (former) presidents ended their terms well. There was an
economic crisis after every one of them. Mexicans have grown tired
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   www.ife.org.mx
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV0     06-30 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STAY THE COURSE VERSUS PASSION FOR CHANGE AS MEXICANS VOTE
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
