said. ``Now I don't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fernando Rodriguez, 23, who washes parked cars for a living,
said, ``Fox seems like an honest person. Let's see if he'll keep
his promises and not steal like the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   In the highly populated state of Mexico, home to 13 percent of
the country's electorate, university student and PRI militant
Claudia Gonzalez said people should be grateful to the party.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the federal government invested heavily in public
works in Chalco, a former slum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do your schools come from?'' she said. ``From the
government. And remember, that government is a PRI government.
Where does your water come from? From the government. And remember,
that government is a PRI government.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, Elvia Herrera, 65, displayed a Fox sign on her
front window. She lives near an area that was flooded with sewage
recently when neglected pipes burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is a Mafia,'' she said, beginning to cry. ``I've had
it with these thieves. I worked all my life to build this house _
as a nanny, a cook, a cleaning lady, a secretary. And from one day
to the next those people build huge houses for themselves after
they get into office.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Luis Miguel Rionda, a University of Guanajuato political
analyst, said Mexicans have traditionally been cautious voters who
looked for change within the ruling party and took their cues from
unions or neighborhood associations.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mexico becomes more urban and opposition parties gain
ground in state houses and Congress, he said, voters are making
more individual choices. Plus, he said, ``none of the PRI's last
four (former) presidents ended their terms well. There was an
economic crisis after every one of them. Mexicans have grown tired
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   www.ife.org.mx
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
