<HEADLINE>
CENTURIES-OLD TREES PRESERVE NEW ENGLAND'S ANCIENT HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILL, Mass. _ As cars and trucks roared behind him on busy Route
2, Bob Leverett looked out from the French King Bridge across the
Connecticut River. A cigarette boat zoomed upstream below, while a
hawk soared over the sagging power lines. But Leverett was
transfixed by a scraggly white pine tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There it is,'' Leverett said, gesturing at the 100-foot-tall
pine jutting above the rest of the woods on the steep riverbank.
``Just look at the architecture of that big old tree. It's exactly
what we look for.''
</P>
<P>
   The weathered 250-year-old tree marks the spot of a 20-acre
stand of rare old-growth forest Leverett discovered two weeks ago.
Somehow, these trees had escaped the woodsman's ax since before the
American Revolution, despite centuries of logging, farming and
construction going on around them.
</P>
<P>
   The forest in Gill is part of a boom in the discovery of ``new''
old growth fueled by amateur old-growth sleuths such as Leverett, a
59-year-old Tennessee native now living in Holyoke. Once believed
to be virtually nonexistent in New England _ where 19th century
farmers denuded most of the landscape _ old growth is making a
remarkable comeback.
</P>
<P>
   These days, old-growth forests are turning up virtually by the
week. There were about 135,000 acres known in the Northeast a
decade ago. But since then, and especially in the last few years,
hundreds of thousands of acres have been found. They now total as
many as 1,700 acres in Massachusetts, 400 in Connecticut, 50 in
Rhode Island, 3,000 in Vermont, 20,000 in New Hampshire, 50,000 in
Maine, and 500,000 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up in Boston in the '50s, I was under the
impression there was virtually no old growth left in New England,''
said John O'Keefe, coordinator of the Fisher Museum at Harvard
Forest. ``But now we're realizing there are significant patches
left, a small amount relative to the entire land area of New
England, but a lot more than we had previously thought. And that
has people excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The old trees aren't just a living museum or curiosity. Ancient
forests may be ecologically different from their younger
counterparts, inhabited by different mosses and funguses on the
aging trees and, perhaps, a different mix of animals beneath their
shade. In a world where biologists are just beginning to look at
the smallest creatures of the forest, old-growth forests could also
be a reserve of rare microbial life.
</P>
<P>
   However, their benefits are not just ecological.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have forests like these that represent a continuity of past
to present, that, to me, is exciting to contemplate, especially
when I'm out here in one,'' Leverett said in his languid Southern
drawl. In a world racing ahead at a dizzying pace and whose idea of
history is the Bush administration, these forests ``give us pause,
give us time to reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no mystery why the new discoveries are turning up. As
environmental concern over forests, new and old, in New England has
surged in the last decade, so has research into the natural history
of the woods _ sometimes for the express purpose of finding ancient
forests that can be used as leverage to block logging.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best known old-growth tracts are already on public
land _ on Mount Katahdin in Maine, the Sandwich Range wilderness of
the White Mountains, Lookoff Mountain in the Green Mountains, and
in Massachusetts' Mount Greylock state reservation. But many of the
more recent discoveries are on private land with no special
protection; the exact ownership of the forest in Gill is not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over old-growth forests became a national issue in the
late 1980s, fueled by the high-profile debate over preserving the
majestic tracts of the Pacific Northwest, home to the Northern
spotted owl.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the experience in the Northwest _ where thousands of
acres of old growth were clearcut as activists protested _ the US
Forest Service is now searching the 774,000-acre White Mountain
National Forest for more old-growth tracts. Legislation has been in
the works for the last two years in Massachusetts to protect
old-growth tracts on state lands, prompted in part by the onetime
proposal to build a ski slope on Wachusett Mountain straight
through such a forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the turn of the 20th century, 80 percent of our forests had
been cleared,'' said Jack Clarke, advocacy director for the
Massachusetts Audubon Society. ``Now nearly 70 percent of the state
is forested, and just a small amount is old growth. It's important
to protect old growth generally, but, at a minimum, on state
property.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason these now-prized patches of white pine, chestnut oak,
hemlock, and other centuries-old trees have survived is because
many of the species _ especially hemlock _ were not considered
valuable in the heyday of rampant logging a century ago. Also, like
the tract here in Gill, clinging to a slope that plummets more than
100 feet to the river, many were tough for loggers and farmers to
get to. As a result, many were overlooked or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Leverett and others say the effort to save these trees could be
hindered by aesthetic values. The term ``old growth'' conjures
images of the towering trees of Oregon or Washington, 10 feet wide
at the base, with cathedral canopies, and fully aged. The image is
not of New England's relatively meager trees, maybe two feet wide
at the base, and sometimes stunted from growing on rocky, windswept
hillsides. That has made it more difficult for environmental
campaigns to set aside much younger forest so that one day they can
be grand ancient forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about eliminating something special that
already exists, like old growth in the West, that's immediate, and
people can get a real sense of loss,'' said Dave Publicover, a
forest ecologist with the Appalachian Mountain Club. ``But trying
to recreate something, when you won't see the benefits of it for
another 200 years, doesn't evoke the same sense of immediacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Four centuries of European settlement in New England have also
instilled a deep cultural sense of using, rather than preserving,
the land, making it that much harder to save old-growth forests,
some say. ``The paradigm in New England is that forests must be
working for man,'' said Chris Haney, a forest ecologist with the
Wilderness Society. ``It's a huge cultural bias that is not evident
in other regions of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   To Leverett, that paradigm is changing. New England's old-growth
forests provide habitats for some of the region's most imperiled
native species, and so play a crucial role in sustaining
biodiversity, he said. ``There are balances in these forests we
don't want to lose sight of, balances the earth may have the last
word on,'' he said. But, as important, he said,is the forests'
value in unveiling the past, so as to root the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my wife and I came to New England in 1975, we saw the
sugar maples, stone walls, great blue herons, church steeples. All
that seemed New England,'' Leverett said, pausing during a hike
through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's New England to a young person? Sprawl,'' said Leverett,
leaning against an old hemlock as yet another boat sped by on the
river and a truck rumbled over the bridge. ``We'd like to bring
back some of old New England. And we have one last chance to do it
with these forests. We won't get another opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
