 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and i coding)  
 ASSIST FROM US HELPS MALLARD KIN REUNITE IN MOSCOW 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mrs. Mallard is making her way back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In February, thieves sawed off and nabbed the 200-pound bronze
statue of the determined duck matriarch from Robert McCloskey's
``Make Way for Ducklings.''
</P>
<P>
   They also made off with two of her flock, Lack and Mack.
</P>
<P>
   That left Novodevichy Park with only five of the nine original
ducks that Barbara Bush had given the Soviet Union in 1991, a year
after Raisa Gorbachev had admired the duck sculpture while visiting
Boston's Public Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the bronze carnage was too much for Needham native Beth
Hebert, who now runs a small investment firm in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the theft, they looked so lonely, like they had been
orphaned,'' Hebert said of the five remaining ducks, Jack, Kack,
Nack, Ouack, and Pack. (Another duckling, Quack, had been stolen in
1991.) All that remained of the abducted ducks, she noted, were
their bronze webbed feet, embedded in cobblestone imported from
Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who has a year-old daughter, said the Moscow ducks had
been popular among Russian children. ``There isn't anything like
them in Moscow, so they were a huge hit,'' she said. ``Kids were
always all over them.''
</P>
<P>
   So she persuaded Boston's State Street Corp., which is the main
owner of her Moscow company, to pay most of the cost of having new
ones made by Nancy Schon, the West Newton sculptor of Boston's
bronze ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Schon's new ducks, which are being made from the plaster molds
first used in 1987, are expected to be finished and sent to Russia
in August. With the death last year of Raisa Gorbachev, officials
at State Street are hoping that her husband, Mikhail, will attend
the ceremony marking the return of the abducted ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had sent the duck family redux to Moscow to mark the
US-Soviet arms treaty known as START I. A plaque in front of the
ducks, which were placed near a real duck house in front of the
16th-century, onion-domed Novodevichy Monastery, reads, ``This
scuplture was given in love and friendship to the children of the
Soviet Union on behalf of the children of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, whose mother, a Boston native, read the McCloskey tale
to her over and over as a child, said that she had seen the Moscow
version and had wanted to send her a mother a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   On the February day she had planned to go, a blizzard blanketed
Moscow. The next day, she went with a camera only to find three
ducks abducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ducknapped!'' declared the English-language Moscow Times.
</P>
<P>
   Despite four similar, though less serious, abductions of her
duck statues from Boston's Public Garden since they were installed
in 1987, including one in November, Schon still recoils at the
thought of losing one of her bronze babies.
</P>
<P>
   And never before had the determined matriarch disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated when I heard they'd been cut off at the knees
and that Mrs. Mallard had been taken,'' their sculptor said. ``The
whole thing was mean and cruel and vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Schon called the theft a violation against children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few public places, in Boston or Moscow, where
children can go and parents don't say `no,' where they can interact
with a sculpture however they want,'' said Schon, who is part
Russian. ``This is a violation against a lovely, beautiful thought
and gift.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Make Way for Ducklings,'' published in 1941, most of the
ducks wait in the Charles River while Mr. Mallard searches for a
permanent home, which turns out to be a tiny island in the middle
of the Public Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The scene shown in the 35-foot-long duck sculpture is that of
Mrs. Mallard and her eight duckings going to rejoin him _ right
after ``Officer Michael'' stops traffic on Storrow Drive for them
to cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a book about keeping promises, which makes the
theft of Mrs. Mallard all the more upsetting,'' said Schon.
</P>
<P>
   George Russell, director of both community affairs and global
philanthropy for State Street, said that the company is paying
$30,000 of the $55,000 cost of the replacements.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's investment management unit has a majority stake in
the firm that Hebert runs in Moscow, Pallada Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beth mentioned this to us, and after thinking about it we
decided to partly fund the replicas,'' Russell said. ``The major
focus of our philanthropy is programs that support children, and
here is something that really resonated with the children of
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus,'' he added, ``we're a Boston-headquartered global
company, and this was an opportunity to do something meaningful in
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   It will almost certainly be satisfying to Gavril Popov, the
former mayor of Moscow, who spoke at the duck dedication ceremony
there in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life in this city is going to be gradually improved,'' Popov
said to the guests, who included both Gorbachevs and author Robert
McCloskey, who was 76 at the time. Then, turning to the ducks,
Popov said, ``You will live here as well and as happily as you do
in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Schon said that given the deterioration of US-Russian relations
since the hopeful and heady days of the 1990s, she felt a need to
see that America's gift to Russia is made whole again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the idea that this was something that connected our
cultures,'' said Schon, who called the experience of working with a
combined American-Russian work crew to install the sculptures in
1991 one of the highlights of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing how wonderfully we all worked together,'' she
said. ``It was a reminder to me that, despite our governments,
people basically love each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
