<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TARGET AUDIENCE, A FREE TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pitch was in the form of a cover letter attached to a TV set
with a built-in VCR. Please watch our new ads, the pitch implored,
and here's a complimentary new TV to watch them on.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch came from Trellix Corp., a privately held
Concord-based firm that says its personal-computer applications
enable ``mere mortals'' and ``everyday people'' to create and
publish their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the consumers who use the company's applications
don't know Trellix by name, so there seems to be little point in
mounting an expensive ad campaign that would seek to transform
Trellix into a megabrand or household brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the dot-com (company) that spent half its marketing
budget on a single Super Bowl ad?'' Trellix's pitch letter began.
``We didn't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending a lot of money on costly network airtime to
reach many people, Trellix has opted to spend $2.5 million to reach
only the handful of business customers whose decisions will have
significant impact on Trellix's revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Trellix hired the Ellenson Group, a New York ad
agency, to create ads that may be viewed by no more than 200
people; to increase the probability that those 200 folks, all
dot-com marketing managers, will actually watch the ads, the ads
are being sent with a complimentary TV set.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why such a marketing ploy might make sense, it's
helpful to understand Trellix's business model.
</P>
<P>
   One of Trellix's biggest customers is Tripod.com, an online
community run by Lycos Inc., the Waltham-based Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   What Tripod offers its members is the opportunity to build,
create, and update personalized Web pages. Though they often don't
know it, Tripod's members use Trellix's applications when they
create these Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Building personalized Web pages is becoming immensely popular.
According to Trellix president and chief executive Don Bulens, half
the people with Internet access could soon have one or more of
their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what's driving this growth, he says, is the popularity
of new digital cameras, which allow folks to fill their Web pages
with flashy photos.
</P>
<P>
   A proud father, for example, might create a Web site to show off
pictures of a new baby, or a caterer might use his Web site to
alert the world to his skill and services.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers, it seems, want more than one Web site. An
entrepreneur, for example, might want a Web site for her business
and a separate Web site for her family.
</P>
<P>
   Tripod makes money by running banner advertising on its members'
Web pages, and Trellix charges Tripod fees for helping Tripod
members publish their Web pages, Bulens says.
</P>
<P>
   Trellix's new ad campaign, complete with its distribution of of
free TVs, is aimed at key executives at some of the online world's
most popular Internet destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Bulens declines to discuss specifics or name names, but
presumably a TV set and a video with Trellix's TV ads on it went to
someone at iVillage, an online community for women.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that the ad and TV will persuade iVillage to hire
Trellix to offer the same homepage building services it now
provides to Tripod members.
</P>
<P>
   Video ads that come with the free TV feature regular folks who
rely heavily on their Trellix-built Web sites. One is a character
actor; another is a breeder of prize rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1995 by Daniel S. Bricklin, a pioneer of the
spreadsheet, Trellix does not disclose earning or revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In April, it announced it raised $35 million in mezzanine
financing from Goldman Sachs, Dell Computer Corp., and Lycos, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   On its free-TV marketing strategy of going after a small,
precise audience, Bulens says: ``It's well worth it to spend a lot
of money to reach the key people who make decisions about our
product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of a new branding campaign that promotes its ties
to Major League Baseball, FleetBoston Financial has kicked off a
separate $18 million marketing effort to promote its online banking
and investing services known as Fleet HomeLink.
</P>
<P>
   Ads were created by Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston.
The ads seek to build strong brand awareness for HomeLink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
