<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-COMMENT-B     06-30 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCEPTION PLAYERS THE RULE FOR THE CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recruiting begins Saturday. Or, to be precise, at 12:01 a.m.
At that point, the Celtics and the other 28 NBA teams can start
making their sales pitches to their targeted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   There usually are at least three necessities in enticing free
agents: money, playing time, and a legitimate chance to win. Other
factors include year-round golf and proximity to Las Vegas. The
Celtics come up short in all areas. So you can forget any
big-namers coming here, and that includes not only Tim Duncan, but
Rashard Lewis and Austin Croshere. As for Mark Jackson, if Pitino
is concerned about his locker room, he should not go near the
soon-to-be ex-Pacer.
</P>
<P>
   You're going to be hearing the phrase ``exception player'' a
lot. Translated, it means a free agent who thinks he's worth more,
and maybe really is worth more, but won't get any more than the
exception because that is all teams have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   In some locales, notably Orlando and Chicago, big names and big
numbers will be tossed around. The Celtics will have only the
league-allowed exemptions, one at $2.25 million and the other at
$1.2 million, which puts them in the same class as most of the
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   The drafting of Jerome Moiso was a safe selection, even though
Rick Pitino might be two jobs removed by the time the kid blossoms.
(Pitino said Thursday on Boston radio that Moiso is not going to be
a ``difference maker'' next season.) The Celtics still have the
same needs: interior defense (shot blocking), a shooting
guard/small forward who can score, and a big point guard who can
defend. They may have to address one or more of these needs via
trade (Cedric Ceballos is available), and it's still possible that
they can be in the Jermaine O'Neal chase, using Moiso and two other
first-rounders as bait. If they are, they'll likely wait until
August, when O'Neal is somewhat easier to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be very active,'' Pitino promised. ``We're
trying to get more athletic. We've got to go out there and get the
parts to make our team better.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are given the month of July to court the free agents, but
cannot sign them (ha-ha) until Aug. 1. The Celtics aren't in a
position to chase any big free agents, but because the field is
level for most everyone else, they can compete, money-wise, for
most of them.
</P>
<P>
   So while Orlando and Chicago are making their pitches for Tim
Duncan, Grant Hill, Tracy McGrady, and Eddie Jones, the Celtics can
turn their attention to more realistic possibilities. While they
surely have others in mind, here are some players who might make
sense, understanding they can only get one unless they make a
trade:
</P>
<P>
   --Adonal Foyle, Golden State: He is still developing as an
interior player and has found it hard to get decent minutes on a
bad Golden State team. Normally, that would not be a good sign. But
he has size (6 feet 10 inches) and holds the NCAA Division 1 record
for blocked shots (OK, he did it Colgate, but he still blocked
them) and that is a huge Boston need. The Warriors say they want to
re-sign him and can offer him more than anyone else. They may
actually mean what they say now that they have dealt the
disappointing Jason Caffey.
</P>
<P>
   --Derek Anderson, LA Clippers: Pitino needs no introduction to
this guy and vice versa. They were both at Kentucky _ Anderson
transferred there from Ohio State. He is a big guard who can play
both backcourt positions and he knows the Pitino style. But he's
looking for big money and it may be unrealistic to think he'd
settle for the veteran's exception. But he also may have no choice
unless the Clips work a sign and trade.
</P>
<P>
   --Tariq Abdul-Wahad, Denver: He is reported to be involved in a
sign and trade with the Clippers and Anderson, which has been
rumored all spring. He is a big, defensive guard who is used to
being the fourth or fifth option. Unless there is a sign-and-trade
deal, he is not going to command a lot of dough. He can score as
well.
</P>
<P>
   --Tony Delk, Sacramento: Another player whom Pitino knows well
from Kentucky, but there is some bad blood here in that Delk feels
he was jerked around last summer by the Celtics before signing with
the Kings. He doesn't have the size Pitino might want, but he knows
the drill.
</P>
<P>
   --Antonio Daniels, San Antonio: He's Tim Duncan's best friend,
so he may end up where Duncan goes. At 6-4, he does have the size
Pitino wants and he started to come around last season after two
uninspiring seasons in Vancouver and San Antonio. His best move
financially would be to re-up with the Spurs, but if Duncan goes .
. .
</P>
<P>
   --Anthony Carter, Miami: He'll probably stay where he is, but
the Heat can afford to pay him only so much. But he was a pleasant
surprise this past season for Miami and showed he can play with the
big boys.
</P>
<P>
   --Brad Miller, Charlotte: He's a restricted free agent and at
least he wouldn't abuse the Celtics four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   --Danny Fortson: He covers none of the bases _ he doesn't block
shots, he's not a scoring wing man or a point guard. The Celtics
basically have written him off as unsignable, but he could be that
player who'll have to take less. It's unlikely he'd return to
Boston because he wants to play.
</P>
<P>
   --Ron Mercer, Orlando: Only kidding. But he is a wing man who
can score. Then we wouldn't have to ask anymore whom the Celtics
got when they traded him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
