<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WYNONNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYNONNA'S NEW ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music business doesn't know what to make of Wynonna _ and
she knows it. She's too rock for country radio, too country for
rock, too upfront in her opinions, too unpredictable, too
dangerous. So after she ends her current rock-edged ``Big Attitude
Tour,'' which follows her more sentimental country reunion with the
Judds, she is going home to take stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be a mom and a farm girl for a while,''
says Wynonna, a single mother with two children, Elijah, 5, and
Grace, 4. ``And then I'm going to reinvent myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that Wynonna has already reinvented herself. Her
latest album, ``New Day Dawning,'' has everything from pop ballads
to covers of songs by Joni Mitchell (``Help Me'') and the Fabulous
Thunderbirds (``Tuff Enuff''). But this time, she's talking about
radical reinvention, having become ``disheartened by what's going
on in music right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She's at a crossroads. She might do a gospel album next (``I've
always threatened to do it, but maybe I'll really do it this
time'') or a hard-rocking country album of the sort she made when
first going solo after the Judds's breakup in the early '90s, or
maybe a straight blues record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've confused the country audience so much,'' she admits,
while also realizing that the reviews of her latest album have been
``mixed.'' The album is, to be honest, more of a pop record _ at a
time when she has rekindled her country side in the Judds _ so it's
no wonder that many people, from fans to radio programmers, are
puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bitter, but I am hearing people in this business say,
`We love Wynonna, but we don't know what to do with her.' So why
not pull out for a minute?''
</P>
<P>
   Her minute will actually last six months, starting in August.
That's after her solo dates and after the Judds (meaning Wynonna
and her mom, Naomi), play another 10 shows around the country,
though none near Boston. (They played in Hartford in March and it
was a crowd-pleasing, spiritually uplifting affair.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Judds' tour has been like getting on a train going 100
miles per hour,'' she says. ``It's been an incredible ride _ bigger
and better in some ways than I expected, but at the same time, I'd
look at Mom and say, `This is like a weird movie.' We'd sing at
soundcheck and watch my kids run around and marvel at how weird it
all was. A lot of critics came to the shows with the attitude of
`Aw, another reunion. This is going to be gooey, gooey.' But, you
know, we haven't gotten one bad review. The audiences have been
right there for us. It's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   As for another Judds reunion in the future, she says, ``The only
answer is absolutely maybe. . . . But after this tour, Mom and I
have to separate again for the sake of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, I want to do something completely different
musically. I want to be a backup singer for Tina Turner,'' Wynonna
says, half-joking. ``Or maybe a Joan Jett wannabe,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of sick of me. Maybe I want to put on a blond wig and
pretend I'm one of the Go-Go's,'' she says, laughing hard into the
phone from her home outside Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Other, more realistic options include collaborating with Sting,
who has invited her to work with him at his castle studio in
Europe. Another possibility is furthering her acquaintance with
James Taylor and Elton John _ both of whom she met at the televised
Joni Mitchell tribute concert in New York earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was touched by the whole event,'' she says of the tribute.
``I got to meet James Taylor and hang out with Elton John and Joni
embraced me. I cried the whole day. And, you know, I want to get
together more with people like James Taylor. I also told Elton that
I wanted to hang out with him for a weekend at his place in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may also want to be a student again and may take piano
lessons. But right now, I just want to stop the bus and get off and
do some laundry,'' she says. ``I've been rocking on the road for so
long. I'm ready for a sabbatical.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynonna, who has also been working through the pains of her
divorce last year, plans to sell her farm (``I've been there 13
years, so there's a lot of closure'') and build a new one on a hill
overlooking the homes of her mother and sister, Ashley, the movie
actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be on top of the hill, so I can spy on them,''
Wynonna says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another option: Wynonna has been offered a part in a
future movie that Ashley is making. She sidesteps the details, but
sounds very interested. As for Ashley herself, Wynonna says, ``I
adore her. I wish I could merge with her.''
</P>
<P>
   During the sabbatical, Wynonna likewise hopes to lose weight
``and get back to my original weight: 8 pounds, 6 ounces.''
</P>
<P>
   Her interview shtick must come to an end, however, because
Wynonna will soon leave to go sit in with Phish, the Vermont jam
band that is performing in Nashville that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting ready to rent a limo and see Phish and sing `Free
Bird' with them,'' she says, quite seriously this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just on a rock 'n' roll high these days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
