<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY PRI AUTOMATION LEADS IN RACE TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An investment in any technology stock is a bet on the future. An
investment in PRI Automation is a bet on the future of
semiconductor manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   A number of analysts and money managers think PRI is a good bet
for investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Billerica, Mass. company makes systems and software that
automate the production of semiconductors. Chipmaking is already a
complicated business. A silicon wafer on which chips are made
travels eight to 10 miles throughout the factory over the course of
a 30- to 45-day production cycle. During that time it may undergo
as many as 400 to 500 individual processes.
</P>
<P>
   Think Willie Wonka and the Chocolate Factory and you have some
idea of how convoluted and futuristic the whole enterprise is. We
don't know what a chocolate factory costs, but a semiconductor
factory is expensive. A brand new fab, a chip factory, can cost
more than $1.5 billion. And human mistakes in production, even
small ones, can be very costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You drop one tray and it can mean the loss of hundreds of
thousands of dollars,'' said Alan Loewenstein, manager of the John
Hancock Technology fund.
</P>
<P>
   That's where PRI comes in. Its equipment reduces the human
element in chipmaking by automating more of the operation. In the
not so distant future, that human element may shrink still further.
</P>
<P>
   The chip industry stands on the brink of a major generational
shift. Currently, chips are made on 200 millimeter wafers. In the
new wave of factories, they will be made on 300 millimeter wafers.
The current generation of fabs requires $10 million to $15 million
worth of automation equipment; in the next generation that
requirement could jump to $50 million to $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 300 millimeter wafer represents the sizzle for PRI,'' said
David Smith, a money manager at Loomis Sayles and a PRI fan.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and others say that PRI is the clear leader in the race to
the future. They say its equipment is more sophisticated and
flexible than that produced by its Japanese competitors. In a
recent filing, PRI said it has been making major investments in 300
millimeter technology. In the quarter ended in April, PRI's
research and development expenses were $12.7 million or almost 17
percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for PRI, no one has yet ordered a full 300
millimeter fab, although several pilot projects are under way. ``It
is a question of when, not if,'' said Tia-min Pang, an analyst with
SG Cowen Securities Corp, who expects several of the new factories
to be under construction by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that in the hypercompetitive chip business, once a
few big players make the commitment to the new technology, the rest
of the pack will be obligated to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The chip business is notoriously cyclical. Booms give way to
busts overnight. But these days most analysts are bullish about the
industry's outlook for the next few years. Whereas in the past
demand was fueled mainly by sales of personal computers, today the
demand is coming from a raft of telecommunications and wireless
products. Should that strong demand materialize, PRI will be the
beneficiary, as orders come in from both new and older generation
fabs, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main risk to this company is a macro risk,'' said Fred
Wolf, an analyst with Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill. A slowdown in the
world economy or a US recession would hit PRI hard, according to
Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the chip industry, PRI's financial performance
has been erratic. The company earned significant profits in 1996
and 1997 and lost money in both 1998 and 1999 when the economic
downturn in Asia threw the whole chip business into recession.
</P>
<P>
   SG Cowen expects PRI to earn $1.13 a share this year and $2.20
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has also bounced around quite a bit. The
stock got as high as $87 a share in March just before the Nasdaq
Composite Index collapsed. It closed Thursday at $62.25. Since the
spring Wall Street has been edgy about the more speculative
technology companies. Given the uncertainty surrounding the
introduction of the 300 millimeter fab, PRI may be the target of
some of that skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's backers, while conceding the risks, say they
still like the stock. Said David Smith of Loomis Sayles: ``The next
generation fab will happen and at that point no one will want to be
behind the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
