<HEADLINE>
SWEET DREAMS OF THE OPEN ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ I am sitting in a corner booth in a cheap
knock-off of Denny's on the outskirts of this famously quaint town,
trying to determine from my jumble of maps if Nebraska is beneath
the Dakotas or beside them.
</P>
<P>
   The kind waitress had guided me away from our first table with
the emotionless proclamation, ``Too many flies over here.'' She
answers my inquiry about scrapple by saying, ``Kind of like Spam,
only squishier.'' I decide to take a pass.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, I am free, alive, exhilarated. One day I'm in Boston,
listening to the incessant bickering over Fenway Park and the
bragging of twenty-something Internet CEOS who've made millions
from companies that will never make a dime. The next day I am on
the open road, leaving so much of life's clutter behind.
</P>
<P>
   The open road. I've packed a car with every polo shirt I own and
steered it west on the Massachusetts Turnpike. Destination:
Seattle. As I slip the bonds of Route 128, visions of Lewis and
Clark dance in my mind, and I am in harmony with so many courageous
adventurers who came before me. Well, actually I'm in a rented
convertible, but no need to bog down in details.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I pass Interstate 495, my navigator has made it
clear there's not a rest area in America she won't want or need to
visit. By the time I pass Hartford, I am overcome by hunger and
overwhelmed by exhaustion, and the warning of my skeptical editor
echoes in my mind: ``Two days out, you'll regret this.'' Two days
too generous, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But no, absolutely not. There are experiences to be had, goals
to be realized, dreams to be fulfilled along this journey from sea
to shining sea.
</P>
<P>
   I want to pat the head of a Iowan hog, provided he's harnessed,
muzzled, and under the full control of several corn-fed farmhands.
I want to see if my Claritin can withstand amber waves of grain. I
want to ride a galloping stallion across a Wyoming ranch _ or at
least a heavily sedated pony at a country fair.
</P>
<P>
   None of that being quite enough, I want to cover myself in the
necessary bugsprays and lay in a Montana field looking up at the
biggest of starlit skies, stand arm in arm with an Ohio dairy
farmer praising the wholesome taste of milk with Nestle's Quick,
experience what John Steinbeck meant when he wrote, ``We do not
take a trip, a trip takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, I want to see the majesty of this land and the beauty
of all its people. And the first such person I meet is a delightful
old woman named Gertie Gepfer.
</P>
<P>
   The hills are alive with the smell of chocolate, as I climb out
of my car on Cocoa Avenue and step inside the ancient manufacturing
plant where Gertie is waiting to rhapsodize about a lifetime
dedicated to the world's most wonderful brand of candy.
</P>
<P>
   She has the requisite gray netting in her hair, a long navy blue
lab coat covering her flowered skirt, and a faux leather Hershey
satchel where she carries a pen-knife and various other tools of
her trade. Big, owlish eyeglasses dominate her soft face.
</P>
<P>
   She operates a pair of Kiss wrapping machines that take the
famous chocolate drops and cover them, twelve at a time, with a
twist of silver foil and a white Hershey flag, then send them on
their way. She's done this for 52 years, overseeing hundreds of
millions of Kisses rolling across machines that haven't changed
since 1921. And this fall, at 83 years old, she has decided she
will retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've worked long enough,'' she says with that
grandmotherly smile of hers, though a few minutes later, she adds,
``I'll probably sit around and wish I hadn't left.''
</P>
<P>
   She is persistent and durable _ uniquely, exquisitely American.
Her mother worked at Hershey in this most benevolent of company
towns, as did her husband back before he died, and all four of her
children at some point in their lives. Several grandchildren work
at the plant now. Gertie lives five blocks away, and has wandered
as far as na with the Hershey travel club, but still loves her
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful town, and they keep everything so
wonderful,'' she says. ``I don't plan to go anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   I ask Gertie what her favorite candy is, and she smiles again
and says, ``Kisses.''
</P>
<P>
   Back outside, I breathe in the chocolately air that would still
make Milton Hershey proud, unwrap a Symphony Bar and point my car
west. The road is long and sweet before us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
