<SLUG> BC-WOM-BRAKETTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAKETTES ARE DRIVEN TO SUCCEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATFORD, Conn. _ People don't come to this town of 48,000 on
the Houstanic River to see tall buildings, visit museums, or watch
a Major League game.
</P>
<P>
   They come here to play softball.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer since 1947, the town has fielded the Brakettes, who
have won 23 national championships and three world championships,
and have virtually become the farm team for the US Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
   A doubleheader against Team USA, for instance, is nothing less
than a reunion. There are four former Brakettes on the US squad,
one (Danielle Henderson of the University of Massachusetts) is
still on the roster, and Olympic coach Ralph Raymond guided the
Brakettes for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Kris MacLean, who has been a Brakette for five years,
lives in Brockton, Mass., and plays every weekend. She said friends
shake their heads when they hear about her more than three-hour
commute.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Oh, you travel so far just to play softball,' ''
she said. ``But it's not just softball, it's the best softball in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has been part of the fabric of this community since the
Raybestos brake company first sponsored it 53 years ago. That was
when 9-year-old John Stratton started working as a bat boy. He
eventually met and married Brakette catcher Micki Machietto and in
1971 joined the organization, which went on to win eight straight
national titles.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baird, the athletic director at Stratford High, has been
general manager and first base coach for the past 13 years. Patty
Patuski, the town's superintendent of recreation, was a bat girl
for the team and played for the Brakettes.
</P>
<P>
   So if you know Stratford, you likely know the Brakettes.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton has retired from his job as physical education teacher
in the New Canaan school system, but it seems unthinkable he'll
ever retire from softball.
</P>
<P>
   Every winter he goes to Florida, where he works as a pitching
coach and is an assistant in the athletic department at Florida
Atlantic University. His boss? Joan Joyce, the All-American former
Brakette pitcher. Her batterymate was Stratton's wife, Micki, and
both have been inducted into the softball Hall of Fame in Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges the almost familylike image of the team. ``Yeah,
it's like we're in a rut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Stratton and Baird sat in the press box above the DeLuca
Field on Main Street where the Brakettes play, they reminisced as
they thumbed through black-and-white photos of former players such
as Donna Lopiano, now director of the Women's Sports Foundation,
Hall of Famers Donna Schumaker, Bertha Tickey, and, of course,
Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Both men seem to have Brakettes events emblazoned in their minds
as they rattled off what year the team lost the world championship
(it came in second to Australia in 1965), and when it beat Japan
for the world title in 1964. Or when it won three straight national
titles, from 1958-60, all in Stratford.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting and tryouts seem just as free-floating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had only one preseason practice and it got rained out this
year,'' Baird said with a laugh and a shrug. As for recruiting,
well, there's nothing official.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton said the team has a Web site (``but it's broken now''),
and he has no e-mail address. Still, he receives about 30 letters
or videotapes a year from young women, saying, ``I want to be a
Brakette.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly he relies on his extensive network of former
players-turned-college coaches to hear about talent, and goes to
college tournaments to see for himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's worked.
</P>
<P>
   He has led the Brakettes to a 179-29 record in four seasons as
field manager, and is 13-1 this year. He took over twice before,
most notably in 1976 when Raymond suffered a heart attack. Stratton
was left with just two Brakettes in April after the rest had bolted
to join the now-defunct professional league that Joyce, Jane
Blalock, and Bille Jean King had formed. He led the team to a
national title.
</P>
<P>
   Raybestos ran the team until 1985, when the company moved to
Indiana, and D'Addario Industries in Bridgeport took over. Then
Raybestos Products reacquired the team from 1990-95, until it
dropped its affiliation but let the longstanding name remain.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the team got an infusion from Bob Wirz of Milford
and David Carpenter of Westport.
</P>
<P>
   Wirz, who used to work for the Kansas City Royals and the
commissioner of Major League Baseball, now runs Wirz Associates
sports marketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in Connecticut 25 years, and I'd known of the
Brakettes for years, so when I learned they were in need of
sponsorship, I went to David, and said, `What do you think?' ''
Wirz said.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, president of Horsehead Industries, one of the
country's largest privately held manufacturing companies, agreed
and is now chairman of the Brakettes.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wirz said, the Hartford Whalers of the National
Hockey League were also looking to be saved. ``But they didn't have
history on their side, and we really thought of the Brakettes as
Connecticut's hidden jewel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As amateurs, the players don't get paid a salary, but the
estimated $50,000-$75,000 cost of sponsorship goes toward travel
and housing expenses, plus equipment, and rental of the field. He
said part of his challenge is to bring back the draw of the team.
``They used to play for thousands, and we think we can bring it
back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the team only drew about 600 fans on a recent weekend,
Patuski of the recreation department expected the Team USA game to
be a sellout at the 2,700-seat ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, the former Brakette coach who's on his second stint
coaching the Olympic team, said he knows well the strength of the
Stratford team that he guided to a 1,992-162 record with 17
national championships. He also knows it can be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond of Worcester, Mass., recalled that in 1965 he took his
Cochuite Motors softball team to play the Brakettes in the Fourth
of July tournament. Being prematurely confident of themselves, the
Brakettes had engraved their names on the winning trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond's team won, they had to stay up all night waiting for
the new trophies, and the next day the president of Raybestos asked
Raymond to take over the team.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he said, the women who played all hoped to be in
the Olympics, but it would take two decades before that would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was chosen as US coach in 1994, he hasn't looked back,
and doesn't plan to this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I retired from the Brakettes in '94, and it isn't that I don't
care, but I have severed all relations,'' said Raymond, 76. ``I
traveled for 26 years from Worcester to Stratford, and that was
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brakettes insist they won't be intimidated by Team USA.
Nicole Terpstra of Highland, Ind., who just joined the Brakettes
this year, actually benefited from the addition of Brakettes to
Team USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to go to Italy to play, where they have a lot of
pro teams, but John saw me throw and said they needed another
pitcher since Danielle (Henderson) was on the Olympic team,'' said
Terpstra, who has a 7-0 record with a 0.27 ERA as well as one home
run and a .250 average.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday night's game at Sacred Heart, outfielder
Kellie Wilkerson of Mississippi State leads the team with a .633
average and 19 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true Brakette, Terpstra said, ``I'm excited to
play them. I'm not intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as long as there are no trophies to be engraved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
