<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC BANKING ON NASCAR, SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, NBC Sports was on the rocks. The once
proud peacock sustained low ratings for the World Series and NBA
Finals. Those performances followed a questionable decision by the
General Electric-owned network not to spend $4 billion for the
rights to NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the NFL was one thing, but the Olympic scandal in Salt
Lake City was a different matter that nearly had a disastrous
effect upon the network.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol lost his cool. He ranted about
the ``economic absurdity'' of carrying AFC games. He defended the
investigation into allegations of widespread corruption in the
bidding process for the 2002 Winter Olympics. He attacked John
Hancock Insurance Company president David D'Alessandro for
threatening to pull advertising from Olympic coverage if serious
steps were not taken to correct problems within the International
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Eberesol publicly ridiculed D'Alessandro. ``His continual
seeking of front-page publicity, for no other reason than to get
his name in the paper, is a tragedy,'' Ebersol told reporters last
year in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate angst appears to have subsided at NBC Sports. Ebersol
is back in the saddle. The network recently bought the rights to
NASCAR events and joined with old buddy Vince McMahon to start the
XFL, a new professional football league aimed at pro wrestling
fans. The near future is even brighter. In 88 days, the Summer
Olympics begin, and NBC, along with its sister cable stations MSNBC
and CNBC, will lair 441 hours of programming, three times the
amount of coverage in Atlanta. The network is carrying 162 1/2
hours of programming aimed at familes. ``This is my passion,''
Ebersol said. ``The Olympics are the single greatest reason that I
am still working.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol feels the Olympics are not just about winning and
losing, but about the process. About how an athlete, who may never
turn pro or receive a commercial endorsement, can sacrifice his or
her life for four years and have success hinge upon 10 seconds, or
a minute. ``It's about the sacrifice,'' said Ebersol.
</P>
<P>
   Its also about the story.
</P>
<P>
   Barring major news, every second of NBC's coverage will be
taped. Every hour will have about 18 commercials. About 85 hours
will air during prime time. There will lots of stories about
triumph and overcoming odds.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol prides himself on telling stories. Lisa Lax, the
award-winning producer, leads the profile department. The Brandeis
graduate says NBC already has 130 stories, only about a quarter are
on Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The signature piece is on Muhammad Ali, with Denzel Washington
doing the voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said not too long he expected to lose money on the
Sydney Games. NBC paid about $750 million for these Games as part
of a $3.5 billion package with the IOC to televise the Games up
until 2008. News about corruption makes adverstisers uneasy. ``We
thought we could lose between $50 million and $75 million,'' said
Ebersol.
</P>
<P>
   With ad sales expected to reach $900 million by Labor Day,
Ebersol now has a different take. He is expecting to turn a profit
of as much as $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the confidence stems from NBC's decision to air the
Games when most people would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the events will be over and the results known _
not to mention competition from the NFL and pennant races _ Ebersol
said he anticipates ratings of between 17.5 and 18.5, or about 18
million households. The Atlanta Games earned a 21.6 average ratings
and the Barcelona Games pulled a 17.1 rating. The Los Angeles Games
in 1984 earned a 23.2 rating, but that was before the dominance of
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Costas hosts the network coverage, with Jim Lampley on MSNBC
and Pat O'Brien on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card for NBC will be the performances by American
athletes. How will the Australian swim team perform against the
Americans? Will the US women's soccer team defend its gold medal?
</P>
<P>
   Coverage starts Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
