<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART     06-30 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT PLAYING THE ACE CLEARLY A SMART MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston version of ``Do The Right Thing'' was staged
Thursday at Fenway Park and, indeed, Jimy Williams was the man who
did the right thing. In three years, the Red Sox manager will feel
good about his decision; in three months, he may be nauseated.
</P>
<P>
   Williams wanted an injured Pedro Martinez to go on the disabled
list before Thursday night's game at Fenway Park. Martinez didn't
want to do it. Eventually the pitcher was given something most
employees crave in late June: a two-week summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   So Jimy did the right thing, and that means this story will have
a happy ending. In 2002, Martinez will be pleased his manager
protected him from himself. He will see that, for the good of his
health, it is not wise to pitch with both a sore oblique muscle and
sore shoulder when there is half a season to be played.
</P>
<P>
   He had to go on the DL. If he hadn't, he would have continued to
perform hurt. He believes he is obligated to do that, partly
because he is not the only player in his clubhouse _ Jason Varitek
is another _ who plays hurt, and partly because he bristles when
his starts are taken away. That attitude began after Martinez left
the Dodgers, the team that was convinced he could never start
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, there will be a happy ending. There is no
guarantee, though, of a happy now. In the next two weeks, Williams
will have to do a managerial firewalk. He will have to drag his
team, which currently has a Yard Sale/Second Hand chic to it, to
the All-Star break in one piece. He will have to do this without
his best pitcher, who also happens to be his MVP, who also acts as
the bullpen's recharger, who also _ even while hurt _ is the team's
most consistent starter.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot to lose for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy did the right thing. Of course. But the question to many in
New England is this: Did the right thing come at the expense of a
possible World Series ring? The answer is no. Well, not in the way
some people imagine. The Sox beat the Orioles, 12-4, so there will
not be a ghastly losing streak. There will not be a nasty collapse.
But the way the American League is taking shape this year, the Sox
could fall dangerously behind even without a dramatic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, Boston has to win the AL East if it wants to make the
playoffs. There will be no sneaking and tiptoeing through the side
entrance, also known as the wild-card entrance, for the third
consecutive season. The East will not have the wild-card team this
year. The Sox, then, need to play (and be general managed) like a
team that is trying to win the division.
</P>
<P>
   That was going to be difficult even with a healthy Martinez. It
was going to be difficult when the Sox, Yankees, and Blue Jays were
all in as-is mode. As constructed, those teams were triplets on a
chain gang, too close and too similar to escape each other. If one
were able to get a six-game lead on one of the others, that would
be considered a runaway. That used to be unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But on the same day Martinez went on the DL, the Yankees made a
trade with Cleveland. The Yankees traded for experienced lefthanded
power (David Justice) and gave up inexperience and potential (Ricky
Ledee, two prospects). The New Yorkers should have traded for a
starting pitcher first, but that's not the point; they'll get one.
The point is that they have struck first, giving notice that they
plan to do something to rise above the three-way cluster in the
East.
</P>
<P>
   And that means another character must be added to this tale. His
name is Dan Duquette. He must also do the right thing, even if it
seems impossible for him to do immediately. The Sox trade has to be
for a pitcher. There can be no Ohkas, Ericksons, Lees, or Kims at
this point. Duquette has to pry a No. 2 or 3 starter at a time when
most teams are in denial, still convincing themselves that they are
in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Another starter should have been a priority long before Martinez
went on the DL. The necessity should be tolerated because of the
mysterious injuries _ the tight-lipped Sox still haven't said what
they are _ and the Yankees' trade, which is probably the first of
two or three.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it sounds, the first place Duquette should call is
Houston. The Astros are terrible, flatlining at 27-50 in the
National League Central. They are led by a starter who is 1-12.
Opponents nearly hit .330 against him, and he is part of a staff
that has an AL-like 5.36 ERA. His own ERA is a touchdown-plus:
7.10.
</P>
<P>
   But Jose Lima is exactly the type of starter the Sox need. He is
a 27-year-old righthander from the Dominican Republic who was 37-18
over the last two seasons before sinking this year. He plays on a
bad team that plays in a Coors-Field-in-Texas, homer-friendly,
gimmicky park. Since he is having such a bad season, he would come
cheap. And he would help.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette should call every team that is out of the race and make
offers for solid starters. He could ask Detroit about Brian
Moehler, Florida about Ryan Dempster (a dream trade, admittedly),
the Giants about Kirk Rueter and Shawn Estes, and Minnesota about
the now mythologized Brad Radke (5-9, 4.07 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are abstract, so it would be hard to say if
Martinez injured himself by trying to do too much and thus
overreaching for near perfection. That's honorable. It also can be
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox fall behind another three or four games in the next
two weeks, it would be a major step back in the East race. This
time, I'm not being facetious when I say that.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams did the right thing. Now it's Dan Duquette's turn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
