<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-30 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE DEFENDS POSITION ON NEWSPAPER SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Justice Department has defended its approval
of Hearst Corp.'s proposed purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle
and turned down a federal judge's invitation to take part in an
antitrust case over the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Thursday to U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker, a
government antitrust lawyer said the deal was ``not likely to
lessen competition'' because Chronicle's rival daily and Hearst's
flagship newspaper, the San Francisco Examiner, would continue to
publish under new ownership.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Clint Reilly, an unsuccessful bidder for the
Examiner who sued to block the sale, said he disagreed with the
department's assessment but planned no formal reply and hoped the
judge would proceed directly to a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Hearst and for Ted Fang, the publisher of the
free-distribution Independent newspaper who has agreed to take over
the Examiner, were pleased with the letter and were awaiting a
final verdict from the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The letter should assure everyone that ``this matter was
thoroughly and professionally investigated by the department,''
said David Balabanian, a lawyer for Fang and his family-owned
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter and the record at trial supports the position
Hearst has taken,'' said Gary Halling, a lawyer for the New
York-based Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's $660 million purchase of the Chronicle was approved by
the Justice Department March 17 but blocked hours later by Walker,
who said Reilly had raised a legitimate concern that San Francisco
might become a one-newspaper city. Reilly contends that Hearst's
deal with Fang _ essentially giving the Examiner to the Independent
publisher along with a $66 million operating subsidy _ is
insufficient to keep the afternoon newspaper alive is designed to
leave Hearst with a local newspaper monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The trial ended May 31, but Walker issued an order June 9
inviting the Justice Department to consider becoming a party to the
suit or submitting a formal brief explaining its views. The judge
said the department apparently had raised serious questions about
the legality of the sale before approving it, and might have
reached a different conclusion if it had heard the evidence at
Reilly's trial.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from Antitrust Division attorney Mark J. Botti said
the Justice Department had been concerned at first about a
``possible monopoly'' but was satisfied by Hearst's agreement in
March to transfer the Examiner to Fang's company, ExInn LLC.
</P>
<P>
   The department concluded that Fang's company ``had the intent
and the capability to compete in the relevant market, albeit in a
form significantly different from the current Examiner,'' Botti
wrote. Fang has said he plans to concentrate on San Francisco news
and switch from afternoon to morning publication.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Botti's letter reiterated the department's March 17 conclusion
but contained a few new disclosures:
</P>
<P>
   _ The department was not convinced by Hearst's initial claim
that no buyer could be found for the Examiner, and advised the
company that the newspaper's viability could be tested by offering
it for sale along with its share of a joint operating agreement
with the Chronicle. The JOA, in effect since 1965 and scheduled to
run through 2005, allows the two newspapers to share business
operations and split profits while maintaining separate editorial
operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Hearst declined to include the JOA in the deal and
instead added its printing plant to a previous offer of limited
Examiner assets, the department was still unwilling to accept
Hearst's claim that no buyer was available. With that issue
unresolved, Hearst abandoned its claim that the Examiner was a
``failing'' newspaper, which could be closed without violating
antitrust laws, and announced the agreement with Fang's company.
</P>
<P>
   _ The department, which questioned Fang extensively and visited
his plant, knows he plans to publish on a different scale than the
current Examiner but still considers him a competitor to the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   One argument in Reilly's lawsuit is that the transfer to Fang
would reduce competition between the newspapers in the metropolitan
area, which would have continued through 2005 under the JOA. Reilly
said the department had been misled into believing Fang's Examiner
would compete throughout the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
