<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLY-FISHING IN A STREAM OF CONSCIOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURG, N.H. _ Some baseball aficionados become annoyed by
the poets of the game. Guys like George Will and John Updike who
see baseball less as a sport than a metaphor for some cosmic
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Workaday sports journalists such as Roger Kahn and Eddie
Andleman resent the poets' claim to baseball's Truth and Essence.
``You keep track of the score and the standings,'' the poets seem
to say, ``while we continue to search for baseball's deeper
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Truth and Essence of baseball, point out the annoyed
journalists, go little deeper than ERAs and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Within the universe of sportfishing, a similar dualism marks two
ends of a spectrum. On one end is the meat fisherman, who chums the
waters with bloody guts in order to take advantage of a fish's
feeding frenzy. He pulls up his catch roughly by the gills and
whacks it over the head to kill it before it bites him. War is
hell.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is fishing, this guy would say. Don't matter what you do
to get them, long as it's legal. And what's the point of fishing in
the first place if you're not going to kill the fish and eat it?
</P>
<P>
   The other end . . . well, you know the other end. He is the fly
angler who plants himself waist high in a moving stream _ so as to
enter the universe of fish _ and contemplates the reality of trout
until he transcends to a higher plane of nature wherein he is
allowed to think like a salmonoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I were a brookie, I would swim along that eddy and
feed in the pool under those riffles.''
</P>
<P>
   Little can offend this guy more than a box of nightcrawlers and
a spinning rod. He prefers catch-and-release stretches on streams
where the meat guys would be as much out of place as they would be
at a great books lecture in the Belchertown Library.
</P>
<P>
   So, the other day, I found myself standing midstream in the
Connecticut River, a few hundred yards from the outflow from First
Connecticut Lake, about 30 miles from the Canadian Border.
Fly-fishing. Contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   First, Second, and Third Connecticut Lakes, Lake Francis, and
the stream that links them is an astonishingly beautiful part of
New England, much like Vermont's Northeast Kingdom to the west.
</P>
<P>
   I was fishing with Wayne Ogden, who, as we talked about the leap
in interest in fly-fishing following the 1992 film, ``A River Runs
Through It,'' observed wryly: ``Two years later, all the gear they
bought ended up in a closet when they realized how hard the sport
is. How much you have to know and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one minute the brookies are feeding voraciously on the
surface on small caddis when a little rain drives them a few inches
down, requiring a bead head to drop the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden began fly-fishing as a child when he learned the sport
from his grandfather, and inherited some classic bamboo rods and
gear from his mentor. Standing in a rushing stream, thoroughly
focused on the surroundings, Ogden says it is the angler's
concentration level that so thoroughly removes him from his
workaday world.
</P>
<P>
   ``A morning out on the stream drops my blood pressure about 80
points,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Sullivan, guide and remarkable chef fom Tall Timber Lodge
on Back Lake, also questions the effect of the movie that featured
Brad Pitt as a the A.J. McClane fly-fishing protagonist. ``It makes
catching a trout some kind of competitive event,'' says Sullivan.
``But people who fly-fish know it's so much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his essay, ``Song of the Angler,'' McClane complains about
``The chirping plague of analysts,'' who seek to invade the deepest
recesses of the angler's motives for fishing. It is beyond simple
analysis, McClane concludes. Whether one is a dry-fly purist or a
wet-nymph, downstream drifter, the angler is looking for that
hypnotic state.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that fly-fishing hypnosis is the cast, which unfurls
behind then loops in a figure-eight before it shoots forward into
the target area. Ted Williams could land a fly in a tin can, and
did so often at the old Boston Sportsman's Show _ a fact to
confound the baseball and fly-fishing poets at once.
</P>
<P>
   For three days we wandered the waters of upper New Hampshire,
from Clarksville where Murphy Dam spills out a pretty blue arc of a
stream, to the white water below First Connecticut Lake to the calm
waters of Back Lake. The mid-June fishing was only fair, with some
very low water flows. Brook trout were biting, but most of the best
fishing was taking place at the remote ponds, according to guide
Tim Savard, from the Lopstick Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon on the river, about a mile below First Connecticut
Lake, I ran across Ken Allard, who was fishing in a party with
Sullivan. Allard was sitting in the middle of a stream in a
wheelchair where he was casting his light Cahill and catching
brookie after brookie from a pool below some tumbling riffles.
</P>
<P>
   Allard was a bait fisherman most of his life in Manchester,
N.H., but 13 years ago he was injured in a motorcycle accident,
which put him in the hospital for a year, and in bed for another.
It was then he began reading about fly-fishing and, when he was
able, to start tying some fly patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was physically challenged,'' says Allard, ``and I wanted a
challenge, so I started fly-fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   His lifelong buddy, Jim Adams _ the two were Boy Scouts together
_ wheels Allard into the stream and back to his van, and the other
day he was in just the right spot to catch the most fish.
</P>
<P>
   Also fishing the Connecticut were father and son Lloyd and Paul
Clauson from Portsmouth, N.H. Lloyd is 86 and often beats his
50-year-old son in the size and number of fish they catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing,'' says Paul, who works for the New Hampshire State
Liquor Commission, ``is a real bond between us. He is one awesome
dad. We go whenever we can, sometimes to the Isinglass River or
Winnepesaukee. But, once a year we come here. This is beautiful
fishing, something we live for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
