<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     06-30 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUS COMES TO TOWN: ROCKER'S BACK IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before the game, John Rocker stood at the podium in a
crowded, steamy interview room and said, ``I'm happy to be back in
New York, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. It sounded like a whopper. Would Salman Rushdie be happy to
be back in Tehran? Would Art Modell like to move back to Cleveland?
Would Drew Bledsoe and Max Lane say they're happy to be back at the
Paradise Club?
</P>
<P>
   Rocker also said, ``I always seem to pitch well here.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did. Capping one of the more bombastic media events of
this or any baseball season, Rocker pitched and pitched well in his
celebrated return to Shea Stadium, a 6-4 win for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   In a day full of fury, tension, reconciliation, and
anticipation, few expected Rocker would be able to make any
significant baseball contribution in a relatively important June
baseball game at sold-out Shea.
</P>
<P>
   But at 10 p.m., with Atlanta leading the streaking Mets by 2 in
the eighth, Rocker burst through the left-field bullpen door at
full Gump speed. It was what they'd all come to see.
</P>
<P>
   They stood. They booed. Slander. Libel. They used words you
never heard in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker went to work, retiring Robin Ventura (strikeout), Todd
Zeile, and Jay Payton (grounders) in succession to get the Braves
to the ninth. After the final out of his only inning, he walked
off, head high, and made no comments or gestures to the hundreds
hooting behind the Braves' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   In the past eight months, Rocker established himself as New
York's favorite villain. His antics during the playoffs and World
Series, followed by a bigoted rant that appeared in Sports
Illustrated, made him tabloid lunch meat on a par with Bernie Goetz
and Son of Sam. Not since Joey Buttafuoco had there been better
headline fodder. They made him the Ku Klux Kloser. The Hate Hurler.
Johnny Rotten. Stupid Is As Stupid Does. Even his name was perfect.
(itals)Rocker(unitals) as in, ``off his . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   And so he stood at the podium in a packed, sweaty room in the
grimy underbelly of Shea and read the words he'd scrawled on Grand
Hyatt stationery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not the evil person that has been portrayed,'' he said.
``. . . I also am fully aware that the overwhelming majority of the
people in this city are extremely charismatic and full of
personality, although a bit spirited at times, but that doesn't
make them bad people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the big screen in center field, a video of Rocker delivering
his nine-paragraph statement was shown to those ``spirited'' folks
before the game. When it was over, they booed loudly.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was quite a return for the Atlanta reliever. The
Braves arrived at the midtown hotel at about 2 a.m. after
completing their series with the Expos Wednesday night. Late in the
morning, there were TV crews and assembled hecklers standing behind
police barriers at two hotel entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, Rocker and Joe Sambito, a former Red Sox lefty who
represents Rocker for the vaunted Hendricks Brothers agency, left
the hotel and went to the offices of the Major League Baseball
Players Association. They were escorted by the New York police in a
city van and returned to the hotel around 2.
</P>
<P>
   Never in hardball history had there been so much interest in a
particular ballplayer's mode of transportation to the ballpark.
Against the wishes of the Braves and Major League Baseball
officials, Rocker had pledged to ride the IRT No. 7 train to Shea
(9.43 miles from Grand Central to Shea). In his infamous SI
meltdown, Rocker used citizens of the No. 7 to offend virtually
every minority group in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So we waited. While waiting, I bought a MTA MetroCard just in
case Johnny came through the lobby and rushed downstairs to Grand
Central Station to catch the No. 7. I even called the hotel
switchboard and asked to be connected to Rocker's room (in case he
wanted me to get him a pass or a token), but the operator said
there was no such person registered. One can only imagine what name
he's registered under (David Duke? Mark Fuhrman? Rosa Parks?). I
found it amusing that on the occasion of this visit, the Braves'
hotel headquarters is jammed with hundreds of members of the
Bibleway Church _ almost all of them African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Rocker did not take the train (``Rocker Wimps Out''
screamed the Daily News). Meanwhile, the Braves pulled the old
``bait and switch,'' a trick employed by Brian Epstein when he had
to sneak the Beatles in and out of hotels. Decoy black police vans
were stationed at the second floor, Park Avenue overpass exit, and
out front on 42d Street. A half-hour after the Braves' team bus
departed, Rocker was squired out a service entrance and whisked
into a black Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame scene at Shea was preposterous. During batting
practice, there was a World Series-like media contingent around the
cage. Rocker shagged flyballs in the outfield, and appeared to
banter with some of the Shea fans. At one point, he went over to
the rail and shook a few hands.
</P>
<P>
   At Shea, new Rocker Rules were in effect. Beer sales were
limited to two (down from four) per purchase. Sales stopped an
inning earlier. A new canopy covered the Braves' bullpen and a
makeshift black corral kept the bleacher folk out of touch. The
game day police force was increased from 60 to 500. The mayor made
a plea for calm.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Only insults were hurled. No double-A batteries.
</P>
<P>
   He did not talk after the game. And he said his pregame
statement would be his last one regarding the hateful diatribe of
last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments I made over six months ago offended many
people,'' he repeated. ``I am fully aware of this, and for that, I
sincerely apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough. Rocker has apologized. In our country it is not a crime
to be foolish, stupid, or bigoted. We are talking about a
25-year-old relief pitcher, not a pope or head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Time to go back to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
