<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-VANGOGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MFA OFFERS VAN GOGH'S PORTRAITS OF THE SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
VAN GOGH: FACE TO FACE 
Organized by the Museum of Fine Arts, the Detroit Institute of Arts
and the Philadelphia Museum of Art. 
At: the MFA, Sunday through Sept. 24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Famously awkward in his relationships with others,
Vincent van Gogh connected with people more successfully through
paint _ in portraits intense and intimate, where sitters seem to
look into their own souls without giving up their secrets. The
boldness of these pictures, especially the later ones, still stuns.
And while the works constitute a progression from darkness into
light, from the gloom of his earliest work to the explosion of
color at the end, they never gave up their gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Of van Gogh's 800 or so paintings, roughly 150 are portraits,
and 80 of these make up ``Van Gogh: Face to Face,'' opening to the
public at the Museum of Fine Arts Sunday. While they represent a
minority subject in the artist's oeuvre, these drawings and
paintings are some of his most riveting, and were of particular
importance to the artist himself, who wrote that portraiture
``moves me to the depths, and it makes me feel closer to infinity
than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of the exhibition was the desire of its three
organizers _ the MFA, the Detroit Institute of Arts, and the
Philadelphia Museum of Art _ to bring together van Gogh's
well-known, well-loved portraits of the family of the postman
Joseph Roulin, friends of the painter during his sojourn in Arles
in 1888 and '89. What van Dyck had been to Charles I and his clan,
van Gogh was to the Roulins, painting them more frequently than any
other sitters save himself. Unlike a van Dyck or a Sargent, though,
van Gogh did nothing to glamorize his subjects, unless you count
the almost fantastical last images of Joseph and Augustine Roulin,
who are set against swirling floral backgrounds that may indeed be
wallpaper or fabric yet give them a fairytale quality.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to visit any van Gogh show without the baggage
of what we all know of his tragic life: his poverty; his touching
desire to help others, first expressed through serving as an
evangelist to coal miners; his failure to sell more than two
paintings during his lifetime; his suicide in 1890, at age 37. The
organizers of ``Face to Face'' have tried to put a fresh face on a
familiar artist through their focus on portraits. At its most
dazzling, this means a whole room of the Roulins, their repeating
faces creating a mesmerizing effect, like the Hapsburg faces that
surround you in certain rooms of the Prado.
</P>
<P>
   There are, though, missing masterworks that would have made the
show stronger. While there are etchings of Dr. Gachet, the famous
oil of the physician the artist painted with what he called ``the
heartbroken expression of our time'' is absent, as are other key
pictures. These include larger canvases like ``The Potato Eaters,''
which would have anchored this show of small to medium works,
sparsely hung in Gund Gallery spaces on the scale of a cathedral;
something more chapel-like might have been more suitable. On the
other hand, the spare installation will make it easier for the
expected crowds actually to see the paintings, and the works look
less lonely thanks to courageous choices of wall colors _
cranberry, midnight blue, pumpkin _ that warm the space.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh was largely self-taught. In the very first work in this
straightforward, chronologically arranged show, the 1881 drawing
``The Daughter of Jacob Meyer, After Holbein,'' he dutifully copies
from a how-to-draw manual. Already, though, his interests in firm
outline and heavy pattern are present. They continue in work he
made while living in The Hague in 1882-83, when, unable to afford
professional models, he painted old-age pensioners. In the 1882
``Orphan Man With Top Hat,'' he attacked the paper with pencil and
lithographic crayon, leaving dents and scratches that act as
metaphors for a battered life. Wayward strokes of black fly off the
man's shoulders with the kind of contrary independence the artist
would later convey through color.
</P>
<P>
   The topography of faces like that in the 1882 drawing ``The
Wounded Veteran'' resembles deeply rutted mountain ranges. The
``Veteran'' wears an eye patch and medal of honor that together
suggest a sad story, yet van Gogh doesn't sentimentalize him.
Instead, he gives him an expression of deepest disillusionment. The
``Veteran'' is also an example of van Gogh's combining different
media to achieve a great range of blacks, from the sooty veil that
reveals the weave of the paper to the bottomless darkness of the
sitter's velvet collar.
</P>
<P>
   In The Hague, van Gogh befriended a seamstress and erstwhile
prostitute known as Sien, who, with her children, moved in with the
artist. Van Gogh used the whole family as models, depicting them
slouching, as if pulled down by life. In ``Sien Sewing'' her head
is covered by a shawl: She looks like an elderly Virgin Mary. She
sits in a room defined by pale, hasty, scribbly strokes; her chair
is a near-ghost.
</P>
<P>
   The culmination of van Gogh's Dutch years is ``The Potato
Eaters,'' one of the signatures of the Van Gogh Museum in
Amsterdam. Studies for the masterpiece, and related heads, are in
the MFA show, the faces in queasy colors, gleaming like oil slicks,
as if they'll never be clean. Van Gogh's devotion to peasant
subjects like these was partly inspired by Millet. But while many
of Millet's peasants have a spiritual transcendence, van Gogh's
look permanently trapped.
</P>
<P>
   In 1886, van Gogh moved to Paris, where his art was transformed
by encounters with Impressionism and artists moving beyond it,
including Toulouse-Lautrec and Gauguin. Despite his adopting a
bright palette and sputtery brushwork, the somber mood of van
Gogh's paintings didn't lift. The most convincing of the Parisian
works in the MFA show are self-portraits, including one where he
looks almost like a wild beast, the sharp, tawny strokes suggesting
an entire face covered in hair, the background an extended,
hallucinatory halo circling his head.
</P>
<P>
   The small 1887 ``Self-Portrait With Straw Hat'' reads from all
the way across the room. The face is urgent, pushed to the front of
the picture plane, so much so that the edges of the golden hat are
cut off. The artist looks like he wants to press his way out of the
painting: Here indeed is the evangelist as painter. Turn 90 degrees
and you're confronted with a show-stopper, the ghoulish oil of a
disembodied ``Skull'' with red-rimmed eye sockets and the
appearance of a grin: It's about as close to a smile as the show
comes. A thick zigzag of white paint sticks to the skeletal
forehead, like a remnant of bleached skin. The head hovers against
a burst of yellow that prefigures what's to come _ the complete
liberation of color in the paintings van Gogh made in Arles in
1888-89, when he outlined figures in contrasting hues and set them
against shrieking yellows and turquoise.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most valuable comparisons the show offers is the two
versions of ``The Arlesienne, Madame Joseph-Michel Ginoux.'' In the
slightly earlier one, the color sings; in the revision, it screams.
The influence of Japanese prints is much evident in the Arles room,
but it's the faces of the Roulin family who dominate. The ``Madame
Roulin and Her Baby'' owned by New York's Metropolitan Museum is an
odd composition, with the mother halfway out of the right hand side
of the picture, awkwardly holding up the wobbly-looking infant.
``The Baby Marcelle Roulin'' edges toward comedy, with the pudgy
child looking overinflated, on the verge of exploding. In the later
Roulin portraits, Joseph's once-tame beard takes on a life of its
own, erupting in baroque swirls, like water coursing over rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh made five versions of ``La Berceuse, Augustine
Roulin.'' Three are lined up in the MFA show, in the most
breathtaking display in the entire exhibition. Madame Roulin's
ample figure is one a child could sink into, like the squishiest of
overstuffed sofas. She holds a rope to rock an unseen cradle,
another suggestion of the comfort that was in such short supply in
van Gogh's life. She's a mythic figure; seeing her in multiple
makes her more so.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by artists ranging from Rembrandt to Millet to the
neo-Impressionists, van Gogh also affected those who came after
him, portraitists from Francis Bacon to Chuck Close. But in the
10th year of his career, as he was creating some of his most
radical images, he ended it all. The final work in the MFA show is
one of his last self-portraits. The brushwork of the blue
background rises almost like vegetation, alive, about to swallow
the painter _ who, less than a year later, killed himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
