<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ROCKY-BOS &LR;      06-30 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROCKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROCKY AND BULLWINKLE' SOAR ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ADVENTURES OF ROCKY AND BULLWINKLE 
Directed by: Des McAnuff 
Screenplay by: Kenneth Lonergan (based on characters developed by
Jay Ward) 
Starring: Rene Russo, Jason Alexander, Robert De Niro, Piper
Perabo 
Running time: 88 minutes 
Rated: PG (brief mild language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' falls somewhere
between two other movies based on vintage Jay Ward TV animated
series. It's not quite the goony delight that ``George of the
Jungle'' was, but it's miles ahead of ``Dudley Do-Right.'' Never
pretending to be anything more than sheerest eye candy, it's a
sunny, funny, fittingly cartoony blend of computer-generated 3-D
representations of the flying squirrel and his pal the moose with
actors _ in this case Jason Alexander and Rene Russo as the Cold
War enemies, Boris and Natasha, and Piper Perabo's simpatico FBI
agent. True to form, the ex-spies repeatedly bungle their orders
from Robert De Niro's Fearless Leader.
</P>
<P>
   The cheesy drabness of the 1959-64 TV series provided a large
part of the original's flat black-and-white charm. But this
computer-generated resurrection of the squirrel-moose duo gleams
with freshness. They're entertaining to watch in three dimensions,
and the script gives them plenty of three-dimensional space to move
through, what with lots of overhead shots and numerous
opportunities to hurtle through the air or fall from great heights
since being recalled from limbo in Frostbite Falls, Minnesota,
where they've been marking time since their series was canceled in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, no flies have been gathering on Boris and Natasha
since the fall of communism. They've been busy trotting around
firming up the details of the new capitalist Fearless Leader's
cornering of every cable TV outlet, which he plans to use to
zombiefy the American public. Those who might argue that the job
has long since been done, and that the Fearless Leader's efforts
are redundant, would gently be pointed toward the fact that that's
part of the joke. All the film really wants is a flimsy pretext to
set Rocky and Bullwinkle in motion again, and this one is as good
as any. Obviously Janeane Garofalo, Carl Reiner, John Goodman,
Billy Crystal, Whoopi Goldberg, and Jonathan Winters thought enough
of it to show up in cameos.
</P>
<P>
   The new R &AMP; B muster goofball charm, and the actors excel at
acting against nothing, with the keyboard wizards having added the
squirrel and the moose later. Nobody's going to suggest that the
Fearless Leader is going to show up on the clip reel at De Niro's
inevitable tribute night. But it's worth noting that he provides
yet another lesson to actors, never once condescending to his role,
which might be described as Hitler without the mustache. He
performs it crisply and with craftsmanlike attention to detail. As
with so many films these days, part of the fun lies in its comic
references to other movies, a game that peaks when De Niro veers
into a juicy little parody of his oft-imitated ``Taxi Driver''
mirror scene. Animation is turning into the bright spot of the
summer movie picture, and ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' is part of the
brightness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1352EDT &QL; 
