<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-30 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIGN SAYS: GONE TO CUBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but I'm gonna miss Elian Gonzalez. The kid was
good for two or three columns a month _ and more than that when his
Miami relatives went on one of their goofy rampages.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian saga was one of the great long-running media
spectacles of our time, commanding the public's attention more or
less constantly for seven months and three days. Maybe it was no
O.J. trial in terms of star power, but Elian's stay in America gave
us plenty of drama, lots of turmoil and even a pre-dawn commando
raid that added one more chapter to Janet Reno's legacy as the most
controversial U.S. attorney general since ... well, at least since
Ed ``If You're Innocent You're Not a Suspect'' Meese.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's critics hammered her for the decision to grab Elian by
force and return him to his father, but what was she supposed to
do? Juan Miguel Gonzalez wanted Elian back from those Miami
relatives, who had laid claim to him as if he were an abandoned pet
that they'd found alongside the road.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Elian was found clinging to an inner tube after his
mother drowned in an ill-fated attempt to flee Cuba and take up
residence in America. The relatives in Florida, specifically
Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez and Lazaro's daughter
Marisleysis, quickly asserted their custody rights _ even though
they had no custody rights.
</P>
<P>
   When the father arrived in the United States and asked to be
reunited with his son, the relatives refused to comply. They dared
Reno to take Elian by force _ and she did.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives had and still have their defenders in this
country _ I know this because I must have heard from just about
every one of them after I blasted Lazaro and Marisleysis in a
column. But I say their actions were indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Elian's best interests were their top priority _ and
that's a gigantic ``if'' _ the Miami relatives were hopelessly
misguided. What they did, in effect, was kidnap a 6-year-old boy
and force his father to negotiate for the child's release. It was
outrageous and illegal, as court after court properly ruled.
</P>
<P>
   When the case finally reached the U.S. Supreme Court, the
nation's top tribunal would have nothing to do with the bogus
crusade to keep Elian in America _ which cleared the way for Juan
Miguel Gonzalez to take his son home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home,'' unfortunately _ and most of us can agree that it's
unfortunate _ is Cuba, a communist dictatorship ruled by the
notorious Marxist thug Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   It was because of their understandable hatred for Castro that
the Miami relatives and others in the Cuban American community were
so determined to keep Elian in this country. And it was because
Cuban-Americans are voters in this country that so many American
politicians did so much pandering in regard to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Castro also exploited Elian's plight, helping to turn a family
squabble into an international political extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seemed to have an ax to grind _ everybody except Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, who just wanted his kid back. Gonzalez jumped
through every hoop that the Miami relatives and the U.S. government
placed in front of him, patiently awaiting the day when he would be
allowed to do what he should have been allowed to do months ago:
take Elian home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the thought of this delightful child growing up under the
iron fist of Castro is abhorrent to most Americans, including Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said during her weekly news conference yesterday that she
was glad that Elian ``is with his father ... I just wish he were
with his father in a democratic, free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't we all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone to Castro,'' a protester wailed in Miami's Little
Havana after the Supreme Court refused to keep Elian in America.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope that one day Elian will see his homeland emerge
from Castro's tyranny _ or that one day, when he's old enough to
make his own decision, Elian will return to America.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, the decision was his father's. And the United
States had no right to interfere.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
