<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9506 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ASHCROFT-BOS &LR;      06-30 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ASHCROFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD ASHCROFT LEAVES DEFEATISM BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a perfect coda to its breakthrough single, 1997's
``Bittersweet Symphony,'' British rockers the Verve called it quits
just as the band achieved international stardom. The swan song was
splendid, a majestic and melancholic anthem from its third CD,
``Urban Hymns,'' that lifted the notion of beautiful tragedy to
spellbinding heights of pop songcraft. You couldn't have scripted
better source music for a breakup, especially one that followed a
tumultuous decade of temporary splits, multiple lawsuits, and a
steady diet of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, singer-songwriter Richard Ashcroft has risen from the
Verve's ashes with a much-anticipated solo debut, ``Alone with
Everyone'' (Hut/Virgin). Like the proverbial phoenix, Ashcroft
makes a beeline skyward from the pyre. His album is a lavish,
ambitious affair, a sublimely atmospheric collection that builds on
the Verve's textured aura, in the process reviving a genre that's
been all but subsumed by venemous rap-metal and candied teen-pop:
the sprawling rock opus.
</P>
<P>
   The title is borrowed from hard-living poet Charles Bukowski,
but there's not a blood-and-guts rocker on the album. Fans of the
swaggering frontman best remembered for shoving people in the
``Bittersweet Symphony'' video may be disappointed that Ashcroft's
solo effort isn't, as one might have predicted, a surly kiss-off.
It is, rather, informed by the poetry of living not hard, but well.
The man who before lamented ``It's a bittersweet symphony, this
life/Trying to make ends meet/You're a slave to the money/And then
you die'' is now dreaming of his lover _ ``I'm on fire/I'm full of
love and new desire'' _ to the tune of a sinuous, back-looped pedal
steel guitar in ``On A Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has taken a sharp turn from grandiose defeatism into
the realm of lush romanticism. That may sound like a frightful
recipe for oversized, trite love songs. Truly, one doesn't tend to
associate a happy marriage and becoming a father with inspiration
of the rock 'n' roll variety. To make matters worse, Ashcroft's
lyrics still lack the depth of even his chiseled cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   But his sweeping love notes to wife Kate Radley, former
keyboardist for the band Spiritualized who plays on Ashcroft's
album, brim with lush, complex textures that require no biting
riffs or chaotic jams to make their point. These are sedate,
accessible mini-epics _ heavy with strings, each lasting five
minutes or longer _ songs whose meaning are conveyed not so much in
word or attitude as in the visceral emotion that subtly unravels
and reveals itself in the moody, flowing layers.
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``A Song for the Lovers,'' is a temperate,
breezy track, a loose, undulating weave of acoustic guitar,
violins, piano, horns, and percussion. Longtime Verve producer
Chris Potter created a radiant tapestry of instruments, many played
by Ashcroft, with support from ex-Verve drummer Pete Salisbury,
pedal steel guitarist B.J. Cole, bassist Pino Palladino, and
sometime-Rolling Stones pianist Chuck Leavell. Ashcroft's voice is
sullen and charismatic as ever, infusing gently psychedelic pop
songs and fluid, country-flavored ballads with a blessedly
unsettled ambience.
</P>
<P>
   Not every track is as winsome as ``I Get My Beat,'' thick and
propulsive as ``New York,'' sonically enchanting as ``Slow Was My
Heart.'' The rangy ``You on My Mind in My Sleep'' is way too close
for comfort to the Stones' ``Wild Horses'' (this after courts
awarded 100 percent of the publishing rights to ``Bittersweet
Symphony,'' built around a looped sample of ``The Last Time,'' to
the Stones' back catalog company). And ``C'Mon People (We're Making
It Now)'' is ingratiatingly upbeat as the title. By and large,
though, ``Alone with Everyone'' is a mature, complex album that
shines in an increasingly dark, dank rock music landscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
