<HEADLINE>
VOTERS SUPPORT POLITICAL SYSTEM FAVORED BY PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda _ Early results of a referendum on Uganda's
political future showed Friday that more than 80 percent of voters
want to continue with the current ``no-party'' system advocated by
the nation's president.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the president, Yoweri Museveni, still declared
victory, saying the turnout was far too low for him to claim a
strong mandate. His opponents had called for a boycott on a
referendum on whether to continue with the so-called Movement
system or return to a multi-party system. Based on returns counted
by Friday evening, just 40.5 percent of registered voters took
part, far less than the roughly 75 percent in the 1996 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ugandans have spoken about the Movement system of
government,'' said Cecilia Atim-Ogwal, an opposition figure here
and leader of one faction of the Ugandan People's Congress. ``They
have rejected it totally.''
</P>
<P>
   But an official with Movement said people did not stay away
because of the boycott but rather because of rainy weather and
because Museveni's victory had not seemed in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' the official, Moses Byaruhanga, secretary
to the Movement National Referendum Committee, said Friday
afternoon after the first results were tallied. ``This has showed
what the people want.''
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, the results and low turnout seemed to give both
sides something to campaign on next year, when elections for
Parliament and the presidency will be held.
</P>
<P>
   In this campaign Museveni, a former bush fighter who took power
in 1986, has argued that political parties merely divide Uganda by
tribe and religion. Those divisions, he says, gave rise to two
dictators, Idi Amin and Milton Obote, and a distinctly violent era
of Uganda's history since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the multi-party system say that the Movement
system _ which allows political parties in name only _ violates the
freedom of association guaranteed by the constitution. Moreover,
they argue, the Movement is essentially a one-party system, which
they say Museveni manipulates to his political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign diplomats and other experts give Museveni broad credit
for bringing a measure of peace and economic growth to Uganda,
though some western governments have also been pushing him behind
the scenes to open up more politically. He has argued that the
system is open because he appoints his opponents _ like Paul
Ssemogerere, who ran for president against Museveni but later
served as his foreign minister _ to top positions.
</P>
<P>
   The results released Friday accounted for roughly 10 percent of
Uganda's 9.6 million registered voters: the Movement won about 83
percent of the votes cast and the multi-party advocates 17.4
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview on Thursday with a U.N. news service, Museveni
said that any result under 60 percent would show ``a serious
problem with the Movement system.''
</P>
<P>
   The results varied by region, with voters in sections of the
north, where Museveni is unpopular because of a rebellion and
remaining support for Obote, barely going to the polls. Only 11
percent of voters went to the polls, for example, in the northern
town of Kitgum. Atim-Ogwal, a member of parliament, said less than
10 percent of the people in her town, Lira in the north, had voted.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the votes from the west, Museveni's home region and
where he is popular, was not counted by Friday evening. The
remaining results were expected overnight and on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
