<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ While the two leading candidates
in Mexico's upcoming presidential election represent opposite views
of where Mexico's political system will go and have vastly
different personalities, they are remarkably close on the issues.
By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S. (Chicago) _ To an unprecedented degree, the
Mexican election has come north of the border, to the United
States. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MCDONALDS (Millau) _ The trial of the left-wing militant
Jose Bove, accused of criminal damage to a McDonald's, opened here
Friday in a carnival atmosphere as thousands of anti-globalization
protesters crammed into this southern French market town. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to approve
a spending bill that includes funds to help fight the drug war in
Colombia and for peacekeeping in Kosovo before it adjourns for the
Fourth of July holiday. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BOAT (Jakarta) _ They fled in terror, many of them
women and children, after 200 fellow villagers were killed in
Christian-Muslim violence in the Spice Islands. Now, with no trace
of their sunken ferry, it seems that 500 refugees are dead. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ North and South Korea signed a deal to
reunite aging family members separated by the Korean War half a
century ago and to return dozens of North Korean spies held in the
South. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-U.S.-PINOCHET (Washington) _ The United States is expected
on Friday to release some documents related to Gen. Augusto
Pinochet. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-POLITICS (Kampala) _ President Yoweri Museveni has won
his referendum on maintaining a ``no party'' system, but the
ultra-low voter turnout has prompted both sides to claim victory.
By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Doctors won a major victory as
the House early Friday approved a bill giving them an exemption
from anti-trust law so they bargain collectively over fees. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PRESBYTERIANS-SAMESEX-UNIONS (Los Angeles) _ At 5 p.m. our time,
the Presbyterian Assembly meets and will vote on whether or not to
change the church constitution to ban same-sex marriages. Not sure
what they'll do, and it has to be ratified by the local bodies. But
changes in the constitution are very rare. Last one was barring
ordination of gays, which was ultimately approved by the body. This
reflects the continuing, decade-long fight in protestant circles
over the issue of gays, as gays become more open and accepted and
the churches react. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, there will be no RELIGION-COLUMN today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HISPANICS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore makes a
pitch for Hispanic support in a speech before Lulac. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CITRUS (Beijing) _ When China joins the World Trade
Organization, probably later this year, it will be forced to allow
a huge range of foreign goods greater access to its vast markets.
But a few U.S. agricultural items _ including citrus fruits _ have
already gained improved entry in the last few months. In Shanghai,
1,800 cartons of oranges sold out within two hours, and tens of
thousands of tons of grapefruits have sold in Beijing since they
arrived on May 20. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Looking at the winners and losers in the
market in the second quarter. On the last day of the quarter, the
Dow Jones industrial average was down 30 points, or 0.3 percent, at
noon, and the Nasdaq index was up 48 points, up 1.2 percent. The
10-year Treasury note was up 2/32, to yield 6.02 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-PROPERTY (Hong Kong) _ The drastic loss of wealth
among property owners has rippled through the economy in the form
of weak consumer spending and has led to bitterness toward Hong
Kong's first post-colonial government. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-CROPS (Chicago) _ U.S. farmers planted more genetically
modified seed than they had projected in March, according to a
survey by the Agriculture Department. The rise occurred despite
some expectations of cutbacks because of foreign restrictions on
the sale of genetically modified food. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-E-SIGNATURE (Philadelphia) _ President Clinton will sign
the e-signature bill, electronically, at Independence Hall. He also
has to sign a paper version. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The decision by the Japanese government to
bail out a large department store company is re-igniting concerns
about Japan's economic future just as the country seems to be
breaking out of its decade-long malaise. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GAZPROM (Moscow) _ Minority shareholders in Gazprom, the
world's largest natural gas producer, have gained a bigger voice in
running the company under changes pushed by the new administration
of President Vladimir Putin. By Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis' ``Aborad at Home'' and Frank Rich's ``Journal.''
</P>
