<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9578 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-DEATH-MACHINE-EXHIBIT     06-30 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-MACHINE-EXHIBIT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIGHT TO KNOW?  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF JULY 3, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By JOHN DURANT  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The machine itself is nothing much to look at. It's just a
standard laptop computer connected to some common syringe-driving
equipment. What is truly unsettling is the far from prosaic use to
which it has been put. Just by hooking themselves up to it and
tapping in a few very basic commands, four terminally ill patients
have managed to end their own lives under the watchful eyes of
their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   It was developed by an Australian doctor, Philip Nitschke. In
the mid-1990s, the government of the Northern Territory passed a
law permitting voluntary euthanasia under strictly defined
conditions. This law was in force for only a few months before the
Federal House of Representatives legislated to override it. In this
short period, however, four patients obtained permission to end
their lives, and did so with the help of Nitschke's machine.
</P>
<P>
   So why did we decide to buy and display this machine in the
biggest ever development in the Science Museum, the Wellcome Wing?
The answer is simple. Voluntary euthanasia is a big issue. Whether
doctors should be permitted to help terminally ill patients who
want to die is an agonizingly difficult question about which honest
people of good conscience manifestly disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one member of Parliment has written to criticize us for
staging a public debate on the issue of voluntary euthanasia. Yet
surely facilitating a better informed debate on the morally and
socially contentious areas is an essential part of the remit of a
museum of science and technology or art?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Science Museum is committed to dealing with
substantial issues that concern the public, however delicate or
difficult they may be. For example, one of the first exhibits on
the ground floor of the Wellcome Wing will deal with the extremely
controversial question of the use of drugs in international
athletics. This is such a contentious subject that parts of this
exhibit have had to be approved by the museum's lawyers to protect
us from court action.
</P>
<P>
   So the new wing was absolutely the right place for it. In
keeping with the times, the Wellcome Wing won't simply impart
information, it will try to engage visitors in dialogue about the
wider questions that 21st-century scientific ideas and innovations
are raising. Through multiple electronic terminals dotted around
the wing, visitors will be able to express their own views on the
scientific, medical and technological issues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Nitschke appears to have been motivated by two main desires: to
leave the final decision to die in the hands of the terminally ill
themselves, and to provide them with a means of dying that allowed
them to be surrounded by their loved ones at the key moment rather
than by professional caretakers.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's motives are very different. Our main aim is to
stimulate informed public debate about what is unquestionably an
important ethical, legal and social issue.
</P>
<P>
   (John Durant is director of science communication at the Science
Museum in London. The Wellcome Wing opens to the public on July 3,
2000.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9579 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-SERBIAN-SCIENTIST-SPE     06-30 1995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIAN-SCIENTIST-SPEAKS-OUT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN SCIENTISTS UNDER SIEGE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF JULY 3, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By GILLIAN SANDFORD  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For three decades, Milan Kurepa was professor of physics at the
University of Belgrade. But he resigned in 1998 after watching his
once-thriving lab become what he calls ``a workplace of ghosts''
as, one by one, colleagues and students fled the country. Rather
than suffer in silence, he agreed to speak to New Scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Sandford traveled to Belgrade to hear his story.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: You're a known critic of the Milosevic regime. Have
you suffered personally in any way because of that?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: I've never been harassed or threatened. I know some
academics who have been harassed and even fired because of their
anti-Milosevic political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you an example of the kinds of things that happen to
me. A few months ago, I was at a conference of 400 university
physicists and high school teachers. I was due to lecture on the
1998 University Act. This act was brought in by the Milosevic
regime to ensure that all appointments are made on party loyalty,
rather than academic or intellectual ability. It was designed to
stifle universities as centers of free thought and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived at the lecture theater and it was locked and the three
physicists at the conference who belonged to Milosevic's ruling
Socialist Party _ two of whom were organizers _ refused to let me
give the lecture.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Surely the new law doesn't actually state:
``Appointments will only be made on party loyalty?''
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: Under the new law, all rectors, deans and vice-deans of
universities will be appointed by the Ministry of Education instead
of by the universities themselves. Moreover, these deans now have
the power to hire and fire staff without appeal. This effectively
politicizes the university system and makes appointments dependent
on party loyalty, not academic criteria.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Is this why you resigned from your university post?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: I did not want to be put in a position where a minister
of education _ a puppet of the ruling party _ has the power to
decide whether or not I can be a professor. We were also asked to
sign a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   This was, in a way, affirming support for the regime. I did not
want to do that. So I preferred to retire. A wave of resignations
and firings have occurred because of the university law. Around 150
academics either quit or were sacked from Belgrade University.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: How has your scientific work been affected by the
breakup of Yugoslavia, the wars between Serbia and its neighbors,
sanctions, and last year's NATO-led bombing campaign?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: In 1990, I had a thriving atomic physics lab with an
18-person staff. We tried to stay at the cutting edge of discovery.
We were planning to work with polarized electrons. Ten years later,
Serbian science is at the level it was in the 1950s. Most of the
staff _ people I nurtured myself _ have left for other countries,
or retired.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Most UN sanctions against Serbia have now been lifted.
But this doesn't appear to have helped ordinary people like you. If
anything, it seems to have consolidated Milosevic's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: That's a false statement. Now, at least, there is some
free flow of information. When sanctions were in force, Milosevic
used to say to people: ``Look at the EU and the West. They are
against people in Yugoslavia.'' He was able to use sanctions to win
support from people and whip up anti-Western feeling. This was
particularly strong after last year's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember the details of sanctions against South Africa,
but I know that in Iraq children are dying because of sanctions. Is
that Western policy? What kind of policy is that? Has the United
States succeeded in bringing down Castro in nearly 40 years of
sanctions against Cuba? Are there any politicians willing to think
about people _ not about one leader? Poor people suffer, but the
sanctions don't affect the ruling party. Yet most sanctions against
Serbia were lifted quite a while back.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Aren't you free to travel and resume contacts with
colleagues abroad? I hardly know where to start. We expected to
travel all across Western Europe. Years ago, under the Marshal Tito
regime, Yugoslavia's was the best passport to have in the whole of
Eastern Europe. Now gaining a visa takes time and money. I need a
letter of invitation to go to a conference. Someone has to
guarantee that they will support me with sufficient funds to cover
my basic needs. Sometimes, this is quite a humiliating process.
Then I must wait between two days and two weeks for a visa.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom to travel should have enabled me to visit my former
students in other countries and to re-establish connections with
colleagues abroad and with institutions such as the International
Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna. Visits abroad should have meant
guest lectures and joint papers and even joint projects, as well as
access to journals and the chance to buy instruments and equipment.
We probably would also have been able to generate additional
funding. But none of this happened.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: How do you carry out research when you're starved of
contact with the outside world?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: It is not possible to do serious research without
journals, without textbooks, with intermittent water and
electricity, because our experiments take at least a week to do and
we need constant power. Often, we just have to improvise.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: How do you improvise?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: We have a long tradition of improvisation. For the five
years before the collapse of Yugoslavia, we were smuggling in
equipment. We have ended up smuggling all kinds of things in, like
the time a colleague in Manchester brought in parts for an electron
scattering machine. In 1985, I also managed to bring in a large
metal shield, about six feet square, from France. I was fine at
Paris airport but when I reached Belgrade the customs offer asked
what it was and was very suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember how many times during the late 1980s I crossed
the border between Serbia and neighboring countries with gaskets,
potentiometers and other equipment hidden in my pockets, bags,
suitcases, anywhere. Perhaps the most amusing time was when I was
in Brussels and wanted to bring home some xenon gas. It's stored at
very high pressures. We asked the Yugoslav Ambassador if he would
bring it in diplomatic bags, but he refused. A colleague eventually
tried to take it on a plane. When it was X-rayed at the airport,
the security guard asked what it was. When he was told it was gas
under pressure, he just screamed: ``Get it out of here! Get it out
of here!''
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: If it is so difficult to travel to the West, what
about your Western colleagues? Have they maintained contact with
you?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: Some have been very helpful. But generally people have
not been supportive. So many of them never cared enough to even ask
if, for example, we were all right, how we lived, whether we needed
anything. I get letters from some Japanese physicists from the
University of Kyoto, but I have had arguments with my colleagues
from France. Britons are very quiet: they just don't say anything.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Why do you think your colleagues in other countries
have been largely silent?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: I think in most cases they began to believe the
anti-Serbian propaganda in their countries. They believed all those
stories. All the propaganda that said Serbian people were killing
and raping Croatians and Bosnians, that we are beasts.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Was this really all propaganda? Surely, some of it was
true?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: We have a very troubled history in this country _
atrocities have been committed by Serbs and against Serbs. Some
Serbs have been killing and raping, but I believe much that has
been reported is not true.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Bluntly speaking, can you blame us for being
indifferent? After all, we live comfortable lives. No scientist in
a Western country is suffering because of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: If you believe that science is global, then I'm
convinced you should care about your colleagues in other countries.
Colleagues from all over the world are adding to the body of
knowledge called science. It isn't just those in Western Europe. We
in Serbia are no different. If we suffer, then science suffers. We
physicists treat one another as an international gang. We support
each other. It's a sense of togetherness. If I work in five or six
countries, I treat my colleagues there as I treat those here in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Let's move on. In terms of the future, what
specifically would you like your overseas colleagues to do now?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: There is one thing that they can do: supply us with
journals _ preferably from 1991 onwards. Believe it or not, in the
university, we haven't been getting journals for eight years or
more. We don't know what's going on in our fields, which is fatal
for any scientist.
</P>
<P>
   There's a phrase in physics: ``inventing hot water.'' We've done
it several times over here _ believing that we have discovered
something, only to learn that it has already been discovered and
written about. We didn't know because we did not have the journal
articles.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Are there any examples where you've written a paper on
something that's already been discovered?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: I recently wrote a paper on inert gas ionization and the
electronic states of molecules, and submitted it to various
journals. One referee wrote back to say that something similar had
already been done, and that the reference was missing from my
submission. But how was I to know? We don't get any journals. This
has happened more than once.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Countries at war often pay more attention to science _
particularly its military aspects _ than in peacetime. Is this the
case in Serbia? Are any areas of science doing well?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: No areas of science are doing well here. The government
has specialist institutions for defense-related projects, but they
were bombed. I really don't know so much about them.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Are you unwilling to talk about this because of your
personal security?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: No, if someone's working for defense then they are of
course not allowed to talk about it. That's the same in the United
States and Britain. But I don't want to be involved in questions
about military institutions and defense. I just don't like it. If
my intention when I graduated was to work with the military I would
have gone there straight from university and had a big flat. I
didn't choose to do that. That's the choice. And now I'm a poor
person. It was simply that I chose a different way of life and a
different path.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Do you think Serbia's present hardship is a price
worth paying, that it may lead to democracy?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: I don't like that question.
</P>
<P>
   SANDFORD: Why don't you like it?
</P>
<P>
   KUREPA: Because behind the question I feel propaganda again.
This is not a logical question. We were brought into this state of
nihilism by our authorities and nobody asked us if we were ready to
pay any price for this stupidity. We don't have democracy here. I
can't see any connection between the current situation in the
country and the possibility of democracy. We are under an
oppressive government and no one asked us if we wanted this current
situation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
