r a BC-HOSTAGE-ARCHBISHOP-1S     06-30 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSTAGE-ARCHBISHOP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARCHBISHOP WANTS ACCUSED HOSTAGE-TAKER TO GET HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: SUBS 4thgraf, ``I am, to correct Flores' age _ 70 sted
71; combines with HOSTAGE-SNIPER)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOE HOLLEY and BILL HENDRICKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Roman Catholic Archbishop Patrick Flores wants the
man who held him hostage for nine hours earlier this week to get
some psychological help.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I saw yesterday, I saw a very sick man,'' Flores
said Thursday, a day after the ordeal at his chancery office.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop said he was not in a position to recommend
whether Nelson Antonio Escolero, 40, the man charged in the hostage
taking, should face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am suggesting very highly,'' Flores, 70, said, ``that the
man be given the blessing and privilege of psychological
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Escolero, a native of El Salvador who has been in the United
States for 25 years, was being held in Bexar County Jail in lieu of
$2 million bond in connection with the incident Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Flores recounted his ordeal during a news conference held at the
San Antonio chancery, two floors below the office where he was held
captive.
</P>
<P>
   Unharmed and in good spirits after an overnight stay at Christus
Santa Rosa Hospital, the Catholic leader recalled that he tried to
help Escolero with immigration problems, but that the man
threatened him with what he claimed was a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen one,'' Flores said. ``I don't even carry a
pocketknife.''
</P>
<P>
   The weapon turned out to be a harmless military training
grenade, police bomb squad officer Rocky Romero said.
</P>
<P>
   Escolero told Flores he had been arrested twice for possession
of marijuana in 1984 and had paid the fines, but in 1999 he was
jailed and deported for his crimes 15 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted his immigration papers back so he could take his wife
and family to Cuba, ``the only place,'' he said, ``not infected by
capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the afternoon, they were busy with phone
conversations with police negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio police said that a sniper was positioned to take
action if negotiators failed to persuade Escolero to put down his
weapon and release Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at every option,'' police Lt. Dan Akeroyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Akeroyd, who heads the police department's special operations,
acknowledged his SWAT team includes snipers and that one of his
marksmen was in position to shoot if necessary in during the
nine-hour standoff that began at 10:22 a.m. Wednesday inside the
Catholic Chancery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the sniper had in his sights,'' Akeroyd
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that he believed the sniper could see inside
the third-floor office where Flores was being held.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 p.m., Flores decided to do his own negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make a pledge to you,'' he recalled telling
Escolero. ``If you do not kill yourself, I will look for a lawyer
or two to look into why you're being deported. I'll even pay for a
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores also told Escolero he would be happy to help his wife and
family with food vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will walk out of here with my hands raised and your hands
raised, too,'' Flores told Escolero. ``You have to leave the
grenade on top of my desk. In the name of God, in the name of
Jesus, in the name of your family, in the name of everybody else, I
ask you not to take life.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, he said OK. But he said, `You better keep
your promise.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two men walked out of the office holding onto each other. In
the hallway, they confronted police officers. They were told to put
their hands up and then turn around in a circle so they could check
for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Escolero asked to lie down on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the last time I saw him,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said Escolero obviously has psychological problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt that he was a very angry individual, and that
psychologically he was very shaky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
