<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL THAT INCLUDES FUNDS FOR KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING AND
COLOMBIA  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ala., Conn., Calif)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress completed work Friday on an $11.2 billion
spending bill that includes more than $1 billion in emergency aid
to battle drug traffickers and their rebel allies in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the measure by voice vote with virtually no
debate just after noon EDT and sent it to President Clinton for his
signature as Congress was preparing to adjourn for the weeklong
July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approval followed passage in the House late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., complained that the measure contained
too many ``pork barrel'' elements of the kind common to legislation
pushed through in the waning hours of a session.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest controversy concerned the centerpiece of the
legislation, $1.3 billion in assistance to help train and equip
Colombian army and police forces. A crucial component is a fleet of
sophisticated transport and attack helicopters to ferry Colombian
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Critics in both parties have warned that the aid to Colombia
would encourage a dangerous escalation in an unwinnable
Vietnam-style conflict that has already claimed thousands of lives
in the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters, including Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and
Clinton, have pushed hard to help an important Latin American ally
stem the tide of drugs flowing into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to do anything to combat drugs, we must be
responsive to the people who have pledged to fight this plague,''
said Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., who heads the House
Appropriations Panel, which oversees foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   The bill will also finance the military's peacekeeping mission
in Kosovo, provide disaster relief to flood and wildfire victims in
the United States and make a down payment on a new Second Avenue
subway in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republican leaders had bickered for months over
how to package the aid. The House passed a similar $12.7 billion
omnibus bill in late March, but Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, balked at bundling such a wide range of aid, fearing it
would be a magnet for pork-barrel spending.
</P>
<P>
   As the months dragged on with no action, the Pentagon warned
that without prompt financing the armed services would have to
begin canceling training exercises. President Andres Pastrana of
Colombia cautioned that the delay was hurting his country's
anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators finally worked out a compromise
this week on the size and scope of the package and tacked it on to
a popular spending bill for military construction projects. The
final House vote was 306-110, with 171 Republicans and 135
Democrats in favor, and 44 Republicans, 64 Democrats and two
independents against.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans had also hoped to attach an amendment to
permit the limited sale of food and medicine to Cuba. But the
language agreed upon by House Republicans drew a filibuster threat
from Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who said the legislation would
do more harm than good.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Cuba amendment would bar public and private U.S. financing
for the sale of food and medicine, and it would turn into law
current regulations that restrict which groups _ including
relatives and educators _ can visit Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so wrong, so outrageous,'' said Dodd, who supports
lifting sanctions altogether. ``Only poor and innocent people
suffer when you bar food and medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Cuba leaves the amendment's future uncertain.
House Republicans said they hoped to attach it to an agriculture
spending bill after the holiday recess, but if Democratic
objections persist, the deal could be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   The aid package also includes $2 billion to pay for costs the
Pentagon has incurred this year as part of the NATO mission in
Kosovo. The bill provides the military with $1.6 billion to cover
rising fuel costs and $1.3 billion to supplement its health care
program.
</P>
<P>
   Aid was not confined to foreign emergencies. The package has
$661 million to pay reconstruction costs for the 400 families in
Los Alamos, N.M., who lost their homes after the devastating fire
there two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Also tucked in were odds and ends like $17.5 million to improve
fire safety in the Capitol, $4.5 million to reimburse the District
of Columbia police department for costs related to protests at the
recent meetings of the International Monetary Fund and $3 million
toward a new Second Avenue subway in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But easily the most contentious part of the package focused on
the anti-narcotics aid to Colombia and other countries in the
region, including Ecuador and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   This assistance will lead to a much larger U.S. role in helping
Colombia crack down on a flourishing narcotics trade in
rebel-controlled territory in the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes 18 Blackhawk helicopters and 42 Huey II
helicopters to ferry special Colombian army battalions and
Colombian National Police. The mix of aircraft represents a
compromise between the House, which favored the larger, more
expensive Blackhawks, and the Senate, which wanted only the less
costly Hueys.
</P>
<P>
   To help address the critics' concerns about the Colombian
military's poor human rights record, the bill included $122 million
for programs to promote human rights and justice in the region, $29
million more than the administration had requested.
</P>
<P>
   With fears of an open-ended military commitment hanging heavy
over many members, the bill has a provision that limits the number
of U.S. military personnel in support of the Colombia mission to
500 at any one time, unless more are needed for a rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying we want to help, but only if you assure us you do
not abuse human rights and prosecute any violators who do,'' said
Rep. Sam Farr, a California Democrat who lived in Colombia for two
years as a Peace Corps volunteer. ``If you are using this aid to
help the insurgents, you lose the helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aid will support an antidrug plan that Pastrana
announced last year, after working closely with U.S. officials. The
strategy, called Plan Colombia, seeks $3.5 billion in international
aid in the next three years. Beside the enforcement components, the
plan envisions public investment to stimulate Colombia's
beleaguered economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
