<HEADER>
A9625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-INSURANCE-PROBE-HNS &LR;      06-30 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AG INVESTIGATING FORMER CALIFORNIA INSURANCE OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Attorney General Bill Lockyer is
investigating whether a former Insurance Department official
received kickbacks funneled through a football camp attended by the
children of Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush. Quackenbush resigned
earlier this week for allegedly using insurance company fines to
help advance his own political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer's office is investigating allegations that former
department official George Grays pocketed up to $90,000 from the
Sacramento-based Skillz Athletics Foundation, sources said. Skillz,
in turn, had been given $263,000 by a foundation Grays created with
fines levied against insurance companies, documents and testimony
show.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer acknowledged for the first time Thursday that he was
conducting a criminal investigation into Grays' activities at the
Department of Insurance, one day after Quackenbush resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Michioku, a spokeswoman for Lockyer, would not comment on
the investigation, except to say: ``We have obtained documents that
have raised questions, and among the documents have been check
payments to George Grays.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations are the first that someone within the Department
of Insurance may have personally benefited from the $12.5 million
in fines Quackenbush imposed on several insurance companies
following the 1994 Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, a Republican, quit before the Assembly Insurance
Committee was prepared to question him and others about how the
settlement money was spent.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said they already had significant evidence Quackenbush
and his chief aides were using the money for a ``perpetual
political campaign'' instead of helping earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it surprises me very much to also find out there
was a considerable amount of potential criminal activity
surrounding that as well,'' said Democratic Assemblyman Fred
Keeley, a member of the committee that investigated Quackenbush and
the department. ``Frankly, this was an operation that was wildly
out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Grays' lawyer did not respond to requests for comment. Grays has
repeatedly declined to answer questions posed by lawmakers and
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   No one has accused Quackenbush of diverting money into his bank
account. Quackenbush's political consultants were hired by the
earthquake foundations and money went to television and radio
commercials that prominently featured the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Shumate, a GOP political consultant to Quackenbush, was paid
$175,000 from the earthquake fund in connection with $3 million in
TV ads featuring Quackenbush and another $100,000 to develop ways
to sell insurance in minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has said the earthquake foundation money donated to
Skillz Athletics and other nonprofit groups, such as $500,000 to
the Sacramento Urban League, was designed to reach out to minority
communities typically underserved by the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Grays joined the Insurance Department in December 1998 as chief
deputy after serving as Quackenbush's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned in April 2000 and declined to testify before the
Assembly Insurance Committee, invoking his Fifth Amendment right
against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Brian T. Thompson, director of Skillz Athletics Foundation, has
not testified before the Legislature on his relationship to Grays
or on how his organization managed to receive $263,000 from a
nonprofit foundation supposedly set up to aid victims of the
Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Skillz foundation attorney Timothy Charshaf,
Thompson feels betrayed by Grays, who had been a friend for years.
</P>
<P>
   Charshaf acknowledged that Skillz had issued 11 checks to Grays
in recompense for his help in securing the $263,000 grant in 1999,
and to buy football equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it doesn't look right,'' he said. ``Let's just say that
my guy feels betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was originally scheduled to testify Monday at the
Assembly's investigative hearing, but did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented action, the Assembly ordered Thompson
arrested. But when Quackenbush resigned Wednesday, the committee
disbanded, and Thompson was released from his subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   The new information about Grays is just the latest on the
California Research and Assistance Fund, the nonprofit foundation
Grays helped set up with the insurance company fines.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was supposed to be wholly separate from the
Department of Insurance, but testimony showed Grays was deeply
involved in its activities even though he could not legally
represent its interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he had participation basically from soup to nuts,''
Keeley said. ``From beginning to end, he was the dominate figure in
all of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
