u i BC-INDONESIA-BOAT-ART-45     06-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BOAT-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TRACE OF SHIP CARRYING RELIGIOUS REFUGEES FOUND IN ROUGH SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ They pushed and jostled in panic to board
the battered ferry, witnesses said, fleeing a massacre in which up
to 200 of their fellow villagers had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   They were the lucky ones, mostly women and children as well as
more than 30 wounded survivors, crammed aboard the old, wood-hulled
Cahaya Bahari, nearly doubling its licensed load to almost 500
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But only hours into their journey from the far eastern Maluku
islands of Indonesia to a haven on the island of Sulawesi, the ship
sent a distress signal, saying that its engines were dead and that
it was taking on water in heavy seas.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more was heard from the ship, and Friday night, 30 hours
later, rescuers said they had found no trace of the Cahaya Bahari
or of its passengers or crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a miracle if we could find anyone still alive,''
Solaeman, the head of the search and rescue team, told the Reuters
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Antara news agency said that a life buoy had been
found, but it was not clear whether it came from the missing ship.
Searchers pulled two men from the stormy waters, but Solaeman said
they were fishermen from a separate capsized boat _ their lives
saved, perhaps, because of the loss of the Cahaya Bahari.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said strong currents might have swept the foundering
vessel or its passengers out toward the mouth of the Pacific Ocean
in stormy seas where the waves reached nine feet in height. They
said the waters are thick with sharks.
</P>
<P>
   At the small port of Manado, the vessel's destination, The
Associated Press reported that hundreds of relatives _ many of them
also refugees from a long-running religious conflict in Maluku _
clustered at the waterfront, sobbing and whispering.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is pray and hope,'' said Ferry Potoboda, who
said he had 20 relatives on the missing vessel, including wounded
victims and children.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre on May 19 at the village of Duma on Halmahera
Island was one of the worst single incidents in a conflict between
Christians and Muslims that has taken the lives of more than 2,500
people since it erupted 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It involved an attack by Muslim gangs _ apparently including
fighters who had traveled to the region on inter-island ferries _
in what they described as revenge for a wave of killings by
Christians on the island last December.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are
Muslim, but in the Maluku islands Muslims and Christians are evenly
divided. That has made the area fertile ground for agitators
seeking to create unrest in the hope of weakening the central
government in Jakarta.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The fighting first erupted in January 1999 in a marketplace
fight in Ambon that witnesses said appeared to be part of a planned
provocation to touch off a local war.
</P>
<P>
   In Ambon, the small, pretty city that is the center of the
Maluku islands, residents reported Friday that there was some
easing of violence four days after President Abdurrahman Wahid
declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear why that might be. The military is already
in control of Ambon but has lost much of its peacekeeping function
as soldiers have turned against each other according to their
religions, arming, aiding and sometimes apparently leading the
local fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers have broken ranks and joined the fighting as
partisans, and, as a result, Indonesian troops right now have
virtually no credibility in areas where a neutral force is most
desperately needed,'' said the New York-based monitoring group
Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   As the fighting has continued, ferries from Ambon and elsewhere
in the Maluku islands have carried away thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Among other destinations, both Muslims and Christians have fled
to separate religious enclaves on Sulawesi island, where the
refugees aboard the Cahaya Bahari were headed.
</P>
<P>
   When the killings have flared, as they did last week in
Halmahera, small ports have become scenes of panic and anguish.
Crowds fight their way up narrow gangplanks, passing their
belongings and their children up above their heads. Some even
shinny up the ropes that moor the vessels.
</P>
<P>
   They are exchanging one danger for another. Indonesia's badly
maintained and overloaded ferries and the rough seas of the monsoon
season are deadly places to be. Disasters at sea are a way of life
in Indonesia's broad archipelago of thousands of islands.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of passengers have already died this year. Among them
were more than 40 people aboard the Masnait, a small ferry that
capsized and sank in May. They, too, were refugees fleeing the
fighting in Ambon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
