<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CELEBRATION OF US CULTURE, FOR GOOD OR EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   02)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While our blessed and beloved country is at the peak of its
power and wealth and cultural influence (for good or for ill) this
Fouth of July, there are some ways in which we are the poorer.
</P>
<P>
   And one of those is in the decline, and in some cases the
abandonment, of the spirit of comity and compromise in the US
Congress. Not even the searing conflicts of the Great Depression
split the Congress into such dysfunctional cleavage as we endure
today. Friday's Globe account about how Tip O'Neill convinced
Ronald Reagan to intercede 16 years ago with Margaret Thatcher to
foster a peace settlement in Northern Ireland shows how much
leaders of substance and grit can do to overcome the barbed wire
fences of ideology and partiswanship.
</P>
<P>
   It is the lack of such substantial leadership that we suffer
today. Timid and timorous politicians afraid to venture out from
their prepackaged positions can never make it to the statesman
level. There are many rungs on the ladder of leadership, but the
willingness to take on your own most partisan followers, and impose
on your own claque a deal that makes many of them howl, is the test
of statesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Globe reporter John Aloysius Farrell sifted through 10,000 pages
of Reagan White House papers relating to the Irish conflict, and
described how O'Neill and Reagan wove together a joint campaign to
foster Ulster peace while they were battling furiously and publicly
over tax cuts, retrenching of Great Society social programs, and
bitterly-divisive foreign policy issues such as US aid to the
Contra guerillas in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'80's, it was a Republican president battling a
Democratic-controlled House. That situtation is now reversed. But
the personal qualities of O'Neill and Reagan surmounted the snares
and temptations erected by foes of advancing the Irish peace
process. The State Department was, as ususal, tilting toward the
British position. Reagan acolytes trying to crowbar the Contra
money through Congress wanted Reagan to rebuff O'Neill's Irish
overture until the Speaker caved on funding the Latin American
dirty war.
</P>
<P>
   Once Reagan was won over by O'Neill, there was the matter of
Thatcher. The Iron Lady had narrowly escaped death when the
Provisional IRA _ ``terrorists,'' in O'Neill's private letter to
Reagan _ had bombed her seaside convention hotel in Brighton,
England. Some of her friends had been assassinated elsewhere by IRA
bombs. She had good reason to despise the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But Reagan's undeniable affection for Thatcher thawed the Iron
Lady to the point where she acceded to his private entreaties. The
peace process lurched forward. O'Neill and Reagan advanced the
reputation and influence of the Irish moderates led by John Hume,
and the hard men of the IRA Provo units gradually lost ground as
diplomacy advanced.
</P>
<P>
   It culminated in the 1985 signing of the Anglo-Irish accord
granting the Republic of Ireland diplomatic standing to negotiate
directly with the British. And Thatcher's plumb was the invitation
from O'Neill to be the first of Britain's prime ministers since
Churchill to address a joint session of Congress. So with skill and
some schmoozing, some blarney and bluster, some backchannel
negotiation and some highlevel horsetrading, a worthy cause was
advanced by politicians willing to compromise and risk.
</P>
<P>
   Have we a similar stripe of leadership today? Fat chance. Every
House Speaker since O'Neill has fallen into the pit of
partisanship. Tom Foley got licked in the '94 uprising by a
Republican who brayed his support for term limits, only to weasel
out of his pledge once elected. Jim Wright got fanged by Newt
Gingrich, himself unhorsed by a revolt among his own conservative
horse soldiers. The current leader, Dennis Hastert, is widely if
not fairly regarded as a tool of his next-in-line supposed
subalterns, Texans Dick Armey and Tom DeLay, both practicioners of
the Bowie-knife approach to politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican Senate, it is no better. The failure of the
impeachment drive, and the inability of Republicans in Congress to
deal successfully with President Clinton, have poisoned the well.
Clinton's judicial nominations and legislative initiatives are
sidetracked. Lobbysists for guns, tobacco and oil reign supreme and
even sit in on secret sessions to help write legislation favorable
to the NRA, the tobacco lobby and polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are split on which side is more to blame, though Clinton
generally gets the better of the PR war. One key to that may be his
level of confidence, the optimism which he sprays about like a
six-year old with a new water pistol. A very readable new book by
Stephen Ambrose, ``The Victors: Eisenhower and His Boys, the Men of
World War II,'' (Simon &AMP; Shuster) describes Ike's discovery of the
necessity of optimism in a leader. What O'Neill, Reagan and
Thatcher all shared was a talent for projecting optimism that drew
people towards them and their views.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower, commanding his first combat operation, was holed up
in Gibraltar in 1942, but his invasion of North Africa was going
badly. In those gloomy caves of his command fortress, he wrote, ``I
first realized how inexorably and inescapably strain and tension
wear away at the leader's endurance, his judgement and his
confidence. The pressure becomes more acute because of the duty of
a staff constantly to present to the commander the worst side of an
eventuality.''
</P>
<P>
   In those caves, Ike discovered, ``optimism and pessimism are
infectious, and they spread more rapidly from the head downward
than in any other direction.'' The chief had to be optimistic above
all. ``. . . I firmly determined that my mannerisms and speech in
public would always reflect the cheerful certainty of victory _
that any pessimism and discouragement I might ever feel would be
reserved for my pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that kind of optimism which O'Neill, Reagan and Thatcher
conveyed, and which is so glaringly absent in the leaders of
Congress today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
