<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-SIGNATURE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SIGNS LAW ALLOWING ELECTRONIC SIGNATURES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Using a computer, President Clinton put his
electronic signature Friday on a bill allowing Americans to enter
into binding contracts on line.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had to use a pen to approve the ``Electronic
Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act.'' While the new law
gives Internet transactions legal status, it doesn't change the way
presidents have to sign bills.
</P>
<P>
   The law, effective Oct. 1, ``will open up new frontiers of
economic opportunity, while protecting the rights of private
citizens,'' Clinton said. ``With the swipe of a smart card and the
click of a mouse, (customers) will be able to finalize mortgages,
sign insurance contracts, or open brokerage accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony at Philadelphia's Congress Hall, near where
patriots once signed the Declaration of Independence, Clinton used
a computer to show off his e-signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, let's see if this works,'' he said, while inserting a
card encoded with his signature. He also entered the code name
``Buddy,'' which happens to be his dog's name. Then the
presidential signature popped up on the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it worked,'' he said to the audience, which included
about 100 business and college students. ``All of you young people
will someday look back on this day ... and marvel that it was
considered a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, supported in the House and Senate by
overwhelming margins, included most of the consumer protections
Clinton had sought. For example, the law requires that legal
notices that potentially affect health and safety be issued by
traditional means. Those exemptions include cancellation of
insurance, shut-off of electric service, court documents, eviction
notices and product recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those exemptions, industry welcomed the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Gould, executive vice president of iLumin Corp., a maker of
digital signature technology, said that by reducing paperwork,
eliminating couriers and speeding up transactions, online
signatures will result in ``tremendous cost savings'' for both
businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   E-signatures will become commonplace ``very, very quickly,''
Gould predicted. ``It'll change (transactions) as quickly as the
Internet changed our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, some experts predict that as Americans grow
accustomed to digital signatures, they will be willing to make
major purchases online, just as millions now buy books or records.
Instead of merely checking car prices on the Internet, consumers
soon will be taking out loans and buying cars without ever leaving
home, many predict.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have until March 1, 2001, to develop rules and other
safeguards for companies that retain records in an electronic
format.
</P>
<P>
   The e-signature law leaves open the choice of technology for
signing documents. For example, one method uses biometric
technology, which records fingerprints or scans eyes to verify a
person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology most likely to be used involves electronic
authentication for digital signatures. These methods involve giving
the parties entering a contract a secure set of mathematical
``keys'' that are virtually impossible to forge.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: 
www.netculture.about.com/internet/netculture/library/bldigitalsignat
ures.htm
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
