<HEADLINE>
DOWNSPOUT WOES SOMETIMES FIXABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   02, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My downspouts go into the ground, and one got plugged and
made a mess of overflowing water; I dug down and discovered the
pipe goes horizontal a few inches deep under ground, and continues
under the driveway. Things did not improve much when I cleared the
blockage. Now what can I do? The pipe seams clear, but the clay
pipe is cracked where it connects to the downspout.RICHARD COHEN,
Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The underground pipe is a nuisance, mainly because it is
under the driveway and inaccessible. It may still go into a dry
well, but if that dry well is under the driveway and is plugged,
you really have a problem. You could try sticking a snake (they are
normally used for sewer drains) into the pipe and see what you can
pull out. To get to the pipe under the driveway, you could expose
the pipe along one side of the driveway and insert the snake from
there.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, you may have to build a new dry well at least
10 feet from the house.
</P>
<P>
   The cracked pipe at the downspout connection may not be a
problem. There may be some draining into the ground; if the
basement is dry, there is no need to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is always a controversy around using bleach to defeat mold
and algae, those black and green growths that appear often in shady
areas around _ and on _ the house. The same goes for moss, those
beautiful tufts of greenery that grow so many places, including
roofs. While the bleach (and water) will kill these growths, the
bleach is hard on virtually everything it touches.
</P>
<P>
   Fred from Maine called to offer another idea for moss. ``When we
have moss on the lawn, we throw lime on it. So why not throw lime
on moss on the roof? It changes the pH of the soil, and is an easy
way to get rid of it, making it easy to scrape off when
necessary.'' The lime referred to is ground limestone.
</P>
<P>
   Good point, Fred, and it will go in the handyman's vast file of
information.
</P>
<P>
   But be aware that the lime takes a year to be effective. But
heck, in the big picture, we can tolerate the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get rid of moss where it is not wanted is to
drench it with vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   One more comment: If you have moss on the roof, you really want
to get rid of it because it can eventually decay the shingles. But
if it is in the lawn, leave it; it is probably growing in shade
where nothing else will grow anyway, and it is beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wood floors were varnished a month ago with two coats of
polyurethane varnish. I plan to install carpeting, but a handyman
neighbor said don't put down the carpet for six months. Do I have
to wait that long?
</P>
<P>
   HELEN McCREEVAN, Charlestown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This handyman does not think so. I think a month is more than
enough time. The fear, of course, is that the carpet will bond
itself onto the finish, making it difficult to remove in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The polyurethane will cure completely in about three to seven
days hours. If you are in doubt, call the polyurethane people for
an opinion. The phone number is probably on the can.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman's floors have been varnished, and while it was a
long time ago I think I put the rugs down after a few days, and
there have been no cases of the rugs or pads sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you can wait forever before putting carpet down and,
once you do, you get sticking anyway. It's a crap shoot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new wood stoop was sealed with Thompson's Water Seal two
months ago. Can I put a stain over the water seal?
</P>
<P>
   FRED CLANNAGAN, Newton Highlands, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The sealer by its very nature seals the wood, preventing
any paint or stain from working. (Do not use paint in any case.) To
stain, you have two options: 1. Wait at least a full year to let
the sealer wear off. Or, 2. Sand off the sealer to the bare wood,
and restain. If you do stain, use a semitransparent oil stain. Only
one coat is neeeded, and you can do it again, with one coat, in
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My raised ranch has T-1-111 on the sides and back. When it
rains out of the north, water appears on the second (basement)
level. I think it's coming from the seams of the T-1-111. How can I
fix those leaks?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE LYON Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the T-1-111 is leaking in the seams, caulk them with a
caulk to match the paint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I get the brown spots off my dishes in the
dishwasher?
</P>
<P>
   ED MASON, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Soak them in a solution of one part vinegar and three parts
water. Then wash them, but change the washer soap, and use less
soap. Or, soak them in water to which denture-cleaning tablets have
been added. Then wash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
