<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING OVER THE LESSONS OF THE KOREAN CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For my generation, the 50th anniversary of the stormy attack
that began the Korean War brings uncomfortable reminders.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, news photographs of North and South Korean
leaders talking and actually embracing in Pyongyang after half a
century of estrangement bring fresh breezes of hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean conflict, for us, came too soon after World War II.
It rudely interrupted America's postwar idyll. And it tarnished our
new self-image of unquestioned military supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   But that war also taught us some useful lessons about the need,
use and limits of American power.
</P>
<P>
   World War II had already robbed Americans of any illusion that
we could live peacefully to ourselves while ravenous tyrants
subdued other countries beneath their tread.
</P>
<P>
   Adolf Hitler's quick and ruthless subjugation of Germany's
weaker neighbors, spreading to include France and large parts of
Russia, and Japan's path of marauding territorial expansion had
given the Western world a new consensus. We now held it to be
axiomatic that aggression permitted is aggression encouraged, and
that none of us can be completely safe while aggression stalks the
planet unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   It was this same rationale, ever so slightly modified by our
less-than-satisfactory experience in Korea, that led us step by
tentative step into the quagmire of Vietnam. But that's another
part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtful observers, looking back from the past half-century's
perspective, agree today that our leadership in the multilateral
effort that finally stalemated the North Korean aggression was both
right and necessary. It served as a brake against a devastating
contagion of arms that could have spread across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran New York Times foreign correspondent Max Frankel, in his
current memoir, ``The Times of My Life and My Life with The
Times,'' reminds us how our compulsion to resist communist advances
was heated to a fervent intensity after communist forces took over
all of China by vanquishing Chiang Kai Shek in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   But we also discovered one peculiarity of American character.
Our armed forces and American industry can mobilize quickly and
wage lightning-like, sophisticated warfare. The American public,
however, while possessing strong patriotic instincts to rally
behind our national leadership and pull together when the gauntlet
is thrown down, lacks the inclination to sustain that support over
a protracted period of years.
</P>
<P>
   We've been conditioned to expect instant results. We're not
prepared by temperament, training or patience for any long,
twilight struggle.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that public opinion, at first strongly supportive of
our national commitment in both Korea and Vietnam, lost interest
and conviction as the two conflicts smoldered on past two years.
Polls clocked a pronounced decline in public support long before
either struggle ended.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of this essentially American characteristic, recent
presidents have avoided committing U.S. forces to any but quick and
decisive exercises of power. In Grenada and Libya, President
Reagan's armed forces swept in swiftly and overpoweringly, did
their work and left.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush, similarly, sent airborne troops to Panama for
swift, well-planned maneuvers that performed their mission and left
in short days with their quarry, Manuel Noriega, in tow.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has exercised care not to get American troops
bogged down in ground wars, opting for airstrikes in places like
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The most masterful exercise of all was Bush's use of such
overwhelming force to subdue and route Saddam Hussein's
ill-prepared legions from Kuwait. In only five weeks, we dropped
more tons of explosives on that one tiny nation than the entire
combatant forces dropped on all hostile targets in all the years of
World War II! And Bush was careful to organize international
support in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The only unpopular military undertaking since Vietnam was the
clandestine effort in Reagan's administration to raise and support
a proxy force (the contras) to overthrow the elected government of
Nicaragua. That violated both international law and U.S. laws, and
the public did not support it.
</P>
<P>
   This points up a final lesson of the Korean and Vietnamese
conflicts. There is a limit to the effectiveness of U.S. power.
It's called nationalism. People want to determine their own
destinies.
</P>
<P>
   They probably feel, in fact, much as our ancestors did on July
4, 1776. Should we ever encroach upon their sovereign rights, in
their countries, or act as though anti-aggression rules did not
apply to us, we'd be out of character.
</P>
<P>
   World leadership requires not only decisiveness but restraint as
well.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
