<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 2, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-COOKIES (Washington) _ Most of this year's presidential
campaign has dealt with the candidates' positions on campaign
financing, Social Security and helping the uninsured. Now it is
time to deal with what really matters _ whose wife bakes the best
cookies. You know, family values. And the 2000 presidential cookie
contest pits chocolate chips, pecans and coconut against ginger and
molasses. The odds favor the ones with the chocolate chips; with
recipes. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH-UP-BRAS (Undated) _ Six years ago, when the British-made
Wonderbra was introduced in this country, push-up bras accounted
for about 3 percent of the $4.6 billion bra business; today that
figure is closer to 10 percent. Underwear makers are rolling out
push-up bras with the sort of hoo-ha usually reserved for movie
openings, and their arrivals in department stores are being
attended with the frenzy of a Meet-The-Beatles tour. By Penelope
Green.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-MARKETING (Undated) _ Like hair colorists, fashion
designers and chefs, more and more doctors are seeking publicity to
build their businesses. Freed of legal constraints that prohibited
them from advertising and faced with shrinking incomes in the age
of managed care, they are aggressively marketing themselves as
experts on beauty and health in magazines like Vogue, Harper's
Bazaar, Elle, Self and Good Housekeeping and on television shows
like ``Today,'' where they reach millions who are willing to pay
for elective medical treatments. By Anne Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Maybe there's an up side to the
climate change that spells warmer, drier weather for the East
Coast: lavender. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   DUMMY-FILMING (New York) _ The tale of Steven Schoichet, a
maladroit suburbanite whose life is transformed when he comes into
possession of a ventriloquist's prop, ``Dummy'' is the kind of
movie Charlie McCarthy might have starred in if Michael Ovitz had
been his agent. Nearly everyone else in the film is a client of
Ovitz's firm, Artists Management Group, a noncoincidence that helps
explain how a script by an obscure writer with a budget that
wouldn't buy a two-bedroom in Manhattan happened to get this far.
By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   NY-APARTMENT (New York) _ The sight of the couple draped across
the bed engaged in cozy pillow talk was more than a little
discomfitting. Stumbling on the scene, one wasn't sure whether to
eavesdrop, look the other way or join the lovebirds on the sheets.
Convincing as it was, this slice of life was in fact a performance,
enacted by models and staged at a party at the Apartment, a
strenuously hip fashion and home furnishings store masquerading as
a private residence. By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
