A9650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-YOUNGSTERS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-YOUNGSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MALONE TO MILES, NBA GETS YOUNGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The day before Darius Miles made draft history,
the 18-year-old basketball prodigy from East St. Louis High School
(Ill.) was asked how he decided he was ready for the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the high school all-star games, a lot of people just
started talking and that's when it got it in my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Los Angeles Clippers chose Miles with the third pick
in the draft on Wednesday night _ a distinction that made the
sinewy 6-foot-9-inch forward the highest high school player ever
selected _ Miles was a prodigy at 14, traveling around the country
to audition in front of hundreds of scouts at the most prestigious
camps.
</P>
<P>
   This is how kids are indoctrinated to the business of
professional sports. We've come a long way since Moses Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a young kid came to me and asked me if I thought he was
ready, well, I'd look him in the eye,'' said Malone, the second
player in the modern era to jump straight from high school to the
pros. ``You can always look at a kid, talk to him, see his inner
self and find out if he's ready for the pro game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know if I was.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Malone was attending summer school at the University of
Maryland. Fresh out of Petersburg High School (Va.), he was taken
in the third round of the American Basketball Association draft by
the Utah Stars.
</P>
<P>
   He had been to only two basketball camps, including Dave Bing's.
The only footage scouts could rely on was a grainy reel that
appeared on ABC's Wide World of Sports. Malone was not escorted
directly to a TNT interview after he was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did I find out?'' Malone said during a telephone interview
this past week. ``John Lucas came by the dorm and told me. I said,
`Ah, man, you joking, right?' He said, `For real, you been picked
by Utah.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode around in his car. He was my chauffeur. Back then, I
was living off $15 a month. I was playing for orange juice. I had
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone went on to have a Hall of Fame career. He went to a
mature team that featured Roger Brown and Ron Boone, veterans who,
``gave me a lot of knowledge and kept me in my place.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if he regretted turning pro so young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only regret I have is that I should have waited 20 more
years, so I could get paid the big bucks,'' he said, laughing. He
also does not think an NBA-sponsored developmental league will curb
the onslaught of teen-agers wishing to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Miles and DeShawn Stevenson from Washington Union High in
Fresno, Calif., were the 14th and 15th players in the modern era to
make the jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine home, big car, they want to live the life,'' Malone said.
``These young athletes watch these pro ballplayers. That's how it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   A record 18 underclassmen were taken in the first round on
Wednesday night. Seven first-round picks were traded within minutes
or hours after they were drafted. Two of those players, Keyon
Dooling and Courtney Alexander, were moved for future first-round
picks. Orlando did not even ask for a player in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls sent Chris Mihm at No. 7 to Cleveland for Jamal
Crawford, the No. 8 pick, it was not a draft-day swap along the
lines of Chris Webber-for-Anfernee Hardaway in 1993 or Stephon
Marbury-for-Ray Allen in 1996. This was the Cavaliers taking a
player the Bulls genuinely did not want off their hands.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if team executives were saying to the class of 2000:
``Thanks for coming in for the workout. You looked great. But we
have to fill our buildings and coffers today, not in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was that more prevalent than in Orlando, which dumped
its 10th and 13th picks and the contracts of Corey Maggette and
Derek Strong in hopes of clearing more salary-cap room to lure a
free-agent prize to the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were unafraid to take youthful, impetuous gambles.
Forever a mess and consistently at the bottom of the standing, they
essentially recast their team.
</P>
<P>
   Dooling and Miles from the draft. Maggette and Strong from
Orlando. Who knows? With this kind of entertaining crew going up
and down the Staples Center floor, Lamar Odom just might stay a
while.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring image on Wednesday night was of Miles taking
arranged portraits with a group of family and friends that numbered
close to 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave basketball out of it for a second,'' Alexander, one of
the few college seniors taken in the first round, said. ``I think
there is a maturation process that we all need to take. Now, Darius
Miles may be the exception to the rule. Kevin Garnett was an
exception to the rule. Kevin was abnormally mature for his age;
he's very, very mature. People need to understand that this is now
a business. There's no room for boys on this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Darius Miles can't go back. He was headed for St. John's a
couple of months ago, the most prized recruit of the Mike Jarvis
era. But the whispers started. Soon, he was deemed good enough to
make the move, from homeroom to the Ritz-Carlton in a single bound,
with nary a lecture hall in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big jump, from a boy to a man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From Moses to Miles, they keep coming, these kids, with Kobe and
KG plastered to their walls. Busts or All-Stars, for better or
worse. And the migration won't stop as long as they can play. As
Marty Blake, the long-time NBA director of scouting, explained
candidly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody don't like school.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
