<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICAN-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      06-30 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN NEW ERA FOR MEXICO, OLD ELECTION HABITS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Arms outreached in eagerness, thousands of
peasants, Indians and blue-collar workers lunged for the
sandwiches, potato chips and soft-drinks tossed in plastic bags
from open trucks.
</P>
<P>
   These were not victims of a flood, hurricane or earthquake. They
were voters hauled in from all over Mexico by the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) to attend a rally in Mexico
City's colonial Zocalo plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar scene occurred recently when PRI candidate
Francisco Labastida Ochoa staged one of his last campaign rallies
at the main plaza. More than 100,000 followers came, many of them
brought in some 2,000 buses paid for by the party that has governed
Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, leading opponent Vicente Fox Quesada of the
center-right National Action Party had his own rally at the Zocalo,
and more than 150,000 came. The event included dancers in Aztec
costumes, light shows and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't bused in! We came on our own!'' people in the crowd
chanted.
</P>
<P>
   If voters are the quarry, Mexico's governing party is the expert
hunter in a country where new election laws are trapped by old
political traditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Sunday, when the nation's most
contested presidential election will be held, the PRI used its vast
organization to beat the bushes for votes throughout this country
of 100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Handing out food, cash, appliances and making workers sign lists
promising their vote for the PRI is what has always worked for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of poor and rural workers, an estimated 40 million
who earn a minimum wage of about $4 a day, they need whatever they
can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an unequal country, there is always the temptation of
abuse, to trade gifts for a vote,'' said Jose Woldenberg, president
of the Federal Electoral Institute, or IFE, in charge of overseeing
the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many in this country, a kilo of rice or a tin roof is more
important than their vote,'' he added. ``It's a structural fault of
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of a new century, the PRI is employing some of the
hoary old tricks that enabled it to win the presidency and most
other electoral posts for the past 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI denies there is any wrongdoing, and gifts at election
time are not illegal, but vote buying and obtaining people's name
for non-IFE lists are.
</P>
<P>
   As a new generation of voters clamors for greater democracy from
what many pundits say was a de facto party dictatorship during most
of the 20th century, the ancient PRI ploys to get votes is becoming
more questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an image of vote buying,'' said Javier Trevino,
Labastida's senior political adviser. ``You are violating the law
if you are using public funds, and should be punished. But you are
not violating the law if you are just using the time of our
bureaucrats'' to promote the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A thin line, and the PRI is being watched. Today, women, the
young and the Roman Catholic Church are playing bigger roles and
are forming activist organizations as Mexico's demographics and
political landscape change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need change, change in the system of government; we need a
government which stops blaming others and starts taking serious and
honest steps to make the country work,'' said Jail Ixel Garcia, an
18-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 11 million voters in ages ranging from 18 to 24 are
eligible to cast ballots, many for the first time, according to IFE
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 70 million eligible voters, out of a population of
100 million, 52 percent are women.
</P>
<P>
   Parties have wooed the female vote with unprecedented ardor,
vowing to create a national institute to take care of women's
needs, including pre-natal care.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is believed by many observers to have a majority of
women's votes. But women's groups aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   The National Civic Association for Women, an nonpartisan
organization that is urging women to vote, is forming brigades and
giving pamphlets explaining the political platforms of the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are promoting the vote, but we are also telling women to
not be afraid, not let themselves be fooled,'' said Gabriela
Romero, vice president of the association, who is sending out 1,200
observers to monitor the vote in rural states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women are by no means leaning more toward the PRI or the
PAN,'' she said. ``They are concerned about crime, education and
the economy. They will make up their own minds who offers the best
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ana Maria Cervantes, a church volunteer, said the poor aren't as
easily fooled with gifts anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them, `Take the flour, the beans, the pastas, but
don't sell yourself,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In this devoutly Catholic nation, the Roman Catholic Church,
meanwhile, is also playing an unprecedented electoral role.
</P>
<P>
   Shut out from public life since 1857 constitutional reforms, it
has been taking bolder steps since 1992 when these restrictions
were eased.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Mexican Bishops Conference warned parties not to
coerce voters or buy votes, saying electoral fraud was a ``grave
moral error'' and that a political system in which parties
alternate power represents a ``fuller democratic culture.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was taken to mean a change of power from the
PRI and a vote of confidence for Fox, a conservative, devout
Catholic who is against abortion, now illegal in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the church denies it. The spokesman for the Archdiocese in
Mexico City said 80 dioceses in the country are offering workshops
for the faithful on the meaning of democracy and explaining
different political platforms of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the priests are not telling people how to vote or who the
best candidate is,'' said Mexico City Archdiocese spokesman Gerardo
Lopez. ``The priests are within the legal framework of the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the church's stumping for democracy in the
countryside could begin to erode the PRI's strongest base of
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has weighed in with Fox,'' said political analyst
George Grayson, of William and Mary College in Williamsburg, Va.
``It is unprecedented. The church has not been active in this
century or in the late 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As election day approaches, it looms as a historic event in
which the PRI could lose the government for the first time since
1929.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls have consistently shown Labastida, an
economist, former governor and minister of the interior, in a
statistical dead heat with the fiery Fox, a former governor of
Guanajuato and Coca-Cola executive.
</P>
<P>
   A third, but distant, candidate is Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, of the
leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party, who is making his third run
at the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The closeness in the polls and Fox's energetic campaign are
giving many Mexicans reasons to hope for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time we have the illusion of democracy in
Mexico,'' said Gloria Hyverr, 70, one of more than 150,000 who
attended last Sunday's rally for Fox in the Zocalo.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many undecided voters _ 19 percent by some
estimates _ who could also swing the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox speaks with enthusiasm and energy but not with solid
numbers. Labastida is more measured and has a better handling of
statistics, but he lacks internal conviction,'' said Miguel Garcia,
an engineer and management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being part of the system, Labastida doesn't have the moral
force,'' Garcia added. ``In our country the worst problem is
corruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
