<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV02-     06-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVENDER GROWS IN POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe there's an up side to the climate change that
spells warmer, drier weather for the East Coast: Lavender.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants to grow sweeps of it in front of the beach
house, the roses, the pool, the old chicken house. Even people with
clay are growing it _ in sandy raised beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always think of lavender as a Mediterranean plant, or
something that would thrive in the California desert,'' said
Fabienne Audette, the assistant director of horticulture at the New
York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. ``New York used to be too cold
and cloudy to sustain subtropical plants, but now, if we provide a
little protection, the climate change is allowing us to grow
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She did her master's thesis on the effects of water and pH on
lavender, in greenhouse conditions and clay fields. ``Sandy soil
and good drainage are key to growing lavender,'' said Audette, who
was born in Switzerland, lived in southern France (where lavender
grows in fields) and now gardens in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference between Mediterranean and American soil
is that the Mediterranean has been cultivated for thousands of
years,'' she said. ``The soil structure is very loose and tends to
be more alkaline or neutral, and the nutrients have been leached
out.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you have clay soil, grow lavender in raised beds, with
plenty of organic matter. Plant in full sun, on high ground, on a
south-facing slope. Some growers use mushroom compost to help
protect plants from root rot. And if you live in a humid area,
growing lavender in pots will improve air circulation. Go easy on
nitrogen fertilizer, which will promote soft green growth, not
flowers. Audette suggests mulching with a one-inch layer of white
or light-colored sand, grit or gravel.
</P>
<P>
   The blooms range in color from white and pink to green to all
shades of blue. The foliage can be from very silvery to gray blue
or green.
</P>
<P>
   Audette found that lavender, like most desert plants, responds
quickly to water. ``They are very tomentose or leathery, with
little water,'' she said. ``Once they get it, the cells elongate
and divide. The leaves are larger, the stems extended, with seven
or eight whorls of flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Mediterranean, plants may go three months without water,
but as soon as there's a storm, they quickly take up as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Lavenders belong to the Labiatae family, which has
square-stemmed plants like thyme and mint. The genus, Lavandula,
contains 28 species, including L. angustifolia, commonly known as
English lavender.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest description dates to A.D. 46, when Dioscorides
described a plant called stoechas, used as a wine and medicinal
herb. ``He found it on Stochade Island, which is now called Ile
d'Hyeres on the Cote d'Azur,'' Audette said.
</P>
<P>
   In A.D. 76, Pliny described a plant called nard, which sounded
like stoechas, but it came from India. ``The plant had a wonderful
fragrance, and the Romans were so crazy about it for their baths,
they depleted it,'' Audette said. ``So they went to stoechas and
called it false nard.''
</P>
<P>
   Two species of lavender _ angustifoloia and latifolia _ have
long been grown in southern Europe for perfume. And bees or other
pollinators crossed these two species, producing a hybrid called
lavandin, first discovered around 1850.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because L. angustifolia and latifolia were so highly
cultivated, a fungus came through Europe in the 1930's and wiped
out the monocultures,'' Audette said. Then a farmer noticed one
survivor: Lavandin, which he started propagating.
</P>
<P>
   Lavandin is more disease-resistant than lavandula and produces
300 percent more essential oil, Audette said, but it has a high
camphor content. ``About 85 percent of the lavender grown in France
is lavandin,'' she said. And it's probably lavandin in soaps,
sprays and toilet water. ``But for the true perfume _ much sweeter
and mellow _ the essential oil should be angustifolia.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular English lavenders are Hidcote, Munstead,
Sharon Roberts and Twickle Purple.
</P>
<P>
   L. stoechas, also called Spanish, French or Italian lavender, is
the adorable fat flower with the purple rabbit ear. L. viridis,
also called green or yellow lavender, has yellow-cream flowers on
two-foot stems. And don't forget lavandin, 30 inches tall, with
narrow spikes ranging from lavender and pink to blue and deep
violet. And its fragrance is strong, from that camphor.
</P>
<P>
   Like other lavender experts, Audette advises buying cuttings.
Seed-grown lavender is highly variable, which can be interesting
for adventurous types, but you will have a hodge-podge of plants
with different growth habits, shapes and colors.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many different kinds of lavenders, and two recent
books go into explanations: ``Lavender, the Grower's Guide''
(Timber Press, 2000; $30) by Virginia McNaughton and ``The Lavender
Garden, Beautiful Varieties to Grow and Gather'' (Chronicle, 1998;
$19) by Robert Kourik.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for lavender include: Digging Dog Nursery, Albion,
Calif., (707) 937-1130, free catalog; Sandy Mush Herb Nursery,
Leicester, N.C., (828) 683-2014, catalog $4; and Well-Sweep Herb
Farm, Port Murray, N.J., (908) 852-5390; catalog, $2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
