<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROADWAY-FANTASTICKS-     06-30 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-FANTASTICKS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STAGE, A LESSON IN LONGEVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's an old Jewish joke (it's written somewhere
that you must never begin: There's a new Jewish joke) about a poor
man in Poland who goes to his rabbi saying he desperately needs a
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you what,'' the rabbi says. ``We'll give you work
standing outside the town gates, watching for the Messiah. You're
to alert us when you see him coming. And for that, we'll pay you
two zlotys a month.''
</P>
<P>
   This, the poor man complains, is a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   ``True,'' the rabbi replies. ``But think of the job security.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiddle with a few words, and you could tell pretty much the same
joke about New York actors. Many of them would give up a lot,
including a fat paycheck, for steady work, especially for a role
deemed worthwhile. Those lucky souls tend to be in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Bryan Hull, one of those souls, who came to
mind because this was supposed to be the week that we were rid of
``Cats'' once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-running musical in Broadway history was scheduled to
close last Sunday. But it seems it's true about cats having
multiple lives. The play's run at the Winter Garden, which began in
1982, has been extended to September because of a surge in demand
for tickets. These, the theater marquee promises, are the ``final
weeks!'' The exclamation point is presumably the producers' way of
saying that they mean it, that this isn't one of those ``going out
of business'' sales that manage to drag on for years.
</P>
<P>
   But even if ``Cats'' does purr on, it will remain an arriviste
compared with Hull and his fellow performers, who have kept quite a
different musical going, far from Broadway, for an extraordinary
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fantasticks,'' at the Sullivan Street Playhouse in
Greenwich Village, opened on May 3, 1960, and has been there ever
since. Try to remember a time when it wasn't around. It is such a
New York institution that most New Yorkers overlook it, much the
way they give the Empire State Building or the Statue of Liberty a
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show sets a record for endurance with every performance.
Thursday night's was No. 16,627. Hull, 62, has been around for
nearly half the play's life, making him the longest-running
performer in the modern history of New York theater.
</P>
<P>
   For the 7,895th time, he stepped onto the tiny stage Thursday
night, playing an over-the-hill actor, a wig of wispy white hair
covering his own thick graying hair. ``Sir, the players have
arrived,'' the character announced. With that, Hull was off and
running, as he has been since May 20, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Through that long stretch, he has not missed a show, aside from
his allotted two weeks of vacation each year and a three-month
absence in 1998 because of a broken leg. He has never missed a
performance because of a cold or other routine illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, people ask me, `Why are you doing this for 20
years?''' Hull said, his voice radio announcer deep. `` `Well,' I
say, `I have a job.'''
</P>
<P>
   As every actor in this city knows, there may be no more magical
words than those: I have a job. For Hull, who auditioned for the
part six times before getting it, a steady paycheck for 18 minutes
of work a night is ample reward.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unfamiliar with the play, it is an uncomplicated tale
of a boy and a girl, of fathers who scheme to bring the young
lovers together, of lost innocence and faded dreams, of learning
that ``without a hurt, the heart is hollow.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of show that draws disdainful sniffs from New
York sophisticates (the sort of people who would also probably
never be caught dead at the Statue of Liberty or the Empire State
Building). The writer Vivian Gornick once nuked the play in this
newspaper. Sometimes, Hull said, you can see the audience sitting
there stone-faced, as if to say, ``OK, show us why you've been here
40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough people turn up each night to keep the play going,
though they typically are student groups and Japanese tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is a lesson in that. Maybe some of us in this city
are too sophisticated for our own good. Maybe an unadorned fantasy
about love is a necessary antidote to the graphic sex, crude
language and overdone pyrotechnics that usually pass for
entertainment these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charm and the pleasure of it,'' Hull said, ``is that it is
what it is: a simple show.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why it has outlasted the likes of ``Cats'' to
become a New York fixture that, for all anyone knows, will still be
around whenever the Messiah does show up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
