<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-VOLUNTEER-2TA     06-30 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-VOLUNTEER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT COMPLAINING ABOUT WEATHER, DOING SOMETHING ABOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KIRK JOHNSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Some people might scratch their heads at
what Richard G. Hendrickson has been up to for the last 70 years.
Even he seems a little mystified, trying to explain it.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1930, when he was an 18-year-old rawboned kid growing up
on a small poultry and dairy farm on the eastern tip of Long
Island, he has gone out into his yard at least twice a day, in
every sort of weather, to record the temperature and precipitation
and wind velocity as a volunteer for the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson is the longest-serving volunteer east of the
Mississippi, and on July 1, when he formally crosses the 70-year
threshold, Hendrickson will join an elite, if obscure, fraternity
of only six people in the 110-year history of the Cooperative
Weather Observer Program who have served the Weather Service into
an eighth decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farming is drudgery, seven days a week,'' said Hendrickson,
who sold his farm only last year at the age of 87. ``You've got to
do things that are different, to stay you from going nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a bit more to the story than that, of course. Behind
Hendrickson's meticulous weather monitoring was a rapturous love
affair _ with the sky and with nature. Also playing a part was an
eccentric writer with a passion for meteorology who moved in near
the farm when Hendrickson was an impressionable teen-ager in the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   And last, there is a certain harder-to-define essence that has
informed Hendrickson's life, a spirit that seems almost jarring
today in its tough-minded, Old World code: Duty. Hendrickson
measured the weather as a way of serving his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an extremely 19th-century man, and I mean that as a
compliment,'' said his son, Richard H. Hendrickson. ``He was raised
in a farming environment in the teens and '20s, being responsible 7
days a week, 24 hours a day, for the animals and crops. Built into
his very nature is the concept of responsibility; it's the fiber of
his being.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a dedication to consistency, like perfect
attendance at school,'' Hendrickson added. ``It's strange, but it's
worthy of great respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cooperative Weather Observer Program was inspired by the
writings of Thomas Jefferson, who was something of a weather nut
himself. Jefferson envisioned a republic of yeoman farmers, all
gathering and sharing agricultural data about storms and the dates
of the first and last frosts, all for the good of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But that mix of weather and patriotism, not to mention family
farming, has faded. People want to get paid these days, or they do
not stay in one place long enough to allow for a continuity of
data, say weather officials who are struggling in many parts of the
country to keep the old stations afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of observers has declined from its peak
in 1970, when there were 13,500, to only 11,700 today, and many of
the stations are becoming automated.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also many holdouts like Hendrickson who refuse to
come in from the cold. A volunteer in Wyoming, the reigning
longevity champion, has taken readings for just over 70 years. A
weather observer in Brooklyn, Frank Martino, recently passed his
50-year anniversary. The national record is held by Earl Stewart of
Cottage Grove, Ore., who took weather observations every day for 77
years, from 1917 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks just love serving their country, and thank God
there's still people like that around,'' said Robert J. Leffler,
the manager of the cooperative observer program at the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson, who still chops his own firewood and still finds
the time to lie outside on the grass most evenings with his wife,
Lillian, to look at the sky, says he never missed a day's weather
reading in all his decades. Whenever he could not be there
personally _ a cumulative total of only a couple of hundred times
over the more than 25,500 days of his observation career _ he found
a substitute, usually his father, or later his son, to ``take the
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Hendrickson, who is 60, lives nearby. He has agreed
to take over the station permanently whenever his father should lay
the duty aside.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Hendrickson agrees with his son that the unyielding
rhythms of a poultry farm are probably a big part of what shaped
him. Back during the Great Depression and before, the farm was
producing 2,500 white leghorns a week, he said, mainly for sale as
breeding stock. Every night, Hendrickson had to visit all 12 of the
large laying houses to make sure the birds had water and heat, and
in winter, to check the kerosene heaters that kept their drinking
water from freezing. Those nights became his classroom for the
natural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come out at night and hear an owl hoot, I'd hear a fox
bark, I'd hear a farmer's dog bark because maybe a rabbit hopped
too close to him,'' he said. ``I'd look up and see the stars, and
I'd see rings around the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the mid-1920s, the decidedly odd figure of Ernest S.
Clowes entered Hendrickson's deep rural fastness. Clowes (rhymes
with cows) was in his 50s when he moved just down Lumber Lane from
the Hendrickson farm. He was a sometime writer who penned nature
dispatches for the local Bridgehampton newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would write about what the possum said when he came out in
the spring, and what he said to the raccoon, or what the turtle
said,'' Hendrickson recalled of Clowes' nature columns.
</P>
<P>
   Clowes never drove a car, never married, and was so often lost
in his reveries that he would walk right by people as though they
were not even there. For a kid who was facing a hard and
circumscribed life of farming, and who would soon be forced to drop
out of high school to help his father, Clowes' air of education and
higher thought was like a breeze from the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best teacher a young fellow like myself could have
had,'' Hendrickson said.
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1929, Clowes asked young Richard if he had ever
thought of becoming a volunteer weather observer, and so it began.
The full weather station arrived the next summer, and together the
farmer and the writer drove into town to pick up the equipment and
take it back to the farm.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Hendrickson was meticulous. April 7, 1931,
to site one of Hendrickson's early dispatches, was a raw and windy
day with a high of 44 and a low of 38 at Bridgehampton station.
Rain began falling at 8:10 a.m. and ended at precisely 10:55 a.m.,
the 19-year-old wrote _ not a minute sooner or later. The
handwritten sheet for that month, framed under glass, was presented
to Hendrickson by the Weather Service several years ago as a
memento _ the oldest of his dispatches that could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually over the years, taking the weather took on a life of
its own. Hendrickson began keeping a notebook in the pocket of his
work shirt, and his observations about wind and sky and the
northeasters that periodically raked the land eventually evolved
into a book about the weather of eastern Long Island, called
``Winds of the Fish's Tail,'' which he published in 1996 (available
from the author: (631) 537-0893). The title refers to a line by
Walt Whitman, who described Long Island as a fish with its mouth at
New York City and tail at the north and south forks in Suffolk
County.
</P>
<P>
   He also learned to read the weather in ways that went beyond its
mere measurement: How every change in wind direction was a signal
of an altered pattern, and how to read the speed and turbulence of
the jet stream by studying the vapor trails of high-flying
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dry northwest wind gives us our hottest summer days, and
we also get our windiest weather, usually in winter, from the
northwest,'' he said, staring up at the sky on a brilliant sunny
day that was fairly dry, temperature in the low 80s with a light
breeze blowing from the west-northwest. ``We get our heavy rains
from the east and northeast.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most notable weather day of Hendrickson's life,
Sept. 21, 1938, came with no warning at all. He was working in the
chicken houses that afternoon with a professor from Cornell
University's agricultural extension program and a veterinarian,
testing the chickens so that they could be certified for sale as
breeders, when suddenly the building they were in began to shake
from wind and rain. The three men bolted for the farmhouse, and by
the time they looked back, 26 of the farm's outbuildings, including
2 of the large laying houses, were gone.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane of 1938 had arrived. It ripped off the farmhouse
roof as the men cowered below, throwing 40-pound asbestos shingles
400 feet and then driving them into the ground like meteors. Of
Hendrickson's 4,500 young hens, 4,000 were killed by being blown
against a fence and drowned by the downpour.
</P>
<P>
   The 1938 hurricane also marked the end of the Great Depression
on Long Island's East End, Hendrickson said. Houses and barns had
to be repaired, cars and trucks replaced. The great surge of
spending that began in rebuilding from the storm carried on right
through World War II and then through the explosion of wealth that
continues.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather remains, and Hendrickson says it is only a
matter of time before people are reminded of it. He shakes his head
thinking about the newcomers who in their innocence or arrogance
have built homes on Long Island's beachfront dunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how much money they've got,'' Hendrickson said.
``Are we intelligent? Have we learned anything from history?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
