<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9660 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-PUSH-UP-BRAS-$ADV02-2     06-30 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUSH-UP-BRAS-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF THE PERFECT CLEAVAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May an old friend came to town on business. We had lunch at
the sort of late-'80s restaurant that, with its Bisquick biscuits
and corn bread and homemade lime soda, used to be called new
American, and filled in the narrative blanks of our recent
histories; it had been 15 years since we'd seen one another.
Afterward, we picked our way through the rubble on North Moore
Street, decorous in our polymide rainwear and neat black boots, and
_ this being a contemporary story _ repaired to my friend's
tastefully beige room at the SoHo Grand Hotel to examine her
week-old fake breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls,'' as she called them, were high and hard and
absolutely perfect. They were also absolutely riveting, or in any
case I was riveted by them: I felt they were giving me the hairy
eyeball, like Louise Bourgeois' nipply ``Eyes'' sculpture on the
esplanade just below Battery Park City. I went home in a daze,
unable to shake the feeling that I'd been stared down by a pair of
breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuts to you,'' I thought a few days later, strapping on a
couple of ounces of silicone and Lycra, the Ultimo bra with
``outplants,'' _ just one of many new bras designed to give you a
competitive edge, or at least make you feel like the heroine of a
Barbara Cartland novel. Implants, who needs 'em?
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when the British-made Wonderbra was introduced in
this country, push-up bras accounted for about 3 percent of the
$4.6 billion bra business; today that figure is closer to 10
percent. Underwear makers are rolling out push-up bras with the
sort of hoo-ha usually reserved for movie openings, and their
arrivals in department stores are being attended with the frenzy of
a Meet the Beatles tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultimo, $58, sold out on its first day at Saks Fifth Avenue
not long ago, thanks to a waiting list with 2,500 names on it.
Similar scrambles have attended the debuts of Lily of France's
X-Bra, $25, out since February, and Victoria's Secret's Natural
Liquid Miracle Bra, also known as the Natural, $48, out since
April.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Warnaco's Nothing But Curves bra, for which the
company will be spending $3 million to $4 million on advertising
and marketing, went on sale at Macy's for $29. July 3, you will be
able to find it at department stores across the country. Its
appearance completes a six-month barrage of new push-up bras, each
more intricately engineered than the last and sporting more options
than a fully loaded Range Rover. Eager to add heft to my own
shadow, I took a few out for a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   THE X-BRA. The arcs, nay, the swoops of the molded foam X-Bra
are nothing short of aerodynamic. Running a finger lightly over one
particularly graceful angle _ an ``assist'' in underwear parlance _
I thought of hull speed and the famous winged keel employed by the
Australians to wrest the America's Cup away from this country so
many years ago. This is the bra that delivers ``a range of
cleavage,'' thanks to a clasp thingummy at your sternum. ``Start
loose, and then ramp it up during the day,'' suggested a publicist
for Lily of France. ``Empowering, fun, playful, those are the
buzzwords for this product.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwear makers like to borrow language from other arenas, and
so there's a lot of talk of ``empowerment,'' along with ``choice''
and ``flexibility'' in answer to questions about why push-up bras
are enjoying so much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to sell a million X-Bras this year,'' said Eric
Wiseman, president of Bestform Intimates, the company that owns
Lily of France. ``That's a phenomenal number. Why is it so
successful? It puts a woman in control _ it allows her control over
the amount of enhancement she gives herself.''
</P>
<P>
   I fumbled with the tiny plastic flower tab and went straight to
``ramped'' _ a setting that gently eased as the day waned, like an
oh-so-slowly deflating balloon. You could almost hear the faint
wheeze of escaping air, and the sound of diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   THE ULTIMO. ``Wear it with a blazer and no shirt, or a
sweater,'' encouraged Barbara Lipton, vice president and division
merchandising manager of intimate apparel at Saks, ``and let me
know how it makes you feel.'' Very breast-heaving, was the answer.
I wore a slightly too-small button-down shirt, for optimal
button-straining, and that romance-novel effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultimo's silicone innards are eerily fleshy. They're
supposed to ``settle'' and ``warm'' to your body, an action which,
if it occurred, was too subtle for me to discern. The Ultimo was
comfy, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it's a bit cold,'' was the disingenuous suggestion of
more than a few of the Ultimo's competitors. It's not. I wore the
Ultimo on random errands, panting like a Pekingese, enjoying the
rise and fall beneath my chin, but I didn't have the stomach to
sport it in more familiar surroundings. I worried that someone
might think I'd had a little work done.
</P>
<P>
   Why do women want ``a larger breast effect,'' to use the
industry phrase?
</P>
<P>
   My friend Stephen is fond of saying that all genders aspire to
being Jayne Mansfield. An evolutionary psychologist would say
simply that an exaggeration of secondary sex characteristics like
breasts is rudimentary mate attraction; a Freudian might diagnose
such a bosom-focused culture as being hopelessly mired in its oral
stage. Lipton's analysis was succinct: ``Why do women want
cleavage? Because they can have it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   THE NATURAL. With annual sales of $2.9 billion, Vickie's Secret
(an industry executive referred to Victoria's Secret this way, and
I couldn't resist repeating it) is a company built on cleavage:
Twenty percent of its sales are in push-up bras.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the company sells more than 50 percent of all
padded and push-up bras in this country. You could argue that the
rock star status now afforded to breasts is thanks to that
company's marketing efforts. ``We were the first to use
supermodels,'' said Monica Mitro, vice president of public
relations. ``We even created supermodels, like Heidi Klum.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, its Miracle Bra, the American answer to the
Wonderbra, has until this year been a category killer. Which brings
us to the Natural Liquid Miracle Bra, now selling out by word of
mouth only. It's a doppelgaenger to the Ultimo, with outplants that
are a tad less obvious. But the overall effect is still like
wearing someone else's breasts, which is a good thing or a bad
thing, depending on your temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Is there such a thing as too many cleavage options?
Disentangling the Natural from its sisters the other day, I thought
there might be. I was beginning to feel like Mary Smiling, a minor
character in ``Cold Comfort Farm,'' Stella Gibbons' 1932 satire of
the novels of D.H. Lawrence, whose ``second interest was her
collection of brassieres, and her search for the perfect one,''
Gibbons wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hoped that on her death it would be left to the
nation,'' she continued. ``She was an authority on the cut, fit,
colour, construction and proper functioning of brassieres; and her
friends had learned that her interest, even in moments of extreme
emotional or physical distress, could be aroused and her composure
restored by the hasty utterance of the phrase: ``I saw a brassiere
today, Mary, that would have interested you ... ''
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING BUT CURVES. At one end of a vast table in Warnaco's
sky-high Park Avenue boardroom, recent push-up bra history was
being detailed by company executives. Frank Wolfson, designer for
the Warner line, and Gwendolyn Widell, senior vice president of
merchandise development, played Will and Ariel Durant. ``We'll look
at these in the hand first,'' said Widell, and led me from the
Model T, the Wonderbra with its removable pads, to the X-Bra, to
the liquid pockets of the Ultimo and the Natural. It was a foggy
June morning, and Manhattan looked particularly delicious through
the picture windows _ windows whose sheer enormity underscored the
fact that underwear is extremely big business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch,'' said Wolfson, suddenly flicking a delicate, black
winged carapace at me. Nothing But Curves!
</P>
<P>
   Then two veteran underwear models profiled the bra for me in red
python and Caribbean blue, in khaki and a computer-generated rose
print. I was so taken I followed the models back into a dressing
room, where we had a long and satisfying discussion about
shrinkage, gravity and other matters relating to les belle
poitrines, as Aileen Mehle might say.
</P>
<P>
   I took the bra home and wore it for more than a week. It weighs
nothing, and affixes, oddly, somewhere between your heart and your
clavicle. I liked it, though, for being not too hooter-y, but
rather more organizing, like some sort of Kevlar armor, like a
breastplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women don't want a lot of encumbrances in their lives,''
Widell had told me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
