   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ That hissing sound you heard a few days back was
the air going out of a hope long pumped up on the political and
social right that if only the Miranda ruling could be wrestled back
before a conservative Supreme Court like the current one, it would
be overturned and that would show the crooks and liberals -- pretty
much one and the same _ a thing or two. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ Every once in a while, the
Cuban-American community here is smitten by erroneous reports that
Fidel Castro has died. No such thing. After 40 years of total
control of Cuba, he is as alive as ever. He's got his Elian back,
he's got the Republican-led U.S. Congress pushing through
legislation to ease segments of the embargo, he's got the Miami
exile community in the most depressed (and foul) mood it's even
been in.(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ REDMOND, Wash. _ Bill Gates, the squire of
Redmond, where Microsoft Corp. makes its home, has no use for
computer manuals. Gates says that the software programs that have
made him a rich man since he co-founded the company 25 years ago
are much too complex. The stuff that follows in the wake of
Windows, he vows, will be a lot more simple to use and respond to
intuitive voice commands, making all manuals superfluous. Until
that day, Microsoft will beef up its digital help materials, making
them accessible both within individual programs and online. (Glass,
Cox News Service)
