<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0701-C     06-30 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Searching for logic in ruling barring homosexual scoutmasters
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Boy Scouts have a constitutional right,
according to a narrow 5-4 Supreme Court vote, to give the boot to
homosexual scoutmasters.
</P>
<P>
   The next president's Supreme Court appointments could overturn
Wednesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if George W. Bush or Al Gore were Boy Scouts or if
they would use a ``Gay Scout'' litmus test for their Supreme Court
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   I do know that I was a Boy Scout and that I had a homosexual
scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I don't know if our scoutmaster was homosexual. I just
know that all my fellow brave, clean and reverent Troop 210 Scouts
thought he was homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I don't know if my scouting buddies really believed
our scoutmaster was homosexual or if they simply enjoyed spreading
malicious gossip. Boy Scouts will do that even if it is not
helpful, friendly, courteous or kind.
</P>
<P>
   The man never did anything that we knew of that was out of line
except that he had never been married.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, back in the late 1940s and early 1950s, we assumed
that some adult law required all men to get married. I believed
that for a good 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Our scoutmaster also spent his spare time hanging around with
boys. Most of the men in our small, rural town were the strong,
silent type who barely tolerated children. Generally speaking, that
included our fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ARRESTED ADOLESCENCE
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our scoutmaster simply had a case of arrested adolescence.
Who knows? We didn't.
</P>
<P>
   None of us ever spread our gossip to our parents. Spreading
groundless rumors could result in a whipping. A lot of things back
then could result in a whipping.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, our scoutmaster was good. We didn't want to
lose him. Without him, the troop would have either folded or we
would have gotten a scoutmaster who would have made us toe the
line, which was another adult law.
</P>
<P>
   The issue before the Supreme Court involved James Dale, an
assistant scoutmaster who had been an Eagle Scout and had remained
active in the Scouts since the age of 8. When Scout officials
learned Dale was gay from a newspaper article brought to their
attention, they fired the man.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court majority reasoned that Boy Scouts of America
has the freedom to associate with people who accept the group's
stated values just as it has the freedom to not associate with
people who reject its values.
</P>
<P>
   I was far from a model Boy Scout, but I don't recall anything in
the Scout oath, law, motto or slogan that states any values
regarding homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The last part of the Scout oath, where Scouts promise ``To keep
myself physically strong, mentally awake, and morally straight,''
is most often used to show that the organization opposes
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``gay'' and ``straight'' had nothing to do with sexual
orientation back when the Scout oath was written. The question then
is morality.
</P>
<P>
   Morality, however, would imply a decision based on some action
or conduct. There was no evidence that Dale ever participated in
any actions or conduct inconsistent with the stated values of the
Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   If the Boy Scouts had clear, established values that opposed the
condition of homosexuality _ not merely an implied opposition of
homosexual conduct _ then the Supreme Court's decision would not
have been so tortured.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, writing for the majority, said
the Boy Scouts could kick Dale out because his presence would send
a message the organization ``accepts homosexual conduct as a
legitimate form of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Dale's case, there was no evidence of homosexual conduct.
From his actions, Dale was a model of Boy Scout values. There must
be a constitutional nuance here that I don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
