<HEADLINE>
STARS AND GRIPES FOREVER: `THE PATRIOT' GETS BRITS IN A SNIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British are fuming! The British are fuming!
</P>
<P>
   And you can blame most of it on Jason Isaacs' performance as the
sadistic Col. William Tavington in Columbia Pictures' new
revolutionary war epic ``The Patriot,'' starring Mel Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   But Liverpool, England, native Issacs couldn't be more pleased
with his home turf's ruffled feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's thrilling obviously that we are garnering even more
column inches than the reviews would get us,'' Isaacs says. ``But
there's no controversy in my mind or in the filmmakers' minds. Most
of the people writing this stuff haven't seen the film.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute, however, that Isaacs is one rotten apple _
in the film, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a slightly amoral British officer who just wants to win
the war and get the job done and earn himself some huge land
grant,'' Isaacs says of Tavington. ``My superiors are very unhappy
with the way I'm behaving and my men balk at carrying out the
orders I give them. So the notion that the British are represented
badly is nonsense. `I' am the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you have a bad guy in a giant genre war movie like this
who's taking a vote and abiding by the Geneva Convention, you
haven't got much of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, ``The Patriot'' isn't the first recent flick to
get the Brits in a snit. Earlier this year, ``U-571'' raised
English ire when the heroes of a historic World War II submarine
mission where changed from British to American for the film. Gibson
himself has been at war with the Brits since his kilt-wearing turn
in ``Braveheart.'' But Isaacs says a little honest criticism never
hurt anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm pointing fingers from across the Atlantic.
We all know perfectly well that the British empire has civilized
certain places _ we brought them cricket and warm beer and taxes,''
he says, ``and at some point almost everywhere we've occupied has
ended up with us getting kicked out in circumstances of great
acrimony, and this is just one more in a long line for England. And
I can say that because I'm English.''
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
