<SLUG> BC-DIANAROSS-TOUR-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONWIDE CONCERT TOUR BY DIANA ROSS IS BECOMING A SUPREME FLOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 14, 1970, Diana Ross and the Supremes did their final
show.
</P>
<P>
   Anything in a pop star's career _ drug use, marriage, giving
birth, dying _ can be milked to death, but as breakups go, this one
was orchestrated and packaged to the hilt: After 10 years and 12
No. 1 singles, and less than three years after Ross began to get
top billing, the group bid adieu, with Ross introducing her
replacement, Jean Terrell, onstage. Everyone, we were led to
believe, was OK with this and would go on to further success.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the choreographed breakup was the Supremes' last single
together _ ``Someday We'll Be Together.'' It was obvious that
``Someday'' was not simply a hopeful tune about two lovers being
reunited _ this was a tease, a promise that just maybe, down the
road, Diana Ross and her Supremes, the most popular female vocal
group of the '60s, would reunite and return to glory.
</P>
<P>
   Now cut to earlier this month and the Palace of Auburn Hills, a
cavernous arena outside Detroit, and one of the first stops of the
Diana Ross and the Supremes' Return to Love tour. The promise made
implicit 30 years ago in ``Someday We'll Be Together,'' was coming
to fruition. Or was it?
</P>
<P>
   It is Diana Ross and two Supremes onstage, but not the Supremes
that backed her when the group was in its heyday: For up to an
exorbitant $250 per seat, fans would not see Mary Wilson or Cindy
Birdsong, but Scherrie Payne and Lynda Laurence, who were Supremes
only after Ross went solo.
</P>
<P>
   They were recruited, in fact, by Wilson, who kept the Supremes'
name alive for three decades but declined to participate in the
Return to Love tour because, she was quoted as saying, she was
offered only $3 million _ virtual pennies compared with the
reported $15 million-$20 million Ross is making for less than two
months' work.
</P>
<P>
   There are no reports about what Birdsong was offered. She
replaced founding member Florence Ballard in 1967; Ballard died of
a heart attack in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, what could have been the triumphant return by a
legendary group has turned into the summer concert season's biggest
bomb: The Palace was only half full, as was Atlanta's Philips Arena
a few nights later; fewer than 3,000 people showed up for another
early show in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are speaking, and they're not interested,'' says
John Scher, president and CEO of New York's Metropolitan
Entertainment Group, and one of the country's most well-known
concert promoters. ``Ms. Ross is a legendary artist and people
would pay top dollar to see her in an intimate setting. But in
arenas and it not being a true reunion, no.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour, say people in the concert industry, is testimony to
how out of touch a superstar and her handlers can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're marketing to an educated audience, and if they feel
they're being sold a bill of goods they won't pay it,'' says Jerry
Thompson, president of Fort Worth's Caravan of Dreams and
Promoterline. ``With service charges, you take your wife and it's
$550 before you walk out the door. Diana Ross has no new product,
and nobody cares that much.''
</P>
<P>
   And why should they? There is no new CD; no greatest hits boxed
set. And audiences have examples in recent years of how successful
reunion tours can be _ provided they're the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' Hell Freezes Over tour hit the road in the mid-'90s
and sold out stadiums and arenas for months _ despite ticket prices
in excess of $100. But there was a CD _ a compilation of several
new cuts and Eagles favorites such as ``Hotel California.''
</P>
<P>
   The four original members of Kiss did just as well when they
came back in 1996 with a show (makeup, explosions, etc. included)
that harkened to their '70s heyday.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
