<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-CORVETTE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERY FOCUSED CORVETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By CHERYL JENSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULL, Ohio _ Here we are in Dullsville, having a thrill a
minute. Not because of the nightlife, or even the wildlife, but
because we roared into this western Ohio hamlet in Chevrolet's
fastest, most secret, most exciting production Corvette yet.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Z06, it has 385 horsepower _ 35 more than a standard
'01 'Vette _ and it is aimed head-on at weekend racers whose
priorities are speed, speed and speed _ in that order. The car,
with a price of $47,500, reaches dealerships this month and is
likely to show up immediately in autocross competitions or at
Corvette Club track events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Chevrolet has done is to rework its fixed-roof hardtop
model, which arrived as a 1999 model. Although the hardtop was
already the stiffest, lightest and fastest Corvette, Chevy reached
into its bag of tricks to create the Z06: The 5.7-liter V-8 engine
was reworked to produce 385 horsepower; the suspension was revised;
and the unloaded weight was cut to 3,115 pounds _ almost 100 pounds
lighter than the 2001 coupe and convertible and 38 pounds lighter
than the previous hardtop. That model will no longer exist other
than as the Z06.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy engineers say the Z06 easily outperforms its coupe and
convertible siblings, which will not be available with the new
engine. It also handles better and will circle a track faster than
the ``King of the Hill'' Corvette ZR1 of 1990-95, said Dave Hill,
chief Corvette engineer. Hill says the new car is capable of
zero-to-60 sprints in 4 seconds and a quarter mile run in 12.6
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Hill says engineers found the Z06 would do laps at their test
track 3 to 4 seconds faster than the 350-horsepower coupe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All that track talk is well and good, but how does the Z06
perform on the open road? Heading out of Cleveland, the driver's
first impression is that this is definitely a harder-edged car.
It's not a Corvette for everybody. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is stiffer, with a larger, stronger front
stabilizer bar. You feel everything the vehicle encounters on the
road _ a tradeoff for the improved handling.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the gain in handling comes from wheels that are an inch
wider than those on the standard Corvette, and although the tires
are bigger, they are a total of 23.4 pounds lighter. That's because
the Z06 does not use the run-flat tires found on other Corvettes.
In case of a flat, the driver has Chevrolet's best wishes, a
miniature air compressor and a repair kit that includes a squeeze
bottle of sealant.
</P>
<P>
   The car is also noisier, partly due to a hatchback configuration
that amplifies sound, and partly because its weight-loss regimen
included thinner glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On lightly traveled rural roads, the Z06s special nature is
appreciated. The car changes direction quickly, and taking turn
after turn at increasingly higher speeds can make the driver feel
inadequate _ incapable of fully exploiting its grip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there is the revised V-8, called the LS6. Exclusive to the
Z06, it is based on the regular 5.7-liter LS1 in regular Corvettes.
Changes include improved breathing, thanks to a new titanium
exhaust; unique to the Z06, it weighs almost 18 pounds less than a
conventional exhaust system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new engine reaches peak horsepower at 6,000 r.p.m. and peak
torque (385 foot-pounds) at 4,800 rpm. That compares with 350
horsepower at 5,600 rpm and 375 foot-pounds at 4,400 rpm for the
LS1.
</P>
<P>
   The LS6 is amazingly flexible, providing strong acceleration in
almost any gear of the new six-speed manual transmission. Just pick
a gear and let the engine do the rest. Shift if it pleases you.
Don't if you feel lazy. This engine can be a ridiculously relaxed
cruiser. In sixth gear, at 90 mph, it turns over only 2,300 times a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Subtle touches set the car apart from lesser 'Vettes: Z06
emblems on front fenders, light-gray wheels over red brake
calipers, scoops that funnel air to the brakes, racier-looking
instruments, a red engine cover. On a Saturday afteroon in Dull,
about 100 miles southwest of Toledo, it didn't take the Z06 long to
catch the eye of Bobbie Clark, who'd been mowing his lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a retired corrections officer, is responsible for signs
around the hamlet, also known as Dull Station, like ``6 Houses
Makes 1 Dull Town'' and ``Dull Station. Population 22, 6 Dogs and
10 Cats.'' He puts up the signs and spruces up the area, he said,
because he appreciates its history.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy, likewise, has honored the Corvette's history by invoking
the car's legendary first chief engineer, Zora Arkus-Duntov. In
1963, he created the first Z06 package, aimed at purists who wanted
a 'Vette they could pick up at the dealership and take directly to
the racetrack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few other places where a driver can judiciously
put the car's capabilities to good use. The Z06 forces the driver
to become a sneak thief _ grabbing some extra speed on an entrance
or exit ramp or on an open stretch of road when no one's around _
and passing becomes an opportunity instead of an annoyance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Should enthusiasm overcome common sense, help is available. All
2001 Corvettes come with Chevrolet's second-generation
active-handling system, which senses oversteer or understeer and
makes adjustments to help bring the car back into balance. But the
system has been reworked to be even less intrusive to an enthusiast
driver, briefly reducing wheel spin without cutting engine power so
much that the car bogs down.
</P>
<P>
   The system can even detect the difference between a skilled
driver who is visually anticipating a slide and countersteering
correctly, and a driver who is playing catchup, said Hill, the
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   This Corvette certainly doesn't suffer from attention-deficit
disorder, it is very focused _ aimed at the most serious Corvette
enthusiasts, those who want the most when it comes to performance
on the track or simple bragging rights. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
