<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BITTER END TO A WOMAN'S SWEET LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The house where Terisa Mae Anderson used to live reminds me of
Anderson herself, a jewel in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The green and white paint is peeling, the flower boxes are empty
and the magnolia and weeping willow trees could use trimming.
</P>
<P>
   The old rusty Chevrolet Impala, still parked in the driveway
after all these years, has seen better days.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   She used to be spry, working hard every day, voting in every
election, enjoying life. Then she lost her sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all happened after I had surgery in my mouth,'' she says.
``I walked in the house, and all of a sudden I went blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed for Anderson. With her sight gone, she found
it hard to care for herself, let alone keep up her home.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the plumbing went bad, the roof began to cave in.
Men came and took her money, up to $1,600 once, to fix things. They
left only broken promises and Anderson seated in her kitchen, the
only place in the house where the rain couldn't get in.
</P>
<P>
   Now she sits miles away on the other side of town, cowering
under a brown blanket.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the darkness and the deceit and the drenching rain
have wrought for Anderson. But her story is familiar; it happens
thousands of times each year across the country. Rather than
shining as beacons of longevity and perseverance, the nation's
elderly are often cast into the darkness of abuse, neglect and
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services says
that more than 36,000 cases of elder abuse and neglect were
confirmed in the state last year alone. Many victims, like
Anderson, live in unsanitary conditions or without heat or running
water until someone reaches out to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three out of four cases that we see involve neglect,'' says
Stacey Ladd, spokeswoman for the department. ``Some simply need
assistance with meals and other activities of daily living.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 90, came to the department's attention nearly four
months ago. The home where she lived alone had been in disrepair
for years. A radio, tuned to a Christian radio station, was her
only companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in bad shape,'' Anderson says. ``Everything I had
is practically ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   She says things are much better now at the adult foster home
where social workers took her to live. She appreciates each gesture
of kindness. But there is a sadness in her voice, a longing for
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just don't make you feel good at all,'' she says. ``You
just don't know it till you go through it. I still hold on, 'cause
you ain't going to take nothing with you.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson nears the end of her days, the measure of her
earthly goods is unimportant. The important thing is that she
leaves knowing that someone cared.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
