u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     06-30 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, June 30, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: MEXICO-PRI.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-UNIONS (Washington) _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
says he will block action on a House-passed bill sponsored by Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., that would allow doctors to bargain
collectively with health insurers. The measure, which passed the
House early Friday, would give physicians a limited antitrust
exemption so they could band together to negotiate with health
plans over items such as fees. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-ROUNDUP (Washington) _ In a term filled with emotionally
charged cases, some Supreme Court justices took surprisingly
different positions from those they had taken in the past. Their
ideological fence-jumping mirrored the conflicts that the public
still has with such issues as abortion, police power and separation
of church and state. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ A 37-year-old Minuteman missile
will roar out of a central California silo next Friday heading west
over the Pacific in a $100 million test of a new weapon that will
try to knock the missile down. The test of a scaled-back successor
to a weapon in President Ronald Reagan's Star Wars plan, could have
crucial ramifications for U.S. defense strategy. We describe the
test, how it will work and what it will mean for U.S.-Russia and
U.S.-China relations. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRI (Mexico City) _ Voters in Mexico's presidential
election will decide whether the Institutional Revolutionary Party
will stay or go after 71 years of governing this still impoverished
but rapidly developing nation. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-JEWS (Havana) _ According to the Bible, it took Moses 40
years to lead the ancient Hebrews out of the desert and into the
promised land _ about the same amount of time it has taken Cuba's
small Jewish community to get back on its feet under Communist
rule. Depleted by departures since Fidel Castro seized power in
1959, Cuba's Jewish community of 1,500 is rebuilding itself. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ For Al Gore, this is the best of
times and the worst of times. The best because two months from now
he will be anointed as the Democratic Party's first presidential
nominee of the new millennium. The worst because Gore has been
steadily sinking behind Bush in the public opinion polls. By ROBERT
E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
