<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-BOREDOMBUSTERS-100     06-30 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOREDOMBUSTERS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NINE BEST CABLE SHOWS YOU'VE PROBABLY NEVER HEARD OF, BUT
SHOULDN'T MISS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network reruns running you down? We feel your pain. So what
better time to explore cable's netherworld of hidden treasures,
those underappreciated morsels you usually channel-surf right by on
your mad dash to catch ``Friends,'' ``ER'' and ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire''? These easy-to-miss specialty delights run the gamut,
from bizarre to bold, smart to silly, sexy to salacious.
</P>
<P>
   So go forth with this list of off-the-beaten-path shows. View it
as a starter kit to a bolder, more adventurous existence in front
of the tube.
</P>
<P>
   1. He's been gored, clawed, chomped, bitten, savaged, jumped on,
whacked and groped by a variety of creatures, big and small, yet
Australian Steve Irwin keeps coming back for more on the wildlife
series ``Crocodile Hunter'' (7, 8, 10 and 11 p.m. weekdays, Animal
Planet). You should, too. Every episode of this immensely
entertaining and often nail-biting series features Irwin in
seemingly imminent danger of being eaten alive by everything from
lions to tigers to bears _ not to mention pythons and those
ever-elusive crocodiles. What possesses Irwin to go eye-to-eye with
crocodiles in a muddy swamp? Bravery? Dedication? Insanity? Being
the son of naturalists and growing up studying, living and working
with animals explains Irwin's comfort level working with them. What
makes ``Crocodile Hunter'' so addictive is Irwin's factual tirades
and kid-in-a-candy store way of looking ``for crocs.'' How popular
is Irwin? Expect toys, games, a theme park and Croc Hunter action
figures with built-in audio of Irwin saying ``G'day, mate'' and
``What a ripper.'' Can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   2. Admit it. You've strolled into a room in your neighbors' home
and uttered, ``What a piece of. ...'' ``Changing Rooms'' (BBC
America, 4 and 4:30 p.m. Monday, Wednesday and Friday; 8 and 8:30
a.m., Saturday) allows you to ``act'' on such thoughts. In this
unique show, you get to strip, rip and paint the neighbor's room
that most annoys you. The catch: The neighbors get to redecorate a
room in your house. With only two days and a set budget, neighbors
go at it with a team of interior designers and carpenters. The only
condition is that the participants aren't allowed back into their
own homes until the work is done. Will neighbors like the finished
product and remain friends? Or will they hate the results and
strangle one another? ``Changing Rooms'' is hosted by Carol
Smillie, a former fashion model who broke into TV as an assistant
in the British ``Wheel of Fortune.'' Have there ever been any
fisticuffs? ``Not that,'' Smillie says, ``but there have been
neighbors never speaking to one another again. But usually, we all
do a pretty good job. And it's free. So how can you complain?''
</P>
<P>
   3. It's early morning and you're standing in a junkyard,
surrounded by acres of scrap and about as many tools. Here's the
challenge behind ``Junkyard Wars'' (8 p.m., weeknights starting
Wednesday, TLC): Two teams, all dressed up like extras from a ``Mad
Max'' sequel, have 10 hours to create the biggest, fastest,
strongest machine with parts they scrounge out of that junkyard.
Next week, for example, a team of psychologists called ``The Brainy
Bunch'' takes on a team of washing-machine repairmen in a
competition to build a better flying machine. The Brainy Bunch gets
ambitious and builds a full-sized glider using old airplane wings.
Viewers are entertained by the participants and even learn a thing
or two about airplane design. (You'll learn why anyone would put a
``canard,'' or tail, on the front of a plane instead of in the
back. Surely this question keeps you up nights.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Yeah, ``Wedding Story'' (various times weekdays, TLC) is as
sappy as it sounds. Not only are real-life weddings caught on tape,
but cameras follow the bride and groom through dress and tux
fittings to rehearsal dinners to in-laws jockeying for power.
Through all of this, the two lovebirds talk about what they're
getting into and how much they mean to one another. The best
``Wedding Story'' episodes are those of interfaith marriages (lots
of compromises, lots of friction) or when the bride and groom are
so different you wonder just how soon we'll catch them on ``Divorce
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   As one groom said, with a shot of his red-faced bride: ``Boy, I
don't know if I can get through this.'' She thought he said, ``Boy,
I don't know if I want to do this.'' Boy, we almost didn't have a
wedding on that episode. Clarifications brought the two back
together, and their big wedding went off without a hitch, except
for the uncle who had too much to drink. In another episode, the
mother of the bride accidentally smears lipstick on the white dress
an hour before the wedding. No need to fear. A dry cleaner in the
family gets it out in time, prompting someone to ask Mom when
handing her the dress, ``Can we trust you with this?'' She looked
like she was about to deck the guy.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   5. Brian Lamb has been called the Charlie Rose of books, but the
better-known Rose doesn't come close to Lamb in the astute
interrogator category. Lamb chairs the surprisingly spirited
``Booknotes'' (7 p.m. Sundays, C-SPAN) with the authority of a
grade-school teacher taking no mess. This isn't Stephen King or
some other pop-culture writer cruising through an interview with
``Today's'' Matt Lauer. Lamb sits face-to-face with authors to pick
apart their literature and their brains, and usually in a
just-the-facts-ma'am style that's so entertaining and illuminating
you'd think he wrote the book. Lamb can be so deadpan you often
think he hates absolutely everything. But it's fun to see authors
sweat, wondering if they are passing the Lamb smell test.
</P>
<P>
   6. As a TV personality, Tavis Smiley is as stiff as a board. He
once interviewed the comedian George Wallace, one of the
quickest-thinking comics alive today, and Smiley was so
straightforward and, well, ``serious,'' that Wallace nearly got up
and left. But as anchor of the hour-long chat fest ``BET Tonight''
(10 p.m. weeknights, Black Entertainment Television), Smiley
manages to get down to the point at hand with few biases and a lot
of courage, whether it's a discussion about sexuality in the black
church, a one-on-one with Islam leader Louis Farrakhan or rap star
and activist Chuck D. In terms of news and information, he's as
good as BET gets.
</P>
<P>
   7. What makes ``3's a Crowd'' (8:30 p.m. and 12:30 a.m.,
weeknights, The Game Show Network) so addictive is its potential
for complete and utter disaster. Think of ``Newlywed Game'' with an
ex-girlfriend tagging along. Couples invite former loves to the
party to see who knows the guy or girl best. Most of the questions
are of the intimate variety, and more times than not, the former
flames do quite well, which makes the current loves visibly
insecure. ``If she knows you that well,'' a woman says to a
boyfriend who seemed quite happy with the string of right answers
coming from his ex, ``then get a ride home with her tonight.'' This
would get totally out of hand if it weren't for host Alan Thicke, a
most effective mediator.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``The Simpsons'' aside, the networks have had their troubles
with animated projects, giving us ``God, the Devil and Bob'' and
other duds. MTV has been airing ``Daria'' (at various times) for a
few seasons now, and though no one seems to have noticed, it's
turning into one of the best programs on the air. (Yes, you read
that right.)
</P>
<P>
   Daria is a cynical young woman with oversize eyeglasses and a
strong sense of irony as her dominant personality trait. ``Good,''
she says when it begins to rain at a particularly bad time, ``I was
feeling too dry.'' Daria has friends but rarely cracks a smile,
maintaining the same facial expression, deadpan voice and serenely
negative attitude in nearly every situation. Her parents are idiots
and her friends are slackers, but Daria keeps moving through life
as though she's right and we're all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   9. Amario Kreutzberger (aka Don Francisco) has been doing this
for nearly 40 years, which is why ``Sabado Gigante'' (7 p.m.
Saturdays on Univision, KUVN/23) is perfect organized chaos. Part
``Oprah,'' part mess, it's a three-hour Spanish-language variety
show that takes the word ``variety'' to heart. It has some of
everything _ skits, game shows, singing, dancing, even ``serious''
subjects where audiences leave in tears. My Spanish may be limited,
but I'd rather watch one hour of ``Sabado Gigante'' than two hours
of that stilted comedy you get on ``The Tonight Show With Jay
Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
