<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRUE-LOVE0701-COX     06-30 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUE-LOVE0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A whole new twist on `Just Say No'
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ True love may wait, but Bill Hayes couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he promised back in 1993 to postpone having sex until he
was married. And yes, he held hands with hundreds of other young
Christians at The King's Academy in West Palm Beach and pledged to
stay pure. He even signed a True Love Waits card with the sincerest
of intentions.
</P>
<P>
   But that was when he was just 16, before he fell in love for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't plan it or anything,'' said Hayes, now 23. ``We were
dating for nine months. I really cared about her.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral of this story, supporters of abstinence programs will
tell you, is not that Hayes failed to live up to his commitment _
though they condemn his failure. It's that abstinence until
marriage has become a socially acceptable standard that Hayes and
other teenagers have set for themselves since they began their
campaign, a movement that has found its way into public school sex
education curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies their victory. And the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the True Love Waits campaign was launched by the Southern
Baptist Convention in Nashville in 1993, more than a million
teenagers have committed to virginity by signing True Love Waits
cards and pledging to ``respect'' themselves and their sexuality
enough to remain chaste, the SBC says. Hundreds of thousands of
others have promised the same thing through dozens of smaller
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade after those first rallies and pledge drives
began, all that chastity is beginning to show up in the wedding
aisles. This summer, pastors around the country are marrying brides
and grooms who are incorporating the commitment they made to
abstinence into their vows. During their ceremonies, they are
replacing the ``purity rings'' their parents gave them in high
school with wedding bands from their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   For those who didn't make it? ``It's not something I talk about
with other people,'' said Hayes, a King's Academy graduate who
asked that his real name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hayes and those like him, opponents of ``abstinence
only'' programs want to keep a full range of sex education classes
in public schools. To teach only one part of sex education, critics
say, is to champion idealism, not reality.
</P>
<P>
   IDEA TOUTED IN EARLY '90S
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, before the True Love Waits program became
mainstream, abstinence was more likely to be the punch line at the
end of a joke in a high school locker room than an option earnestly
discussed by typical 16-year-olds. But since the early 1990s, the
ideal has been touted by public figures and morphed into a part of
the federal government's curriculum for sex education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996 more than 1,000 ``abstinence only'' educational
programs have sprung up in school districts across the country, and
in that time, sex among teens has decreased. According to a Centers
For Disease Control and Prevention study, the percentage of teens
who had sex by the time they graduated from high school dropped
from 72 percent in 1990 to 64 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to abstain ``is determined by a whole variety of
things,'' said JoAnne Grunbaum, a health scientist with the CDC.
``It's hard to know what influenced it: Environment, peer norms,
education, adult practices. Change is complex and there's not just
one good answer.''
</P>
<P>
   True Love Waits and the dozens of other church-based abstinence
programs that have sprung up in the past few years are quick to
take some of the credit. They deserve it, they say, because they
have built a very public social support system for virginity and
brought chastity out of the closet. True Love Waits participants
have held dozens of rallies and concerts and stacked hundreds of
thousands of cards end to end on the Mall in Washington, across the
Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco and to the roof of the Georgia
Dome. The message: Virginity is safe, smart and cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is about being a man of character and integrity,''
says Scott Mawdesley, a 27-year-old virgin who says his pledge to
abstinence has been kept strong by the support of three roommates
from college who are also virgins and with whom he talks regularly.
Of his girlfriend of seven months, he says: ``I respect her, and I
don't want to use her, and the way I respect her is by respecting
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach County School District _ which began offering
``abstinence only'' seminars for middle and high school students in
1998 _ incorporates the character and integrity part but has tried
to leave the God part out of it. (Traditional sex education is
still taught in health courses.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not allowed to mention anything about God,'' says Kathy
Seppia, program director for ``Be The One,'' an abstinence program
taught in 32 district schools last year. ``We don't take a moral
stand on anything.'' (Neither the Martin nor St. Lucie County
school districts have applied for the federal government
abstinence-only grants).
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, statewide about half of the abstinence only
programs have their roots in church-financed organizations.
</P>
<P>
   What these federally financed programs teach is that abstinence
is the ``expected standard'' until marriage and that sex outside of
marriage ``is likely to have harmful psychological and physical
effects.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like the conservative Christian party line that's
because it is, says Rob Boston, a spokesman for Americans United
for the Separation of Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, the Christian Coalition tried to take sex education
out of schools altogether. When that failed, they regrouped and
began pushing in Washington for an ``abstinence only'' curriculum.
In 1996, they successfully lobbied Congress to attach $250 million
in federal money to abstinence-only curriculums with the mandate
that no information on other forms of birth control be added.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a one-sided look at human sexuality, critics
claim. The danger: While students may get traditional sex education
in health class, those who are receiving only abstinence education
are missing crucial information. And, liberals say, it's naive to
think that pushing abstinence will keep teens from having sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brothers, among a cadre of influential conservative
politicians, would disagree. And they're putting their money where
their beliefs are. Florida will dedicate a record $10 million to
``abstinence only'' education this year, and, if elected, George W.
Bush _ who has called up teens to forgo sex until they are in a
biblical marriage relationship _ has promised to nearly triple
federal money for abstinence only education.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks abstinence for teens is a bad idea,'' says
Boston. ``But there's a hidden agenda going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   A RELIGIOUS DEBATE BREWING
</P>
<P>
   Just beneath the surface of this debate, a battle over the best
way to teach sex education is brewing between the secular left and
the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Explains Amy Stephens, a spokesperson for Focus on the Family, a
Christian organization in Colorado Springs, Colorado: ``Liberal
atheists'' fear losing the control they gained in the '60s and '70s
over the country's sex education programs. And Planned Parenthood
is worried about losing government money to ``abstinence only''
programs. Lillian Tamayo, the CEO for Planned Parenthood of Palm
Beach and the Treasure Coast, views the battle from the other side:
``I think we're watching political and religious extremists shaping
social policy.'' From both sides statistical bombs are hurled. This
from Planned Parenthood: In 1999 a Planned Parenthood survey found
that 84 percent of Americans believe that the full range of sexual
education should be available to students. ``Which makes you ask,
who are these people (in the religious right) and who are they
representing?'' Tamayo says.
</P>
<P>
   PLEDGES SAID TO DELAY SEX
</P>
<P>
   From Focus on the Family: Even when pledges of virginity are
broken, they delay the beginning of sexual relations by years,
saving taxpayers millions of dollars in health-care costs from
abortions and sexually transmitted diseases. Leading Stephens to
ask, ``What, exactly, (are groups like Planned Parenthood) so
scared of?''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Oates, an astute 25-year-old youth-minister at Christ
Fellowship Church in Palm Beach Gardens, knows both sides of this
debate and has both feet clearly on the side of abstinence. The
debate has stirred up the church and forced pastors to deal much
more aggressively with the issue of sexuality _ and to deal with it
more realistically.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly divides the men and women into groups and asks the
kids to anonymously write down any questions they have about sex
and pass them forward. ``Those nights are always well-attended,''
says Oates, a virgin who's getting married next month. And he deals
with the subject frankly in his sermons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 14, I used to pray that Jesus wouldn't return yet
because I wanted to have sex,'' Oates tells about 100 18- to
30-year-olds at a recent Monday night singles service. ``But I'll
tell you this, heaven will be better than any sex you have down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude typifies the religious right's naive approach to
sexuality, Tamayo says. Promises of spiritual ecstasy may work for
the faithful Christian teens from the solid, two-parent homes, but
it's not going to work for everyone. For those who don't abstain or
believe, she says, ``we need to arm them for real life so they can
make real-life decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mawdesley has a retort to this that doesn't invite a
rejoinder. Believing that kids are going to have sex regardless of
the risk or the warnings is to believe that God doesn't exist, he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   If the Darwinists are right, and humans evolved from animals,
then, like animals, ``our sexuality will always dominate us.''
</P>
<P>
   But if people were put here by God, fully formed, as
creationists like Mawdesley believe, then they can and should
control their sexual urges. ``And I'm here to tell you we can
control it,'' Mawdesley says. ``I'm proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
