<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JACKSON, OTHERS CALL FOR HALT TO EXECUTIONS AT KILLER'S
FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY DORSETT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In life, Gary Graham was known as a convicted
murderer. In death, he was hailed as a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 people turned out Thursday for the funeral of
36-year-old Graham, who preferred to go by the African name Shaka
Sankofa. He was executed last week for the 1981 murder of a man
outside a Houston market.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was convicted based in the testimony of one witness. He
had pleaded with courts and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential hopeful, to halt the execution.
</P>
<P>
   The burial service lasted more than three hours, with the Rev.
Jesse Jackson preaching for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In his sermon, Jackson called on more blacks to register to vote
and urged other governors to join Illinois Gov. George Ryan, a
Republican, in placing a moratorium on executions. Voter
registration cards were distributed during the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pick up the baton where Shaka left it,'' Jackson said,
then echoed a sentiment from Graham's final statement: ``We've lost
this battle, but we haven't lost the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who spoke portrayed capital punishment as the
product of a racist system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This death penalty is anti-poor and anti-people-of-color and
we must stand up to that,'' said Robert Muhammad, a Nation of Islam
leader in Houston. ``Gary Graham is dead; long live Shaka
Sankofa.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral was boisterous as often as it was somber. A gospel
choir was on hand, and the service opened with African rituals that
included chants and drums.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of fists thrust into the air amid the declaration,
``March on black people, march on.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the last speakers, the Rev. Chris Wright, who said the
benediction, received thunderous applause when he announced that
Nov. 7, Election Day, would be Bush's political ``execution date.''
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Clements of the victims' rights group Justice For All
decried the ceremony Graham received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very disturbing that respected civil rights leaders
would come to Houston to pay homage to the killer, robber, raper
Gary Graham, one of the worst human rights violators Houston has
ever seen,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
