u f BC-HONG-KONG-PROPERTY-74     06-30 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-PROPERTY-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG HOMEOWNERS PROTEST DROP IN PROPERTY PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ With a solemn raising of the Chinese flag and the
dulcet tones of Hong Kong schoolchildren singing the Chinese
national anthem, this former British colony on Saturday morning
marked the third anniversary of its reversion to Chinese
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong may seem more like China with each passing year, but
it is still wrestling with the legacy of 156 years of colonial
rule. Last week this prosperous city was treated to the spectacle
of 2,000 well-dressed homeowners taking to the streets to protest
the plunge in property prices.
</P>
<P>
   Brandishing signs with such unproletarian messages as ``Negative
Equity Is Eroding Our Society,'' the crowd demanded that the
government prop up the real estate market. The commentators poked
fun, but the rally has sparked a genuine debate about one of Hong
Kong's most durable colonial-era practices.
</P>
<P>
   Property prices here are effectively set by the government
through a system of land auctions that dates from when the British
crown owned all the land in Hong Kong and parceled it out through
99-year leases. That arrangement worked nicely as long as asset
values in Asia rose year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, residential property prices have dropped 50 percent
_ a lingering effect of the Asian financial crisis. Hong Kong's
real estate market, unlike that of other parts of Asia, shows
little sign of recovery. And the government, as the regulator of
prices, is getting the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of middle-class people who are under financial
strain, and they're angry,'' said David Dodwell, the author of a
book, ``The Hong Kong Advantage,'' about the local economy. ``A lot
of them paid very high prices for apartments because they assumed
the price would continue to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people is Thomas Lo, the sales director of a
health-care company here. Lo bought his two-bedroom apartment in
April 1997, near the peak of the market, for $610,000. Two months
later, on the eve of the handover to China, a real estate agent
offered him $650,000. Lo decided to hold onto it. Today he figures
the apartment is worth no more than $320,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my kind of income, I should be able to live a
comfortable, relaxed life,'' Lo said. ``But now I'm looking at
buying a used car. Before, I would always buy the latest model of a
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Lo, 38, said he does not feel sorry for himself. He can still
afford to make his mortgage payments. But he said he cannot imagine
selling the apartment at a big loss. So rather than trading up to a
bigger place in a few years, he fears he will be stuck in this one
until retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Churchouse, a property analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, estimated that roughly 20 percent of Hong Kong residents
are in Lo's situation _ that is, the current market value of their
apartments is less than the amount of the mortgage outstanding on
the properties.
</P>
<P>
   But far more people have suffered a dramatic loss of wealth,
which has led to bitterness toward Hong Kong's postcolonial
government. The organizers of the homeowners' rally, leaders of the
pro-government Liberal Party, were nonplused when demonstrators
shouted ``Down with Tung,'' a reference to the city's
Beijing-appointed chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse in property prices is also rippling through the
economy in the form of weak consumer spending. Although Hong Kong
is enjoying a robust economic recovery, it is driven largely by
exports. A decline in export markets, particularly the United
States, could derail the recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cliff here; there is the potential to fall off that
cliff, either by inactivity or intervention,'' said Nicholas
Brooke, chairman of Brooke International, a real estate agency.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's land policy has also widened the gap between rich
and poor. Because the government doles out new land sparingly, it
commands high premiums. Private developers recoup their huge
investment by charging astronomical rents. The result is that more
than 70 percent of residents cannot afford to own homes.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Hong Kong's 7 million people live in public
housing. Another 25 percent buy private housing subsidized by the
government. With their salaries frozen in the wake of the Asian
crisis, these middle-income people have little hope of moving to
better apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Hong Kong becomes gradually more democratic, the divisions
between the rich and poor are no longer tenable,'' Dodwell said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He and other experts said Hong Kong needs to overhaul its land
policy. During the Asian crisis, the government suspended land
sales to stabilize prices. In mid-June, under pressure from
property tycoons, it took a more modest step _ pulling off the
market 16,000 subsidized apartments that it had planned to sell.
</P>
<P>
   A few commentators have called on Hong Kong to get out of the
property business altogether. They say that as long as the
government controls the land, the territory will be doomed to
cycles of boom and bust. But even they concede that it would be
extraordinarily difficult to unravel a system of land ownership so
deeply rooted in Hong Kong's colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any pressure from Beijing to take radical steps.
Whatever its views about Hong Kong's other colonial relics, it
seems content to stay out of the property market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can change the ownership of the land,''
said Ian K. Perkin, chief economist of the Hong Kong General
Chamber of Commerce. ``The only question you can ask is `How can
you deliver the right amount of land to guarantee stable, or
gradually increasing, land prices?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
