<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VANITY-BIOGRAPHIES-AR     06-30 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANITY-BIOGRAPHIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSIONING A BIOGRAPHY ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARGALIT FOX   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose you want a renowned author to write your life story, but
you don't happen to be famous _ or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair. Now a new Internet service allows ordinary
citizens with somewhat deeper than ordinary pockets to commission
custom portraits from eminent biographers like Judith Thurman,
Francine du Plessix Gray and Diane Wood Middle-brook.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, called the BioRegistry (www.bioregistry.com), was
created by Phyllis Rose, a biographer whose most recent book is
``The Year of Reading Proust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has surfaced periodically in the history of biography an
interest in what Virginia Woolf called `the lives of the
obscure,''' Rose explained. ``Anybody who thinks seriously about
biography wants to write about `ordinary' people, but there's no
market for it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, armed with her Rolodex, Rose, the author of lives of Woolf
and Josephine Baker, set out to create one. She conceived of the
site last spring after her mother died and a friend helped her
build a memorial Web page. Rose, who said she had found the
experience ``incredibly satisfying,'' realized she could offer a
similar service to others. The Bio-Registry, which offers memorial
portraits as well as profiles of the living, made its debut last
November.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a 2,000-word biography starts at $4,000. (Fees are
lower for what the site calls ``well-trained but unpublished''
writers.) The finished pieces can be posted on the Bio-Registry
site or on the client's own Web site, or they can be privately
printed.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, Rose said, there have been no takers, so the future
success of the site is unclear. But the Bio-Registry's real
significance may be to expand traditional notions of biography, its
authors and their subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed historically, the site is a natural outgrowth of the
time-honored tradition of biography for hire. ``In essence, it's a
continuation of what was going on all through the 19th century,
where you would have almost vanity-published books of notable
citizens,'' said Justin Kaplan, who received a Pulitzer Prize in
1967 for ``Mr. Clemens and Mark Twain.'' ( Kaplan is not in the
Bio-Registry's stable, though he confessed to fantasies of riding
horses out West for months on end while faithfully taking down the
life of his tycoon host.)
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, for instance, Col. William d'Alton Mann,
self-styled New York dandy and noted scoundrel, published ``Fads
and Fancies of Representative Americans at the Beginning of the
20th Century, Being a Portrayal of Their Tastes, Diversions and
Achievements.'' Expensively bound in gold-stamped leather, the book
comprised glowing biographical sketches of scores of prominent
people, including President Theodore Roosevelt. The cost of
inclusion ranged from $1,500 to $9,000, princely sums at the time.
(There was a reason Mann could command such prices: those who
didn't shell out for a biography would see their peccadilloes
reported in unsparing detail in Town Topics, a weekly scandal sheet
he also published.)
</P>
<P>
   But where the BioRegistry breaks with tradition _ besides
eschewing blackmail _ is in its ecumenicalism. Much as the advent
of photography democratized artistic portraiture (oil paintings for
Astors, Kodak moments for you and me), the new electronic
technology, Rose hopes, will broaden the definition of who is
considered a fit subject for a written portrait.
</P>
<P>
   It also broadens opportunities for the biographer. ``Biography
is absolutely the worst-paid endeavor in the world per hour of
work,'' said Thurman, who received a National Book Award in 1983
for a life of Isak Dinesen and whose biography of Colette,
``Secrets of the Flesh,'' was a National Book Award finalist last
year. ``This is an idea also for letting very skilled biographers
use their talents in a way that would not be arduous and make some
money, to be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   For each prospective project that interests them, Rose
explained, BioRegistry authors will submit fee requirements _ say,
$2 or $5 a word. The client will be charged twice that amount, with
half going to the writer and half to the BioRegistry.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, the author of ``At Home With the Marquis de Sade,'' said
she had signed on because she saw the Internet as a refreshing
alternative to the impersonal, conglomeratized world of book
publishing. ``Many of us are just fed up by all the traditional
channels,'' she explained. ``It seems to me that working in a small
community like this, there might be a new release, a new way out.''
</P>
<P>
   For Middlebrook, the author of lives of the poet Anne Sexton and
the cross-dressing jazz musician Billy Tipton, the site is an
acknowledgment of the singular demands of her craft. ``I was quite
fascinated that she had hit upon this idea for expressing the
occupation of the biographer as an occupation,'' she said of Rose.
``It's not that I see it as a source of work so much as a source of
professional identity.''
</P>
<P>
   On its face, however, writing a BioRegistry portrait might seem
closer to the work of a press agent than to biography. Since
background materials are furnished by the client (warts included at
the client's discretion), the writers are freed from the burden of
doing original research _ and of providing journalistic balance.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's authors say they're not troubled. ``I do lots of
journalism, some of it serious and some of it not,'' Thurman said.
``I feel no shame or problem with navigating back and forth into
deep and shallow waters.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Thurman's next project will be the life story of a
21-year-old dot-com millionaire remains to be seen. ``This appeals
to me abstractly,'' she said. ``I'm not sure, when it comes down to
the crunch, that if I'm writing something else I'll be willing to
tear myself away and go do a private commission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
