<SLUG> BC-FBN-MUNOZ0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An all around good guy
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ When he played professional football, Anthony
Munoz had the reputation of standing tall on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the sport, the Bengals' Hall-of-Famer often seizes
the opportunity to stand tall in the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, that's where you'll find him.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz will be guest speaker at the ninth annual ``God and
Country Celebration'' sponsored by Far Hills Baptist Church. The
religious/patriotic series has welcomed many prominent speakers to
the dais throughout its run but Munoz is, no doubt, the only one
who has thrown a pancake block on Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
   At two services beginning at 9 a.m. and 11 a.m., the hulking
gridiron legend will share his thoughts about life between the hash
marks and how it relates to family and faith. After the programs, a
luncheon is planned for local coaches and athletes at which Munoz
will host a question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his ferocious on-field persona, Munoz has always been
considered one of the good guys of the sports world. After a
standout college career, he graduated from the University of
Southern California and was drafted in the first round by the
Cincinnati Bengals in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In the pros, Munoz's solid technique and attention to detail
made him the blueprint for athletes at his position. He played in
two Super Bowls, was selected to the Pro Bowl 11 straight times and
made a member of the 1980s All-Decade Team. Munoz was named AFC
Offensive Lineman of the Year six times and in 1991 was voted NFL
Man of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his accomplishments on the football field, Munoz has been
a role model for scores of youngsters. As the father of two
college-bound athletes, he is a dedicated family man and a
concerned citizen who has received a slew community awards.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when he's not working as a football analyst on TV
and radio, Munoz lectures for Athletes in Action, co-chairs a
cystic fibrosis golf tournament and is on the advisory board of
Citizens for Community Values. He takes part in numerous football
camps but still finds time to address military personnel around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Lyle, program director at Far Hills Church, explained
that the ``God and Country Celebration'' is not only a program of
praise but also one of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance for us to honor our God-given rights of freedom
and freedom of religious expression,'' she said. ``Secondarily, its
also an opportunity to get people into our church to see what we're
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
