<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY DEBATES ISSUE OF LENIENCY FOR PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ John Paul II issued a worldwide call on Friday for
leniency for prisoners during the Holy Year, adding his moral
authority to a roiling political debate in Italy about justice and
overcrowded prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which has about 53,000 people in a prison system built
for less than 43,000, currently has its largest prison population
since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since members of the ruling center-left coalition began
gingerly discussing the possibility of freeing thousands of
prisoners through a general pardon or amnesty, prisons across Italy
have erupted in disturbances and protests, with prisoners _ and
sometimes their guards _ holding strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who in his message told governments that ``a
reduction, even a modest one, of the term of punishment would be
for prisoners a clear sign of sensitivity to their condition,''
plans to visit inmates at a prison in Rome next week, part of a
Holy Year day devoted to inmates. The Vatican has helped raise the
expectations of Italian inmates, and put pressure on politicians to
grant clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the president of Italy pardoned Mehmet Ali
Agca, the Turkish gunman who tried to kill the pope in 1981. The
pardon was made mainly at the urging of the pope, who had
campaigned for Agca's release while making forgiveness a theme of
the Holy Year.
</P>
<P>
   In the current debate over prisoners, the center-right
opposition, led by media tycoon Silvio Berlusconi, leader of Forza
Italia, has so far rejected suggestions that parliament approve a
general pardon to ease prison conditions. The opposition has argued
that the entire penitentiary system needs an overhaul, but that
dangerous criminals, AIDS patients and drug addicts could be set
loose in a general pardon. Italians generally have little faith in
their judicial system, but they are also increasingly concerned
about crime. Polls suggest that most Italians oppose an amnesty or
pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are 20 different proposals on a pardon or
amnesty in parliament, but the government of Giuliano Amato has not
yet issued its own draft bill. Instead, various proposals have been
floated as trial balloons by various politicians, filling frontpage
headlines in Italian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, where elections are expected to take place within a
year, the battle has many layers beneath the pros and cons raised
in public debate. On Thursday, Berlusconi had a private meeting
with Justice Minister Piero Fassino to discuss the issue.
Afterward, the opposition leader rejected the notion of a general
pardon, which in Italy could release prisoners who have less than
two years of their sentence to serve.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not rule out an amnesty, which, in Italy, would
release prisoners under similar conditions; but it would also
expunge their criminal records, and clear the books on ongoing
trials. ``Let us wait until they make more serious proposals and we
will give them the required attention,'' Berlusconi told reporters
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts argue that an amnesty would help unclog
Italy's backlog of court cases, and be more effective than a
general pardon. But Berlusconi, who has been acquitted on appeal of
several convictions of accounting fraud and bribery, but still
faces trials on other false accounting charges, could benefit
personally _ and politically _ from an amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   And that has led center-left politicians to make sarcastic
remarks about Berlusconi's personal motives and pious remarks about
the opposition's failure to heed the pleas of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime minister Giuliano Amato's center-left coalition is
deeply divided and in disarray. Many political analysts, and even
members of his coalition, suspect that the Amato government could
end up reaching an agreement with the opposition to grant an
amnesty, hoping to avert a confidence vote that could force early
elections, which the center-left fears it would lose in its present
frazzled state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
