u f BC-CHINA-CITRUS-460&AMP;ADD-     06-30 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CITRUS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CITRUS FRUITS MAKE THEIR DEBUT IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ At the Sidaokou wholesale market they have been
snapped up, these strange golden orbs bedecked with American-flag
stickers and the name Ocean Spray.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have driven two hours to buy them. But most just
regard these fruits with curiosity _ are they oversized oranges? _
and read the poster that explains: ``Grapefruits from Florida ...
Famous Brand Name ... Healthy and Tasty ... Good for Your Blood and
for Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first imported product and sales are very very good,''
said Rong Zhifang, a saleswoman, hovering behind her cartons.
</P>
<P>
   When China joins the World Trade Organization, probably later
this year, it will be forced to allow a huge range of foreign goods
greater access to its vast markets. But a few American agricultural
items _ including citrus fruit and pork _ have already gained
dramatically improved entry in the last few months, under a recent
U.S.-China agricultural agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And in Beijing the fate of the invading oranges and grapefruits
is seen as a glimpse of China's future, presaging the sudden new
opportunities and problems that free trade will bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrival of American agricultural products is just a
start,'' said the Beijing Morning News in one of many articles that
have appeared recently about the American fruit. ``Once China joins
the WTO, the story about the boy crying wolf will soon become a
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Western companies are drooling at the prospect of
China's potentially huge market, aggressively promoting their
products.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual Food China 2000 Exhibition last week in Beijing,
U.S. producers of chicken, ice cream and fruit juice _ to name a
few _ turned out in stands decorated with red, white and blue
bunting to give buyers from Chinese restaurants, supermarkets and
hotels a taste of the future. There was even a booth promoting
American pork, to a country where a surplus of pigs has driven down
pork prices to near-record lows this year.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the citrus booth _ with its free fruit slices and
drinks _ that commanded the longest lines. ``This will certainly
open up new business opportunities for me,'' said Ding Yong, a food
distributor for cafeterias. ``The juices are great.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, of course, is something of an issue. Imported oranges are
about three times the price of Chinese products. Grapefruits here
cost about $1.50 each, compared with about 10 cents for somewhat
similar Chinese fruits called youzi (pronounced yo-zuh) and huyou
(pronounced hoo-yo).
</P>
<P>
   These price differentials will narrow somewhat when China enters
the WTO, since the fruits now carry an average import tariff of 40
percent. But even as tariffs are cut, imported fruit is likely to
remain quite a bit more expensive than domestic varieties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And other hurdles are likely to remain for a long time, as
China's slow-moving bureaucracy adjusts to the realities of more
imports. The Florida grapefruits that arrived in China on April 20,
for example, were stuck in quarantine for the next four weeks,
their release blocked by a series of logistical problems.
</P>
<P>
   First, the inspection documents provided by the Florida
producers were considered invalid by Chinese customs authorities.
Then the quarantine inspectors sealed the warehouse after noticing
that some cases contained dead insects. The inspectors ultimately
cleared the fruits, but not before Chinese distributors had paid
them thousands of dollars in storage fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have met with so many troubles from these fruits, and I
still have many grapefruits in the ports waiting to be inspected,''
said Zhang Zhimin, the sales manager for China Cereal Import and
Export Co., which is handling the citrus imports. ``Although sales
are good now and I am quite optimistic, there are still many
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The citrus fruits are coming in under the U.S.-China
Agricultural Cooperation Agreement signed late last year. Under the
accord, China said it would drop barriers that had previously
prevented the import of some American agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   China agreed to recognize the U.S. pork inspection system, for
example, which it had called inadequate. It also dropped what had
previously been a near-blanket ban on citrus imports, put in place
to protect against infestation by the Mediterranean fruit fly, or
medfly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, the United States promised not to send
fruits to China from local counties experiencing medfly
infestations.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 20, more than six huge shipments of fruit have
arrived here, including 16 tons of Sunkist oranges in the
northeastern part of Dalian and 60 tons of grapefruits in the
coastal city of Tianjin. By the end of May, they could be found in
upscale markets in Beijing, where the press has provided detailed
analyses of their flavor, appearance, breeding and value.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, the 1,800 cartons of oranges that arrived on May 11
sold out within two hours. In Dalian, they lasted just three days.
Tens of thousands of grapefruits have sold in Beijing since they
arrived on May 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the high prices affect sales in China?'' asked the
Beijing Morning News. ``It seems not. The Chinese people have shown
unexpected enthusiasm for these fine-quality oranges.'' Chinese
experts urged their compatriots to carefully observe the invasion
and learn from American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the initial burst of enthusiasm for the fruit may not
be surprising in a country where consumers worship all things
American. U.S. fruit growers and distributors are determined to
maintain the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Calling grapefruit the ``No. 1 Fruit in the U.S.,'' material
from Beijing Shiyi Futai Trade Co. says its grapefruits help
``protect your heart, blood vessels and kidneys.'' The fruit ``has
the natural anti-cancer element of folic acid, and natural fruit
colloid, which can lower cholesterol.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of flashy television ads, featuring a popular music TV
host named Ke Lan, is planned to promote American oranges.
</P>
<P>
   There is still much work to be done. At the China Food 2000
Exhibition, Sunny Chen, an executive chef from a hotel in Xian,
declared that consumers there were ``not ready'' for the flavor of
grapefruit, as he threw a rind into the trash can _ even though he
personally liked the fruit and predicted success with the more
worldly palates of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But at the huge Xidan Market in the capital, six flag-festooned
grapefruits sat forlornly on the shelves on one recent day _ more
museum pieces than comestibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look! Fruit from America,'' said Gui Shufeng, a retiree who
was strolling in the market with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them _ a little tart and a little sweet,'' said Gui,
who had tasted grapefruit while visiting his daughter in New York.
``But I'm not sure if Chinese will buy them. They're expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
