<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEACHERS-TESTS01-COX     06-30 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-TESTS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANTI-REFORM STORM BREWS IN SCHOOLS, TEACHER UNION HEAD SAYS
 &HT;    400&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A rebellion is brewing among worried teachers and
parents that is threatening public school reforms, Bob Chase,
president of the National Education Association, warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teacher members have big concerns, big fears and big
questions about the way standards and testing are being used, and,
unfortunately, all too often abused,'' Chase told educators at a
conference held to prepare for the annual convention of the
nation's largest teachers union, which opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a number of states, parents have become radicalized,'' he
said. ``They're saying, 'Too many kids are failing, so let's
abandon standards and accountability.' That's the exact wrong
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase is a former Connecticut teacher who comes from the
dominant pro-reform wing of the 2.5-million-member NEA. He stressed
that he considers himself to be ``a consistent, strong and even
passionate advocate for standards-based reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach grew out of three summits in which state governors
and business leaders met with reform advocates. It urges states to
adopt educational standards, districts to redesign courses to
prepare students to meet those standards, and states to then test
the students to see if they meet the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I regret to report that in all too many states,
standards-based reform is being very poorly implemented ... in a
haphazard manner with poor alignment of curriculum, standards and
testing,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, whose organization includes more than half of the
nation's public school teachers, said reformers in many states have
``botched'' several changes. He emphasized these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Students ``are being tested on subjects they are not being
taught.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tests ``are being designed that have little to do with the
standards that have been created by, in all too many instances, God
knows who.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Standards are being imposed without ``adequate preparation''
of teachers, additional money for new course materials and
equipment, or extra help for the students with the biggest learning
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Test scores are being used ``to stigmatize and punish
high-poverty schools, `` instead of being used ``as diagnostic
tools to guide positive intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been truly egregious problems in Virginia,
California, Texas, Massachusetts and many other states,'' Chase
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Chase cited examples of ``mind-boggling'' mistakes in Ohio, even
as he praised Gov. Bob Taft's ``common-sense decision'' to form a
state commission to figure out how to reform the state's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said, ``In a nutshell, what the state had done was take
existing Ohio proficiency tests _ tests which were originally
designed for use as diagnostic instruments to identify areas where
students need help _ and by fiat declare that these tests would be
used as high-stakes tests (to evaluate a school's performance) and,
worst of all, eventually as exit tests'' that students must pass in
order to earn a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The tests weren't aligned to state standards, because Ohio has
no state standards. That meant that a student could be denied a
high school diploma because the courses in that student's high
school didn't cover the same topics as the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said, ``Our challenge is to rescue standards-based reform,
and do whatever we can do to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a few states ``did it right'' as they
introduced reforms, said Stanford University professor Linda
Darling-Hammond, who is executive director of the National Council
on Teaching and America's Future.
</P>
<P>
   She said the reforms are working best in Connecticut, Kentucky,
Maine and Virginia, which was one of the states that Chase said has
made big mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: National Education Association: www.nea.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's email address is Andym(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
