<SLUG> BC-NEW-AD-COLUMN-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MADISON AVENUE IN A PREHOLIDAY RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Madison Avenue prepared for a long holiday
weekend, executives were scrambling to complete a spate of deals.
</P>
<P>
   Bates North America in New York, part of the Bates Worldwide
unit of Cordiant Communications Group, was concluding plans to
expand its offerings into technology advertising by acquiring
Donino, White &AMP; Partners in Atlanta, a shop with billings estimated
at over $100 million from clients like BellSouth, the Digital and
Applied Imaging unit of Eastman Kodak and the UUNet Technologies
division of WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   The plans call for Bates North America to operate a new unit,
named DWP Bates Technology, after acquiring the business assets of
Donino, White for a minimum of $30 million in Cordiant stock to be
paid over three years. Frank Donino, chief executive at Donino,
White, is to become chief executive at DWP Bates Technology, which
could later be expanded to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Torello, a spokeswoman for Bates, said Thursday that
negotiations were continuing and declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson World Group in New York, part of Interpublic
Group of Cos., is expanding into personnel-recruitment advertising
by buying Nationwide Advertising Service in Cleveland for
undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, with offices in 41 cities in North America, produces
print and Internet ads for Fortune 100 companies, governments and
universities seeking to fill job openings. Nationwide, with an
estimated $400 million in capitalized billings, will operate as an
autonomous unit of McCann-Erickson; John Graham will continue as
chief executive and Tom Richey will remain president.
</P>
<P>
   There were two other deals involving Interpublic, the agency
company that owns Draft Worldwide and Lowe Group in addition to
McCann-Erickson. Interpublic is taking an unspecified minority
stake in Software Associates International in Mount Arlington,
N.J., which offers customer-sales-support software and database
products for the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   Software Associates has 170 employees working for clients like
Johnson &AMP; Johnson; Shaleen Gupta, president and chief executive,
continues in that post.
</P>
<P>
   And Draft, based in Chicago, acquired Sloan Group in New York, a
creative marketing agency that specializes in youth, entertainment
and technology advertising. Sloan, which has 50 employees working
for clients like HBO, will operate as an autonomous unit of Draft's
KBA Marketing division.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two other deals are taking place in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom Group in New York is acquiring Court Burkitt, a London
agency formed in 1986. Court Burkitt will be merged with the London
office of Griffin Bacal _ part of the DDB Worldwide division of
Omnicom _ to form Burkitt DDB under the aegis of BMP DDB, the DDB
British agency. Terms of the acquisition, reported by Campaign, the
British advertising trade publication, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin Bacal brings to Burkitt DDB clients like Burberry and
Hasbro, while Court Burkitt brings clients like the John Lewis
department stores and Peroni beer. Combined billings were estimated
at $80 million. At Burkitt DDB, Hugh Burkitt, chairman of Court
Burkitt, becomes chairman, while Jonathan Hoare, managing director
of Griffin Bacal, becomes managing director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity in London to build an extension of the
DDB brand,'' said Tom Griffin, co-chairman and chief executive at
Griffin Bacal in New York. ``The case in London is different than
the U.S.,'' where Griffin Bacal will continue operating under that
name.
</P>
<P>
   The other British deal concerned Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New
York, which has agreed to be acquired by WPP Group. Y&AMP;R is buying
Partners, a London agency specializing in creative design and brand
identity consulting for clients like Harrods, Unilever and Warner
Bros. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Partners, which has 75 employees and revenue estimated at over
$11 million, will become part of the Diversified Communications
Group of Y&AMP;R. Aziz Cami, managing partner at Partners, continues in
that post.
</P>
<P>
   Another brand image and consulting agency, d/g, in New York and
Paris, agreed to sell a 60 percent stake to Future Source
Communications in New York and Toronto, for undisclosed terms. The
agency, formerly known as Desgrippes/Gobe, has 175 employees and
revenue estimated at $30 million, from clients like Coca-Cola and
Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   The top executives at d/g will continue in their posts: Marc
Gobe, 54, president and chief executive in New York, and Joel
Desgrippes, 55, president and chief executive in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, True North Communications in Chicago acquired Event
Management and Promotions in Santa Monica, Calif., which will
become part of a True North division named Marketing Drive
Worldwide. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Event Management, with more than 40 employees and revenue
estimated at over $10 million, from clients like Kellogg and Sony,
will be renamed EMP/Marketing Drive. Jamie Wark, 39, president at
Event Management, will be president at EMP/Marketing Drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
