<HEADLINE>
SITE OF THE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HowStuffWorks.com: A site that, believe it or not, actually does
what it says, describing in simple, earnest (and exclamation
point-filled!) language how stuff, of all kinds, works. &QL; 
Where: www.howstuffworks.com &QL; 
What's cool: Right now, it's the special section on how fireworks,
uh, work. Consider it an explosive expose on aerial explosives,
perfectly timed for a hot holiday. &QL; 
Features: The site is loaded with lots of goodies, explaining not
just basic technology such as cell phones, diesel engines and the
Internet, but also more unstuff-like stuff, such as bread and
chocolate, your body, tattoos, weather and passports. There's a
nice selection of suggested reference books, the latest news about
interesting stuff, and other odds and ends. The site's No. 1
question: how ``Star Wars'' light sabers work. That leads to a
discussion of rotoscoping using common video editing software, how
green- or bluescreening works and more. We'd like more
illustrations, but there are some, and it's all well done and
penetrable by laypersons. &QL; 
You'll like this if: You're annoyed because there's nothing to see
when you take stuff apart in the digital age. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
