<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH AND SOUTH AGREE TO PLANS TO REUNITE SEPARATED FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Red Cross officials from North and South Korea signed an
agreement Friday to begin reuniting families separated by more than
50 years of conflict on the Korean peninsula. The accord, an
outgrowth of breakthrough reconciliation talks between the two
countries two weeks ago, also provides for the return of North
Koreans who were imprisoned in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Under Friday's agreement, about 100 South Koreans will travel to
the North Korean capital, Pyongyang, to meet with relatives, while
100 North Koreans will meet with family members in Seoul. These
initial reunions are scheduled to take place over four days,
beginning on Aug. 15, according to South Korean media reports from
North Korea, where the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the deal is expected to reunite thousands of Koreans
who were separated from relatives when the peninsula was divided at
the end of World War II. South Korean officials estimate that there
are nearly 8 million people in the South, about 660,000 of them
over 60 years old, who have relatives living in the North.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean War broke out 50 years ago last month, and although a
1953 armistice suspended the fighting, North and South are
technically still at war, and only a handful of separated families
have been allowed to take part in officially sanctioned reunions in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   For reunions, Red Cross officials agreed to set up a permanent
visitation center where separated families can meet. The officials
said they had not yet decided where to establish the center.
However, they mentioned as possible candidates scenic Mount
Kumgang, on North Korea's east coast, and Panmunjom, the village in
the heavily armed demilitarized zone along the two countries'
border.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached after four days of talks between
representatives from the Red Cross of both Koreas at Mount Kumgang.
</P>
<P>
   ``This South-North agreement is the first concrete result
following the summit meeting, and it means that we have entered the
realization phase in dealing with the separated family issues,''
said Park Ki-ryun, secretary general of the South Korean Red Cross.
``We will try our best to insure that exchanges will occur without
complications.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his expectations for the family reunions were, Choi
Seung Chul, the head of North Korea's Red Cross, said: ``Things
will work out very well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for the return of all North Koreans who
served prison terms in the South who want to return home. The North
Koreans, most of whom were convicted of spying for the North, would
be allowed to go in early September.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean Defense Ministry has said that 50 of the 88
former prisoners, who are mostly elderly, have indicated that they
want to return to North Korea. There was no mention in the
agreement of South Korean soldiers who may still be behind bars in
the North.
</P>
<P>
   To facilitate meetings between separated family members, North
and South Korean officials will trade lists of 200 separated
relatives and begin checking to see whether the individuals on the
list are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The visitation center will not be set up until the North Korean
prisoners are returned, the reports said. The center is expected to
identify hundreds of separated family members a month and bring
them together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
