<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV02-NY     06-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE'S SHENANIGANS CAST LIGHT ON PUBLIC CHOICE THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no secret that the rivalry between the software leaders,
Microsoft and Oracle, is bitter. Still, the acknowledgment last
week by Oracle that it financed a series of escapades intended to
embarrass Microsoft provided some lively summer entertainment _
especially the Keystone Kops caper in which private investigators
offered office cleaners $1,200 for the contents of a pro-Microsoft
trade group's wastebaskets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the cross-fire of invective that ensued, the two foes
found some common ground in what is known as public choice theory,
whose practitioners use economic principles to analyze government
decision-making, especially the influence of special-interest
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in a statement, declared that Oracle's shenanigans
amounted to nothing less than ``dramatic evidence that Microsoft's
competitors have engaged in a massive and ongoing campaign to
unfairly tarnish Microsoft's public image and promote government
intervention to benefit themselves.'' Translation: The government's
antitrust case was a result of successful lobbying by Microsoft's
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Without regret or irony, Lawrence J. Ellison, the Oracle
chairman, called his company's campaign ``a public service'' that
brought hidden information to light. Oracle's private eyes failed
to buy any garbage of the Association for Competitive Technology, a
group that backed Microsoft in the antitrust case, but they did
turn up documents showing that two similar groups, the Independent
Institute and the National Taxpayers Union, were financially
supported by Microsoft. Those documents were passed to reporters
for The New York Times, The Wall Street Journal and The Washington
Post, who wrote articles about Microsoft's backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left undisclosed,'' an Oracle statement said, ``these
Microsoft front groups could have improperly influenced one of the
most important antitrust cases in U.S. history.'' Oracle, too,
seems to believe that public relations and lobbying can affect
federal antitrust cases.
</P>
<P>
   Public choice theory, to be sure, is a serious discipline. James
M. Buchanan won the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Science in
1986 for his public choice research, and two other Nobel laureates,
George J. Stigler and Kenneth J. Arrow, have made important strides
in the field. But applying public choice theory to federal
antitrust actions runs into some logical problems. Do Microsoft's
competitors have a stake in the suit? Of course they do. And
Microsoft's rivals, who offered information and evidence to
prosecutors, say they were not lobbying, just educating the
government. (Of course, most any lobbyist would say that.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet such statements of the obvious do not show that the
government is dancing to the tune of the Microsoft-bashing band.
People who have worked in the Justice Department's antitrust
division over the years say the arithmetic works like this: Since
consumers rarely know what is going on, 90 percent of antitrust
leads come from competitors. But fewer than 1 in 10 complaints by
competitors prompt an investigation, and only a tiny fraction of
those lead to a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have 350 smart people in the antitrust division to
separate the wheat from the chaff,'' said Robert E. Litan, director
of economic studies at the Brookings Institution and a former
Justice Department official. ``That's how antitrust enforcement
works.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the most compelling evidence against Microsoft
came from the company's own documents and e-mail, not from anything
competitors supplied. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Public choice theorists suggest that politics was behind the
Microsoft case, noting that the senior Justice Department officials
are political appointees and that the 19 state attorneys general
are elected officials. Yet the suit has never been much of a
populist cause. Microsoft and Bill Gates personally retained very
favorable poll ratings throughout the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement is not supposed to be done by referendum.
The Justice Department is a law enforcement agency, and the
judiciary is institutionally independent from the other branches of
government. Buchanan, the public choice pioneer, has noted that the
framers of the Constitution wisely used separation of powers and an
independent judiciary to curb the effects of self-seeking special
interests on government.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people can disagree about the Microsoft case.
Microsoft believes that Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who found
the company a monopolist that has repeatedly violated the nation's
antitrust laws, was mistaken. That is now a matter for the U.S.
Court of Appeals or the Supreme Court. Lobbying or image campaigns
or public choice theory will not affect the outcome; no use bidding
for wastebaskets now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
