A9725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMA VOTE ENABLES KREMLIN TO DISMISS REGIONAL GOVERNORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's lower house of parliament voted solidly Friday
to give the Kremlin the right to fire any of the nation's 89
governors for cause, handing President Vladimir Putin another
powerful weapon in his bid to centralize power in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house, or Duma, voted 399-9 in favor of the proposal,
which now goes to the upper house. The landslide vote means that
the measure almost certainly will become law, no matter how the
upper house votes, because the Duma would need only 300 of Friday's
399 votes to override action by the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has moved quickly to rein in the governors, potentially
powerful political forces who sometimes have run their provinces as
autocrats, almost independent of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma already has passed another bill that would sweep the
governors from their guaranteed seats in the upper house of
parliament, diluting their influence in Moscow and _ just as
important _ ending their immunity from criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are looking into political corruption in
two-thirds of the 89 regions, officials say. Should the legislation
passed Friday become law, Putin could dismiss a governor for any
violations of the Russian constitution, as long as a federal court
approves the act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1745EDT &QL; 
