<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-VOYEURISM-LADN &LR;      06-30 1666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYEURISM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME, HOME ON THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
  More and more, somebody's watching 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most people, home is a sanctuary, a place to hide from the
world. For Lisa Nowicki, it's her stage.
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki's modest apartment on the edge of Hollywood looks
unremarkable at first _ light colors, a little fireplace and
balcony, and a bedroom loft overlooking the narrow living room. But
then you notice one major difference: In every room, a videocamera
is bolted to a wall, and every few seconds, each camera snaps a
picture and sends it to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the evidence _ the hype surrounding reality television
shows like ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' thousands of live
Webcam sites on the Net _ it seems we've become a closed loop of
voyeurs and exhibitionists, staring at each other through the
mediated lens of TV and 'Net.
</P>
<P>
   For Nowicki, it's the role of a lifetime, her lifetime, in her
apartment, before an audience of thousands. At
AspiringActresses.com, a Web site that runs 24/7, subscribers can
peek in on literally every part of Nowicki's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor, you're always looking for some other way to
distinguish yourself, and I thought, `Well, why not?' '' said
Nowicki, a pretty, pleasant woman from Chicago in her late 20s who
has been trying six years to make it in the acting business.
``Maybe it's a long-running documentary. It's like 'EdTV,' 'The
Real World' and 'The Truman Show' all blended together.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki is part of a Webcam world that has been building in size
for a while, attracting some of the same audience that has made
reality TV shows such ratings monsters. While sexually oriented
Webcams sites have done booming business for some time, the new
ones _ like Nowicki's and competitors such as Crushed Planet and
TheRealHouse.com. _ focus on more or less real life, if you
consider life in front of a camera all day real.
</P>
<P>
   Sex certainly is shown on these sites when it happens, but even
the salacious stuff is only a small part of the participants'
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like ``Being John Malkovich,'' the wacky 1999 film
where people pay to be literally inside the actor's head for 15
minutes at a time. His is not a glamorous life: Generally, all they
see him do is eat leftover Chinese food, or order linens from a
catalog. But they turn out in droves, paying $200 each, for that 15
minutes of time in the actor's head.
</P>
<P>
   The difference here is that in most cases, these are people
you've never heard of, even if, like Nowicki, they hope their
Internet exposure will make them famous.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to take a peek at people's lives isn't new, argues
author Simson Garfinkel, whose recent ``Database Nation'' explores
the collision between technology and privacy. ``It's just that
technology allows more people to see it,'' said Garfinkel. ``And
there's the possibility of a personal connection if you desire
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People could make money off their diaries and
autobiographies,'' Garfinkel said. ``The real difference is you can
get instantly there.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Winner, the man who runs Nowicki's site and eight other
sites that he collectively calls LIFEcam, says there's definitely
money to be made. The Canoga Park college couple in his CoupleTV
site attract as many as 10,000 viewers at a time, including
thousands of subscribers who each put up $19 a month to watch their
antics, sexual and otherwise, on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Winner acknowledges his sites provide a good business for him,
but says he does it ``because I just love exposing secrets. To me,
people-watching is so fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   He splits subscription proceeds with each site's participants,
though Nowicki, who's been decidedly more mild-mannered on screen
than her fellow LIFEcam counterparts, says she makes only enough to
pay some bills and avoid ``having to waitress seven nights a week''
to cover living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Winner put himself on screen about nine months ago, to better
understand what his employee/stars were experiencing. And he said
he found it a transforming experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camera becomes a friend,'' Winner said. ``It becomes not
just a one-way mirror looking in at you, but a portal looking out.
When that camera is on, you don't feel lonely. It's sort of the
same reason people have their TV on. They're really hooked in, more
than anyone else in the world. I do know once they get hooked in,
they're in it for more than just money, or their exhibitionism.''
</P>
<P>
   That interaction with the rest of the world, in what would be a
haven from the craziness of daily life for most folks, can be
tiring, though.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Smith, a 22-year-old structural engineering associate,
is leaving The Real House (at www.therealhouse.com) after 10
months, in part because she tired of having to chat every day with
subscribers and keep a diary, both requirements of residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some energy,'' Smith said. ``I can't keep up with it
any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   That interaction with the fans is a crucial part of what makes
these sites work, and fans use it to voice opinions on seemingly
everything they see and read.
</P>
<P>
   The Real House's president, Giovanni Barone of Santa Monica,
sent along one such piece of fervent, if frequently misspelled, fan
mail meant for Smith:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi Suzzane, Your boyfriend doesn(')t seem to be concerned
about you and the way he makes you feel sexually. I say this
because he doesn(')t care if you are exposed to the camera while
you guys are making love but he always...ALWAYS!!! covers himself
while you guys are (having sex.)''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of scrutiny by viewers got old, Smith said, even
though she says she quickly was able to ignore the cameras
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sometimes because some people, when watching you,
seem to get an opinion of their own about how you are and how your
relationship is,'' Smith said. ``They definitely voice their
opinion. They look at it like it's a soap opera that isn't real.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki said she is starting to get double takes from people in
public places who ask whether she's on the Internet, a sign that
someone is watching. And though Smith found the fan interest an
interference sometimes, particularly for her camera-shy boyfriend,
Nowicki welcomes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I get to the point, say, that I'm working on a show,
I would keep on doing it,'' Nowicki said. ``I just think it's so
much fun. I just stare up at (the camera) sometimes and make faces
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Nowicki and the other LIFEcammers, Smith only received
free rent and utilities for living in The Real House, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith initially became part of the place when her
then-boyfriend, Niko, signed both of them up. Once they were in,
though, the couple quickly split up when Niko was captured on
camera having sex with another woman. Both continued to remain in
the house, though Niko, too, is about to move out, essentially
because of a vote by the site's fans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith sees living in the house as a good and unique
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a test, to put myself in a different experience,'' said
Smith. ``I just wanted to be put in a weird situation. I didn't
mind it. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The participants on Woodland Hills-based Crushed Planet (at
www.crushedplanet.com) don't get paid a lot of money, either, says
co-CEO Harry Gantz. He and brother Joe are best-known for their HBO
reality show ``Taxicab Confessions,'' where a cabbie encourages his
fares to discuss intimate details of their lives while hidden
cameras are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the Web allows the Gantzes to show more than just
highlights of someone's life, Harry Gantz says. One of their shows,
``First Apartment,'' featuring a couple sharing their first
apartment together, provides the unedited reality dose that fuels
the Webcam world.
</P>
<P>
   Gantz has his own theory why it appeals to participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in a sense a personal expression, the same way someone
might be dabbling in art,'' Gantz said. ``It's the most idealistic
time of life, when people are most concerned with personal
expression. They've seen Webcams and think here's a situation where
they can trust the technology to show their lives honestly. The way
we set it up, people think, 'Wow, I have a chance to express myself
by being on this Webcam.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barone said he picks only certain kinds of people to take part:
``I base it on their personality, their charisma, how they hold
themselves, if they're talkative and very charming and
enthusiastic, those kinds of characteristics. They don't have to
necessarily get along with everyone. And if there's something
interesting about them, (like) they're in a band.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask participants why others would watch their lives, and they
scratch their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was just me (in the house), I don't have any idea,''
said Smith. ``But with other (Real House residents), I can see the
attraction. You have actual contact with these people. Lots of
drama goes on. I think that's the attraction. That and the fact
that you can actually talk to these people and interact with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantz attributes it to post-modern existential angst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to do with this feeling of people feeling so
disconnected to the world,'' Gantz said. ``They live in little
apartments. This in a sense makes you feel connected, by being with
these other real people. If you can care about (`The Sopranos'),
don't you think there's a bigger potential to care if it's someone
who's real?''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 4,000 people a day, from all over the world, may
watch Nowicki, typically keeping a window open on their computer's
desktop to monitor what's happening in her life as they live
theirs, Winner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just an enormous number of people who just really
appreciate the subtlety of watching life,'' Winner said. ``Why do
people watch? Because it's really, really entertaining. It's all
live, all subtle, but rather hypnotic: What's going to happen
next?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
