<P>
   ``It was a test, to put myself in a different experience,'' said
Smith. ``I just wanted to be put in a weird situation. I didn't
mind it. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The participants on Woodland Hills-based Crushed Planet (at
www.crushedplanet.com) don't get paid a lot of money, either, says
co-CEO Harry Gantz. He and brother Joe are best-known for their HBO
reality show ``Taxicab Confessions,'' where a cabbie encourages his
fares to discuss intimate details of their lives while hidden
cameras are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the Web allows the Gantzes to show more than just
highlights of someone's life, Harry Gantz says. One of their shows,
``First Apartment,'' featuring a couple sharing their first
apartment together, provides the unedited reality dose that fuels
the Webcam world.
</P>
<P>
   Gantz has his own theory why it appeals to participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in a sense a personal expression, the same way someone
might be dabbling in art,'' Gantz said. ``It's the most idealistic
time of life, when people are most concerned with personal
expression. They've seen Webcams and think here's a situation where
they can trust the technology to show their lives honestly. The way
we set it up, people think, 'Wow, I have a chance to express myself
by being on this Webcam.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barone said he picks only certain kinds of people to take part:
``I base it on their personality, their charisma, how they hold
themselves, if they're talkative and very charming and
enthusiastic, those kinds of characteristics. They don't have to
necessarily get along with everyone. And if there's something
interesting about them, (like) they're in a band.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask participants why others would watch their lives, and they
scratch their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was just me (in the house), I don't have any idea,''
said Smith. ``But with other (Real House residents), I can see the
attraction. You have actual contact with these people. Lots of
drama goes on. I think that's the attraction. That and the fact
that you can actually talk to these people and interact with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantz attributes it to post-modern existential angst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to do with this feeling of people feeling so
disconnected to the world,'' Gantz said. ``They live in little
apartments. This in a sense makes you feel connected, by being with
these other real people. If you can care about (`The Sopranos'),
don't you think there's a bigger potential to care if it's someone
who's real?''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 4,000 people a day, from all over the world, may
watch Nowicki, typically keeping a window open on their computer's
desktop to monitor what's happening in her life as they live
theirs, Winner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just an enormous number of people who just really
appreciate the subtlety of watching life,'' Winner said. ``Why do
people watch? Because it's really, really entertaining. It's all
live, all subtle, but rather hypnotic: What's going to happen
next?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
