<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ After 38 years, the Confederate
battle flag is coming off the Statehouse dome on Saturday, July 1.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAGSIDE _ CRAWFORDVILLE, Ga. _ Soren Dresch's home-based
company is to the flag business what L.L. Bean is to polo shirts.
Need the skull and crossbones? Use your credit card and order it
from the Ruffin Flag Company catalog. You'll find the rising sun of
Japan, the red maple leaf of Canada, the Red Cross, the St. Andrews
Cross, the flag of every U.N. nation, the flag of every state.
Today, South Carolina will remove the controversial Rebel flag from
its state house dome and raise a square version at the Confederate
Soldiers Monument in front of the capitol. Both banners are
stitched by Ruffin seamstresses. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BARNES-MONEY _ Gov. Roy Barnes, Georgia's wealthiest governor,
released his 1999 tax returns Friday (a day ahead of the 7/1
deadline for all state officials to submit financial disclosure
statements). Barnes reported net worth of $7,662,430 (down nearly
$2 million from his last report) and annual income of $722,231. He
paid $196,405 in federal taxes and $31,280 in state taxes.
Disclosure follows recent AG's ruling that Barnes must fully
disclose, despite having his assets in a blind trust. (Pruitt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ ANDREWS, N.C._ Will there be mourning in the T-shirt
shops, or hoots of joy from residents getting their privacy back?
Whichever, we'll be there monitoring the downsizing of the Rudolph
search operation, as agents move from a factory-sized compound into
a token presence is a small office. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOROWITZ _ WEST PLAM BEACH, Fla. _ A warrant is out for the
arrest of former suburban Boca Raton adoption lawyer Stuart Gordon
Horowitz, who resigned the bar amid charges his mishandling of
several adoptions left a trail of heartache in South Florida and
the Treasure Coast, legally walked away from more than $2.5 million
in debts, bankruptcy court records show. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-INSPECTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ In a ruling that could undermine
the new federal system of inspecting meat and poultry, a federal
appeals court Friday struck down an experimental program in Alabama
in which company employees inspect chickens. Federal law requires
government employees to perform the inspections, the ruling said.
(Montgomery, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN location Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S &QR; 
Government
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LULAC _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore addresses the
League of United Latin American Citizens. (Shepard, Cox News
Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on the NYT wire in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-TESTS _ CHICAGO _ Teachers from across the country
discuss whether to assist or resist the trend toward using tough,
state-mandated tests to determine the future not just of their
students, but of the teachers themselves. The 2-day conference on
high-stakes testing precedes the NEA convention. (Mollison, Cox
News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION _ ATLANTA _ NASA declared this week that the
cornerstone of the International Space Station, the long-delayed
Russian-built service module, is finally ready to go _ a critical
step in what space agency Administrator Daniel Goldin says will be
a ``landmark'' year in a project that is 10 years late and tens of
billions of dollars over budget. (Toner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   GACITIES-SMOG _ ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes is expected to send a
letter today (Friday) to the EPA asking that Macon, Columbus,
Augusta and eight additional counties in metro Atlanta counties be
added to the list of areas in violation of federal smog standards.
The official designation probably won't be made by the agency until
the end of this year. But it means that new areas will likely face
the same kind of stringent measures _ such as auto emission
inspections and submittal of regional traffic plans _ that 13 metro
Atlanta counties have been under for years to clean up the smoggy
air. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 17.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH_MEXICO _ Like most government officials in the United
States, Gov. GW Bush's dealings with Mexico have been with leaders
of the PRI. What happens if PAN candidate Vicente Fox prevails in
the Mexican presidential election? (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BUSHPRI _ Gov. George W. Bush touts his good relationship with
Mexican officials as proof of his international abilities. But the
governor's in with officials from the ruling PRI party, which is
facing serious election challenges this year. What happens to Bush
if the PRI loses the July 2 election? (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   PERFECTSTORM _ The special effects for summer blockbuster ``The
Perfect Storm'' were whipped up on a movie set in Los Angeles. But
on October 30, 1991, nature was directing all the action off the
coast of New England as the storm that spawned the movie reached
the peak of its fury. There really was a perfect storm. It really
did sink the Andrea Gail and all hands aboard. And there really
were 100 foot waves. And at the time, however, the National Weather
Service had as difficult a time convincing peop POL-TICKER _ A
brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from Cox staff
and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-DOME _ LONDON _ The New Year's fanfare is long over. And
now it can be made official, the Millennium Dome is a disaster. In
fact, it is so bad that the British government would close it if it
had the 200 million pounds to shut it down. It is truly awful, so
bad that even a new manager from Euro Disney has been unable to
generate any interest in it. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., June 28, on the NYT Wire in (i) International
and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ The Boy Scouts have a
constitutional right, according to a narrow 5-4 Supreme Court vote,
to give the boot to homosexual scoutmasters. The next president's
Supreme Court appointments could overturn Wednesday's decision. I
don't know if George W. Bush or Al Gore were Boy Scouts or if they
would use a ``Gay Scout'' litmus test for their Supreme Court
appointments. I do know that I was a Boy Scout and that I had a
homosexual scoutmaster. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _
ATLANTA _ We gathered at the little Inman Methodist Church as we
have too often in recent years, to say goodbye to our Aunt Ida Mae,
who would have celebrated her 93rd birthday on Dec. 1. We are
fortunate in funerals. Our cousin, Don Harp, is a preacher. He
knows exactly what to say when a family member crosses the Jordan.
One of the things he pointed out at Aunt Ida Mae's funeral was that
we are running out of what Tom Brokaw and a lot of us think of as
The Greatest Generation. ``Who among us is going to take their
place?'' Don asked. It is a worrisome question. (Jim Minter is a
former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The mother of the victim arrived
on the crime scene at the same moment I did. Supported on either
side by friends, Keith Watson's mother approached the yellow tape,
shaking and sobbing, ``I want to see my baby. I want to see my
baby.'' ``You can't come this way, ma'am,'' an officer directed
her, then became silent, as understanding dawned: This is the
mother. Hugging herself, she cried, ``No! No! No!'' as her friends
delivered her into the waiting arms of her family. (McCarty, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-ADS _ Try an unlikely place - Chick-fil-A.
</P>
<P>
   The College Park restaurant chain has fired off a letter to
fast-food rival Burger King asking it to stop using a promotion for
the hit movie 'Chicken Run.'' Chick-fil-A claims spots in the
promotion closely imitate the theme for the popular cow campaign.
``The cows were the ones who told us about it, but they didn't have
a lawyer in the stable,'' said spokesman Don Perry. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOWDOW _ The stock market's worst performance in six years came
to a close on Friday as the first half ended, leaving investors in
a mood of shaky confidence that the worst of the spring sell-off is
over. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HALFWAY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Some couples are splitting the
difference when it comes to commuting and living in one of the
towns and communities halfway between San Antonio and Austin.
Besides closer commuting for both parties, areas such as San Marcos
and New Braunfels have cheaper houses on the market. (Poe, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   E-SIGNATURE _ WASHINGTON _ When a new law allowing electronic
signatures on commercial contacts is signed (and then e-signed)
into law by President Clinton on Friday, will it usher in a golden
age of electronic commerce? Experts discuss the prospects. (Geewax,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving on NYT wire in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-TEXAS _ SBC Communications is on the brink of receiving
federal approval to offer long-distance calling in Texas, which
would mark only the second time a regional Bell telephone company
has secured permission to provide that service to its local
customers. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPEEDWAY _ TALLAHASSEE _ Jeb Bush decides a day before the Pepsi
400 to award $2 million to Daytona International Speedway, a
private corporation, to build a pedestrian overpass. Last year Bush
vetoed a $3 million line item for the same project and in March, he
indicated his disapproval for a $1.5-million line item in this
year's budget, despite a visit from NASCAR scion Bill France Jr. So
why did Jeb change his mind? He says it's good for economic
development. Coincidentally, his brother and presidential candidate
George W. is the race grand marshal this year. (Date, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in Sports (s) category
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-MAZDA626 _ Russ test drives the Mazda 626. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   MORMONS-HINCKLEY _ SALT LAKE CITY _ Mormon president Gordon
Hinckley turns 90 with a birthday bash that includes Atlanta native
Gladys Knight singing with the Mormon Tabernacle choir. In an
exclusive interview on his birthday, we ask Hinckley about how and
why he has taken the church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
more public during his tenure, and ask him about Mormon growth
around the world, especially in the Southeast. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-LOVE _ True love may wait, but Bill Hayes couldn't. Yes, he
promised back in 1993 to postpone having sex until he was married.
And yes, he held hands with hundreds of other young Christians at
The King's Academy in West Palm Beach and pledged to stay pure. He
even signed a True Love Waits card with the sincerest of
intentions. But that was when he was just 16, before he fell in
love for the first time. ``I didn't plan it or anything,'' said
Hayes, now 23. ``We were dating for nine months. I really cared
about her.'' The moral of this story, supporters of abstinence
programs will tell you, is not that Hayes failed to live up to his
commitment _ though they condemn his failure. It's that abstinence
until marriage has become a socially acceptable standard that Hayes
and other teenagers have set for themselves since they began their
campaign, a movement that has found its way into public school sex
education curriculums. And therein lies their victory. And the
controversy. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DRAGONCON _ Living long and prospering, Star Trekkies beam into
Atlanta this week for the sci-fi convention, ``Dragon Con.'' We get
a behind-the-scenes look at the confab, including a screening of
the new film, ``Trekkies,'' and get Trekkies' views on the
lampooning they take. (Licklighter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ROCKER _ NEW YORK _ Following the John Rocker saga in New
York. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TOUR DE FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-LANCE _ Feature story on defending Tour de France
champion Lance Armstrong. Tour director Jean Marie LeBlanc calls
Armstrong the best winner the Tour can imagine. ``The rebirth of
Armstrong is amazing and is good for the rebirth of the Tour,''
LeBlanc said. (Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman). 36.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-STRATEGY _ As the U.S. Postal Service riders gathered
at Futuroscope for the start of the Tour de France, Austinite Kevin
Livingston was asked via telephone about the team's strategy. ``The
overall plan is to get into Paris with Lance wearing the yellow
jersey,'' Livingston chuckled. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-COMPETE _ Some well-known cyclists claim that defending
Tour de France champion Lance Armstrong's recent achievements are
that monumental. These cyclists, including French hero Laurent
Jalabert, claim it was Armstrong's unique preparation and not his
immense talent that got him his incredible Tour win in 1999.
(Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman). 37.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-CONTENDERS _ The 1999 Tour de France field wasn't
considered strong, that for the first time in 43 years there was no
defending champion. This year's field, however, is strong and will
include two other Tour champions joining Austin's Lance Armstrong,
the 1999 victor. Armstrong still is clearly the favorite, but he
should be pressed more than last year when he finished with a
7-minute, 37-second cushion over runner-up Alex Zulle. Armstrong's
margin of victory was the fourth largest posted in the past 20
years. (Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman). 21. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-FATIGUE _ The Tour de France is the most physically
demanding major sporting event in the world. It's tortuous mountain
climbs and desperate sprints contested over 2,255.7 miles and 21
stages. It's hearts pounding as fast as 200 beats per minute and
legs continuing to churn when they sear with the will-sapping
lactic acid of fatigue. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman). 21.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-JULICH _ Bio/short story on Bobby Julich, a Texan
riding in the Tour. (Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman). 4.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-ROSTER _ Roster and very brief bios on the nine-person
Postal Service Team. (Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman).
(w/mugs of all riders)
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS _ Two graphics: Full-page color graphic on the tour
course with stage information, the teams entered, glossary of
terms, how a racing bike is constructed and, of course, a map.
Also, a graphic of Lance Armstrong that details his typical day
during the Tour. Artists: Robert Calzada and Don Tate.
</P>
