<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An expanding area with mainly clear and pleasant conditions will
dominate the nation east of the Mississippi River. High pressure
centered over West Virginia will promote sunshine and near seasonal
temperatures from the Carolinas to Maine. The return circulation of
warmer air into the Plains will be accompanied by patches of
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms will develop over Minnesota and western
Michigan as a front pushes into the upper Great Lakes. A stalled
front from Florida to Texas will be the focus of thick clouds and
showers. A few strong storms may develop over Central Texas and
south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will dominate the northern and central Rockies, but
thunderstorms will develop later in the day as cooler air moves in
from the Pacific. The monsoon in the Southwest will be active with
numerous storms in Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WETTEST MONTH
</P>
<P>
   In Rochester, Minn., last month, the amount of rain fell as it
never had before. A total of 12.50 inches of rain were measured at
the city's airport, making June 2000 the wettest month on record in
Rochester. The previous record was 12.33 inches in July 1978. Of
course, weather anomalies are constantly occurring around the
globe. While the unusual wetness around Rochester occurred at an
official reporting site, countless weather anomalies go unreported
because they happen over oceans or sparsely populated land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
