<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9754 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OPRAH-LADN &LR;      06-30 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORY OF O
</HEADLINE>
  Winfrey talks to her fans 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They came in pairs, threes and larger groups, in minivans and
SUVs, dressed in their nicest clothes _ not the fanciest, but the
most put-together.
</P>
<P>
   They were looking for the secrets to living in the moment,
curing themselves of ``the disease to please,'' learning how to put
themselves first _ at least some of the time.
</P>
<P>
   They came to see Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey, the self-described ``colored girl from
Mississippi'' who rose to television stardom through her own
determination, the media mogul with the Midas touch for nearly
every venture she pursues, a woman who readily laughs and sometimes
cries during her daily talk show, making her viewers do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey brought her sold-out Personal Growth Summit to the
6,300-seat Shrine Auditorium on Thursday night, the final stop
following other one-night appearances in Detroit, Atlanta and
Chicago. She talked without rest for more than an hour, then
fielded questions from the audience for another hour.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of the summits mirrors the tone of her new O
magazine and her somewhat reinvented top-rated talk show: Helping
people _ mainly women _ find the best in themselves and discover
their own happiness.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was set with up-tempo Motown tunes and slides showing
inspirational words from Ralph Waldo Emerson, Eleanor Roosevelt,
Benazir Bhutto and even Joe E. Lewis. &QL; 
--Oprah on taking time each day for meditation or introspection:
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself first so that you can DO for the rest of the
world. If you can't give yourself a minute (that will improve
everything else in your life), then shut up. Stop complaining.'' &QL; 
Winfrey, dressed in a striking red floor-length evening coat,
frequently spoke off the cuff, occasionally visiting a Lucite
podium centerstage and even less often resting her spike-heeled
feet in an upholstered chair. &QL; 
--Oprah on self-awareness:
</P>
<P>
   ``Each trial in your life is there to show you who you really
are. It's the world standing outside you yelling that you are
broke, you are diseased, you are not worthy, and it's up to you to
go inside yourself, to be strong enough inside yourself to say,
`This is who I am.''' &QL; 
She spent much of the time pacing or meandering across the broad
proscenium, hitting on mantra-like key phrases and backing them up
with humorous and sometimes poignant personal anecdotes as well as
snippets of poetry and pearls of wisdom from celebrated
philosophers. She also brought her acting skills into play as she
characterized her grandmother, her father, ex-slave Sojourner Truth
addressing a suffragette gathering, the plaintiff's attorney in her
Texas beef market trial, and a few colorful fans she has met. &QL; 
--Oprah on intentions:
</P>
<P>
   ``When the person asks the question, don't just say `yes' before
it gets out of their mouth. ... What is your definition of `nice'?
For me it boiled down to being accommodating, the disease to
please.''
</P>
<P>
   When solicited by charities, she now says, ``Let me get back to
you.'' Then she ponders her intention: Would she be writing that
check to make the individual happy? To be perceived as generous? If
the charity itself and the good the money could do for it are not
among her initial reactions, she said she declines. (She made no
mention of the $10 million gift she made the day before to A Better
Chance, an organization that provides educational opportunities to
academically gifted minority students.) &QL; 
There was no doubt she was preaching to the converted, just as
political candidates and itinerate evangelists have always done.
Several remarks elicited replies of ``amen'' and ``uh-huh'' as
could be heard in a Baptist church service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Oprah on relationships:
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone shows you who they are, believe them the first
time. The lesson is to try to surround yourself with people who are
going to lift you up, not people you know are toxic.'' &QL; 
Even before the program, women in the audience were speaking her
language. Lynda Roberts of Huntington Beach came with her three
grown daughters, Laura, Renee and Carrie. ``We want to live our
best life,'' Roberts said. ``We talked about it on the way, all the
improvements we want to make, and we hope to be inspired
tonight.'' &QL; 
--Oprah on life's possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what happened to me isn't a miracle, it's a possibility
for anybody who chooses. And that doesn't mean you'll have a talk
show. It means you find your own calling.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the power of one human being to be able to change
the face of the planet,'' Winfrey said toward the end of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   But she did not profess to have all the answers, any foolproof
guide to life. ``I don't speak as a therapist or any kind of
authority, but as a friend with something to share.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
