<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9760 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-DUMMY-FILMING-$ADV02-     06-30 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUMMY-FILMING-$ADV02-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, ACTION ... COSTUMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mosquitoes zoomed in squadron-style as dusk curtained
Whitestone, Queens. Paranoia suddenly seemed to fill the air with
their sinister whine. In recent news accounts, this area had become
identified with ground zero for West Nile virus: a local chicken
had reportedly become infected with the disease. As it would later
develop, the chicken was in the clear. But the actors filming the
new indie movie ``Dummy'' had no way of knowing that. They were not
leaving flesh to fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting devoured,'' the actor Adrien Brody said, hiking
the legs of his geek high-water pants and letting rip with a spray
can of Off. Perched in a director's chair, Illeana Douglas swabbed
Muskol on her naked forearms. On a lawn in front of a
``Sopranos''-style colonial house, Milla Jovovich engaged her
boyfriend, John Frusciante, the guitarist of the Red Hot Chili
Peppers, in a bug-proof lip lock.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Moments later Frusciante was walking around the snack table
dazedly, complaining that his mouth had gone numb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suck on one of these, honey,'' said Verna Hampton, a caterer
who owns Verna's Vittles. Then she handed him one of the Blow Pops
she had brought, ``to calm the masses,'' as she explained.
</P>
<P>
   There were no masses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   There was a skeleton crew. There was a producer who drove to the
set in a banged-up Golf. There was an unknown 29-year-old
writer-director. There was a small cast of actors with unorthodox
professional trajectories and Next Big Thing bios, all working for
union scale.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a local family parading up and down 159th Street
with a 4-year-old got up in tights and a cape. ``See that kid
dressed as Batman?'' Gregory Pritikin, the director, asked. ``He
was Superman 20 minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do Spider-Man, too, if you need him,'' the father
called out.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of Steven Schoichet, a maladroit suburbanite whose life
is transformed when he comes into possession of a ventriloquist's
prop, ``Dummy'' is the kind of movie Charlie McCarthy might have
starred in if Michael Ovitz had been his agent. Nearly everyone
else in the film is a client of Ovitz's firm, Artists Management
Group, a noncoincidence that helps explain how a script by an
obscure writer with a budget that wouldn't buy a two-bedroom in
Chelsea happened to get this far.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' said the English actor Jared Harris, who is part
of the ``Dummy'' ensemble, ``Adrien was interested in doing it and
AMG helped it to happen. It's not as if they're shoving actors down
producers' throats.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A favorite of directors (at 27 he has already made films with
Spike Lee, Steven Soderbergh, Terrence Malick and Ken Loach), Brody
plays the lead role. Douglas is his older sister, a ``bitter
wedding planner who wants to sing,'' she explained. Jovovich is a
riot-grrrl type poetically named Fangora. Steven's crush, Lorena,
is portrayed by Vera Farmiga, a newcomer whose anonymity should end
by August, when three movies in which she acted _ with Robert De
Niro, Edward Burns and Richard Gere _ are released.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer code for films like ``Dummmy'' is ``quirky,'' a cliche
that translates as, ``Where's Blockbuster going to file this one?''
Directors claim to hate the term. Actors say it trivializes their
range. But ``genius'' is about the only word directors enjoy seeing
attached to their work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A reporter on the set of ``Dummy'' found himself wondering how
performers get into their parts, how they inhabit characters who,
say, live in demented households, talk through dummies, sing in
rock groups called the Botanical Booger Ensemble and
surreptitiously smash gifts at the weddings they stage. The visitor
arrived expecting Stanislavskian responses. The answers he got ran
to a simpler concept: costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I think about with a character is how much
money they make a year,'' said Douglas, who was not on call but was
visiting the set to lend support. ``Then you know how they dress,
and you don't put them in clothes they can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, Harris and Farmiga all made similar points about
interpretation, not to mention, indirectly, about class.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clothes are always very much in step with who the character
is,'' said Brody, whose spiked Mohawk nearly upstaged his
performance in Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam.'' ``For `Dummy,' we
tried to find any article that could look boyish or could have been
from his childhood wardrobe. Anything that was stylish we
removed.'' Farmiga imagined her character, Lorena, as cautious,
shy, hesitant, meek _ did someone say a dormouse?
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably shops at Daffy's or Fashion Bug or Annie Sez,''
Farmiga said. ``We bought her shoes at Payless. And it all really
influences the way you play the part because, for one thing, the
shoes put your posture in a certain position and force you to walk
in a certain way.''
</P>
<P>
   When an actor is in the right clothes, Harris said, ``it gets
you a long way'' toward capturing the character. In Solondz's
``Happiness,'' Harris disappeared so deeply into the role of the
wife-beating, womanizing, sleazeball Russian cabdriver that people
who barely recognized him in the movie still talk to him about his
character's '70s-style fake-snakeskin shirt.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``When you've got the visual right, subconsciously you're
already hitting certain marks about the character,'' Harris said.
``After `Happiness,' people came up to me and said: `That shirt!
Brilliant!'''
</P>
<P>
   The clothes Douglas wears as Heidi Schoichet are ``slightly
incongruous for her surroundings,'' she said. ``Slightly vintagey,
very bright colors, nothing fits very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas herself had on snug yellow stretch hip-huggers, yellow
Converse All Stars and a midriff-revealing T-shirt bought at the
Beverly Center in Los Angeles. A puppy was pictured on the front,
beneath a legend that read ``Too Cute.'' Waiting for the crew to
set up a shot, she and Pritikin also talked clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guayabera,'' the director said of his shirt, a type
common in Latin American countries. ``It's from Guayabera, a small
island off Chicago. Typically, I wear shirts that come with lots of
pockets. This one has just two, so it's a mutant, irregular. It
doesn't look like it fits properly because they never do. Still,
I'm really glad I found one that makes me look like a barber.''
</P>
<P>
   The wooden clothespins clipped to the pocket? ``I always
accessorize with clothespins,'' Pritikin said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas added, ``Everyone on movie sets has them, although I
never saw one outside my childhood until I started making films.''
</P>
<P>
   You see all kinds of things you never expected on the sets of
movies. Take, for example, the sight of Jovovich, supermodel, and
Frusciante, rock star, with their feet hooked behind their heads,
practicing yoga on someone's front lawn. Frusciante is an
alternately coruscating and delicate guitarist who once left the
Chili Peppers to pursue some career alternatives that brought him
within Kubler-Ross distance of dying, then abruptly cleaned up,
returned to the group, and can now discourse extensively on
ashtanga yoga. Jovovich, of course, is the L'Oreal face who started
modeling at 11, was doing Avedon covers for Vogue four years later
and then transformed herself into an eerily plausible alien in Luc
Besson's science fiction mess, ``The Fifth Element,'' en route to
becoming a cross-dressing 15th-century farm girl in ``The
Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest surprise on this movie has probably been Milla,''
Pritikin said. ``You wouldn't think it to look at her, but she's
one of the funniest, most spontaneous, quick-witted people. She's a
regular Shemp Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Jovovich could have raided the Three Stooges' closet
for her role as Fangora. Her outfit for the night's shot, a
stalker-style courtship raid she helps Steven make on Lorena's
house, involved a pair of Army fatigues, some pointy-toe shoes with
bows on the vamp and a knit Guatemalan ski mask that the film's
costume designer, Marie Abma, had found at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I really wanted to think about with Fangora,''
Jovovich said, ``is how cool is she? She's a total dork, but she's
also the coolest person in town.'' A tomboy ``who's never had a
boyfriend,'' Fangora is still a virgin, Jovovich explained, ``and
hasn't really got a style.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Fangora not only has abundant style, but also style of
a pretty specific sort: punk chick circa early Exene Cervenka.
``She goes out in these crazy outfits like an `I Love New York'
T-shirt that we drew on with a picture of a guy shooting a gun,''
Jovovich said. ``Then she wears a frilly, cupcakey old green prom
dress, with a garter and fishnets that I put my head through the
legs of, and some lady shoes that she probably stole. She wears a
shell-pink sequined cape with horns. Fangora's extrovertedness is a
defense, but you walk with your head held high in this life, people
will believe it. Fangora's a complete nimrod. But you see her on
film, and she really rocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
