   DROUGHT-REMINISCENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Raised in West Texas, a reporter's childhood was
indelibly branded by the terrible seven-year drought of the 1950s.
During a drought there is always some rain _ just never enough. She
can clearly recall the first time she saw rain. Her brother said it
was only a tease, but looking back now she sees it as a promise. By
MARY ROGERS. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-BOREDOM BUSTERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Network reruns running you down? We feel your pain. So
what better time to explore cable's netherworld of hidden
treasures, those underappreciated morsels you usually channel-surf
right by on your mad dash to catch ``Friends,'' ``ER'' and ``Who
Wants To Be a Millionaire''? These easy-to-miss specialty delights
run the gamut, from bizarre to bold, smart to silly, sexy to
salacious. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PATRIOT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The British are fuming! The British are fuming! And
you can blame most of it on Jason Isaacs' performance as the
sadistic Col. William Tavington in Columbia Pictures' new
revolutionary war epic ``The Patriot,'' starring Mel Gibson. But
Liverpool, England, native Issacs couldn't be more pleased with his
home turf's ruffled feathers. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIANA ROSS-TOUR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ For the first time in 30 years, Diana Ross and the
Supremes are on the road again _ only this time, the Detroit diva
is taking along two second-stringers, and charging up to $250 for
the best seats. And the public is staying away in droves. Pop music
critic Dave Ferman looks at the faltering Return to Love tour _ and
what a genuine event it could have been. By DAVE FERMAN. Story has
moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
