<P>
   WRIGHT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ For my generation, the 50th anniversary of the stormy
attack that began the Korean War brings uncomfortable reminders. At
the same time, news photographs of North and South Korean leaders
talking and actually embracing in Pyongyang after half a century of
estrangement bring fresh breezes of hope. The Korean conflict, for
us, came too soon after World War II. It rudely interrupted
America's postwar idyll. And it tarnished our new self-image of
unquestioned military supremacy. But that war also taught us some
useful lessons about the need, use and limits of American power. By
JIM WRIGHT. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
