<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRUNDYSIDE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deciding to move an entire town pits safety against strong
emotion
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The residents of Grundy, Va., are not the first folks forced to
pack up their town and move to higher ground. In Soldiers Grove,
Wis., and English, Ky., in Pattonsburg, Mo., and Valmeyer, Ill.,
the local citizens, fed up with decades of devastating floods,
finally abandoned their soggy homes to rebuild in dryer locations.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups applaud such relocation efforts as a more
sensible _ and less expensive _ alternative to building more levees
and rebuilding damaged buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disasters cost and cost and cost,'' says Mary Hudak, a
spokeswoman for the Atlanta office of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency. ``Getting people out of harm's way is a better
way. The people in Grundy are in a very vulnerable area because of
the floods every 20 years or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to move usually is left in the hands of the
townspeople, Hudak says. And, in some cases, such as in
Princeville, N.C., they decide not to move.
</P>
<P>
   The historic North Carolina town of 2,100 was nearly swept away
last September when Hurricane Floyd came through and destroyed
nearly two-thirds of the 600 homes and damaged most of the downtown
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Given an opportunity to move the town that was founded by freed
slaves in 1885, the citizens voted to stay. The 20-foot earthen
dike along the Tar River has been shored up and the downtown
business district is being revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our heritage, and this is where we plan to stay,''
Mayor Delia Perkins said shortly after the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak admits emotional issues often outweigh the economic ones.
``Our thoughts were, `Why put yourself in a place where you would
be vulnerable again?' But it was their choice. And there is a loss
of that sense of community when a town is relocated. That's what
they wrestled with in Princeville. In the end, they decided to stay
because they said their ancestors had struggled with things far
greater than a flood.''
</P>
<P>
   _Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
