<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-ROUNDUP-$ADV02-     06-30 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ROUNDUP-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ODD ALLIANCES SHOW UP IN JUSTICES' RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 2)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a term filled with emotionally charged cases,
several Supreme Court justices jumped ideological fences,
reflecting conflicts that the public still has with such issues as
abortion, police power and separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the social issues, the only consistency was inconsistency,
much like the country itself,'' said David Garrow, a law professor
at Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the jurists have often divided into ideological
camps with Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justices Antonin
Scalia and Clarence Thomas on the conservative side and Justices
John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Stephen Breyer and David
Souter on the more liberal side. Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and
Anthony Kennedy have been the swing votes.
</P>
<P>
   But during this term the conservative Thomas surprised many
court-watchers when he joined with Stevens, Souter and Ginsburg as
well as Kennedy in a cable TV ruling. The five voted to strike down
a law requiring cable companies to either completely scramble or
take off the air sexually explicit broadcasts during hours when
children might see them.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing the unusual five-some were conservatives William
Rehnquist and Antonin Scalia, moderate Sandra Day O'Connor and
liberal Stephen Breyer, who argued that the restrictions were
proper.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, the conservative Scalia lectured the liberal
Breyer on the importance of an undiminished right to trial by jury
for a defendant accused of a hate crime. In a 5-4 ruling, the court
said that juries, not judges, must decide whether those guilty of
violence were motivated by bias and therefore subject to longer
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   However, later in the term, Scalia and Breyer teamed up to
defend the right of federal agents looking for illegal drugs to
squeeze bus passengers' carry-on bags. The other seven justices
ruled that such searches were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was term where it was extremely difficult to know where
each justice would come out on any particular case,'' said Daniel
Troy, an expert on the court at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute here. ``On some of the biggest cases of the
year, the court surprised a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although all the justices but Breyer and Ginsburg were
appointed by Republican presidents, the court reaffirmed three of
the most controversial decisions of earlier, more liberal Supreme
Courts. These rulings involved abortion, school prayer and the
Miranda rule requiring that suspects be told of their rights to
remain silent and to have an attorney during police questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning surprise of the term came when Rehnquist broke
ranks with his fellow conservatives and wrote the majority opinion
upholding the 1966 Miranda decision. His action led to the term's
most bitter split among traditional allies. In his opinion for the
seven-member majority, Rehnquist said the Miranda rule was so
embedded in America's culture and so rooted in the Constitution
that Congress could not legally overturn it with a less-stringent
1968 law.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice's switch enraged Scalia, who along with
Thomas, called the original Miranda ruling ``judicial arrogance''
and accused Rehnquist of turning his back on his own previous
criticisms of Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also surprised court experts when they affirmed
1962 and 1963 Supreme Court decisions barring prayer in school. In
a Texas case the court ruled, 6-3, that a school district violated
the Constitution by allowing a student to lead prayers before high
school football games.
</P>
<P>
   With Rehnquist, Scalia and Thomas dissenting, swing voters
O'Connor and Kennedy joined the more liberal justices to say that
the local school board was giving preferential treatment to a
particular religious viewpoint by granting the student the right to
use the school's public address system at a school-sponsored event.
</P>
<P>
   However, in another religion case, the court, by a 6-3 vote,
went the other way and broke down part of the wall separating
church and state. This time the swing voters as well as Breyer
jumped to the conservative side, ruling that the federal government
may lend computers and other educational equipment to parochial
schools. The decision _ which overturned two previous cases
limiting government aid to religious schools _ came amid a
politically charged, nationwide controversy over allowing students
to use taxpayer-supported vouchers to attend private schools,
including religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, the court finally voted in a way that many
expected. In a 5-4 decision, it struck down Nebraska's ban on
so-called ``partial-birth'' abortions, jeopardizing similar
restrictions in 29 other states. The justices, with O'Connor
joining the more liberal justices and Kennedy joining the
conservatives, said the Nebraska ban was too broadly written and
violated a woman's right to end her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Court scholars said that besides abortion, the only issue where
the justices took their traditional ideological stances this term
was the question of federal vs. state power.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six years, the Rehnquist-led court steadily has
chipped away at the power of the federal government to impose its
will on the states.
</P>
<P>
   In a Florida case the court ruled 5-4 that state workers
alleging age discrimination may not sue their employers under a
federal law because states are immune from federal lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In another 5-4 decision, the court said Congress exceeded its
power when it passed a section of the Violence Against Women Act
giving victims a right to sue their attackers in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Following are the high court's major decisions in other
categories:
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL LIBERTIES:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Washington state law allowing grandparents or others to sue
for the right to visit a child ``at any time'' illegally infringes
on parents' rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 6.2-million-member Boy Scouts of America is a private
organization and may therefore bar openly gay people from serving
as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE POWER:
</P>
<P>
   _ Police may stop and frisk suspects who run away at the sight
of an officer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Police may not stop and frisk someone based on an anonymous
tip that hasn't been confirmed independently.
</P>
<P>
   FREE SPEECH:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cities may ban nudity in night clubs that feature erotic
dancing in cases where there are ``harmful'' effects on the
community.
</P>
<P>
   _ Public universities can force students to pay fees even when
some of the money raised goes to organizations they find
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   _ States may force abortion protesters to keep at least eight
feet away from women entering health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   _ A state law barring individuals from giving more than $1,075
to a political candidate per election does not violate free speech
rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ California's free-for-all primary election system, which
allowed voters to choose candidates without regard to party
affiliation, violates the rights of political parties to define
their own message and decide their own candidates.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL REGULATIONS:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Food and Drug Administration lacks the power to regulate
the manufacture and sale of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   _ People injured in auto crashes may not use a federal law to
sue automakers for not installing airbags when they were not
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patients may not use a federal law to sue health maintenance
organizations for giving doctors financial bonuses to hold down
treatment costs.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL:
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington and other coastal states may not add their own
regulations to federal safety rules for huge oil tankers operating
in their waters.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Massachusetts law aimed at boycotting companies that do
business with Myanmar, also known as Burma, treads illegally on
existing federal sanctions. It compromises the president's ability
to speak for the nation with one voice in dealing with other
governments.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
