<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DIGITAL-COLUMN-LADN &LR;      06-30 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE FUTURE LOOKING DANGEROUS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Joy's career has been about linking people through
technology, developing a key version of the Unix computer language,
as well as the more recent Java and Jini languages. But perhaps
nothing has created a set of connections, of leaps across
boundaries, so fast, with such an amazing array of people, as his
recently published ``Why the Future Doesn't Need Us'' in Wired
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It is Joy's lengthy, thoughtful consideration of where
technology may take us, especially if we don't pay attention as
developments coalesce in genetic manipulation, nanotechnology and
robotics (GNR, in his parlance).
</P>
<P>
   Together, he argued, GNR could result in threats to the species'
future even worse than the ones the world has faced from
biological, chemical and nuclear weapons. He suggested we may, as a
species, want to decide against pursuing some areas of research,
because the potential for disaster is so great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it is always hard to see the bigger impact while you
are in the vortex of a change,'' Joy wrote. ``Failing to understand
the consequences of our inventions while we are in the rapture of
discovery and innovation seems to be a common fault of scientists
and technologists.'' In a week when publicly funded researchers in
several countries and a private company finished mapping the 3.1
billion bits of DNA that comprise the human genome, the piece is
worth pondering (go to www.wired.com/wired/archive/8.04).
</P>
<P>
   Joy talks about his essential optimism about science and the
future, and his growing concern that the optimism is misplaced.
Based on reaction since the piece came out, Joy is far from the
only one concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of latent anxiety on the part of people about
what the future holds,'' said Wired editor in chief Katrina Heron.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the piece's publication, the magazine began
receiving some of the dozens of responses published in this month's
issue, from game designers, software engineers, professors,
historians, ministers, authors, two Nobel laureates, two Dysons
(historian George and physicist father Freeman), even a class of
14-year-olds from a small Italian village.
</P>
<P>
   And the reactions have continued, from all directions, Heron
said. Among the people who have contacted Joy were President
Clinton, several members of Congress and others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wired has set up an e-mail address, whythefuturewired.com ``so
that readers can receive updates and alerts on issues related to
the article,'' Heron wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the hope is that it will spark a growing national and
international discussion that will be part governmental in
nature,'' Heron said. ``There are very different groups of people
who need to discuss this, need to discuss it in discrete groups,
then have some sort of global discussion, because we're really in
this all together.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, those discussions have indeed begun. The World
Economic Forum began a colloquium on the subject, Harvard's Kennedy
School of Government pondered whether to set up a department on the
question, and the Los Angeles chapter of Physicians for Social
Responsibility gave Joy their Caldicott Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much that we agree with everything he's saying,''
said Jonathan Parfrey, executive director of the 2,700-member
group. ``The very fact that he is identifying things that could be
dangerous to human survival we found to be quite compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Parfrey likened Joy's piece to some of the warnings Albert
Einstein made in the years his theoretical work on the atom became
the underpinnings for creating nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Einstein said the splitting of the atom changes everything
except our way of thinking, therefore we drift toward unparalleled
catastrophe,'' Parfrey said. ``For a lot of these (current
scientific developments), the path leads back to Bill Joy. He is
now, like Einstein in his day, sending up a warning that there are
things to be worried over, and I think we should listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, when Joy spoke May 31 before the organization,
whose parent won the 1985 Nobel Peace Prize for its opposition to
nuclear weapons, reaction to his speech was divided, Parfrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sense there were people who were very much fascinated
by what he had to say,'' Parfrey said. ``At the same time, there
were people who were somewhat skeptical. When it comes to virtually
any of these really big questions, people can focus on the garbage
truck spewing diesel in the front yard, but can they really focus
on killer robots taking over the planet?''
</P>
<P>
   On such questions may the future ride. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
