<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: NAIL BOMBER SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   David Copeland, 24, a self-confessed fascist, was sentenced to
six life terms after a London jury found him guilty of three
murders in a series of bombings aimed at the city's gay and
nonwhite populations. The three deaths resulted from a nail bomb
that devastated a Soho gay bar and injured 139 people. The jury
rejected his defense of diminished responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ON-THE-SPOT FINES
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair said he would propose at a special
crime summit meeting at 10 Downing St. that police be given power
to march drunken rioters to cash machines and make them withdraw
$150 fines. English fans caused widespread disturbances in Belgium
last week in the Euro 2000 soccer tournament during a game between
England and Germany. Blair spoke at an ethics forum in Tubingen,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: EX-PREMIERS CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   Two former prime ministers supported each other and won
parliamentary votes that effectively killed investigations into
corruption charges against them. Tansu Ciller had been charged with
siphoning $71,000 from a discretionary fund while she was in
office, and Mesut Yilmaz was said to have sold mobile-phone
licenses at giveaway prices. Parliament voted down motions that
would have sent the cases to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: SECESSION BILL PASSES
</P>
<P>
   Parliament has given final approval to a bill that will make it
harder for Quebec to secede if there is ever a third referendum
there. The bill authorizes the Commons to negotiate a province's
secession only after a referendum vote where the option of
independence is clearly stated and where secessionists win a clear
majority. Quebec separatists attacked it as a ``pseudo law'' that
sets up English-speaking Canada as a judge of a political process
that is internal to Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: 5,000 ORDERED OUT
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong court ruled that 5,000 mainland immigrants would
have to leave. The ruling adhered to the policy set by Beijing last
June, when it overturned a decision by Hong Kong's highest court
granting residency to mainland immigrants with at least one Hong
Kong parent. The ruling applied to immigrants who arrived in Hong
Kong after the first court decision, and claimed a right to
residency under it.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: CENSORSHIP LIFTED
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in a landmark case that censorship
imposed on an English-language weekly, The Sunday Leader, and a
sister publication was illegal and ordered that the paper be
reopened. It was closed for violating guidelines about reporting on
the war against separatist Tamil rebels. The court said the chief
censor had no authority to censor news reports or close the paper.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: LAND REFORM PLEA
</P>
<P>
   The head of the land restitution commission said a sizable
infusion of cash is essential if efforts to redistribute land to
poor blacks are to avoid confrontations like those in Zimbabwe. In
both countries, whites still control much of the most fertile land,
and since blacks won majority rule in Zimbabwe and South Africa,
land reform has been a pressing issue, with more than 63,000 claims
pending in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NETANYAHU ON RISE
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper poll of 590 people showed Benjamin Netanyahu, the
rightist former prime minister, beating Prime Minister Ehud Barak
by a significant margin _ 8 percent _ for the first time since
Barak beat Netanyahu and took office a year ago. According to the
Maariv-Gallup poll, Netanyahu would get 44 percent of the votes in
a new election, and Barak 36 percent, with 20 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CHINA PLANE PLEA
</P>
<P>
   A leading Cabinet member, Haim Ramon, said Israel should move to
halt the sale of a $250 million airborne radar system to China in
order to repair frayed ties with Washington. ``It is impossible to
postpone the deal,'' Ramon told Israeli Radio. Martin Indyk, the
U.S. ambassador to Israel, told Israeli legislators that
U.S.-Israeli ties would suffer if China got the plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
