<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-EAMES-EXHIBIT-LADN &LR;      06-30 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAMES-EXHIBIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTIC MAKES PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
 
 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were the power couple of modern design, working in their
Los Angeles studio from the 1940s through the '70s to create
furniture and artwork that embraced the technology of their age.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Ray Eames were husband and wife (not brothers, as
some think), and while the handsome Charles was most identified
with their designs, he was quick to point out his wife's
contribution. ``She is equally responsible with me for everything
that goes on here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than marble and oils, the couple turned to the materials
of their day _ plastics, fiberglass and plywood. Rather than a
singular work of art, it was functional furniture for the masses,
with an artistic sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Their ambition was to bring high design into every American
home. Nowhere is that ambition more evident than in those Eames
chairs _ the molded plywood chairs of 1940 and 1946, the
fiberglass-reinforced plastic armchair of 1949, the wire-mesh
chairs and wire sofa of the early 1950s, the black leather lounge
chair and ottoman of 1956. Many of the pieces are still being
manufactured today. The Ronald Reagan National Airport terminal in
Washington, D.C., has been lauded for its new look, but the chairs
in the waiting areas were designed by the Eameses back in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as C. Ford Peatross, the Library of Congress' curator
of Architecture, Design and Engineering Collections, pointed out,
``Almost everything the Eameses designed in terms of furniture is
still in production, or has come back into production.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's work, which also includes architectural projects,
product design, paintings and film production, is the subject of an
exhibition that runs until Sept. 20 at the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Eames was born in St. Louis in 1907, growing up in the
industrial Midwest. There he trained as an architect and became
fascinated with the manufacturing process and the properties of new
materials. His wife, Ray, was born in Sacramento in 1912, and
studied at several art schools in the East.
</P>
<P>
   So while he brought an engineering background to their work, she
brought one of color and flowing form. In 1941, the couple married
and moved to Los Angeles, where he took a job designing sets for
MGM. At night, the couple would experiment on creating an
inexpensive method for bending plywood in more than one direction.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the war ended, they set up their studio in L.A.,
which was their base for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Postwar America was a time of optimism that technology could
lead to a better life, and this mirrored the Eameses' own beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   With new advances in the molding process, the Eameses set out to
create a chair that was not only simple, comfortable and could be
mass-produced _ but which also had a whole new look, almost like a
sculpture. And you could plop yourself down on it.
</P>
<P>
   The chairs were a hit with the public. At the Museum of Modern
Art's 1946 show, ``New Furniture Designed by Charles Eames,'' one
of the chairs was placed in a transparent revolving drum and
allowed to bang about inside, to show its durability.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949 came the colorful plastic molded armchair that would
become common in homes, offices and schools. The design was quickly
imitated and is still in use today.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve of 1949, the couple moved into their now-famous
Eames House in Pacific Palisades, which was built from standardized
construction elements found in trade catalogs. The project was
begun shortly after the war, with Charles Eames collaborating with
architect-designer Eero Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   The steel-and-glass house has been described as Zen-like with
Mondrian colors, but as with the Eameses, it's hard to pin down.
Inside, the Eameses designed the furniture and even the eating
utensils.
</P>
<P>
   After 1955, the couple became involved in making educational
motion pictures, notably the classic ``Powers of Ten'' (1968),
which demonstrates the concept of orders of magnitude by
contrasting views from the Earth's surface with the universe's
edge, then back to an atom.
</P>
<P>
   Their involvement with big business _ corporations like IBM
would sponsor their work _ has been problematic for some critics.
The height of the Eameses' popularity was during the Cold War, so
some see them as emblems and ambassadors of capitalism rather than
as pure artists.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the Eameses banked on institutions that were
out to make a profit to help them with their vision of a
progressive future for the average Joe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, seven years before his death, Charles had second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a more efficient technology, and we got pesticides
in the soil. We wanted cars and television sets and appliances, and
each of us thought he was the only one wanting that. Our dreams
have come true at the expense of Lake Michigan. That doesn't mean
that the dreams were all wrong. It means that there was an error
somewhere in the wish, and we have to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Charles' death, Ray Eames continued to work on various
design projects until her death on Aug. 21, 1988, 10 years to the
day after her husband's.
</P>
<P>
   How much of the Eameses' influence remains? Well, there are
those chairs, of course. Today, some of what they created looks as
quaint and particular to its time as a Model T does to its. But
within the Eameses' colorful designs _ whether for a child's top or
a functional house _ a playful, joyous optimism and inventiveness
is evident.
</P>
<P>
   That spirit of creativity, which future artists will draw from,
is the Eameses' ultimate legacy and will endure even after all
their chairs have become museum pieces. &QL; 
----- &QL; 
What: ``The Work of Charles and Ray Eames: A Legacy of
Invention.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where: Los Angeles County Museum of Art, 5905 Wilshire Blvd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When: Museum hours are noon to 8 p.m. Monday, Tuesday and
Thursday; noon to 9 p.m. Friday; 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday; closed Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Adults are $7; students 18 and older with ID and senior
citizens over 62 are $5. Children and younger students are $1;
children 5 and younger are free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: (323) 857-6000 or www.lacma.org on the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
