<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CYC-TOUR-CONTENDERS07     06-30 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-CONTENDERS0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong field for this year's Tour de France
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ The 1999 Tour de France field wasn't
considered strong, given that for the first time in 43 years there
was no defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   A broken arm left 1996 Tour champion Bjarne Riis on the
sidelines. A knee injury wiped out Jan Ullrich, the 1997 champion
and 1998 runner-up. An embarrassing drug controversy knocked out
1998 winner Marco Pantani.
</P>
<P>
   Of the field of 180 riders, only Alex Zulle and Bobby Julich, a
Corpus Christi native, had ever finished on the Tour podium. And
Julich was knocked out of the three-week-long race after he crashed
in the eighth stage, a time trial in Metz in Northen France. His
arm and chest injuries were too severe for him to finish the
remaining 13 stages.
</P>
<P>
   This year's field, however, is strong and will include three
Tour champions, with Ullrich and Pantani joining Austin's Lance
Armstrong, the 1999 victor.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong still is clearly the favorite, but he should be
pressed more than last year when he finished with a 7-minute,
37-second cushion over runner-up Alex Zulle. Armstrong's margin of
victory was the fourth largest posted in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Count on the charasmatic Pantani to yank some of the limelight
from Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian, known as ``Il Pirata'' for his shaven head and
penchant for wearing colorful bandanas, is his country's most
popular athlete, edging Olympic skiing hero Alberto Tomba, and one
of the biggest names in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Pantani also is his country's most controversial athletic
figure.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for the slight 30-year-old came to a climax last
summer, during the Giro d' Italia, the second most glamorous
cycling event after the Tour. Pantani, wearing the race's pink
leader's jersey, held an overwhelming advantage on the next-to-last
day of the Giro. Only something unforeseen could keep him from
repeating as champion.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six hours before the scheduled end of the three-week-long
race, he was suspended after a drug test detected an abnormal level
of red blood cells in his system, indicating the use of the hormone
erythropoiten (EPO), a banned performance enhancing substance.
</P>
<P>
   He then announced he would not defend his 1998 Tour title,
claiming that the route was too flat and not conducive to his
riding style. Pantani's subsequent exile from cycling was a long
and emotionally torturous. During his time away, Pantani crashed
his car three times, broke up with his girlfriend of five years and
had a falling out with his family. He went into hiding in March,
saying that he was suffering from depression.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was secretly training for his sport's big races this
year, although he did not return to competition until the Giro.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly wasn't truly excited about competing until he had
an audience with Pope John Paul II at the Vatican City the day
before the Giro started. Pantani didn't win the Giro, but he did
well in the mountain stages to indicate he would be in excellent
form for France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've regained Pantani the man. As for Pantani the champion,
we'll see,'' said Felice Gimondi, president of Mercatone, Pantani's
team.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble still is tagging after Pantani.
</P>
<P>
   He faces trial in Italy after being charged with ``sporting
fraud'' in April. Italian judicial officials allege that Pantani,
in at least two instances, used EPO to boost his performance. He
denies the charge. The allegations go back five years, when doctors
discovered that he had an abnormally high level of red blood cells
in his system while he was treated for a broken leg at a hospital
in Turin, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, the German cycling star, has been plagued by injuries
and weight problems. But he also has been brilliant in the Tour,
sandwiching his victory 1997 at age 23 with runnerup finishes in
1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, who says he can't resist cream cakes, has been nine
pounds overweight this season, which is not much for the average
person. But the weight gain was debated in cycling circles,
considering that the most elite in the sport have only about 3
percent body fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no further problems with my weight,'' Ullrich told
Kicker, a European sports magazine. ``The matter is closed as far
as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich tuned up for the Tour with a nice performance in the
Tour de Suisse. He led for several stages before giving way in the
rougher, mountainous stages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
