<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0701-COX     06-30 1891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Measuring the hispanic vote
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore is leading George W. Bush by a 16-point margin among
Hispanic voters, the fastest-growing minority group in America and
one that could play a pivotal electoral role in some key states,
according to a Knight Ridder Newspapers poll released today.
Despite his lead _ nearly 50 percent to 34 percent nationwide _
Gore is getting far less support among Hispanics than Bill Clinton
got in each of his two presidential races. Some 16 percent of the
Hispanics in his own Democratic Party said they either will vote
for Bush or are leaning toward him. The same poll showed Hillary
Clinton leading Rick Lazio 63-21 percent among Hispanics in the New
York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN COURTING HISPANICS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain asked Hispanic voters to pick George W. Bush for
president, calling his former rival a leader on immigration with
``a well-earned reputation for reaching out to all his
constituents.'' Bush and McCain traded harsh words during their GOP
primary battle last winter, but McCain has said he'll campaign for
Bush now. He praised the Texas governor warmly _ and defended the
Republican Party's record _ in remarks to the League of United
Latin American Citizens in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   527S SHOT DOWN
</P>
<P>
   After a long losing streak, campaign finance reform scored its
biggest success when Congress closed a loophole that had enabled
so-called ``527'' tax-exempt political groups to raise millions of
dollars in secret contributions to influence national races.
President Clinton is expected to sign the bill. Fears that hoards
of secret cash could be deployed in the 2000 election cycle by the
527s _ named for the enabling section of the tax code _ spurred a
bipartisan effort to force them to disclose the source of funds
they use for advertising and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   LABORING FOR THE LABOR VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Republicans descend on Philadelphia in a month to nominate
George W. Bush for president, but some very important Democrats
were paying courtesy calls there this week: Al Gore and House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt several days ago; President Clinton
today. All three were there to speak to the national convention of
the 1.3 million-member American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees union. Clinton urged union workers to get out
the vote for Gore. ``The Republicans have given us the awfulest
mugging over the last 20 years,'' he said. ``And now they're all
acting like we're being mean and negative if we point out what
their positions are.''
</P>
<P>
   THE `TEXAS TRUTH SQUAD'
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO launched a series of town hall meetings to educate
members about life in Texas under their governor. ``You're hearing
a lot about what George W. Bush says he would do as president. But
it's time to hear about what he has done as governor of Texas,''
said AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. A teacher, a prison guard and
a retired food worker told about 100 union brethren at the first
``Texas Truth Squad'' in Philadelphia that Bush wasted state budget
surpluses on tax cuts instead of spending them on working families.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN POLICY AT THE BORDER
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, aware he might have to forge relations with a
new ruling party in Mexico, is working hard to stay out of Sunday's
presidential election there. ``If elected, I look forward to
working with whomever the good people of Mexico choose to serve
them as president,'' he said. Bush also offered a carefully crafted
comment about Mexico's reputation as something less than a
full-fledged democracy, a reputation built in part on the fact that
one party has been in control since 1929: ``I believe a free and
fair presidential election in Mexico will be an affirmation of
Mexico's continuing political progress.''
</P>
<P>
   SHADING HITTERS TOWARD RIGHT FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush shifted gears after the primaries and
targeted their appeals to the political middle. But the political
middle these days seems to be a little to the right of center.
Nearly half of all likely voters in a Voter.com-Battleground poll
described themselves as ``somewhat conservative'' and leaned toward
Bush in the race. Gore was doing about as well among those who
described themselves as at least somewhat liberal, but the problem
for Gore is that twice as many of the likely voters in the poll
described themselves as conservative as those who said they are
liberal.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY CLOCK RAN OUT ON NADER
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader is seeking an exception to the rule that cuts off
federal matching funds once a candidate is officially nominated for
president. Nader already has received the Green Party's nomination,
but in a letter to the Federal Election Commission, his lawyers
have asked that he continue to receive federal funds through the
end of the Democratic convention in mid-August. This would allow
him to continue to raise money that is matched by the federal
government. Otherwise, Nader no longer would be eligible for
federal funds for his campaign. The request must be acted upon by
the six-member FEC.
</P>
<P>
   OIL GAME BLAME
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party's Ralph Nader asserted that the Clinton-Gore
administration's energy policies had set the stage for higher
gasoline prices this summer by allowing oil company mergers in
recent years. Nader said the administration was doing ``too little,
too late'' about high gasoline prices by having the Federal Trade
Commission investigate possible price gouging. He said a much
broader investigation by the Justice Department and state attorney
generals was warranted. He also called for increasing the nation's
oil reserves and taxing oil companies' profits found to be
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   END RUN FOR ENRON
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, George W. Bush placed a call to his friend Tom
Ridge, the Republican governor of Pennsylvania, to vouch for Enron
Corp., the giant Houston energy and trading company that, at the
time, was battling to sell electricity in Pennsylvania. After a
nasty regulatory fight, Enron cracked into Pennsylvania's market _
and in the ensuing years, Enron and Bush both have seen their
influence widen nationally and internationally. Along the way,
Enron and its executives have been Bush's most generous
contributors, giving more to his various campaigns _ over $550,000,
according to the New York Times _ than any other source.
</P>
<P>
   PASS TAKEN ON ANOTHER EXECUTION
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests from civil rights and Latino advocacy groups,
George W. Bush refused to grant a stay of execution in a death
penalty case laced with charges of racial bias. Jessy San Miguel,
28, was put to death by lethal injection Thursday night, after Bush
declined to grant his request for 30 more days to explore whether
racially tinged remarks biased the jury to sentence him to death
for a brutal 1991 rampage in which four people were shot to death
inside a walk-in freezer during a Taco Bell robbery.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS WOULD FLUNK BOTH OF THEM
</P>
<P>
   The nation's teachers give both presidential candidates low
marks for their proposals to fix the nation's most troubled public
schools. Only half agree with Al Gore that underperforming schools
should be shut down and reopened under a new principal, compared to
about seven in ten voters nationally. Teachers are even more firmly
opposed, by a 2-1 ratio, to George W. Bush's plan to give children
in failing schools vouchers to help them move to a private or
religous school. Voters overall are evenly divided on vouchers.
Ninety-one registered voters identified themselves as teachers in
the Washington Post/Kaiser/Harvard poll.
</P>
<P>
   BUT THE REAL ACTORS ARE UNION
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is searching for real people _ or at least
actors who look like them. In a casting notice sent to talent
agents this week, a company representing the campaign said it was
looking for ``a wide range of assorted, real-looking people'' to
appear in spots for George W. Bush that are to be filmed in July.
Describing the spot as a ``nonunion commercial,'' the memo asked
for ``everyday people on the street'' with a ``strong emphasis on
Hispanic and Caucasian.'' The notice was a surprise to officials of
the Screen Actors Guild, which is on strike against the advertising
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ROUGH ROAD FOR RICK
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Rick Lazio's campaign gaffes are mounting _ and
everyone's starting to keep score. The latest stumble was a
high-profile and conspicuously underattended fund-raising bash in
New York. That event adds to the growing list of Lazio lapses:
missing a vote on a critical heating-oil bill, which became ammo
for Hillary Clinton; falling under a corruption cloud for a
suspicious stock option deal; skipping out on the annual Lesbian
and Gay Pride Parade in New York; making remarks offensive to
Native Americans, and driving a gas-guzzling vehicle to an event
about energy prices _ and leaving the engine running as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTING DOWN TO VEEP TIME
</P>
<P>
   Media attention on vice presidential selections has seemed to
focus more on the Republican side, in part because George W. Bush
is gabbier than Al Gore, his convention is sooner, and he seems to
have more choices. But if Gore is to be taken at his word, he's
under the same time constraints as Bush. He told reporters in late
April that his choice wouldn't be dictated by Bush's choice and
that he expected to make his selection by the time the Republicans
convene at the end of July, even though the Democratic convention
is two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   WEB VEEP BUZZ: KEATING
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating has become the name-of-the-moment as
a potential running mate for George W. Bush. Keating's name
surfaced in Internet reports as the current favorite, albeit with
caveats saying everything could change. The Bush campaign took the
news in stride. ``It's not true. The governor has made no
decision,'' spokesman Ari Fleischer told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   TIPPER: LET HUBBY PICK JUSTICES
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court's stuck down Nebraska's ``partial
birth'' abortion ban 5-4, Tipper Gore said her husband would
protect a woman's right to end a pregnancy and urged women
supporters to help elect him. ``Take a look at what the Supreme
Court did yesterday and realize how thin, thin, our margin of
support is,'' she said at a ``Women for Gore'' reception in
Washington. ``The next president is definitely going to be able to
change the Supreme Court for the next 30 years'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   IMPENDING PROTESTS CAUSE WORRY
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after voting to set aside Pershing Square in
downtown Los Angeles as a gathering place for protesters at the
Democratic National Convention in mid-August, the Los Angeles City
Council is reconsidering the move under pressure from the police
and merchants' groups worried about violence or disruptions at
convention hotels and the jewelry mart near the square. The police
now propose putting demonstrators in a fenced-off parking lot near
the convention site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
