<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-DOCTORS-UNIONS-HNS &LR;      06-30 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COLLECTIVE BARGAINING FOR DOCTORS FACES GRIM PROGNOSIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Friday he
would not support a House-approved collective-bargaining bill for
doctors, all but dooming the legislation that would give physicians
more power over cost-cutting health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which passed the House 276-136 early Friday,
would give health care professionals the same rights enjoyed by
union workers to negotiate with insurers and managed care companies
over fees and services.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dismissal by Lott, the lopsided House vote was a
political boost for Rep. Tom Campbell, the Republican sponsor of
the bill who is waging an uphill battle for Senate in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated,'' Campbell said Friday. ``I believe that improving
the way Americans receive their health care is a cause worth
fighting for. . . . Medical professionals should be allowed to
provide care for their patients as they think best and today
Congress empowered them to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Managed care companies have fought Campbell's legislation,
saying it would lead to billions of dollars in escalating medical
costs and too much clout for physicians, while the American Medical
Association has said doctors need to be empowered to fight managed
care providers to improve patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Campbell's effort to address voter concern that cost
cutting by health plans is compromising patient care, Lott's
prognosis for the measure was grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I would support at all,'' Lott, R-Miss.,
told a news conference. ``I just don't think that is something we
should be moving toward. I don't think we need more lawsuits in
America and I don't think we need more labor unions and that's
basically what they are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Lott's quick rejection of the bill was not
surprising, given Campbell's low standing in the polls against Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have been a little more diplomatic about it if he
thought Campbell had a good chance of winning,'' said Jack Pitney,
a political science professor at Claremont McKenna College in
Claremont, Calif. ``You don't want to alienate your members before
they even take the oath.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Field Poll showed Feinstein leading Campbell 58 to 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lott nor House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., likes
the substance of the Campbell measure. Both leaders have been
inclined to side more readily with managed care companies than
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert prevented Campbell's bill from coming up for a vote for
months, until Campbell held a news conference in which he attacked
the speaker for filching on two promises to allow a vote on the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the leaders has a real material incentive to be overly
deferential to Tom Campbell,'' Pitney said. ``He's leaving the
House, so he won't be a factor in the House next year, and he is a
long shot to being in the Senate. The most likely place where Tom
Campbell is going to be a powerhouse next year is the campus of
Stanford University.''
</P>
<P>
   If he loses the Senate race, Campbell is expected to return to
teach law at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Ornstein, a resident scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute, a Washington think tank, said most Republicans ``can't
stand the idea'' of doctors with union rights and fear the
implications of moving in the direction of collective bargaining
for professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans don't want this kind of hassle coming forward,''
Ornstein said. ``I wouldn't be surprised to find that Lott and
other Republicans might have talked to Campbell to try and persuade
him to back off from his position, which is not going to happen
with Tom Campbell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell spokeswoman Jackie Corcoran said she did not view
Lott's rejection of the legislation as a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down a difficult road before in the House,''
Corcoran said. ``We were able to get a vote before and we were able
to get a bill. I don't see how this is any different.''
</P>
<P>
   When Campbell was unable to get a House vote, he accused fellow
Republicans of delaying a vote so they could continue ``milking''
money from both physicians and insurance plans _ in the form of
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's legislation would not allow physicians to strike and
the collective-bargaining law would expire after three years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
