<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-TAMOXIFEN-NYT &LR;      06-30 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TAMOXIFEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA APPROVES TAMOXIFEN TO HELP LOWER RISK OF INVASIVE BREAST
CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The drug tamoxifen, already widely prescribed to treat breast
cancer and to help prevent it in women at high risk for the
disease, received approval from the Food and Drug Administration on
Thursday for another use: to lower the risk of invasive breast
cancer in women who have had surgery and radiation for ductal
carcinoma in situ, often referred to as DCIS or intraductal
carcinoma.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year course of the drug will be recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen, also called Nolvadex, is the first drug approved to
treat intraductal carcinoma, which is a very early form of breast
cancer that is still confined to the cells lining the milk ducts.
It is noninvasive, meaning that it has not spread to other tissue
in the breast, or to lymph nodes or other parts of the body. The
tumors are usually too small to feel, and most are detected by
mammography.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 40,000 cases of intraductal breast cancer a year
in the United States. They are not counted as part of the 180,000
cases of invasive breast cancer diagnosed yearly. The number of
intraductal tumors detected has increased sharply in the last
decade because mammography has become more sensitive, and more
women are being screened.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the condition is not invasive, intraductal tumors
can spread widely through the milk ducts like the branches of a
tree, and until the 1980s most cases were treated by mastectomy.
Now, more than half are treated with either lumpectomy alone or
lumpectomy with radiation. But studies have found that the tumors
can recur within five years after lumpectomy and radiation, in 6
percent to 21 percent of patients. After 10 years, the risk of
recurrence can be 30 percent to 40 percent, and about half of the
recurrences are invasive. Recurrences are usually treated by
mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of tamoxifen for women with intraductal tumors was
based on a study published in The Lancet, June 1999, of 1,804 women
who had had lumpectomy and radiation for DCIS. Half took tamoxifen,
and half took placebos. After about five years, the women who took
tamoxifen had 43 percent fewer cases of invasive breast cancer.
Survival in the two groups was similar.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is being approved for women who have had both
lumpectomy and radiation because that combination was studied. But
once a drug is approved, doctors can prescribe it for other
patients, including those who have had lumpectomy alone.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kimberly VanZee, a breast cancer surgeon at Memorial Sloan
Kettering Cancer Center in New York, said that many doctors had
already begun recommending tamoxifen for women with intraductal
tumors, especially since the Lancet study appeared. But she said
many women refused to take the drug, because of exaggerated fears
of its side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamoxifen has had so much negative press,'' she said, adding
that she thought it was not deserved. Standard chemotherapy is
riskier than tamoxifen, she said, and yet many women fear tamoxifen
more.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effects of tamoxifen are hot flashes and
vaginal discharge. Less common, but more serious side effects
include an increased risk of uterine cancer and blood clots in the
lungs and legs, which occur in less than 1 percent of women. But
endometrial cancer is usually detected early, and is considered
highly curable, VanZee said. The risks of stroke and cataracts are
also slightly increased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
