<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JUDD-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART     06-30 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDD-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYNONNA JUDD IN TIE-DYE   AND A STATE OF GRACELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT5, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elvis was in the building on Thursday night at Irving
Plaza. She had red hair and wore a purple tie-dye jacket, and
called herself Wynonna Judd. The country star, making a rare club
appearance to introduce her latest album, ``New Day Rising''
(Mercury Nashville), projected enough self-confidence and loony
charisma to pass as a female reincarnation of the King. She even
did the karate moves and muscle-flexing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Elvis had some bad qualities, and so does Wynonna (like
Presley, a first-name-only star). Her biggest vocal flaw revealed
itself throughout Thursday's set: merely adequate breath control.
Fudging the sustained notes in her cover of Joni Mitchell's ``Help
Me,'' relying on her back-up singers when she got slightly winded,
Wynonna revealed that even after 18 years in showbiz, she still
sometimes pushes too hard. She's a belter and a growler, but
sometimes that pedal-to-the-metal singing approach doesn't serve
the vocal cords.
</P>
<P>
   This is a small quibble against someone with a far rarer talent
than perfect timbre. Wynonna is one of those real stars who mix
monumentalism with humanism; she cuts through her own big show to
uncover raw feeling. This is one of her Elvis-like qualities _ she
can't help being honest, at least in performance. Even unbearably
trite songs like ``Testify to Love,'' from the ``Touched by an
Angel'' soundtrack, became visceral when Wynonna claimed them.
</P>
<P>
   Her other link to Elvis is her ability to cross racial lines
musically without seeming like a minstrel. Her uptempo songs were
mostly unsanitized Memphis soul, far looser than most Nashville
artists dare. Her new album's title track echoed the Wilson Pickett
classic, ``Midnight Hour.'' During ``Who Am I Trying to Fool?'' she
intoned a ``Hey baby'' worthy of Barry White. Clutching the hand of
a smitten male fan _ and then kissing it _ during that song, she
asserted herself as a stellar love-woman.
</P>
<P>
   The intimacy Wynonna established with both her audience and her
sometimes banal material, did not shrink her presence in the least.
Wynonna could modestly allow her outstanding backup singers to go
full-force during their designated solos, because even if her voice
was smaller, her way with it was huge.
</P>
<P>
   Her sweeping charm overcame any weaknesses caused the set by
superficial Nashville songwriting. She even escaped blame for
softening the words in her version of the Macy Gray song ``I Can't
Wait to Meetcha'' and for singing the worn-out hymn ``How Great
Thou Art.'' These choices were imperfect _ rather corny, very
country. But, truthfully, Elvis made the same ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0277 </DOCNO>
