u i BC-FRANCE-MORNING-PILL-N     06-30 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MORNING-PILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE REVERSES DECISION ON MORNING-AFTER PILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's highest administrative court on Friday reversed
a decision that had allowed nurses in high school health centers to
hand out a ``morning-after pill'' to prevent pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of State overruled a decision made by an education
minister last year, saying that the official had misunderstood a
1967 law, which says that hormonal contraceptives may only be
distributed under prescription by pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Deputy Education Minister Segolene Royal, a
Socialist, told high school health centers to stock the pill,
called Norvelo, for circumstances in which doctors could not be
reached immediately. That decision made France the first country in
the world to allow public school nurses to dispense such postcoital
contraception pills.
</P>
<P>
   The decision applied to schools that had girls as young as 12 in
them. Although nurses were advised to try to inform the child's
parents, they were not required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said in Friday's ruling that the pill was in the
category of drugs that could present a danger if not used under
medical supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The Norvelo pill can be taken up to three days after sex. It
prevents implantation of a fertilized egg, and opponents have
called it tantamount to abortion because it keeps an embryo from
developing.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church here strongly opposed Royal's decision, and
the National Confederation of Catholic Family Associations said it
``rejoiced'' at Friday's ruling but regretted that the court had
not gone further to reaffirm parental authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Voltaire Network, a civil rights group, said it was
``worried about the dramatic consequences of this decision for
young women who had no choice but to submit to a pregnancy that was
unwanted or even forced.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal said Friday that the government would immediately propose
a new law governing contraception.
</P>
<P>
   When she made her decision, health and education officials said
they hoped the policy would reduce unwanted pregnancies and lower
the abortion rate, which is higher here than in Germany, Italy or
Spain, but lower than in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Yet abortions have failed to decrease despite the easy
availability of contraception. French schoolchildren receive little
or no sex education, and surveys suggest that they are ill-informed
about sex, contraception and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The union of school nurses accepted last year's policy decision
eagerly.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the French government allowed pharmacists to sell the
pills without a prescription.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0278 </DOCNO>
