<P>
   CHINA-ANTIMISSILE-REVIEW (Beijing) _ It's hard to find any
foreign-policy expert here, in or out of government, who believes
the stated U.S. rationale for a continental anti-missile defense:
that it's merely intended to stop the likes of North Korea or Iraq.
Even Westward-leaning scholars here think the new push for missile
defense in Washington reflects an underlying conviction that the
United States must better prepare for battle with China. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   SKIMPY-CLOTHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Skin is in. American women are
wearing less than ever before. Summer itself is hotter. And over
the past decade, the proliferation of the Wonderbra coincided with
global warming so that just as cleavages became more pronounced,
shorts became shorter. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-PROGRAM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just as surely as any
shrink-wrapped Microsoft disk, the human genome is a program, a set
of precisely coded instructions that evolution has written for the
design, operation and unfortunately rather limited maintenance of a
person. That people should be operated by such a specific script is
as amazing as it would be to find that robots have souls. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-CELEBS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some statements from
celebrity women who have explained why they chose to appear nude in
Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Will move in `e' category or as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MUSIC (Undated) _ The history of cinema parallels the
history of recorded music in that both have been concerned, since
the necessary technical discoveries were made at the end of the
19th century, with composing in time: composing images, and later
sounds, in film; composing sounds alone where music is concerned.
With a grand inevitability, therefore, Jean-Luc Godard's video
``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' presents itself also as ``Histoire(s) de
la Musique,'' and it is fitting that the soundtrack alone should be
available. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ If the news is true, the record
business is not being nice to classical music. The Washington Post
reports that such respected labels as RCA Red Seal, Deutsche
Harmonia Mundi and Melodiya, all owned or distributed by the
international giant BMG, will be either shunted aside as minor
activities of the American, pop-oriented RCA label or put out of
business altogether. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EUROPE-MUSIC (Undated) _ The book is called ``Kein' Angst,
Baby!'' (``Don't Worry, Kid!''), and it has a voluptuous Valkyrie
sizzling on the cover. Written for opera singers by opera singers
and first published in 1992 by the New York Opera Newsletter, it is
a guide to auditioning in Germany. American singers long regarded
the German audition tour as a useful career move. But things have
changed. German theaters are not hiring singers as they used to. By
Anne Midgette.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-NIGHTSPOT (Zagreb, Croatia) _ The Factory, one of
Zagreb's trendiest nightspots, has even more to offer than bottled
beer and ubiquitous techno music: it has become one of the city's
most popular theaters. By Chloe Veltman.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-PRINCESS-ART (Undated) _ Long before the Greco-Roman
specter of Lady Liberty arrived in New York Harbor in 1886, another
woman symbolized the United States. Sometimes known as L'Amerique,
or the Indian Princess, she was a American Indian figure who first
appeared on maps in the 16th century. She represented continental
America alongside female allegories of Europe, Asia and Africa.
This early character, along with Liberty and the lesser-known
Columbia, is the subject of ``The Changing Face of Liberty: Female
Allegories of America,'' at the New-York Historical Society through
Sept. 3. By Sarah Bayliss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-APARTMENT (New York) _ The sight of the couple draped across
the bed engaged in cozy pillow talk was more than a little
discomfitting. Stumbling on the scene, one wasn't sure whether to
eavesdrop, look the other way or join the lovebirds on the sheets.
Convincing as it was, this slice of life was in fact a performance,
enacted by models and staged at a party at the Apartment, a
strenuously hip fashion and home furnishings store masquerading as
a private residence. By Ruth La Ferla. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   PUSH-UP-BRAS (Undated) _ Six years ago, when the British-made
Wonderbra was introduced in this country, push-up bras accounted
for about 3 percent of the $4.6 billion bra business; today that
figure is closer to 10 percent. Underwear makers are rolling out
push-up bras with the sort of hoo-ha usually reserved for movie
openings, and their arrivals in department stores are being
attended with the frenzy of a Meet-The-Beatles tour. By Penelope
Green.
</P>
