<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S.-     06-30 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S.-ART-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMIGRANTS IN U.S. WILL BE FACTOR IN MEXICO'S ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas, Calif., N.Y., Wash., Iowa, Ohio, Mich., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Mexican election has come north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican presidential candidates have campaigned in Chicago, Los
Angeles and Washington, even though Mexicans cannot vote from
abroad. The politicians are urging Mexicans from New York to San
Francisco to call their family and friends back home, advising them
how to vote on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Political parties have organized caravans of buses and cars _
even evoking history by going on horseback _ to take registered
voters to polling places set up in border towns in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And in what experts call an extraordinary step toward linking
Mexicans north and south of the Rio Grande, three Mexicans living
in the United States are running for seats in Mexico's Congress. If
they win _ and chances are good for at least two of them, in
Chicago and Los Angeles _ they will live in the United States and
represent Mexicans here.
</P>
<P>
   The extension of the hotly contested campaign in Mexico to the
barrios of the United States is a sign of how important the 10
million Mexicans living in here have become to Mexico. In a
presidential race in which the governing party is considered
vulnerable for the first time in 71 years, expatriates have been
courted and lobbied like never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole family is there, and I tell them the importance of
voting,'' said Rosario Rabiela, who owns Decima Musa, a restaurant
in Chicago's heavily Mexican Pilsen neighborhood. ``We are here,
but we contribute so much in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Emigrants ``are going to be a big factor in this election,''
said Robert Smith, a sociologist at Barnard College who studies
Mexican migration to the United States. ``They will call their
people back home and tell them vote for so-and-so. They are also
big leaders of public opinion in the towns where they're from.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three main presidential candidates have barnstormed
in the United States in recent weeks. The third, Francisco
Labastida, of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, initially criticized his opponents for campaigning here. But
he has sent his wife and other representatives to the United
States, run campaign ads in American newspapers, and last week met
just south of the border with 350 leaders of Mexicans in Chicago,
Los Angeles, Dallas and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   There are even telephone calling cards being marketed in the
United States that feature a 10-second message, complete with
swelling music, from Vicente Fox, the opposition candidate running
neck and neck with Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans living in the United States can vote only if they have
election cards and go to Mexico on July 2. Fox, of the National
Action Party, and the other main candidate, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of
the Party of the Democratic Revolution, have sponsored caravans to
take Mexicans who qualify from cities as far-flung as New York and
Yakima, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   For those staying at home, Mexicans in New York, Florida,
Illinois, California, Texas, Iowa, Washington, Ohio, Michigan and
elsewhere are holding ``symbolic'' elections, and will deliver
their ballots to Mexican election officials to register their
political views.
</P>
<P>
   For decades Mexicans here had been dismissed by the Mexican
government, and no effort was made to involve them in the political
system. But now, Mexicans abroad have reached such a critical mass
_ an estimated one in nine Mexicans lives in the United States _
and have become an economic lifeline for countless people in
Mexico. Mexicans here send about $7 billion a year to their
families and to churches and public programs in their hometowns,
the country's third biggest source of legal foreign exchange, after
oil and tourism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It used to be presidential candidates couldn't leave the
country for six months before an election _ Mexicans were that
afraid of foreign influence,'' said Rodolfo de la Garza, a
political science professor at the University of Texas. ``I was
quite surprised when these guys were up here running around,
campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Garza said some emigrants had begun ``influencing politics
in Mexico.'' adding, ``They shape the local campaign, get the local
government to respond to domestic pressures, embarrass the mayor by
saying `we're not going to give you this money.'''
</P>
<P>
   While he and other observers say it is unclear how many Mexicans
here are intensely interested in Mexico's politics and thus how
influential they will be, at least some are paying close attention.
Fox got a rally and parade in Chicago in May, and some people are
actively coaching relatives about Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Being allowed to vote in Mexico's elections is a major issue for
some Mexicans here. Immigrants from other countries have that
right, but the number of Mexicans in the United States _ possibly
15 percent of the Mexican electorate _ makes it sensitive for the
Mexican government and a potentially touchy subject for U.S.
politicians too.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mexico's Congress passed a bill to give expatriate
Mexicans the right to cast ballots at certain foreign locations,
but the bill was blocked in the senate by the PRI. That has made
the issue even bigger here, and both Fox and Cardenas champion it.
Mexicans here are presumed to be more supportive of opposition
candidates because they blame the PRI for economic hardships that
prompted them to emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On visits here, PRI representatives say they support voting
rights too, although they express wariness about cost and
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in favor of Mexicans here having the right to vote,''
said Francisco Guerrero Aguirre, a senior PRI official campaigning
for Labastida this week in Chicago, where a Mexican population of
an estimated one million is second only to that of Los Angeles.
``We are concerned about how it will be implemented. Imagine the
possibility of fraud or intervention of other countries. But the
PRI is very much interested in having contact with Mexicans in the
U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic elections, in which people with proof of Mexican
citizenship can vote at mock polling places on street corners and
outside neighborhood grocery stores, are partly meant to keep the
voting rights issue alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that our vote is not going to be used in the
elections, but we can use this information to have influence,''
said Joel Magallan, executive director of Tepeyac Association, a
Mexican organization in New York, who said there would be 15
polling places in the city, one in Harlem and others in the Bronx,
Brooklyn, Queens and Staten Island. He said sending the voting list
to Mexico would also prevent unscrupulous people from casting
ballots under the names of emigres.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prospect of Mexican congressmen who live in the
United States is considered more than symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these guys win congressional seats, that would really be
big,'' said de la Garza. France has an elected representative for
overseas citizens, but some Mexicans are talking about going
considerably farther. The National Action Party recently introduced
a proposal in Congress to reserve 10 of the 500 seats for Mexicans
abroad, and others talk of slates of U.S. candidates in the 2003
congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution has two candidates in
this election, Raul Ross Pineda, director of Mexican affairs for
the American Friends Service Committee in Chicago, and Jose Jacques
Medina, a community organizer in Los Angeles. The PRI candidate is
Eddie Varon Levy, a lawyer in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are not named on the ballot, but are on regional
party slates. The more votes a party gets in a region, the more
congressmen it gets. By that calculus, Ross and Varon are
considered likely winners, while Jacques is less likely.
</P>
<P>
   If they win, they plan to commute to Mexico at least part of the
time Congress is in session _ about six months a year, in two month
stretches. Their priorities include streamlining the process for
sending money to Mexico, making it easier for Mexicans abroad to
invest in their hometowns, and influencing United States
immigration and drug policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be a special kind of congressman,'' said Ross,
who advocates voting rights for Mexicans abroad and will not be
voting in Mexico on Sunday. ``My main obligation is going to be to
represent people who live in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Varon said, ``we'll set up offices here too _ in
Oklahoma, Chicago, California, wherever concentrations of Mexicans
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
