<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-COMPETE0701-     06-30 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-COMPETE0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong has a point to proveArmstrong has point to prove as he
sets out to defend his championship
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ Although he is the defending Tour de
France champion, some well-known cyclists have decided that Lance
Armstrong's recent achievements aren't that monumental.
</P>
<P>
   These cyclists, including French hero Laurent Jalabert, claim it
was Armstrong's unique preparation and not his immense talent that
got him his incredible Tour win in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand. I was a world champion in 1993. I've been
here a long time. I don't know why my detractors are saying what
they've said,'' Armstrong said. ``I've always had class. I've
ridden in the front, and I've won the big races . . . at some point
this has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he still likes to think of himself as a
``outsider.'' ``They think that since the Tour never was my
specialty, that one year I just decided to focus on it and I won,''
Armstrong said from his part-time home in Nice, France. ``They
think if they change their focus, then it's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear as the world's top cyclists gather for the Tour
prologue in Futuroscope this afternoon that Armstrong has changed
the way other top competitors prepare for this torturous marathon
event that will span three weeks and go through three countries
before it ends July 23. That's when the cyclists will hop on the
historic Orient Express to Paris and cap off the 2,255.7-mile Tour
with an 85-mile trek through the City of Lights.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's approach in 1999 might have been novel, but it was
nothing more than smart practice habits. He picked up those habits
while competing in swimming meets and running triathlons while
growing up in Plano before concentrating on cycling and moving to
Austin a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's plan last year was simple. He mapped out the 1999
course and rode the Tour stages in the months leading up to the
Tour. He knew he would be strong in the time trials. Because his
climbing ability had been a weakness, he paid close attention to
the mountains so there would be no surprises once the Tour started.
</P>
<P>
   His familiarity with the routes allowed him to be more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   That mind-set probably won't change this year, although it's
likely other previously more conservative riders might adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sort of more traditional way to win the Tour has been to
make up what you lost in the mountains by making it up in the time
trials,'' said Chris Carmichael, Armstrong's longtime coach. ``And
then you limit your losses in time and rely on your team to be
strong in the flats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Lance didn't do that last year. He attacked the time
trials and he attacked the mountains. So in the time trials, he
made up some serious time on the real climbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could ride more conservatively this year and not really
attack, then have his team control it. That way you don't expose
yourself as much and that's the good way to win overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not in Lance's makeup. That's why Lance is
different. He looks for every opportunity to help him win. He races
every day like it's the final day.''
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE: DODGE THE LIMELIGHT
</P>
<P>
   It has been an odd year for the Tour winner because Armstrong
still has yet to garner total respect from his competitors and from
the critical French-based media.
</P>
<P>
   Jalabert again said Armstrong peaked too soon after the
28-year-old Austin resident turned in almost flawless performances
in the Classique des Alpes and the Dauphine Libere, two Tour
tuneups. Those races were in May and early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong is 100 percent fit, and that seems premature,''
Jalabert said after Armstrong's third-place performance at the
Dauphine Libere. ``The Alps in the Tour are scheduled in 10 weeks'
time, and it will be hard for him to maintain his condition so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong contends he is in the best shape of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, others have criticized him for spending too much
time making money and not enough time training.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was profiled nationally by USA Today earlier this
year. The story detailed Armstrong's ever-increasing popularity,
while mentioning his multi-million-dollar endorsement deals. He
likely will make $7 million this year, with last year's Tour win
swelling his total endorsements to $15 million over the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The French newspaper L'Equipe reprinted the USA Today story and
put editorial comments in italics throughout the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pay much attention to it,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty negative,'' said Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's
Austin-based agent. ``It's ironic, because Lance really loves Nice.
He speaks French fluently, but he's still an American (to the
French).''
</P>
<P>
   Even longtime friend Miguel Indurain, the legendary Spaniard who
won five consecutive Tours, wondered earlier this year if Armstrong
was spreading himself too thin between riding and endorsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would recommend to Lance is to have people work for him
and do the press and the events,'' Indurain said through a
translator. ``That way he can concentrate on riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every rider who wins has the same problem. Every one who has
won the Tour for the first time, it has changed his life forever.
Lance became very popular. Everyone knows him. If I could advise
him, I would tell him to keep training so he can be in the best
shape possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A TOUGHER TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's popularity not only has increased his bank account,
it also has allowed his U.S. Postal Service team to build a strong
squad of supporting riders for the Tour. Including Armstrong, there
will be nine U.S.P.S. riders competing. Six of them are American
and rode with Armstrong last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Osipow, director of operations for the U.S.P.S. team, said
he was able to add five to six new corporate sponsors to the team.
These sponsors paid a minimum of six figures to have their logos
displayed on the U.S.P.S. jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable new additions to the roster have been Cedric
Vasseur of France and Viatcheslav Ekimov of Russia. Vasseur led the
1997 Tour and wore the yellow jersey for five days. Ekimov, who
specializes in time trials, is a former Tour stage winner.
</P>
<P>
   The third addition was Benoit Joachim of Luxembourg, who also
excels in time trials.
</P>
<P>
   Austin resident Kevin Livingston is on the team and again will
help Armstrong in the mountain climbs.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Bruyneel, the U.S.P.S. team director, said Tour experience
rather than potential played a huge part in team selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice of the team was based on the experience of last
year,'' Bruyneel said. ``I selected the riders for this year based
on who had the experience of defending the leader's jersey last
year. That was a big factor, plus the experience of Ekimov and
Vasseur and the solid fitness of Joachim. It's no use going to the
Tour de France with one leader and eight climbers. I learned that
from last year _ you need people for the high mountains, middle
mountains and flats. You need a well balanced team.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S.P.S. member Tyler Hamilton of Marblehead, Mass., has proved
this year that he is a cyclist on the rise. Hamilton likely will
play a significant role in the mountains riding for Armstrong. He
won the Dauphine Libere last month, with Armstrong, in a rare turn,
riding to give his teammate the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was not a real surprise that Tyler won the
Dauphine,'' Bruyneel said. ``That was an objective before the start
of the race. He has improved a lot in the climbs. Last year, he did
a couple of good mountain stages but there was some inconsistency.
This year, he made big improvements in May in training and at the
Dauphine. He knows we will again count on him to assist Lance in
the mountains, and he now has evidence he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong acknowledged the strength of his Tour teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team did a good job for me last year, and they seem to be
a stronger group this year,'' he said. ``One thing (Armstrong's
win) did. We were able to buy a stronger group of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
