<HEADLINE>
NOBODY KNOWS WHAT ROAD MEXICO WILL FOLLOW
</HEADLINE>
  (For immediate use.)   
 SUBSCRIBERS: This column is moving early in advance of the Mexican
election. Mr. Martinez's next column will move the week of July
16. 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's MARTINEZ COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the MARTINEZ COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Mexico has taken more time to establish a
clear democracy than any other Latin American country.
</P>
<P>
   With two unusual exceptions _ Francisco I. Madero's presidency
(1911-1913) and the decade of the liberal republic of Benito Juarez
(1867-1876) _ Mexicans have always lived in an ironclad and deaf
autocratic tradition. An all-powerful president with the right to
designate his successor, and a political party that has governed
without allowing the slightest dissent are the hallmarks of life in
Mexico for past 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   These days, everything seems ready to change with the election
on July 2, except for blind political authoritarianism. For those
who observe from afar the fierce electoral campaign, it's easy to
see that the opposition candidate Vicente Fox's followers in the
National Action party, or PAN, aren't willing to accept the
possibility of a defeat, nor the right of their rivals to think
differently.
</P>
<P>
   For most Mexican intellectuals, to express support for the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, or for its official
candidate, Francisco Labastida, means a spontaneous confession of
venality or stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the only way to change a corrupt political
system is to vote for Fox has became a fixed idea in the mind of
thinking Mexicans. Some have even said that the only possible road
for democracy in Mexico is alternation in power, without thinking
that a forced alternation is as antidemocratic as a forced
continuity.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so serious that Labastida has to win by a
margin of more than 5 percentage points. If the official candidate
wins by a slim margin, he wouldn't be capable of governing a
peaceful country because he wouldn't be accepted as a legitimate
president.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the journalists, sociologists and writers with whom I
have talked in the last weeks say they are not satisfied with the
two main candidates and have decided to vote for the candidates of
smaller parties. And every time such intentions have been expressed
or written about, they have been attacked by supporters of Fox
because, from their point of view, only Fox has a chance of
defeating Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they are right, but there is more than one motive for
Mexicans not to be happy about their future, whatever it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who could have renounced his candidacy
to pave the way for a united opposition _ with all the personal
benefits this might have guaranteed _ has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   On the one side, history is against such a move. The National
Action party was created in 1939 as an act of rebellion against the
progressive policies of Cuauhtemoc's father, President Lazaro
Cardenas. On the other side, Cardenas does not believe that Fox
will fulfill his promises. The only thing both candidates agree on
is that they will oppose electoral fraud in any form, and this
accord was reached just one month before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the PRI's Francisco Labastida is among the cadre of
elite young leaders who have helped modernize Mexico, few believe
he'll also be capable of modernizing the PRI. And when the polls
were not favorable to him in May, he sought the party's help to
reverse the tendency.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has appeared awkward in public debates and he has been
less than clever in his public declarations, but nobody doubts that
he would be a capable bureaucrat _ as gray as former President
Miguel de la Madrid and as honest as Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, on the contrary, is an enigma _ similar in more ways than
one to Juan Domingo Peron. Like the Argentinian leader, Fox is
willing to tell everyone what they want to hear, and he isn't
afraid of contradicting himself. And, also did Peron, he has been
able to obscure a conservative background by using leftist
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when he was the governor of Guanajuato State, he
was one of the most ardent advocates of privatizing Pemex, the
state-owned oil company, despite its being one of the great symbols
of Mexican nationalism. Today he defends vigorously the exact
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN was created as the Catholics' answer to the
anti-clericalism of the elder Cardenas. Fox has already made
several gestures intended to please the Church, among them paying
public devotion to the Virgin of Guadalupe and promising to push
legislation to increase the restrictions on abortion. But when
confronted by opposition forces, he swears that he would never use
the power of the state to impose particular religious faith or life
style.
</P>
<P>
   Even Fox's most ardent supporters admit that he is an incurable
populist. He is tall, congenial and eloquent, and he likes to dress
as a cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's problem, then, is to decide which is the least of two
evils _ populism or continuity. Many in the country are not happy
about the six years of Zedillo's presidency, despite the fact that
he has done more to change the political habits of Mexico than all
of his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's success, though, is imperfect. The New York Times, in
its June 19 edition, said that although the electoral campaign has
been ``the cleanest and most competitive in Mexico's history,''
there have been numerous instances in which the PRI has tried to
buy votes or threaten peasants, workers and public employees.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, Zedillo's predecessor, won the
presidency in what seemed a fraudulent election. Yet he succeeded
in creating a sense of national prosperity, which was reinforced by
the signing of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Had Salinas wanted to, he could have imposed the political
reforms many Mexicans have long demanded. He did not. He has since
said that PRI factionalism prevented him from acting: His duty, he
said, was to unite the PRI so that reforms could be made by Luis
Donaldo Colosio, the man he had chosen to be his successor.
</P>
<P>
   But Colosio was murdered before he could be elected so the
weakest of the heirs of Salinas was the one who accomplished that
improbable and enormous task.
</P>
<P>
   If Fox wins, he will owe Zedillo a debt of gratitude for helping
to create a country now ready to practice democracy in a mature
manner. If Labastida wins, he will be the first president who was
not selected by the arbitrary ``finger'' of his predecessor. The
problem is that the winner must have a very clear margin of
victory, and nobody knows if that will be possible.
</P>
<P>
   No country changes overnight. A few years will have to pass
before Mexico's autocratic traditions give way to the traditions of
tolerance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
