A9933 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FACTORY-KILLINGS-HNS &LR;      06-30 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACTORY-KILLINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMERAS DOCUMENT SHOOTING OF FOOD INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAYWARD, Calif. _ In an ironic twist, the most damaging piece of
evidence against a San Leandro sausage maker facing triple homicide
charges may have been created by the defendant himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Alexander, 39, charged with gunning down three government
meat inspectors at his Santos Linguisa Factory, turned on the
store's surveillance cameras shortly before the shooting rampage,
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's employee, Brooke Silverglide, 21, of San Jose, told
the police she helped her boss climb into an attic in his office to
turn on the factory's two security cameras, one in the front retail
area where the shootings occurred and the other in the rear office.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the court records said, the cameras captured
Alexander shooting unsuspecting meat inspectors Jeannie Hillery,
Tom Quadros and Bill Shaline, who had arrived at Santos Linguisa
for an unannounced inspection.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander's original intent in turning on the cameras was to
help prove that he was being harassed by the inspectors, not to
tape a shooting, defense attorney Stuart Hanlon said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander ``felt they were harassing him, and something
traumatic happened between turning on the camera and him going out
there,'' Hanlon said. ``Something snapped and that's what the trial
will be about.''
</P>
<P>
   In a chilling sequence of events, the video shows Alexander
firing numerous shots at federal inspectors Hillery, 56, of
Alameda, and Quadros, 52, of Hayward, and state inspector Shaline,
57, of Sacramento, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander then ran outside and allegedly chased another food
inspector who was waiting for police officers to arrive. Quadros
had called for police assistance moments before the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   State inspector Earl Willis told detectives he was chased around
the corner and down the street as the suspect fired gunshots at
him. He was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Elliott, assistant district manager of the U.S. Department
of Agriculture, told the police that sanitation problems were
discovered in Alexander's factory in January and government meat
inspectors shut the business down for some time.
</P>
<P>
   There were instances when both state and federal inspectors were
asked to leave by Alexander when they came to see if he was abiding
the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May, Alexander called the USDA's office in Alameda,
saying he wanted to be reinstated again, but ran into more trouble
for not processing the meat in accordance with federal standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
