<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES     06-30 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER'S UNLIKELY CAMPAIGN IS HAVING AN UNEXPECTED IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: ``Withering Heights'' in 3rd from last graf is correct)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It was nearing 10 o'clock at night, but in the
sweltering lecture hall that served as the stage for this political
rally, the Green Party's nominee for president of the United States
was still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   He railed against an ``apartheid economy'' that was benefiting
only the rich, and he bemoaned the state of affairs in a country
with ``far more problems than it deserves and far more solutions
than it applies.'' And he scoffed at the notion that he might be a
``spoiler,'' drawing enough votes away from Al Gore to tip the
election to George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't spoil a system,'' said Ralph Nader, ``that's spoiled
to the core.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience of 300 people or so loved it, repeatedly breaking
into applause and giving the 66-year-old Nader a standing ovation
coming in and heading out.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know whether, as current polls suggest,
Nader's Raiders will have more impact on the race than the Buchanan
Brigades of the likely Reform Party nominee, Pat Buchanan. But one
thing is clear on the campaign trail with the country's best-known
consumer advocate: He is running an exceedingly more energetic race
than he did four years ago, when he essentially stood in as a
protest candidate, spending less than $5,000, speaking rarely and
taking 1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the difference between a person running and a person
standing still,'' Nader said by way of comparison to his 1966 White
House bid. He has campaigned in every state this year _ flying
commercial coach class, frequently using his senior-citizen's
discount _ and he appears well on his way to his goal of raising $5
million, with the help of the vast direct-mail network he has built
over the years and plugs from several big Hollywood names.
</P>
<P>
   He may wind up as a passing phenomenon in this campaign, like
Bill Bradley or John McCain. But for now, Nader is attracting a lot
of attention _ among the media, among left-leaning voters who see
him as a more reliably liberal voice than Gore, and among leaders
of organized labor, who agree with his stands on trade. Nader is a
staunch critic of the North American Free Trade Agreement and the
World Trade Organization, both of which he depicts as evidence of a
``corporate globalization'' that harms worker rights and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Polls in recent weeks have put him at between 5 percent and 10
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a stretch to call Nader a natural politician, and
his one-and-three-quarter-hour nomination acceptance speech on
Sunday in Denver may have been a tad long. But he seems highly
animated, and has a lot of sound bites down. He even claims to be
enjoying his life as a politician, though he chooses a rather grim
analogy to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I have programmed myself so that if something is important
to do, it's enjoyable,'' he said in an interview Monday, after
speaking at a women's center in San Francisco's Mission District.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, there are some professional people who do that, too,''
Nader continued. ``A good doctor, if he believes it's important to
treat people, he'll enjoy treating people, even though outsiders
may say, `Oh, My God, what horrible tragedies and near-misses, what
pain you're dealing with.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Nader's depiction, most of the country is in pain. ``At no
time in our history have the children of America been in such
crisis,'' he said in San Francisco the other day. And most
wage-earners, he told the crowd here, are working harder and longer
than ever but have less purchasing power than they had in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Nader sees the West Coast _ with its mix of liberals, radicals,
environmentalists and others who lean to the left _ as a fertile
ground for his campaign. And indeed in California, where Nader has
been involved in tort initiatives and has campaigned for so-called
``patient protection'' and HMO-reform initiatives, polls show his
support in the 5 to 7 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Though the number is small, much of that support comes at the
expense of Gore, who most analysts believe has to win California to
win in November. But even with Nader campaigning hard in the state,
Democrats here profess to have little concerned about his impact.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reaching out to Nader and his backers, they have so
far been dismissive. ``Ralph Nader is a 66-year-old Corvair in this
race ready to be rear-ended,'' said Bob Mulholland, campaign
adviser to the California Democratic Party. ``This is the most
serious vote of people's lives, and they're not going to throw it
away.'' He said the party would not ``waste one ad'' campaigning
against the Green Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nader became famous because of the Corvair, and he's been
doing college campuses ever since,'' Mulholland said. ``And now he
wants to be president? It's a joke, it's ridiculous. Only in
America can someone completely irrelevant run for president.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Nader's message is a bit complicated. He says that
he hopes his candidacy will energize turnout for Democratic
candidates in close races for the House of Representatives, and
thus help turn power over to House Democratic leaders, and away
from the Republicans in the House leadership whom he calls ``beyond
the pale.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the presidential level, Nader has nothing but venom for
Gore and President Clinton, whom he accuses of offering ``some of
the most intensive demonstrations of political cowardliness in
American history.'' He says the race offers voters two
``Republicrat'' candidates, barely distinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only distinction between Bush and Gore is the velocity
with which their knees hit the floor when big corporations knock on
the door,'' said Nader the other day in Los Angeles, campaigning
outside a public housing project.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A seasoned political strategist might suggest that while Nader
remains so hot, he should be barnstorming the country. He did
follow up his nomination acceptance in Denver with the swing here,
and he said he plans many such swings. But afterward, he headed
back to Washington, D.C., where aides said he planned to spend the
rest of the week, mostly conducting media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Oakland, speaking Monday at a downtown school called the
University of Creation Spirituality, Nader elicited hisses of
agreement from the crowd when he blasted several big-name Democrats
in California, including Gov. Gray Davis and U.S. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein. And he drew sustained applause when he described the
state of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the central planks of his campaign are pledges to enact
universal health insurance, to change labor laws to make it easier
for unions to organize and to eliminate corporate welfare.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If there was any good news for Gore out of the rally here, it
would seem to be that Nader's crowd was, by and large, so
left-leaning that many voters there were not even the vice
president's to lose. Several people in the audience said they had
voted for Green or Libertarian Party candidates in the past.
</P>
<P>
   What seemed to resonate with them most was Nader's ``honesty _
just the sense that nobody is going to own him,'' as Corine
Thornton, a 77-year-old retired waitress, put it. She voted for
Nader four years ago: ``I just was no longer satisfied with voting
for the lesser of two evils.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mateo Williford, a 28-year-old self-described ``traveling
activist,'' rejected the idea that a vote for Nader was a wasted
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're ever going to have the possibility of three, four,
five political parties,'' he said, ``we have to make the choice to
start bringing those in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people were not even sure about the whole electoral
effort on Nader's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that all this energy is being put into the
political system,'' said Jonah Zern, 22, who graduated from Cornell
University last year with a degree in environmental policy. ``I
mean, the idea that one person can represent 250 million people is
absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader is not without potential vulnerabilities to exploit.
Eyebrows were raised recently when the financial disclosure
statements of America's most famous corporation-basher revealed
that he was worth nearly $4 million, in large part because of some
savvy stock investments in high-technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader scoffed at the notion that there was anything untoward
about reaping such gains. He said he lives on about $25,000 a year,
giving away 80 percent of his after-tax income, and that any of his
gains in the market represent a ``de facto philanthropic fund'' for
his favorite causes.
</P>
<P>
   No one really expects it, but what if Nader wound up in ``that
corporate prison we used to call the White House,'' as he describes
it, having to deal with the lawmakers ``who have turned Capitol
Hill into Withering Heights''?
</P>
<P>
   Would he find it all daunting? Nader thought about the question
for a while, and said no. ``First of all, I've been in Washington
too long, I've seen what kind of characters were in power, who
should have been daunted but weren't.'' So no, daunting wasn't the
right word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would find it challenging to be president,'' he said.
``Daunting has almost a stuck-in-the-headlights, taken aback sense,
that maybe you're surprised by what you find yourself having to
cope with. I don't think that would be the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
