<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CAMPFIN-BOS     06-30 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CAMPFIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS AGAINST PACS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be easy to minimize the victory that campaign finance
reform finally achieved in Congress this week _ easy, but wrong.
</P>
<P>
   True, the loophole Congress closed was a small one. ``Stealth
PACs,'' operating under Section 527 of the tax code, will no longer
be able to keep their donors secret, but they will still be able to
operate, like scores of other ``independent'' political
organizations, using huge soft money contributions to advance their
political ends. And even the elimination of all soft money, as the
McCain-Feingold and Shays-Meehan bills would do, is only the first
major step toward democratizing a national politics still
controlled far too much by moneyed interests.
</P>
<P>
   So Congress this week only healed the blister on top of the boil
on top of the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the large majorities _ 92-6 in the Senate and 385-39 in
the House _ show the enormous potential for bipartisan progress.
Republican Senator Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, reform's arch foe,
had boasted that the GOP lock on the issue was impregnable because
voters didn't care. This week he was reduced to encouraging
senators to vote for reform so they wouldn't suffer at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the stealth PAC loophole was a good step. More
important, Congress created a coalition that should now press its
momentum for more substantial reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1915EDT &QL; 
