<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ANTHRAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING RANKS OVER ANTHRAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Boston to the Pentagon, health officials are addressing the
threat of biological weapons that have the potential to cause
deaths on a scale with nuclear weapons but at a fraction of the
cost and difficulty. In Boston and elsewhere the focus is on
creating a computerized warning system in which a sudden spiking of
emergency-room visits or deaths would alert authorities to the
possibility of such an attack. Without such a system, casualties
could mount for days as patients suffer from symptoms that, in
initial stages, look like just a severe flu.
</P>
<P>
   That plan is not controversial. The Defense Department's
two-year-old program _ requiring members of the military to be
vaccinated against the most probable threat, anthrax _ is
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the armed forces have vaccinated against a range
of diseases uncommon in the United States, from cholera to yellow
fever. But because of a small number of adverse reactions to the
anthrax vaccine, none of them fatal, some personnel are refusing to
take it, and an antivaccine campaign has arisen on the Internet.
Protesters have caught the attention of congressmen, who have
raised their own questions about the Pentagon's program.
</P>
<P>
   Such questions are valid and could serve a public health purpose
for the nation by raising awareness of the havoc that an
``aerosolized'' anthrax-spore weapon in the hands of a foreign
power or a group of terrorists could wreak. On Thursday, a CIA
official warned of the danger of bioterrorism at Congress's
first-ever hearing on the global danger of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Bacillus anthracis usually affects animals but in its inhaled
form is almost 100 percent lethal to human beings who get a
substantial exposure and no immediate treatment. In recent years,
US officials have suspected 10 foreign countries, including Iraq
and North Korea, of possessing or developing anthrax weapons. ``The
threat is so serious,'' the Defense Department stated in response
to a call in May by 35 congressmen to halt vaccination, ``that our
commanders-in-chief in Korea and Southwest Asia are adamant in
their insistence that all of their forward-deployed forces . . . be
vaccinated.''
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine that the Pentagon has turned to is one that since
1970 has been given in a series of six injections to veterinarians
and others who work with animals. In three decades, the vaccine has
been found effective and safe, causing occasional reactions similar
to those brought on by other vaccines. The most common is redness
and swelling at the injection.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon, of the 440,000 military personnel who
have received a total of more than 1.7 million vaccine shots, 31
people have required hospitalization. Of the 31, six have been
determined to have illnesses probably caused by the vaccination and
have been granted waivers from further anthrax shots.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this creditable record, the military is regularly
vilified on Internet Web sites for its handling of the anthrax
vaccine. It is a classic instance of how double-edged computer
communication is: While special software will make it possible in
Boston for health officials to detect worrisome ``clusters'' in
emergency departments that might signal bioterrorism, Internet
links have helped to foster resistance to the anthrax vaccine among
service personnel. In both cases, here and in the military, health
officials should follow through on their plans to protect American
lives from an insidious killer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
