<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BROADCAST-B     06-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BROADCAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATIONAL AIRWAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 02, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A harmful war rages over the rights of religious broadcasters,
pitting Republicans in Congress against the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are licenses to run what's called noncommercial
educational stations. They date back to 1945 when the government
set aside 20 percent of the FM dial for educational programming. In
1952, 242 television channels were also reserved. The goal was to
create educational shows for the entire community, children and
adults, that would be free from commercial pressure. Today there
are more than 370 noncommercial educational television stations
(NCETV). One local example is WGBH.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy arose because Cornerstone TeleVision, a religious
broadcaster near Pittsburgh, wanted to take over one of two
stations licensed to a public broadcaster. The public broadcaster
agreed because it had money problems. The full plan: Cornerstone
would take over the public NCETV channel, sell its commercial
channel, and split the profit with the ailing public broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   Some Pittsburgh residents and community organizations cried
foul. They insisted Cornerstone would not meet the community's
educational needs.
</P>
<P>
   It's an understandable concern. Cornerstone's Web site shows its
deeply religious orientation. A message from its president, Oleen
Eagle, says the station's goal is ``to impact our culture and
reverse society's moral downslide by broadcasting the Gospel and
bringing a fresh, positive, Christ-centered outlook. . . . At the
heart of our mission are the Three E's: Entertainment. Evangelism.
Edification.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the FCC approved Cornerstone's NCETV request,
pointing out a tendency to defer to applicants' judgments about
programming unless they are ``arbitrary or unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   But FCC chairman William Kennard and commissioner Gloria
Tristani did dissent in part, saying Cornerstone had failed to
prove its programming would be ``primarily educational.''
</P>
<P>
   The order also contained what would become a bomb: ``additional
guidance'' from the FCC. It said that more than half the broadcast
hours of NCETV stations must ``primarily serve an educational,
instructional, or cultural purpose in the station's community of
license.'' Religious programming could indeed qualify as
educational, but not if it was ``primarily devoted to religious
exhortation, proselytizing, or statements of personally held
religious views . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like common sense. To broadcast on an NCETV station,
adhere to NCETV educational rules. But the National Religious
Broadcasters, an association of Christian broadcasters, called the
FCC ruling ``a dangerous decision'' that interfered with religious
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen wrote ill-advised bills. In the House, the
``Religious Broadcasting Freedom Act,'' said the additional
guidance was invalid because the FCC could not make up new rules
unless it did so through official rule-making procedures. The FCC
said it was only issuing an explanation, but, caving in to
pressure, it still rescinded the guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill that passed in the House and has moved to the
Senate, ``The Noncommercial Broadcasting Freedom of Expression Act
of 2000,'' claims noncommercial educational broadcasters should use
stations to ``primarily serve an educational, instructional,
cultural, or religious purpose in its community of license'' _
adding the word ``religious.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing this bill would be a disaster. Related Senate bills
should also be scrapped. NCE stations are a valuable government
effort to reserve a corner of the crowded airways for education.
And while the First Amendment says government must defend the
``free exercise'' of religion, it's a violation of the separation
of church and state for government to promote religious purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, religious broadcasters have not had their free
speech rights trampled. They air on commercial and noncommercial
stations. The ``2000 Directory of Religious Media'' includes 285
television stations and 1,731 radio stations. So based on FCC
figures, at least 17.6 percent of TV stations (of 1,616 in total)
air religious content, as do at least 13.7 percent of radio
stations (of 12,615 in total).
</P>
<P>
   After the outburst, Cornerstone chose not to assume the NCETV
license. But it could have. And, as Kennard has argued, since only
a majority of its shows were supposed to be educational, a minority
of shows could have been solely religious in purpose.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the FCC has been timid. It should have let its
``additional guidance'' stand. Because it didn't, it may have to
fight much harder to protect the educational mission of NCE
stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
