<HEADLINE>
AFFIRMING INTERNET PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 03, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A decision by the Clinton administration will discourage federal
agencies from using tiny computer files called cookies to identify
computer users. This useful step ought to prompt Internet companies
to protect the privacy of their customers as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of National Drug Control Policy set off a controversy
when newspapers revealed that anyone who visited its Web site on
drug information received an unwanted gift _ a hidden cookie on
their computer. The office had subcontracted the work to the
DoubleClick ad company, which used the cookies to track the number
of visitors to the site.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick stirred up its own controversy last winter when it
tried to link millions of cookies and other information into huge
databases for marketing campaigns. The company backed down, but
fears linger that something intrusive could be done with personal
information available on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the drug site was well timed to remind people of
the dangers of cookies. DoubleClick might have been using them
anonymously, but it is technologically easy to attach people's
names to the computer files. Anonymity is essential on such a
sensitive topic as drug information.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the controversy, the Clinton administration has
decided that cookies will almost never be used on federal Web
sites. Agencies will have to demonstrate a compelling need to gain
an exception from the rule. Some agencies have been slow to respond
to the order, the magazine Wired News reports, but if the White
House keeps the pressure on, they will be sure to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Private Internet companies have yet to adopt a concerted policy
on privacy, one that would discourage the collation of data, be
especially sensitive to such confidential matters as health and
income, yet not inhibit the innocuous use of cookies. There is no
harm in advising customers which goods to purchase, based on their
prior buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission is looking into the privacy issue,
and Representative Edward Markey (D-Mass.) has filed legislation to
establish privacy standards. If the dot-coms do not become
protectors of privacy, then the government will have to police more
than just itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
