u i BC-HONGKONG-GENDER-CHOIC     06-30 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-GENDER-CHOICE-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY HONG KONG PARENTS WANT TO CHOOSE BABIES' SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In an off-the-rack world, Hong Kong remains
stubbornly made-to-measure. Wander into any alleyway off the main
shopping boulevard, Queen's Road, and you can order tailored suits,
personalized Chinese scrolls, custom-designed furniture or handmade
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in one of these narrow streets _ behind locked doors on
the eighth floor of a nondescript office building _ is Anthony S.Y.
Wong's fertility clinic. For $2,450, Wong offers the ultimate in
customized service: He helps parents choose the sex of their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Wong does not advertise, and the sign on his door identifies the
clinic only as the Victory Medical Laboratory. But he is happy to
discuss his treatment, which he says has had an 83 percent success
rate in 100 births since the clinic opened in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a couple has a boy and wants a girl, we help to get them a
girl,'' said Wong, a dapper 44-year-old with a master's degree in
biochemistry and the trace of a British accent. ``If a couple has a
girl and wants a boy, we help them get a boy. We think of this as a
form of family planning.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, more than 90 percent of Wong's customers choose
boys. That has drawn fierce criticism from doctors and politicians,
who say he practices a reckless form of genetic engineering. Last
week Hong Kong's legislature passed a law banning sex selection,
except in cases when it is necessary to prevent the transmission of
a hereditary disease.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be a couple of months before the law takes effect.
In the meantime, Wong says business is booming. The Gender Choice
Center is the only clinic in Hong Kong that offers sex selection,
and couples are rushing to sign up while they can still do it
legally.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, they are laying bare a social phenomenon that is
little discussed but widely prevalent in Hong Kong: the
determination to control virtually every facet of childbirth. From
selecting the sex to scheduling the delivery _ down to the minute,
never mind the day _ people here go to extraordinary lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Wong's clinic are Chinese medicine shops, which
sell potions made from the antlers and tails of deer. By drinking
these concoctions, men are supposed to become more virile and
increase their chances of fathering a son. Couples also consult
charts that predict the sex of a baby by cross-referencing the
mother's age with the month of conception. A particularly popular
one is said to come from the imperial palace of the Qing dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Western culture, parents do not automatically want a boy,''
said Cyd Ho, a female legislator who opposes sex selection. ``But
in Chinese culture, boys are still the precious gem, particularly
in the eyes of the grandmother. We have to say no to this form of
gender discrimination.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wong is unruffled. ``Sex selection among Chinese people is
nothing new. It has been going on for ages and ages,'' he said.
``The government wants to stop the only method that has been proven
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of disagreement about that. Wong's method, which
was developed by an American doctor, Ronald J. Ericsson, rests on
the assumption that sperm bearing the male, or Y, chromosome swim
faster than sperm bearing the female, or X, chromosome. Ericsson's
innovation was to place the sperm over an albumin-based medium,
which has layers of increasing density.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the sperm that make it to the bottom layer are mostly
male. To increase the odds of a boy, sperm are distilled from that
layer and used to inseminate the prospective mother. To increase
the odds of a female baby, sperm are distilled from less dense
layers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific proof that this works,'' said Kenneth
Mao, a specialist in fertility. ``But it may improve your chances a
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his skepticism, Mao opposes banning the procedure. He
noted that in a few cases it might prevent abortions by couples
desperate not to have a girl. The abortion rate for female babies
is no higher in Hong Kong than in the United States. But elsewhere
in China, boys are so highly prized that parents resort to abortion
and infanticide.
</P>
<P>
   Wong said he had a code of ethics to prevent abuses. He asks
couples to sign a pledge that they will not terminate the pregnancy
if the procedure fails. And he said he does not permit couples to
select the sex of their first baby. The procedure, he says, is
meant to balance families with multiple children.
</P>
<P>
   Wong holds himself up as an example. He and his wife have two
girls, and they dearly wanted a son. By the miracle of sorted
sperm, he said, they had a boy, now 4{.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Wong's precautions are not enough. Without a ban,
such as exists in Britain and some parts of the United States,
disreputable clinics could set up shop like back-alley
abortionists, they say. Even the spread of properly licensed
clinics could lead to a population imbalance, given the Chinese
mania for boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we let this spread far and wide, Hong Kong will be full of
boys,'' Ho said. ``Men will end up having to seek their wives
outside Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the demographic implications, some critics say sex
selection devalues childbirth in a city where people already treat
it like a dentist's appointment, something to be penciled in months
in advance. One obstetrician here said she had lost patients by
refusing to deliver their babies by Caesarean section at the
precise time dictated by a master of feng shui, the ancient art of
choosing auspicious locations and dates for harmonious balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it good enough just to have a baby?'' asked Mak Chung
Man, a Chinese herbalist who treats infertile couples. ``To control
the gender is asking too much. It's like going to a casino and
betting on certain chips.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Wong, he said he would abide by the law. But he noted
that it did not prohibit artificial insemination _ merely the
sorting of sperm. So could he move that part of his operation to
nearby Macao?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving me ideas,'' he said quietly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
