<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, Ext. 218.
WASHINGTON, June 30 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Patients-p
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 51-47, a patients' rights
measure. An amendment to an appropriations bill for federal
agencies, the provision would guarantee some patients access to
emergency room care and allow suits against health management
organizations in federal courts. Supporters said it would offer
greater patient protections than a bill approved last year that
barred lawsuits. Opponents said the measure would not cover all
insured Americans. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Patients-f
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday rejected, 47-51, a proposal to apply
patient protections to all insured Americans. The measure would
have been part of an appropriations bill for federal agencies.
Supporters said it would have covered approximately three times the
number helped by the limited patients' rights legislation that
passed. Opponents said the measure would have created a
bureaucratic federal health plan. A ``yes'' vote favors the
provision.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Sdisc
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 92-6, legislation to require
tax-exempt groups to disclose their finances. The bill, endorsed by
the House on Tuesday, would force political groups to report
contributors and spending. Supporters said it would control
campaign financing. Opponents said the plan would restrict free
speech. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: HRdisc
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday passed, 385-39, a bill to force
tax-exempt groups to disclose donors and expenses. Supporters said
it would control campaign financing. Opponents said the plan would
restrict free speech. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Rx2000
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 217-214, the Medicare Rx2000
Act. The bill would allow senior citizens to choose among
prescription drug plans managed by insurance companies. Federal
subsidies would ensure that all eligible citizens 65 and older
would be covered. Supporters said that seniors would pay less for
prescription care. Opponents defended uniform Medicare coverage,
denouncing the bill as unworkable. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Emergency
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 306-110, an $11.2 billion
emergency spending bill. The legislation provides funding for
troops in Kosovo, hurricane relief and drug trafficking prevention.
$1.3 billion would aid the Colombian Army. Supporters argued that
the Colombian provision would stem the flow of drugs into the
United States. Opponents denounced it as an escalation of Central
American military conflict and a poor substitute for drug
rehabilitation and education programs. A ``yes'' vote supports the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
