<HEADER>
A9966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-RUSSKIES-BO     06-30 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RUSSKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANTIARMS RACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 03, 2000) (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Washington and Moscow stumble toward a showdown over American
plans to deploy a national missile defense, their avoidable
confrontation is bringing out the worst in each country's
military-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has objected strenuously to the specter of an American
national missile defense system, threatening to withdraw from all
arms limitation agreements if Washington abandons the 1972 ABM
Treaty for the sake of 100 missile interceptors that, when tested,
could not distinguish warheads from simple decoys outside the
earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   As if Washington's heedless rush toward a technologically
dubious missile defense system were not bad enough, Moscow has
responded with an equally unrealistic proposal to obviate the need
for an American system with a missile defense system of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is the political will,'' Russian President
Vladimir Putin said during a recent trip to Berlin, speaking of his
proposal to deploy a missile shield over Russia and Europe, and
perhaps even the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as Putin may have in mind development of a boost-phase
antimissile defense _ one that targets missiles before they escape
the atmosphere, when they are traveling slower than in space and
giving off an easily identifiable heat signature _ his idea would
be worth pursuing cooperatively. But Russian defense officials have
not been very forthcoming in subsequent discussions on boost-phase
cooperation, and US officials insist they need to have some
national antimissile defense in place before 2005, when they fear
North Korea might be able to hit outlying islands of Alaska and
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, existing Russian interceptors around Moscow have
too short a range to protect Europe, much less the United States.
They are nuclear-tipped and meant to work on the principle of
``nuclear direct intercept'' _ to destroy targeted missile warheads
by setting off nuclear explosions within a kilometer of incoming
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in Moscow Times, the independent defense
analyst Pavel Felgenhauer _ who used to serve that function for Red
Star, the paper of the Soviet Red Army _ described the missile
defense system created to protect Moscow:
</P>
<P>
   ``The A-35 system was designed not to protect Moscow per se, but
to disable the first wave of incoming US warheads and give the
Soviet leadership 10 to 15 extra minutes to get airborne and out of
town before all hell breaks loose. Since Moscow was doomed anyway,
close-range nuclear intercept was considered acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is this left-over Soviet system of missile defense of
no use to anyone else, it also stands as a grotesque technological
metaphor for the relation between rulers and ruled in the homeland
of what Soviet officials liked to call ``real existing socialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Felgenhauer went on to explain that the missile defense Putin
has been touting to Europe would not use the A-35 system in place
for Moscow but Russia's ``S-300 long-range anti-aircraft missiles
or more advanced versions of the same weapon to shoot down rogue
missiles during the `boost phase.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since these S-300 missiles, which use shrapnel from conventional
explosives, are designed to bring down aircraft, Felgenhauer
explained, they would be useless against ICBMs _ as useless as
American interceptors whose infrared sensors cannot tell an empty
balloon from one containing a nuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's offer to cooperate on missile defense with Europe, then,
could only be what Felgenhauer called ``the same old Soviet `peace
initiative,' designed to produce cracks in Western ranks . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for Americans should not be that Russia is
indistinguishable from the imploded Soviet Union. Putin's Russia is
much weaker and has been much more cooperative on security matters.
The lesson should be that America's military-industrial complex, in
pursuing the boondoggle of a missile defense that is not yet
technologically possible, is stimulating its Russian counterpart to
peddle a complementary delusion.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian leaders in both countries need to solicit the
advice of honest, independent scientists and replace delusions with
policies that can truly make both more secure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
