<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GAZPROM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN GOVERNMENT ASSERTS MORE CONTROL OVER GAZPROM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's government strengthened its influence Friday
over natural gas giant Gazprom, the nation's biggest company,
loosening the grip of a entrenched management that shareholders say
has ignored their interests and obscured the company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   The government's increased control, which came in a shareholder
vote for a new board of directors, reflects a broader effort by
President Vladimir Putin to exert more authority over the country's
most important companies like Gazprom, which is Russia's biggest
cash-earner and supplier of a quarter of Western Europe's natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a common theme of the Putin presidency _ more
control over state assets,'' said Stephen Sullivan, head of
research at United Financial Group investment bank in Moscow.
``Gazprom is one of the state's major assets and it hasn't been
well served by the company in terms of shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   In the vote for a new board, shareholders tipped the balance to
favor the government, which controls 38.4 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The vote greatly reduced the influence of Gazprom s chief
executive, Rem Vyakhirev, who had wielded tremendous power in the
company. Shareholders also blocked Vyakhirev's proposal to require
a unanimous board vote to oust him as chief executive. Now a simple
majority of the 11-member board can remove him.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser close to Putin, Dmitry Medvedev, was elected
chairman, replacing former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who
used to run Gazprom. Over the past year, Chernomyrdin saw his
influence in the company wane. Earlier this week he denied Russian
press reports linking him to corruption charges by the Swiss
prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Minority shareholders won two seats on Gazprom's board,
including the first-ever foreign representative. That helped
strengthen Gazprom's share price, which soared on foreign exchanges
Friday. Local shares closed up more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom is one of Russia's most popular companies among foreign
investors. It is a giant, with revenue expected to total $15.9
billion this year, according to United Financial Group. However,
management has not adequately accounted for its vast assets,
investors and analysts say. Of the 546 billion cubic meters of gas
the company produced last year, its annual report accounts for
sales of only 474 billion, according to Moscow-based investment
bank Brunswick Warburg. That means about 13 percent of last year's
production is missing.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1924EDT &QL; 
