<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-MARCHING-BOS &LR;      06-30 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-MARCHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER GIRDS FOR THE RETURN OF `MARCHING SEASON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Mad Dog was foaming at the mouth.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny ``Mad Dog'' Adair worked himself up into a froth a couple
of weeks ago, spitting as he told how the Irish Republican Army was
driving innocent Protestant families from their homes all over
north and west Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with Mad Dog's story: It wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   After it emerged that 21 Catholic families had been intimidated
from their homes by the likes of Adair's buddies last month, while
there were no reports of Protestants being forced out, Mad Dog was
forced by his superiors in the Ulster Defense Association to
rescind his threat to shoot Catholics that he had delivered to a
group of reporters with his face hidden by a black ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   Now as all eyes turn Sunday to this sad, angry town, keeping a
leash on Mad Dog and his pack of bitter loyalist thugs is essential
if Northern Ireland is going to emerge from this year's annual
``marching season'' with the peace process intact.
</P>
<P>
   For pro-British loyalists, hardliners who want no part of
accommodating Catholic nationalists who aspire to a united Ireland,
this is their Alamo, their last stand. They have painted this
year's attempt to get a Protestant parade down the
Catholic-dominated Garvaghy Road in apocalyptic terms.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the barrier here, a 20-foot metal gate that
is locked and secured by the Royal Ulster Constabulary and British
troops, Catholics who live in the housing projects on either side
of the Garvaghy Road are as equally adamant that the Orange Order
not be allowed to march the traditional route.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has brought in 2,000 troops to back up the police for
the marching season.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants say they march to commemorate the 17th century
victory of the Protestant William of Orange over the Catholic King
James II, which established the Protestant hegemony in Northern
Ireland that has now crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics say the parade is a display of triumphalist bigotry,
aimed at reminding them who's boss.
</P>
<P>
   With such polarized, opposite views of the same event, there is
no hope for a compromise over the parade, unlike the compromises
that have pushed the political process in Northern Ireland far
along over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last November the Ulster Unionists dropped their demand that the
IRA begin disarming before they would sit in a power-sharing
government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political representatives. But
the power-sharing government collapsed after just 72 days when the
IRA refused to commit itself to disarming or saying their war was
over.
</P>
<P>
   The unionists compromised again, rejoining the government after
the IRA pledged to allow international inspectors to verify that
its arms remain locked up in hidden dumps, mostly in the Irish
Republic. On Monday, the two international inspectors, former
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and former African National
Congress general secretary Cyril Ramaphosa, announced that they had
inspected several arms dumps and said they were convinced the IRA
was serious about keeping its arms locked up to move the peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
   But the spirit of compromise that has been so evident in Belfast
this past year is nowhere to be found on the mean streets of
Portadown, the most segregated, bitter place in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The hatred is palpable here, always was. Catholics feel
isolated, sealed off from the rest of the town, and have no
intention of compromising so the Orangemen can enjoy a 15-minute
stroll down the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen of Portadown, meanwhile, are the most belligerent,
most uncompromising in Northern Ireland. They profess to be a
religious organization, but routinely include loyalist paramilitary
members as part of their entourage. Nearly every year, the
loyalists manage to kill innocent Catholics during their standoff
in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago loyalists set a Catholic home in Ballymoney on
fire, killing three young boys, an act that led to the suspension
of the Orangemen's stand on the field opposite Drumcree Church.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Police Chief Ronnie Flanagan said he feared hardliners
might seek to take over the march this year, producing more
violence. Loyalists have increasingly described this as their final
stand. The Orangemen usually try to march from Drumcree Church down
the Garvaghy Road on the second Sunday of July. But this year, they
formally applied for permission to march twice, this and next
Sunday. Their applications were rejected by the Northern Ireland
Parades Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Police and British military officials see this year's tactics by
the Orangemen as a concerted effort to draw out the standoff even
longer than usual, to stretch police and army resources as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Police are especially worried about ``Mad Dog'' Adair, a
maverick within the Ulster Defense Association, the biggest
loyalist paramilitary group that has, with a few murderous
exceptions, observed a cease-fire since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   According to senior detectives in the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
Adair is a multiple murderer who transformed a Belfast brigade of
UDA gunmen from petty racketeers to an efficient assassination
squad. In the early 1990s, Adair's ability to murder innocent
Catholics and especially a number of Sinn Fein members contributed
to the IRA being forced to consider calling its own cease-fire in
1994, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Adair was imprisoned, on what even republicans saw as cooked up
charges by a police force determined to get him off the street, but
he became a leading advocate for the peace process once in prison.
Some now believe that Adair was mainly interested in getting
himself out of prison, an argument that seems more credible now
that Adair has so publicly opposed the peace process, which he has
dismissed as having become a capitulation to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Police are worried that Adair and other UDA dissidents have been
able to organize the stragglers left in the Loyalist Volunteer
Force, a vicious, sectarian gang of murderers who were led by Billy
Wright until his murder by Irish republicans in the high-security
Maze Prison in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Wright's new group is headquartered here in
Portadown, where few loyalists have any faith in the peace process.
Wright and his followers had been members of the Ulster Volunteer
Force, the smaller of the two main loyalist paramilitary groups.
But the Ulster Volunteer Force threw him out, and threatened to
kill him and his followers, when Wright opposed the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Ulster Volunteer Force who support the peace
process and dissidents loyal to Wright have been killing each other
in an internecine war over the last few years. Adair, however, has
brought a sense of discipline to the dissidents, as he did when he
took over the UDA on the Shankill Road in Belfast a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   A detective who hates Adair conceded that he ``inspires loyalty
and he gets his men to put their pints aside until they do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fear among police is that Adair will assume a
legendary status among loyalists as Wright once did, being seen as
the great defender of the besieged Protestant working-class.
</P>
<P>
   This may not only be the last stand of loyalists in a place the
locals call Portydown. It may be Mad Dog's first stand, something
that sends shivers down the spines of those who hoped and may have
even begun to believe that the bad old days and the likes of Billy
Wright were behind them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
