<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PERFECT-GRACE-BOS &LR;      06-30 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-GRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `PERFECT STORM' DEVOTEES, EBAY OFFERS THE LADY GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the swirl of The Perfect Storm comes the perfect gift for
the mariner with everything else _ a fuel-guzzling movie prop with
sides of steel, a 360-horsepower diesel engine, a permit to catch
tuna, and a fake name on the stern.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Grace, purchased last year by Warner Brothers and used
to portray the ill-fated fishing boat Andrea Gail, went onto the
Internet auction block Thursday for those Perfect Storm
afficionados who want more than the plastic mackerel and squid
props also for sale at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding on eBay (www.ebay.com) closes July 7. As of Friday
night, the high bid was $86,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``See the movie. Buy the boat,'' teases the WB publicity
literature, and indeed, this baby's loaded. It comes with models of
radars, fishfinders, satellite faxing equipment, and radios that
were not around when the Gloucester, Mass.-based Andrea Gail sank
with all hands in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   How times change. Last September, in deference to the friends
and relatives of the six lost men, movie crews had draped tarps
over the vessel's ``Andrea Gail'' lettering when the cameras were
off. Now the 93-ton prop has become ``the perfect opportunity to
own an important piece of marine and move history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something just a little crass and hit-and-run about
all of this,'' declared Michael Salvi, a former Gloucester
fisherman, reflecting the views of some who remember the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more forgiving, partly because $25,000 from the sale
will be donated to The Gloucester Fund and the people impacted by
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, profits are part of the game, but those film people were
genuinely sympathetic,'' said Louis Linquata, a fisherman who had
worked with several of the 1991 victims. ``They still are.''
</P>
<P>
   For the future Lady Grace/Andea Gail owner, there's one hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer has to make the pickup in Hamburg, Germany, where the
vessel is headed to participate in the Mid-July European opening of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Fraser, editor-in-chief of National Fisherman, finds this
a somewhat amusing way to buy a boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to bid for a boat unseen, then fly to another
continent and bring it home,'' he said. ``At least it appears that
you can start fishing part way home.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   While the vessel holds a current permit for tuna, its permit for
sword fishing _ the operation that put the Andrea Gail on the
silver screen _ has expired, according to Kate Naughten, a
spokeswoman for the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the specifications suggest a remarkably dynamic craft.
For example, Warner Brothers lists the boat as 72 feet long. The
Coast Guard registration lists it as 57.9 feet long. Warner
Brothers says the fuel tanks hold 6,000 gallons on one Web page,
and 10,000 gallons on another page. Either way, a 360-horsepower
engine quaffs 12 gallons an hour, and with the going price for
diesel about $1.20 a gallon, the vigilant mariner should think
twice before saying ``fill 'er up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've gonna really have to like the movie to spring for this,
because it's gonna be worse than a Hummer to operate,'' quipped one
fisherman on the Boston Fish Pier.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. The 22-year-old Lady has got her sea legs.
Warner Brothers bought the vessel in early 1999 in Ocean City, Md.,
and almost made a filming date in Los Angeles via the Panama Canal
when an actor's scheduling conflict foiled the shoot. So the vessel
turned around and went all the way back, past Norfolk to Gloucester
for another film date.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back again to southern California after surviving
Hurricane Lenny off Cuba and a breakdown off El Salvador. This
spring the boat returned to Gloucester, and is now en route to
Germany. That's 25,000 miles and change in 17 months, which begins
to rival what the clipper ships did in the early 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   Now Warner Brothers wants someone else to bring the boat home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
