<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-FATIQUE0701-     06-30 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-FATIQUE0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eating on the run, riders are models of efficiency
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Tour de France is the most physically
demanding major sporting event in the world. It's torturous
mountain climbs and desperate sprints contested over 2,255.7 miles
and 21 stages. It's hearts pounding as fast as 200 beats per minute
and legs continuing to churn when they sear with the will-sapping
lactic acid of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tour, Lance Armstrong and the other human engines mounted
on bikes will have to burn massive amounts of fuel to pedal all
those miles. Those who are most efficient at that task have the
best chance of being cloaked in the yellow jersey at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to the physiology of performance,'' said Eddie
Coyle, head of the Human Performance Lab at the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates vary on just how much daily fuel a Tour de France
rider needs. Some say 7,000 calories, about five times what an
average 150-pound man might need simply to exist. Some say 8,000
calories a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's six hours a day expending up to 9,000 calories every day,
and it's going on day after day,'' said Coyle, who has done
sophisticated measurements on Armstrong and some other elite
endurance athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a Men's Health article compared the 8,730 daily
calories consumed by cyclist David Phinney and the intakes of some
other athletes. Then-heavyweight boxer George Foreman wolfed down
4,579 calories in a day, 7-foot San Antonio Spurs basketball star
David Robinson loaded up with 5,030, decathlete Dan O'Brien used
4,213 to fuel his practice in 10 sports, 6-foot-7-inch swimmer Matt
Biondi consumed 4,752, NFL defensive end Bruce Smith 4,074 and
marathoner Steve Spence ate 4,157.
</P>
<P>
   Tour de France riders have to take in as much as they expend
each day because they don't have much else to burn. Armstrong has
about 3 percent body fat.
</P>
<P>
   Typically if a rider starts losing weight on the Tour, he won't
be able to reverse the trend and will be on his way out. The
cyclists all know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be eating or drinking something every 15 minutes when
they're riding. They know exactly how much they need to take in,''
Coyle said. ``The first hour or two is more like a rolling meal.
They'll be handed food from the cars or they'll grab a feed bag, a
bag with a long string.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat after the first hour until about an hour to go,''
Armstrong said. ``I eat a lot of simple sugars in the race like
energy bars or cookies. After the race it's complex carbs like
potatoes and pasta.''
</P>
<P>
   During the race, Coyle said riders need to consume 60 grams of
carbohydrates per hour. They'll eat bread and jelly and sandwiches
and a variety of other foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bananas are one of their favorite foods. It's the original
energy bar. It even has a wrapper,'' Coyle said. Bananas also are
rich in potassium, the depletion of which can lead to muscle
cramping.
</P>
<P>
   Sports drinks are popular for replacing lost nutrients and
fluids. It's been estimated that Tour riders sweat away 10 to 12
liters of water a day.
</P>
<P>
   While replenishing food and water is vital for Tour riders,
that's just the basics. What counts is how efficiently they are
able to convert food into energy. Even the very best aren't .300
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 25 percent goes to power the pedals,'' Coyle said. ``The
rest becomes heat. For Lance, less and less goes to heat. We've
seen his efficiency increase by 6 percent in recent years. Before
that he was just average (among elite cyclists).''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle said there are 10 different measures he uses for measuring
cycling performance, with muscle efficiency being just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one category where he is superhuman, but Lance is
high in everything,'' Coyle said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Armstrong is ``incredible'' when it comes to the
level of lactic acid his muscles produce. He doesn't generate much
of the burning energy sapper, which allows him to work at very high
levels for longer periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   A measure the cycling world likes to use is maximal oxygen
intake or VO2max, which is measured in meters per kilogram of body
weight. According to Coyle, Armstrong's rating is between 80 and
82, which again puts him on the high end, even for elite cyclists.
Tour de France legend Miguel Indurain has been reported to have a
rating between 92 and 95, but Coyle said it's more like 78.
Indurain almost has been said to have a resting heart rate of 28
beats per second, but Coyle said it's in the 40s, like Armstrong's
and many other cyclists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many myths being perpetuated,'' Coyle said.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of three grueling weeks and more than 2,000 miles
should dispel a few.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, start your human engines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
