u a BC-GA-WATER-NYT &LR;      06-30 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT AND GROWTH POSE CHALLENGES TO WATERING METROPOLITAN
ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALPHARETTA, Ga. _ The long drive leading to the water treatment
plant is bordered by grass that is suspiciously green, with flowers
that are clearly healthy and _ can that be a purely ornamental
fountain recklessly gurgling water in the midst of one of the great
droughts in Georgia history?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK; it's all done with recycled water,'' said Mike
Leonard, the plant's general manager. ``I just wish we could get
everyone to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will probably be many years before the suburban
homeowners of the South begin routinely soaking their gardens with
used bath water. As serious as the drought is _ and in the last
week it has edged farther into neighboring Alabama and South
Carolina _ it is essentially a passing phenomenon, and the warnings
of water system managers like Leonard have still not changed the
basic instincts of Atlanta-area residents to water their sprawling
lawns for hours at a time. (The summer's strict watering
restrictions across the metro region have helped, though.)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it is the region's stupendous growth, not its
weather, that poses the most serious challenge to its water supply,
putting the Atlanta-Fulton County Water Treatment Plant on the
front lines of the effort to keep the eight-county metropolitan
region of 3.2 million people from running dry. The ring of suburbs
around Atlanta has been one of the fastest-growing settlements in
American history, and the state of Georgia says that at the current
rate of growth, the region will exceed its water capacity in 2030.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, himself a suburban resident with a browning lawn, has
seen that growth firsthand at the helm of a gleaming,
state-of-the-art plant that supplies drinking water to about
300,000 people in the section of Fulton County north of Atlanta
city limits. When the plant opened in 1991, it pumped 3.8 billion
gallons of water a year; in 1999, its output more than quadrupled
to 16.8 billion gallons. The county has had to expand the plant
well ahead of schedule to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just keep moving in, and it's all centered right in our
area,'' said Leonard, relaxed in a polo shirt while millions of
gallons of treated water flowed to the region's faucets in pipes
beneath his office. ``And when summer comes, they turn on the
timers on their watering systems and just let them run. This
summer, we really felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of warm-weather water consumption in a suburban area
like North Fulton is poured directly on lawns and gardens, making
suburbanites much bigger water consumers than their city
counterparts. Faced with an extremely dry April and May, homeowners
who rely on the plant turned on their hoses and did not stop, and
Leonard's plant was often unable to keep up with demand. The big
computer screen in his office, which shows graphic representations
of storage tanks and pipelines, spent several days this spring
flashing alarms about dangerously low water pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The plant and the distribution network rushed to keep up, but
many homes in the county had only a trickle of water. A major fire
on one of those days could have caused a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   At Leonard's urging, the Fulton County area outside the city of
Atlanta quickly imposed a ban on watering between 10 a.m. and 10
p.m., but it was not enough _ water levels fell every morning and
every night. Now the county has one of the strictest bans in the
state: outdoor watering can be done only between 10 p.m. and 5
a.m., and then only on alternate days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working,'' Leonard said. ``For now, we're doing OK. I've
been telling people, dirty's beautiful. If you don't wash your car,
you get a red badge of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard gets to work around 6 a.m. preparing for more water
distribution headaches, but his more pressing concerns are for the
future. Every drop pumped by his plant is sucked directly from the
adjacent Chattahoochee River, the principal water source for a
region without underground aquifers from which to draw. Most of the
other counties and cities farther downstream also draw from the
river and are also planning to step up their use, while Alabama and
Florida are threatening a legal battle if Georgia does not begin to
reduce its reliance on that river and others.
</P>
<P>
   To save water, high-tech plants like the one in North Fulton
will have to begin more processing of treated sewage water, sending
it out to be consumed. But at the same time, the accelerating
development in the region is filling the river with sediment and
pollution, making it even harder to treat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make it past the year 2030, we're going to have to rely on
greater treatment technologies,'' said Pat Stevens, the
environmental planning chief at the Atlanta Regional Commission,
the planning body that encompasses the eight county metro area and
the city of Atlanta. ``It puts a lot of pressure on these plant
managers to come up with solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, 51 and the father of two daughters, is an Atlanta
native who spent his summers as a teen-ager working for the city's
water department, later studying chemistry and business at Mercer
University. He has since become an expert on water quality, serving
as drinking water enforcement chief for the Environmental
Protection Agency before coming to work for Fulton County in 1990.
Much of his job involves finding new ways to use chemicals and
filtering techniques to keep the water pure, like selling cakes of
dried river sediment as compost instead of sending them downstream
for another county to treat.
</P>
<P>
   But Leonard has also become an evangelist for water
conservation, urging businesses to spend money on water-recycling
devices, planting drought-tolerant varieties of grasses and shrubs
around his home and _ since the watering ban _ making a nuisance of
himself around his Alpharetta neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive around my neighborhood wondering why all those
people were pouring all that perfectly nice drinking water onto the
ground,'' he said. ``Now I just turn them in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
