u w BC-CLINTON-DISBAR-NYT &LR;      06-30 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISBAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARATION FOR CLINTON DISBARMENT TRIAL MOVES FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A committee of the Arkansas Supreme Court filed
suit in Little Rock, Ark., Friday asking a state court to enforce
its recommendation that President Clinton be stripped of his law
license for falsely denying under oath that he had a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The filing set in motion the preparation for a full-fledged
trial in a Little Rock courtroom, perhaps as early as this fall,
over Clinton's fitness to be a lawyer. The lawsuit before the
Pulaski County Circuit Court became inevitable last month when the
committee said that the president should be disbarred for what it
said was ``serious misconduct'' in his testimony in the sexual
misconduct lawsuit filed against him by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kendall, a Washington lawyer who is representing
Clinton in the Arkansas case, said Friday night, ``We fundamentally
disagree with the complaint filed today and will defend vigorously
against it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case will be heard without a jury. It was first randomly
assigned by a computer Friday to Judge John Ward of the Pulaski
County Circuit Court. But Ward immediately recused himself, noting
that Clinton first appointed him to the bench in 1988, when Clinton
was governor of Arkansas. Ward said in an interview that ``it would
create an impression of impropriety should I accept that case.''
</P>
<P>
   The case will be sent back to the computer to be assigned to
someone else, but court officials acknowledged that it might not be
easy to assign it to an impartial judge.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in Arkansas are elected, but governors fill unexpected
vacancies in the middle of judicial terms. Because Clinton served
as the state's governor for many years, he was able to appoint
dozens of state judges.
</P>
<P>
   Even those he did not initially appoint ran for their seats in
partisan elections and thus are either associated with the
Democratic or Republican parties. Some of the other seven judges on
the court suggested that they would ask to be excused from
presiding over a trial involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers have 30 days to respond to the formal
request for disbarment. Court officials said that would mean the
trial could occur as early as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Professor John DiPippa of the University of Arkansas Law
School at Little Rock said Friday night that finding a suitable and
willing judge was only one of the issues that could delay the
trial. In addition, DiPippa said that Clinton's lawyers would be
able to postpone the trial perhaps even until the president left
office by filing various motions.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial occurred while Clinton was still president, he
probably would not appear on his own behalf. When the committee
reached its conclusion recommending disbarment, Clinton said that
his lawyers would mount a vigorous defense, but that he would not
participate personally while still in office.
</P>
<P>
   Dipippa said that no matter what the judge decides, the ruling
may be appealed directly to the state Supreme Court. He added that
such cases are routinely appealed whether the trial judge decides
in favor or against the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the case against Clinton involves his testimony
during a January 1998 deposition in Paula Jones' sexual misconduct
suit. In the presence of the federal judge presiding over the case,
Susan Webber Wright, he said that he did not have sexual relations
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   That August, he told a federal grand jury that he did, in fact,
have an inappropriate intimate relationship with Lewinsky. Wright
cited Clinton for contempt of court, fined him and recommended that
the state Supreme Court consider disciplinary action against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-LANCE0701-CO     06-30 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-LANCE0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong ready to ride
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ On a sun-splashed Sunday afternoon in
Paris last July 25, the director of the Tour de France actually
smiled at the notion of a brash, tough-talking Texan winning his
country's quintessential sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 fans lining the Champs Elysees that day
to watch Lance Armstrong take his celebratory victory stroll past
the Eiffel Tower and the Arc de Triomphe, there appeared to be as
many people waving Lone Star and American flags as there were
flag-waving fanatics from rabid cycling countries such as France,
Italy and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance Armstrong is the best winner the Tour can imagine,''
proclaimed Tour director Jean Marie LeBlanc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebirth of Armstrong is amazing and is good for the
rebirth of the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc was keenly aware then that Armstrong, a survivor of
testicular cancer, was the feel-good story the event needed to
distance itself from drug allegations that threatened the race's
existence the year before.
</P>
<P>
   That feel-good story opens a new chapter today when the
three-week-long Tour begins with the traditional prologue, a
9.9-mile mini time trial in Futuroscope. The scientific-themed
amusement park about 200 miles southwest of Paris was the site of
Armstrong's fourth stage victory in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 180 participants representing 20 teams from eight countries
will compete in 21 stages over 23 days. Those who finish the
grueling race will ride 2,255.7 miles, starting southwest of Paris,
then turning north to Britany, before heading back to the center of
the country for the Tour's relatively easy, flatter stages. Then
the riders will head south to the Pyrenees mountains, with steeper
climbs ahead of them in the French Alps. The cyclists will stray
briefly into Switzerland and Germany before heading back to the
final stage in Paris, which starts at the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   This year's route promises to be more punishing than 1999, with
more treacherous mountain climbs and fewer flatter stages.
Armstrong, who excels in time trials, also is an excellent climber.
He won the first mountain stage of the 1999 Tour, with the victory
basically cementing his title more than a week before the cyclists
got to the finishing stage in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, speaking last week by phone from his spring-summer
home in Nice, France, wouldn't predict a repeat victory. But he
talked as if there were no doubts in his mind that he would claim
another Tour for the U.S. Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better than I did last year,'' Armstrong said.
``Mentally, I'm more aware of what I need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I had no idea I really could win the Tour. I never
thought I could do that. I was really surprised when I won it. Now,
I know I can do it because I know what I had to do last year.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more emphatic about his ever-growing confidence when he
arrived in Futuroscope this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I'm not as nervous as I was last year,''
Armstrong said. ``My life is pretty comfortable right now.
Fatherhood has helped calm me down when it comes to racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have watched Armstrong continue to develop since last
year's momentous achievement say he should be the undisputed
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, Lance is at least as good as last year, and
mentally he is stronger than last year,'' said Johan Bruyneel, the
director of Armstrong's U.S. Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's even better than he was last year,'' said Chris
Carmichael, Armstrong's longtime coach. ``He's ready to go. He's
another year removed from the cancer. And he won the race last
year, so he will be really confident.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST-SELLER MATERIAL
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's Tour preparation has been no different from last
year. He again rode all of the Tour's routes during his training
sessions, a feat that once was unthinkable in international cycling
circles, concentrating especially on the climbs. Until the 1999
Tour, most top competitors had been dependent on others to map out
the route of each stage. Armstrong took out the middleman so that
he would be familiar with every nuance when he rides the routes for
real.
</P>
<P>
   The only negative training episode occurred in late May, when he
suffered a mild concussion. The injury, which Armstrong suffered
after a downhill crash on a training run in the French Alps, made
international headlines. After spending a night in the hospital and
a weekend off his bike, he was competing again, finishing third in
the Classique des Alps and the Dauphine Libere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my crash was overblown,'' Armstrong said. ``I
recovered more quickly than they thought I could. It definitely set
things back some. But it was probably a good thing. I was maybe
ahead of schedule (before the crash). So it came at a good time.
Now if I had to spend 10 days off my bike, then it would have hurt
my training for the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparation aside, nothing else has been the same for the
28-year-old since that July afternoon when he won the Tour, the
third most popular sporting event in the world behind the Olympics
and soccer's World Cup. Even the French media, which never has
warmed up to Armstrong's American habits, applauded Armstrong's
achievement, with L'Equipe, the French daily sports newspaper,
calling his feat the ``comeback of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the bike, Armstrong has become a father _ his son, Luke
David, was born in October _ and a best-selling author. His book,
``It's Not About the Bike,'' ranked ninth on Sunday's New York
Times best-sellers' list for non-fiction.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IS RICH
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong last was in Austin in April for his ``Ride for the
Roses'' weekend to raise money for the Lance Armstrong Foundation.
His wife, Kristin, stayed an extra week to oversee the selling of
their mansion on Lake Austin, a home he designed and had built in
1996. The home, which he named ``Casa Linda'' to honor his mother,
Linda Armstrong, was completed five months before he was diagnosed
with advanced testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to sell the house,'' he said. ``The thing was, I
wasn't really there for the sell. It wasn't like there was this day
that I sort of walked out and said, `This is it, I'll never be
back.' But earlier in the season, when I left for France in
February, I had a feeling that it would be the last night in my
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely cared a lot for that house.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he returns to Austin this fall, his family, which also
includes a yellow tabby cat named Chemo and a small white Maltese
named Boone, temporarily will live in a house in Tarrytown.
Sometime soon, the Armstrongs will finish plans for their home near
Lake Travis, which will have more privacy than the previous one,
which was accessible to every boater sailing by on Lake Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's wealth also has increased about seven times since
his Tour win. He is expected to make about $7 million this year,
roughly the same salary as Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman.
According to Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's Austin-based agent, $5
million of his client's annual income has come from endorsements.
His salary with U.S. Postal was $500,000 before his Tour win. It
has been renegotiated to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has lent his name to several high-profile companies.
He has been featured in eight national television commericals
representing Nike (three), American General Insurance, AIM Mutual
Funds, Wheaties, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Bridge Information
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of his marketing deals have come from American
companies. In the winter off-season, Armstrong proved to be a
popular speaker, with companies paying up to $100,000, plus
first-class expenses for two, to get Armstrong to appear at their
functions. Before the Tour, Armstrong's asking price was $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's the favorite to repeat his Tour victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have asked which one would be harder to win, the first
one or the second one,'' he said. ``That's a good question. It was
hard to win the first one because I'd never done it before. The
second one, I don't have the anonymity as I did last year. When
you're the defending champion, you're a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I made my comeback from cancer. If you compare that
to repeating as defending champion, I think coming back from cancer
and winning the first one was definitely harder. This one should be
a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
