u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-30 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI SURVIVES BY TAKING ADVANTAGE OF MARTIN'S NERVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A handful of games into Andre Agassi's
unnerving fifth-set slide toward extinction Friday, the
introspective soul-searcher stopped his service motion to allow a
bird to swoop into Center Court, circle, and then exit.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the carrier pigeon that he was looking for. There was
no message to help Agassi decode the unassuming but unrelenting
Todd Martin as he continued to plunge into a 2-5 chasm.
</P>
<P>
   But on his way to saving two match points, Agassi came to rely
on Martin's demons to aid his tense and improbable 6-4, 2-6, 7-6
(3), 2-6, 10-8 escape on the fifth day of Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   From across the net, the second-seeded Agassi watched his U.S.
counterpart lose his nerve on returns, try too much on second
serves and begin missing forehand volleys on floating returns that
dangled in front of Martin's eyes like soap bubbles. It was like
1996 again, when in the semifinals at Wimbledon, Center Court
became a burial site for Martin's composure when he failed to close
out MaliVai Washington after taking a 5-1 lead in the fifth and
final set, only to lose by what is now the hauntingly familiar
score of 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is possible for players to develop certain
reputations where you can count on certain weaknesses,'' Agassi
said. ``I wouldn't put the label `choking' on Todd. While there was
a certain opportunity he definitely let go of, it takes a lot more
than one time before you feel like that's actually a weakness of a
certain player.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at 5-2 down, while I was aware of the fact that he's
managed to do that here before on Center Court, I certainly didn't
expect it. But when I got the break with the double fault at
30-all, it did start crossing my mind, `Make him play, at least
make him win it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It took a while. A 3 hour47 minute match that was suspended by
rain after three sets and one game of play Thursday night finally
ended after a 70-minute fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   The resilience of Pete Sampras, the defending champion, was not
tested Friday. After tendinitis crept into his lower left shin
Wednesday, Sampras was given another day of rest when his
third-round match with Justin Gimelstob was postponed until
Saturday due to rain.
</P>
<P>
   The elements also washed out Venus Williams' third-round match.
Between rain delays, Venus sat as a hooded spectator for her
sister's match against Cristina Torrens-Valero. Against a backdrop
of wild applause, Serena Williams walked onto Court One in her
white warm-up jacket, with her first name stitched stylishly across
the back. It might as well have been a heavyweight boxer's shiny
silk robe. With 12 aces, Serena Williams unleashed a flurry of
power to dismiss the Spaniard, 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking good, and I'm feeling good,'' said Serena
Williams, looking for her second Grand Slam after winning the U.S.
Open last summer. ``I think that I'm actually doing a lot of things
better than I was at the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up to Williams at the U.S. Open was taking note.
Understanding how sharp she'll have to be to get past Williams
should they meet in the semifinals, Martina Hingis made quick work
of the 22nd-ranked Silvija Talaja of Croatia, 6-2, 6-2, to advance
to the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a great situation here,'' said Hingis, who was defeated
in the first round here last year. ``I have nothing to defend. I
just can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring an upset, Hingis and Venus Williams will meet in the
quarterfinals. Friday, jumping ahead was a matter of reflex.
Because for another day, the American dream final of Sampras and
Agassi still has life after Martin experienced a re-creation of his
1996 collapse on Center Court. Visibly drained from his unthinkable
finish, Martin couldn't deny the similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, for sure, there were points where I got tight, and those
were critical points,'' said Martin, who was serving for the match
at 5-2 in the fifth set but double faulted at 30-all. ``From there,
you know, I tried to keep '96 in my mind so I could draw from the
positives that I found from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do it again. That was part of it. I was trying not to
think so much about, `OK, you're up, 5-2, you're serving at
15-all.' You say, `What's the best way to win this point?' Then, at
30-all, I overhit my first serve, and on the second serve I said,
`You know, let's be aggressive with it.' I remember that's the
thing I struggled with most a few years ago. I was aggressive with
it, and I didn't make it. Sort of live by the risks, die by the
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had a 5-3 lead and two match points on Agassi's serve.
But he allowed one second serve by Agassi to handcuff him, and then
lost control of a volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the serve, it ended up taking a little bit of a low bounce
and sliding a little bit,'' Martin said. ``I think if I was a
little more composed and a little bit more relaxed, then I can
adjust to that ball and get it in play.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't unwind, though, and Agassi drew life from Martin's
distress. He took advantage of a backhand by Martin that died into
the net for a break point to tie the fifth set at 5-5. Then Agassi
continued his run of four straight games by changing his tactics _
coming in on one point, staying back on the next _ to go up, 6-5.
Although Martin steadied himself to hold serve in front of a crowd
that stirred each time Agassi was in peril, he couldn't hold it
together through the end.
</P>
<P>
   On the 18th game of the fifth set, Agassi watched Martin send a
backhand into the net for the final break he needed, the one that
gave him the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I needed a little help from him at 5-2 down,''
Agassi said. ``I was very lucky to get back into that match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
