<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-STRATEGY0701     06-30 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-STRATEGY0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong's plan shouldered by his mountain men
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As the U.S. Postal Service riders gathered at
Futuroscope for the start of the Tour de France, Kevin Livingston
was asked via telephone about the team's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall plan is to get into Paris with Lance wearing the
yellow jersey,'' Livingston chuckled. ``The Tour, you have to
respect it. It's a three-week race. There are too many variables.
So much can happen. We'll have to see how the race plays out. But
if you're going to win, you have to win the hard days.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the hard days in the Tour are the climbs, and the
route this year is more demanding than the one on which Armstrong
pedaled to triumph last year.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven climbs so severe they are rated ``beyond
classification'' in this Tour and they all fall from July 10-July
16 as the Tour hits the Pyrenees and then the Alps. The most
picturesque, storied and character testing should be on Mont
Ventoux, a 6,260-foot-high lump of heartbreak dubbed the ``Giant of
Provence.''
</P>
<P>
   It's on such climbs that Livingston will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest job should be to make sure Lance has some teammates
in the mountains,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Tyler Hamilton are the team's specialist in that area.
George Hincapie, Frankie Andreu and Viatcheslav Ekimov are better
on flat terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The main job of all members of the team, which also includes
Cedric Vasseur, Benoit Joachim and Steffan Kjaergaard, is to aid
and protect Armstrong. It is not an easy task. It's believed that
helpers, or ``domestiques,'' who ride in front to break the wind
for the team's leader, expend 30 percent more energy in an an event
that already taxes the body to its limits.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating U.S. Postal's strategy for the Tour is its
director, John Bruyneel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day we talk. We try to make a strategy and then see what
happens,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston added that as the day's race develops, sometimes an
experienced rider like Andreu will make a quick strategy decision.
More likely, though, decisions will be made from a car armed with a
radio, television and communications system.
</P>
<P>
   The riders are all plugged into radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing,'' Livingston said. ``They're about as big
as a credit card and as thick as three credit cards. The mic is
clipped on the jersey. You pinch it to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The riders can all talk to each other, not just the director.
The team will be linked just as tightly on the 43-mile fourth
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a team time trial this year. We have to step up so
that it doesn't hinder Lance and hopefully even helps him,''
Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston and another U.S. Postal rider, Christian Vande Velde,
both suffered fractured collarbones earlier in the season. Vande
Velde appeared to have recovered from that only to be sidelined by
an infected and swollen area near his tailbone, believed to have
been caused by a particularly nasty spider bite. He has been
replaced by Kjaergaard for the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said, ``In terms of the injury, I'm fully recovered.
Once I got back on the road I started training pretty hard. I don't
feel like I lost too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
