<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-DATABASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYSMART SELLING CUSTOMER DATABASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ In what may be an increasingly common scenario
in the dot-com world, personal information on thousands of
Toysmart.com customers has been put up for sale in potential
violation of Toysmart's own privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection
in June, is planning to sell customer information to settle its
debts with creditors, confirmed David Lord, chief executive of the
Waltham, Mass. online toy seller.
</P>
<P>
   Lord also said his company was contacted last week by the
Federal Trade Commission about the sale of Toysmart's customer
list. Lord said his company is negotiating a settlement with the
FTC, which just weeks ago lobbied Congress for stronger legislation
to protect consumer privacy over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For Toysmart, the dilemma is between selling its customer list
to pay back more than $20 million in debt, and keeping its pledge
not to share customer information with outside parties. It is a
problem that could become more common as dozens of online retailers
appear headed for financial failure, privacy advocates warn.
</P>
<P>
   As Toysmart's attorneys scramble to untangle its unanticipated
quandary, lawmakers and privacy advocates are quick to condemn
Toysmart's plans to sell its customer list.
</P>
<P>
   In a searing statement released Friday, TRUSTe, an industry
watchdog based in San Jose, Calif., said it ``believes that the
sale of this data is ethically wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line here is we believe this is an invasion of
privacy,'' said Bob Lewin, executive director of TRUSTe, which has
more than 2,000 corporate members, including Yahoo!, Lycos,
Microsoft Corp., and Excite(at)Home.
</P>
<P>
   Lewin's comments were extraordinary since Toysmart is a member
of TRUSTe.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Lt. Gov. Jane Swift, who has adopted a strong
consumer privacy plank, said she is searching for a legal remedy to
either prevent the sale or, failing that, to require that all
customers on the list be notified of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Office of Consumer Affairs is looking into this,'' said
Swift, who also happens to be a Toysmart customer, having purchased
an ant farm and a Winnie the Pooh drum for her godchildren last
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   FTC officials declined to comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy experts say customers of Toysmart volunteered personal
information based on the company's pledge not to share or sell that
data. Toysmart's policy, posted on the company's Web site, states,
``When you register with toysmart.com, you can rest assured that
your information will never be shared with a third party.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates are also concerned that anyone buying the list
_ which contains names, home addresses, e-mail addresses, telephone
numbers and order information _ will not be bound by Toysmart's
privacy policies because the list will have been purchased during a
bankruptcy court proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a huge loophole,'' said Marc Rotenberg, director
of the Electronic Privacy Information Center in Washington, D.C.,
and a professor at the Georgetown University Law Center. ``We
simply don't think companies should have the right to sell customer
data in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a scenario that will inevitably be repeated as numerous
Internet commerce Web sites head towards financial doom and are
left with little more than their customer lists as assets. In an
era where information is power, such lists are coveted by
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Lord said several companies have expressed interest in buying
the Toysmart list, but all are ``family oriented companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not sell our information to an inappropriate
organization,'' Lord said. ``We reserve the right to accept or
reject any bid. We will not alienate our customers, not while I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart attorney Harry Murphy, of Hanify &AMP; King in Boston, said
the company is ``working with the FTC to reach a resolution that is
satisfactory to both the FTC and the company.'' Possible remedies
could include selling the list to another toy company that promises
to commit to specific privacy protections.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Steer, a spokesman for TRUSTe, said the case is
precendent-setting and points to a potential ``information Valdez''
in which the personal data of millions of people who buy products
online from retailers that later go bankrupt can be scattered far
and wide without the consumers' knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more companies go belly up, this type of incident can
happen again and again,'' Steer said. ``So it's important that we
plug this up now before we end up with an information Valdez where
personal and private information are uncontrollably spilled out.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of online retailing is widely known to be in the midst
of a financial shakeout with many companies expected to fail in the
next few months. As they go under, many will be tempted to sell
their customer data to help pay debts.
</P>
<P>
   London-based Boo.com, for example, sold data on 350,000
customers to Fashionmall.com after going out of business earlier
this year. Another online casualty, CraftShop.com, is actively
seeking a buyer for its customer data, despite a vow on the
company's Web site to ``never release it to any person or any
company for any purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   These promises, some point out, were written without considering
the possibility of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be funny for a Web site to say, `We promise to
protect your privacy unless we go out of business,' '' said John
Zittrain, professor at Harvard Law School. Zittrain said customer
information is routinely sold by non-Internet businesses, from
catalog companies to medical practices, making the Toysmart case
somewhat ambiguous. ``This is not a slam dunk for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is a sale of Toysmart's customer list, given the
hailstorm of criticism that has fallen on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not advise my client to purchase this list because of
the numerous, highly sensitive privacy related issues,'' said an
attorney who represents a Toysmart creditor and who declined to be
identified. ``In this case, what comes to mind is a hornet's
nest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
