<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-DRUGS-405(2TAKES     06-30 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DRUGS-405(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, IN INTERVIEW, ASSAILS PHARMACEUTICAL COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attacking the pharmaceutical industry for engaging
in ``corporate chutzpah'' and for ``gouging the consumer
unfairly,'' Vice President Al Gore said Friday that he would take
on the drug manufacturers next week at campaign stops in
battleground states from California to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on the veranda of his home here, Gore cast
himself as a longtime critic of the industry's excessive prices and
profits. He does, in fact, have a long record on the topic, dating
to his days as a young Tennessee congressman in the early 1980s,
when he played a crucial role in defeating legislation that would
have granted patent extensions on lucrative medicines.
</P>
<P>
   So Gore is dusting off his congressional record and past
speeches to stake out policies at odds with the manufacturers. But
a careful review of his record, and a detailed talk with the vice
president himself, makes clear that his views are more nuanced than
his fiery rhetoric suggests. And some of the same drug companies
that Gore now criticizes have hired his friends and advisers to
represent them as lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Gore's positions have been embraced by the
pharmaceutical industry. For instance, pharmaceutical manufacturers
are among the biggest beneficiaries of the government's tax credit
for research and development, and Gore favors legislation that
would make that credit permanent. While he argued for greater
disclosure of the industry's pricing practices, the vice president
allowed that some information probably should remain proprietary.
And Gore has also been a strong supporter of the biotechnology
industry, which through collaborations and mergers is increasingly
becoming part and parcel of the prescription drug business.
</P>
<P>
   With his heightened, anti-industry rhetoric that consumers are
``being ripped off'' by drug makers, the vice president is
positioning himself as a champion of a far-reaching Medicare
prescription drug benefit for senior citizens. He is also
attempting to sharpen the political distinctions between himself
and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who supports a benefit that would
rely more heavily on private insurers _ an approach the industry
favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself as a basher of the pharmaceutical
companies,'' the vice president said. ``I see myself as opposing
the excesses that have accompanied their enormous market power,
excesses that have come at the expense of consumers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Industry lobbyists say privately that they have mixed feelings
about Gore. His support for innovation and new technology endears
him to them, and he is not nearly as strident a critic as the Green
Party candidate, Ralph Nader. But industry executives are becoming
increasingly nervous about Gore as the presidential campaign
progresses. And when asked about Friday's escalating attack, their
trade association responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly sad to hear the vice president arguing for reducing
incentives for biomedical innovation,'' said Alan F. Holmer,
president of the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, in a statement. ``If his rhetoric became government
policy, patients would suffer. Thankfully, no one will be fooled by
political posturing four months before an election.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is reflected in the financial contributions the
two major presidential contenders have received. To date, Bush's
campaign has received $221,715 from pharmaceutical company
executives, while Gore has received $50,700, election records show.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry is one of the nation's most
lucrative, and secretive, businesses. It consistently ranks as the
most profitable industry in the Fortune 500 list of companies; in
1999, the industry's net profit after taxes was 18.9 percent of
revenues, as compared with 15.8 percent for the next most
profitable industry, and 5 percent overall, according to a recent
compilation by the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers argue that their prices are justified by the high
costs, and extreme risks, of researching and developing new
medicines. And they say they need substantial profits to plow back
into research and development, clearing the way for the next
generation of wonder drugs. From the industry's perspective, any
threat to profits or drug prices is a threat to innovation.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not made the prescription drug issue a
cornerstone of his campaign, one of his top health advisers said
this week that the Texas governor is philosophically opposed to
tampering with the industry's ability to develop life-saving
medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that would dampen innovation, particularly price
controls, ought to be avoided,'' said Dr. Bill Roper, who was a top
health official in the administration of Bush's father, and is now
dean of the School of Public Health at the University of North
Carolina. ``We need to trust the marketplace,'' he added. The Bush
campaign did not make the Texas governor available for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Friday that he, too, is opposed to regulating drug
prices, or profits. ``I don't see it as the government's role,'' he
said. But he does say the industry's profits are out of line, and
he favors policies that would, in effect, cut into profits and curb
prices.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gore said he supported a legislative amendment,
recently passed by the House of Representatives, that would require
the drug companies to agree to reasonable prices for drugs that are
invented in collaboration with government scientists.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 90 such collaborations underway with the
National Cancer Institute alone. But the industry has consistently
opposed a reasonable drug pricing clause, and its protests were a
main reason why the National Institutes of Health abandoned such a
provision in 1995. ``If I had been in the Congress, I certainly
would have voted for it,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Gore supports the idea of requiring drug
companies to pay a fee to the government for medicines developed
with the help of government grants. Some of today's top-selling
drugs got their start in the federally financed laboratories of
university scientists, and Gore said that the public ``ought to
have some right not to be gouged on the purchase of products that
they themselves helped to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the vice president favors a proposed rule that
would make it more difficult for companies to use the regulatory
process to delay competition _ a rule the industry opposes. And he
is against a highly publicized provision that has been circulating
in Congress to extend the patent for Claritin, the top-selling
allergy medication.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's stance on Claritin puts him somewhat at odds with one of
his closest advisers and friends, Peter Knight. Last year,
Claritin's manufacturer, Schering-Plough Corp., hired Knight to
help develop a lobbying campaign for the patent extension, among
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Knight has since given up his lobbying business, and Gore
insisted today that he has never talked with Knight, or other
friends who have represented drug companies, about pharmaceutical
issues. ``All the positions I've taken,'' he said, ``are against
their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was clearly well-briefed for the hour-long interview, and
seemed to relish the opportunity to go on the offensive against an
industry he has long taken an interest in. At one point, he reached
back to recall the private meeting he had 18 years ago with Rep.
Richard Bolling, the powerful chairman of the House rules committee
_ a meeting that led to the defeat of the patent extension
legislation the industry coveted.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gore said, he was particularly irked that the
industry refused to make public data that would have supported its
position. ``It was the most astounding example of corporate
chutzpah I had ever run across,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a serendipitous moment for the vice president, his
11-year-old black labrador, Shiloh, wandered onto the veranda
midway through the conversation to nuzzle against his leg. As it
happens, Shiloh takes medicine for arthritis. ``This dog here,''
Gore said, ``gets a cheaper price for the same drug than humans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
