<HEADLINE>
AGASSI MARATHON AGAINST MARTIN GIVES SAMPRAS A REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There was a break in the action, except for Andre
Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours 45 minutes into a match that had begun the previous
night and seemed intent on stretching into the next one, the
competitors, spectators, theatrics, and heroics were well past the
point of exhaustion during this changeover at Wimbledon's Centre
Court Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And here came Agassi racing to his seat as if he were playing a
game of musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tossup as to which was more startling: the burst of
energy or that Agassi was still standing. When this rendition of
American auld lang syne with his fellow senior citizen was
suspended by rain in the gloaming Thursday, Agassi was flat on his
back, a victim of the treacherous surface. For a while, he was
lower than that, a victim of Martin's majesty.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who turns 30 next Saturday _ a milestone Agassi
reluctantly reached in April _ was serving for the match at 5-2. By
the time he slumped toward his seat while Agassi was racing toward
his, Martin was serving for his life.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Agassi had put him out of his misery, 6-4,
2-6, 7-6 (7-3), 2-6, 10-8, with a display that illustrated again
why he is the world's top-ranked male player and showman.
</P>
<P>
   There is one man seeded ahead of him in the Wimbledon pecking
order, however: perennial champion Pete Sampras. And Agassi
inadvertently helped his archrival _ and prolonged the suspense
surrounding Sampras _ with the elongated melodrama that co-starred
Martin. Scheduled to play the final match on Centre Court, Sampras
instead got the night off because the length of the matches, an
early-evening suspension for rain, and just plain lack of time
prevented all the business on the docket from being completed. So
Sampras got extra time to rest for his third-round match against
Jason Gimelstob and to rehabilitate the acute tendinitis of the
lower left leg that has made his bid for a record-tying seventh
Wimbledon and a record-setting 13th Grand Slam title a dicey
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras probably would have been too worn out to play, anyway,
had he watched Martin-Agassi. Not only was it a worthy reprise of
the 1999 US Open final Agassi won after dropping two of the first
three sets, it was a stirring tribute to the golden age of American
tennis _ starring Sampras, Agassi, Martin, Jim Courier, Michael
Chang, and, to a lesser extent, MaliVai Washington _ that is
gradually acquiring a coat of rust.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Martin could almost be heard creaking from the
cumbersome brace on his right knee and the torn ligaments in his
left ankle that had limited him to 11 matches this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the way Martin was serving (28-11 advantage in aces) and
volleying (28-9 in winners), Agassi wasn't in a particularly
nostalgic mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all secondary to the fact that we're both here to
win,'' he said. ``Whoever you have to play, you have to take care
of business. It's just highly competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   And Agassi's prospects were looking highly dubious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I'd gotten to the point where I was controlling
play,'' said Martin. ``Even the points I wasn't dictating, I felt
like Andre was forcing when he had a little bit of an opportunity.
(But) you know, the tide can turn very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   As quickly as it took Agassi to stop double-faulting and start
showing the flair that makes each of his matches a passion play.
Surviving two match points at 5-2, he finally started landing his
serves with regularity and slashing his returns at impossible
angles for Martin to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to feel like you're really against the wall,''
Agassi said. ``Then at that point, you're just thinking, `Just make
the guy earn it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had berated Alan Mills for not suspending play earlier
Thursday night, but he called and apologized to the tournament
referee Friday morning. He eventually had just enough time to keep
his dinner reservation with paramour Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such intrigue or exertion for No. 1 women's seed
Martina Hingis. She breezed to a 6-2, 6-2 win over Silvija Talaja
and hasn't been challenged yet here this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played very well,'' she said, ``very focused from the first
point on to the last.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pleasant contrast to 1999 when Hingis came here alone
amid rumors of a rift with her mother-coach, Melanie Molitor, and
left in a shambles after becoming the first top seed to lose to a
qualifier in the first round. That implausible conqueror, Jelena
Dokic, seems to have inherited Hingis's problems this year, even
though she doesn't realize it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hingis, 19, is best buddies with Molitor again, Dokic
is left to cope with the fallout from the outrageous behavior of
her father, Damir.
</P>
<P>
   He was evicted from a tournament at Birmingham, England, last
year for a drunken display in which he labeled WTA Tour honchos
``Nazis.'' And on Thursday, he made that performance look like an
exercise in gentility. He ranted against England, calling one side
of the country ``fascist,'' changed his opinion of the WTA to
``criminal and poison,'' and smashed a television reporter's cell
phone after asking to borrow it. Dokic wasn't arrested only because
the journalist, Sky TV's Gary Saggers, declined to press charges
after police were called in. And the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP;
Croquet Club issued a statement saying the senior Dokic would be
banned from the grounds if there is another such episode.
</P>
<P>
   And his daughter, all of 17 years old and the darling of this
event when she advanced to the quarterfinals last year, was left to
answer for him. She didn't want to, and the press conference
moderator/censor admonished interrogators to confine all questions
to tennis. But nobody wanted to know about Dokic's doubles victory
with Jennifer Capriati. They wanted to know about Daddy Dearest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this many times: I have a great relationship with my
dad, him going to tournaments with me,'' said Dokic. ``He's always
been with me in tennis, a big influence. Doesn't bother me at all.
I like having him around.''
</P>
<P>
   So another tennis prodigy's drama continues. But unlike
Martin-Agassi, there's nothing uplifting about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
