<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ASPINALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ASPINALL, 74, BRITISH GAMBLER AND ZOO OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ John V. Aspinall, a rakish millionaire who made his
fortune in the port-and-cigar world of upper-class gambling tables
in London and devoted it to creating country estates for breeding
gorillas and tigers _ species that he said he preferred to humans _
died on Thursday in London. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that man should be guided by primitive instinct rather
than reason, and determined to close the gulf between the species,
Aspinall delighted in romping with his wild animals.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged his zookeepers to do likewise, sometimes with
horrific consequences. Five were mauled to death in the last 20
years, the most recent one this February, yet Aspinall successfully
fought off laws that would have barred the workers from entering
enclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 30 best friends, he said, half were animals, and he
argued that at one time there had been a golden age in which beasts
and humans had been equal. Asked once whether he would leave his
children in the company of his wild animals, he said, ``I'd rather
leave them with gorillas than with a social worker.''
</P>
<P>
   The success he had in fleecing some of London's more louche
aristocrats and rich foreign visitors in his Mayfair gambling clubs
and then spending the profits on his own eccentric model of animal
protection was sometimes said to have done as much for
redistributing the wealth in Britain in the 1960s as the social
programs of the liberal intelligentsia who regularly excoriated him
for his extreme right-wing views.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Aspers,'' he ran with a high-living set that included
business buccaneers like James Goldsmith, Tiny Rowland and Lord
Lucan, the Belgravia aristocrat who disappeared in November 1974
after bludgeoning his family's nanny to death with a lead pipe in
the darkened foyer of his home, believing her to be his wife.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Lord Lucan has been a subject of high-society
rumor and subway-wall graffiti ever since, with sightings of the
disgraced peer periodically reported in the tabloid press.
Aspinall's death is not likely to end the speculation, which a
quarter-century of denials has not dimmed, that he and his gambling
cronies somehow managed to spirit Lord Lucan out of Britain to a
new life abroad.
</P>
<P>
   John Victor Aspinall was born in India on June 11, 1926, the son
of _ or so he long thought _ Robert Aspinall, an army surgeon.
Years later when he pressed his supposed father for money to cover
his gambling debts, he discovered to his delight that he had more
exotic origins. His real father was George Bruce, a soldier who had
had his way with his mother, Mary Grace Horn, under a tamarind tree
after a regimental ball.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 6, Aspinall was sent to preparatory school in
England, and in 1938 his mother, divorced by that time, married Sir
George Osborne, who paid for the young man to go to private
boarding school at Rugby.
</P>
<P>
   He was expelled for being ``idle and rebellious,'' and he served
in the Royal Marines for three years before going to Jesus College,
Oxford, where he devoted himself to dandified dress and gambling.
He boasted of never having attended a single lecture.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of his final exams at the university, he feigned
illness and went to the Gold Cup at Ascot instead. He consequently
never earned a degree, but he did bet on the right horse, and his
professional life was launched.
</P>
<P>
   By that time he had fallen under the influence of an adventure
book called ``Nada the Lily,'' by Rider Haggard, about an
illegitimate Zulu prince who lived outside his tribe among wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956 Aspinall married Jane Hastings, a Scottish model, and
moved into an Eaton Place apartment where he installed a garden
shed housing a capuchin monkey, a 9-week-old tigress and two
Himalayan bears. In what was to become a typical pattern of
cavalier behavior, he paid no attention to the annoyance of
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, gambling was illegal, and the game he set up had
to float from one high-toned address to another to escape the
authorities. He attracted so many well-placed players that when the
game was finally shut down by the police in 1958, the action led to
the passing of a new law permitting gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 he opened the Clermont Club on Berkeley Square, which
became famous for the Mayfair set that frequented it and for
Annabel's in the basement, the dance and dinner club that became
London's most fashionable and exclusive evening spot. Membership in
Aspinall's gambling rooms was limited to 600 and included five
dukes, five marquesses and 20 earls.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the Clermont Club financed the opening of
Howletts, Aspinall's first zoo, at a neo-Palladian mansion outside
Canterbury. In 1972 he sold the Clermont Club and established his
second grand park on 275 acres at Port Lympne, near Folkestone.
</P>
<P>
   The need for cash prompted him to return to running gambling
clubs in London, and he set up two new successful ones in
Knightsbridge and Mayfair. In 1983 he made $30 million from their
sale, but a decade later he was in financial difficulties again,
and in 1992 he set up yet another gambling spot.
</P>
<P>
   He was often pictured at ease with his beloved wild beasts,
having his eyelids delicately tweaked by a gorilla, having new-born
tiger cubs dumped in his lap by their mother, or being surrounded
by a peaceable wolf pack. A tall, rangy man with a booming voice,
Aspinall liked to shock the sedate and once announced that when
making love, he roared like a lion and beat his chest like a
gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   While experts were skeptical of his approach, they were obliged
to admire his breeding breakthroughs with Siberian tigers, ocelots,
and gorillas, and his success at introducing some of them into the
African wild.
</P>
<P>
   These triumphs were overshadowed, though, by the deaths of the
five assistants, two killed by the same tigress in 1980, one
trampled by an elephant in 1984, another mauled by a tiger in 1994,
and the last, Darren Cockrill, 27, crushed by an elephant four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   His Darwinian beliefs led him to make admiring comments about
the benefits of diseases like malaria which rid the world of
inadequate human stock and culled it of 2 billion undesirables. But
it also led him to support animal preservation and to criticize
``the import of rare animal skins to satisfy the witless wishes of
women.'' He had no time for equality of the sexes, saying that his
wife was ``the perfect example of the primate female, ready to
serve the dominant male and make his life agreeable.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his one political effort, he ran unsuccessfully for
Parliament in 1997 as the candidate of his friend Jimmy Goldsmith's
single-issue Referendum Party against Britain's deepening
involvement in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966 he divorced his first wife and married Belinda Musker.
Then in 1972, he divorced again and married Lady Sarah Courage, the
widow of the racing driver Piers Courage, who had died in a crash
two years earlier. Besides her, he leaves two sons, Damian and
Bassa, a daughter, Amanda, and two stepsons, Jason and Amos
Courage.
</P>
<P>
   A half-brother, James Osborne, said on Friday that the two wild
animal parks that now boast 1,100 animals and more than 80 species
would be run by the John Aspinall Foundation ``in the manner and
philosophy of their founder'' _ dedicated to preservation rather
than exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   On finding out last year that the cancer in his jaw was probably
terminal, Aspinall had a characteristically bluff reaction. ``You
can have 5-to-2 against me making it, or better yet, I'll give you
3-to-1,'' he said. ``It's a good bet. I only have a 30 percent
chance of surviving this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
