<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-ASSOCIATES-ART     06-30 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ASSOCIATES-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEER-GROUP PRESSURE HURTS A FORD OFFSPRING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to Finance 101, when an old-line manufacturing company
finds that one of its offspring far surpasses it in profit growth,
the best course is to liberate this child star to soar on its own.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Ford Motor Co. followed the textbook two years ago
and spun off the Associates First Capital Corp. as a dividend to
shareholders , the stock of the unit _ founded in 1918 to finance
Model T's _ promptly flopped to earth.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, with the shares at $22.3125, investors who had once
eagerly awaited the day that Ford would unleash the unit's
unrecognized value were sitting on a loss of nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why such market disregard for a company that has seen its
earnings jump 19 percent or more in each of the last five years and
has had rising operating earnings for 101 consecutive quarters,
compared with the year-earlier periods?
</P>
<P>
   Various clouds hang over the company, also referred to as the
Associates or First Capital, but several analysts and investors say
they are far less worrisome than has been suggested by the
depressed state of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent is the fact that the financial services business in
general has been in considerable tumult, with rapid consolidation,
high-profile casualties and new high-technology entrants scrambling
to fill niches. One of the biggest failures was the Money Store, a
second-mortgage lender that the First Union Corp. bought for $2.1
billion in 1998 but that proved such a drag that the bank announced
last week that it would shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   Another depressant has been fear that the Federal Reserve, in
its drive to cool off a white-hot economy, will tighten monetary
policy too much and tip the economy into recession.
</P>
<P>
   That could clearly hurt the Associates, whose prime clientele
are blue-collar and clerical workers and which is already seeing a
rise in delinquencies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the company's costly shutdown early this year of
its poorly performing unit that financed mobile homes. The move
involved a special $110 million charge against first-quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also point to some profit-margin erosion and glitches
in the integration of Avco Financial Services, a 1999 acquisition
that added more than 1,200 branch offices and six new countries,
and to a new law in Japan, where the Associates' foreign business
is heavily concentrated, cutting the maximum interest rate it can
charge to 29 percent from 40 percent. And in a report earlier this
month, The Wall Street Journal said the Justice Department was
preparing to file a lawsuit contending that the Associates has
discriminated against black borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   But this litany, many people on Wall Street say, does not
justify a price-to-earnings ratio of less than 10 _ especially for
a company with such an outstanding record of growth, even during
recessions. In 1992, for example, when the 1990-91 downturn had its
biggest effect on borrowers, the Associates raised its profits by
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's proven its mettle through various kinds of
environments,'' said Robert Napoli, financial services analyst for
ABN Amro in Chicago, who figures that the stock should climb to
about $43 by the end of next year, based on projected earnings of
$2.70 a share and a price-to-earnings multiple of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Money Store's failure, of course, means one less competitor, and
the Associates' setback in manufactured housing appears to reflect
aggressive rate-cutting by Green Tree Financial, the ailing unit of
Conseco Inc. The Associates said the discrimination accusations
involve just 3 of 90 independent brokers with whom it dealt in one
city, Detroit. It also said that it was prepared for the change in
Japan's usury law and that the impact would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pretty harsh environment for financial
companies,'' said Jeff G. Morris, a portfolio manager whose Invesco
Financial Services fund held 1.29 million Associates shares on May
31 and who has high regard for the company's management and the
diversity of its business, which includes credit cards, truck
financing, personal loans and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Guthrie, chief financial officer of the Associates, said
that the company was not as vulnerable to rising interest rates as
many people thought, and that it would be looking at the industry's
current upheaval as a chance to take advantage of low prices for
other companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get some bargains,'' Guthrie predicted.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own company's stock, he added, ``I think it's a
screaming buy.'' Associates has authorization to buy back $50
million worth of its shares but says it will not have the capital
to begin making purchases until later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
