<HEADER>
A0041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-30 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MARTIN, THE MELODRAMA IS ALL TOO FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Deja Vu, who I'd thought was a famous Romanian tennis
player, appeared at Wimbledon Friday. The word was around. In
Centre Court somebody said, ``If that's not deja vu, then Todd
Martin isn't the tallest guy to come up short in this precinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin soon recognized deja vu himself, and it was a sight
to make his eyes sore enough to weep. Maybe Martin, the best
6-foot-6-inch specimen ever to decorate a tennis court _ as game as
he is high _ did sob in private after what happened to him Friday
in full view of 13,812 witnesses and millions across the globe. He
was entitled.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in the fifth set was serious, big-time, drop-dead
deja vu, courtesy of winning Andre Agassi: 6-4, 2-6, 7-6 (7-3),
2-6, 10-8. Agassi had been floudering like a trout with asthma,
gasping at the depths of 2-5, and soon two match points.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it hit me _ as it hit Martin in the chops. I felt like
a guy walking into a movie house, taking a look, and groaning,
``Oh, no. I've seen this one before. In fact, this is where I came
in four years ago'' _ with Martin leading MaliVai Washington, 5-1
in the fifth. Same court. Same full house. Semifinals. Amazingly,
almost the same score, favoring that Martin beneficiary,
Washington: 5-7, 6-4, 6-7 (6-8), 6-3, 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I remember now. This flick is called ``Pulp Affliction.''
It seems a joyful tale of an all-American (from Northwestern) boy
marching triumphantly behind a huge serve and trenchant volley.
Martin is further ahead than Napoleon on the way to Moscow but . .
. but . . . there is no happy ending in store. Not if you are Todd
Martin, or one of his faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels come off. The battery goes dead. The fuel line
freezes. He is afflicted by a pulpiness of his strong right arm at
enough critical moments _ not many, but just enough _ to allow
Agassi to squirm free in a two-reel melodrama that consumes almost
four hours over two days, bounding into the third round.
</P>
<P>
   At the Thursday evening intermission, the screen going black in
a drizzle, so did Agassi. He skidded, flopping onto his back,
convincing the authorities that the lawn is too damp and slippery
for further activity.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly enough, upon Friday's resumption, that backbone of
Agassi's was up against one of the venerable arena's forest green
walls. But it is a backbone that won't bend.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had been pounding aces (28 in all) and Agassi hadn't been
able to serve well enough to keep his lofty foe away from the net.
He found himself lagging 1-3 in the fifth, and had to duck two
break points to get to 2-3. But at 2-4 the total collapse of the
1992 champ, the little bald guy from Las Vegas, seemed imminent. He
double-faulted and Martin is way up, two breaks and 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough because deja vu was kicking in. Even though
Agassi was thinking, ``Hope is just about gone. If I'm gonna lose,
I want to lose my way _ making him hit the shots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 straight games, Martin muscled his serve through Agassi,
and at 5-2 he opened with an ace. Three points from a nice shower.
Not this time. A double fault and a ripping Agassi forehand return
cut the lead to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Andre's turn. He got to 40-30, but a lob floated over his head
and he was in a maze of five deuces and two match points. Martin
could taste the win now as he looked at a second serve on the first
match point.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed the backhand, double-barreled it into the net. His
great opportunity was probably gone right there, although they
played 38 more minutes. Agassi rescued the next match point with a
daring volley, but Martin was still ahead, 5-4, and with serve.
</P>
<P>
   He stared deja vu in its beady eyes and said to himself, ``Don't
let it happen again.'' He was in a spot he shouldn't be in. A guy
with his class on grass (two semis and two quarters at Wimbledon)
rated a seeding, not a second-round scuffle with Agassi. But when
the injudicious tourney committee jiggled the seedings, they forgot
Martin and inserted such as the undeserving homeboy, Greg Rusedski,
who was beaten at the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   On losing to Washington in 1996 he confessed ``choking,''
describing the dread condition: ``I couldn't breathe, couldn't move
my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   This time he experienced those afflictions ``to a lesser
degree,'' he said. ``The momentum changed. You don't feel it until
it happens. Then it's a matter of how quick you can get it to stop.
Unfortunately it took me a couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   By then Agassi had the scent, ``although I had my tense, tight
moments,'' he said. ``At 5-4, it came across my mind that this has
happened to him before. He gave me some help. But I had to have the
mentality to execute my shots under pressure, so that he'd have to
hit his. Todd played tremendously to have me down 5-2 . . . but
great things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for the admirable Todd Martin, caught in the clutches of
deja vu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
