<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorneys spar in Coke case
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney Willie Gary came out swinging Friday, strongly denying
allegations that he illegally solicited fees from Coca-Cola workers
involved in the racial discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This garbage that I was trying to solicit clients is
ridiculous,'' Gary said in a telephone interview. ``They requested
to meet with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary also said the allegations, made by the group of attorneys
representing the class of 2,000 black employees, were a
``smokescreen'' to hide an inadequate agreement in principle that
was reached two weeks ago to settle the case.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Coca-Cola, which is being kept confidential
until it is completed, was reached by a team led by plaintiffs'
attorney Cyrus Mehri. Gary was not involved in the settlement
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realizes he probably didn't get enough money and is worried
that he may lose the class,'' Gary said of Mehri. That could
happen, Gary said, if individual class members decide to ``opt
out'' of the settlement and file individual lawsuits against Coke
for monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mehri's team filed a motion alleging that Gary's
law firm solicited fee agreements from class members in violation
of a local federal court rule. Gary's law firm does not represent
the class as a whole. Recently, however, his firm started to
represent four of the eight plaintiffs in the case and at least
four other individual class members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gary firm is soliciting fee agreements that require class
members to fork over 25 percent of their settlement shares for
nothing,'' Mehri's team said in its motion.
</P>
<P>
   The motion asks U.S. District Judge Richard Story to stop Gary's
Stuart, Fla., firm from continuing the alleged practice and to
invalidate any agreements that have been reached so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of our brief is that you're not above the law,
whether you're a corporate giant or a high-flying lawyer,'' Mehri
said Friday. ``As we did with Coke, we will stand up for the rights
of the class members and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary said his firm is not trying to take money received by a
class member as a result of work performed by Mehri's team.
</P>
<P>
   He said he initially got involved in the case because some of
the plaintiffs had developed a ``lack of trust'' in Mehri's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, Mehri's team was hired to help fight discrimination
within the Coca-Cola Co.,'' Gregory Allen Clark, one of the four
plaintiffs Gary represents, said Friday. ``Lo and behold, we sadly
learned that those very same attorneys that we hired treated us
poorly, disrespectfully and as if we had no rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But plaintiff Kimberly Orton, who stuck with Mehri's team, is
quite satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, I have never had a lack of trust in our
attorneys,'' Orton said. ``Their work has been outstanding,
committed and filled with integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary also accused Mehri's team of having a ``slave contract''
with plaintiffs in the case.
</P>
<P>
   He said provisions in Mehri's agreement require plaintiffs,
under certain conditions, to pay exorbitantly high fees and
penalties if the plaintiffs reject Mehri's legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff Linda Ingram sharply disagreed with Gary's
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The provision was put into the agreement to protect the entire
class from any one person putting their individual interests above
that of the class,'' Ingram said. ``We all discussed that provision
and agreed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied the allegations but agreed to a
settlement for the class, which should be finalized at the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
