<HEADER>
A0046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PERFECTSTORM-COX     06-30 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECTSTORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie doesn't exaggerate '91 storm
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Special effects for the summer blockbuster ``The Perfect Storm''
were done on a movie set in Los Angeles. But on Oct. 30, 1991,
Mother Nature was directing the action off the coast of New England
as the storm that spawned the movie unleashed its fury.
</P>
<P>
   There really was a perfect storm. It really did sink the Andrea
Gail. And there really were 100-foot waves. At the time, however,
the National Weather Service was having as much trouble convincing
people that nature could whip up such a storm as Hollywood may have
persuading moviegoers that George Clooney really is a Gloucester
fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain amount of skepticism to our warnings,''
says retired forecaster Bob Case, who was the deputy meteorologist
in the Boston office of the National Weather Service when the storm
formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a beautiful autumn in New England,'' he says. ``Not too
many people could fathom _ or believe _ 100-foot waves and
hurricane-force winds in a storm that was heading from east to
west. You were looking at a set of meteorological circumstances
that come together maybe every 50 to 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Case helped coin the phrase ``perfect storm'' in describing it
to author Sebastian Junger, whose book by the same name inspired
the film. According to Case, the storm's formation was caused by
the rare convergence of three separate weather systems in the days
preceding Halloween 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a strong disturbance associated with a cold front
that moved through New England on Sunday, Oct. 27. It passed
without incident, but began to intensify rapidly as it encountered
the edge of an unusually intense high pressure area over
southeastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``These circumstances alone could have created a strong storm,''
says Case. ``But then, like throwing gasoline on a fire, a dying
Hurricane Grace delivered immeasurable tropical energy to create
the perfect storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by warm, moist air from the Gulf Stream, the storm turned
and headed west _ the opposite direction of New England's familiar
nor'easters _ catching both fishermen and coastal residents off
guard. By the morning of Wednesday, Oct. 30, the storm was bearing
down on the Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew something was going to happen,'' recalls Ross
Dickman, who worked in the weather station of Boston's Logan
Airport that day. By afternoon it was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could lithat ``Storm'' director Wolfgang Petersen has
represented the fury of the storm accurately.
</P>
<P>
   They take exception, however, to promotional claims that it was
``the storm of the century.'' New England has seen several such
storms _ including the Hurricane of 1938, the Blizzard of 1978 and
the winter storm of 1993, which dumped up to 50 inches of snow in
North Georgia and also raised 100-foot waves off the New England
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using a bit of poetic license to call it the worst,''
says Case. ``But it's probably in the top 10 storms in the last 50
to 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Case is also piqued by one other aspect of Hollywood's version
of the real storm. ``In the book, Sebastian Junger describes me as
`fit, balding and in my mid-50s,''' he says. ``In the movie, they
replace me with a television weatherman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
