<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-CONTROV     06-30 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-CONTROVERSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF PLAYERS STILL AT CENTER OF CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEN-WIMBLEDON)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A day after the police led Jelena Dokic's
father away and Alexandra Stevenson accused one French player of a
racial slur and another of pushing her mother, there was a warning
issued to Damir Dokic and a mystified look on the face of
Anne-Gaelle Sidot.
</P>
<P>
   Sidot was the player accused of pulling down the hat of Samantha
Stevenson and pushing her at a recent tournament. In another
incident, Alexandra and Samantha Stevenson said Sidot's boyfriend
had cried out, ``Let's get her,'' after a practice session.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Amelie Cocheteux, who allegedly used a racial slur
in Alexandra's direction, said, ``All of this is purely invented.''
Friday, Sidot had a chance to defend herself.
</P>
<P>
   After losing her third-round match to Tamarine Tanasugarn, 6-1,
4-6, 6-1, Sidot acknowledged yanking down Samantha Stevenson's hat,
but said it was only in response to an insult Alexandra's mother
had directed at her. As for the threat allegedly issued by her
boyfriend, Sidot said: ``It's a lie. Never, never, never, never.
She said so many wrong things, so I'm not surprised that she said
another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also not shocking to see a release issued jointly by the
World Tennis Association and the All England Club regarding the
rowdy and hostile behavior Damir Dokic displayed on Thursday. The
father of Jelena Dokic boisterously stormed around the grounds and
smashed a reporter's cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be monitoring the conduct of Mr. Dokic closely,''
officials said in the release. ``Should this again fall below
acceptable standards, it would lead to Mr. Dokic being banned from
the grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Jelena Dokic, with her father nearby, cruised through
her doubles match Friday with her partner, Jennifer Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great relationship with my father,'' Dokic said.
``He's a big influence. I like having him around. Doesn't bother me
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of her own circus, there was irritation clearly
registered on Sidot's face. She could not understand why
accusations were being aimed at her, but Sidot did have her own
opinions about Alexandra Stevenson's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I never had problems with players or with coaches,''
Sidot said. ``So, I don't understand. Maybe she doesn't feel good
in this world, I don't know. She said that if she knew before it
was going to be like this, she would have sent Alexandra to school.
I mean, it's more her who has a problem than us. She said something
bad about me, but it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi Loses His Cool
</P>
<P>
   Just before Referee Alan Mills postponed the Andre Agassi-Todd
Martin match on Center Court Thursday night because of rain, Agassi
expressed his concerns about the increasingly slippery grass.
Still, play continued until Agassi took a bad fall. Mills stepped
out and suspended play, but Agassi was furious and shouted his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I phoned him up this morning and told him that I apologized
for certainly raising my tone,'' Agassi said. ``At that moment, I
was very frustrated and concerned because of what happened at
Queen's club.''
</P>
<P>
   A week before Wimbledon, in a similar circumstance, Agassi
slipped and tweaked his back in a match at Queen's club. On
Thursday, he was not hurt by his fall, but he did take his time
gathering himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just laying there trying to stall, hoping it would rain
more,'' Agassi said with a smile. ``I went over and toweled off,
just worked it like a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' Status in Doubt
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup is just over three weeks away and Pete Sampras'
injury (tendinitis) has put the U.S. team's makeup in question. But
another issue was also posed Friday: should Davis Cup Captain John
McEnroe play doubles?
</P>
<P>
   ``As exciting as that would be for the public, and the press,''
said Todd Martin, ``it also takes away from the productivity that I
think John can have on the rest of the team during the practice
week, and then even during our doubles match. I think that would
hurt us more than help us.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
