<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INCUBATORS-$AD     06-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INCUBATORS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY VETERANS SEE DOUBTS ABOUT INCUBATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By SARA ROBINSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're known as incubators _ but one venture capitalist now
calls them incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   The high-technology bounty of the last few years yielded a small
crop of these companies, which nurture nascent Internet start-ups,
then spin them out or sell them as they mature. Among the
best-known publicly traded incubators are CMGI of Andover, Mass.,
and the Internet Capital Group and Safeguard Scientifics, both of
Wayne, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   But as the technology market has come down to earth, some people
are questioning the very rationale behind taking public what is
essentially a venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem is that the core business operation of the
incubators _ launching their portfolio companies into the public
markets _ has lost much of its allure in recent months, as
offerings have been postponed or canceled and as first-day gains
have shrunk considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street in general has become less receptive to the kind of
companies that most incubators are nurturing _ early-stage
businesses with big ideas but no products or profits. So the ``time
to market'' has lengthened for many Internet companies in the
incubators' portfolios. This means that the risk of owning these
companies has increased while the real value of an incubator's
investments has decreased sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Roger McNamee, a general partner at Integral Capital Partners,
noted that while the public market is a beguiling source of
low-cost capital for these incubators, it comes at a steep price _
time horizons and expectations that are incompatible with a venture
capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incubators were compelling in 1998, 1999, because the time
frame for creating market value in ventures was very short,'' he
said. ``If recent trends persist, it will take much longer to build
market value in new ventures. This suggests that some incubator
funds will ultimately incinerate the capital that goes into them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the technology market has cooled, incubators' share prices
have turned icy: CMGI is down 66.9 percent this year through
Friday, to $45.8125. Internet Capital has tumbled 78.2 percent, to
$37.015625, and Safeguard is down 41 percent, to $32.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Incubator stocks are viewed by Wall Street as a way to tap into
privately held companies before their initial public offerings.
Analysts have typically computed target prices for incubators by
tallying the value of the holdings _ for the private companies,
they estimated the public value _ and added a premium for good
management and for synergies between the holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the better-known private incubators, Idealab of Pasadena,
Calif., and Divine InterVentures of Lisle, Ill., are poised to go
public, hoping for a taste of the spectacular Wall Street success
enjoyed by companies like Internet Capital in its initial offering
last August; its shares were priced at $6 but rose to $200 by Jan.
3.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one investment bank is wary about the timing.
Credit Suisse First Boston had been scheduled to be lead manager
for Divine InterVenture's public offering. But last month, after
the bank tried to postpone the sale until the fall, Andrew J.
Filipowski, chief executive of Divine InterVentures, jettisoned
First Boston and hired Robertson Stephens to lead the offering
instead. Last week, Divine InterVentures postponed its offering,
which is for up to $200.1 million, until next Thursday. Idealab's
initial offering, for up to $30 million, is not yet scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the credentials of both Filipowski, a former chief
executive of Platinum Technology, and Bill Gross, the venture
capitalist who is chief executive of Idealab, some analysts are
wary about their long-term prospects. Another problem for
incubators is that they tend to be invested in the kinds of
companies that are not in favor at the moment _ those focused on
e-commerce, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is more interested in companies that are making net
profits now,'' said Gail Bronson, a senior analyst at IPO Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Idealab has a portfolio that includes companies like eToys,
whose business model looked much more compelling last year. Divine
InterVentures, like Internet Capital, is focused on
business-to-business exchanges, an area that generated much
investor enthusiasm late last year but is also cooling because of
market saturation.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, recent new-issue successes have been in areas like
Internet infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Core technology and infrastructure companies are more likely
to attract venture funding immediately and not need the services of
an incubator,'' said Bronson, adding that incubators tend to
finance companies at an earlier stage of development than do
traditional venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Incubators may also suffer from competition with other
incubators for management teams and ideas. Internet Capital had the
first-mover advantage in the business-to-business e-commerce
sector, but Divine InterVentures does not.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as more incubators go public, they compete with one
another for investor capital, possibly driving down their stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Should investors be placing bets on incubators at all?
</P>
<P>
   Henry T.C. Hu, a professor at the University of Texas
specializing in law and finance, says no, partly because an
incubator's public investors do not have access to detailed
information about the companies in its portfolio. ``How do you
convey to the public how much these opportunities are worth?'' he
asked. ``It's very different from the kind of information flow
between a venture capitalist and their investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with a mutual fund, he said, incubators suffer because
their holdings are not publicly traded and thus are neither priced
by the market nor reflect its movements.
</P>
<P>
   Others think the incubator model still has value.``The symbiosis
between companies is there, and it's real,'' said Phil Leigh, vice
president of Internet research at Raymond James, the brokerage
firm. It is just that ``one's perception of that value gets overly
optimistic in a bull market and gets overly scrutinized in a bear
market.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
