<HEADER>
A0054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HOROWITZ0701-COX     06-30 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOROWITZ0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adoption lawyer wanted on three felony charges
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Former Boca Raton adoption lawyer Stuart
Gordon Horowitz, who resigned from the bar amid accusations his
mishandling of adoptions left a trail of heartache across South
Florida, is wanted on three felony charges, authorities confirmed
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy court records also show Horowitz, 31, and his wife,
Susan, legally walked away from more than $2.5 million in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Donald Ganzel of the Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office
warrant division said this week the charges were filed June 14.
Horowitz is charged with grand theft, failure by an intermediary to
obtain prior approval of expenses, and failure of an intermediary
to report intended placement of a child.
</P>
<P>
   All three are third-degree felonies, each punishable by a prison
term of up to five years and a fine of up to $5,000, according to
state laws. Ganzel did not have details of the charges and the Palm
Beach County state attorney would not confirm them.
</P>
<P>
   Ganzel said the warrants were good only in Florida but could be
expanded if authorities learn the wanted person has left the state.
The Horowitzes listed a Colorado address late last year, records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz's criminal attorney, Michael Dutko, did not return
calls. His civil attorney, Michael Wood, would only say he did not
know Horowitz's current address and did not know he'd moved to
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz resigned from the Florida Bar in November 1997 after at
least 17 people complained about his practices. Some were clients
who said they lost money or the chance of adoption; some were birth
mothers who said Horowitz failed to support during their
pregnancies as agreed. Two families said they were promised Chapter
7 bankruptcy protection for himself and his wife as well as his law
practice, claiming their debts were $2.53 million. A deed filed
with the Palm Beach County Clerk of Courts shows the Horowitzes
sold their suburban Boca Raton home in November 1999 for $238,000
and listed a new address in Englewood, Colo., a Denver suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy was closed last December after a court-appointed
trustee concluded that all of Horowitz's $245,772 in assets,
including his home and any proceeds from its sale, were protected
from creditors under state law. The Horowitzes kept their assets.
</P>
<P>
   Broward County prosecutors closed their investigation of
Horowitz in September 1999 and turned the case over to Palm Beach
County. Assistant State Attorney John F. Hanlon Jr. said Horowitz
had moved his law office from Hollywood to Boca Raton before most
of the alleged incidents, and it was the home county for most of
the alleged victims.
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon suggested Palm Beach County charge Horowitz with grand
theft, saying Horowitz billed his clients certain fees without
obtaining prior court approval, as required by law for those kinds
of fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our firm belief that this was never done by Horowitz,''
Hanlon wrote Ken Selvig, Palm Beach County's chief assistant state
attorney, in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Jaffe and Simie and Shelley Platt have said Horowitz led
them to believe he'd taken all the necessary steps for adoption,
but in each case had not contacted the birth father.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Jaffe had obtained custody of half-sisters Amanda,
then 4, and Sierra, then 6. She formally adopted Sierra in October
1998, but Amanda's birth father, Scott Charlton, who was in prison,
had said he had been looking for Amanda for the last year and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   The birth mother said at the time that Horowitz knew all along
who Charlton was and Charlton knew where to find her. She said she
left it to Horowitz to obtain consent forms. The case, originally
filed in Martin County, was moved to Palm Beach County, where a
judge gave custody to Jaffe in January 1999. Horowitz resigned from
the Bar before Jaffe could submit her complaint.
</P>
<P>
   In the Platts' complaint to the Bar, they said they adopted
their son Isaac, but Horowitz didn't tell them the birth father had
filed for custody. The two sides later agreed to turn the baby over
to the birth father. The Plattses later sued Horowitz, but the case
was frozen when Horowitz filed for bankruptcy protection. David
Gold, the Platts' attorney, said Friday he will file to reopen the
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
