<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chick-fil-A ruffled over Burger King ad
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where's the beef?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, between Chick-fil-A and Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   Feathers are flying at the College Park-based restaurant chain
over a Burger King promotion tied to the hit summer flick ``Chicken
Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick-fil-A filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court late Friday
against Burger King, seeking a halt to a promotion in which
characters from the movie hold up cards that say: ``Save the
Chickens: Eat A Whopper.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims the Burger King promotion is too similar to
Chick-fil-A's popular ads featuring cows that urge consumers to:
``Eat Mor Chikin.'' The Burger King TV spots tell consumers to eat
more beef and, at one point, the chickens mistakenly spell Whopper
with a ``C'' before correcting it, the suit contends.
</P>
<P>
   The Chick-fil-A cows frequently misspell words. The cow ads have
been an integral part of the company's marketing efforts for five
years, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be a direct imitation of our campaign,'' said
Chick-fil-A spokesman Don Perry. ``Our concern is obviously the
dilution of our trademark and infringement on our copyrights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely serious,'' Perry said. ``It confuses the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   A Burger King Corp. spokeswoman said the Miami-based chain is
reviewing its options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to be chicken, but I simply cannot comment
further since this is a legal issue,'' said spokeswoman Kim Miller.
``However, I can assure you we don't believe there is any merit to
the situation and we will certainly defend ourselves vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
