<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 2, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TERM-REVIEW (Washington) _ It was a Supreme Court term of
surpassing interest, rich in symbol and substance, a vivid reminder
of the court's power to scramble settled expectations, put old
questions to rest and, ultimately, to have the last word. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-AIDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ How much would it cost to contain
the global AIDS epidemic? The answer is: How much would it cost to
banish ignorance, to deaden lust, to shame rape, to stop war, to
enrich the poor, to empower women, to defend children, to make
decent medical care as globally ubiquitous as Coca-Cola _ in short,
to get rid of all the underlying causes of the epidemic in the
Third World? By Donald G. McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-LYING-REVIEW (Undated) _ What is it about legal
proceedings and particularly those pre-trial sworn interviews known
as depositions that turn sophisticated people into quibblers,
dissemblers or amnesiacs? Why can't they just respond to the
questions posed as people respond in everyday conversations? By
Adam Liptak.
</P>
<P>
   SKIMPY-CLOTHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Blame ``Sex and the City'' or
blame the decline of the ozone layer, but skin is in. American
women are wearing less than ever before. Summer itself is hotter.
And over the past decade, the proliferation of the Wonderbra
coincided with global warming so that just as cleavages became more
pronounced, shorts became shorter. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-PROGRAM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just as surely as any
shrink-wrapped Microsoft disk, the human genome is a program, a set
of precisely coded instructions that evolution has written for the
design, operation and unfortunately rather limited maintenance of a
person. That people should be operated by such a specific script is
as amazing as it would be to find that robots have souls. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-CELEBS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some statements from
celebrity women who have explained why they chose to appear nude in
Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLUES-REVIEW (London) _ Britain is endlessly wondering
``How'm I doing?'' But unlike Ed Koch, the self-congratulating
former mayor of New York, Britain rarely expects a positive answer.
And lately, a nation that is always sensitive about perceived
slights to its international status has found more than usual to be
upset about. And now along comes ``The Patriot,'' a film about the
American Revolution that presents the English as effete war
criminals with snobby accents who herd families of fledgling
Americans into barns and set them on fire, just for fun. To Britons
sick of being pushed around, this obnoxious affront to
retrospective pride may be the last straw. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ All of Mexico's
presidential candidates call themselves democrats, but the voters
will really be choosing between two sharply different ways of
political life. The longtime ruling party, known as the PRI, offers
its tradition of top-down control and doing what it takes to stay
in power. The opposition comes from a contrasting wellspring of
grass-roots struggles for citizens' rights and the fight for the
balance of powers. The opposition is democratic, in the way that
most Americans understand the term. The PRI is not. Yet Mexicans
are clearly torn about this choice. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ANTIMISSILE-REVIEW (Beijing) _ It's hard to find any
foreign-policy expert here, in or out of government, who believes
the stated U.S. rationale for a continental anti-missile defense:
That it's merely intended to stop the likes of North Korea or Iraq.
Even Westward-leaning scholars here think the new push for missile
defense in Washington reflects an underlying conviction that the
United States must better prepare for battle with China. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
