<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SPEEDWAY0701-COX     06-30 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEEDWAY0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush turns around and OKs $2 million for Daytona Speedway
 &HT;    By S.V. Date
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ On the eve of his presidential candidate brother's
appearance at the annual Pepsi 400 stock car race, Gov. Jeb Bush
announced a $2 million state grant for the racetrack to build a
pedestrian walkway _ a project he deemed unworthy of public money
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush a year ago vetoed $3 million for a pedestrian bridge over
the eight-lane road adjacent to Daytona International Speedway,
questioning how the state as a whole would benefit from a project
for a company that in 1999 reported a pre-tax income of $95
million.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush gushed in a news release about the walkway's
importance to Florida, just a day before brother and presumptive
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush was to serve as
grand marshal at the Daytona track. ``It's exciting to be able to
assist this world-class facility with an investment that will
stimulate economic growth,'' Jeb Bush said. ``These funds will
encourage new job growth and increased opportunities for Florida
residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quickly seized on the flip-flop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money for a campaign appearance,'' said state
Democratic Party spokesman Tony Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What changed over the past year? What's changed is that his
brother is in a hotly contested race for the state of Florida. . .
. This smells looking at it from any angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Liz Hirst denied any attempt to help George
Bush's campaign. ``This was done to help the state of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, the governor said publicly that he had
the same reservations about the project as last year, hinting
strongly that he would veto it again should it appear in the
2000-01 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Hirst said the money was awarded now because the City of Daytona
Beach and the company had met the criteria required by the
governor's Office of Tourism, Trade and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
