<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINESCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-30 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO -- 713-220-7733 &HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY, JULY 2
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ABSENT BUSH, GORE TALKS UP LIBERTIES
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sweet land of liberty. Now there's a grand, overarching theme
that should make a presidential candidate's heart (or at least his
speech writer's) go pitter-patter as the Fourth of July approaches.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't heard much from George W. Bush and Al Gore about
the under- &QL; 
lying principles of our generally exceptional nation, unless you
count the throwaway lines.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Bush's efficacious pander to the League of United
Latin American citizens included a flourish on ``life, liberty and
the pursuit of happiness.'' Touching but not very informative.
</P>
<P>
   Inattention to the biggest-picture ideas is not likely to have
much effect on the outcome of the presidential race unless one of
the major contenders announces in late October an unanticipated
affection for establishing a monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Supreme Court's 5-4 votes on abortion rights and other
culturally divisive issues, Gore, of course, hopes he can make the
bank shot and get some mileage from the threat that Bush's high
court nominees might pose. Polling has shown repeatedly, however,
that only rarely are voters driven by a single issue, even abortion
or other emotionally charged questions that make their way to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   To make any inroads, Gore would have to convince voters that
Bush presents a more broad-gauge threat. That was exactly the point
of the recent ``Courting Disaster'' treatise from the People for
the American Way Foundation. Lord knows this tax-exempt 501(c)3
wasn't promoting Gore _ oh, no _ but if you're really dense they
provided a helpful subtitle: ``How a Scalia-Thomas Supreme Court
Would Endanger Our Rights and Freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it says something comforting, if not ennobling, about
the strength of our democracy that the major party candidates would
rather go hammer and tong over salmon-defeating hydroelectric dams
in the Pacific Northwest than to offer straightforward musings on
the founding concepts of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's not a good idea to let the campaign pass
without having an understanding of the candidates' views of such
basic tenets.
</P>
<P>
   So, both campaigns were asked to make their big guy available.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore's limousine picked up speed last week in downtown
Philadelphia, just a few blocks from Independence Hall, the vice
president warmed quickly to the question of what his tenure in the
White House would mean to basic constitutional liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolute protection of them,'' Gore began. ``I believe that
our Constitution is a living and breathing document that has not
only the enumerated liberties mentioned in the Constitution but
also liberties such as right of privacy that has been found by the
Supreme Court in the Constitution even though the word does not
appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminently sensible answers like this send strict
constructionists around the bend and contrast with what Bush has
had to say on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   When outlining his criteria for Supreme Court nominees, Bush
said last fall: ``The most primary issue is will they strictly
interpret the Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, although he wouldn't like it, needs to be drawn out on
this point. On which issues has the court gone too far? Privacy,
voting rights, jury selection, gun control, environmental
protection?
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible to question the governor directly on the
point, as his handlers failed to make him available. Perhaps they
thought there would be a pop quiz on the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was cagier when the issue was turned around and he was
asked how constitutional principles might be diminished by a Bush
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know the governor's views on all these
questions,'' Gore replied initially and unconvincingly. The highly
electronic vice president probably could have pulled out his Palm
Pilot and told you if Bush had, since birth, said three or more
words about the shroud of Turin or Kerensky debt.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, given just a moment, Gore conjured up a dig at
the constitutional implications of a George W. Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that he opposes a woman's right to choose,'' Gore said,
noting Bush's relentlessly narrow take on abortion. This comment
came the day before the Supreme Court's big abortion &QL; 
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that he has said that his two favorite Supreme Court
justices are Justice (Antonin) &QL; 
Scalia and Justice (Clarence) &QL; 
Thomas,'' Gore said. ``Those would be the last two that I would
name as models for future ... nominations.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be a slender reed on which to hang much of a
presidential campaign, but in this area the vice president is going
with what he's got.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
