<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELYCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-30 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO -- 713-220-7733 &HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY, JULY 2
 &HT;    
 &HT;    IDIOCY TO GIVE IN TO NADER, BUCHANAN
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader agreeing on anything
seems strange enough.
</P>
<P>
   To realize they not only agree on political points _ such as
mutual opposition to the North American Free Trade Agreement _ but
are particularly united in their convictions they should get free
rides in their campaigns for president goes past strange to
downright weird.
</P>
<P>
   Were it Nader alone who wants government money to pay for
campaigns; or, if just he feels justified in demanding another free
political ride by requiring his and Buchanan's inclusion in any
presidential debates, that's one thing.
</P>
<P>
   (After all, this is a man who has been known for decades as a
consumer advocate opposed to so-called big business and in favor of
extensive defenses for the consumers he thinks are victimized by
corporate interests. He, the man who made seat belts mandatory in
automobiles, seems quite a logical choice to win, as he recently
did, the presidential nomination of the Green Party, a relatively
small political collective known for its emphasis on populism and
environmentalism.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's very much another thing for Buchanan, the super
conservative, notably on social issues, to so lust for government
money to finance his presidential campaign that he is willing to
leave the Republican Party to charge into the Reform Party. He thus
hopes to be the political beneficiary of $12.6 million in
government funds.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Buchanan toiled to take control of the name of the
Reform Party, if not the actual concept of the party Ross Perot
created, he has done it to win the government funds Perot earned
for the party with his showing in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and his troops have quite cheerfully worked to drive
completely from the Reform Party any who oppose the onetime GOPer
and/or his nomination in the slightest degree.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Buchanan is using the Reform Party
name and reputation in his relentless drive to be included in all
the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting aspect of that mission is Buchanan's clear
belief his oratory skills put him head and shoulders above Democrat
Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There likely is more than the proverbial grain of truth in that
conviction. But, there is no truth in Buchanan's (and Nader's)
claims that, someway, it's not fair for the major parties to make
it so difficult for third-party or independent candidates to be
included in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only fair, it would be less than responsible for the
debate organizers to allow the participation of anyone who doesn't
meet the requirement candidates must draw at least 15 percent in
polls conducted before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The notion Nader, Buchanan or anyone else should be allowed
debate participation just because they want it is absurd. Does
Nader or Buchanan just want himself included or do the two fairly
well-known political types want any and everyone who might want to
be president to be allowed to participate?
</P>
<P>
   As Buchanan has griped more than once: Gee whiz, it's really
tough for someone who's not a major-party candidate to raise
himself to that level. It's idiocy to whine that it is not fair to
require small-party candidates to achieve the level of major-party
candidates so the lesser knowns will have better shots at winning.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief, is this idiocy. It's not just political idiocy, it
is just plain idiocy.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no remote way it is fairness. On the contrary, it is
not fair to Gore and Bush to have a couple of losers taking up
debate time. And, it's sure not fair to any American voters who
still are trying to make up their minds about whom they want to
support.
</P>
<P>
   If it's fair for Nader and Buchanan to participate in
presidential debates primarily because they want to, then it ought
to be just as fair for any and all off the streets who have
announced they want to be president to be included in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested it might be ``fun'' to let Buchanan and
Nader in on the debate action. Clearly, those who suggest that
never had to sit through a Republican debate with Alan Keyes
shouting it was only fair he be heard _ as much as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute Buchanan for Keyes and try telling folk that would be
fair _ and fun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
