<SLUG> BC-GENE-CROPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACREAGE OF GENETICALLY ALTERED CROPS STAYS LEVEL, GOVERNMENT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Despite growing controversy over the use of
biotechnology in agriculture, American farmers are not
significantly scaling back their planting of genetically altered
crops, according to a recent government survey.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture, which conducted the survey,
estimates that genetically altered crops were planted on about 69
million acres of American farmland last spring. That compares to
about 71 million acres planted with the crops a year ago, according
to seed industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Argriculture Department, however, refused to interpret the
figures, saying they were not comparable to earlier statistics the
agency had compiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have the data to go one way or another,'' said
John Willard, a spokesman at the department.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest seed companies, which have invested billions
of dollars to create genetically altered crops, say the survey
largely confirms their own data, which suggests that overall
biotechnology acreage has not declined much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monsanto's projections continue to show that we expect total
acreage to be flat to slightly up,'' said Scarlett Foster, a
spokeswoman at Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that hidden in the Agriculture Department's
numbers are hints that after several years of spectacular growth _
biotechnology planting went from 3 million acres in 1996 to 69
million this year _ the planting of altered crops may be in
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a leveling off shows a level of concern,'' said Charles
Margulis, a spokesman at Greenpeace USA. ``Two years ago the
industry said 100 percent of the soybean crop would be genetically
engineered by the year 2000 and we're at about half that. And with
increasing concern, that could fall even further.''
</P>
<P>
   The planting of genetically altered crops has become a
contentious issue because of agitation from environmental activists
who say they are potentially dangerous to humans and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   American seed companies counter by arguing that the genetically
altered crops have been deemed safe by the Food and Drug
Administration and that the companies have not seen adverse health
effects even though they have been in the nation's food supply for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department survey released Friday seems to
contradict a March study that showed farmers intended to plant
fewer acres than they did a year ago. But the big seed companies
disputed some of those numbers and the department conceded that the
figures from an earlier study were not entirely comparable.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey released Friday, 54 percent of the
soybeans, 25 percent of the corn and 61 percent of the cotton
acreage in the United States was planted with genetically altered
seeds, which are biologically altered to create their own
insecticide or to make the crops immune to chemical spraying that
kills weeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
