A0073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-GUTHRIDGE-RESIGNS     06-30 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GUTHRIDGE-RESIGNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Carolina's Guthridge retires
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ It was Thursday afternoon, and several North
Carolina players joined coach Bill Guthridge for what they thought
would be a routine session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out just like a normal day,'' fifth-year senior
forward Brian Bersticker said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Guthridge dropped the bombshell. On Friday, he would step
down as head coach. Soon, Bersticker would be playing for his third
North Carolina coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock,'' he said. ``None of us were prepared for
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bersticker's reaction summarized the mood in this tight-knit
community, which was stunned when Guthridge gave up the reins to
one of college basketball's dynasties after just three seasons. Not
long ago, Guthridge said in a newspaper interview that he might
coach another five years. As recently as last Tuesday, Guthridge
was joking with reporters as they prepared stories on the upcoming
NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   But at a hastily called news conference Friday at the Smith
Center, Guthridge said he had simply run out of energy and could
not get his ``batteries recharged'' for what would have been his
fourth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went on my vacation in May I was tired,'' said
Guthridge, who turns 63 in July. ``When I got back, I hoped I could
get myself ready again. But it just wasn't there. I gave myself a
month to see if I could do it but I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   He said he began talking to athletics director Dick Baddour
about the possibility a week ago but did not make a final decision
until Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team deserves somebody who can give them 100 percent,''
Guthridge said. ``And I didn't think I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years as an assistant to Dean Smith, college
basketball's all-time winner, Guthridge took over the North
Carolina program for the 1998 season. With a record of 80-28, he
averaged nearly 27 wins per season, won an ACC championship by
taking the ACC Tournament in 1998 and made two trips to the Final
Four, in 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success, the 1999-2000 season took something out of
Guthridge. After a four-game losing streak in January, the Tar
Heels dropped out of the rankings for the first time in 24 years.
North Carolina was eliminated by Wake Forest in the first round of
the ACC Tournament and finished the regular season 18-13, the most
regular-season losses for the school since the 1951-52 season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its record, North Carolina received its 26th consecutive
NCAA Tournament bid. Then, the Tar Heels then got hot in the
tournament, upsetting No. 1 seed Stanford on the way to the South
Regional championship and North Carolina's second Final Four bid in
three seasons under Guthridge.
</P>
<P>
   Having weathered that storm, it appeared that ``Coach Gut''
would stick around. Point guard Ed Cota is the only real loss from
last season's team, and the Tar Heels have a promising recruiting
class coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't last season; it was just an accumulation of
things,'' Guthridge said. ``I know now how Dean felt three years
ago (when he retired).''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Guthridge ended his 33-year association with the
North Carolina basketball program. The final two years of his
contract probably will be spent working in the athletics department
in a position that has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really decided what my future plans are,'' Guthridge
said. ``Right now, I'm going to the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   The 58 wins Guthridge posted in his first two seasons was an
NCAA record. In 1998, he became only the seventh coach in NCAA
history to take a team to the Final Four in his first season on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Smith said, ``To me, this is a day of
celebration for a fantastic career.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
