<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-PATRIOT-FILM-FIS     06-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-PATRIOT-FILM-FISCHER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUBRIS, BUT NO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, July 1, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a `separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DAVID HACKETT FISCHER    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYLAND, Mass. _ Despite terrific pacing and beautiful costumes
and photography, something has gone wrong in ``The Patriot,'' the
new Mel Gibson movie about the American Revolution. Signs of
trouble appear in the idyllic opening scenes. Gibson plays a
reluctant hero named Benjamin Martin, a widower with seven perfect
children, a ``Gone with the Wind'' plantation and a work force of
free and happy Black Folk who toil in his fields as volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the plot unfolds. We learn that Martin was the hero of an
earlier Indian war, but he decides to sit out the War of
Independence until the villainous British Colonel Tavlington (who
somewhat resembles the real-life British officer Banastre Tarleton)
burns his plantation, carries off the happy Black Folk, kills one
of his children and threatens to hang another.
</P>
<P>
   Martin impulsively decides to fight, mainly for revenge against
Tavlington, and wins the war more or less single-handed. With a
little assistance from George Washington, Nathaniel Greene and
Light Horse Harry Lee, and a lot of help from his long-suffering
sons and neighbors, Martin reforms American tactics, defeats
General Cornwallis and sets up the British surrender at Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   The film purports to be a history of the American Revolution.
Its Web site tells us that it is ``loosely based'' on fact. How
loosely might that be?
</P>
<P>
   In short, ``The Patriot'' is to history as Godzilla was to
biology. Egregious errors appear in every scene.
</P>
<P>
   Some inaccuracies are introduced to create an illusion of
authenticity. Tavlington, for example, is dressed in a red coat. In
fact, Tarleton's mounted legion wore green, but these are the
Redcoats, and red their coats must be (an issue discussed at length
in Alan Alda's hilarious spoof ``Sweet Liberty''). A similar
example appears in the written documents that the tangled
underplots require. Eighteenth century ink was black, which on the
documents we have from those days has faded to a soft brown. To
make the letters seem authentic in the film, they are freshly
written in faded brown ink.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Gibson's character is ``loosely based'' on five historical
figures: Francis Marion, Daniel Morgan, Elijah Clark, Thomas Sumter
and Andrew Pickens, combined into an American hero without fault or
flaw. The climactic battle where Mel Gibson defeats General
Cornwallis and kills Tavlington is ``loosely based'' on a
combination of the Battles of Cowpens (which Tarleton lost in
Cornwallis' absence) and Guilford Courthouse, Hobkirk's Hill and
Eutaw Springs (all of which Cornwallis won). Cornwallis was not
defeated in the Carolinas. Tarleton was not killed.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also heavy with anachronism. The dialogue alternates
between 21st century slang and loose quotations from irrelevant
historical materials. Mel Gibson is made to say ``I prefer one
tyrant 3,000 miles away to 3,000 tyrants one mile away'' _ a
garbled quote from Boston Tory Mather Byles _ and then lapses back
into slang.
</P>
<P>
   Other errors introduce to the American Revolution events far
removed in time and place. The extreme violence reaches its peak
when the villain Tavlington confines the inhabitants of town in a
church, sets it ablaze and burns them alive.
</P>
<P>
   Something remarkably like this event actually happened, but not
in South Carolina during the American Revolution. It happened in
the French village of Oradour-sur-Glane on June 10, 1944, during
World War II, and it was done by Emmerich's countrymen of the 2nd
S.S. Panzer Division. There were atrocities enough on both sides in
the American Revolution, but the German director has converted an
18th century British and American loyalist army into the S.S.
</P>
<P>
   The British villain Tavlington is so steeped in evil and
Cornwallis is so feckless and incompetent that the two men become
mere caricatures. (So does the saintly American hero.) The real
Tarleton was deeply conflicted, and more dramatic than the
cardboard villain we are given here.
</P>
<P>
   The inaccuracies in ``The Patriot'' are all errors in the first
degree: willful and premeditated. Emmerich is quoted on the Web
site as saying, ``On certain kinds of points, we had to decide what
is most important, historical accuracy or the dramatic impact.''
One wonders if there was ever any point where the filmmakers
decided accuracy was the more important.
</P>
<P>
   (David Hackett Fischer, professor of American history at
Brandeis, is the author of ``Paul Revere's Ride'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
