<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-PAYROLL-NYT     06-30 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PAYROLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE ACQUISITION PUSHES YANKEES' PAYROLL OVER $100 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees did not need Sammy Sosa or Juan
Gonzalez to establish an historic payroll plateau. The acquisition
of David Justice did the job just fine.
</P>
<P>
   In obtaining Justice from the Cleveland Indians, the Yankees
inherited his $7 million salary, which catapulted their payroll
beyond the $100 million mark, making them the first baseball team
to wade in those expensive waters. George Steinbrenner, the
Yankees' principal owner, doesn't like to establish standards, but
he can't escape this one.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball payrolls are computed in different ways for
different purposes, the method used by both Major League Baseball
and the players association to determine season payrolls puts the
Yankees' adjusted payroll at nearly $103 million, or $102,724,260
if all of the players' salaries are added. That total is up from
the record level of $92.5 million at which the Yankees began the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The primary change resulted from two trades. In adding Justice,
who joined the Yankees Friday in St. Petersburg, Fla., and sending
Ricky Ledee to the Cleveland Indians, the Yankees exchanged Ledee's
$240,000 salary for Justice's $7 million. The Indians were
delighted with that exchange rate, but the Yankees weren't going to
let money stand between them and another shot at the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Yankees got Jose Vizcaino from the Los
Angeles Dodgers for Jim Leyritz. That trade added a net of $2.5
million to the Yankees' payroll because Vizcaino has a $3.5 million
salary and Leyritz $1 million. To help offset the difference, the
Dodgers included $500,000 in the deal, but even if that sum were
subtracted from the total payroll, the Yankees would still be in
the nine-figure payroll area.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians did not send any money with Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Historic though it may be, the Yankees' bulging payroll will not
evoke any congratulatory notes. The arrival of a $100 million
payroll is generally seen as further evidence that something
drastic has to be done to resolve the growing disparity in
payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who began the season with the second-highest
payroll, are now more than $15 million behind the Yankees. But at
the other end of the salary scale, the four lowest payrolls
combined _ belonging to Minnesota, Florida, Kansas City and
Pittsburgh _ don't equal the Yankees' figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inexorably marching toward a club being over $100
million,'' Commissioner Bud Selig said, ``so I guess no one will be
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the frugal head of a club with a payroll that
falls somewhere between the Yankees and their poorest cousins said
he was not disgusted that the Yankees had reached the $100 million
landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a big deal for me,'' he said, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``This is a natural evolution of the game. I might
not like it, but so what?''
</P>
<P>
   A lucrative television contract has enabled the Yankees to spend
more than other teams. This is the last year of the Yankees'
12-year, $486 million deal with Cablevision. No other team has
earned even half that $40.5 million annual average in that period.
</P>
<P>
   An even bleaker prospect is ahead for the Yankees' competition.
Whether they sign a new contract with Cablevision or embark on
their own cable network through YankeeNets, the Yankees will reap
far more revenue in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have estimated that if the Yankees and Cablevision
negotiate another deal, it could be worth $100 million a year to
the team that has won the World Series three times in the last four
years. Should the Yankees decide to create their own network, they
would generate even more revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams could console themselves because the Yankees added
Justice and not Sosa or Gonzalez. If they had succeeded in
completing a deal with the Chicago Cubs for Sosa, the Yankees would
have had to sign him to a contract extension to secure his needed
approval for the trade. That extension would have been worth
somewhere in the $16 million to $18 million range.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could argue that because Justice has spent nearly
half the season with the Indians, the Yankees' share of his salary
will actually be $3,615,384. But when Major League Baseball and the
players association compute a season's payroll, the entire salary
is charged to the acquiring team.
</P>
</TEXT>
