<HEADLINE>
STORAGENETWORKS IPO A SMASH HIT ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet IPOs can still be lucrative _ as long as the company is
one helping to support the Internet and not merely trying to sell
things on it.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of discriminating exuberance was in evidence Friday,
as investors fell over themselves buying debut shares of
StorageNetworks Inc., a Waltham, Mass. company that seeks to make
data storage as handy as electricity or phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Shares shot up from $27 to $97.25 in first-day trading on
Nasdaq, more than tripling the value of the $243 million initial
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said StorageNetworks' show-stealing performance was a
sign of Wall Street confidence in firms that focus on
infrastructure niches, such as data storage, in contrast to
dot-coms or the latest e-retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a great future, that whole segment of the market,''
said John Webster of Illuminata Group, industry analysts and
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say if you want to host a number of applications for
your customers, rather than go out and buy the storage you need,
you got to StorageNetworks and say, `Build the storage utility
here.' And whenever you want capacity, you get capacity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   StorageNetworks is creating a fiber-optic network that will
allow companies to store a virtually unlimited amount of data to
which they will have access over the Web, according to the
company's Securities and Exchange filing.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street got a hint of the strong response when the price
range on the deal, underwritten by Goldman, Sachs, was adjusted
from $17 to $19 a share to $23 to $25. The company has 88.2 million
shares outstanding after the IPO, giving it a market capitalization
of more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight week that Massachusetts-based
companies were standouts in an otherwise sagging IPO market. On
June 23, Charles River Laboratories of Wilmington and
Manufacturers' Services Ltd. of Concord traded 25 percent higher in
their New York Stock Exchange debuts.
</P>
<P>
   StorageNetworks shares could see a pullback after the initial
enthusiasm subsides. The company has competitors, and there is some
uncertainty about whether businesses will trust their data storage
to another company through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The successful IPO was notable for other reasons, however.
Earlier in the week, SEC documents revealed a nasty dispute with
EMC Corp. of Hopkinton, Mass., including the possibility of a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   EMC makes the actual gear for data storage with its disk-drive
assemblies for big computer databases; StorageNetworks buys that
equipment and makes the capacity available remotely. Several former
EMC managers are now at StorageNetworks, including chief executive
Peter Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Although the StorageNetworks-EMC relationship was thought to be
complimentary, EMC accused StorageNetworks of misrepresenting its
investment in the company, stealing away employees, and
misappropriating confidential EMC data.
</P>
<P>
   Two other events colored the IPO:
</P>
<P>
   Bell and the chief technology officer, William D. Miller, both
sold millions of dollars worth of their shares in the company in
January, something that executives are usually hesitant to do
because it could show a lack of confidence in the business going
public.
</P>
<P>
   And in its prospectus, StorageNetworks had to correct statements
made by Bell in news media interviews during the run-up to the IPO,
on such topics as the company's jump on competitors and the
cost-savings its services can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, StorageNetworks pulled far away from five other
firms that also went public.
</P>
<P>
   EXFO Electro-Optical Engineering Inc., a Canadian company, was
second-best, as shares rose 18.75 to 44.75.
</P>
<P>
   The others _ Precise Software Ltd., an Israeli software firm;
Mobility Electronics Inc., a portable communications technology
firm; the Russian cellular phone company Mobile TeleSystems; and
the Chinese Internet portal Netease.com Inc. _ had only modest
gains or losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
