<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIPOLLINI'S BACKUP AWAITS HIS FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ The good news for Daniel Atienza's fans _
all three of them _ is that the 25-year-old Spaniard is still in
the Tour de France. The bad news is that his status is shaky
because the race has not started yet.
</P>
<P>
   Atienza, a hewer of wood and bearer of water for the Saeco team
from Italy, is part of the nine-man team only because Mario
Cipollini is not.
</P>
<P>
   Cipollini, 33, the star sprinter and team leader, hurt some ribs
in a crash during a training ride two weeks ago. At first he
announced that he would not ride in the Tour de France, in which he
won four consecutive daily stages last year. But lately he has been
wavering.
</P>
<P>
   With hours to go before the team rosters are official, Cipollini
is still out, so Atienza is still in. Will the Italian, a master of
theatrics, appear in Futuroscope at the last minute for Saturday's
opening time trial, clad in the Julius Caesar toga he favors for
special occasions and oust his doppelgaenger?
</P>
<P>
   That question may be somewhat less than burning, but it is as
big as they come in the torpid countdown for the 20 teams preparing
for Saturday's start of the three-week, 2,274-mile race in
Futuroscope.
</P>
<P>
   A better question might be why Futuroscope? The technology theme
park, a shrine to the pocket-protector set, is a favorite with the
Tour de France, and not only because its owners, the Amaury
publishing company, are also the main shareholder in Futuroscope.
That deal went through on March 28, but the bicycle race has been
coming here to western France since 1986, a year before the park
officially opened. It was a wasteland then, a condition not notably
improved by the addition of the Lake of Images and Cyber Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   This visit did not have to happen. Another candidate for the
start was Guadeloupe, a prospect that stirred the blood. But, in
place of gentle Caribbean breezes and beaches of soft volcanic
sand, there will be guided visits to the Gyrotour and Our Friend,
the Radio Telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Futuroscope is more practical, the organizers insist, with an
abundance of hotels and parking lots _ and no need to fly 180
riders and their entourage halfway around the world. Including the
start in 1990, the Tour de France has visited the park five times
before this weekend. The race has never been to Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, back to the Futuroscope it is.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the pre-race festivities, the riders were assembled
Friday for an address by race officials about their
responsibilities toward the public and the sport itself. That
translated basically into a warning about drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will take the risk of playing with fire and ruining his
reputation?'' Jean-Marie Leblanc, the head of the organizers,
asked. He called for ``a serene atmosphere with no suspicion, a
return to the friendliness of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the widespread news media speculation
about drugs that has plagued the Tour de France since the Festina
scandal two years ago. The Festina team was expelled then for
systematic use of illegal performance-enhancing substances, notably
EPO, and several teams quit to protest police searches.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc congratulated the International Cycling Union, which
oversees the sport, for its decision last week to freeze selected
riders' urine samples and test them for EPO once a new French
examination for the artificial hormone has been officially approved
_ supposedly a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   Riders, Leblanc pointed out, thus face being disqualified and
penalized long after the race ends in Paris on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tour de France is a monument of cycling,'' he said, ``and
we have a duty to protect it. In three weeks, when the Tour has
finished, let us hope that the race's reputation has been
completely restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Many riders have publicly welcomed the testing decision, as did
Lance Armstrong, the defending champion, at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of the myth of widespread doping in cycling, and it
really is a myth,'' Armstrong said. ``This sport has been singled
out and it's doing everything it can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
