<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FOOD-INSPECTIONS-0701     06-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-INSPECTIONS-0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEAVE INSPECTIONS TO INSPECTORS, COURT RULES
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inspecting animals headed to slaughter must remain
the sole responsibility of federal meat and poultry inspectors and
not left to plant employees as the Department of Agriculture has
done in some chicken plants, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by a three-judge panel, in response to a lawsuit
brought by the meat inspectors' union, sarcastically dismissed the
USDA's contention that having federal inspectors oversee the work
of plant employees on the slaughter line was sufficient to meet the
legal definition of an inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, the government believes that federal employees
fulfill their statutory duty to inspect by watching others perform
the task,'' Circuit Judge A. Raymond Randolph wrote. ``One might as
well say that umpires are pitchers because they carefully watch
others throw baseballs.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Department of Agriculture said the agency
couldn't comment until its ``officials and lawyers have had a
chance to review the judges' findings.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is the latest blow to the Agriculture Department's
massive effort to modernize food inspection in America by
introducing bacteria testing while moving many inspectors into
oversight roles where they primarily track results of the tests.
Last year a judge in Dallas refused to let the USDA close a plant
that had failed those tests.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ruling dealt with the inspection of animals at
slaughter houses but could nonetheless have a broad impact on the
Agriculture Department's modernization efforts, according to
industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision means that it may be impossible to modernize the
inspection system without modernizing the statutes,'' said Caroline
Smith-DeWaal, who heads the food safety division of the Center for
Science in the Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   Smith-DeWaal said the decision focuses heavily on provisions in
federal law dating back 90 years that require an animal-by-animal
inspection at slaughter houses by officials of the Agriculture
Department. In a pilot program set up in about 15 chicken plants,
the department left much of that work to plant employees while
inspectors took random samples of carcass to see if the employees
were catching diseased animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent federal employees are doing any systematic
inspecting under the (pilot program), they are inspecting people
not carcasses,'' Randolph wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The American Federation of Government Employees, the arm of the
AFL-CIO that represents meat and poultry inspectors and filed the
suit, delighted in the ruling and its tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's reflective of the skepticism that the court
brought, and rightfully so, to the argument the government made,''
said Anne M. Wagner, the union's assistant general counsel for
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said meat and poultry inspectors favor the use of
bacteria testing but would like to see the tests used in
conjunction with traditional government inspections. Wagner said
that's what consumers expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now people believe when they buy meat that somebody has
actually looked at the carcass,'' she said. ``We don't really
accept the fundamental philosophy that (the modernized inspection
program) mandates the elimination of inspectors.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges sent the case back to the U.S. District Court in
Washington, D.C. Wagner said she did not know how quickly the court
will enforce Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program in slaughter houses was the subject of a Cox
Newspapers investigation earlier this year, which revealed that
high percentages of diseased chickens were getting through the new
inspection system at two Gold Kist, Inc. plants in Alabama. The
revelations triggered an investigation by the Agriculture
Department's office of the Inspector General, which confirmed many
of the findings of the Cox report but declared there to be no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Tucker Foreman, who ran the food inspection operation
under President Carter, echoed the comments of Smith-DeWaal that
the latest ruling could require a rewrite of meat and poultry
inspection laws as part of the modernization effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Foreman, who now works with the Consumer Federation of
America, said she wasn't upset by Friday's ruling even though her
group has endorsed the pilot inspection program. She said she's
withholding judgment because results of the bacteria testing
haven't been made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say we've lost something important here because I just
don't know if that's the case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery's e-mail address is scottm(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
