<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0111 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LYCOS-TERRA-BOS &LR;      06-30 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-TERRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRA PARENT TO UNDERWRITE BERTELSMANN INVESTMENT IN LYCOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. isn't taking any chances with its new German content
provider, Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   In its agreement to be bought by Terra Networks, the Waltham,
Mass. company has arranged for Terra's parent to make up most of
the difference if Bertelsmann doesn't come through with a promised
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, Bertelsmann and Spain's Terra Networks said in May the
German publishing giant would buy $1 billion worth of advertising
and services from a new company to be formed by the merger of Lycos
and Terra. Executives have described the revenue as a key
competitive advantage for the new company, Terra Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   But in a filing to the US Securities and Exchange Commission
this week, Terra Networks disclosed that its majority owner,
Telefonica SA, has agreed to pay for up to two-thirds of the total,
$675 million, ``if necessary,'' if Bertelsmann doesn't put up the
full amount over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann is only ``obliged'' to pay $325 million for ads and
other services during the first two years of the agreement, the
filing states.
</P>
<P>
   All sides say Bertelsmann hasn't reduced its commitment to buy
the full $1 billion worth of advertising and e-commerce services.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Lycos chief executive Bob Davis said he
insisted Telefonica back up Bertelsmann's role before he agreed to
the merger. Davis said he worried Bertelsmann could reduce its
commitments over the five-year course of the agreement. ``Five
years is a long time,'' Davis said. ``This is a little more
assurance.
</P>
<P>
   A Bertelsmann representative in New York said the details of the
agreement were consistent with the company's previous statements.
Terra declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's participation in the agreement is seen as central
to the success of Terra Lycos because the German publishing giant
would supply the new company with content ranging from its Stern
magazine in Germany to its big stable of American authors, movie
studios and record labels.
</P>
<P>
   The material could help Terra Lycos attract viewers from the
likes of America Online Inc., which is buying Bertelsmann
competitor Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' deal with Terra was worth $12.5 billion when it was
announced May 16, but shares in Terra have slipped since then to
make the agreement worth around $10 billion, based on Terra's
closing price Friday of $36.469 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   A chief concern has been the role of Telefonica's controversial
chairman, Juan Villalonga, who has alienated many in Spain's
government and faces a reopened insider-trading inquiry by
regulators there. He and Telefonica deny wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga enjoys support from investors, however, and earlier
this week Telefonica's board of directors declined to act against
him. Lycos shareholders must still approve the merger, at a special
meeting expected in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Terra's filing also gave details about the company's financial
outlook and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the document, Terra had an operating loss of $86.3
million, last year on revenue of $47.7 million. Lycos had an
operating loss of $67 million on revenue of $138.5 million during
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Terra said, it expects its losses will continue ``for the
foreseeable future,'' and that expenses will exceed the combined
company's revenue for at least the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Lycos would have to pay Terra
Networks a termination fee of $347.6 million if its shareholders
don't approve the merger in most circumstances, chiefly if a rival
bidder emerges for Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Terra's filing also includes a section titled ``Risks Related to
Being Part of the Telefonica Group.'' Among other things, Terra
noted that other Telefonica companies ``could compete with us, and
they may pursue their own Internet-related bsuiness or operational
strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Telefonica's Argentine telecommunications unit also
runs a Internet portal targeting the same home users Terra Lycos
aims to attract, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk is that Internet use in Latin America may grow more
slowly than expected. Terra said it received 73 percent of its
revenue from Latin operations. And Terra warned its free-Internet
access offerings in Spain, Brazil, Mexico and other countries could
prove costly.
</P>
<P>
   Terra also outlined new five-year employment agreements for
senior Lycos executives including Davis, who would be chief
executive of the new venture. He would get a base salary and bonus
of $500,000, plus a $5 million payment in case of severance. He
would also receive options to acquire 2 million Terra Lycos shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
