<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GAY-UNIONS0630-COX     06-30 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-UNIONS0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay Georgians look to Vermont for validation
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The passionflower climbing a fence in their yard is in
bloom. The roses are a healthy pink. A waterfall spills into a
round, stone pool where lilies grow.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Deeb and Jerry Gonzalez built the garden, behind their home,
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of work on it,'' says Deeb, 35, a physician. ``It
doesn't just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeb and Gonzalez, 29, a marketing engineer, tend their
relationship as carefully as their garden _ which is saying a lot,
considering the sweat they poured into a once swampy back yard with
dead trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we go to bed, we pray together, and we thank God for
what we have,'' Gonzalez says.
</P>
<P>
   And for what they're about to get: hitched, Vermont-style.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday, gay men and lesbians who live in or visit
Vermont may enter into legal arrangements that are same-sex
marriages in almost everything but name. Such unions are something
new, unique in American history. Deeb and Gonzalez are planning
their trip for September, to mark the two-year anniversary of their
Georgia commitment ceremony, which has no legal standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important step forward for us as a family,'' says
Gonzalez, sitting on a beige love seat and holding hands with Deeb.
``We're doing everything we can to protect our family. That's what
it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   The men met four years ago at a country and western bar in
Atlanta. At first they were ``kind of like any other couple that's
infatuated,'' Deeb says. ``Then, when reality finally sets in, you
start talking about the difficult core issues of values. We talked
about religion and politics and honesty and trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Their values matched. Two years ago in September, Deeb and
Gonzalez, wearing black tuxedos, stood before a minister at their
Decatur church and exchanged gold bands and vows of love in front
of about 100 family members and friends. Then they took a honeymoon
in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been married for two years,'' Gonzalez says. ``It's not
recognized by the state or the federal government, but it's
recognized before God and before our families and our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Photos from the ceremony and Hawaii decorate the walls of their
four-bedroom house. But the men won't officially be ``next of kin''
until their civil-union ceremony. Even that status will probably
apply only in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's law confers on same-sex couples the rights and
responsibilities enjoyed by married couples, from health insurance
benefits to inheritance rights. The federal government isn't
expected to recognize such unions for income tax calculations,
Social Security benefits, immigration rights or other matters. And
it's unclear whether Vermont civil unions will hold any sway in
Georgia or other states.
</P>
<P>
   But for Deeb and Gonzalez it's a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change takes time,'' Deeb says. But the couple isn't willing
to wait forever: They've spoken with lawyers and say they may one
day challenge Georgia's opposition to same-sex unions in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lead our lives like any other couple who goes to work every
morning,'' Deeb says. ``Take out our trash, take care of our yard
and everything else. But it becomes an issue when we don't have the
same legal rights and benefits that other legally married couples
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Gonzalez: ``Something as basic as hospital visitation
rights. If something were to happen to Ray, I wouldn't be able to
visit him because I'm not next of kin.... That's something pretty
ridiculous, that I wouldn't be able to see the most important
person in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and Deeb know one other couple from metro Atlanta going
to Vermont for a civil-union ceremony, two women from their church,
Christ Covenant Metropolitan Community Church. The women, who
declined to participate in this article, are going to Vermont this
month, and the men are eager to hear how it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're picking a small town because they don't want any
publicity,'' Gonzalez says. ``We're doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Deeb: ``There are gay-friendly justices of the peace and
town clerks who don't have a problem with it. We'll probably find a
town where they will welcome us. We'll chose our town carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll come home and watch their garden grow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
