<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IMMIGRANTS-CITIZENS-$     06-30 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-CITIZENS-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEWER IMMIGRANTS ARE BECOMING CITIZENS
 &HT;    With IMMIGRANTS and IMMIGRANTS-DATA. For release Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America has more immigrants, but fewer are becoming
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Only about one-third of the nation's immigrants have obtained
citizenship, the smallest proportion in the past century. The
phenomenon was detailed in a U.S. Census Bureau report released
late last year that sparked a debate over the reasons for the
decline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, only 35 percent of foreign-born people in the United
States were naturalized citizens, compared to 64 percent in 1970.
During the major wave of immigration in the early 20th century,
about half of all immigrants became citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Immigration and Naturalization Service say the
decline was caused by policy changes that made it more difficult
and more expensive to become a citizen. The huge backlog of
naturalization cases also has discouraged many immigrants from
applying, said Harry Pachon, president of the Tomas(cq) Riviera
Policy Institute, a research group on Hispanic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Other social analysts question whether the numbers indicate an
growing unwillingness among immigrants to assimilate to life in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The large proportion of immigrants from Mexico _ 28 percent of
the foreign-born population in the United States _ could have much
to do with the decline. In 1990, about 22 percent of the
Mexican-born population had become naturalized citizens. By 1997,
the number had fallen to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many immigrants from nearby Mexico may be less willing to seek
U.S. citizenship than those from Europe and Asia. Immigrants from
Asia increased their citizenship rate from 40 to 44 percent between
1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   People with higher levels of education also are more likely to
seek citizenship than those who have not completed high school, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
