<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ULMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFRED ULMER, 83, OFFICER IN INTELLIGENCE AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla.)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alfred C. Ulmer Jr., a former official of the Office of
Strategic Services and the CIA, died on June 22 in Virginia Beach,
Va. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Ulmer did intelligence work in the Navy in World War II and then
joined the OSS. He served in Turkey, Egypt, Italy and Austria,
overseeing intelligence operatives who were gathering information
about the German military in North Africa and the Balkans, his
family said.
</P>
<P>
   The service was disbanded by President Truman late in 1945, and
Ulmer joined the CIA not long after it was founded in 1947. He
retired in 1962 and received the agency's Intelligence Medal of
Merit.
</P>
<P>
   In his CIA years, he was stationed in Madrid, Athens, Paris and
Washington. He ran the agency's Far East operations from 1955 to
1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, we had fun,'' he said in a 1994 interview. ``We went all
over the world and we did what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Powers wrote in his book ``The Man Who Kept the Secrets:
Richard Helms and the CIA'' (1979) that in 1956 Frank Wisner, a
senior CIA executive, told Ulmer, ``It's time we held Sukarno's
feet to the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Sukarno was Indonesia's leader. Powers wrote that
the director of central intelligence, Allen Dulles, and his
brother, Secretary of State John Foster Dulles, ``did not want to
overthrow Sukarno exactly, just force him to suppress the PKI'' _
Indonesia's large Communist Party _ ``send the Russians packing and
get on the American team.''
</P>
<P>
   So the agency aided anti-Sukarno rebels, but they were
confronted successfully by Sukarno's forces and, Powers wrote,
Allen Dulles decided that the rebels must be told that the United
States had to disengage. ``The result,'' Powers said, ``was a
humiliation for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In a major covert operation in Japan, the agency spent millions
of dollars in the 1950s and '60s to support the conservative party
that dominated the country's politics for a generation, the Liberal
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ulmer was born in Jacksonville, Fla., and graduated from
Princeton in 1939. After the CIA, he worked in the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Doris Gibson Bridges ended in divorce. He is
survived by a son, Nicholas, of Geneva; a daughter, Marguerite
Ulmer Power, of Virginia Beach; five grandchildren; a brother; and
two sisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BARNUM-MUSEUM-565&AMP;ADD     06-30 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNUM-MUSEUM-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD BARNUM MUSEUM IS REBORN ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a combination zoo, museum, lecture hall, wax
museum, theater and freak show, a Museum of Un-Natural History
that, according to one historian, was ``a central site in the
development of American popular culture.'' It burned in July 1865,
was rebuilt a few blocks away, and burned again in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, P.T. Barnum's American Museum opened once again, on
the World Wide Web, a medium perhaps well suited to the
circus-meister's fantabulous claims.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and producers at the Center for Media and Learning and
the New Media Lab, both part of the City University of New York
Graduate Center, have rebuilt the five-story museum in virtual
space on a Web site. The Web address is
http://web.gc.cuny.edu/ashp/lostmuseum.
</P>
<P>
   Supported in part by a grant from the National Endowment for the
Humanities, the site will provide students and history buffs with a
full archive of information about the museum and relevant
19th-century subjects. It will eventually include a variety of
investigative paths to take through the five-story building, for
those wanting to play detective and figure out who set it on fire
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Barnum, who believed that every crowd had a silver lining and
that a sucker was born every minute, reveled in the museum's claim
of being the most visited spot in America. He reported that the
museum, which was open 15 hours a day, six days a week) often had
up to 15,000 visitors a day (that would be more than 16 suckers per
minute), though an accurate guest count might have been beyond his
capacities.
</P>
<P>
   Signs in the museum, which was at Broadway and Ann Street,
reportedly pointed enthusiastically toward a magnificent,
not-to-be-missed attraction, ``The Egress,'' which was actually an
unmarked exit. Those rushing to see said egress would find
themselves outside, needing to pay another 25-cent admission fee.
</P>
<P>
   Those two bits bought visitors the chance to see Tom Thumb, the
midget; Anna Swan, the giantess from Nova Scotia, whom Barnum
dressed in 100 yards of satin and 50 yards of lace; the Fejee
Mermaid (supposedly a mummified maiden, but actually the desiccated
head of a monkey and the body of an orangutan, attached to the back
of a fish); and the wax museum figure of Jefferson Davis, the
Confederate president, wearing a woman's dress, in accordance with
rumors that he tried to escape from Union forces in drag.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of the original attractions were saved from the
fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``A red-shined fireman seized with either hand Franklin Pierce
and James Buchanan by their coat-collars, tucked the Prince
Imperial of France under one arm and the Veiled Murderess under the
other, and coolly departed for the street,'' according to an
article in The New York Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some one had stuck a cigar in General Washington's mouth, and
thus, with his chapeau crushed down over his eyes and his head
leaning upon the ample lap of Moll Pitcher, the Father of his
Country led the van of as sorry a band of patriots as not often
comes within one's experience to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the exhibits, however, left behind only
their legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot to work with,'' said Joshua Brown, director
for the Center for Media and Learning/American Social History
Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guessing,'' he said. ``Part of the problem is
it's Barnum, so a lot of it is humbug.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Peter Buckley, an associate professor of history at Cooper Union
and a Barnum scholar, worked as an independent reviewer of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at the little things that they've had to do to
reconstruct it,'' he said of the online museum. ``They had to try
and get the right texture for the floorboards and walls, so they
had to go down to an old building in the South Street Seaport and
take photos of old pine boards, hoping that was close to the
original texture, and then mapping those textures throughout the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet surfers can see a film about Barnum, visit the main
salon in the museum, zoom in on pictures on the walls, open exhibit
drawers to read archival documents, and read contemporary accounts
of the fire and of Davis' escapades.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brier, a co-director of the New Media Lab, said, ``It's
a way of imagining the past, and we practice it in an
unconventional way, so instead of writing monographs, we produce
films and CD-ROMs, and now we're working on the re-creation of a
space that no longer exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Ades Vasquez, the lab's managing director, said, ``We'd
like it to be a model, for solving different mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Internet, which provides free admission to a
wide variety of curiosities of varying authenticity, is an apt home
for Barnum. In any case, he provides a fine lens on the era in
which he lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe what's uniquely American about Barnum was this effort _
he called it democratic, but it might be something else _ to bring
everybody together, regardless of class background,'' Buckley of
Cooper Union said. ``It was the whole period of the 1840s when I
believe it's possible to say that a distinct American popular
culture was developed, and the museum is central, and Barnum is
central, to that development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
