<HEADER>
A0129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COURT-RAPE-BOS &LR;      06-30 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-RAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING SEEN AS WEAKENING RAPE VICTIMS' PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a decision women's activists say will cause rape
victims to choose between privacy and prosecution, the state's
highest court has held a rape crisis center in contempt for
refusing to turn over telephone hotline records sought by lawyers
for an accused rapist.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court's 20-page ruling represented an
unusual splintering of opinion, with two of the high court's three
females members, Chief Justice Margaret Marshall and Associate
Justice Ruth Abrams, dissenting and Justice Judith Cowin writing
the majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-2 ruling against the Boston Area Rape Crisis Center,
which faces civil fines as a result of the decision, the high court
acknowledged that ``there is no longer a need for the records to be
produced'' because the defendant pleaded guilty to assault charges,
closing the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, however, Cowin says that the communications
between the counselor and the victim should have been made
available for possible release to the defense because there was
some question whether the counselor convinced the victim she was
raped.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the information confidential would have denied the
defendant ``a right to learn whether the young woman's
conversations with the counselor are consistent with her
accusations against him,'' Cowin writes.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrams warns that the majority opinion overrules an earlier
SJC decision that set up strict standards governing the release of
records from rape crisis centers. She cautions that the opinion
will result in virtually ``automatic'' review of some privilege
material by judges.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams argues that the victim's contacting a rape counselor
before reporting the incident to police ``should not provide the
reason for being forced to disclose her privileged communications
with a counsellor she turns to for advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and victim's advocates sided with Abrams saying the
ruling will make it easier for confidential rape counseling records
to be obtained, while defense attorneys contend there are already
strict rules in place to protect the privacy of rape victims.
</P>
<P>
   Boston lawyer Wendy Murphy, who represents the rape crisis
center, called the decision ``extremely disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends the message that if you become a crime victim, you
have to choose between prosecution and privacy, between justice and
healing,'' said Murphy, who is considering a federal appeal. ``That
is not a fair choice. It's an outrageous choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Geoffrey Packard, president of the Massachusetts Association
of Criminal Defense Lawyers and a senior trial counsel for the
Committee for Public Counsel Services, called Murphy's argument
``nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense lawyers have to go through a very difficult process in
order to look at these records,'' he said. ``The bar is set very
high, and judges aren't just turning them over willy nilly.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the SJC has established stringent rules for gaining
access to rape counseling records, including proof from the
defendant that there is a specific and legitimate need. Even then,
the records must be turned over to a judge who reviews them in
private before deciding what, if anything, may be released.
</P>
<P>
   The high court created those rules after overturning a 1985
state law that cloaked rape counseling records in the same level of
confidentiality reserved for priests and penitents, saying that an
absolute bar to the release of such records was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Craig Neumyer, the Lynn man accused of the rape, had
argued that the alleged victim's counseling records contained
evidence crucial to his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Packard and other defense attorneys also said they believe the
decision is limited in scope, and is unlikely to have far-reaching
impact.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted that the SJC in 1996 vacated contempt charges
against the director of a Worcester rape crisis center who was
ordered jailed after she refused to release counseling records of a
client, suggesting that Neumyer's lawyers had more valid reasons to
seek the counseling records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling preserves a defendant's ability, in narrowly
limited circumstances, to have access to information that bears
meaningfully upon his guilt or innocence,'' said William Leahy,
executive director of the Committee for Public Counsel Services,
who represented Neumyer.
</P>
<P>
   But John Zanini, a prosecutor with the Suffolk District
Attorney's office, which submitted an amicus brief advocating that
the records remain confidential, said the high court's ruling
``tilts the balance in favor of defendants rather than victims like
this girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Neumyer was charged with raping the 18-year-old victim after
they drank and smoked marijuana together for several hours in 1996.
The woman contacted the Boston Area Rape Crisis Center the next
day, saying she was uncertain whether what had happened to her was
rape. A counselor told her that it was rape and the victim
contacted police, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in what the center's attorneys say was a violation of her
privacy rights, the victim disclosed her contact with the center
during a probable cause hearing, opening the door for Neumyer's
attorneys to ask for the records.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Cowin in the majority were Justices Neil Lynch, John
Greaney, Roderick Ireland, and Francis Spina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
