<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOWDOW0701-COX     06-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWDOW0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small gains close dismal quarter
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market ended its worst quarter in two years
on Friday with broad but anemic gains as investors concentrated
mostly on the sector that suffered the biggest setback in the past
three months _ technology.
</P>
<P>
   All the major stock market indexes posted losses in the
April-June period, but the technology-loaded Nasdaq composite
experienced the biggest drop in 10 years, falling just over 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three of every four stocks in the Nasdaq 100 _ an index
of the 100 largest and most active Nasdaq stocks _ suffered losses
vs. 43 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Among the losers were some of the best-known technology stocks,
including Novell, down 68 percent; Qualcomm, 61 percent; Compuware,
51 percent; and Amazon.com, 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That was a far cry from the beginning of the year, when demand
for Internet and so-called dot-com stocks prompted some analysts to
talk of a new era for the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite, which didn't close above 4,000 until Dec.
29, surged another 1,000 points in the next two months to a closing
peak of 5,048.62 on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then a combination of events, including extreme caution by many
analysts, a setback in the biotech sector and unexpected profit
weakness in some high-profile companies, triggered a sell-off that
eventually sent the Nasdaq tumbling 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The index has rallied since its May 23 low, but its decline in
the second quarter was its worst slump since the 1990 bear market,
when the index fell more than 25 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for investors is that the biggest losses occurred
early in the latest period, prompting many analysts to believe the
worst of the stock market's correction that started in the spring
is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is expected to be more volatility, but the technical
structure now in place suggests that the low has been seen and that
the stage is set for an eventual move higher,'' said Prudential
Securities technical analyst Ralph Acampora.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's decision on Wednesday not to raise
interest rates was viewed by investors as a reason for optimism,
tempered however by the Fed's suggestion that further rate hikes
are likely since inflation is still a threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates six times since June 1999 to cool what
it regards as an inflationary economy.
</P>
<P>
   With the next Fed meeting not until Aug. 22, investors will turn
their attention to second-quarter earnings reports in July,
according to Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst David Kim.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near term, the market will also focus on the June
employment report, still a week away, and the June producer and
consumer price data in a little over two weeks,' said Kim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both reports have the potential for major bearish surprises,
especially with the Fed's focus on labor market conditions, and the
recent oil run-up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's trading, the Nasdaq composite was the market leader,
rising all day to close at 3,966.11 with a gain of 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indexes would have posted losses except for late buying
that produced narrow gains: 0.5 percent for the Dow Jones
industrial average, to 10,447.89, and 0.9 percent for the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500, to 1,454.60.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date, the Dow is the biggest loser, falling just over 9
percent, with the S&AMP;P-500 dropping 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Nasdaq composite's 37 percent plunge at the worst
point of its second-quarter sell-off, that index finished the first
half down only 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The second quarter was the worst period for the stock market
since the July-October stretch in 1998, when Asian currency
problems and a Russian debt default sent investors searching for
safe havens in bonds and blue chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The losses by the Nasdaq, the Dow and S&AMP;P 500 since the end of
1999 make the first six months of 2000 the worst half-year period
for the broad market since 1994. That was the last time the Federal
Reserve raised interest rates multiple times, also in an effort to
combat inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
