<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SBC-TEXAS0701-COX     06-30 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-TEXAS0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBC gets to go the distance, FCC says
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ SBC Communications, the largest of the remaining
regional Bell companies, has become the second Bell to win the
right to offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission announced Friday that it
has voted to permit the San Antonio-based Bell to offer
long-distance service in Texas, about seven months after giving
similar approval to Bell Atlantic in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The decision helps set the ground rules that Atlanta-based
BellSouth and Denver-based U.S. West will have to meet to also
enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Edward E. Whitacre Jr., SBC chairman and chief executive
officer, shrugged off the current price war in long-distance and
touted the FCC decision as key to a future in which customers look
to one company for all their communications services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-distance rounds out our full-service bundles and is key
to capitalizing on our company's single biggest growth opportunity
and new core business _ data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's approval is effective July 10. SBC said Friday it will
launch service that day under the name of its corporate forebear,
Southwestern Bell.
</P>
<P>
   When the seven ``Baby Bells'' were created in the 1984 breakup
of AT&AMP;T, each was forbidden from offering long-distance service on
its home turf. But the Telecommunications Act of 1996 permitted
entry for any Bell that could persuade regulators that its own
local market was open to competition.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth had for a time hoped to be the first Bell into
long-distance, only to be repeatedly stymied. BellSouth did win
state approval in South Carolina and Louisiana, only to be rejected
by the FCC. But in its home state of Georgia, the company's efforts
have been beset by complaints of rivals and concerns of the Public
Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said BellSouth systems could not handle the large shifts
of customers to new carriers that will likely follow approval. For
nearly a year, those systems have been undergoing tests monitored
by consultants at KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC will start looking at the KPMG tests Wednesday to see if
this time the company has made the grade _ especially in the light
of Friday's FCC decision. If BellSouth passes the KPMG tests, it
would ask the PSC to endorse long-distance approval in Georgia, and
an application to the FCC would follow that.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Vice Chairman Jere Drummond congratulated SBC and FCC
Chairman William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   ``(They) deserve praise for bringing a meaningful choice for
long-distance service to Texas consumers. In
</P>
<P>
   August, BellSouth plans to seek approval to offer consumers a
true choice for long-distance service in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC's application applies only to Texas, but the systems
involved are used through its region, so other approvals are
expected to follow. BellSouth on Friday saw its stock drop $1.56 a
share to $42.63.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's on Friday lowered its long-term ratings on
BellSouth, a move spurred by December's news that BellSouth would
provide up to $8 billion to help fund acquisitions by Dutch-based
KPN Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's also affirmed its short-term ratings on
BellSouth Capital Funding Corp. and BellSouth Telecommunications
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
