<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG, HAMILTON SIT ATOP US POSTAL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no question that Lance Armstrong, last year's winner of
the Tour de France, is the designated leader of the American-based
US Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   There's also little question about the identity of his strongest
teammate: Marblehead, Mass. native Tyler Hamilton, who will be
riding in his fourth Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's win last month at the Dauphine Libere stage race in
southwestern France proved that. Armstrong finished third, 36
seconds behind. The winner credited Armstrong for helping him get
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Lance, I never would have won, because with him, I was
able to stay in control,'' said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was leading the race, but halfway through one stage,
Hamilton got word on his radio headset from team director Johann
Bruyneel that Armstrong was feeling ``a little subpar and I was
given the green light.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was only fair, since Hamilton aided Armstrong in his Tour
win last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Tour, Hamilton and a dozen other riders were set
back six minutes after crashing during the second stage. But
despite another crash a week later, Hamilton stayed with the
leaders and finished in 13th place. He placed fifth and third in
the time trials.
</P>
<P>
   It was his third Tour, and ``definitely opened my eyes to my
potental,'' said Hamilton, 29.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hamilton said there's no doubt whom the entire team will
work for in the Tour, which starts Saturday and finishes in Paris
July 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus this year is on Lance and on getting him to Paris in
the yellow jersey,'' said Hamilton, adding that the victory by the
American was a surprise to both participants and spectators in the
European-dominated race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were the underdogs and this year we're the
favorites,'' he said. ``I think we proved a point last year.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be three other Americans riding on the nine-man team:
Frankie Andreu, Kevin Livingston, and George Hincapie. Christian
Vande-Velde, of Boulder, Colo., was slated to ride his second Tour,
but dropped out after suffering a spider bite and possible
infection last week and has been replaced by Denmark's Steffen
Kjaergaard.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Americans will be competing, two each for Credit
Agricole and Italy's Mapei.
</P>
<P>
   Although Armstrong, 28, is the favorite, based on his win last
year and his strong spring, nothing is assured in the 23-day,
2,254-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   The 180 riders will cover seven mountain stages in the Pyrenees
and the Alps, with just one day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Armstrong, riders that bear watching include two
former winners wo missed last year's Tour: Germany's Jan Ullrich
(1997) and Italy's Marco Pantani (1998). Also keep an eye on
Switzerland's Alex Zulle, who has twice finished second, and
France's Laurent Jalabert and his teammate, Spaniard Abraham Olano,
who have both finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Then there France's Richard Virenque, who was expelled from the
Tour in 1998 for doping charges and grudgingly accepted into last
year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of drugs were still prevalent last summer. Some of the
French press dubbed Armstrong ``Superman'' and doubted that he
could ride so well after a bout with cancer without the help of
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was on the US Olympic teams in 1992 and 1996, but in
October 1996 contracted testicular cancer, which spread to his
lungs and brain.
</P>
<P>
   He resents the criticism and said at a press conference this
week that he welcomes moves to stamp out illegal drug-taking and
that cycling has been unfairly targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of this myth of widespread doping in cycling,''
Armstrong said. ``Because that's just what it is: a myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was world champion in 1993 and proved from the start of my
career that I was one of the best. So why the detractors? Why the
surprise? At some point it's just got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Cycling Union ruled last week that urine
samples from race participants would be frozen and tested for the
banned substance EPO, when a method of detection has been
perfected.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said his win last year has raised his standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've won the Tour once, you can't come back and say
honestly that you hope to finish in the top five,'' he said. ``I'm
going back to the Tour to win it, and if I don't, it will be a big
disappointment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
