<HEADER>
A0182 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MISTRESS02-COX     06-30 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MISTRESS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No easy answers in affairs of heart
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   British novelist Joanna Trollope thrives on casting a literate
light on the domestic circumstances of ordinary people. Her
characters face contemporary crises that force them to re-examine
entrenched middle-class values and hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marrying the Mistress'' focuses on the love problems of three
generations of men in the Stockdale family. Guy, a sixtysomething
judge, decides to leave Laura, his wife of 40 years, for his
mistress. Far from being a bimbo, Merrion, more than three decades
Guy's junior, is an established attorney. Their love has an
unassailable rightness and depth, their affair has lasted seven
years, and Guy's decision to break up his home late in life is
painfully, carefully reached.
</P>
<P>
   Laura manipulates son Simon into acting as her divorce attorney,
and makes demands on him that nearly destroy his marriage to
Carrie, who has always found her mother-in-law to be disapproving
and intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Simon and Carrie's teenage son, Jack, falls in love
with a willful schoolmate who dumps him. Simon's brother Alan,
happy as a clam in a gay relationship, seems to be the only
Stockdale man not to suffer the slings and arrows of outrageous
Eros.
</P>
<P>
   Trollope writes with her usual humor, mixing slang and proper
British terminology to great effect. Early on, one court official
confides to another about Merrion: ``What's gone past is not just
an advocate, any old lady advocate. What's gone past is His Honor's
babe.''
</P>
<P>
   And Trollope, once again, paints from a deft psychological
palette, carefully constructing Guy's long avoidance of his
marriage problems and Laura's maniacal manipulation, showing how
variations are passed on to son and grandson. It makes for nuanced,
riveting reading.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the book's resolution disappoints. Few would argue with
Trollope's reaffirmation of the need to get out of a bad marriage
or work on a good one. But Simon's epiphany and rededication to his
marriage is contrived, and the fate of Guy and Merrion's
relationship seems predetermined by middle-class values and
violates their carefully constructed characters.
</P>
<P>
   Trollope seems to be saying that May-December relationships will
not work, signified by Guy and Merrion's inability to envision a
life together. Such vision is rare these days, the province of
retirement ads in which gray-headed couples walk hand in hand on a
sunset-lit beach, all thanks to their good investments.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, in literature more than in life, we have to gamble on
love and the stock market. After all her careful construction, one
wishes Trollope had allowed His Honor and His Honor's babe to go
for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Marrying the Mistress. By Joanna Trollope. Viking. $23.95. 293
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A nuanced look at domestic discord.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold is an online editor for ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
