<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-TS-COX     06-30 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-TS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poets' words gain meaning when they read them aloud
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Dionisio D. Martinez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the first days of the Colonies, the United States has been
something like a mutt in search of its pedigree. Nothing
illustrates the point more clearly than our poetry. What's more
American: W.S. Merwin's ``The River of Bees'' or Langston Hughes'
``The Negro Speaks of Rivers''? We struggle for tradition,
convinced that it has something to do with time. Some countries, we
tell ourselves, have thousands of years of tradition. But, in fact,
tradition starts from zero, and what many of us miss is that we're
in the process of creating a uniquely American voice.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I was in my senior year of high school, I had
discovered a number of American poets. Having fallen in love with
their words on paper, I came across recordings of these men and
women reading their poetry. There was Archibald MacLeish, with his
very delicate voice, something like a trout stream in spring,
reading epics swelling with history, reading love poems to the wife
he loved madly until the end, helping me understand that there
could be a synthesis between form and the imagination's
recklessness. There was Robert Frost, with his shattered but
determined voice that worked on so many levels: Geographically, it
often began in New England; philosophically, it was boundless. Anne
Sexton came to me with her matter-of-fact poems, her throaty voice.
She was the Tom Waits of those days.
</P>
<P>
   Above them all was T.S. Eliot, his New England accent coated
with a pseudo-British hue. Though much of his work was over my head
at the time, I was too intrigued to turn away. His voice lingered
long after I returned those scratched albums to the library. What
we see on the page and what we hear from the poet are two very
different things. These records would irrevocably change my
approach to poetry, my view of it.
</P>
<P>
   Harper/Caedmon recently released ``T.S. Eliot Reads T.S.
Eliot,'' 2 1/2 hours of the Nobel Prize winner reading his work.
Unfortunately, it is available on cassette only. In these sessions
from 1947 and 1955, Eliot's voice is finely tuned; the cocky
attitude, the impeccable timing, the unexpected pauses are all lost
in the poor definition of a cassette.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocre sonics aside, this is T.S. Eliot, the blueprint for so
many contemporary poets. His reading of ``The Waste Land'' is a
riveting juggling act in which all the voices come in with their
idiosyncrasies. This is probably how an ancient Greek play would
sound if it were written for a single actor, someone competent
enough to handle every character and chorus.
</P>
<P>
   In a live reading of ``Macavity: The Mystery Cat,'' Eliot is
obviously playing to the amused audience but never stumbles. His
delivery of ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock'' is
heartbreaking at the very least: One hears a formal voice breaking
loose in the more mundane passages of the poem. Contrary to what
most of us were taught, Eliot is not a difficult poet detached from
the world. On the contrary, in his own way, he painted everyday
life as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   We still ask ourselves: ``And would it have been worth it, after
all, / Would it have been worth while, / After the sunsets and the
dooryards and the sprinkled streets, / After the novels, after the
teacups, after the skirts that trail along the floor _ / And this,
and so much more?'' The tapes are replete with these questions.
Maybe that's part of the attraction: We claim we want answers but
are really in search of someone who can articulate questions that
curl and cling to the throat, refusing to make themselves audible.
Ranging from ``Ash Wednesday'' to ``The Four Quartets,'' from
``Preludes'' to excerpts from two of his plays, the works on these
tapes are a capsule of contemporary Western thought _ our triumphs
and disappointments, our doubts, our certainties.
</P>
<P>
   For an overview, ``The Caedmon Poetry Collection'' was also
recently released. It compiles 3 1/2 hours of some of the greatest
recorded poetry in the English language, along with a brief piece,
in Spanish, by Pablo Neruda. The collection includes two rare
recordings of W.B. Yeats (``The Song of the Old Mother,'' ``The
Lake Isle of Innisfree''); Dylan Thomas with his dramatic,
heartbreaking voice (``A Refusal to Mourn the Death, by Fire, of a
Child in London,'' ``Fern Hill,'' ``Do Not Go Gentle Into That Good
Night''); the pure American English of William Carlos Williams
(``The Seafarer''); and the almost hypnotic reading of ``Epistle to
Be Left in the Earth'' by Archibald MacLeish.
</P>
<P>
   Irony, one of the most misused words in our language, is
applicable here. All at once, I approach the patience of middle
age, my hearing falters, and my listening skills begin to sharpen.
These are the same poems I heard in my teens, but now some of the
mysteries clear up, the ideas and images often coming quite close
to life as I see it now. I wouldn't mind being around a quarter of
a century from now, reading and hearing these poems again, looking
back and thinking of how much I missed when I was merely 44.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO
</P>
<P>
   T.S. Eliot Reads T.S. Eliot. Caedmon/HarperAudio. $22. 2 hours,
35 minutes (3 cassettes).
</P>
<P>
   The Caedmon Poetry Collection: A Century of Poets Reading Their
Work. Caedmon/HarperAudio. $29.95 CD, $20 cassette. 3 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   Dionisio D. Martinez is a poet and writer in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
