<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TWEAKS GOP; `TRUTH SQUAD' TAKES AIM AT BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON TWEAKS GOP
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in Philadelphia on Friday that
Republicans will talk a good game when they arrive for their
convention in late July but are not eager to to point out the
serious differences that divide the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have the awfullest time trying to figure out what the
differences are,'' Clinton told a group of union members. ``They're
going to love everybody and help everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a gathering of the American Federation of Federal,
State, County and Municipal Employees, Clinton recited a litany of
issues on which Democrats and Republicans diverge, from the
patients' bill of rights to the minimum wage to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also questioned Texas Gov. George W. Bush's commitment
to Hispanics, saying he had not urged Republican senators to
confirm Enrique Moreno, a Texan whom Clinton nominated as a federal
judge. ``If he had asked them to give him a hearing, they would
have done it,'' Clinton said of Bush. ``He didn't say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH SQUAD TAKES AIM AT BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The city where Gov. George W. Bush will be nominated for
president has been chosen by a ``Texas Truth Squad'' _ made up of
union members from Bush's home state _ for the beginning of a
national speaking tour intended to besmirch the governor's record.
</P>
<P>
   The squad, consisting of a teacher, a prison guard, a food
worker and a social worker, made its debut on Thursday at a union
luncheon in Philadelphia presided over by John J. Sweeney, the
president of the AFL-CIO, which has endorsed Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Squad members asserted in a series of short speeches that during
Bush's two terms as governor, Texas has consistently ranked near
the bottom in providing health insurance for children, retirement
pensions, environmental protection and pay for state workers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking special aim at Bush's claim to be an education reformer,
the group said he had diverted money from public schools and tried
to raid teacher retirement funds at a time when the state ranked
45th in the College Board test scores. The squad is scheduled to
make at least a dozen appearances around the United States before
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Daytona, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE No public events
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
