<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-GENDER-C     06-30 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-GENDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gender issues bending military readiness?
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Timothy Furnish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a Nixon could go to China. Only a Clinton could criticize
Sister Souljah. And only a Stephanie Gutman, a civilian and
(obviously) woman journalist with liberal credentials from The New
York Times and The New Republic, could write a book suggesting that
the presence of women in the U.S. military might hinder the
nation's ability to win wars.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman makes a compelling argument that for the past decade
America's civilian and military leadership has foisted upon the
military, with the notable exception of the Marines, a physical and
psychological double standard that sacrifices war-fighting
capability on the altar of a spurious gender equivalency.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman judiciously mixes empirical data with an impressive body
of anecdotal evidence drawn from her observations at Fort Jackson
in Columbia, S.C., the Great Lakes Naval Training Center near
Chicago and on board the aircraft carrier USS John C. Stennis, as
well as interviews with male and female military personnel. What
she found is best summed up by one female Army recruit: ``There was
this double-
</P>
<P>
   think with women being both excellent warriors, ready to kill
the enemy, and delicate wallflowers who had to have gender-normed
grading and different (physical training) tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are, on average, physically weaker and slower than men.
Such politically incorrect facts have been documented by civilian
scientists in studies at the Army Research Institute of
Environmental Medicine. Specifically, they have determined that a
woman has 55 percent to 60 percent the upper body strength of a
man, a greater fat-to-muscle ratio, lighter bones that break more
easily and less cardiovascular capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The military attempts to camouflage such differences with
different physical training test standards. For example, the Army
requires 17- to 21-year-old men to do 42 push-ups and run two miles
in less than 16 minutes, while women of the same age category need
perform only 18 push-ups and get three minutes longer for the run.
</P>
<P>
   The most ludicrous example of the danger of gender-norming is
the grenade test. Since the majority of female trainees could not
throw a live grenade the 35 meters required to get themselves out
of the blast radius, the Army mandated extra throwing practice for
women, right? No. The brass changed the test so women merely had to
drop the grenade into a concrete bunker.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of this issue is psychological. Male trainees
understandably bristle at the blatant double standards and
Orwellian cloud of denial that makes even broaching the issue a
career-killer. But even more harmful to the military's mission is
the inescapability of biology: Young men and women pair off
romantically, undermining unit cohesion and distracting them from
their duties. The converse of erotic involvement is ``fem fear'':
drill sergeants afraid to touch a female recruit even for
instruction, enlisted men reluctant to look at a female peer for
fear of sexual harassment charges, commanders unwilling to give
female officers mediocre evaluations lest they be accused of
lingering Neanderthalism.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the military is just lying in its own tawdry bed of
sexual recrimination, self-made at the 1991 Tailhook and 1996
Aberdeen scandals. These Navy and Army imbroglios could not have
occurred at a worse time _ amid the armed services' scrambling to
justify their post-Cold War budgets; ever-mounting pressure from
the National Organization for Women and its congressional allies to
allow women in combat; and the fawning, distorted media coverage of
``Sgt. Mom'' going off to serve in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman takes a different tack, however, attributing Tailhook
more to media propaganda and a civilian culture unable to fathom
that drunken bacchanalias are the price we pay for young men
willing to go in harm's way at supersonic speeds, and ascribing
Aberdeen to the Army's total prostration before the extreme
feminist shibboleth that ``all sex is rape.'' Her apologetics are
unconvincing here, however. Natural though it may be for warriors
to indulge their testosterone around women, lasciviousness in the
defense of America is still vice.
</P>
<P>
   That questionable interlude aside, there is little to criticize
Gutman for, other than erroneously calling the Pentagon the
``Puzzle Palace'' (that's actually National Security Agency
headquarters at Fort Meade, Md.) and an irritating fixation on male
soldiers' physiques as ``hunky'' and ``Chippendalelike.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutman's book is a crucial contribution to the debate about our
21st-century military. Particularly insightful are her proposed
solutions to gender-based problems: among them, emulating the
Marines' gender-segregated basic training; standardizing physical
training requirements; implementing job-specific strength tests;
and eliminating gender quotas in recruiting. She admits these
suggestions would reduce the number of women in the military from
its current 15 percent, but asserts that's the price to pay for
women strong enough to do their jobs. Let the debate begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Kinder, Gentler Military: Can America's Gender-Neutral
Fighting Force Still Win Wars? By Stephanie
</P>
<P>
   Gutman. Scribner. $25. 300 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A crucial contribution to an ongoing debate.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Furnish of Alpharetta, Ga., is a doctoral candidate in
history, a former member of the 101st Airborne Division and an
officer in the Army Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
