NYT-06-30-00 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0188 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-BRYSON-C     06-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEW-BRYSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOK-REVIEW-BRYSON
 &HT;    Bryson's hearty g'day from Down Under
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one would mistake Bill Bryson for the Crocodile Hunter. On
TV, the khaki-shorted Steve Irwin pokes at man-eating reptiles and
crawls under houses looking for deadly snakes. In his latest
travelogue, the tweedy, bearded Bryson visits a secondhand
bookstore and picks up a volume about crocodile attacks and tells
us the horrifying tale of an American model who was standing under
a waterfall in western Australia when she noticed a half-submerged
snout swimming toward her. She was last seen being dragged beneath
the surface, a startled look on her face.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson tells this story as he sits in a comfortable pub with a
book and a cold one. If he personally saw a live crocodile during
his Australian travels, he doesn't mention it.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the thing: It doesn't matter. Bryson is such a good
storyteller _ scary and funny in all the right places _ that you
don't much care if he never left his bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson has become an enormously popular travel writer by coming
off as the most literate, humorous tour guide you never had. He
weaves research and chance encounter into an entertaining narrative
sprinkled with self-deprecation. The formula worked nicely in his
previous books about England (``Notes From a Small Island'') and
the Appalachian Trail (``A Walk in the Woods'').
</P>
<P>
   Australia, one of the most eccentric places on Earth, seems
tailor-made for his drollery. It's distant, exotic, barren for
great stretches, yet it feels familiar to someone who grew up in
the States and lived in Britain for 20 years, as Bryson did. He
always imagined Australia as an amiable mingling of the two
cultures _ ``Baywatch'' with cricket, as he puts it. He found it
was much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   With the Olympics approaching in Sydney, this is a highly
exceptional year for Australia. Usually, Bryson notes, the world's
interest in the land down under doesn't go much past Nicole Kidman
and Mel Gibson. He checked The New York Times index for 1997 and
found only 20 articles predominantly about Australia. The globe's
sixth-largest nation ranked ahead of bananas but behind ice cream
in importance.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, it seems, simply doesn't draw attention to itself. It
doesn't start wars, overfish international waters, grow large
amounts of illegal narcotics. It truly is a ``no worries'' kind of
place.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson sets out to redress this attention deficit by taking us
along on three trips to the country. He rides an Indian Pacific
train across the Outback. Gets lost walking around a Sydney suburb.
Descends into the Great Barrier Reef in a semisubmersible. Visits a
combination pet supply/pornography shop outside Canberra. Braves a
really bad hotel in Darwin, which is worth mentioning only because
it occasions one of those comeback lines you wish you could snap
off on command. The desk clerk, who doesn't seem to have heard a
word of Bryson's complaints, blithely tells him to come again as he
checks out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would sooner have bowel surgery in the woods with a stick,''
the author replies.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson is particularly fascinated by Australia's menagerie of
dangerous animals. The island continent and its surrounding waters
contain the world's deadliest snakes, most venomous insects, most
toxic and tooth sea creatures. Like a camp counselor spinning ghost
stories around the fire, Bryson delights in confronting us with
most of them _ from great white sharks to funnel-web spiders _
often as he regards their stuffed specimens in a climate-controlled
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Take the box jellyfish, whose tentacles pack so much toxin that
people who have been stung keep screaming in agony after they've
been given morphine. Bryson saw one in a large glass cylinder at
the Northern Territory Museum, next to displays of stingrays,
scorpion fish and 30 types of sea snakes, all found in nearby
coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonder to me that anyone goes within a hundred feet of
the sea in northern Australia,'' writes Bryson, who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking about all that poison is enough to make you order
another round.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sunburned Country. By Bill Bryson. Broadway Books. $25. 307
pages. (Audio: Bantam Doubleday Dell. $49.95 CD, $39.95 cassette.
12 hours, unabridged. Read by the author.)
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Put another country on the barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0191 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE02-COX     06-30 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An enigmatic survivor amid reality's illusions
 &HT;      What I Think I Did: A Season in Survival
 &HT;    in Two Acts. By Larry Woiwode. Basic Books. $25.
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voice at the other end was firm yet guarded.
</P>
<P>
   I introduced myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes?'' Larry Woiwode said.
</P>
<P>
   A distance of 1,000 miles is not always bridged in a single
telephone call, and Woiwode is not an expansive man. He is among
the least well-known of America's major writers, his talent worthy
of comparison to anyone of his generation. But it is not a name
immediately recognizable. He came to prominence early on, with
poems and stories in The New Yorker under the slightly mysterious
byline ``L. Woiwode,'' then with his first novel, ``What I'm Going
to Do, I Think,'' in 1969. It was not only widely praised, here and
abroad, but was even a best seller, an intensely lyrical story of a
couple in the first years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his next novel, ``Beyond the Bedroom Wall,''
published in 1975, that seemed to establish Woiwode (pronounced
WHY-woody) as a writer of uncommon gifts. A finalist for the
National Book Award and the National Book Critics Circle Award,
``Beyond the Bedroom Wall'' was the evolving story of a prairie
family and of a mother's death. From its incantatory opening
paragraph through the mature years of those who would survive her,
``Beyond the Bedroom Wall'' was told not in sequential narrative
but in a series of stopped moments, as in a family album. Critics
not given to overstatement called it one of the great American
novels of the second half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   And then something happened. More novels and story collections
followed _ ``Poppa John,'' ``Born Brothers,'' ``Silent Passengers''
_ but the reviews were mixed and sometimes worse. With his wife and
children, Woiwode had moved from New York back to his native North
Dakota. He had also become unapologetically religious, and serious
writers _ serious artists of any kind _ become suspect once they
admit to religious belief. In Woiwode's case, autobiographical
parallels had always been evident in his fiction and in time they
became darker. ``I wonder how the parallels in my own life inform
the fiction,'' he once told Publishers Weekly. ``I only construct a
fiction in a way that I feel will work _ and the devil take the
hindmost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I Think I Did'' is neither autobiography nor fiction, but
rather a memoir in the form of meditation, with past and present
changing into one another like the colors of a chameleon. One act
describes Woiwode and his family trapped in a blizzard during the
winter of 1996-97, the other his life as a young man in New York
when he hung around with an aspiring teenage actor named Robert De
Niro and caught the eye of William Maxwell, a revered editor at The
New Yorker. The one is often hypnotic in its imagery (``... a wind
hits and streaks of snow revolve to the horizontal and double in
volume, a white-out''), the other a recollection of another life
and another world entirely. Of De Niro he writes: ``When he's
unhappy his parents come up, and he turns on himself, somberly
angry, as if the responsibility he takes for keeping in touch with
them, in order to keep in touch, identifies him as their cause for
being apart. An only child's trial.''
</P>
<P>
   But between these two acts, both told in the present tense, is
an Intermission that might as easily be called a credo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time,'' Woiwode writes, ``is the lesser compatriot to language
and so time, whom most of us revere, bows to language. It is
helpless before language. Language is greater, omniscient. With
language people arrange adornments that endure, while time merely
passes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Woiwode is speaking here of his response to reading Joseph
Brodsky, who had read W.H. Auden's ``In Memory of W.B. Yeats.''
Reading Brodsky, he came to a realization both aesthetic and
religious. But the formulation of the idea seemed to me to have got
things backward, and so I called him at his farm in North Dakota.
If people arrange adornments through language, doesn't that in
itself imply an order of priority? If they are only that _
adornments _ wouldn't that which they adorn be the truer, more
enduring reality?
</P>
<P>
   His voice has a gravelly edge, and his manner of speaking
conveys a resistance to changing his mind easily _ changing it, at
least, whenever some stranger from Atlanta calls. ``What we call
real does not endure,'' he says. ``Trees die and flowers wither.''
Language alone, he goes on, survives our own mortality and enables
us to construct versions of what we call reality. The words of the
psychologist Erik Erikson, used a quarter-century ago as an
epigraph in ``Beyond the Bedroom Wall,'' suddenly are crystallized:
```Reality,' of course, is man's most powerful illusion; but while
he attends to this world, it must outbalance the total enigma of
being in it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Woiwode himself is an enigmatic writer, enormously gifted and
yet trapped, it sometimes seems, within private furies. He writes
of North Dakota farmers tying ropes around their waists when they
check on their livestock in a storm, tethering themselves to
something solid so they can find their way back. Even then, some
have not. The burden of Woiwode's work is testimony to his will to
survive storms of another kind, and evidence of a resoluteness more
impressive even than the gifts that brought him a passing world's
fickle attention.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
