<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REID-LEGACY02-COX     06-30 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REID-LEGACY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's urban music industry in full swing
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid's departure _ and the subsequent
downsizing of 11-year-old LaFace _ is unquestionably the biggest
blow Atlanta's music scene has been dealt. His was the most
successful imprint based in this city. And it was Reid and LaFace
that attracted other labels, other performers, producers and
executives here.
</P>
<P>
   And primarily because of that, he leaves behind a local urban
music industry that is well on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Grammy-winning producer Dallas Austin is strongly established in
his '50s-like drugstore/playground/studio off Northside Drive,
where he's been working with artists like Michael Jackson and
Madonna and his own personal projects, TLC and Monica, about as
long as LaFace has been around.
</P>
<P>
   Off Piedmont Road, in the industrial gray and black office of So
So Def Records, Jermaine Dupri is running a 7-year-old,
multimillion-dollar-selling label that just put out its first
soundtrack (``Big Momma's House''). He's also planning a follow-up
to his platinum rap debut, and he continues to watch artists _ for
whom he writes and creates music (Da Brat, Jagged Edge) _ climb the
charts.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three members of TLC continue to call Atlanta home,
as do Usher, Monica, Kelly Price, Montell Jordan, Outkast, Blaque
and Ideal. Grammy-winning songwriters Kandi Burruss and Tameka
``Tiny'' Cottle and the hitmaking collectives at Noontime (who have
produced songs for Toni Braxton and Jim Crow) and Organized Noize
(TLC, En Vogue) are here, too.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those waiting in the wings. Here are five
Atlantans to watch:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Johnte Austin, 19, Stockbridge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   By age 17, Austin had already written his first hit record and
gotten a royalty check so big he bought his family a house.
</P>
<P>
   The song, R&AMP;B ballad ``Sweet Lady,'' established dancer, MTV
host and Guess model Tyrese as a singer and won an American Music
Award and a Grammy nomination for male R&AMP;B vocal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnte and those guys basically gave me the song that will
probably, proudly, be my signature,'' says Tyrese.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the ingratiatingly bashful Atlanta-born teen put off
being a singer, temporarily, and went full blast with his pen.
Austin has since helped write Top 10 Billboard hits for Aaliyah
(``I Don't Wanna'') and Ideal (``Get Gone''), and the new release
from Toni Braxton (``Just Be a Man About It'').
</P>
<P>
   ``After doing talent shows since I was 12, trying to be a
singer, I kind of didn't know this is the direction I would take,''
he says. ``I'm blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shakir Stewart, 25, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   This 1995 graduate of Morehouse College claims he really didn't
start his education until a year after school. That's when Reid
asked the Oakland, Calif., native to work for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only has he been teaching me the aesthetics of a hit
song,'' says the energetic Stewart, who can appear as if he's
speeding even as he sits at his desk, ``but more importantly, he's
taught me about being a black man in this world, not just in this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the recently promoted vice president and general
manager of Reid's publishing arm, Hitco, the former party thrower
is in charge of a multimillion-dollar company whose
writers/producers include She'kspere (on Sinead O'Connor's new CD)
and Beyonce of R&AMP;B quartet Destiny's Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I'm the hook-up man,'' he explains. ``I do whatever
I need to do to enhance the correct exposure for my client. But I'm
also part Les Brown, motivational speaker. I energize my clients to
do their best work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Joi, 29, East Point, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Joi is already a star, she just hasn't found her place in the
constellations yet. Vocally, her sensual electricity roars up there
with such '70s soul sirens as LaBelle. Few in the Nashville
native's peer group of mostly video-only performers can ignite a
crowd the way she does. All Joi's needed since her longtime
friend/producer Dallas Austin's label folded three years ago was a
record deal. And as of February, that's taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think this will finally work this time,'' says Joi,
who has been with two record labels _ both of which closed _ since
her 1994 debut (``The Pendulum Vibe''). ``Now I'm with a
well-oiled, large machine (Universal Records/Crazy World). I have
more control over things, and I've learned all the proper lessons
so this can be the thang it needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, she started working on an album due in January
2001. ``I would be done if I wasn't preparing for this wedding (to
Big Gipp of Atlanta rap act Goodie Mob) and getting the kitchen
remodeled.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ian Burke, 34, Grant Park, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Burke is the human line that links many of this city's biggest
acts. He put TLC together when they were Second Nature, but passed
them along to more connected management before they became best
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   He was the manager of the hip-hop act Arrested Development.
``But I was green, and I knew I couldn't take them to the next
level,'' he says. The next level turned out to be a Grammy-winning
debut.
</P>
<P>
   He had rappers Outkast as well. But he left to work with the
group's producers. Outkast went on to get a Grammy nod.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly this Mount Vernon, N.Y., native has a knack for spotting
music talent. Now he's hoping to be around when millions of others
notice it as well. Burke runs his own Greenhouse Management Co.
(rock band Edith's Wish, rapper Sole) and the new production
company/label Wish Recordings, with TLC's Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, I feel, will be the moment I finally see an act from the
early stages to the big success. Seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kawan ``KP'' Prather, 27, Jonesboro, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by his usual three or four hours of sleep, Prather is
doing five or six jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He is vice president of A&AMP;R at LaFace Records. ``I pick the
producers and songs for our artists,'' most recently Usher and his
4 million-selling CD ``My Way'' and Pink's gold debut, ``Can't Take
Me Home.'' He also helps ``find the direction of the album.
Something that makes everyone happy. Easy, huh?'' he smirks.
</P>
<P>
   He is also CEO of LaFace's subsidiary label, Ghet-o-vision,
which signed Atlanta rap duo the Youngbloodz (``U-Way'') and just
co-released the ``Shaft 2000'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta native leaves his Buckhead office, it could be
to record something as a member of rap trio P.A.; or he could be
out of the sound booth and behind the board as producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you forgot the other two things I am,'' he adds
enthusiastically. ``I'm a father and husband. And with all I do, my
(3-year-old) son really knows me. That's what I'm really proud
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
