<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REID-TIMELINE02-COX     06-30 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REID-TIMELINE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAFACE TIME LINE
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  October 1989. With a five-year, $20 million joint venture deal
with Arista Records in hand, Reid and Edmonds leave Los Angeles and
launch LaFace Records (a combination of their nicknames). It
actually started in Reid's former Country Club of the South home
(which LaFace singer Usher now owns) but soon moved to a Norcross,
Ga., office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1991. TLC is formed when Reid's then-wife, R&AMP;B singer Pebbles
(``Mercedes Boy''), puts her back-up dancer, Rozonda ``Chilli''
Thomas, together with Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins and Lisa
``Left-Eye'' Lopes, then in a trio called Second Nature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1993. Reid and Edmonds unveil the husky singer they've
deemed the First Lady of LaFace, Toni Braxton. Her self-titled
debut album sells more than 7 million copies and earns her best new
artist and best R&AMP;B artist/female Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  September 1993. Edmonds finally confirms that the rumors are
true, he and Reid would split as a production entity. Neither has
really said why, until now:
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of reasons,'' Reid says. ``No. 1 was, I think
I used to (upset him) because I would sit in the studio and be on
the telephone. (Husky laugh). No. 2: I started to have a true love
of the business and working with other artists. No. 3: In some
respects, Kenny might have felt like Kenny needed to grow as a
writer and producer and he needed to do it by himself... And I
supported that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 30, 1994. After catching Reid's younger brother Bryant's
attention at an Atlanta talent search, 15-year-old R&AMP;B singer Usher
Raymond releases his self-titled debut on the label. Producer Sean
``Puffy'' Combs guides the artist and album.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 1994. TLC's ``CrazySexyCool'' is released and goes on
to sell more than 13 million copies, making TLC the best-selling
female group in the country. Reid and Edmonds are profiled in Black
Enterprise as two of the 50 top black entertainment power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 7, 1995. LaFace announces that it has renewed its
agreement with Arista Records and parent company BMG, at an
estimated value of $100 million over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 23, 1997. LaFace releases the ``Soul Food'' soundtrack,
followed a week later by the movie. Executive producer Edmonds'
$7.5 million baby earns $11.4 million its first weekend in
theaters, making it No. 2 in box office totals to George Clooney's
``The Peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 1999. The Recording Industry Association of America
names ``CrazySexyCool'' the best-selling hip-hop album of the 20th
century (odd, since the songs aren't really rap).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Late November 1999. The Los Angeles Times suggests that
founding Arista Records President Clive Davis _ who's responsible
for signing Whitney Houston and helping to revive the career of
Santana _ will be replaced by Reid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 10, 2000: Backstage at Arista Records' 25th anniversary
party, Davis tells The New York Times that he'll step down when his
contract expires June 30.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 3, 2000: Reid is named Davis' successor as president of
Arista Records. That same day, BMG announces that Edmonds has a new
joint venture with Arista to form his own label.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal- Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
