<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REID02-COX     06-30 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REID02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The man who built Atlanta's urban music scene opens up about his
move to New York
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's only after talking for hours, first in his black Mercedes
and then in his Dunwoody home, that Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid starts to
worry, just a little, about what he's said.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in loose linen rather than his standard tailored
business suit, he seems more relaxed than usual, a man comfortable
with his success and in control of his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really feeling like a change,'' Reid offers.
</P>
<P>
   He's even volunteered to lay out on the floor for photographs.
But his slight self-consciousness _ was he too relaxed, too chatty?
_ hints at just how odd and new all this attention feels to him.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Reid never talks this much. In part, because people only
recently began asking him to.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly because the 44-year-old has spent most of his career
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know how strange this is for me to be the
focus,'' he says in a voice as calming as the soft jazz coming from
the stereo. ``I'm used to helping stars. Not being treated like
one.''
</P>
<P>
   This week he takes the helm as president of Arista Records, one
of the largest pop labels in the country. And the move into the
spotlight, which follows a tumultuous power struggle between Arista
founder Clive Davis and parent company BMG, seems a natural
progression.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, Reid created LaFace Records with partner
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds and built it into a major R&AMP;B and rap
label. For nearly a decade, LaFace _ and a handful of other
Atlanta-based labels and producers _ have dominated the popular
music charts with such R&AMP;B artists as TLC and Toni Braxton and rap
groups Outkast and Goodie Mob.
</P>
<P>
   LaFace was a partner with Arista from the beginning. And with
Reid running the day-to-day operation, LaFace became a very
lucrative property for parent company BMG. In the last fiscal year,
Arista made about $500 million (10 percent of which came from
LaFace revenue). With his new job comes a higher public profile.
For Reid it will be an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'80s the Cincinnati native made his professional
debut with the R&AMP;B group the Deele as the drummer. He was visible,
but barely, sitting way in the back of the group's ``Two
Occasions'' video, in oversize shades, his Jheri-curled head often
bowed over his kit.
</P>
<P>
   In career No. 2, Reid was part of the multi-Grammy-winning team
that produced more than 25 No. 1 pop and R&AMP;B singles from the
mid-'80s until it split in 1993. (Still, noted cultural critic
Nelson George remembers people referring to Reid as ``the other
guy.'' As in: ``Who set the all-time record for consecutive No. 1
singles on the R&AMP;B chart with `Baby, Baby, Baby' by TLC; `End of
the Road' by Boyz II Men; and `Humpin' Around' by Bobby Brown?
Babyface and the other guy.'')
</P>
<P>
   And as co-president of LaFace Records, he was the rare executive
in urban contemporary music who didn't show up in his artists'
videos. You could have missed that Reid helped develop TLC, the
best-selling female group in the country. Or that he signed Usher,
the closest thing R&AMP;B has had to a teen pop idol since Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   His talent has been finding talent and creating crossover stars.
Now, he's charged with bringing a contemporary edge to Arista,
which has long relied on pop stars such as Whitney Houston, Aretha
Franklin and Annie Lennox.
</P>
<P>
   Reid insists he's not leaving LaFace or Atlanta behind. He has
not named a new president; he says he will continue to direct the
label. He's keeping his house here, too _ he'll spend weekdays in
New York, weekends in Atlanta with his three children. His new
wife, though, 30-year-old Erica Holton, will probably leave her
substitute-teaching days behind.
</P>
<P>
   But still, he worries. As the first black man in recent memory
to run a major, all-genres record label, he's about to take center
stage. His words will carry more weight. So he wonders, did he get
too relaxed, too chatty, in his first substantive interview since
being named?
</P>
<P>
   You decide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
