r l BC-SCRAMBLED-DOGS02-COX     06-30 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCRAMBLED-DOGS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An officer, a gentleman, and a scrambled dog ...
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock and Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ga. _ It's Saturday at Dinglewood Pharmacy. And it
seems like everybody in Columbus _ even folks in Jaguars from
Alabama _ has scrambled dogs on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Like its maker _ 68-year-old Lieutenant Charles Stevens, this
Army town's favorite grill sergeant and soda jerk_ the scrambled
dog is a local institution. It's the Holy Grail of hot-dog lore,
the Rolls Royce of the weiner world and a much-ballyhooed hangover
cure.
</P>
<P>
   But frankly, when all is said and done, it's just a souped-up
weenie on a bun.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the bad boy so fine is the way Lieutenant _ his given
name and what everyone calls him _ dresses it down and gives it its
marching orders. After deftly chopping the beef-pork-and-red-dye
hot dog into fat pink links, he ladles on more than a cupful of his
secret-recipe chili (``often imitated, never duplicated,'' the menu
says). He then tops it with sliced dill pickles, chunks of American
cheese, onions if you like, and the signature fistful of oyster
crackers. Some people squiggle it with mustard and ketchup.
Everybody eats it with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing it's in a drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   The concoction, says Dinglewood owner Terry Hurley, was created
by then-cook Sport Brown, using a chili recipe devised by a
pharmacist's wife in about 1930. When Brown got sick in the early
'50s, Lieutenant moved up in rank from nighttime cook to daytime
commander. Now his little-changed formula (he omitted the salt) has
survived Dinglewood's four owners and three locations. Lieutenant's
caricature graces mugs, T-shirts and greeting cards. He has a
resume, a business card and a photo of him with the late ``Good
Times'' actress Esther Rolle, who stopped by one day.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken man who's neither bark nor bite, Lieutenant works
``practically every day'' for a crowd that just can't get enough of
the doggone things. Most weekdays, the throwback fountain goes
through 20 gallons of chili. Saturdays, though, can require 60
gallons to top 500 dogs and fill to-go orders, especially for
families heading to Florida. ``They freeze it and take it with them
so they can have the same hot dogs while they're there,''
Lieutenant says.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. George Busbee used to send a Highway Patrol car by
to pick up a gallon. Lieutenant also has catered to Prince Charles
at the governor's mansion and to President Carter at Washington
brunches.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as if Lieutenant's scrambled dogs might
fade as his health declined. But now he's feeling better and thanks
President Clinton for allowing ``retired'' workers to earn more
while they accept Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sit down, you go down,'' he figures.
</P>
<P>
   And though his doctor doesn't recommend it, Lieutenant eats one
scrambled dog a week. He just takes his medication first.
</P>
<P>
   Dinglewood Pharmacy is at 1939 Wynnton Road, Columbus.
706-322-0616. Closed Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
