<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DRAGONCON01-COX     06-30 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGONCON01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sci-fi fans find others of their world
 &HT;    By Kirk Kicklighter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The downtown Hyatt Regency was awash in a sea of black T-shirts
and Klingon garb Thursday morning as ``Star Trek'' fans waded
through the lobby. In the corner atrium bar a Xena princess
look-alike shared a gin and tonic with a vampire. And everywhere
phasers and light sabers were holstered in a peaceful celebration
of the joys of sciencee screening of a recent documentary film,
``Trekkies,'' that pokes fun at the ``Star Trek'' faithful. The
film depicts the extremes of Trekkie devotion, from people who
enroll in summer camps to learn the Klingon language to a
middle-aged man who dresses in Star Ship Enterprise garb for weekly
trips to the supermarket. At one point in the film, Brent Spiner,
the actor who played the android Data on ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation,'' observes: ``I don't think I've ever met anyone, `Star
Trek' fan or not, who wasn't peculiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, perhaps, the audience cheered. ``Who has seen
someone very close to themselves in the movie so far?'' asked Eric
Watts as he led a group discussion of the film. A few hands were
raised. ``We know that people are apt to make fun of us, and that's
part of what the movie is about,'' said Doug Cassell, 30, of
Spartanburg, S.C. ``We're not stupid. What's stupid is watching
baseball night after night on TBS.'' The ``Star Trek'' shows always
communicated the universal truth that it doesn't take an alien land
to make one feel like an alien. Trekkies and their science-fiction
brethren at DragonCon have long known they don't quite fit in at
the office or at home, but they feel at home with one another
through ``Star Trek.'' In the end, say the Trekkies, their fandom
is more about community than about weirdness. As Trekkies
themselves are quick to point out, most people are drawn to
something that just grabs them. Is a panel discussion dissecting
the minutiae of ``Star Trek Voyager'' any more bizarre than an
academic symposium on asceticism in early 19th-century New England?
</P>
<P>
   Watts, 38, a crew-cut graphic designer from Marietta, has been a
``Star Trek'' fan since 1977 and has helped organize the ``Star
Trek'' programming for DragonCon since 1993. This year's convention
offers 25 ``Trek''-oriented events, including a panel discussion on
writing ``Star Trek'' episodes and serialized novels, a Miss
Klingon Empire Beauty Pageant and a conversation with actor Walter
Koenig, who played Pavel Chekov in the original series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year we were here at DragonCon we had a seminar
called `Get a Life _ the Deranged Trekkie,'''said Watts. ``The
truth is, 98 percent of all sci-fi fandom is relatively normal.
It's the other 2 percent that gets all the press attention.''
</P>
<P>
   For Watts, ``Star Trek'' does what all good art as entertainment
does: shed light on real life. ``The original `Trek' always had a
moral in each episode and actually made commentary on social
issues,'' said Watts. ``Like the famous early episode where Frank
Gorshin played an alien who was half black and half white ... that
was `Star Trek' tackling race, and in the '60s no less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek,'' despite decades of change, still teaches that
there really is a right way to do things, that humans and aliens
have to communicate to understand each other, and that honor and
bravery still count for something in a cruel, impersonal galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this might sound strange, but `Star Trek' helped me
learn how to calm myself down when I'm really upset,'' said Mirrani
Houpe, 22, a preschool teacher from Chapel Hill, N.C. ``Because in
the episodes, you learn that losing your cool only leads to
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Houpe left Chapel Hill at 3 a.m. on Tuesday to reach Atlanta in
time for the DragonCon volunteer orientation. Like many younger
Trekkies, she has been a fan all her life, taking over the Trekkie
mantle from her parents. ``When I was an infant, they would put me
in front of `Star Trek' on TV to keep me from crying,'' she said.
``I started taping episodes when I was in first grade.'' But being
a Trekkie hasn't always been a smooth ride for Houpe. ``I had a
really hard time in school. I wore (`Star Trek') T-shirts and had
my notebooks decorated with all this stuff,'' she said. ``And, of
course, kids made fun of me. But it was part of me. Now my
co-workers are like `Why?,' and I say, `Look, you go home and you
take care of your kids or whatever you do, and I'll do my ``Star
Trek'' thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Houpe said being among Trekkies is like being in a parallel
world where everyone can exchange their everyday masks for a
Trekkie cloak. ``These people don't try to be cool. They're not
interested in being cool ... or respected,'' she said. ``They're
interested in being with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   DragonCon runs through Sunday in the Hyatt Regency at Peachtree
Center. Tickets are available from Ticketmaster, 404-249-6400, or
www.ticketmaster.com. Or go to www.dragoncon.org.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Kicklighter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
