<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-WHITEHOUSE02-COX     06-30 2060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whitehouse gets new `do' for 200th birthday
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mary Trevor steps through the spiked iron gate into
Pennsylvania Avenue and the noontime sauna of a D.C. summer. She
has just toured the White House, and the president's place met with
her approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too formal, and yet ... dignified,'' says the
Clevelander, accompanied by a son-in-law and two grandchildren.
``I've seen many of the palaces of Europe, but this was something
really different. Very American.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the White House _ celebrating its bicentennial with
special lectures, exhibitions and festivities _ is even more
American in its style of operation than its decor. Because ``it
belongs to you, the people'' (as President Clinton says in a
documentary film at the White House Visitor Center, a separate
building a couple of blocks away), the house is more open to public
view than any national leader's residence in the world. Tours are
free.
</P>
<P>
   Never to return, of course, is the down-home hospitality of
Andrew Jackson _ who in 1837 placed a 1,400-pound cheese in the
grand foyer for all Washingtonians, dooming several carpets _ but
you can still get an intimate sense of the people who lived here.
Gazing at their portraits, strolling through immaculate rooms that
seem to have arrived by time machine a minute earlier, scanning the
18-acre grounds that soothe the city's center like a cool cloth on
a fevered forehead, you take a little voyage into the past.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps even get a clearer focus on what America is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House is the nation's common homestead; we're all
drawn there,'' says William Seale, the house's official historian.
``It has constantly changed, and yet Lincoln would have no trouble
finding his way around. Even for George Washington (who approved
the building's plans but never got to live there), the house would
be the one thing in the city he'd recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every American recognizes the image, too, and yet the
house itself surprises you. It's beautiful in a way different from
what you'd expect: not the gleaming snow-white temple of power seen
in photographs but a real house for real people, with a creamier
color, softer glow. Looking between the brooding elms, ashes and
beeches on the front grounds, you see the time-roughened texture of
the sandstone walls and realize that this place is old. Fragile,
even.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ready for its 1.25 million annual visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house,'' Seale says, ``is probably in its spiffiest
condition ever, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   'Twas not always so. The White House has had its spells of chaos
as well as splendor.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed, on the model of English country houses, by the
Irish-born James Hoban, who spent his early career in Charleston,
S.C. His design beat the proposal by an anonymous architect
believed to be Thomas Jefferson. The house that Washington
approved, of which John Adams became the first occupant on Nov. 1,
1800, was only a fifth as large as what Hoban originally designed,
but would remain the nation's largest residence until after the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The house was gutted by a fire set by British troops in 1814;
only a miraculously timed rainstorm saved the stone shell. James
Monroe's rebuilt interior was stately. But the house's style varied
widely with the tastes of presidents and first ladies. Says Seale,
``Some of them were not interested in a showplace. In the pictures
you see rocking chairs, straw mats _ downright tatty.''
</P>
<P>
   When Union troops clogged the city, Lincoln let some flop on the
East Room floor. Grant and Hayes slathered the place with heavy
ornamentation derided as ``Steamboat Gothic.'' Chester A. Arthur
set Louis Tiffany loose in the house, but few of the designer's
contributions remain.
</P>
<P>
   It was Theodore Roosevelt in 1902 who made the most additions
(including the West Wing, with its Oval Office and executive work
rooms, not on the tours) and the most sweeping renovations to date.
He set the simple but elegant tone that remains today. ``T.R.'' _
who added the lamp that hangs beneath the north portico like a
magnificent pendant at a queen's throat _ is vividly captured in
the John Singer Sargent portrait in the East Room.
</P>
<P>
   The house was gutted again in 1948 _ on purpose. Truman moved
his family out for four years to restore the badly aging interior
and reinforce the walls with steel because, in Seale's words,
``Harry was very conscious of The Bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason that the style and upkeep kept fluctuating is that
the house's budget ``is inadequate for its needs and has always
been a political football,'' says Neil W. Horstman of the White
House Historical Association (a private nonprofit educational group
nurtured by Jacqueline Kennedy at its founding in 1961).
</P>
<P>
   From Monroe's French furniture to Nancy Reagan's china, White
House expenditures attract bitter jibes from Congress and the
press. So Mrs. Reagan established an endowment fund, a nonprofit
subsidiary of the association, which now stands at $30 million. In
recent years, the sumptuous refurbishment of the Blue Room in
Monroe's original choice of Empire style, and a new dining table
for the State Dining Room, were paid for by the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest changes in life at the White House involve security.
How could the cheese-doling Jackson in 1837 have foreseen some nut
flying his plane into the South Lawn? Visitors on the tour must
laboriously pass through metal detectors, though tour rooms are
remarkably free of visible security agents. (The great majority of
the 3,000 people who work in the White House daily are involved in
security, many stationed in underground rooms.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, tours are set up so that you can't hope for even
a distant glimpse of the president and his family. It's a far cry
from 1889, when Caroline (Mrs. Benjamin) Harrison complained of
``the circus atmosphere'': visitors wandering uninvited into the
family quarters (which occupy the top two floors) to gawk. Though
these private quarters and related rooms (including a bowling
alley, putting green, dentist's office and beauty parlor) are off
limits to tours, Seale says you're not missing much: ``Imagine a
high-end but fairly typical 1920s hotel,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Tour guides, then, try to provide some sense of the living
executive presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president came down just a few minutes ago, for meetings
in the West Wing,'' says the amiable Secret Service guide leading a
recent early-morning tour. ``He'll receive Mr. Arafat at noon in
the East Room, so that room won't be included on the tour today.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the grim business of presidential safety is more
evident. In 1995 the Secret Service closed Pennsylvania Avenue on
the north and E Street on the south to traffic for a block on
either side of the White House. Though pedestrians can still walk
right up to the spiked iron fence (kids love to hang on it) to
shoot pictures, the area has become depressingly ugly. Police
barriers of concrete and orange plastic make it look like a war
zone. There is a plan to transform these blockaded areas into
beautiful pedestrian malls, but it's stalled in political wrangling
and is not expected to get moving until a new adminstration takes
power next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dose of reality when you come out of that beautiful
house,'' says Kevin Trimble of Stockton, Calif. ``A sad commentary
on our world today.''
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, as a motorcade was assembling on the closed
section of Pennsylvania, Secret Service agents could be seen in the
open back of a van, wearing riot gear and holding M-16 rifles.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, at other oments, the White House's essential
timelessness shines through.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in the late twilight of summer, with the
pedestrian traffic winding down and the chandeliers twinkling
softly through the tall windows, one imagines the life inside, down
through the years. T.R. chasing his kids through the hallways.
John-John peeking from beneath JFK's desk. Nixon, and later
Clinton, tensely hunkered, waiting for news of possible
impeachment. ...
</P>
<P>
   And over there, on the northwest corner of the lawn, is an odd
sight: a collection of tall, bent, canvas-covered objects. They're
the lighting scaffolds for the TV correspondents who pose in front
of the White House, covered against a misting rain.
</P>
<P>
   And there, hopping to and fro among the steel stanchions _
oblivious of who's in, or out, of the big old house _ are
squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Touring the White House
</P>
<P>
   The tours are free, but you pay with your feet in long lines. In
peak season _ now until Sept. 2 _ you must first go to the White
House Visitor Center, 1450 Pennsylvania Ave., for free same-day
tickets on a first-come basis. The line may form as early as 6 a.m.
It isn't terribly long when the office opens at 7:30, but by 9 a.m.
all of that day's 3,000 to 5,000 tickets are usually gone. If you
can plan eight to 10 weeks in advance, contact the office of your
U.S. representative or senator to request one of 1,000 free advance
tickets distributed for each day's Congressional Guided Tours.
These begin 8:15 to 8:45 a.m. Visitor Office: 202-456-7041; www
</P>
<P>
   .whitehouse.gov. For self-guided tours in nonpeak season
(Saturday before Labor Day until third Tuesday in March), you
should line up no later than 9 a.m. at the Visitors' Entrance on
East Executive Avenue, Tuesdays through Saturdays. Gate opens at
10, closes at noon; tour takes 30-40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Visitor Center
</P>
<P>
   This exhibit hall, handsomely housed in a corner of the Commerce
Building at 1450 Pennsylvania Ave., is the next best thing to a
visit to the house itself. Included with the lively exhibits is a
30-minute film that includes rare footage of President Truman
playing the piano; Jacqueline Kennedy leading a tour; FDR with
Fala, his Scottish terrier. 202-208-1631; www.nps.gov/whho/whvc.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Historical Association
</P>
<P>
   Ensconced in an elegant town house on Jackson Place northwest of
the White House, facing Lafayette Square, the association helps in
the preservation of the house and educating the public about its
history. In the gift shop are guidebooks, ``The White House: A
Historic Guide,'' and ``The Living White House,'' published by the
association and the National Geographic Society, beautiful steals
at $5. 202-737-8292; www.whitehousehistory.org.
</P>
<P>
   White House Bicentennial and Special Events
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The White House in Miniature.'' A 1/12th-scale model of the
White House serves to illustrate the changing design and decoration
of the house over 200 years. Through Sept. 17 at National Building
Museum, 401 F. St., N.W. 202-272-2448; www.nbm.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Designing for Democracy: Furnishings from the President's
House.'' Select furnishings from the permanent White House
collection. Through Aug. 26 at the visitor center. 202-707-5000;
www.loc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Thomas Jefferson: Genius of Liberty.'' An exhibit that
probes the complexities and vast talents of the third president and
re-creates his donated personal library that seeded the Library of
Congress (also celebrating its bicentennial). Through Oct. 31 at
Library of Congress, 101 Independence Ave. 202-707-5000;
www.loc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fall Garden and House Tour.'' The hours and itinerary of
regular White House tours are extended to include Jacqueline
Kennedy, Children's and Rose gardens. Military bands entertain on
the South Lawn. Oct. 7 (9 a.m.-noon, 2-5 p.m.), Oct. 8 (1-5 p.m.).
202-707-5000; www.loc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``200 Years at the White House: Actors and Observers.'' A
symposium on the White House as a working home and political
crossroads, from the words of presidents, first ladies, house and
office staff. Sponsored by White House Historical Association, Nov.
14-16 at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, 1615 H St. 202-737-8292;
www.whitehousehistory
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Candlelight Tours.'' Holiday season tours, identical and in
addition to regular day tours, begin at 5 p.m., and anyone in line
by 7 p.m. is admitted. Three evenings in December to be announced.
202-208-1631; www.nps.gov/whho/whvc.
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
