<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The White House tour: History by the roomful
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  East Colonnade: As visitors file down this airy passage, they
view the Jacqueline Kennedy Garden, featuring Hillary Rodham
Clinton's arrangement of 20th century American sculpture. Guests
continue into a holding area that might be called the Hall of Jowls
for its grand portraits of presidents Fillmore, Arthur and Taft.
One may buy souvenirs (glittering White House Christmas ornaments:
$11) while waiting to be led by guides in groups of 25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ground-floor corridor: Edith (Mrs. Theodore) Roosevelt decreed
that first ladies' portraits be placed here. Nancy Reagan looks
sleek and thoughtful in scarlet; Rosalynn Carter, soulful in
lavender.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Library: Used as a laundry room by Abigail Adams, converted to
a library in Theodore Roosevelt's 1902 renovation. It's a cozy,
gray and rose, Federal-style room, but you sense that no one's
cracked a book here since Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  China Room: Quick: Know anything about Rutherford B. Hayes?
Now you do: His 1879 china, painted with such American fauna as
wild turkeys, is the house's most flamboyant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diplomatic reception room: Gold-and-white Federal decor. Scene
of FDR's fireside chats (there are 28 working fireplaces in the
house). Entrance/exit for the Marine 1 helicopter pad on the South
Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  East Room: The House's largest room, gold and white, scene of
receptions and musicales. The Gilbert Stuart portrait of Washington
(model for the dollar bill) is the last remaining object from the
original 1800 house. Seven presidents lay in state here. Check out
the chunky, Deco-ish eagles supporting the 1938 Steinway grand
piano.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Green Room: It's been green ever since the Monroes rebuilt the
house and made this their card room (favorite game: whist) in 1817.
Several fine early-1800s pieces by Duncan Phyfe, the Scottish-born
cabinetmaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blue Room: An oval reception room recently returned to the
French Empire style chosen by the Monroes in 1817. Chandelier is
removed to make room for the first family's Christmas tree. In
Rembrandt Peale's portrait, Jefferson's eyes glitter with benign
intelligence, while the third prez's domed memorial can be seen
through the windows, across the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Room: Empire style; carved lions, dolphins, lyres. Used
for teas, the room has a velvet-backed fireplace shield that was
used to keep ladies' wax-based makeup from melting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  State Dining Room: Dominated by the 1869 portrait of a
contemplative Lincoln. Arranged with up to 14 tables set for 10
people each. (Additional guests must settle for the vice president
in the Red Room).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grand foyer, Cross Hall: English cut-glass chandeliers from
1775; marble walls and floors from the Truman renovation. First
family descends the Grand Staircase on state occasions. This
impressive space is also what might be called the Hall of Mediocre
Portraits: likenesses of Ford, Bush and Reagan that seem to be the
work of disgruntled Democrats. The warmth of Jimmy Carter, however,
is well-captured in Herbert E. Abrams' portrait.
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Hulbert
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
