<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0209 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-SPORTS-ABRIDGED-     06-30 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-SPORTS-ABRIDGED-ART-$ADV02-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING)  
 A BLACK COLLEGE HAS TROUBLE ACCEPTING A WHITE QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eleventh in series)  
 (For release Sunday, July 2)  
(EDS: Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New
York Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is
Lived in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort
by a team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of
ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that Americans
continue to face. These stories, two or three each week, will be
approximately 6,000 words. The News Service will move each story in
advance, and an abridged version will also move, at approximately
3,000 words. They will move in the ``a'' news category and will
carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. Because the articles are
organized into chapters, papers with severe space restraints may
choose to spread a single article over several days. Please see
RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-NYT for a detailed list, or call 888-346-9867
or 212-556-1927.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT120-125 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 
 Sections of this report concerning the Morgan family, Jabari Morgan
and life at Southern University were contributed by Kirk Johnson.  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ A late summer morning and the sun was already
harsh on the dusty high school football field. The shirtless blond
19-year-old in shorts stained with sweat kept dropping back to
pass, his hands at times so wet it was hard to grip the ball. He
was throwing to a friend, working ``up the ladder,'' as it is
called, starting with short passes and ending long.
</P>
<P>
   But his mind wasn't totally on his receiver. He could feel the
eyes of the man in the dark glasses who sat in a car on the other
side of a chain-link fence, a hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The boy knew the man was watching. It had been subtly arranged.
The National Collegiate Athletic Association does not allow
tryouts, but if a college coach happens by a field where kids
regularly throw the ball around, well, a coach may argue, where's
the harm?
</P>
<P>
   At that time, in July 1996, Southern University, a football
powerhouse among black colleges, desperately needed a quarterback,
and the boy, Marcus Jacoby, badly needed a place to play
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   After half an hour, the man in dark glasses, Mark Orlando,
Southern's offensive coordinator, had seen enough and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   It had gone well. The boy was invited to the coach's apartment,
where after a short visit he was offered a full football
scholarship. The coach explained that the boy had a shot at the
starting job, that the presumed starter had flunked off the team
and that the two remaining backups did not have the coaches'
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds good,'' said Jacoby, who had been a star at Catholic
High, one of Baton Rouge's schoolboy powers. ``But I have to think
about it _ talk with my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Jacoby was unaware that if he accepted the scholarship,
he would be the first white to play quarterback for Southern
University. And he would be the first white ever to start at
quarterback in the 76-year history of the black Southwestern
Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby had grown up in Baton Rouge, and yet he knew practically
nothing about Southern, had never even been to the other side of
town to see the campus. Until that July day, he had spent his life
surrounded by whites.
</P>
<P>
   THE BUSINESS OF HOW TO SUCCEED
</P>
<P>
   In three his years as Southern's head coach, Pete Richardson had
turned a laughingstock of a program into a national force. Southern
won 11 of 12 games his first year, 1993, and two years later it was
the No. 1 black college in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy for a black man to become a head coach. Despite
his record, Richardson, 54, has never had an offer from a Division
I college; only three of those 500 institutions have black head
football coaches. Instead he worked his way around the black
college circuit, serving as an assistant in Texas and Arkansas,
then taking the head coach's job at Winston-Salem State in North
Carolina, and finally, in 1993, getting his big break at Southern,
the largest historically black college in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and Marcus' parents, Glen and Marian Jacoby,
discussed everything from Southern's rich athletic tradition to the
engineering courses that interested Marcus, but for a long while
they didn't mention the thing that worried the parents most. The
quarterback is the team leader. Would a black team accept a white
leader? Would the black campus?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it will be that big a deal,'' said
Richardson. ``Sure, there will be some adjustments from all sides.
But Marcus will have the backing of the administration as well as
the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson pointed out that there were other minorities on
campus. He meant that of the 10,500 students, 5 percent were not
black, but what Mrs. Jacoby kept thinking about was how it would
feel to be in a stadium with her husband and 30,000 black fans.
</P>
<P>
   The coach didn't say it to the Jacobys, but no one knew better
than he about the strain that Marcus would feel being a minority.
As a successful black man, Richardson was used to the stares of
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   When he coached at Winston-Salem, he had a state government car.
``Whites look at you and ask you what you're doing driving the
state's car,'' he said. ``You pull over to get some gas and people
will address you the wrong way or policemen will look at you
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach thought he could make this Jacoby thing work. He
wasn't sitting there fretting whether Marcus could learn to be a
minority. There was no time for that. The first game was six weeks
away. As he would say later, his first-string quarterback had
flunked out and he didn't have ``ample time to find another black
quarterback.'' Marcus would have to do what all good football
players did, what Richardson himself had done: suck it up.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure the Jacobys, the coach told them about his staff. Of
six assistants he had hired when he started in 1993, two were
white, one Asian. He was told that Southern fans would never stand
for that. But after his 11-1 debut season _ the year before they
had been 6-5 _ a popular T-shirt on campus featured a photo of the
integrated staff, with the words ``In Living Color.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning, Richardson knew, often made problems go away. ``I don't
care what color Marcus is,'' Richardson said. ``If I believe he can
help our football team, I want him.''
</P>
<P>
   HARD WORK OR PRIVILEGE?
</P>
<P>
   From the Jacobys' home, in the upper-middle class white Tara
section of Baton Rouge, Southern was a 20-minute car trip,
literally to the other side of the tracks. As Marcus drove to the
first practice, he began imagining himself playing a game, he
recalled. ``Would I see a white face?''
</P>
<P>
   Southern's decision to sign a white quarterback made headlines,
first locally, then nationally, and the reaction of some whites he
knew startled him. When Jacoby called his girlfriend to talk about
it, her mother answered. ``The niggers over there will kill you,''
he recalled her saying. ``There are bullets flying all over the
place. It's a war zone.'' When his girlfriend got on the phone, she
said, ``Marcus, I don't want you to call me again.''
</P>
<P>
   To many on the white side of town, who had never visited this
campus bustling with middle-class black students on the bluffs of
the Mississippi, it was as if Jacoby had voluntarily moved to the
ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern coaches were impressed with Jacoby's arm and had
never seen a quarterback learn Richardson's complex offense so
fast. The other quarterback hopefuls would leave practice at 6, but
Jacoby stayed to do extra throwing and often studied game films
well past midnight. Within days of arriving, he was first-string.
</P>
<P>
   That sparked anger among many of his new black teammates. For
more than a year they had been friendly with the two quarterbacks
now relegated to backup, and they resented the newcomer,
complaining that he had not earned his stripes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several felt the decision was racial. ``It just became the fact
that we were going to have this white quarterback,'' said Sam
George, a quarterback prospect who was academically ineligible that
year. ``It wasn't about ability no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the coaches, Jacoby was isolated. In the locker room,
he recalled, ``I would walk around the corner and people would just
stop talking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day at lunch,'' he said, ``I'd sit down at a table full
of guys without being invited and they would continue their
conversations as if I wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the huddles there was dissension. Scott Cloman, a
Southern receiver, recalled: ``The minute Marcus was like,
`Everybody calm down, just shut up,' they were like: `Who are you
talking to? You're not talking to me.' You know, stuff like that.
If it was a black person it wouldn't be a problem. They all felt
that `I'm not going to let a white person talk to me like that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His entire time at Southern, Jacoby kept his feelings about all
this inside, sucking it up, repeatedly telling the stream of
inquiring reporters what a great experience it was being exposed to
a new culture. ``As soon as I signed and walked onto the campus,''
he said to one interviewer, ``I felt like part of the family. I
definitely feel at home here.''
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL AND STUDENTS IN STEP
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, 1996, six weeks after Jacoby arrived, Southern
opened its season away, at Northwestern State, with him at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Morgan, a supervisor at the local Exxon plant who attended
Southern in the 1960s, is one of many middle-aged black men who
rarely miss a practice, let alone a game. His wife, his mother and
his aunt graduated from Southern, too, as did 25 other relatives.
And now, his son Jabari, a drummer, who had dreamed of being in the
famous Southern band since he was a little boy, was out there
marching for the first time, a freshman living out his fantasy on
that same September day.
</P>
<P>
   Families like the Morgans were fiercely proud of their school
and its role in helping generations of blacks into the middle and
professional classes _ even if the state had long treated it as
second-rate.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern had become the flagship of the nation's largest
historically black public university system, with 15,000 students
on three campuses.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-1990s, change was brewing. The year before Jacoby
arrived, Southern and LSU settled a 20-year-old federal
desegregation lawsuit. LSU pledged to double its black enrollment;
Southern pledged to double its nonblack enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni like the Morgans worried. Would Southern soon become just
another satellite campus of LSU? Were black public colleges facing
extinction? Was the white quarterback the beginning of the end?
</P>
<P>
   But Jabari could not have cared less, he was so consumed with
the band. It didn't matter to Jabari if Jacoby was purple, as long
as Southern won and people came to see the halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   A MUTINOUS BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   Southern lost its first two games. The team was young _ 10 of 11
offensive starters were new _ but what people remembered was the
11-1 record from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   During the second loss, Jacoby recalls, ``I heard the entire
stadium booing me.'' Fans were yelling, ``Get the white boy out!''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Williams, a Southern offensive lineman, believed that the
opposing team hit Jacoby harder because he was white. Cloman
recalled that after one Southern loss, opposing players said,
``That's what you all get for bringing white boys on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby was hit so hard and so often the first game that he was
hospitalized with a concussion. In the school paper, a columnist
wrote about the ``Jacoby nonblocking scandal'': ``Someone should
validate or refute the current rumor that Southern's offensive line
(or some of its members) purposely missed blocks.'' But Jacoby
still believes that it was just the mistakes of an inexperienced
line.
</P>
<P>
   After Southern's second straight loss, an angry fan confronted
Jacoby and threatened him. A coach had to jump between them. For
the rest of his career, Jacoby would have a police escort at games.
</P>
<P>
   WINNING WORKS WONDERS
</P>
<P>
   Southern won six of its next seven games, beating the two
top-ranked black colleges, and was invited to the Heritage Bowl in
Atlanta, the black college championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't getting booed nearly as much,'' Jacoby said. Some
teammates began warming to him. ``Things had changed,'' he said,
``to the extent that some of the players were calling me `the
man.'''
</P>
<P>
   He felt he was developing real friendships with several
teammates and Southern students. When Cloman needed a place to stay
for a month, Jacoby had him to his parents' home and the two grew
close. ``Marcus was the first white person I ever really got to
know,'' recalled Cloman. ``I always felt a lot of tension around
whites. I'd go into a store and I could just feel the tension.
Sometimes you just feel like, `I can't stand white people.' I
didn't understand them. I really didn't want to be near them.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents treated me like a son,'' said Cloman. Some players
now joked when they saw Cloman, ``Where's your brother?'' ``And
some,'' he said, ``called me `white lover.' Didn't bother me. I had
come to understand the Jacobys. A lot of times people fear what
they can't understand. Because of being around the Jacobys my
attitude toward whites in general changed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Heritage Bowl that first year, on national television,
Southern took a 24-10 halftime lead against Howard University, then
fell behind, 27-24. In the closing minute, Southern drove to
Howard's 15-yard line. On third down, with 42 seconds left, Jacoby
dropped back, and under pressure, threw off the wrong foot,
floating a pass into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the crowd gasp,'' he said. ``I couldn't believe this
was happening.'' He'd been intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dragged myself off the field and sat on a bench and buried
my head in my arms,'' said Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby said a few people came by and patted him on the back, to
be encouraging. ``But I heard, `You screwed up real bad this time,
whitey.' And: `You're as dumb as they come.' It was the lowest
point of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Orlando, the defensive coordinator, who is
white, received an anonymous call: ``If Jacoby ever plays for
Southern again, we'll kill him _ and you.'' He said he had been
averaging a threat a week that season. A few weeks later as Orlando
and Jacoby left the locker room and headed to their cars, Orlando
pointed to several trees. Jacoby could see a yellow rope hung from
each tree. The ropes were tied in nooses.
</P>
<P>
   THE EYES OF SOUTHERN ARE UPON HIM
</P>
<P>
   On campus, Jacoby struggled with all the daily irritations that
go with being the minority. As a white who grew up among whites, he
was used to being inconspicuous. Here, he always felt on display.
``I hated that,'' he said, ``because it was like I had become just
a novelty act.''
</P>
<P>
   College is a place where young people are confronted with new
ideas _ sometimes only partially understood _ and encouraged to
speak out about them. And yet Jacoby felt that when he did, he was
criticized. At first, in his African American history class, when
slavery was discussed, he said he tried to be conciliatory. ``I
would say something like, `I kind of feel for you.' And it was
like, `Quit Uncle Tomming.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then he worried he wasn't being true to his white roots. ``I
felt that I had lost my pride and the respect of friends that I had
grown up with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For one oral report, he decided to speak his mind and said that
it was unhealthy for blacks to dwell too much on past racial
violence. ``There have been tragedies like slavery throughout
time,'' he said. ``I don't think one is more important than any
other.'' When he finished, he recalled, ``there was an eerie
silence and I saw at least three or four people glaring at me.''
</P>
<P>
   COMEBACK AND COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   What got Jacoby through his second year at Southern was a
determination to avenge that Heritage Bowl interception, to show
everyone he could be a champion. He moved through the 1997 season
with a passion.
</P>
<P>
   Again, he was first string, but he had competition. Sam George
had returned from academic probation. George was a popular figure
on campus, known for his hard-partying ways. Though he was only
5'7,'' he had a strong arm and terrific speed. He excited fans with
his scrambling derring-do. ``And,'' said Scott Cloman, ``he was
black.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jacoby started, Richardson liked bringing in George when
the team seemed flat and needed a spark. Both quarterbacks saw race
as the true reason behind Richardson's substitutions. Jacoby was
convinced the coach was giving the black quarterback playing time
in order to pander to black fans; George was convinced Richardson
was starting the white quarterback as part of Southern's promise to
be more diversified.
</P>
<P>
   George wound up playing in 5 of 12 games. By Southern's third
game, against Arkansas Pine-Bluff, both quarterbacks were bitter.
After winning their first two, Southern was losing to Pine-Bluff
7-6 at the half, when Richardson decided to bring in George. Jacoby
was devastated; he felt he was a proven winner and shouldn't be
yanked for one bad half.
</P>
<P>
   George threw a last-ditch 37-yard pass on a scramble play that
tied the game, and threw another touchdown in triple overtime for a
36-33 Southern win.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, come Monday practice, Jacoby was the starter again.
George was frustrated and perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Southern had a 9-1 record going into its two final games. A win
in the next game _ the Bayou Classic, against archrival Grambling _
would assure a return to the Heritage Bowl and a chance for Jacoby
to redeem himself.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando suggested that if Jacoby played a little more like
George, sometimes scrambling out of the pocket, he might be more
effective. Jacoby felt that he was being told to become something
he was not, but he was so desperate, so worn down and nervous about
being yanked, he followed the coach's advice. He ran as he rarely
had before, and it worked. In a 30-7 win against Grambling, Jacoby
threw three touchdowns and played the entire game. He was named the
Bayou Classic's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   A month later he achieved his football redemption, throwing the
winning touchdown pass in a 34-28 Heritage Bowl victory over South
Carolina State, capping an 11-1 season that earned Southern the
black national championship. ``I was happier than I had ever been
at Southern,'' he recalled. On the trip back from Atlanta he slept
soundly for the first time in months.
</P>
<P>
   THE GOING GETS TOUGH
</P>
<P>
   The more you achieve, the more that's expected. After that 11-1
season, the talk on campus was that Southern would go undefeated in
1998. But in the opener, trailing 7-0 at the half, Jacoby was
pulled for Sam George. Southern lost anyway, 28-7.
</P>
<P>
   In practice on Tuesday, Jacoby overthrew a pass to one of his
ends, John Forman, and Forman yelled at him in front of everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Forman would say later that it was just the frustration of
having lost the opener, but to Jacoby it was so much more, the
final straw. Forman was Sam George's roommate. He was sure Forman
was trying to subvert his control of the team to help George. He
was sure it was race. ``It was like I was right back where I had
started two years before, with a lot of the same attitudes against
me. I felt I had lost the team.''
</P>
<P>
   He quit, football and Southern.
</P>
<P>
   NO MORE APOLOGIES
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was surprised and asked Jacoby to stay. But more
recently, he said, he understood Jacoby's decision. Because of
``the type person he is,'' the coach said, ``it was the best thing
for Marcus because it would have killed him.'' Richardson meant
Jacoby just wasn't emotionally equipped to continue being the
solitary white.
</P>
<P>
   When Branch Rickey of the Brooklyn Dodgers wanted to break major
league baseball's color line in 1947, he chose Jackie Robinson, not
simply because he was a great black ballplayer _ there were greater
black stars. He knew Robinson had experience inside white
institutions. Robinson was 28 that first year in the majors, a
mature man who had graduated UCLA and served in the U.S. Army.
Jackie Robinson knew what it was like to be the minority.
</P>
<P>
   When Richardson went after Jacoby, he was just looking for a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters hounded Jacoby to find why he left, but until now, he
has never spoken openly about it. He had never mentioned race. In
brief interviews, he told them he was burned out, and in a sense
this was true. He had burned out on being the minority. And as a
white, he didn't have to be. ``You kind of look over your shoulder
and see your old life and you say, `I could go back.'''
</P>
<P>
   A white quarterback at Southern did make people think. Mo Morgan
had been against it at the start, but after watching Jacoby at
practices, he changed. ``I looked at the three quarterbacks that
were there and he was the best at the time. I'm just telling you
straight out. It wasn't his ability and I'm not saying he was
brighter than the other kids. He just put in the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby moved on to attend LSU, majoring in finance, but his
Southern experience still unsettled him. At times, he talks about
being lucky to have experienced another culture, but at other
moments, he describes it as ``two and a half years of a personal
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, he appreciates walking around anonymously on the
mostly-white LSU campus. ``I got burned out as far as being
somebody,'' he said. ``At LSU, I've just enjoyed being a part of
the crowd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
