A0212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-3     06-30 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts, style, financial and travgel articles this week
for release Sunday, July 2, 2000. Review of the Week stories will
move Saturday morning:
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded 'e')
</P>
<P>
   COVER STORIES
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTIC-SONGS (Undated) _ Kate Smith introduced ``God Bless
America'' on her radio show on Armistice Day, Nov. 11, 1938. It was
an instant sensation. Within weeks, the song was ubiquitous:
crackling across radio airwaves, sung in churches, schools and
ballparks, championed by many as a replacement national anthem for
Francis Scott Key's ungainly ``The Star-Spangled Banner.'' But not
every American took solace in the skyward-striving strains of ``God
Bless America.'' In the winter of 1940, Woody Guthrie was bedeviled
by the song: everywhere he went, Kate Smith's belting seemed to
follow him; the more he heard the song, the angrier he got. Soon
came ``This Land is Your Land,'' offering a folksier reverence.
This call and response between revered troubadours is one of the
most piquant episodes in American pop music. By Jody Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE-FRUIT-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``Strange Fruit'' may not have
been on the soundtrack as the Freedom Riders boarded buses or
college students registered black Mississippians or marchers
marched from Selma to Montgomery; ``We Shall Overcome,'' more
optimistic and upbeat, better fit the zeitgeist. But it was the
song which, by confronting racial injustice in the starkest
possible terms at a time when it simply hadn't penetrated popular
culture, inspired many to march in the first place. By David
Margolick.
</P>
<P>
   FILM
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOT-FILM (Undated) _ ``The Patriot,'' the new movie starring
Mel Gibson, will prove to many a satisfying way to spend a summer
evening. It's got big battles and wrenching hand-to-hand combat, a
courageous but conflicted hero and a dastardly and totally
guilt-free villain. There is just enough brain bran to keep the
post-film discussions from being dominated by people who want to
focus on how cool it was when Mel hit that guy with the hatchet.
Why, some may think it's the best Revolutionary War movie ever
made. Which brings us to our point: it is also one of the very few
Revolutionary War movies ever made. By Jamie Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MUSIC (Undated) _ The history of cinema parallels the
history of recorded music in that both have been concerned, since
the necessary technical discoveries were made at the end of the
19th century, with composing in time: composing images, and later
sounds, in film; composing sounds alone where music is concerned.
With a grand inevitability, therefore, Jean-Luc Godard's video
``Histoire(s) du Cinema'' presents itself also as ``Histoire(s) de
la Musique,'' and it is fitting that the soundtrack alone should be
available. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ If the news is true, the record
business is not being nice to classical music. The Washington Post
reports that such respected labels as RCA Red Seal, Deutsche
Harmonia Mundi and Melodiya, all owned or distributed by the
international giant BMG, will be either shunted aside as minor
activities of the American, pop-oriented RCA label or put out of
business altogether. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EUROPE-MUSIC (Undated) _ The book is called ``Kein' Angst,
Baby!'' (``Don't Worry, Kid!''), and it has a voluptuous Valkyrie
sizzling on the cover. Written for opera singers by opera singers
and first published in 1992 by the New York Opera Newsletter, it is
a guide to auditioning in Germany. American singers long regarded
the German audition tour as a useful _ indeed, essential _ career
move, and this book helped the uninitiated negotiate everything
from writing a letter to a German agent to dealing with German
telephones and money matters. But things have changed. German
theaters are not hiring singers as they used to. By Anne Midgette.
</P>
<P>
   SUPREMES-MUSIC (Undated) _ For a teenager living in the suburbs
of Detroit in 1964, the royals of AM radio were alarmingly obvious:
The Beatles were the imported kings of rock 'n' roll and Aretha was
the native Queen of Soul. Then along came the pop princess Diana
and her ladies in waiting, the Supremes. By David A. Keeps.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   CHAUTAUQUA-DANCE (Undated) _ In 1983, Jean-Pierre Bonnefoux,
recently retired as a principal dancer with the New York City
Ballet, was asked to take charge of the summer ballet school at the
Chautauqua Institution, a gated community of 225 acres along the
shore of Chautauqua Lake, in the northwest corner of New York
state. Bonnefoux accepted the offer and, 18 years later, can be
justly proud of his achievements. Summer by summer, he has
transformed the school into one that attracts some of the country's
best ballet students. By Roslyn Sulcas.
</P>
<P>
   ABT-DANCE (New York) _ Hats off to American Ballet Theater for a
heroic season. The repertory looked better on stage than on paper
and a clever Band-Aid approach kept performances at a high standard
despite an inordinate amount of illness and injury among the
dancers. It was the season of the unexpected. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   BOULDER-DANCE (Boulder, Colo.) _ Far from the Eastern shores of
the American Dance Festival and Jacob's Pillow, a multiplicity of
summer dance gatherings in Colorado illustrates the surprising
cultural vitality of the Rocky Mountain state as well as tensions
affecting arts presenters nationwide. Three festivals Blazing a
trail along a risky frontier is Boulder's Colorado Dance Festival,
one of America's few dance-only presenters and widely considered
one of its top three dance festivals. By Daniel Gesmer.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   STAR-TV (Los Angeles) _ Darren Star is not only one of the most
successful writer-producers on television, but also one of the most
prolific. By the fall season, he will have three shows on the air:
``Sex and the City,'' the hit comedy series that seeks to offer a
candid view of sex and relationships among some beautiful women in
Manhattan; ``The Street,'' about successful and handsome young
turks on Wall Street; and the suddenly controversial ``Grosse
Pointe,'' which is Star's tongue-in-cheek look at a teen-age
television soap opera that's very much like ``Beverly Hills,
90210.'' By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   BEGGARS-TV (Undated) _ Although Brandon Tartikoff, the legendary
NBC programming chief, did not live to see his series idea reach
the air, Showtime's ``Beggars and Choosers,'' an hour comedy about
the embattled president of a fictional flagging network, fulfills
his vision. By Hilary De Vries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-NIGHTSPOT (Zagreb) _ The Factory is a noisy place. By
9:30 on a Tuesday night, trails of moisture slither down the
paint-splattered walls and a fat belly of smoke hangs in the air
inside. But as crowds of fashionably dressed young Croatians gather
expectantly outside the drab, inconspicuous entrance, work could
not be further from their minds. The Factory, one of Zagreb's
trendiest nightspots, has even more to offer than bottled beer and
ubiquitous techno music: it has become one of the city's most
popular theaters. By Chloe Veltman.
</P>
<P>
   ART/ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT-POSTERS (Washington) _ The little-known role of posters
in popularizing flight in the early 20th century is the focus of
``Looping the Loop: Posters of Early Flight,'' the first museum
exhibition on the subject in this country, on view at the National
Air and Space Museum here through July 9. The show, which will
travel through 2002, moves next to the Thames Science Center in
Newport, R.I. (July 22 to Oct. 8), and then to the Virginia Air and
Space Center in Hampton (Oct. 29 to Jan. 7, 2001). By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-PRINCESS-ART (Undated) _ Long before the Greco-Roman
specter of Lady Liberty arrived in New York Harbor in 1886, another
woman symbolized the United States. Sometimes known as L'Amerique,
or the Indian Princess, she was a Native American figure who first
appeared on maps in the 16th century. Wearing a feather headdress,
accompanied by a parrot and perched on an alligatorlike reptile,
she represented continental America alongside female allegories of
Europe, Asia and Africa. This early character, along with Liberty
and the lesser-known Columbia, is the subject of ``The Changing
Face of Liberty: Female Allegories of America,'' at the New-York
Historical Society through Sept. 3. The exhibition comes at a time
when native women have seen renewed popularity. By Sarah Bayliss.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded `t')
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IOWA-MASON-CITY (Mason City, Iowa) _ Often it seems time
has stalled in 1912, year of `The Music Man,' in Meredith Willson's
hometown, Mason City. By Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ECUADOR (Undated) _ Ecuador switches to a dollar
currency. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Making cabs more accessible to
the disabled. By Betsy Wade.
