<P>
   RENAULT (Paris) _ Louis Schweitzer is, in short, the very model
of French establishment probity. Yet he now finds himself as
chairman and chief executive of the auto giant Renault, which likes
to boast that it was built on a bet. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R-BLOCK (Undated) _ The carefully constructed image of H&AMP;R
Block as America's trusted tax preparer was marred a decade ago,
when consumer advocates accused the company of marketing advances
on customers' tax refunds at usurious interest rates. Critics said
flat fees for the two-week loans disguised annual rates as high as
250 percent. Plaintiffs' lawyers filed a host of class action
lawsuits. Block is on the verge of resolving the litigation this
month without admitting any wrongdoing. But critics of the proposed
settlement call it a sham, saying Block has effectively hired
lawyers to sue it on the company's own _ extremely favorable _
terms. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ While all eyes are on the disappointing
action in many big-name, large-capitalization stocks, the enviable
performance of a wide swath of the stock market has been ignored.
That is the large group of stocks made up of lesser-known,
medium-sized companies with market values of between $1 billion and
$10 billion. These are known as mid-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
