</P>
<P>
   CONTRARIAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ If there's a sure-fire way to sell
something these days, it's to say the thing is natural. The Natural
used to be Roy Hobbs, Bernard Malamud's mythic baseball player, but
now it's an obsession that all of us seem to share about a life we
have somehow lost. By Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ Investors who follow hot-handed
investment advisers may get burned.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR-COLUMN (Undated) _ The demographics of Madison Avenue are
increasingly out of synch with those of consumer buying power, and
it shows in how little marketing is done to the 50-plus crowd. In
and over. By Fred Brock.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-MEDICINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Money &AMP; Medicine: Report on
doctors who turn their backs on managed care, and what becomes of
them. By Jennifer Steinhauer
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is no secret that the rivalry between
the software leaders, Microsoft and Oracle, is bitter. Still, the
acknowledgement last week by Oracle that it financed a series of
escapades intended to embarrass Microsoft provided some lively
summer entertainment _ especially a Keystone Kops caper in which
private investigators offered office cleaners $1,200 for the
contents of a pro-Microsoft trade group's wastebaskets. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS
</P>
<P>
   BOSS-HOSS (Undated) _ Monte Warne is a down-home Renaissance
man, a Michelangelo of machinery: A licensed aircraft and
airplane-engine mechanic, an aircraft designer, a licensed private,
commercial and crop-duster pilot, a lifelong motorcyclist and a
former motorcycle and car racer. So whatever possessed him to build
the outrageous Boss Hoss, a motorcycle with a Corvette V-8 engine?
By Jim McCraw.
</P>
<P>
   CARSMART-CORVETTE Dull Station, Ohio) _ The Corvette Z06:
Dullsville it isn't. By Cheryl Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded `l')
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-COOKIES (Washington) _ Most of this year's presidential
campaign has dealt with the candidates' positions on campaign
financing, Social Security and helping the uninsured. Now it is
time to deal with what really matters _ whose wife bakes the best
cookies. You know, family values. And the 2000 presidential cookie
contest pits chocolate chips, pecans and coconut against ginger and
molasses. The odds favor the ones with the chocolate chips; with
recipes. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH-UP-BRAS (Undated) _ Six years ago, when the British-made
Wonderbra was introduced in this country, push-up bras accounted
for about 3 percent of the $4.6 billion bra business; today that
figure is closer to 10 percent. Underwear makers are rolling out
push-up bras with the sort of hoo-ha usually reserved for movie
openings, and their arrivals in department stores are being
attended with the frenzy of a Meet-The-Beatles tour. By Penelope
Green.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-MARKETING (Undated) _ Like hair colorists, fashion
designers and chefs, more and more doctors are seeking publicity to
build their businesses. Freed of legal constraints that prohibited
them from advertising and faced with shrinking incomes in the age
of managed care, they are aggressively marketing themselves as
experts on beauty and health in magazines like Vogue, Harper's
Bazaar, Elle, Self and Good Housekeeping and on television shows
like ``Today,'' where they reach millions who are willing to pay
for elective medical treatments. By Anne Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Maybe there's an up side to the
climate change that spells warmer, drier weather for the East
Coast: lavender. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   DUMMY-FILMING (New York) _ The tale of Steven Schoichet, a
maladroit suburbanite whose life is transformed when he comes into
possession of a ventriloquist's prop, ``Dummy'' is the kind of
movie Charlie McCarthy might have starred in if Michael Ovitz had
been his agent. Nearly everyone else in the film is a client of
Ovitz's firm, Artists Management Group, a noncoincidence that helps
explain how a script by an obscure writer with a budget that
wouldn't buy a two-bedroom in Manhattan happened to get this far.
By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   NY-APARTMENT (New York) _ The sight of the couple draped across
the bed engaged in cozy pillow talk was more than a little
discomfitting. Stumbling on the scene, one wasn't sure whether to
eavesdrop, look the other way or join the lovebirds on the sheets.
Convincing as it was, this slice of life was in fact a performance,
enacted by models and staged at a party at the Apartment, a
strenuously hip fashion and home furnishings store masquerading as
a private residence. By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review for
Sunday, July 2, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TERM-REVIEW (Washington) _ It was a Supreme Court term of
surpassing interest, rich in symbol and substance, a vivid reminder
of the court's power to scramble settled expectations, put old
questions to rest and, ultimately, to have the last word. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-AIDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ How much would it cost to contain
the global AIDS epidemic? The answer is: How much would it cost to
banish ignorance, to deaden lust, to shame rape, to stop war, to
enrich the poor, to empower women, to defend children, to make
decent medical care as globally ubiquitous as Coca-Cola _ in short,
to get rid of all the underlying causes of the epidemic in the
Third World? By Donald G. McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-LYING-REVIEW (Undated) _ What is it about legal
proceedings and particularly those pre-trial sworn interviews known
as depositions that turn sophisticated people into quibblers,
dissemblers or amnesiacs? Why can't they just respond to the
questions posed as people respond in everyday conversations? By
Adam Liptak.
</P>
<P>
   SKIMPY-CLOTHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Blame ``Sex and the City'' or
blame the decline of the ozone layer, but skin is in. American
women are wearing less than ever before. Summer itself is hotter.
And over the past decade, the proliferation of the Wonderbra
coincided with global warming so that just as cleavages became more
pronounced, shorts became shorter. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-PROGRAM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just as surely as any
shrink-wrapped Microsoft disk, the human genome is a program, a set
of precisely coded instructions that evolution has written for the
design, operation and unfortunately rather limited maintenance of a
person. That people should be operated by such a specific script is
as amazing as it would be to find that robots have souls. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-CELEBS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some statements from
celebrity women who have explained why they chose to appear nude in
Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLUES-REVIEW (London) _ Britain is endlessly wondering
``How'm I doing?'' But unlike Ed Koch, the self-congratulating
former mayor of New York, Britain rarely expects a positive answer.
And lately, a nation that is always sensitive about perceived
slights to its international status has found more than usual to be
upset about. And now along comes ``The Patriot,'' a film about the
American Revolution that presents the English as effete war
criminals with snobby accents who herd families of fledgling
Americans into barns and set them on fire, just for fun. To Britons
sick of being pushed around, this obnoxious affront to
retrospective pride may be the last straw. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ All of Mexico's
presidential candidates call themselves democrats, but the voters
will really be choosing between two sharply different ways of
political life. The longtime ruling party, known as the PRI, offers
its tradition of top-down control and doing what it takes to stay
in power. The opposition comes from a contrasting wellspring of
grass-roots struggles for citizens' rights and the fight for the
balance of powers. The opposition is democratic, in the way that
most Americans understand the term. The PRI is not. Yet Mexicans
are clearly torn about this choice. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ANTIMISSILE-REVIEW (Beijing) _ It's hard to find any
foreign-policy expert here, in or out of government, who believes
the stated U.S. rationale for a continental anti-missile defense:
That it's merely intended to stop the likes of North Korea or Iraq.
Even Westward-leaning scholars here think the new push for missile
defense in Washington reflects an underlying conviction that the
United States must better prepare for battle with China. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
