<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES SPAR IN LIVELY TV DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The race for the Mexican presidency was a show
like Mexico has never seen. The leading candidates slugged it out
on television, calling each other names and wrangling fiercely over
the merits of change in a country ruled by the same party for 71
years.
</P>
<P>
   But when the dust settled, it was hard to find much difference
on the major issues between the two leading candidates, Francisco
Labastida of the governing party and Vicente Fox of the
right-of-center opposition, who are neck to neck in the last days
before Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   On economic issues, the most deeply felt by Mexicans, the two
were so close that they used the same slogan: ``An economy with a
human face.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates downplayed the nationalism which used to be a
campaign mainstay and favored good relations with the United States
_ although they did not say it too loudly. They even agreed on what
not to bring up, so the crucial national security issue of
narcotics was largely absent.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates reflected a consensus among Mexican voters, who
have embraced the global economy but want a fairer share of it, and
seek better government through peaceful, orderly reform. And with
Mexico linked to the United States more firmly than ever, its
politicians room to maneuver is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   A leftist contender, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, contrasted with his
rivals, calling for a renegotiation of the North American Free
Trade Agreement and more confrontation with the United States. But
the most recent polls show that although Mexicans admire Cardenas'
honest zeal, they will not elect him president.
</P>
<P>
   Both Labastida and Fox were strong supporters of NAFTA, which
has transformed Mexico into an export powerhouse, creating millions
of jobs in sectors that supply the booming U.S. market. Both were
critical of government policies that catered to the markets but did
little to close the widening rift between rich and poor and between
northern Mexico, where the export industries are based, and the
south, where unemployment is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, the candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, which has ruled Mexico for seven decades, distanced
himself from President Ernesto Zedillo, even though the
government's tight fiscal policies have generated a recovery and
growth surge, without which the PRI campaign would have been
doomed. The PRI candidate criticized his party's president for
neglecting the purchasing power of working-class Mexicans. He
proposed to double or triple current subsidies to Mexican farmers
in regions hurt by U.S. competition through NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   Fox stood on his experience as a former Coca-Cola executive and
his record of boosting Mexican entrepreneurs when he was governor
of Guanajuato state. He said he would create a cabinet ministry,
separate from the Finance Ministry, to create jobs through private
investment, promote ``aggressive policies'' on behalf of small
businesses and send ``massive resources'' to the poorest regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one among the analysts can make out whose proposals are
better,'' said Damian Fraser, the head of Latin American research
for UBS Warburg. ``Labastida has more experience in government and
represents continuity. Fox has a somewhat greater commitment to
free market polices.''
</P>
<P>
   The final polls showed Labastida and Fox in an even tie, with
Cardenas well behind. Fox is from the moderate conservative
National Action Party, known as the PAN, but spearheaded a diverse
group of Mexicans who want a change from the ruling system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the similarities, Labastida did score one propaganda
coup against Fox. In a much-commented-upon television commercial,
he showed a video clip of Fox speaking in English during a visit to
the United States, describing a program he set up in Guanajuato to
train gardeners for skilled jobs in the United States. At end of
the commercial, Labastida appears and says that he plans to create
jobs for Mexicans in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Even though relations with the United States have never been
closer, Mexicans retain a gut wariness of their neighbor.
Nationalism was unusually dormant through much of the leading
campaigns, but in the final days the PRI revived it with
accusations that Fox received illegal donations from across the
border. Fox denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates both promised a harder line in defense of
Mexican immigrants. Fox stressed a proposal to make a free labor
market in the hemisphere in the coming years to parallel the free
trade market, opening the border to the millions of Mexican
migrants who now risk their lives to cross it illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Education was another hot-button issue, where Fox and Labastida
diverged. Fox made a risky pitch to Catholics, who are more than 90
percent of the population, suggesting he would make more room for
the Catholic Church in public education. The floater drew a furious
response from the PRI, whose anti-clericalism and commitment to
non-religious public schools dates back to its founding. It was not
clear how the overture played among the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida also gambled, with a nationally broadcast radio
commercial saying he would bring English and computer courses to
all public schools. The opposition ridiculed the proposal as
impractical and elitist. But PRI media analysts found that the ad
was a hit with working class voters and they extended its stay on
the air for an extra two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The issue too explosive for either candidate to dwell on was
Mexico's number one national security concern, the narcotics trade.
One PRI state governor, Mario Villanueva, is on the lam and wanted
by Mexican authorities for drug money-laundering. But Fox's party
also had a bleak record for combatting traffickers in Baja
California and Chihuahua, two borders states it governed in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates said they would fight crime and corruption by
overhauling the justice system. Labastida said he would dissolve
the attorney general's office, the central federal justice
institution, and create a new justice system more like the United
States, where the fight against drugs would be isolated in one
agency, federal prosecutors in another and federal police in a
third.
</P>
<P>
   Many sparks in the campaign flew from the friction between two
very different men. Labastida is an institutional man who served 37
years in government without making a big wave or a big mistake. Fox
handily outperformed him in both debates because Labastida seemed
noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's forcefulness and populist informality both helped and hurt
him. In a survey by Consultores y Marketing Politico, public
opinion research firm, more of those interviewed liked and trusted
Fox, but thought Labastida had ``the personality to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   The split that made the contest so intense is over the record of
the PRI, tarnished by corruption and repeated economic crises. Fox
appealed to Mexican voters to abandon their deepset risk aversion
and throw off a system of rule which has dominated their entire
lives.
</P>
<P>
   From a podium high above a huge crowd in Mexico City's central
square, Fox boomed out the slogan that summarized his crusade:
``Don't stop now, Mexico!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
