<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES $11.2 BILLION EMERGENCY SPENDING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to tighten, reorganize and rewrite)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Without dissent, the Senate approved on Friday an
$11.2 billion emergency spending bill whose centerpiece is an aid
package to equip and train Colombia's security forces, who are
battling drug traffickers and their rebel allies.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes about $2 billion to finance the
Pentagon's peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, as well as millions of
dollars of disaster aid for flood and forest fire victims in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the House overwhelmingly approved the measure, the
Senate endorsed the aid package by voice vote and joined the House
in adjourning for the weeklong July 4 recess. President Clinton is
expected to sign the bill soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even as lawmakers agreed on the broad package of international
and domestic assistance, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, vowed to block a House Republican measure to allow the
limited sale of food and medicine to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans tried to attach the Cuba provision to the
emergency aid package, but Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois
backed down in the face of a threatened filibuster by Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., that would have delayed the entire
package.
</P>
<P>
   Lott told reporters he would fight against tacking the Cuba
amendment onto any other bill. ``I oppose both, and if I can find a
way to kill them, I will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuba amendment would bar public and private American
financing for the sale of food and medicine, and it would turn into
law the current regulations that restrict which groups can visit
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The aid to Colombia was a top priority of the administration and
Hastert. More than 90 percent of the cocaine entering the United
States comes from Colombia, and supporters of the $1.3 billion aid
package say American assistance is important not only to stabilize
a vital ally, but to curtail the flow of drugs into this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a landmark vote, striking the drug war at ground zero
_ Colombia,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga..
</P>
<P>
   But critics warn that the plan is a dangerous escalation of
American involvement into a decades-old civil conflict. Opponents
have also complained that much of the aid will be going to the
Colombian army, which has a poor human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes 18 Blackhawk and 42 Huey II helicopters
that will be used to ferry special Colombian army battalions to the
rebel-controlled south, the heart of the narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This critical assistance will help the government of Colombia
respond to the drug emergency and support its democratic
institutions,'' said Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the director of the
White House office on drug control policy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the international aid, the package also includes
$661 million to repair damage caused by the fire in Los Alamos,
N.M., two months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
