<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN SAVES RETAILER WITH TAX FUNDS; $6 BILLION IN DEBT TO BE
WRITTEN OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese financial authorities bailed out a highly
indebted department store company Friday, averting a major
corporate bankruptcy but reigniting concerns about Japan's economic
future just as it is showing signs of breaking out of a decade-long
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Reconstruction Commission, the agency charged with
overseeing reform in the banking system, said the government would
spend 97 billion yen, $924 million at Friday's exchange rates, of
taxpayer money to help rescue the store chain, the Sogo Co.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement paved the way for Sogo's other bankers to forgive
more than 630 billion yen in loans, roughly $6 billion. The banks
had wavered for weeks on whether to grant Sogo's request for the
debt forgiveness, one of the largest loan write-offs in Japanese
bank history.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement may have created far bigger problems for the
government, which is facing heightened scrutiny of its use of
taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to rescue the company _ and ease pressure on the
banks to which Sogo owes a total of $16 billion _ raises questions
about where the government will draw the line on the use of public
money. The precedent set Friday could mean that thousands of
companies will press for debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the government's decision casts doubt upon its
commitment to an overhaul of the economy, which has yet to
decisively rebound from a decade of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests that every time the Japanese government looks over
the precipice and sees what it means to clean up this economy, it's
just too scary,'' said Ronald Bevacqua, senior economist at Commerz
Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is not the first country to aid a private company. The
United States rescued the Chrysler Corp. 20 years ago, and South
Korea used public money to prop up businesses during its economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan has taken the concept farther. The government here has
spent at least 7.7 trillion yen, more than $80 billion, to restore
the banking system. The government has offered small and mid-sized
businesses 30 trillion yen in loan guarantees to keep them afloat _
only to see a large number of them fail anyway.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the banking crisis in early 1998, the Bank of
Japan bought corporate debt securities to keep companies from
suffering a short-term cash crisis. The Japan Development Bank was
permitted to extend emergency credit lines to struggling companies
like the Nissan Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Sogo is not Nissan, never mind Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is sensible to forgive some debt as we go through
the process of restructuring the economy here, but is this the
right company?'' asked James Fiorillo, senior banking analyst at
ING Barings in Tokyo. ``I think not.''
</P>
<P>
   Sogo's restructuring plan envisions a return to positive net
worth more than a decade from now. And there is widespread doubt
over whether Sogo can entice shoppers back into its dowdy stores.
</P>
<P>
   The government had hoped to avoid a public bailout of a private
company. But it was pushed into that position by Shinsei Bank, the
former Long-Term Credit Bank, which the government sold last year
to a private group led by an American investment firm, Ripplewood
Holdings LLC. Under the terms, the government must buy back any
loans made by Long-Term Credit Bank whose book value falls by 20
percent or more for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sogo's loans fell into that category, and on Wednesday, Shinsei
asked the Deposit Insurance Corp. to buy back 97 billion yen of the
200 billion yen Sogo owes it. Shinsei had already set aside 103
billion yen in reserves against a potential default on the loans.
Once it became clear that the government would be holding the
loans, not Shinsei, Sogo's other large creditors threatened not to
forgive Sogo debts unless the government did the same.
</P>
<P>
   While the government was worried about destroying Sogo and
putting its 9,900 employees out of work, it was more concerned
about the impact of Sogo's failure on the banking system, according
to officials.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Sogo's creditors had not adequately reserved against
potential default.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the government must still worry about the
stability and soundness of banks that have already received public
assistance and are supposedly in the process of seriously reforming
their business practices suggests that the financial crisis is not
really over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in crisis management mode in Japan,'' Fiorillo
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
