<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-FRANCE-MCDONALDS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MCDONALDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH RALLY BEHIND A NEW HERO WHO VANQUISHED A MCDONALD'S
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLAU, France _ Fearing that the trial of Jose Bove would turn
their quiet little town into an actual battleground for the forces
of anti-globalization, most store owners kept their iron gates
closed Friday. The McDonald's restaurant, which Bove is charged
with ransacking last year, was blockaded by two dozen police
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But as the trial opened, the atmosphere seemed more like a
French Woodstock than a Seattle. Thousands of teen-agers with green
hair, middle-aged men with pony tails, retirees wearing T-shirts
that said ``The world is not merchandise and I'm not either'' and
others set up tents and strummed guitars in the streets in support
of Bove, the sheep farmer who has become something of a national
hero with his fight against multinationals and what he calls the
industrialization of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Bove, who has a likable grin under his handlebar mustache, added
to the carnival air by riding into Millau's main square with his
nine co-defendants on a cart pulled by a tractor _ a not-so-veiled
reference to the way the condemned went to the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   And, when he finally climbed the courthouse stairs, he stood at
the door with his fist raised long enough for the pack of news
photographers to get a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtroom, the defendants, dressed in sports shirts,
laughed and made jokes as the charges were read and they were asked
to respond to them. One, accused of spraying the premises with
orange paint, said he was only sorry he had not used green paint.
</P>
<P>
   Bove, however, was more serious. At one point he compared
himself to Gandhi, saying that Gandhi too, had been accused of
``violence'' in his day. ``The dismantling of McDonald's was a
strong action, symbolic and nonviolent,'' Bove told the court,
saying the fast food giant's arrival in Millau was a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Bove was a little known farmer and union official until last
August, when he and the nine other men took a tractor, pick axes
and buzz saws to the local McDonald's. Bove declared at the time
that he was incensed by what he believed an unfair tax imposed by
the United States on French delicacies like Roquefort and pate de
foie gras in retaliation for Europe's decision not to import
hormone-treated American beef.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Bove has become a national celebrity. He has a
packed speaking schedule, a more prominent job with his union and
dinner invitations from high level government officials, including
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who set up their tents in the fields around this
town and then boarded shuttle buses to the courthouse said they had
come to pay homage to a hero, a man who was willing to stand up to
the forces of globalization and the arrogance of the American
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tax decision was outrageous,'' said Arianne Gurreau, a
schoolteacher who was camping with her boyfriend. ``I think the
judge needs to see that there are all these people who think what
he did was correct. We are fighting for values here, for the right
to care about what we eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Many came with their own fights inspired by Bove. ``What
prompted us to come is the problem of water,'' said Giselle Joffre,
a retired government worker who had made the trip with her husband,
Roger. ``In our town it is terribly expensive because we are
working with a big company. It is the same with all these
multinationals doing what they want. It all comes back to the same
thing. We have to support each other.''
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly not what many Millau residents had braced for.
Most had seen pictures of protesters, including Bove, at the World
Trade Organization meeting in Seattle and feared that this
demonstration too would turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were so scared,'' said Christianne Chazal-Martin, a
gift shop owner who decided to stay open. ``First one got talking
and then another and they went on and on about how bad it was going
to be. A lot of people really resented this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bove's attack on the McDonald's here last August was only one of
a number of attacks on the fast food chain, which is often a target
of anti-American sentiments. But Bove became instantly famous when
he was thrown in jail for it and then refused to pay bail for three
weeks in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he did pay the bail with money supplied by a group
of supporters, many of them American.
</P>
<P>
   His trial is expected to last two day. Bove faces charges that
could result in a fine of as much as $70,000 and up to five years
in jail. But it is considered unlikely that he, or any of his nine
co-defendants will serve any jail time for the vandalism, which
resulted in $110,000 worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bove's lawyers, including a former president of a prominent
human rights organization, have lined up more than a dozen
witnesses, most of whom are also prominent farming advocates from
other countries. But much of the first day was spent arguing about
pictures of the McDonald's after the ransacking.
</P>
<P>
   Bove's lawyers pointed out that some of the windows were not
smashed.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the demonstration had hoped to gather 30,000
people for the opening of the trial, though police officials said
they believed the number was closer to half that. With speakers, a
farmers market and a free rock concert in the evening, however,
there was plenty to do. Many said they came as much to have fun as
to make a political statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came first for the party,'' said Michael Phelippeau, 16,
who came with his friend Dennis Roulleau and was wandering from
booth to booth with his sleeping bag under his arm. ``But my father
is a farmer and I am here representing my family too. We believe in
what Mr. Bove believes in. We don't want the multinationals to tell
us what to eat. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKETING-DOCTORS-$AD     06-30 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETING-DOCTORS-$ADV02-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS WHO LOVE PUBLICITY AND MAGAZINES THAT OBLIGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By ANNE JARRELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. David Bank desperately wants to be a celebrity
dermatologist. So desperately that for the last three years he has
paid a publicist $3,000 a month and given away thousands of dollars
in free services to journalists to get his name in magazine
articles and to appear on television shows, where he offers medical
advice on everything from laser surgery to sunscreen protection.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of getting his name out has been worth it, he said. The
dermatology practice at his clinic in Westchester County has grown,
and so also has the caliber of his patient roster. Blythe Danner
and Chevy Chase are celebrities he boasts of tending to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm one of the best doctors out there, and I want to
get the word out,'' Bank, a Columbia medical graduate, said. To do
that, he often invites writers and editors of leading women's
magazines to visit his clinic in Mount Kisco, N.Y., where he
performs laser treatments, chemical peels, botox injections,
liposuction and other high-priced procedures free _ with the
understanding that they will write about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good working relationship,'' he said, though sometimes,
he said, ``it can bite you.'' About a year ago, he related, he
treated an old skiing scar on the knee of Lauren Purcell, who was
then an editor at Mademoiselle, using a pulse dye laser to repair
the mark, a procedure that normally costs $300 to $800. He said
that Purcell promised to write about her free treatment, but never
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Bank said. ``It's part of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Purcell, now the articles editor at Self magazine, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Like hair colorists, fashion designers and chefs, more and more
doctors are seeking publicity to build their businesses. Freed of
legal constraints that prohibited them from advertising and faced
with shrinking incomes in the age of managed care, they are
aggressively marketing themselves as experts on beauty and health
in magazines like Vogue, Harper's Bazaar, Elle, Self and Good
Housekeeping and on television shows like ``Today,'' where they
reach millions who are willing to pay for elective medical
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   But where does this leave the interests of readers and viewers?
Are they receiving accurate, unbiased information about medical
procedures that can profoundly affect their health and appearance?
Are magazines making household names of the best doctors _ or the
ones with the best publicists? Most pointedly, when journalists
accept free services from physicians, are they obligating
themselves to deliver favorable coverage, in effect serving as
shills?
</P>
<P>
   More than journalistic ethics are at stake. Every time a
doctor's name appears in a health or beauty article, a reader is
likely to take that as an endorsement and go under the knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, women make more decisions based on the
magazines than their doctor referrals or friends combined,'' said
Dr. Debra Jaliman, a Manhattan dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that accepting free treatment is
widespread at women's magazines, where most articles about the
booming fields of cosmetic surgery and dermatology appear, and that
it leads to mostly positive coverage. Dr. Patricia Wexler, a
much-quoted Manhanattan dermatologist who has achieved the
celebrity status to which Bank aspires (patients wait months to see
her), said: ``All the time I give free botox, collagen, chemical
peels to journalists who will write about it. They quote me as if I
were George Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Beraka, a Manhattan plastic surgeon, who also gets a
lot of press, said: ``Absolutely all the time, doctors give writers
free services to get them to write about it. Free face-lifts, even
that, sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laurie Polis, a dermatologist who directs the SoHo
Integrative Health Center, a sleek, Zen-theme clinic, said: ``I
feel strong-armed. I don't want to barter services for mentions,
but I can't bite the hand that feeds me.''
</P>
<P>
   Polis described how a contributing editor for More, a beauty and
fashion magazine for older women, recently had a free day of
treatments, including ``botox, a facial, a dermabrasion peel,'' and
met with the clinic's staff for free consultations. Shortly after,
Polis said, the reporter called and requested full-body laser
treatments with a Cool Touch laser, a new machine. ``My jaw was on
the floor,'' Polis said, adding that when she balked, the reporter
``threw a hissy fit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people are so entitled,'' she said. ``Laser
treatments are expensive, and what she wanted would have taken six
treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   The More writer, Lynn Schnurnberger, said that Polis had
promised her the laser treatments, then reneged. ``I was angry with
her because she offered me something and then didn't come
through,'' Schnurnberger said. Her day of beauty, she said,
consisted of a ``short, 20-minute dermabrasion peel'' and free
consultations; no botox or facial, as Polis maintains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with taking free services
as long as you say in your article it was free,'' the writer said.
She said she is still working on the article and expects it to run
next year.
</P>
<P>
   About receiving free treatments in the course of reporting,
mainstream journalistic practice is clear: it is a conflict of
interest for reporters and editors to accept products or services
of value from those they cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally unethical, and any journalist at a respectable
publication would be fired for it,'' said Judy Foreman, who writes
a health column for The Boston Globe. ``Anyone can't help but be
influenced by free treatment. Even for a moment, assuming they're
not, there's still the appearance of a conflict. The publications
should pay for services they want to write about.'' (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Even if reporters disclose that a treatment was free, something
rarely done, experts in medical ethics are skeptical that the
interests of the reader can be well served. ``Of course getting a
free service influences'' journalists, said George Annas, the
chairman of health law at the Boston University School of Public
Health. ``It's just as disingenuous and self-serving for them to
say otherwise as it is for doctors to say they aren't influenced by
the drug companies who hand out freebies.''
</P>
<P>
   But most women's magazines operate under different rules from
daily newspapers. Just as magazine fashion editors take gifts of
$1,000 Prada handbags or 25 percent discounts on Jimmy Choo shoes,
maintaining that it is a professional courtesy that does not
influence their decision about what to put in their pages, magazine
beauty editors and writers receive spa and medical treatments and
say the same thing. (The New York Times prohibits journalists from
accepting gifts from news sources.)
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Myers, editor in chief at Elle, said her magazine allows
its writers to accept free treatments related to articles they are
writing. ``I can see why it looks suspicious, but the proof is in
the piece,'' she said. ``We do not feel obligated to write
positively about a doctor, whether we paid or not.'' Cynthia Leive,
the editor in chief of Self, said her magazine had no clear-cut
policy on writers and editors accepting free treatments. ``We
grapple with this issue all the time,'' she said. Later she called
back and added, ``Of course this is against journalistic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Wells, the editor in chief of Allure, said her magazine
pays for any services it writes about. ``My policy is that we
always pay,'' Wells said. ``If someone is violating my policy, I'll
have to see it and deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of health and beauty articles in women's magazines know
that the same doctors' names appear over and over. These physicians
have often achieved their status because they have publicists who
send journalists mass mailings and sometimes set up meetings and
appointments for free treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the writers never visit the doctors' offices, they know
the physicians will interrupt appointments to return calls and
offer sound bites. But health experts say readers form an
inaccurate impression about these often-quoted doctors. ``Obviously
the average consumer thinks that when he reads Doctor X's name over
and over again in the magazines, he's the best,'' said Ross
Frazier, a spokesman for the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fierce appetite among some cosmetic surgeons and
dermatologists to have their names in the press. Foreman of The
Boston Globe said that at a conference last year of the American
Society of Plastic Surgery, where she sat on a panel, physicians
clamored to know how to get quoted and whether they should hire
publicists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't understand the difference between advertising and
journalism,'' she said. Foreman said most of what she writes about
is derived from research and scientific studies. She considers it
``a total turnoff'' if a doctor hires a publicist.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Behrman of Behrman Communications in New York, who
represents the often-quoted Dr. Helen S. Colen, a Park Avenue
plastic surgeon, said, ``It's so competitive out there that doctors
feel they have no choice but to hire a publicist to put them in
touch with the media.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's a fact: women are inclined to go check out
doctors they read about over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1982, when the Supreme Court upheld an order by the
Federal Trade Commission requiring the American Medical Association
to permit doctors to advertise, the association's policy has been
neither to encourage nor to discourage medical advertising, said
Dr. Herbert Rakatansky, the chairman of its council on ethical and
judicial affairs. Hiring publicists to get exposure for services
they offer is tantamount to advertising, he said. Doctors are now
subject to false advertising and fraud claims under consumer laws,
and their ads must be truthful, he added.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the procedures that doctors discuss in the press
are accepted practice, some treatments have no scientific backing
or are too new to have a history.
</P>
<P>
   ``No consumer should ever take the word of a doctor they read in
the magazines,'' said Dr. David J. Goldberg, a dermatologist and a
former president of the American Society for Laser Medicine and
Surgery. ``My clinic is one of a handful in the country that does
all the major testing for the government, but my name almost never
gets quoted. Why? Because I don't spend the money to get my name in
the magazines.'' (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
