<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKETING-DOCTORS-ART     06-30 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETING-DOCTORS-ART-$ADV02-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: the magazines.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Joann Moroz, 62, a nurse who lives in Briarcliff, N.Y., said
she went to Bank, the Mount Kisco dermatologist, for laser eye
surgery last October after seeing his name in magazines and on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Using an erbium laser, he operated on her to remove crow's feet,
but her face never healed properly, she said, and she had ``welts
and scars'' around her eyes. When she complained, Bank injected her
with cortisone, prescribed a scar-healing cream and assured her
things would be fine, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she was not satisfied and in January visited Dr. Roy
Geronemus, a Manhattan laser specialist, to seek treatment for the
scars.
</P>
<P>
   About Bank, Moroz said: ``It really infuriates me that I see his
name everywhere. I went to him because I thought he had to know
what he was doing: he's in every magazine in the country, he's on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Moroz said she had not complained to Bank but intended to seek
reimbursement of the $2,000 she said she had paid, plus the cost of
Geronemus' work.
</P>
<P>
   Geronemus said he would not comment on a patient under his care.
Bank also declined to comment about Moroz, citing patient
confidentiality. But he said: ``With any procedure there's always a
small number of patients who have complications. It doesn't
necessarily mean that anything was done wrong on the part of the
physician.'' Bank said he had been using the erbium laser to
perform eye surgery since 1992, and it's ``a routine procedure''
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be cautious about implying that there has been any
factual investigation here,'' he added. ``To report one person's
claim of a suboptimal result and to imply it is in any way the
physician's fault is thin at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors are disdainful of promoting themselves with
publicists. Dr. Vicki Levine, a physician in the dermatology
department at the New York University Medical Center, whose
specialty is laser surgery, frowns on the practice. ``It makes
medicine like haircutting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Duenwald, Harper's Bazaar's executive editor, said, ``I
wish the magazines would get together and ban all doctors who use
publicists.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikely. Last year, Dr. Thomas Romo, a Manhattan
plastic surgeon, enjoyed a coup when he was featured in long
articles in two magazines within months. Both articles chronicled
face-lifts Romo performed at less than his usual fee with the
understanding they would be written about.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Biddle Barrows, the former Mayflower Madam, received a
full lift for an article by James Servin in Harper's Bazaar in
February 1999. (She plans to write a book about her experience.)
Then, Marie Claire ran an article about a face-lift Romo performed
on a patient he found for the magazine. A financial arrangement
``that's appealing for both the doctor and the patient'' was made,
said Susan Yaeger, Romo's surgical consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler, the high-profile dermatologist, does not have a
publicist. But in her climb to the top she has always given free
treatments to journalists writing about her. ``I did a $2,500 peel
on a Ladies' Home Journal editor,'' she said. ``I did collagen in
Michael Musto's lips, and he wrote about it in The Voice. I did
Candace Bushnell's collagen for a story in Vogue. I did an acne
consultation for a piece by Rebecca Johnson at Vogue, and I gave
Simon Doonan a free consultation for a column he did in The
Observer.''
</P>
<P>
   Musto said that Wexler solicited him at The Village Voice in the
early '90s through a publicist. ``It was a pioneering thing then,''
he said. ``Collagen was just starting to be widespread. She
proposed it to a number of writers, and I was the only one who took
her up on it. I spoofed the whole thing, called it the Paris Lip.''
He also made the rare disclosure in print that he received the $400
treatment at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Doonan, who wrote about his consultation in The New York
Observer of May 8, referred to Wexler as ``dermatological royalty''
but did not mention that her $350 fee for an audience was waived.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who received free consultations from Wexler and two
other dermatologists for her November 1996 Vogue article, said that
receiving no-cost services ``in no way affects how I write about a
doctor.'' She added that Vogue, where she is a contributing editor,
generally does not publish negative accounts of treatments because
its focus is on ``celebrating this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Astley, Vogue's beauty director, confirmed that writers and
editors are often ``comped'' _ given complimentary services _
including more than $5,000 worth of cosmetic dentistry that Julia
Reed, a senior writer, received from Dr. Larry Rosenthal in the
course of profiling him in the November 1998 Vogue. But Astley
insisted this practice did not affect the objectivity of her
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel any obligation to report on services that may
have been comped and we don't think are good, whether it's as
simple as a manicure or more elaborate like a dermatological
peel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vogue doesn't run negative criticism of books or movies or
usually even of fashion collections or of beauty products or
services or professionals,'' she said. ``Our overall message is
very positive and upbeat. For us a negative review is simply to not
include it in the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   One detail that escaped Reed's glowing profile of Rosenthal, her
dentist: his license was suspended for six months in 1987,
according to the New York State division of professional licensing,
which would not disclose the reason. Rosenthal explained in an
article in The New York Times on Jan 31, 1999, that he had been
disciplined for misusing prescription forms to obtain sleeping and
diet pills, but he said another person had stolen the forms and
used them.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for a women's magazine article to criticize or even
question the treatments proffered free to writers. So rare that
Bank, the Mount Kisco dermatologist, was surprised when an article
in the April issue of Mirabella presented a dissenting view of his
hyperbaric oxygen treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Holly Millea, the writer, described being zipped
into a sleeping-bag device and flooded with oxygen for 45 minutes,
a procedure that Bank says slows aging, relieves migraines, fights
depression and helps with weight loss. Millea quoted two other
doctors who called the procedure clinically untested and suggested
it was, well, snake oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only time that has happened to me,'' Bank said,
adding that In Style did an article on the same treatment, and
``their writer liked it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
