<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARNES-MONEY0701-COX     06-30 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNES-MONEY0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor's wealth drops $2 million
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roy Barnes remains by far one of Georgia's wealthiest
governors. But since taking office, he has seen his personal
fortune dwindle by almost $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney and his wife, Marie, were worth $9.5 million at the
beginning of 1999. Now, the Barneses' net worth is reported at $7.7
million, according to personal financial disclosures and tax
returns released by his office Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The governor continued to post handsome earnings by most
standards _ more than $722,000 this year, much of it from
inestments. But it's far less than the nearly $2 million in income
he declared in tax returns last year.
</P>
<P>
   And the Barneses' paid about half the taxes in 1999 _ $227,685 _
that they paid for the year before taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes reported his personal assets _ including a list of
investments in his blind trust _ in advance of the July 1 deadline
for state-mandated disclosure for elected officials and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, an attorney representing the blind trust had
argued that listing the individual assets would undercut the
purpose of the trust _ namely to keep an official ``blinded'' to
his own investments so they can't color his decisions in office.
The attorney asked state officials for an opinion on how much the
governor had to disclose.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Thurbert Baker responded earlier this
month, ruling that a blind trust is not exempt from state reporting
requirements. Barnes, he said, would have to list the trust's
assets the same as if he managed ithimself.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes complied, providing a nearly inch-thick stack of
documents, with some of them _ state and federal income tax records
_ going beyond state disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures show a considerable personal wealth hit by
recent stock market fluctuations _ bank stocks, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The value of Barnes' largest single asset going into 1999,
Alabama National Bankcorp, plunged by almost 30 percent from the
year. The trust, which held nine bank stocks and securities,
dropped in value from about $7 million when the governor
established it upon taking office, to about $5.8 million at the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the first time Barnes' personal wealth has fluctuated.
While running for governor in 1998, Barnes reported a net worth
approaching $11 million, which also was influenced by bank stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   A review of the trust's assets shows Barnes is still invested in
bank stocks, Alabama National Bankcorp and at least three others.
</P>
<P>
   But the Atlanta attorney managing Barnes' trust apparently has
opted for a more conservative strategy, buying an undisclosed
amount of state and local municipal bonds, according to the
disclosure. The trust holds at least 15 bonds, including some
issued by the state of Georgia. All are valued over $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also continues to hold in trust 10 real estate properties
in his home county of Cobb, three of them with other investment
partners.
</P>
<P>
   His income tax records show more than $476,000 in income poured
into the trust during 1999, most of it in legal fees from cases
before he took office.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes reported nearly $111,500 in income from a partial year's
salary as governor. In addition to the rental and office
properties, he and his wife own a home and 13 acres in Mableton
valued at $400,000. They have retirement accounts worth $1.3
million. Both of those assets are held outside the trust.
</P>
<P>
   Their only financial liability is a $19,362 mortgage on their
home.
</P>
<P>
   Income tax returns show the Barneses gave $55,373 to charities
last year, most of it to their Methodist church in Cobb County, and
to education funds.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' chief of staff, Bobby Kahn, said that despite questions
over the blind trust disclosure, the governor has no plans to push
for a change in state law to exempt him from the state ethics in
government act. Kahn said Barnes has no plans to dissolve the blind
trust.
</P>
<P>
   While the head of Georgia Common Cause had argued against
Barnes' disclosure of his trust assets, Robert Pregulman, program
director for the Georgia Public Interest Research Group, applauded
the move Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know more about where our political leaders have their
money invested,'' he said, ``you have a better chance to watchdog
them to be sure they do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
