<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-LAB-SECURITY-370     06-30 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-LAB-SECURITY-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO END UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA'S SECURITY ROLE AT 2 NUCLEAR
LABS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson announced Friday
that he planned to strip the University of California of its
responsibility for security at Los Alamos and Lawrence Livermore
national laboratories in the aftermath of a series of major
security lapses at the troubled Los Alamos laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California, which has held the government
contract to manage Los Alamos since the laboratory opened during
World War II to develop the atomic bomb, will continue to run the
scientific and research aspects of both Los Alamos and Lawrence
Livermore.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson said he would immediately seek to renegotiate the
university contract and would find a different organization to
handle security and facilities management at the two laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of California's performance in managing
security at our weapons laboratories is unacceptable and must be
immediately addressed,'' Richardson said Friday. ``Safeguarding
security at our nation's weapons laboratories warrants nothing
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he has asked Gen. John A. Gordon, the director
of the National Nuclear Security Administration, the new,
semi-independent agency that oversees the government's nuclear
weapons facilities, to handle the contract renegotiations with the
University of California and to recommend a new organization to
handle lab security by Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding an effective way to improve the security and
management at the laboratories without compromising the strength of
their cutting-edge science and research will be one of my top
priorities,'' Gordon said in a statement Friday. Gordon met with
the provost of the University of California on Thursday to inform
him of the decision to change the management of lab security.
</P>
<P>
   University of California president Richard C. Atkinson offered
only a cautious statement in response to Richardson's actions.
``The U.S. Department of Energy has advised us that it will explore
ways in which additional expertise might help address security
issues,'' he said, adding:``The University welcomes the opportunity
to work with DOE in this effort and to create a path forward that
meets all security needs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The University of California's contract to manage the two
weapons labs has been under scrutiny since last year, following the
Wen Ho Lee case. Lee was fired from Los Alamos in March 1999 for
security violations uncovered in connection with the government's
investigation of allegations of Chinese espionage at the lab. After
he was fired, investigators discovered that he had downloaded vast
amounts of secret nuclear data from the classified computer network
at Los Alamos and copied it onto portable tapes, some of which are
now missing. He was arrested in December on charges of mishandling
classified material. He has not been charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the University of California's management has
increased over the past month following the discovery that computer
hard drives containing nuclear secrets had disappeared from a vault
at the Los Alamos lab. The two hard drives were found by a lab
employee, but the FBI is now conducting a criminal investigation at
the lab to determine who removed them.
</P>
<P>
   Lax security at Los Alamos has become a major issue in Congress,
and lawmakers have repeatedly questioned Richardson about whether
he would hold the University of California accountable and end its
long hold on the lab contract.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the University of California's status as lab
contractor has also raised broader issues about the inherent
conflict between science and security in weapons development.
Scientists at the national weapons labs believe strongly that an
open exchange of ideas is needed to achieve the best science, even
in the national security area. The scientists cherish the notion
that one of America's premier universities manages the labs,
fostering an academic environment. But to protect U.S. military
advantages, the government wants to keep secret the advances
achieved at the weapons labs. The result is an endless tug of war
between the scientists and security and counter-intelligence
officials that dates back to the wartime Manhattan Project.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California's contract does not expire until
2002, but Richardson said in an interview today that the security
crisis at Los Alamos has convinced him that he must renegotiate the
agreement now, and has already decided to take security matters
away from the university. ``We want to keep UC's assets, basically
providing a good environment for science, and get rid of their
liabilities, basically security,'' Richardson said. ``There is no
reason why we should keep their weak management and security
components.''
</P>
<P>
   While UC runs both Los Alamos and Lawrence-Livermore, Sandia,
the nation's third nuclear weapons lab, is managed by Lockheed
Martin Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
