<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-CUBA-$ADV02-COX     06-30 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LATEST ASSAULT ON EMBARGO AGAINST CUBA HAS ANTI-CASTRO LOBBY ON
DEFENSIVE
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV02.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Moments before boarding the chartered jet that
would whisk him and his son Elian back to their Cuban homeland last
Wednesday, Juan Miguel Gonzalez faced the microphones and cameras
to bid the United States a heartfelt farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has allowed me to meet very beautiful and brilliant
people in this country,'' he said of the weeks he had spent here
working for Elian's return. ``And I hope in the future, this same
impression I took from this country can become true between Cuba
and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He may soon get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Elian left, House Republicans hammered out a
proposal for easing four decades of Cold War sanctions against
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, slated to be taken up by the House of
Representatives and the Senate toward mid-July, would permit the
export of American farm products to Cuba and expand sales of U.S.
medicine there.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's sponsor, Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., sees
it as the first step toward gradually ending the crippling economic
embargo, and eventually tearing away the estrangement, that divides
the United States and its impoverished neighbor 90 miles away
across the Florida Strait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first brick out of the wall,'' Nethercutt said in a
telephone interview with Cox Newspapers. ``It is a finger out of
the dike, and the water's coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   More holes could soon come unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   There are two other bills pending before Congress aimed at
overhauling U.S. policy meant to isolate the island nation and
strangle the repressive regime of its Communist leader Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   That approach, critics contend, has failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a policy that hasn't worked for 40 years,'' said Rep.
Marshall Sanford, R-S.C., who introduced a bill last May to end
U.S. restrictions on travel to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to re-evaluate,'' said Mark Seigel,
spokesman for Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., author of a bill to end the
U.S. embargo against Cuba. ``Cubans, 11 million people, are no
better off today than they were 40 years ago when the embargo took
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight Eisenhower imposed an economic embargo on Cuba
in 1960, after Castro set up a totalitarian dictatorship in Havana,
seized American-owned farms and refineries across Cuba as part of
his self-styled Marxist revolution, banned religious activities and
political dissent and cozied up to the Soviet Union, the arch-foe
of U.S. interests at the time.
</P>
<P>
   One of Eisenhower's final acts in office was to break diplomatic
ties with Cuba in January 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, President John F. Kennedy tightened the
embargo, and later prohibited U.S. travel to Cuba, forbade American
banks to finance Cuban undertakings and froze Cuban-owned assets in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   It was the right policy for its time, contends Julia Sweig,
deputy director of Latin American programs with the Council on
Foreign Relations, a New York-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``On strategic grounds, you can make the case that we won,''
said Sweig. ``Our foreign policy goals during the Cold War, of
reigning Cuba in and keeping the Soviet Union out of this
hemisphere, have been achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   The secondary objective _ bringing down Castro _ is a different
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has that succeeded? Evidently not,'' said Sweig. ``Has it
succeeded in giving the Cuban people a reason to withdraw what
support they do give to Castro? No. Have we had the Velvet
Revolution there? No. It's pretty hard, in terms of evidence, to
say that it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, U.S. policy toward Cuba has become an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   A hallmark of President Clinton's foreign policy, after all, has
been a commitment to engagement, the notion that U.S. trade and
investment, exposure to American practices and ideas, could be
strong engines for change in places like China, Russia, Vietnam
and, as of early June, even North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's instincts, he said last week, are to reach out to Cuba
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I think that anything we can do to engage the Cuban
people, to get them involved in the process of change, to get them
to look outside the world, to get them to look beyond the present
system they have, is a positive thing to do,'' he said at a White
House news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1996, in fact, Clinton was trying to do just
that, by gradually widening provisions for American academicians,
journalists, athletes and others to visit Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The thaw ended abruptly, though, in February 1996, when Castro
ordered Cuban MiG fighters to shoot down two unarmed civilian
airplanes owned by the Miami-based Cuban exile group Brothers to
the Rescue. As they neared Cuban air space on a mission to drop
anti-Castro leaflets over Havana, the planes were destroyed. Three
Cuban-Americans and one Cuban national were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deliberate decision to murder those people changed
everything,'' said Clinton. ``And it made me wonder whether Mr.
Castro was hoping we never would normalize relations, so then he
could use us as an excuse for the failures of his regime.''
</P>
<P>
   The embargo has powerful supporters in this country as well,
including Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms,
R-N.C. He joined with Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., in 1996 to pen
legislation that elevated the embargo from a presidential order to
a federal law. Clinton signed it three weeks after Cuba downed the
Cessnas.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ending or easing the embargo requires an act of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many members of Congress have deferred to colleagues
of Cuban origin or descent _ such as Florida Reps. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, both Republicans _ to take
the lead in formulating U.S.-Cuba policy. With the strong backing
of the country's most powerful anti-Castro lobby, the Miami-based
Cuban American National Foundation (CANF), these members have
sustained the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing a lot,'' said CANF executive vice president Dennis
Hays, who insists that retaining the embargo maintains pressure on
Castro. Easing it, he said, would only provide access to resources
that could strengthen him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with the regime is counter-productive for our
purposes,'' Hays said, ``and for the cause of allowing the Cubans
to form a normal government.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Cuban-Americans support the embargo, however, and few
strategic analysts think it serves the best interests of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no question that it should end, in terms of a
rational view of the situation,'' said Montclair, N.J., historian
Jane Franklin, author of Cuba and the United States: a
chronological history.
</P>
<P>
   Said Franklin, ``You just can't keep holding American policy
toward Cuba hostage to the most right wing of the Cuban-American
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-month saga of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez has done
something no policy wonk has yet managed to pull off. It has put
U.S. policy toward Cuba on the radar screen for a lot of Americans
_ and their Congressional representatives _ who paid little
attention up to now.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Nethercutt, is creating a congressional consensus for
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's put a human face on Cuba,'' Nethercutt said, ``a face
other than a bearded one.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdens(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.canf.org
</P>
<P>
   www.house.gov/nethercutt
</P>
<P>
   www.cfr.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-US-CUBA-$ADV02-COX     06-30 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
