</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-H&AMP;R-BLOCK-$ADV02-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW QUESTIONS ABOUT BLOCK'S LUCRATIVE TAX LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Texas, Mo.,   Ill.)   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The carefully constructed image of H &UR;  &LR; &AMP; &UR;  &LR; R Block as America's
trusted tax preparer was marred a decade ago, when consumer
advocates accused the company of marketing advances on customers'
tax refunds at usurious interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said flat fees for the two-week loans disguised annual
rates as high as 250 percent. Plaintiffs' lawyers filed a host of
class action lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Block is on the verge of resolving the litigation this month
without admitting any wrongdoing. But critics of the proposed
settlement call it a sham, saying Block has effectively hired
lawyers to sue it on the company's own _ extremely favorable _
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The court proceedings have brought to light details of Block's
business practices that the supreme courts of two states, and other
judges, found sufficiently egregious to warrant trials on whether
the company had betrayed its clients' trust.
</P>
<P>
   A Maryland state judge, for example, found that Block
deliberately confused customers by training its tax preparers to
never use the word loan and instead to sell ``two-day refunds.''
Company documents and testimony by Block officials in various
lawsuits show that Block, whose 9,000 offices prepare one in seven
income tax returns each year, was far more deeply engaged in the
high-cost loan business than its customers or even its critics
realized.
</P>
<P>
   Block, for example, has always emphasized that rather than make
the loans itself, it helps customers obtain them from lenders _ now
exclusively Household Bank, and before that mainly Beneficial
Finance, which Household's parent company bought last year. Federal
law prohibits income tax preparers from making loans to customers,
a rule intended to prevent collusion between taxpayers and tax
preparers.
</P>
<P>
   But the court records show that Block since 1992 has had an
ownership interest in the loans; last year, it retained a
49.9999999 percent interest _ ownership, in other words, of just
one penny shy of half of every $10 million in loan profits. By
holding less than a 50 percent interest in the loans, Block
complies with the anti-collusion rules.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers say that stake, which was not disclosed to
customers until earlier this year _ when Block began acknowledging
an unspecified interest in the loans _ may explain why the company
did not solicit bids for lower rates on its clients' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the costs increased starting in the 1995 tax year, when
the Internal Revenue Service, worried about fraud tied to refund
loans, suspended its system of providing early notification to
lenders on whether it would honor a taxpayer's refund request. That
increased the risk of unpaid loans, Block says, forcing the company
to raise fees to as high as $89, from what had been as little as
$29, depending on the size of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Effectively, that increased the interest rate on many refund
advances to more than 500 percent on an annualized basis _ roughly
what Mafia loan sharks in New York charge their best customers,
according to a senior official in the New York Police Department.
In some cases, processing delays raised the effective cost of loans
to as much as 1,500 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with the IRS again providing early indications on
refunds, Block says that loan fees were cut by 40 percent over all,
and that it experimented in a few areas with no-fee loans.
</P>
<P>
   The court records show some customers receive their loan
proceeds only a few days faster than if they had waited for the IRS
to deposit the money directly into a checking account _ at no
charge.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the lawsuits, Jenny Lillis, a Block executive who at
the time was in charge of placing advertising, testified in 1995
that ``it's the client's choice, any individual's choice, to spend
whatever amount of money they want in order to get their refund
money back from the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides its undisclosed half-interest in the loans, Block also
secretly collected fees from its banking partners on each loan,
according to the court records, beginning at $3 in 1989 and rising
to $9 by 1997. That year, the company began disclosing the $9 fee
in fine print, after a Texas court ruled that the banks' payments
to Block, if hidden, could violate the state's commercial bribery
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   The refund loans produced 8 percent of Block's total profits
last year, their peak contribution in the three years that the
company has broken out such results. Block, based in Kansas City,
Mo., reported net income of $19.1 million from the loans _ a profit
margin of 21.1 percent. Refund loans accounted for 3.5 percent of
1998 profits and 5.5 percent of 1997 profits.
</P>
<P>
   Block says it always acted properly in arranging the refund
anticipation loans. Clients, many of them repeat borrowers, have
taken out 30 million of the loans since 1989 _ proof, the company
says, of customer satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The court cases, the company added in a statement, ``are
typically driven by a small group of aggressive lawyers, not by
dissatisfied customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Block has defended itself aggressively, too, and the company
has never lost a lawsuit over the loans.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, its chief litigator, N. Louise Ellingsworth of the
Bryan Cave law firm in St. Louis, obtained court orders barring
lawyers in one case from sharing knowledge with the lawyers in
other cases, which meant long delays as testimony was taken and
re-taken from the same Block and Household executives.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ellingsworth and a spokesman for her law firm repeatedly
declined to comment on any aspect of the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, efforts began to settle the litigation _ but
not with the lawyers who had been in hot pursuit of the company.
</P>
<P>
   That month, testimony shows, lawyers for Beneficial met with
three Chicago area attorneys, one of whom was suing the lender over
refund advances it made for clients of Jackson Hewitt Tax Services,
a Block competitor that was subsequently acquired by the Cendant
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, these lawyers filed two new lawsuits, one
against Beneficial and Block, the other against only Beneficial.
The cases against Beneficial went nowhere, and in January 1999,
Block's lawyers persuaded Judge William B. Zagel of the U.S.
District Court in Chicago to dismiss the suit against it.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, though, Block and Beneficial resumed talks with the
Chicago lawyers. None of the lawyers on either side would say what
prompted the conversations, but they occurred soon after a series
of decisions against Block.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important were rulings by the supreme courts of
Maryland and Texas that loan customers' claims could be tried as
class actions. Ellingsworth had argued that each customer should
have to sue Block individually _ a procedure that would have
discouraged lawyers from pursuing the cases, because filing fees
alone would exceed the damages that could be recovered by any one
customer.
</P>
<P>
   A New York judge ruled that Ellingsworth had engaged in
``patently deceptive'' and manipulative conduct that obstructed
judicial proceedings. Block's lawyers had to pay almost $41,000 in
damages to lawyers suing the company for time they spent fighting
this conduct; later, a New York appeals court barred Ellingsworth
and a colleague from representing Block in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Ellingsworth argued that she had always acted in good
faith and that the actions that offended the New York judges were
Block's, not hers. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   By last July, Block and Beneficial had reached agreement with
the Chicago lawyers on the outlines of a settlement intended to
resolve the refund loan cases around the country. One of the
plaintiff's lawyers, Daniel Harris, agreed to revise his pending
case to serve as the vehicle for the agreement _ though Block,
which had been dismissed from that suit, had to ask the court to
reinstate it as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Harris sent a copy of his draft to Ellingsworth. She
faxed him a response, saying she would be making her revisions in
red ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me as out of line for her to do that,'' said Harris,
who described the sequence of events as ``kind of weird.''
Nonetheless, he said, he adopted some of his adversary's changes _
though Ellingsworth, he added, complained that he had not
incorporated them all.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Zagel gave preliminary approval to the
settlement. In February, he issued an order freezing all the other
cases around the country, several of which were about to go to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, Block and Household each have
agreed to put up half of a $25 million fund that would pay $15 to
each individual or married couple who took out a refund loan, so
long as no more than 1.67 million claims were filed. If there were
more claims, the size of each payment would be reduced. Any
unclaimed money would revert to Block and Household.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than one million claims have been filed, though
lawyers critical of the settlement say the number would be greater
if the window for filing claims was not restricted to a period when
most people are not thinking about taxes: from April 17, the last
day of the most recent tax filing season, till Dec. 17, which is
before the next season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Block and Household also agreed to pay a total of $4.25 million
to Harris and the three other law firms that ultimately negotiated
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Zagel has scheduled a hearing for July 11 to hear objections to
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Of the lawyers with suits pending against Block, at least 13 are
opposing the settlement, arguing that the company had essentially
hired counsel to sue on the terms it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kirby, a New York lawyer with cases pending against Block
in Brooklyn and Manhattan, said the company ``held a silent auction
with only one bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward M. Carstarphen, a Houston lawyer with a class action case
awaiting trial in Texas, said that under the state's commercial
bribery laws, Block was at risk for $1.2 billion in his case alone.
Block lawyers dismiss such figures as wild fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   John C. Coffee, a Columbia University law professor retained as
an expert by the lawyers opposing the settlement, calls the
proposed deal ``pathologically flawed'' and contrary to two recent
U.S. Supreme Court rulings on fairness in class action settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee, in an affidavit, said that since Block had won dismissal
of an earlier lawsuit brought by Harris' three co-counsels, those
lawyers were not hired guns representing clients but instead had
been ``disarmed to the point that they resembled pacifists.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagel has said he sees no merit in Coffee's argument.
</P>
<P>
   Household Bank, in court papers, has said that the proposed
settlement resulted from ``extensive and difficult arms-length
negotiations that spanned nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These protracted negotiations, conducted in utmost good faith,
entailed considerable give-and-take on both sides,'' said the bank,
a unit of Household International of Chicago, ``and ultimately
yielded a settlement that confers a substantial benefit on the
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Block, in a statement, said the settlement is a good deal both
for its shareholders and its refund anticipation loan customers,
because it ``will include all RAL customers, end all current RAL
litigation and discourage future litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Harris, the Chicago lawyer, twice refused to be
interviewed about his discussions with the company's lawyers. ``I
have to ask Block,'' he explained each time. Then Harris called a
reporter back and said he wanted to be interviewed about the
reasons that the settlement ``is a good deal'' for refund loan
customers, given ``how weak the claims are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This litigation has been going on for years, and it has not
been very successful,'' Harris noted.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client, DeCarlo Turner, a municipal worker in
Dolton, Ill., was wronged when she was told that a refund loan
would cost $29 and Beneficial later tacked on a $20 paperwork fee
at the loan closing. ``It was a bait-and-switch,'' Harris said. But
he added that it was unclear how many people were damaged in this
way and if they could be identified _ which made pursuing a class
action case problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, he said, was it clear that Block had done anything wrong by
collecting fees from the banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it illegal for Beneficial to pay Block a portion of the
finance charge?'' Harris said. ``Is that a kickback? That
depends.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.S)
</P>
<P>
   As for other lawyers who pressed the argument, ``it was an issue
that was frequently, often, generally, lost, because it is about a
relationship between Block and its customers,'' he asserted. ``It
is not a lawyer-client matter that is a fiduciary relationship as a
matter of law, so trying to prove that on a classwide basis would
be kind of impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said there were other weaknesses in the plaintiffs'
cases, too, including questions about whether some cases were too
old to be eligible for recompense. But he acknowledged that until
Beneficial initiated the settlement discussions, he had not
questioned anyone under oath about the refund loans and had not
examined any internal bank documents.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The settlement of the lawsuits over refund advances would come
as Block is trying to transform itself into a full-service
financial company selling investment advice, retirement plans and
accounting to the mainly working-class and middle-class Americans
who are the prime market for its tax preparation services.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Block acquired Olde Financial, a brokerage firm,
along with a mortgage company and the nation's seventh-largest
accounting firm. The company's chairman and co-founder, Henry W.
Bloch, 77, plans to retire in September; active leadership of the
company is scheduled to fall to its president, Mark A. Ernst, a
former American Express executive who has championed the
full-service strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The refund loan business, Block has said in securities filings
and court papers, is aimed at low-income people. While Block and
its banking partners describe the loans as a benefit to their
customers, an internal memo filed in court showed that at
Beneficial, at least, there had been debate about the propriety of
the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Kuntz, who at the time worked for Beneficial, recounted
in the 1995 memo how she had dressed down a colleague for
describing the refund anticipation loan clients as ``one step above
pond scum.'' The true picture, she wrote, was of a person ``one
step away from financial disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire concept of this RAL program is appealing to the
poor, the destitute and the desperate,'' Kuntz wrote. ``Even the
most desperate customers I have interviewed have expressed dismay
at the prices'' charged for the loans, ``but they have resignedly
acquiesced because of their financial plight.''
</P>
<P>
   Household Bank said it had no comment on the memo.
</P>
<P>
   Kuntz wrote that the ``average fiscally sound person'' would not
take out a high-interest loan to get his own money back from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The refund loan business depends on people ignoring a truism of
financial planning: Avoid tax refunds, because they represent
interest-free loans to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Documents in the court records show that when President George
Bush lowered payroll withholding rates in 1992, Block contacted its
refund loan customers to show them how to increase their
withholding back to the old levels. Linda MacDougall, a Block
spokeswoman, explained that many customers want large refunds,
regarding them not as a lost opportunity to use their money sooner,
but as ``their annual bonus check'' from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Lillis, the Block advertising executive, testified in one of the
lawsuits that Block's research found that many customers judged the
company's competence by the size of their refund.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Block has continued looking for ways to increase profits from
its refund loan customers.
</P>
<P>
   This year Block began its Refund Rewards program, offering a
prepaid Mastercard to customers due tax refunds. Refund Rewards
also offers discounts on automobiles, air travel and other goods
and services that MacDougall, the Block spokeswoman, described as
``valuable benefits'' to help people stretch their tax refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Like debit cards, the prepaid charge cards allow customers to
draw down their refund loan proceeds as they make purchases. But if
the balance slips below $50 for 60 days, Block closes the account
and refunds the balance _ after deducting a $19.95 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer Federation of
America, a nonprofit advocacy group in Washington, said the prepaid
card was a bad deal and appeared to be designed to create status
for people who could not otherwise qualify for a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be far more sensible for taxpayers to take the refund
and deposit it in a checking or savings account,'' he said, ``than
to let Block earn interest on their money.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-FLAGSIDE0701-COX     06-30 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAGSIDE0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big wave of flag sales arises from South Carolina debate
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORDVILLE, Ga. _ Soren Dresch's home-based company is to the
flag business what L.L. Bean is to polo shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Need a skull and crossbones? Use your credit card and order it
from the Ruffin Flag Company catalog. You'll find the rising sun of
Japan, the red maple leaf of Canada, the Red Cross, the St. Andrews
Cross, the flag of every U.N. nation, the flag of every state.
</P>
<P>
   Even South Carolina has called.
</P>
<P>
   Today, South Carolina will remove the controversial Rebel flag
from its Statehouse dome and raise a square version at the
Confederate Soldiers Monument in front of the capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Both heavy cotton banners are stitched by Ruffin seamstresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in a position to make the type of Confederate flag
in the time we needed,'' said Michael Sponhour, spokesman for the
South Carolina Budget and Control Board, the state agency
responsible for coordinating today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only could they supply what we needed,'' Sponhour said,
``but they had the best price.''
</P>
<P>
   Dresch, 36, sold South Carolina 50 square battle flags for $30
each. The next lowest bidder offered flags for $71 each.
</P>
<P>
   Dresch started the company a decade ago, ultimately moving it to
this rural town an hour west of Augusta, Ga. He named the company
for Edmund Ruffin, the man thought to have fired the first shot of
the Civil War at Fort Sumter off the coast of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Apostolic Lutheran seamstresses in Michigan and
Wisconsin comprise the backbone of the company's staff. They piece
together premium, custom-ordered flags in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not exactly like the Amish, but they're good with
sewing machines,'' said Dresch, an Ohio native. Because Ruffin is a
mail-order outfit, Dresch could run the business from anywhere. He
wanted a small-town location near metro Atlanta and found two
houses for sale in Crawfordville.
</P>
<P>
   It is only happenstance, Dresch said, that the business is
located across the street from the A. H. Stephens State Park, named
for a former Georgia governor _ and the vice president of the
Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know who Stephens was,'' said Dresch.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's enduring flag controversy has caused a boom at
Ruffin, run out of a 1,400-square-foot cottage with wooden floors
and a tin roof. Four rooms are cluttered with flags, license
plates, key chains, ties and Confederate coffee packaged with the
slogan, ``The Taste That Secedes.'' Outside, Confederate flags
flutter on the porch and on two poles outside.
</P>
<P>
   The family business barely can keep in stock 3-foot-by-5-foot
Confederate naval jacks, familiar rectangular banners with a blood
red background and a sea blue ``X'' marked by 13 white stars _ one
for each state of the Confederacy. Dresch estimates he's lost
nearly $10,000 in sales because they can't make enough battle
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently, the demand has kept us stressed out,'' said Dresch,
a communications and advertising graduate from the University of
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin made 5,000 battle flags at the beginning of May, selling
them all in about a month. The company made 10,000 more and has
rushed out more than a thousand of them to market.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Ruffin has supplied Confederate battle flags to
members of the South Carolina General Assembly, who sell the flags
to the general public. Legislators stopped taking orders in May.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Dresch has backed yellow Penske rental trucks up to
the granite South Carolina state house and delivered boxes upon
boxes of flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants one because of the South Carolina situation,''
Dresch said. ``Whenever you drive off the interstate (in South
Carolina) or go on a state highway, you see them everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Dresch is concerned the Rebel flag uproar has pigeon-holed his
company as a Dixie-only company. To broaden Ruffin's image, he's
promoting the company through an additional Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Dresch's clients include Jamaica, which ordered flags for a new
international airport on the island, and the Vermont Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the Elian Gonzalez saga, a Miami flag dealer
called and wanted 100,000 Cuban banners made in a week _ a demand
Ruffin just couldn't meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just so unrealistic,'' Dresch said.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, black lawmakers have asked Dresch to reproduce the
Peach State's flag from before 1956, the year the Legislature added
the Confederate battle emblem to the state banner. Friends who
support Georgia's Rebel insignia have asked Dresch not to make the
pre-1956 version.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be hypocritical if I didn't make it,'' said Dresch.
``We're a flag business. We're not a political entity. If I
attached a political significance to everything, I wouldn't make
anything and I'd be out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
