<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-SPINOFF-1STLD-WR     06-30 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-SPINOFF-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T MAY SPIN OFF ITS LONG-DISTANCE UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes ``44 cents'' to ``31 cents'' in 3rd graf. Changes
``$27.02'' to ``$33'' in 7th graf, which begins ``In recent years
...'') 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is considering spinning off its long-distance telephone
operation, the largest in the United States, as a separately traded
tracking stock, people close to the company said this week.
</P>
<P>
   No such plan has yet been presented to AT&AMP;T's board by its
management, the people said. AT&AMP;T declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   One reason AT&AMP;T may want to issue a new stock to track the
long-distance unit is that the shares have languished recently.
Shares of AT&AMP;T hit a new 52-week low during trading Friday and
closed at $31.8125, down 31 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company's management is eager to bolster the stock price and
may believe that issuing a new stock could boost AT&AMP;T's share
price.
</P>
<P>
   If the shrinking consumer long-distance unit were made separate,
the remainder of the company would show faster growth. Those
remaining units would include the operation that sells
communication services, as well as data services, to business
customers, and AT&AMP;T's cable television operation, the largest in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's consumer long-distance operation generates about $20
billion a year in revenue, but is shrinking. In the first quarter,
that unit reported $5.1 billion in revenue, down 5.6 percent from
the comparable period of 1999. The consumer long-distance business
is shrinking, because many other companies compete against AT&AMP;T in
the long-distance business and prices have come down quickly in
that market.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many companies have offered new shares that are
meant to track the performance of specific units in those
companies. Tracking stocks do not, however, represent any actual
economic interest in the unit that they represent. In April, AT&AMP;T
offered new shares meant to track the performance of its
fast-growing wireless business. Those shares of AT&AMP;T Wireless Group
were offered to the public at $29.50 on April 27 and closed Friday
at $33.
</P>
<P>
   Companies generally offer tracking stocks for their units that
are growing quickly. Because AT&AMP;T's consumer long-distance unit is
shrinking, however, it is unclear what investors would be willing
to pay for such a stock.
</P>
<P>
   While it is shrinking, AT&AMP;T's consumer long-distance unit does
generate a lot of cash for the company. In the first quarter, that
unit generated $2 billion in earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization, up 4 percent from the comparable
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people own AT&AMP;T's stock, making it one of the most
widely held in the nation. For decades, AT&AMP;T enjoyed a monopoly in
the long-distance telephone industry, but that monopoly began to
crumble under assault from the government and from competitors like
MCI in the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Since the old American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. was broken up
in 1984, the remaining long-distance company has lost share in the
long-distance market every year. It has been very hard for AT&AMP;T to
compete against smaller companies that have lower costs, according
to analysts and industry experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
