<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNDERWRITING-ART-NYT &LR;      06-30 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERWRITING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND QUARTER SEES SLOWDOWN FOR BUSINESSES RAISING CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Wall Street, the second quarter roared in like a
wildfire then fizzled to a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp downturn in the Nasdaq stock market in April doused the
market for new issues of stock that had been strong in the first
quarter. By late June, dozens of companies had shelved plans to go
public, and some that tested the market were sorely disappointed.
Rising interest rates depressed the market for all sorts of new
corporate bonds, especially those from companies with poor credit
ratings, which are known as junk bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount of money raised in the United States by
investment banks _ $451 billion _ was down 24 percent from the
second quarter of 1999. The total number of stock and bond
offerings in American markets fell to 3,823 in the second quarter
from 5,047 in the second quarter of 1999. Last quarter ranked
eighth in terms of amounts raised by quarter in the United States
capital markets, according to Thomson Financial/Securities Data in
Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The slump hit investment banks just as they were rushing to hire
new bankers, and raising pay and improving benefits to keep their
employees from leaving for Internet start-ups. Disclosed fees for
underwriting new issues sank about 45 percent, to $2.64 billion,
from $4.8 billion in the first quarter of 2000, and about 20
percent from $3.29 billion in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first quarter was as heady a market as we'd ever seen,''
said Jeff Edwards, co-manager of stock capital markets at Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. But after the stock market swooned in mid-April, he
said, ``there was a general pullback of all investors, retail and
institutional.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the newfound reluctance of investors to buy shares
of untested companies, underwriters managed to float some landmark
new issues. Most notable was the $10.6 billion spinoff of shares in
AT&AMP;T Wireless, the biggest initial offering by an American company.
</P>
<P>
   The $9 billion of that total raised in the United States
accounted for more than one-third of the $24.5 billion raised
through first-time stock offerings in the quarter, and it accounted
for the bulk of the initial offering proceeds raised by two of the
biggest investment banks, Merrill Lynch and the Salomon Smith
Barney unit of Citigroup. Each of those firms was a lead manager,
along with the Goldman Sachs Group, of the AT&AMP;T Wireless offering,
and received credit for one-third of the proceeds from the United
States, or about $3 billion. Aside from that deal, Merrill raised
about $900 million in initial offerings and Salomon raised about
$750 million, according to Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   An initial offering is the most lucrative type of underwriting,
leaving investment banks with as much as 7 percent of the money
raised from investors. Goldman Sachs again was the leading
underwriter of initial offerings and all issues of common stock,
commanding about 25 percent of the market so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman managed several huge offerings during the rockiest
period of the quarter in April, including the $4.6 billion initial
offering of the insurer MetLife and the $3 billion spinoff of the
T-Online subsidiary of Deutsche Telekom of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over the quarter, Mark Tercek, a managing director
of Goldman's stock underwriting business, said: ``While market
conditions were more difficult, we were still able to get a lot of
deals done for companies of all stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, investors are taking a more disciplined approach
than they were during the IPO frenzy that ran through much of last
year and into the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very ebullient, extraordinary period of time and it
largely is over,'' Tercek said.
</P>
<P>
   After a weak May, the market for new stock started to recover in
June and companies rushed back in to sell stock. Still, the market
for new stocks was significantly stronger than the market for debt
issued by corporations. As the Federal Reserve continued to raise
short-term interest rates, investors were wary to buy bonds,
especially those that mature in 10 years to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors showed a distinct aversion to risky bonds promising
high yields. There were only 66 junk-bond offerings in the quarter,
down almost two-thirds from 178 in the second quarter of 1999. They
raised just $7.5 billion, down from $32.2 billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual shutdown of the junk-bond market came at the worst
time for many young Internet companies that found that they could
not finance their growth plans either by issuing stock or by
borrowing in the public bond markets. That situation left some
Internet retailers and other electronic-commerce companies no
choice but to sell out or go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   For blue-chip companies, the borrowing was easier at the end of
the quarter, after the Labor Department's report on employment in
May eased fears of further rate increases by the Fed. After that
report hinted that the economy might be cooling, investors showed
more interest in high-grade corporate bonds that mature in 10 years
or more, said Randy Snook, managing director of corporate bond
underwriting at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the year has been unusual in that the amount of
short-term issuance has been quite high,'' Snook said. ``You can
count the number of 30-year bonds issued from corporations on two
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters were encouraged by the reception for a $9.5 billion
sale of bonds in the United States by Deutsche Telekom, which was
split almost evenly among 5-year, 10-year and 30-year notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not expecting an avalanche of activity,'' said Snook.
But, he said, ``We feel we have entered a period of much better
market conditions than we've had in much of the first and second
quarters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
