<SLUG> BC-GORE-LULAC-0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE FIRES UP LATINOS OVER CONFIRMATION FLAP
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore sought to shore up his
standing with Hispanic voters Friday night with a speech that
included subtle reminders of the Latino community's political
differences with the Republican leadership of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to one of the oldest Latino political organizations,
Gore stoked the anger of hundreds of Latino activists over the
GOP-controlled Senate's refusal to confirm Enrique Moreno, an El
Paso lawyer, to a federal judgeship in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to call upon the Congress to stop playing politics
with judicial nominations and confirm Enrique Moreno,'' Gore said
during the final proceedings of the national convention of the
League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a terrific nominee,'' Gore added. ``And I do not
understand the delay. I do not understand the excuses that are
offered.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton nominated Moreno to the 5th Circuit Court of
Appeals last September, but the nomination has languished in the
Senate. Texas's two Republican senators, Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchinson, have blocked the nomination, saying Moreno is too
inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   But LULAC National President Rick Dovalina, said Moreno ``could
not be more qualified.'' Moreno, a graduate of Harvard Law School,
has been in private practice since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Moreno judicial appointment was one of several issues Gore
mentioned that have driven Hispanic voters away from the Republican
Party since the 1994 GOP takeover of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited the GOP's past opposition to bilingual education,
federal hate crime legislation and the appointment of Bill Lann Lee
to head up the Justice Department's civil rights division.
</P>
<P>
   And in an apparent reference to anti-immigrant measures pushed
during Pete Wilson's term as governor of California, Gore said, ``I
also don't understand why some have been so vitriolic in their
discrimination against immigrants because I believe in an America
where we recognize our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   To further underscore his differences with the Republican
leadership of Congress, Gore brought with him Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson, who has been under fire on Capitol Hill for security
lapses at Los Alamos nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, the highest ranking Hispanic in the Clinton cabinet,
received a standing ovation as he arrived on stage to introduce
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, did not
mention his likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
But his criticism of the Republican leaders in Congress underscored
Bush's political dilemma of distancing his own brand of
``compassionate conservatism'' from the harsher, anti-immigrant
rhetoric that, until recently, has been a hallmark of the GOP
takeover of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's targeting of the GOP congressional leaders comes as polls
show Bush making inroads with Hispanic voters, a key voting bloc
for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has a wide lead over Bush among Hispanic voters,
the Texas governor is getting much more support than Republican
presidential candidates usually do.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a national poll of Hispanics this week by the
Knight Ridder news organization showed Gore leading 50 percent to
34 percent. But that was less than the 71 percent of Hispanic votes
Clinton got in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a survey released this week by Miami pollster Sergio
Bendixen showed Gore ahead among Hispanics by 22 percent
nationally, but showed Bush running ahead by 75 percent to 16
percent among Cuban Americans, who are concentrated in Florida and
New Jersey, two of the most important states in the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics make up only about 5 percent of the overall
electorate, but they have much bigger percentages of voters in the
four biggest states: California (13 percent), Texas (20 percent),
New York (9 percent) and Florida (12 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In California, the most populous state, recent polls have showed
Gore leading 2-1 among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush will be in California next week to address the
national convention of the National Council of La Raza, another
influential Hispanic organization.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
