<HEADLINE>
STOCKS DOWN SHARPLY IN 2ND QUARTER, LEAVING ALL INDEXES LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks plunged in the second quarter of the year,
leaving all the major indexes down for the first half as the
Federal Reserve continued to try to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index lost 13.3 percent in the quarter, its
first loss since the third quarter of 1998. The decline more than
wiped out its January-March advance and left it down 2.5 percent
for the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average declined 4.3 percent in the
second quarter and is now down 9.1 percent so far this year. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slumped 2.9 percent in the
quarter and closed out the first half down 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also decided that many high-tech and Internet shares
were overpriced and it was time to cash in some profits, sending
many issues plummeting. Amazon.com, the cyberspace retailer, closed
midyear at 36 5/16 after trading as high as 106 11/16 during the
Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly did deflate a good portion of the speculative
bubble called the Internet,'' said Ned Riley Jr., chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisers in Boston. ``A number of
investors finally recognized that there is risk in the risk-reward
equation.''
</P>
<P>
   But investment money has to go somewhere and this time the
beneficiaries tended to be drug and other health-care companies,
real estate investment trusts and utilities. Stocks of
semiconductor companies also climbed.
</P>
<P>
   And technology was not a one-way street. After hitting a record
5,048.62 late in the first quarter, March 10, the tech-dominated
Nasdaq composite fell as low as 3,164.55 on May 23 before
recovering to 4,064.01 on June 21 and then tailing off again. It
closed Friday at 3,966.11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve's 50 basis-point tightening was a bit of a
watershed,'' said Timothy M. Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager for
Dreyfus Corp., referring to a May 16 increase of a half percentage
point in the overnight lending rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In mid-May, things suddenly reversed'' in the stock market, he
added. ``Interest-rate sensitive stocks went out of favor and tech
came back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors shied away from fledgling companies, many of
them with no profits and scarcely any revenue. A flurry of 18
initial public offerings reached the market this week to lift the
quarter's total to 104, but this was far short of the 141 companies
that went public in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world changed,'' said Richard Peterson, market analyst at
Thomson Financial Securities Data, which tracks initial public
offerings, noting that 52 of the 104 deals were marketed at prices
below the range projected in their original filings. In the first
quarter 91 of these issues were priced above the filing range.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the quarter's biggest Nasdaq stars were technology
companies, led by Ixys Corp., a semiconductor company based in
Santa Clara, Calif. With a 3]-point surge Friday to 53], the stock
nearly quadrupled from its March 31 price of 13 9/16. Adept
Technology, up 6 11/16 Friday, ended the quarter at 46}, up from 12
on March 31. The biggest loser, excluding companies that filed for
bankruptcy, was Fidelity Holdings of New York, which lost 94
percent of its value, closing at 1\.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Keithley Instruments, which
makes electronic measuring equipments, soared 264 percent followed
by Lilly Industries, up 142 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Entrade, a Northfield, Ill., business-to-business Internet
company, plunged 77 percent, to 7 1/16. The Chyron Corp. Dynex
Capital also lost more than 70 percent of their market value.
</P>
<P>
   The average technology mutual fund fell about 13 percent during
the quarter, according to Christopher Traulsen, an analyst for
Morningstar. This contrasted with an 18 percent advance in the
first three months of 2000. Last year, the average tech fund soared
135 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some flight to quality, into bigger, steadier
companies'' within the technology stock group, Traulsen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
