<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NY     06-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: VOYEURISM FOR THE ENTIRE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Orwell was a loser.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend observes, if Orwell could really see into the
future, he would have registered Big Brother as a brand. He would
have known that the ominous specter he raised in ``1984'' would, by
2000, become a crowd-pleasing entertainment franchise.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Big Brother,'' the latest CBS exercise in ``reality''
television, debuts Wednesday night, right after the latest
installment of the unstoppable ``Survivor,'' millions of us will
delight in spying on 10 Americans trapped in a house for 90 days
with two bedrooms, one bathroom, 60 microphones and 28 video
cameras. Far from being the triumph of totalitarianism that Orwell
brooded about, ``Big Brother'' will be yet another slam-dunk for
capitalism. The estate of the man who coined the phrase might have
had a cash cow to rival the one that T.S. Eliot's heirs have found
in ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS paid some $20 million just to obtain the rights to the ``Big
Brother'' TV format from the Dutch entertainment company, Endemol,
that originated the show. The network knows it will see a still
bigger profit, for in 2000, voyeurism moves the goods.
``Survivor,'' whose sponsors include the U.S. Army (and therefore
the U.S. taxpayer), forced ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
to flee from a competing time slot and vanquished even the NBA
finals in the Nielsens. ``Big Brother,'' which is to air five
nights a week (and 24 hours a day on AOL), threatens to bring the
country to a standstill. As for those spoilsports who don't want to
play Peeping Tom, Leslie Moonves, CBS's president, has politely
suggested they just switch channels. And he's right _ this is a
free country. It seems downright patriotic that CBS should bring
America together in a shared affirmation of our freedom to peep (or
not to) on the night after the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, politicians and journalists loudly attacked their
local versions of ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' for sadistically
turning their players into cutthroat rats in a maze, especially
after one castaway voted off the island in the Swedish ``Survivor''
subsequently committed suicide. In America, no one cares how the
people on these shows are treated _ the only protest has been from
PETA over the ``unethical'' treatment of actual rats, which were
eaten on ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   There has also been some grumbling by press watchdogs, including
CBS's own Andy Rooney, that the network is blurring the line
between news and entertainment by using its morning newscaster as
the official voice of Big Brother and by stuffing its news shows
with interviews of ``Survivor'' survivees. But it seems laughable
to single out CBS when, as Howard Kurtz reported in The Washington
Post this week, journalists from his paper, CNN and The Wall Street
Journal are leaping to play ``themselves'' in a fictional Showtime
movie starring James Garner.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the phenomenal appeal of ``Survivor'' and
``Big Brother''  &UR; is &LR;  the news right now _ perhaps not
coincidentally at a time when the shows' promos bleed into amateur
videos of real-life wilding in New York's Central Park and
Americans are said to be alarmed about Internet invasions of their
privacy. We may learn more about the country from these TV series
than we will from the political parties' version of ``reality''
television (the infomercial conventions, which will get far less
network air time). ``Survivor'' has already held up a mirror to the
demographics of American Social Darwinism, 2000: The first 2 of the
16 ``castaways'' voted off the island were two of the oldest. Next
to get the boot was another despised species, a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the news from ``Survivor'' is bad. When Regis' game
show briefly ruled, we feared that Americans were driven by greed.
Now we learn, with relief, that money isn't everything after all,
because it's the desire to be famous, more than the infrequent cash
prizes, that are driving thousands to compete to expose themselves
on ``Survivor,'' ``Big Brother,'' MTV's ``The Real World'' and the
many clones on the way. (NBC may adapt the Dutch ``Chains of
Love,'' in which a woman is chained to five men simultaneously.)
``It's basically an audition for fame,'' says John de Mol, the
Dutch originator of ``Big Brother.'' Even the losing contestants on
``Survivor'' become talk- and news-show fixtures _ sometimes
sharing the spotlight with Darva Conger, whose one-night fling on
the scandal-tossed ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' has
blossomed into a (so far) five-month career as a TV celebrity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Donald Trump if rampant prosperity might have made
get-rich-quick game shows pale next to ``Survivor'' in the buzz
sweepstakes, he theorized: ``Making money is easier than making
fame, so fame might be more desirable _ though I'd still go with
the money myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What's harder to explain is why supposedly privacy-conscious
Americans are so eager to audition en masse for these shows or to
gleefully spy on others by watching them. But Jeffrey Rosen, whose
new book, ``The Unwanted Gaze,'' is the definitive text on privacy
perils in the digital age, feels sanguine about ``Big Brother.''
It's ``silly to huff and puff about wanting to watch lurid
television,'' he says. ``It's a human impulse.'' He adds that the
exhibitionism of the contestants, even at the price of being
humiliated in prime time, is also understandable in the
post-Monicagate era. ``Being on TV is now seen as more important
than being a good citizen,'' he explains. ``Bill Clinton showed
that in a culture of exposure, shamelessness is a self-defense; no
amount of bad behavior is embarrassing as long as you continue to
be on television. The distinction between fame and infamy has been
eradicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Also eradicated, apparently, is the distinction between reality
and unreality. The only viewers who could think ``Survivor'' is
real are those who thought ``The Blair Witch Project'' was a
documentary. It's every bit as fixed as game shows were in the time
of Charles Van Doren. Contrary to the show's opening announcement,
no one on screen was ``forced to abandon ship'' or ``marooned'';
the participants are volunteers living on what is essentially a
movie location, complete with product placement, pseudo-``Lord of
the Flies'' makeup and dozens of unseen cameramen and technicians,
publicists and prop men (who provide ``Robinson Crusoe''-esque
fonts for the parchment island maps). CBS isn't about to let anyone
fall ill, break the law or go hungry. Instead of threats from
actual natives, the castaways are dogged by canned tribal chants
that seem to be piped in from a road company of ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Survivor'' is for its participants a
theme-park experience: an attenuated sleep-over version of
Disneyland's Adventureland rides, with actual wildlife instead of
audioanimatronics. Watching it on TV is no more partaking of
``reality'' than is watching Hollywood's ``The Perfect Storm.'' Nor
is ``Big Brother'' likely to be more real: CBS and AOL promise that
we'll see no sex and hear no R-rated words, despite the ubiquity of
cameras and mikes in the tiny house (in the wilds of CBS's Studio
City lot).
</P>
<P>
   This would all be harmless were we certain that the line between
``reality television'' and actual reality is universally clear. But
TV's exploitation of the Central Park videos of packs of men
mauling dozens of women after the National Puerto Rican Day Parade
makes one wonder. Though the videos were broadcast over and over
for gratuitous titillation long after they ceased to qualify as
fresh news, the voyeuristic overkill aroused no more public protest
than the prospect of ``Big Brother.'' Nor did many question the
ethics of the amateur videomakers, most of whom, says Robert
Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, sold their tapes to
news outlets for cash, in a transaction emulating that between
``reality''-TV packagers and the networks. Since in this case,
unlike ``Survivor,'' people were actually being hurt, did any of
the cameramen at least report the crimes unfolding in their
viewfinders? ``Not one of them as far as we know ever called 911
and said you got to do something about this,'' says Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   Well, times change. When 38 onlookers couldn't be bothered to
call the cops as Kitty Genovese was stabbed to death in Queens in
1964, it was a cue for national soul-searching. Now those
eyewitnesses would not only escape censure but, if they had a
camera handy, could break into the hottest genre in showbiz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
