<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T CONSIDERS SPINOFF OF LONG-DISTANCE BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is considering spinning off its long-distance telephone
operation, the largest in the United States, as a separately traded
tracking stock, people close to the company said this week.
</P>
<P>
   One reason AT&AMP;T may want to issue a new stock to track the
long-distance unit is that its shares have languished recently.
AT&AMP;T hit a new 52-week low during trading Friday and closed at
$31.8125, down 31 cents. Management is eager to bolster the stock
price and believes that issuing a tracking stock might accomplish
that if the shrinking consumer long-distance unit is separate.
</P>
<P>
   E-SIGNATURE BILL IS SIGNED INTO LAW
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed legislation giving legal weight to
electronic signatures. At a ceremony in Philadelphia, the president
used both the traditional felt-tip pen signature and the more
high-technology method of inserting a signature card into a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. APPROVES SBC'S TEXAS REQUEST
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications received approval to sell long-distance
telephone service in Texas. That is the second instance of a
regional Bell telephone company being allowed to provide such
service to its local customers.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS SEEK ANTITRUST EXEMPTION
</P>
<P>
   Elated with a victory in the House, doctors opened a campaign to
persuade the Senate to give them an exemption from antitrust laws
so they could bargain collectively with insurance companies over
fees and other issues. But the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott,
said he would stand in their way.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL SPENDING AND INCOME RISE
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending rose by 0.2 percent in May, the Commerce
Department reported, matching expectations. Americans' incomes,
which include wages, interest and government benefits, rose 0.4
percent in May, slightly more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND-QUARTER SLUMP FOR UNDERWRITERS
</P>
<P>
   The amount raised in the United States by investment banks in
stock and bond offerings _ $451 billion _ was down 24 percent from
the second quarter of 1999. Fees for underwriting new issues sank
about 20 percent from $3.29 billion in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   $765 MILLION INVESTMENT IN ITALTEL
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems and the private investment firm Clayton, Dubilier
&AMP; Rice agreed to acquire 80 percent of Telecom Italia's computer
network equipment unit, Italtel, for $765 million. The two
investors hope that by forging an alliance with Cisco and by making
the company independent from its Italian parent, they will make it
become more competitive. The investors said they hope to sell
shares of the new company to the public soon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA EXERTS CONTROL OVER GAZPROM
</P>
<P>
   Russia's government strengthened its influence over Gazprom, the
natural-gas giant. Shareholders voted in a new board, tipping the
balance to favor the government, which controls 38.4 percent of the
company. The vote greatly reduced the influence of Gazprom's chief
executive, Rem Vyakhirev, who had wielded tremendous power.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN RESCUES A DEPARTMENT STORE
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Financial Reconstruction Commission, the agency charged
with overseeing reform in the banking system, said the government
would spend 97 billion yen, or $924 million, of taxpayer money to
help rescue Sogo, a highly indebted department store.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS TO CLOSE EARLY
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States will close at 1 p.m. Monday and will be closed on Tuesday in
observance of the Fourth of July. Most overseas markets, however,
will be open both days. U.S. markets will reopen on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
