<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG0701-COX     06-30 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. flag ceremony stirs both sides
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The Confederacy, dressed in the gray woolen
garb of its proud but beaten army, will come back to life as its
controversial battle flag is removed today from the Statehouse
dome.
</P>
<P>
   Just before noon, a pair of cadets from The Citadel will lower
the Rebel flag from the copper-clad dome.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, a battalion of Civil War re-enactors will
raise a battle flag at the Confederate Soldiers Monument on the
Capitol's northern grounds. Two drummers will snap off a cadence,
and the flag will be hoisted on a 30-foot pole surrounded by a
black iron fence. Demonstrators on both sides of the volatile issue
plan to converge. Backed by the Council of Conservative Citizens
and the Confederate States of America Historical Preservation
Society, a vehicle caravan dubbed the ``Million Rebel March'' will
protest the flag's removal.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP, which triggered today's events with its economic
boycott of South Carolina, will march in silent protest before the
formal ceremony. The NAACP complains the Rebel symbol is gaining a
more prominent position _ street level instead of hundreds of feet
in the air. ``It's going to be tense because there's concern how
the hard-nosed on both sides will react,'' said pro-flag state Sen.
Glenn McConnell (R-Charleston), who helped draft the compromise
passed this year by both chambers of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us who love the flag would have preferred it stayed on
the dome,'' said McConnell, who runs a Civil War memorabilia shop
in Charleston. ``But there would have been a tidal wave of
resentment if it had stayed up. . . At the same time, the state has
a responsibility to remember the lives of those who gave their
lives at the call of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials declined to estimate today's potential
crowd. But they're prepared to handle as many as 45,000 people.
That many marched Jan. 17 to observe Dr. Martin Luther King's
birthday and to protest the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Significant historical threads make the Civil War a significant
part of South Carolina's past.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were the first shots of the Civil War fired near
Charleston, but South Carolina _ the first state to secede from the
union _ also was the last state in the nation to stop importing
slaves from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The battle flag was raised over the Statehouse dome in 1962
during a Civil War celebration. At the time, the state was
resisting federal mandates for school desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War is still very much alive here,'' said Bernard
Powers, a professor of African American history at Benedict
College, a historically black school in Columbia. ``When you put
all of those things together, you see race has been a very
important issue in the unfolding of South Carolina history.''
</P>
<P>
   Unmoved by the legislative compromise, the NAACP is continuing
its economic boycott of the state's $14.6 billion tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
   When the state House approved legislation in May to remove the
battle flag, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you once had to strain to see a flag 300 feet in the
air, it would now be 30 feet in the air, larger, with lights, and a
fence,'' said Mfume, head of the nation's largest civil rights
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But groups like the South Carolina Chamber of Commerce have
parted ways with the NAACP. The business community pressured
legislators to move the flag, which generated unwanted publicity by
the nation's media and late-night comedy shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, it brings finality to the issue,''
said Deb Woolley, spokeswoman for the state chamber.
</P>
<P>
   However, Powers, the Benedict historian, said blacks are by and
large unappeased by the compromise. Gov. Jim Hodges will not attend
the flag-raising ceremony at the soldiers monument. However, he
will speak inside the Statehouse after the lowered flags are given
to an official from the State Museum. Owners of the Capitol
Restaurant, less than a block from the Statehouse, were unsure
whether they'd open this morning. They usually serve breakfast on
Saturday. But regulars have insisted they'll stay far away from
downtown today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be anywhere near here because it's going to
be a clash of two ideologies,'' 43-year-old trial lawyer Mark
Whitlark said over a cheese omelette and grits. ``What's happened
is that the rallies have galvanized people on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Said law partner Paul Ballou, ``We hope it's not going to be
ugly _ but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Two booths away, 80-year-old flag supporter Ryan Scott waited
for his coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our heritage, part of our hurting,'' Scott said.
``My great-grandfather fought in that war. He survived it. But a
lot of people didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
