u i BC-CHILE-U.S.-PINOCHET-N     06-30 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-U.S.-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI DECLASSIFIES REPORTS ON AMERICANS KILLED UNDER CHILE'S
PINOCHET 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI collected intelligence on an American
student living in Chile who was killed soon after Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's takeover of Chile in 1973, according to newly
declassified documents made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a December 1972 report from one informant, the FBI said that
the student, Frank Teruggi Jr., had attended a ``Conference on
Anti-Imperialist Strategy and Action'' held by former Peace Corps
volunteers who, the FBI said, ``espouse support of Cuba and all
Third World revolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly declassified documents did not indicate that the
information on Teruggi was shared with Chilean officials. Though
Chilean authorities have never confirmed that Teruggi was executed,
he was arrested at his apartment days after the coup and tortured
at the National Stadium, witnesses said. His body was discovered in
the morgue 10 days later, riddled with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   The document on Teruggi was one of several hundred released
Friday, ordered by President Clinton last year as part of a major
declassification project on human rights abuses under Pinochet's
1973-90 dictatorship .
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's release, which represented the final government
disclosures on three Americans killed in Chile during the Pinochet
dictatorship, disappointed family members and human rights
activists.
</P>
<P>
   While the documents offered some details, they broke no new
ground as to the circumstances under which the Americans perished.
In addition to Teruggi, those killed were Charles Horman, an
American journalist whose plight was portrayed in the 1982 movie
``Missing,'' and Boris Weisfeiler, a mathematics professor who
disappeared in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA had released only six documents concerning Horman's
death. It released another dozen or so on the death of Teruggi, all
concerning the attempts of the dead man's father to see a document
the agency refused to release 24 years ago. The intelligence agency
continued to withhold that document Friday, arguing that its
information was provided by a foreign intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the release does not give us the complete picture,
it does add some more information that will help us complete the
picture eventually,'' said Peter Kornbluh, senior analyst at the
National Security Archive, a group that has worked to make public
American operations overseas. ``Our quest is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Horman, whose husband was killed at the age of 31, held up
documents no more than an inch thick, many with chunks of black
lines keeping whole paragraphs secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either they're withholding documents,'' she said, ``or they
really didn't do anything to protect an American citizen or to
investigate his detention in Chile at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   The only new insight Horman gleaned came from an informant who
approached the U.S. Embassy in 1987 to say that Horman had been
killed in the National Stadium for being a ``foreign extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   On learning that the man they had killed was an American
citizen, stadium officials panicked and had his body dumped on the
streets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But American Embassy officials had doubts about the informant's
credibility, and eventually lost contact with him.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the documents released Friday involved Weisfeiler,
44, who apparently was picked up by the military while hitchhiking
in Chile. His body has never been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   At her home in Newton, Mass., Weisfeiler's sister, Olga
Weisfeiler, spent Friday combing through the documents, and they
confirmed what she had gradually come to suspect since a Chilean
lawyer reopened her brother's case this year: that her brother had
been tortured and killed at a secretive concentration camp in the
Chilean countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case was closed by the Chileans after 60 days, without
evidence, without a body, without anything,'' she said. ``In our
minds, this case remained open.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there had been expectations of a final explanation of
Teruggi's death, the only information to emerge Friday involved the
FBI surveillance report. Though the report had been mentioned in
other documents, it had not been previously released.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the FBI, Tracy Silberling, said there would be
no comment on the bureau's surveillance of Teruggi. ``Generally,
with Freedom of Information documents, we let them stand on their
own, and at this stage we couldn't get someone to comment on
them,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
