<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD BLACK, VIOLINIST AND VERSATILE COMPOSER, DIES AT 77 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Mass., Pa., Md.)   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arnold Black, a violinist and a composer of concert
works, theater music and film scores who was also the founding
director of the Mohawk Trail Concerts chamber series in Shelburne
Falls, Mass., died on Sunday at his home in Charlemont, Mass. He
was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was undetermined, but he had had heart trouble in
recent years, his wife, Ruth, said.
</P>
<P>
   Born on May 2, 1923, in Philadelphia, Black was found early on
to have cerebral palsy. Treatment and therapy improved his
condition, but all his life he lacked mobility in his right side,
which made his decision to study the violin all the more
remarkable. He graduated from the Juilliard School having majored
in violin and composition. As a violinist he attained considerable
success, becoming the concertmaster of the Baltimore Symphony and
the assistant concertmaster of the National Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   But composing increasingly claimed him. In the early 1950s Black
was composer in residence at the Circle in the Square Theater,
where he worked with the director Jose Quintero and wrote scores
for some acclaimed productions, including ``Ulysses in Nighttown,''
based on the James Joyce novel and starring Zero Mostel.
</P>
<P>
   While in England in 1959 with a touring production of that play,
he met Ruth M. Lloyd, a Royal College of Music graduate, who became
his wife that year. In addition to his wife, their daughter,
Hilary, survives him.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who until two years ago maintained a second residence in
Manhattan, served as director of the Mohawk Trail Concerts for more
than 30 years. He also wrote theater scores for productions at the
National Shakespeare Company and the Eugene O'Neill Theater
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDS-260&AMP;AD     06-30 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDS-260&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIAL SENATE FUND-RAISING PROVES LUCRATIVE FOR LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio has collected roughly $4.5 million in
donations since entering New York's U.S. Senate race six weeks ago,
benefiting from the same antipathy toward his opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, that helped propel the fund raising of Lazio's
predecessor, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio took in almost as much as Clinton in the three-month
fund-raising period that ended Friday, even though he began
soliciting money only halfway through, according to figures
released by the two campaigns. Clinton collected $5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very encouraged by the outpouring of support for
Congressman Lazio and his mainstream message,'' a campaign
spokesman, Michael Marr, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical Senate race, Lazio's total for such a short span
would be considered startling. But having entered the race very
late _ Giuliani dropped out on May 19 to focus on his treatment for
prostate cancer _ Lazio remains far behind Clinton in financing.
</P>
<P>
   That could hinder Lazio, who is not well known, as he seeks to
parry Clinton's attempts to use aggressive advertising to cement a
negative image of him.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether Lazio can continue reaping money at
this pace or merely had an initial burst of donations after
becoming the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $4.5 million that he has raised for his
Senate campaign, Lazio had $3.5 million in the account for his
House re-election campaign as of March 31. After spending $2.6
million, his campaign had $5.4 million in the bank as of Friday,
Marr said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It could not be determined whether the money was being spent as
quickly as it was being received.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns are required to report their fund-raising
statistics, including the identities of donors, to the Federal
Election Commission by July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is spending money as fast as she is collecting it. With
the figure reported Friday, Clinton has now raised $17.9 million.
She ended the last period on March 31 with $6.6 million, and
finished this one with $6.4 million, her aides said, meaning that
she spent slightly more than the $5.1 million that she raised in
the period.
</P>
<P>
   When he abandoned the campaign in May, Giuliani had just broken
the fund-raising record of $21 million set by a nonincumbent
candidate for Senate, Oliver L. North, a Republican who lost a
contest in Virginia in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The spending record for the Senate is a moving target: Jon S.
Corzine, a wealthy former investment banker, spent almost $35
million _ nearly all of it his own money _ to win the Democratic
Senate primary in New Jersey in June.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to spend much more in the general election
against Rep. Bob Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani excelled at using direct mail to harvest money from
people around the nation who loathe Clinton. Lazio is seeking to
follow the same strategy.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling out of the race, Giuliani returned nearly $3
million in donations last week, enclosing a letter that asked that
the money be sent to Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman's aides said they hoped to begin receiving that
money in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign has a few million dollars left, and the
mayor has not decided what to do with it. He is barred from giving
it directly to Lazio's campaign but could donate it to a Republican
committee that could help Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   With the release of the figures Friday, both the Lazio and
Clinton campaigns adopted the traditional stance of promoting their
successes while trying to lower expectations for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely strong filing, and we are very pleased,''
said the Clinton campaign manager, Bill de Blasio.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we expect that Rick Lazio and the national Republican
fund-raising machine will outraise us, we are very proud of the
support we have received.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Marr responded: ``Hillary Clinton's complaints about
the vast right-wing conspiracy continue. The fact is that the Lazio
campaign is up against the awesome power of the White House,
Clinton's Hollywood allies and various other special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Congressman Lazio will prevail in this race because his
mainstream record and message resonate with an overwhelmingly
majority of New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday the race drew in Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the former
presidential candidate, who had campaigned for the mayor. McCain
released a statement attacking Clinton and the Democrats for
spending the unregulated contributions known as soft money on
behalf of Clinton. McCain also promoted Lazio as a staunch advocate
of overhauling the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for the Clinton campaign, said, ``I
guess Senator McCain must not know that Rick Lazio is one of the
biggest soft money fund-raisers in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
