u a BC-OBIT-GARRY-NYT &LR;      06-30 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GARRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM J. GARRY, 56, EPICURE AT BON APPETIT MAGAZINE'S HELM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Macnab in last graf is cq)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William J. Garry, the garrulous editor of Bon Appetit magazine
whose editorial eye focused on both epicurean pleasures as well as
home entertaining, died on Thursday in Los Angeles, where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Garry, who was 56, died of lung cancer, said Maurie Perl, a
spokeswoman for Conde Nast Publications, the publisher of Bon
Appetit.
</P>
<P>
   Garry edited Bon Appetit for 15 years and helped raise the
magazine's circulation to 1.2 million a month. His editor's letter
was a frequently discussed staple of the food business.
</P>
<P>
   Born in San Francisco in 1944, Garry graduated from Dartmouth
College and earned a master of fine arts degree at Columbia
University. Intrigued by the theater, he began his career as a
stage manager, actor and director.
</P>
<P>
   He soon shifted his focus to writing and editing, serving in
editorial positions at magazines as various as Epicure, several
spinoff publications of House Beautiful and a business magazine
called Free Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career at Bon Appetit in San Francisco as managing
editor in 1980, when the magazine was owned by Knapp
Communications. When Conde Nast bought Knapp Communications, which
also owned Architectural Digest, in 1993, Garry came along. The
magazine's business operations were moved to New York then.
</P>
<P>
   His approach to the epicurean arts was free wheeling. His
editor's letter in Bon Appetit's July 2000 issue, for example,
details Garry's park-bench dinner with an Elvis impersonator, at
which the impersonator ate a meal of fragrant, soulful barbecued
pork, and Garry, ``feeling fairly ridiculous,'' ate a hummus
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   He was not afraid of ruffling feathers. Bored by food magazines'
seemingly predictable coverage of asparagus every springtime, Garry
proclaimed an April day last year ``Give Asparagus a Rest Day.''
Three years ago, Garry was so appalled by the food served at a
banquet for the National Magazine Awards, held at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, that he ordered room service.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, when the magazine first published a survey of great
American restaurants, rather than accentuate the painstaking
science behind the selection process, Garry told The New York Times
in an interview: ``I don't believe in polls. So we sat down and
threw a lot of food at each other and came up with the winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry is survived his wife, Mary Duncan Macnab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
