A0277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HARLEM-DEVELOP-NYT     06-30 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC JOHNSON THEATERS OPEN IN HARLEM, CASTING A SPELL OF RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A milestone in what some people have called the
miracle of 125th Street was reached Friday when the long-awaited
Magic Johnson Theaters opened, bringing Harlem its first multiplex,
with amenities like stadium seating to rival any movie house in the
city. For the first time in many years, local residents will no
longer have to travel to the Bronx or the Upper West Side to take
in a first-run movie.
</P>
<P>
   But long before the first screening of ``Shaft'' Friday
afternoon, ripples from the nine-screen movie theater and the new
$66 million Harlem USA shopping and entertainment complex of which
it is a part were already spreading up and down the broad street
that serves as Harlem's main thoroughfare. The six-level shopping
center, at 125th and Frederick Douglass Boulevard, is home to
several national chain stores, including an HMV record store, a
Disney Store, an Old Navy and a Modell's Sporting Goods store.
</P>
<P>
   National chain stores, fearful of crime and skeptical of whether
enough buying power existed in low-income and minority
neighborhoods, have long shunned communities like Harlem. Now
retailers across the country are closely watching Harlem USA to see
if the ambitious project will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   One regional retailer that has responded to the new shopping
center is the aptly named Lazarus, a 40-year-old children's
clothing store one block east of the new shopping center. Last
year, the owners spent $500,000 to renovate the store, which has a
new multicolored sign, a brightly lighted interior and a clean and
up-to-date appearance. Harlem USA had a lot to do with the store's
make over, said George Adams, the general manager for the last 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street came back alive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he is not worried about competition from Old Navy
because his store has catered to the same families for three
generations and emphasizes personal service.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of vitality are everywhere on 125th Street, from the
recently added bright red paint on the KFC outlet across the street
from Harlem USA to the new or spruced up clothing stores like
Ashley Stewart, Scheme and Avenue. Pedestrians crowd the sidewalks
and there are long lines at the cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   Some shoppers said they could scarcely believe the
transformation. ``I used to think, maybe it's all talk, talk,
talk,'' said Julie Duncan, a retired telephone service clerk who
has lived in Harlem all her 53 years, ``but then it came to
light.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacant spaces began disappearing and rents began climbing around
three years ago when it became clear that the shopping center would
actually be built, said Barbara Askins, the president of the 125th
Street Business Improvement District. Annual rents in the area
around the shopping center have doubled and now average $60 to $70
a square foot, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the new facades, no one would mistake 125th Street
for the shopping corridor along Third Avenue in the 60s in
Manhattan. Rhythm and blues and salsa music permeates the air and
street vendors peddle a wide range of goods _ from books and
compact disks to hand-painted tiles and flavored ices.
</P>
<P>
   After years of disappointments, development in Harlem is
proceeding with breathtaking speed, generating many hundreds of
jobs and changing people's lives in small ways as well as large
ones. For example, Askins said, Harlem residents previously had to
leave the neighborhood to find the weight-lifting equipment that
Modell's carries, or a gym like the branch of the New York Sports
Club that recently opened at Harlem USA.
</P>
<P>
   But not every recent development project in the neighborhood has
succeeded, however. East River Plaza, an East Harlem shopping
center that would be anchored by a Costco warehouse store and a
Home Depot, has stalled because of a lack of financing for a $30
million parking garage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
