<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-JULICH0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former teammate Julich could prove tough challenge
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four years ago, when former teammate Lance
Armstrong was battling testicular cancer, Bobby Julich seemed to be
the great American hope to win the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Julich, born in Corpus Christi and raised in Glenwood Springs,
Colo., finished third in the 1998 Tour behind Marco Pantani and Jan
Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   But Julich has yet to return to that same form. He was forced to
withdraw from last year's Tour after the time trial in Metz, which
was won by Armstrong. Julich injured his chest and shoulder and
could not continue.
</P>
<P>
   He also was forced to pull out of the Tour of Spain in
September, when he suffered a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Julich has resumed racing this year, representing a new team,
Credit Agricole of France. If he returns to form, he can be a
formidable opponent to Armstrong because he is an excellent climber
and can hold his own in the time trials.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
