<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.Y. ruckus over Rocker dying down
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This time, the fireworks were planned.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like a potentially lethal combination: The New York
Mets' long-scheduled ``Fireworks Night'' on Friday and Day 2 of
controversial Braves closer John Rocker's inflammatory visit to
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet things didn't feel as hot as they had Thursday, when, after
six months of waiting, 46,000 fans, 700 police and 300 media got
their first look at Rocker. Thursday's final line score: A 1-2-3
eighth inning from Rocker, countless boos and two arrests as Mets
fans made clear they hadn't quite forgiven him for his anti-New
York comments in a December magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   While many among Friday's crowd wore the now ubiquitous ``Rocker
Sucks'' T-shirt, even many who showed up early to jeer him during
his outfield wind sprints suggested the big Brave would have an
easier night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure it will be safer here tonight because everyone's had
a day to cool down,'' said Glenn Starkey of Parsippany, N.J.,
waving a sign at Rocker that described him as ``Forrest Chump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They got all the stress level out last night,'' agreed Steve
Fazio, 18, of New Paltz, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a T-shirt that proclaimed Friday ``John Rocker Battery
Night,'' Fazio swore he was ``unarmed.'' Even the normally
merciless tabloids pulled back a bit Friday, with the New York Post
labeling Thursday's performance ``Rocker's Revenge,'' and the Daily
News gave him points for his pitching and for ``apologizing to the
city'' in a statement broadcast on the scoreboard before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one believed things couldn't get bad again real fast
Friday. New York police still kept watch on some subway platforms
along the line Rocker had threatened to ride Thursday, and four
officers surrounded Rocker in left field when he autographed balls
for more than a dozen Mets fans.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking a beer and looking on, Joseph Giammarino called the
autograph seekers ``traitors'' and suggested the good feelings
might not last.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets lit up tonight,'' Giammarino said of Rocker,
``they'll be on him worse than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
