<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FREEAGENTS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSIER AND LINDROS EXPECTED TO JOIN CLASS OF FREE AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the free-agency period ready to begin in the National
Hockey League Saturday, the Vancouver Canucks and the Philadelphia
Flyers had to make decisions Friday involving two significant
players.
</P>
<P>
   The players, Mark Messier of the Canucks and Eric Lindros of the
Flyers, could become members of the rebuilding New York Rangers,
who are under new management. But neither big center is the certain
and powerful force on the ice that he used to be. Coincidentally,
both players use their fathers as agents, which is unusual in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Team executives declined to disclose publicly Friday whether the
Flyers had decided to cut Lindros loose and whether the Canucks had
severed their ties with Messier.
</P>
<P>
   Messier, after three seasons with the Canucks, is 39 years old.
A popular captain who left the Rangers as a free agent in 1997
after six seasons, Messier could stay in Vancouver another season
if the Canucks picked up a $6 million option on his contract.
Should they decline, they would owe him a $2 million buyout and he
would become an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, it is unlikely we will exercise our
option,'' General Manager Brian Burke of the Canucks said this
week. In 66 games last season, Messier had 17 goals and 37 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Messier, Mark's father and agent, said Friday that the
Canucks had not extended his son's contract and that an extension
was not expected before Friday's midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 through 1990, Messier played on five Stanley Cup
champions for the Edmonton Oilers. He added another ring with the
Rangers in 1994. Glen Sather, the general manager and coach of
those Oilers teams, is the new general manager of the Rangers. It
is expected that Messier will sign with Sather's Rangers, perhaps
for a lower salary, to finish his career in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There are hints of more movement along the Oilers-Rangers
pipeline. A report in The Hartford Courant on Wednesday said that
the Rangers would name Ron Low as coach. But John Rosasco, a
Rangers spokesman, said Sather would not name a coach until at
least July 8. Low is a former coach of the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' situation is more complex than Messier's. He will
either become a restricted or an unrestricted free agent Saturday.
Lindros, also a center, earned $8.5 million with the Philadelphia
Flyers last season, playing 55 games and compiling 27 goals and 32
assists. But he suffered four concussions during the season, the
last in the playoffs against the New Jersey Devils. And much
bitterness was evident in relations between the Lindros camp and
Bobby Clarke, the Flyers' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke had to decide whether to give Lindros another $8.5
million contract as a qualifying offer and keep certain rights
regarding him as a restricted free agent. By doing this, the Flyers
could trade Lindros and get value in return. Or they could allow
him to sign with another team and get up to five first-round draft
choices as compensation. They could also match any offer and keep
him on their team.
</P>
<P>
   But offering him another contract would obligate the Flyers to
pay Lindros even if he could not play because of post-concussion
symptoms. According to his agent and father, Carl Lindros, Eric is
still suffering some ill effects and does not have medical
clearance to resume training.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers could rid themselves of any obligation to Lindros by
declining to offer him the $8.5 million contract. That, however,
would make him an unrestricted free agent, able to sign with any
NHL team with no compensation to the Flyers. When Lindros, 27, is
healthy, he is considered one of the best players in the sport. He
was the league's Most Valuable Player in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said early Friday that the Flyers had not yet decided
what to do about Lindros, but would make their decision before
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Clarke said, when asked what the team would
do. ``Everything's a gamble. If someone wants him, it's a gamble on
their part. If we want to keep him, it's a gamble on our part. What
can I tell you? Something's going to have to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought the Flyers would do regarding his
son, Carl Lindros replied: ``I have no idea. Absolutely none. We're
just sitting and waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his son's health, Lindros said: ``He's progressing. He
still has symptoms.'' But he declined to be specific about what
problems persist.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, at the NHL draft in Calgary, Alberta, Clarke
said that the Rangers, the Toronto Maple Leafs and the Los Angeles
Kings had been given permission to talk with Lindros. The Dallas
Stars and the Carolina Hurricanes have also inquired about his
availability.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the Lindros family and the Flyers has
deteriorated. Carl and Eric Lindros have questioned the medical
treatment provided by the Flyers for the concussions and also for a
collapsed lung that Lindros suffered in the 1998-99 season. Clarke
has bitterly criticized Carl Lindros' involvement in Eric's career,
as well as that of Bonnie Lindros, Eric's mother.
</P>
<P>
   A similar rift, though less extreme, existed between the Rangers
and the Messier family in 1997. The friction involved Madison
Square Garden executives and Doug Messier. It is no longer thought
to be an obstacle to Messier's returning to the team.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior player, Lindros admired Messier and made no secret
of his desire to play alongside him with the Rangers. Although many
years have passed, those who know Lindros say he retains his
admiration of Messier and his desire to play with him.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Flyers grant Lindros free agency, his next contract
could be for considerably less money than he earned last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers led the league in payroll last season with more than
$60 million, and one of Sather's goals is to curb the escalation of
salaries. Last summer the Rangers spiked the pay scale by signing
several free agents, including Theo Fleury and Valery Kamensky.
Their poor performances last season _ the Rangers missed the
playoffs for the third consecutive year _ led to the dismissal of
Neil Smith as general manager and John Muckler as coach.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among the unrestricted free agents this summer are Vladimir
Malakhov and Claude Lemieux of the Devils, Matthieu Schneider of
the Rangers, Paul Coffey and Gary Roberts of Carolina, Shayne
Corson of Montreal, Lyle Odelein of Phoenix, Igor Larionov of
Detroit and Mike Eastwood of St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
