<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 06/30/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Attention editors:
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New York
Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived
in America.'' The following photos are part of the Eleventh part of
the series:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT125) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-6 --
Jabari Morgan, a recent graduate of Southern University in Baton
Rouge, La., played cymbals with Southern University's marching
band. Upon learning that the university had recruited a white
quarterback for it's football team, Morgan couldn't have cared
less, as long as Southern won and people stayed in their seats for
the halftime show. More famous than Southern's football team, it
had real power and importance on campus. ``The whole point of
letting the white guy dance is that we were saying to the world,
'Hey, you can learn our culture just like we can learn yours.'''
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT124) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-5 --
Jabari Morgan, flanked by his parents, Mo and Wanda Morgan. The
Morgan family is full of proud and passionate Southern University
graduates, including, most recently, Jabari, who played cymbals
with Southern's 180-piece marching band. Upon learning that the
university had recruited a white quarterback for it's football
team, Jabari couldn't have cared less, as long as Southern won and
people stayed in their seats for the halftime show. Mo Morgan felt
otherwise. ``I didn't like the fact that he was there.'' (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT123) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-4 --
Pete Richardson, Southern University's head football coach,
recruited Marcus Jacoby, the first white ever to play quarterback
for the university. Richardson had turned a laughingstock of a
program into a national force. Richardson and Jacoby's family
discussed everything from Southern's rich athletic tradition to the
engineering courses that interested Marcus, but for a long while
they didn't mention the thing that worried the parents most. Would
a black team accept a white leader? (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT122) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-3 --
Marcus Jacoby, 11, playing for Southern University in the Bayou
Classic against Grambling University. In a 30-7 win against
Grambling, Jacoby threw three touchdowns and played the entire
game. Even though Jacoby was named the Bayou Classic's most
valuable player, he soon burned out on being the minority at
Southern, a football powerhouse among black colleges. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT121) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-2 --
Marcus Jacoby, who presently attends Louisiana State University,
had once struggled with all the daily irritations that go with
being a minority in college, while attending Southern University, a
football powerhouse among black colleges. Increasingly, being the
minority made him feel alienated. Jacoby eventually quit the team,
the campus, and football. ``I learned early on that I was a pioneer
in all this and no one else had gone through it and often the best
advice I could get was from myself. Because I was the only one who
knew the whole situation.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT120) BATON ROUGE, La. -- June 30, 2000 -- RACE-SPORTS-1 --
Marcus Jacoby, center, No.11, struggled on and off the field as
starting quarterback at Southern University, a football powerhouse
among black colleges. Jacoby was unaware that if he accepted a
scholarship to Southern, he would be the first white ever to play
quarterback for the university and the first white ever to start at
quarterback in the 76-year-history of the black South West Athletic
Conference. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The following photos are also part of our daily report:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DAVENPORT, N.Y. -- July 7, 1999 -- MOYNIHAN-FARM -- The
farm of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. The four-term
senator's spiritual home, the site of the 19th-century schoolhouse
where he has written his 18 books, a political base that tied the
man born in Hells Kitchen to the history and hills of upstate New
York, is up for sale. The $1.1 million farm includes two houses,
two barns, fields, ponds, a stream and ``8,000 feet of road
frontage.'' Sen. Moynihan walking with Hillary Rodham Clinton on
his farm in Davenport, N.Y., last July. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ATLANTA -- June 30, 2000 -- GAY-UNIONS-COX -- Gay men
who live in or visit Vermont may enter into legal arrangements that
are same-sex marriages in almost everything but name. Vermont's law
confers on same-sex couples the rights and responsibilities enjoyed
by married couples, from health insurance benefits to inheritance
rights. Jerry Gonzalez and Ray Deeb are planning to travel to
Vermont this September for a ``Civil Union'' ceremony, the closest
thing to a legal marriage for homosexual couples. (Cathy Seith/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 30, 2000 -- IRAQ-MISSILES-B&AMP;W --
Eighteen months after American and British warplanes destroyed its
missile factories, Iraq has rebuilt its missile program and held a
series of short-range flight tests, including one on Tuesday. The
tests come as the Clinton administration's policy is under fire
abroad and in the presidential campaign. Bomb damage assessment
photos of the Ibn Al Haytham Missile Research and Development
Center in Iraq presented to reporters during a news conference in
December, 1998. At right, is the facility before it was bombed.
(Department of Defense/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- JULY-FOURTH -- With July 4
falling this year on a Tuesday, and many people taking Monday off
as well, much of the rush to leave town was underway on Friday.
Passengers board a seaplane ferrying travelers to East Hampton,
Long Island, from lower Manhattan, Friday. (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HAVERSTRAW, N.Y. -- June 30, 2000 -- NY-HUDSON-DEVELOP
-- An odd coalition of idealists and entrepreneurs, ranging from
Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist and Nobel Laureate Toni Morrison to
a powerful Westchester County developer, have a vision of turning
this town in the Hudson Valley into one that draws throngs of
well-heeled tourists in search of small-town charm. Morrison is
renovating this 19th-century home the intention of renting
apartments out to artists. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- NY-HARLEM-DEVELOP -- Magic
Johnson, right, with Kenneth Lombard, president of Magic Johnson
Theaters, during ceremonies marking the opening of the Magic
Johnson Theaters in Harlem, Friday. The opening of the theater
complex added another anchor to the neighborhood's developing
economic renaissance. (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHICAGO -- June 30, 2000 -- MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S. 2 -- To
an unprecedented degree, the Mexican election has come north of the
border. Mexican politicians are urging Mexicans from New York to
San Francisco to call their family and friends back home advising
them how to vote in Sunday's election. A mock election booth in
front of a fruit and vegetable market in a predominantly Mexican
neighborhood in Chicago earlier this week. Chicago is home to the
second largest Mexican population after Los Angeles. (Steve
Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CHICAGO -- June 30, 2000 -- MEXICO-ELECTION-U.S. -- To
an unprecedented degree, the Mexican election has come north of the
border. Mexican politicians are urging Mexicans from New York to
San Francisco to call their family and friends back home advising
them how to vote in Sunday's election. Members of Chicago's Mexican
community listen to a debate about the upcoming presidential
elections in a restaurant on Tuesday. Chicago is home to the second
largest Mexican population after Los Angeles. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN, JULY 2 --
DUMMY-FILMING -- The tale of Steven Schoichet, a maladroit
suburbanite whose life is transformed when he comes into possession
of a ventriloquist's prop, ``Dummy'' is the kind of movie Charlie
McCarthy might have starred in if Michael Ovitz had been his agent.
Nearly everyone else in the film is a client of Ovitz's firm,
Artists Management Group, a noncoincidence that helps explain how a
script by an obscure writer with a budget that wouldn't buy a
two-bedroom in Manhattan happened to get this far. Inside the
costume trailer on the set of ``Dummy,'' from left: Milla Jovovich,
Adrian Brody and Vera Farmiga. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN, JULY 2 --
DOCTORS-MARKETING -- Like hair colorists, fashion designers and
chefs, more and more doctors are seeking publicity to build their
businesses. Dr. David E. Bank, a dermatologist at the Center for
Dermatology, Cosmetic and Laser Surgery, in his office. (Edward
Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- PATRIOTISM-DEBATE-2 --
Norman Podhoretz, right, is the editor at large of Commentary
magazine, a senior fellow of the Hudson Institute and the author of
``My Love Affair With America,'' to be published on Tuesday. Victor
Navasky is the publisher and editorial director of The Nation, the
Delacorte professor of magazine journalism at Columbia University
and the author of ``Naming Names,'' a study of the Hollywood
blacklist. Together, they have spent more than three-quarters of a
century in journalism, and for many years they have disagreed,
often vehemently, about the issues that have shaped American life.
For this Fourth of July weekend, The New York Times asked them to
discuss patriotism. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- June 30, 2000 -- HARVARD-WEB-BOS -- While some
medical schools have become household names through their Web sites
and contracts with online companies, Harvard, ever the skeptical
traditionalist, has kept its distance from the wired world.
``There's a difference between practicing medicine over the
Internet and providing education,'' says Dr. Thomas Delbanco of
Beth Israel Deaconess Hospital, a Harvard University affiliate.
(Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WEST NEWTON, Mass. -- June 30, 2000 -- MOSCOW-DUCKS -- In
February, thieves sawed off and nabbed the 200-pound bronze statue
of the determined duck matriarch from Robert McCloskey's ``Make Way
for Ducklings.'' They also made off with two of her flock, Lack and
Mack. That left Novodevichy Park with only five of the nine
original ducks that Barbara Bush had given the Soviet Union in
1991, a year after Raisa Gorbachev had admired the duck sculpture
while visiting Boston's Public Garden. Sculptor Nancy Schon is
creating new mallards to replace those stolen from Moscow's
Novodevichy Park. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- JUDD-MUSIC -- Wynonna Judd
made a rare club appearance Thursday night to introduce her latest
album, ``New Day Rising.'' Judd reaches out to fans during her
concert. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DOUGLAS, Ariz. -- June 30, 2000 -- MEXICO-U.S.-BORDER --
Five years after the Clinton administration and the Republican
Congress began a massive law enforcement buildup along the
Mexican-U.S. border to fight the war on drugs and illegal
immigration, federal and state courts are now buckling under the
strain of the enormous criminal caseload. A border patrol agent
stationed at a check point on a highway near Douglas, pulls over
vehicles during spot inspections last January. (Monica Almeida/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- PATRIOTISM-DEBATE -- Norman
Podhoretz, right, is the editor at large of Commentary magazine, a
senior fellow of the Hudson Institute and the author of ``My Love
Affair With America,'' to be published on Tuesday. Victor Navasky
is the publisher and editorial director of The Nation, the
Delacorte professor of magazine journalism at Columbia University
and the author of ``Naming Names,'' a study of the Hollywood
blacklist. Together, they have spent more than three-quarters of a
century in journalism, and for many years they have disagreed,
often vehemently, about the issues that have shaped American life.
For this Fourth of July weekend, The New York Times asked them to
discuss patriotism. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- June 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 2 --
INVEST-PUTNAM-VOYAGER -- Putnam International Voyager, a top
performer in its group, is run from Boston by the British managers
Nigel Hart, left, and Andrew Graham. Putnam's Class A shares
returned 35.3 percent a year, on average, for the three years
through June 23, compared with 12.2 percent for its peers in the
foreign stock category, according to Morningstar Inc.(Michael
Quan/The New York Times)
</P>
