<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GACITIES-SMOG0701-COX     06-30 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GACITIES-SMOG0701-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air cleanup isn't just for Atlanta
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As metro Atlanta faced its 11th ``smog alert'' of the
summer on Friday, Gov. Roy Barnes recommended adding eight metro
counties and Columbus, Macon and Augusta to the hit list of places
violating federal clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency agrees with the
state's recommendations, residents of those areas could face some
of the same restrictions _ including auto emissions testing and
stringent curbs on industries _ now imposed on 13 metro Atlanta
counties for exceeding ozone pollution levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Regional Transportation Authority also would extend
its jurisdiction _ which now covers only the 13-county Atlanta
region _ to include the new areas. GRTA is the superagency created
by the General Assembly last year to ease traffic congestion and
implement transportation plans to clean up the dirty air.
</P>
<P>
   The eight metro Atlanta counties that would be added to the list
are Barrow, Bartow, Carroll, Dawson, Hall, Newton, Walton and
Spalding. In addition, the counties of Richmond (Augusta), Bibb
(Macon) and Muscogee (Columbus) should be added, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the deadline for the nation's governors to submit
their recommendations for the EPA's list of areas that cannot meet
its tougher standard on ground-level ozone. Ozone is the chief
ingredient of smog, caused by emissions from automobiles,
factories, coal-burning power plants and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new rule _ the ``eight-hour standard'' _ is tied up
in the U.S. Supreme Court because of a legal challenge by trucking
groups and others who claim that the EPA overstepped its legal
bound.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes asked the EPA to hold off on making a final decision on
his recommendations until the court rules, probably by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials say it is unclear what strategy they
will pursue if the court rules against the EPA. However, the old
ozone standard _ which the 13-county metro area violates _ still
would be in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the governor's letter was in the mail Friday, his
recommendations were coming under fire. Wesley Woolf, director of
the Southern Environmental Law Center's Atlanta office, said Monroe
and Houston counties should have been included as part of the Macon
nonattainment area because of a major coal-burning power plant in
Monroe and sprawl and congestion in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the governor has recommended is minimal,'' Woolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the final outcome, it will take several years to
implement measures to clean dirty air in the newly designated
areas, said Ron Methier, air quality chief for the state
Environmental Protection Division.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning up the air in the Augusta, Macon and Columbus areas,
however, may not require major changes beyond those already being
mandated by state and federal authorities, Methier said. Those
requirements include tougher controls on coal-fired plants, the
removal of sulfur from gasoline and diesel fuels, and adding
emissions control devices on sport utility vehicles and some trucks
.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that those are the only requirements needed to bring
those areas into compliance with the new ozone standard,'' Methier
said. ``They may not need (transportation plans) such as those
required for metro Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
