<P>
   (NYT19) DAVENPORT, N.Y. -- July 7, 1999 -- MOYNIHAN-FARM -- The
farm of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. The four-term
senator's spiritual home, the site of the 19th-century schoolhouse
where he has written his 18 books, a political base that tied the
man born in Hells Kitchen to the history and hills of upstate New
York, is up for sale. The $1.1 million farm includes two houses,
two barns, fields, ponds, a stream and ``8,000 feet of road
frontage.'' Sen. Moynihan walking with Hillary Rodham Clinton on
his farm in Davenport, N.Y., last July. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ATLANTA -- June 30, 2000 -- GAY-UNIONS-COX -- Gay men
who live in or visit Vermont may enter into legal arrangements that
are same-sex marriages in almost everything but name. Vermont's law
confers on same-sex couples the rights and responsibilities enjoyed
by married couples, from health insurance benefits to inheritance
rights. Jerry Gonzalez and Ray Deeb are planning to travel to
Vermont this September for a ``Civil Union'' ceremony, the closest
thing to a legal marriage for homosexual couples. (Cathy Seith/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 30, 2000 -- IRAQ-MISSILES-B&AMP;W --
Eighteen months after American and British warplanes destroyed its
missile factories, Iraq has rebuilt its missile program and held a
series of short-range flight tests, including one on Tuesday. The
tests come as the Clinton administration's policy is under fire
abroad and in the presidential campaign. Bomb damage assessment
photos of the Ibn Al Haytham Missile Research and Development
Center in Iraq presented to reporters during a news conference in
December, 1998. At right, is the facility before it was bombed.
(Department of Defense/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- JULY-FOURTH -- With July 4
falling this year on a Tuesday, and many people taking Monday off
as well, much of the rush to leave town was underway on Friday.
Passengers board a seaplane ferrying travelers to East Hampton,
Long Island, from lower Manhattan, Friday. (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HAVERSTRAW, N.Y. -- June 30, 2000 -- NY-HUDSON-DEVELOP
-- An odd coalition of idealists and entrepreneurs, ranging from
Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist and Nobel Laureate Toni Morrison to
a powerful Westchester County developer, have a vision of turning
this town in the Hudson Valley into one that draws throngs of
well-heeled tourists in search of small-town charm. Morrison is
renovating this 19th-century home the intention of renting
apartments out to artists. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- NY-HARLEM-DEVELOP -- Magic
