York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN, JULY 2 --
DUMMY-FILMING -- The tale of Steven Schoichet, a maladroit
suburbanite whose life is transformed when he comes into possession
of a ventriloquist's prop, ``Dummy'' is the kind of movie Charlie
McCarthy might have starred in if Michael Ovitz had been his agent.
Nearly everyone else in the film is a client of Ovitz's firm,
Artists Management Group, a noncoincidence that helps explain how a
script by an obscure writer with a budget that wouldn't buy a
two-bedroom in Manhattan happened to get this far. Inside the
costume trailer on the set of ``Dummy,'' from left: Milla Jovovich,
Adrian Brody and Vera Farmiga. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN, JULY 2 --
DOCTORS-MARKETING -- Like hair colorists, fashion designers and
chefs, more and more doctors are seeking publicity to build their
businesses. Dr. David E. Bank, a dermatologist at the Center for
Dermatology, Cosmetic and Laser Surgery, in his office. (Edward
Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 30, 2000 -- PATRIOTISM-DEBATE-2 --
Norman Podhoretz, right, is the editor at large of Commentary
magazine, a senior fellow of the Hudson Institute and the author of
``My Love Affair With America,'' to be published on Tuesday. Victor
Navasky is the publisher and editorial director of The Nation, the
Delacorte professor of magazine journalism at Columbia University
and the author of ``Naming Names,'' a study of the Hollywood
blacklist. Together, they have spent more than three-quarters of a
century in journalism, and for many years they have disagreed,
often vehemently, about the issues that have shaped American life.
For this Fourth of July weekend, The New York Times asked them to
discuss patriotism. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- June 30, 2000 -- HARVARD-WEB-BOS -- While some
medical schools have become household names through their Web sites
and contracts with online companies, Harvard, ever the skeptical
traditionalist, has kept its distance from the wired world.
``There's a difference between practicing medicine over the
Internet and providing education,'' says Dr. Thomas Delbanco of
Beth Israel Deaconess Hospital, a Harvard University affiliate.
(Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WEST NEWTON, Mass. -- June 30, 2000 -- MOSCOW-DUCKS -- In
February, thieves sawed off and nabbed the 200-pound bronze statue
of the determined duck matriarch from Robert McCloskey's ``Make Way
for Ducklings.'' They also made off with two of her flock, Lack and
Mack. That left Novodevichy Park with only five of the nine
original ducks that Barbara Bush had given the Soviet Union in
1991, a year after Raisa Gorbachev had admired the duck sculpture
while visiting Boston's Public Garden. Sculptor Nancy Schon is
creating new mallards to replace those stolen from Moscow's
Novodevichy Park. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
