<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-WITNESS-SLAYING-NY     06-30 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-WITNESS-SLAYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN GETS LIFE WITHOUT PAROLE FOR ORDERING SLAYING OF 8-YEAR-OLD
WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ A man convicted of ordering the killings of
an 8-year-old murder witness and his mother was sentenced Friday to
life in prison without the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   A jury failed to agree last week on whether the man, Russell
Peeler Jr., deserved the death penalty, leaving the judge no choice
but to impose a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, G. Sarsfield Ford of State Superior Court, said
Friday that prosecutors had not met their burden of convincing the
jury that aggravating factors in the case warranted the death
penalty. On June 8, the jury convicted Peeler of murder, conspiracy
to commit murder and two counts of capital felony.
</P>
<P>
   The January 1999 killing of the witness, Leroy Brown Jr., and
his mother, Karen Clarke, outraged the public and prompted a swift
strengthening of Connecticut's witness protection laws. Prosecutors
said Peeler had directed his brother, Adrian, to carry out the
killings to prevent the boy from testifying against Peeler in
another murder case. Peeler, 28, was convicted in that case for the
fatal shooting of Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr., without
the boy's testimony. Prosecutors argued that the life sentence
imposed Friday added nothing to Peeler's punishment because he was
already serving life sentences for Snead's murder and conviction in
a drug case.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler is awaiting a separate trial on murder charges. In
court Friday, Russell Peeler Jr. maintained his innocence, The
Associated Press reported. ``I feel for the family, but we didn't
have anything to do with it,'' the AP quoted him as saying. ``I am
not an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the court, Clarke's brother, Oswald, told Peeler
that he would suffer in prison. ``You will wish you had received
the death penalty,'' Clarke wrote.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
