<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CYC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-30 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Armstrong remains inspiring Tourist
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The Tour de France is considered the single most grueling event
on the face of the earth, and there is no reason to attempt such a
feat of idiocy except that some people, which is to say people like
me, have a need to search the depths of their stamina for
self-definition. It's a contest in purposeless suffering.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lance Armstrong &LR;  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   But suffer he must, so Lance Armstrong charges off again today
on another bicycle trip around France, with detours into Germany
and Switzerland. ``La grande boucle,'' they call it. ``The Big
Loop.'' It's big all right _ 2,000-plus miles of hard riding before
the ceremonial finish down the Champs-Elysees on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Pedaling as fast as he can, for all he is worth, Armstrong will
speed across marshlands, streak through rolling hillsides and churn
up winding Alpine roads that are challenging to automobiles. Legs
churning, always churning, his body alternately baking in the
summer sun and being pelted with freezing rain, he will pass
through some of the world's most beautiful landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   But he will see almost nothing but the riders around him, 179
similarly driven men who want what he has and couldn't care less
about what he represents.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, Armstrong is a flesh-and-blood miracle, a cancer
survivor and the reigning champion of the Tour de France, cycling's
Super Bowl. His story is arguably the most amazing in the history
of sport, any sport, considering how he should have been dead three
years ago and how hellishly difficult this 23-day test of one's
muscular and mental limits can be.
</P>
<P>
   The storied event, first contested in 1903, was nearly destroyed
by an insidious drug scandal in the summer of 1998. But Armstrong,
clean on all counts, free of his disease and filled with hope
instead of dope, single-handedly saved it in the summer of 1999,
when the Tour de France became the Tour de Lance.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the 28-year-old Texan didn't need to re-prove he could
defeat the skeptics, cynics and France's spectacularly diverse
topography one more time. But ride Lance must, because this is who
he is, and this is what he does.
</P>
<P>
   If last year was difficult, an Armstrong encore will prove a far
greater challenge. The field is exponentially tougher, with two
champions who preceded him, Germany's Jan Ullrich and Italy's Marco
Pantini, returning from an injury and a suspension, respectively,
and France's former world No. 1, Laurent Jalabert, back after
boycotting the '99 race. Also, the mountain stages are
hyper-difficult this year, and Armstrong is a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   Post-cancer, he's no longer the one-day sprinting wonder of his
youth, and his new celebrity, albeit deserved, has extracted a toll
on his workout regimen, as did the minor concussion he suffered in
a tumble during a May training session. Nonetheless, he returned to
form in June, and the U.S. Postal Service team's manager, Johan
Bruyneel, says of him: ``Physically, he is as good as last year,
and mentally he is stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started (1999) with a big motivation but only a dream of
winning. Now Lance has shown it is possible, and that makes a
difference in how you approach the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, like cancer, can be a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous unlucky gents have ridden off the dangerous
high-country roads with fatal consequences, most recently an
Armstrong teammate, Fabio Casartelli, in 1995. In 1967, England's
Tom Simpson died of asphyxiation, literally pedaling himself to
death on the grueling climb up Mount Ventoux in Provence, a
debilitating route the Tour returns to this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the autopsy, Simpson's body was found to be full of
amphetamines. Illegal drug use had long been the Tour's nasty
little ``secret,'' but during the dark summer of '98, a 30-year
veteran of the Tour, Willy Voet, was arrested for trafficking in
performance-enhancing drugs just days before the race. His public
revelations rocked the sport. Ultimately, six teams dropped out,
and another was expelled.
</P>
<P>
   But when you see firsthand what the Tour entails, you find
yourself asking, ``How is it possible to compete without using
drugs?'' Not surprisingly, Armstrong's daily triumphs were met with
increasing cynicism. Some went so far as to suggest the aggressive
cancer treatments, which pumped plutonium into his system five
hours a day, had turned him into a superhuman mutant. The French
media took to calling him ``The Martian.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lance didn't test positive for anything _ he never has _ and
none of the other riders did, either. The Tour's honor would be
restored, and as a bonus, Armstrong gave a measure of hope to a lot
of ill people. It would seem his suffering was hardly purposeless.
It's good he's back. Good for him and for many others.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
