<HEADER>
A0306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HISTORY-GRUNDY0702-CO     06-30 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-GRUNDY0702-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Novelist helps Virginia hometown cling to its past
</P>
<P>
   By Don O'Briant
</P>
<P>
   GRUNDY, Va. _ Novelist Lee Smith has been proving Thomas Wolfe
wrong for years, going home again and again to the tiny coal mining
town where she was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved coming back,'' Smith says on a recent visit,
navigating her SUV through downtown Grundy. Passing a sign proudly
proclaiming her as a native daughter, she slows down and laughs.
``Isn't that something?'' she says in a Southern twang any country
music singer would die for. Then she turns off the main road and
pauses behind the building that once housed her father's Ben
Franklin five-and-dime store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent many wonderful hours there,'' says Smith, 56.
``Sometimes my father would bring me to his office and let me sleep
on a pallet while he worked on the books through the night.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in that office on the second floor that Smith would sit
and peer through a two-way mirror to observe the everyday
minidramas unfolding in the store below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I witnessed not only shoplifting, but fights and embraces as
well,'' she says. ``Thus I learned the position of omniscient
narrator, who sees and records everything yet is never visible. It
was the perfect early education for a fiction writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's beloved dime store is gone now, converted to a teen
center where coal miners' daughters and sons play video games and
laser tag, shoot pool and sip sodas.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, soon will be gone, along with the two movie theaters
where Roy Rogers and Trigger appeared live onstage and Lash LaRue
demonstrated his prowess with a bullwhip. Gone, too, will be the
string of stores, most empty now, that hug the banks of Slate
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   After a century of enduring devastating floods every 20 years or
so, downtown Grundy is being moved to higher ground. Everything
along the creek will be demolished for a U.S. Corps of Engineers
flood control project scheduled over the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything you've been connected to is literally going
underwater, it's galvanizing,'' says Smith, who now lives in
Hillsborough, N.C. ``That town where we grew up and went to school
and came to pay our taxes, where we got a marriage license or
bought our son a bike for Christmas will be gone forever. The only
thing left of it will be our memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. Smith and 30 high school students, along with
high school English teacher Debbie Raines and Buchanan County
librarian Pat Hatfield, have launched an oral history project to
record these memories in a book. The project is being funded by
grants from the Virginia Arts Commission and the Virginia
Department of the Humanities. Smith plans to publish the
coffee-table book this fall and to host an autograph party and
reunion of the students who worked on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose our memories so gradually we don't realize it. This
book will help us to remember,'' Smith says as she maneuvers the
SUV back onto the main drag, which is dotted with a Pizza Hut,
Wendy's and other fast food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there is my old stomping ground,'' she says, nodding
toward a row of neat white houses with perfectly maintained yards
and flower beds. ``I lived in this neighborhood and delivered
papers. This is the house where I grew up right here. It won't be
affected, but some will be raised on stilts and the rest will have
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, like the young people she is working with on the book,
admits she couldn't wait to leave Grundy. ``I felt closed in
because of all the mountains around us. I was also completely
surrounded by relatives on eerie side. I didn't like everyone
knowing what I was doing. Later, I realized what a wonderfully safe
and blessed childhood I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith would have written the book herself, but when she got the
idea two years ago, she was just starting a novel, ``The Last
Girls'' (due out next year), and working on a musical, ``Good Ol'
Girls'' (performed last year at the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill). There was no time to spend months in her hometown
conducting and transcribing interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I thought, maybe Debbie's students would love to do
this,'' says Smith, who had held several writing workshops with
Raines classes in the past. ``I like to work with high school
students, so I coerced her into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after agreeing to help with the project, Raines was
hesitant. ``Did Lee realize what she was asking or had she simply
lost touch with reality?'' Raines recalls. ``Was it really possible
that a detached Generation Y would suddenly think it `cool' to
listen to adults?''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was both surprising and rewarding, Raines
says. Equipped with tape recorders and a list of questions, the
students were sent to interview the old-timers about what Grundy
was like when they were teenagers and the town was booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were terrified at first,'' Smith says of the students.
``They practiced interviewing their families and went out in teams
of two. One could maintain eye contact and the other one could see
that everything was working. After a few disasters, they started
taking two tape recorders. They were sure that people would not
talk. And toward the end they were sure that people would never
shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, Raines watched in amazement as the kids
grew more confident and returned with fascinating tales about their
neighbors. ``Yes, Lee knew exactly what she was doing,'' Raines
says. ``It just took me a while to catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories they recorded were about the people of Grundy in
particular, but they are universal in nature. They are the stories
of thousands of other small towns where the young people leave in
droves every year in search of jobs or adventure. In Grundy, the
kids have few choices. Most of the coal that everyone said would
last a hundred years has already been mined. A few companies are
still operating, but the Saturdays when the downtown overflowed
with miners and their families are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South _ pockets of the South like this area _ is changing
enormously,'' says Smith, who has written about the Appalachian
people in ``Oral History,'' ``Black Mountain Breakdown,'' ``Fair
and Tender Ladies'' and other novels. ``First television and now
the Internet. Everything is becoming so much more standardized.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other small towns, Grundy has its share of fascinating
characters and stories. It was the site of the last hanging in
Virginia, an event that drew 3,000 spectators, some with picnic
luncheobacco, or the solid gold doorknobs on all the doors. But the
most amazing thing was when he said he was an alien from outer
space . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Others residents who were interviewed remembered the devastating
floods. In her interview with students Reece Hale and Jennifer
Lester, store owner Inez Ramey described how she used to hide her
money under the linoleum. When the last flood hit in 1977, she
barely had time to retrieve her money before the building was swept
away by floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   Smith recalls going down to the basement of her father's store
after one of the floods and finding a huge fish flopping on the
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Hahn, who interviewed his grandfather, learned some
fascinating details about life when coal was king. ``Every Sunday
he would go to the Morgan Theater, where every seat was filled,''
Hahn says. ``Mostly they climbed mountains and went to the movies
for entertainm
</P>
</TEXT>
