<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Easy fishes for fun with finny art fest
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 2.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Something fishy is going on in the Crescent City
this summer. The place is swimming with fish _ more than 200 big
ones, creatively painted by Louisiana artists.
</P>
<P>
   Festival of Fins, the biggest public art show ever in the Big
Easy, is expected to reel in more than 420,000 tourists just to see
the fish _ not counting a million or so locals. That translates
into a $42 million splash in the economy by the time the displays
come down at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Chicago's extremely popular Cows on Parade last
summer, the art project brings an added dimension of whimsy to a
river town already known for rolling with the good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about smiles and fun,'' says John Hopper, executive
director of the Young Leadership Council, which organized the fin
fest, ``and our other two goals of providing accessible public art
and increasing tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiberglass fish, designed by Mardi Gras float builders Kern
Studios, are 4 1/2 feet long and 5 feet tall. Sponsors, who paid
$3,000 for a fish, can keep them or donate them to a charity
auction in November.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming solo and in schools, the finny guys are scattered
throughout the central business district, the Garden District, the
French Quarter and the riverfront. They sport fanciful names such
as ``Sweet Gar Named Desire,'' ``Better Beaded Than Breaded,''
``Fin Fatale,'' ``Uncle Samon'' and ``Fin de Siecle.''
</P>
<P>
   Half the fun is seeing how many you can find.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss tourist Elisabeth Zahner was snapping pictures of the
cigar-chomping ``The Loan Shark'' in front of the Shell Oil
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love these fishes!'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Ebling and her son Ford, 10, visiting from Bowling
Green, Ky., were making a game of spotting fish around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really fun,'' said Ebling, who couldn't resist adding,
``Much better than cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
