<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' SCRIPT FOR SUCCESS IS PURE HOLLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dear Network Executive,
</P>
<P>
   Everybody from sneaker manufacturers to cereal packagers to the
local burger joint is about to capitalize on the nation's joyful
fascination with the Los Angeles Lakers, and I'm sure that you, a
creative artist in your own right, wish to share in the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore I submit for your consideration this script for a
prime-time movie about the behind-the-scenes cliffhanger drama of
the Lakers' championship season. I envision Gregory Peck as Phil
Jackson and Shaquille O'Neal as himself (unless he is busy on
``Kazaam 2,'' in which case let's see if Jim Carrey is free).
Working title: ``Lakermania: Not the Lakers, but the Average Viewer
Goes for This Kind of Shlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Office interior. Sunlit palm tree visible through window
indicates it's Los Angeles in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss (bouncing blonde on knee, addressing bearded man): My
team's decade-long championship drought upsets me and leaves this
city neither emotionally healed nor economically enriched. It can
win the title in 2000 only if you agree to be its coach. Well?
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson: No.
</P>
<P>
   Buss: Here's a blank check. Please reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Spine-tingling music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: OK, I'll do it.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness exterior. A canoe glides to a river shore, an
enormous man climbs out, and he is greeted by Jackson, whose beard
is longer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq: Thanks for inviting me to your Montana offseason retreat,
which symbolizes a quirky intellect unbound by the urban
materialism more common to NBA people.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Thank you. If we are to win the championship in the
upcoming season, you've got to buckle down.
</P>
<P>
   (Shaq's expression changes to indicate he isn't used to being
talked to like that, and he takes a step toward Jackson, towers
over the coach.)
</P>
<P>
   Foreboding music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq: OK, I'll do it.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball practice gym interior. Shaq addresses Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq: In learning how to win, I have looked in the mirror and
identified the major impediment to the Lakers' success.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Which is ...?
</P>
<P>
   Shaq (pointing to younger man holding comic book): Him.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant: Me? Is this another reference to the fact I refuse
to ever pass the ball?
</P>
<P>
   Shaq: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   (An alarmed Jackson steps between the two.)
</P>
<P>
   Troubling music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe: OK, I'll pass the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Dimly lit living-room interior. Kobe addresses younger woman
holding comic book.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe: I love you, and can't live without you, let alone average
22.5 points a game without you.
</P>
<P>
   Girlfriend: But I can't marry you, knowing that the NBA
lifestyle will forever tempt you with groupies and strip joints.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe: I shall prove my love for you by scoring 25 points, grab
seven rebounds and dish out seven assists in tomorrow's game, and
you then will be obligated to marry me.
</P>
<P>
   Romantic music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning newspaper stops spinning to reveal headline: ``Kobe
Scores 25, Gets 7 Boards, 7 Assists, 1 Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Locker-room interior.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq (to nameless teammates): We've won 16 games in a row as
midseason approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Nameless teammates (bantering happily): Everything's going very
well. ... Hard to imagine what could go wrong now. ... Wouldn't
anticipate anything like a losing streak at this point. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Allow me to warn you against the dangers of
complacency.
</P>
<P>
   Complacent music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Headline: ``Lakers Lose 6 Out of 9 Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Team-bus interior.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: You've all got to buckle down.
</P>
<P>
   John Salley (fastening seat belt): Like this?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Ha ha ha. Ah, the lighter side of the team experience.
Thanks, John, for cutting through the tension.
</P>
<P>
   Funny music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Headline: ``Lakers Win 19 in Row.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel-suite interior. All the Lakers are there. A woman who
bears a striking resemblance to a young Yoko Ono speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Fernandez Rice: My blind love for my husband prompts
me to demand that he take all the shots from now on.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry (panicky): Gee, what a distraction this has the
potential to become, another crisis on our way to the championship!
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Glen, do Christina's views reflect your own?
</P>
<P>
   Oh-boy-is-he-on-the-spot music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Glen: Christina who?
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Staples Center interior. Lakers huddle on sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: We're on the verge of the championship. Hard to believe
after all we've been through behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq: On the one hand, we could win and be heroes. On the other
hand, we could lose and be bums.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe: I'm nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous music.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Close-up of scoreboard reading Lakers 116, Pacers 111.
</P>
<P>
   Fans outside Staples Center dance merrily, toss flower petals
and shout ``Yippee!'' in celebration of Lakers' triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Postgame locker room is a shambles. Remnants of a party all
around. Lakers players clutch empty champagne bottles. Jackson sips
Japanese tea.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: Nice job. I love you guys.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Love you too, man.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson: To win again next season, you've all got to buckle
down.
</P>
<P>
   Players: We'll see _ in ``Lakermania 2''!
</P>
