<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG WEEKEND COMING FOR SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif _ Los Angeles Sparks coach Michael Cooper was
not overly pleased with his team's performance against the Indiana
Fever on Wednesday at Conseco Fieldhouse, but he had to admit that
a win is better than a loss, no matter how ugly.
</P>
<P>
   And there is something to be said about winning four games on
the road and extending a winning streak to seven games.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Los Angeles has managed to defeat the
WNBA's winningest team, the Houston Comets (13-2). It also managed
to scrape by with a 74-72 win over the Washington Mystics on Monday
and defeat New York in front of thousands of Liberty fans at
Madison Square Garden the day before.
</P>
<P>
   So yes, a win is a win. But even more noteworthy is that Los
Angeles (11-2) is finding a way to get those wins under various
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the Sparks hope to extend their seven-game streak
at home, as they take on the Cleveland Rockers at 5:30 tonight and
the Detroit Shock at 5 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets still sport the best record in the league and have a
one-game lead on the Sparks entering Friday's play, but Los Angeles
is building steam.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-game win streak is the franchise's best, one better
than the former record (set in 1999).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lisa Leslie was named player of the week for her
efforts against Houston, Miami and New York. In that three-game
stretch, she averaged 20 points, 10.7 rebounds and 3.33 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika, who led Los Angeles against Indiana with 19
points, has been a major scoring threat for the Sparks in the past
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   To extend their win streak, the Sparks will have to defeat
Cleveland, the third-place team in the Eastern Division, and
Detroit, the East's second-place team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers enter tonight's game with a loss after falling to
one of the new expansion teams, Portland Fire, 80-69 last Saturday.
Detroit has defeated its past two opponents, including an 82-78 win
over the Seattle Storm in which Wendy Palmer led her team with 32
points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
