<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ACLU-DEMCONV-LADN     06-30 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACLU-DEMCONV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU, OTHERS SUE LOS ANGELES OVER CONVENTION EXILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A coalition of civil liberties, labor and protest
groups sued the city of Los Angeles on Friday, claiming LAPD
security plans will keep demonstrators too far from Staples Center
and interfere with their free speech rights during the Democratic
National Convention next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection of a presidential candidate is a critical focal
point in our democratic process, a time when we should be
encouraging speech, not putting it in a straitjacket,'' said
American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California executive
director Ramona Ripston, whose lawyers brought the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU attorney Dan Tokaji said the security buffer and a
designated ``protest pit'' would so marginalize protesters as to
make it impossible for them to express their constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ACLU will ask a federal court judge to issue a
preliminary injunction as early as Wednesday to block
implementation of the security plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic constitutional rights cannot be put on ice simply
because a political convention is in town,'' Tokaji said.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council has ordered that Pershing Square downtown be
opened to the expected 50,000 protesters as a ``safe haven,'' but
is reconsidering in the face of a public outcry and warnings from
the Los Angeles Police Department and Secret Service that the area
cannot be secured.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Debra Gonzales said the city will work with
protest groups within security constraints, which include assuring
the safety of President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and
convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say there won't be room for compromise,'' Gonzales
said. ``But obviously the secure area was established in
consultation with the DNC and the federal agencies responsible for
security. They said the area had to be secure. We've tried to be
reasonable, but obviously there is disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   DNC committee spokesman Peter Ragone said organizers will work
with all parties, including the ACLU. The lawsuit was filed on
behalf of Service Employees International Union Local 660, the Los
Angeles Coalition to Stop the Execution of Mumia Abu-Jamal and the
D2K Convention Planning Coalition, an umbrella group for anarchists
who protested in Seattle and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC wants the issue, ``resolved in a way that protects the
freedom of expression of the demonstrators while also being mindful
of the security of delegates who are expressing their views,''
Ragone said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish said the ACLU action comes
more than a year after its attorneys declined to sit at the
planning table with police, citing a shortage of staff lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said he could not comment directly on the lawsuit, but
said police are committed to protecting protesters' rights, as well
as to preserving law and order.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets to a balance between First Amendment rights and
providing security at the events, it must come down to common
sense, to being reasonable,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   The security buffer around Staples Center stretches from Venice
Boulevard on the south to Olympic Boulevard on the north; and from
the 110 Freeway on the west to Flower Street on the east.
</P>
<P>
   The designated protest site is at Francisco Street and Olympic
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of protest groups contends that those distances
have been upheld by courts as excessive, and wants access to two
fenced parking areas just north of the center, and to the
sidewalks. It also wants to terminate a couple of marches at 11th
and Figueroa streets, inside the current security buffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think people should be allowed speech activities within the
secure, or no access, zones,'' Tokaji said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Volokh, a UCLA law professor who specializes in
free-speech issues, said there is a balance of interests
governments must consider in drafting security plans that place
limits on assembly and speech.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the restrictions are applied equally to all groups,
``the government has some, though not unlimited latitude to try to
prevent traffic tie-ups and violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government, however, cannot impose unreasonable or overbroad
restrictions, such as banning leafleting or protesting in a blanket
manner over an excessively large area.
</P>
<P>
   There is some leeway for unusual circumstances, too, which could
apply to the DNC, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a high-profile political event, which in the
past has led to violence, and there is a situation where there is a
serious security concern, then the City Council would have more
flexibility in imposing these restrictions,'' Volokh said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the city cannot be overbroad, or impose restrictions that
are disproportionate to the risk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, the deputy city attorney, said the city is sensitive
to and committed to protecting protesters' constitutional rights.
She said, however, there is case law allowing the city to place
reasonable limits on the time, place and manner in which people
gather in consideration of others' safety, property protection and
transportation flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said people are free to associate and to exercise
free speech as long as they don't violate the law,'' Gonzales said.
``We've always worked with protest groups, but we can't dismiss
security issues.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
