<SLUG> BC-DONUTS-THEATERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRISPY KREME BUILDING NICHE MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATSWORTH, Calif. _ Krispy Kreme is going silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Southern doughnut maker is pairing up with Pacific
Theatres in an unusual partnership that gives theatergoers the
chance to snack on powdered and jelly along with their popcorn and
jujubes.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme has opened its second location in the San Fernando
Valley and has plans for a third within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The new location, which opened Tuesday inside Pacific Theatres'
Winnetka Stadium 21, might be the only Krispy Kreme outlet in a
movie theater, said the doughnut retailer's Southern California
franchisee. Its upcoming outlet is planned for another unlikely -
but wise - location: at California State University, Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme already has similar outlets at Cal State Fullerton
and Dodger Stadium, but the theater pairing is a unique one, said
Richard Reinis, chairman of Great Circle Family Foods, the
exclusive Southern California franchisee for Krispy Kreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised to see it here. It's pretty unusual to see it
next to the movie theater,'' said Beverly Fleming of Chatsworth.
``I'll keep coming here because it's closer.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlets, with a more limited menu and a bit less decoration
than the regular stores, are a new concept that Reinis said he
hopes will catch on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect to have other points of sale, either under our
direct control or under other reputable strategic partners ...
throughout the Valley and the rest of the Los Angeles area,''
Reinis said.
</P>
<P>
   The doughnuts are not made on-site, but rather delivered from
nearby stores such as Krispy Kreme's Van Nuys location.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Frost, manager of the Winnetka Stadium 21 theaters, said
the outlet has been selling 400 to 500 dozen doughnuts since its
Tuesday opening. As the public's awareness of the outlet grows, he
expects to sell more.
</P>
<P>
   The doughnuts are a little more expensive than at the regular
stores: $4.50 for a half-dozen, or 75 cents each. The store is open
``from 10 a.m. until the last doughnut is gone,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   A theater manager by training, Frost said he had a lot to learn
managing the doughnut shop as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that's completely new to Pacific Theatres,''
he said. ``I was surprised when I found out how many people are
here from the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0461 </DOCNO>
