u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-1STLD     06-30 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TWEAKS GOP; `TRUTH SQUAD' TAKES AIM AT BUSH; KENNEDY
CHALLENGER OFF BALLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Adds a third item, about the challenger to Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON TWEAKS GOP
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in Philadelphia on Friday that
Republicans will talk a good game when they arrive for their
convention in late July but are not eager to to point out the
serious differences that divide the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have the awfullest time trying to figure out what the
differences are,'' Clinton told a group of union members. ``They're
going to love everybody and help everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a gathering of the American Federation of Federal,
State, County and Municipal Employees, Clinton recited a litany of
issues on which Democrats and Republicans diverge, from the
patients' bill of rights to the minimum wage to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also questioned Texas Gov. George W. Bush's commitment
to Hispanics, saying he had not urged Republican senators to
confirm Enrique Moreno, a Texan whom Clinton nominated as a federal
judge. ``If he had asked them to give him a hearing, they would
have done it,'' Clinton said of Bush. ``He didn't say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH SQUAD TAKES AIM AT BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The city where Gov. George W. Bush will be nominated for
president has been chosen by a ``Texas Truth Squad'' _ made up of
union members from Bush's home state _ for the beginning of a
national speaking tour intended to besmirch the governor's record.
</P>
<P>
   The squad, consisting of a teacher, a prison guard, a food
worker and a social worker, made its debut on Thursday at a union
luncheon in Philadelphia presided over by John J. Sweeney, the
president of the AFL-CIO, which has endorsed Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Squad members asserted in a series of short speeches that during
Bush's two terms as governor, Texas has consistently ranked near
the bottom in providing health insurance for children, retirement
pensions, environmental protection and pay for state workers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking special aim at Bush's claim to be an education reformer,
the group said he had diverted money from public schools and tried
to raid teacher retirement funds at a time when the state ranked
45th in the College Board test scores. The squad is scheduled to
make at least a dozen appearances around the United States before
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY CHALLENGER OFF BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson, the entrepreneur who had hoped to be the
Republican challenger to Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, did not have
enough valid signatures to put his name on the ballot, leaving
Massachusetts without a Republican contender for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The state ballot law commission ruled Friday that 153 of the
10,139 signatures that Robinson turned in on June 6 were invalid,
leaving him 14 short of the 10,000 signatures he needed to secure a
spot on the ballot. The commission, a panel of three Republicans,
one Democrat and one independent appointed by the governor, found
that 90 of those invalid signatures were forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has five days to appeal the ruling. Without a
Republican on the ballot, Kennedy will face only Carla Howell of
the Libertarian Party on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Daytona, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE No public events
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000630.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHER-NYT &LR;      06-30 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A SCHOOL IN HARLEM, A NIGHTMARE RESONATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's public school system needed qualified
teachers willing to work in its most downtrodden districts.
Jonathan Bassoff wanted just such a job.
</P>
<P>
   Though raised in Colorado and schooled in Iowa, Bassoff wanted
to teach in Harlem, as his mother had done before the family moved
west. Shortly after receiving his master's degree in education last
year at New York University, Bassoff took a job at Community School
200.
</P>
<P>
   But Bassoff, 26, is not teaching there anymore. This spring, two
sixth-grade boys were charged with raping one of Bassoff's
fourth-grade students in a school stairwell. Days later, Bassoff
was fired for what his termination letter, without elaboration,
called ``egregious'' conduct, and the school's principal and
assistant principal were demoted and reassigned elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That a 9-year-old girl could be raped by two 12-year-olds in a
school stairwell demonstrates on its face that Community School 200
is not like most American schools. But the school's daily disorder
and the troubled backgrounds of many of its students also highlight
the obstacles facing the best-intentioned recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rape, teachers say, C.S. 200 was a place where
students blithely walked out of classrooms and wandered the halls,
and where administrators did not respond to teachers' appeals to
stop them. Novice instructors were promised mentors to coach and
acclimate them to such challenges as maintaining control of a
classroom, but the teachers say they would seldom see the mentors.
</P>
<P>
   Bassoff and other teachers say the rape occurred when the
9-year-old girl and her classmates were supposed to be in the
lunchroom under the supervision of other school employees. Bassoff
had left them there before going to lunch himself. Even before
classes began, Bassoff said, he found little support from the
school's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   When Bassoff arrived at the school, the fourth grade already had
a reputation for unruliness. Vondora Jordan, whose daughter was one
of Bassoff's students and who regularly visited the school as
president of the Parents' Association, said Bassoff's class ``was
known as the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Mr. Bassoff was an excellent teacher,'' Jordan said.
``He did what he could in the classroom. But he didn't have an
aide, and it was hard to control those students.''
</P>
<P>
   Bassoff concedes that he is not a tough disciplinarian. But he
also said the school did little to help him. Though he was promised
a mentor, the mentor visited him only twice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   During a faculty meeting a few weeks before the alleged rape,
one first-year teacher, Archie Manning, asked what _ short of
physically restraining a student _ he could do when someone decided
to leave class. He said he knew the procedure was to call the
principal's office and report it, but that rarely seemed to result
in anything that discouraged repeat incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Grubbs, a third-grade teacher who was at the meeting,
said Diopoulos, the school's principal, and Agnes Howell, the
assistant principal, had two reactions. First, they said, students
should not leave class. And second, if the teacher was in control,
students would behave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, they gave no answer,'' Grubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Diopoulos, who was demoted to an assistant principal and has
been reassigned to Public School 92 in Harlem, declined to answer
questions about his tenure at C.S. 200. ``I tried the best I could
for those children,'' he said. ``Some people are irritated because
they weren't doing what they should be doing. I guess they're
getting their licks in.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell said that she did give extensive support to Bassoff and
other first-year teachers, helping them plan lessons and sometimes
sitting in on classes. Now working in the District 5 office, she
said she believes she was unjustly removed.
</P>
<P>
   The principal and assistant principal were reassigned, rather
than fired, in part because they had tenure in their former,
lower-ranking positions. But Bassoff, as an untenured teacher,
could be dismissed without lengthy hearings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
