<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0438 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICO-PRI-ADV-2TAKES     06-30 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-ADV-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN VOTERS CHOOSE BETWEEN SECURITY, CHANGE 
 
(ADV FOR SUNDAY JULY 2; INCL. TRIM MARKERS) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico chooses a new national government today in
a vote that could prove the fairest, and one of the most important,
in this nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In making their selection, the country's nearly 59 million
eligible voters will have to balance promises of stability against
vows of clean and credible government, schemes of economic progress
against calls for a new deal for the poor, visions of the future
against legacies of the past.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, they will have to decide whether the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, will stay or go after 71
years of ruling this rapidly developing but still impoverished
land.
</P>
<P>
   Most opinion polls showed PRI presidential candidate Francisco
Labastida locked in a tight race with Vicente Fox, the
blunt-talking candidate of the center-right National Action Party.
Although the polls differ as to who has the lead, most give each
man about 40 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a left-leaning former governor and son of a
PRI founder who has been running for president against the ruling
party for the past 12 years, has about 18 percent of the vote, the
polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Two splinter candidates share the remaining few points.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 71 years we have been putting up with tricks and lies,''
Fox said in an appeal for support on a nationally televised news
program Wednesday, the final day of campaigning. ``Now is the hour
to look out for our children. The future is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidates and independent election watchdog groups
have complained of uneven media coverage benefiting the PRI and of
a deluge of government spending, especially in rural areas, aimed
at assuring Labastida's election.
</P>
<P>
   However, reforms pushed through the Mexican Congress four years
ago make difficult, if not impossible, the sort of ballot-box
stuffing and outright vote theft by which critics say the PRI has
retained power in local, state and federal government. Most
Mexicans now understand that their vote will be free and secret,
according to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vote with confidence that your vote is secret and will be
respected,'' President Ernesto Zedillo, a member of the PRI, said
in television spots that saturated the airwaves last week.
</P>
<P>
   That alone marks today as a political watershed.
</P>
<P>
   The political organization that became the PRI was forged to end
the bloody squabbling among victorious generals of the Mexican
Revolution. The party has controlled Mexican national politics
since 1929, making it the world's longest-ruling regime.
</P>
<P>
   Many historians say the party was born with a sort of ``original
sin'' because its first presidential election, like several others
since, was marred by fraud. But through its decades of rule, the
party also has won widespread popular support by producing relative
peace, a long-lasting economic expansion and real improvements in
the lives of Mexico's poor majority. Until recently, those enabled
many Mexicans to overlook the cronyism and corruption that also
have marked the PRI's long reign, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Agustin Basave, a former assistant interior minister and
disenchanted PRI ideologue who now teaches political science at a
Mexico City university, explained:
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI in the last 70 years in power has weaved a profound
network of support that remains strong,'' Basave said. ``In spite
of all the scandals and corruption, the PRI has penetrated the
whole country at the grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is in every tiny, little town,'' he said. ``It is the
party that, with all its defects, has done something for people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got fertilizer. Your brother-in-law got a government job.
Someone else got some money to go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI also enshrined in Mexico's constitution strict six-year
term limits that prevented its presidents from becoming dictators
of the sort that have plagued much of Latin America throughout
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Latin America struggled with coups and civil wars,''
Basave said, ``the PRI was building roads and increasing
educational spending.''
</P>
<P>
   That largesse and social tranquility fostered a loyalty in many
Mexicans that prevails to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party has done a lot in 70 years,'' said Jose Villa Yanez,
72, a retired customs officials who attended a Labastida rally in
Mexico City the other day. ``It's given us work. It's educated us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we have, we have because of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   But such opinions are in the minority now, according to most
polls. Once assured of 80 percent of the vote or more in national
elections, the PRI now struggles to hold onto less than half of the
electorate. And the disenchantment has worsened as the economy and
political freedoms have improved.
</P>
<P>
   A June survey published by Banamex, Mexico's largest private
bank, found that while most Mexicans were generally unconcerned
about the economic outlook, some 71 percent expressed
dissatisfaction with the overall situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere have the PRI's roots dug deeper and lasted
longer than on the farm, home to the poorest and least-educated
quarter of Mexico's 100 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the countryside there is an alliance from years back with
the party and the governments of the party,'' Labastida said in an
interview as he campaigned in northern Sonora state last month.
``Because in Mexico, half the land was redistributed. Communal
farms and small private land holdings were created.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is counting on the rural vote to win today's election
for him. But some analysts, and some farmers, say that is not as
certain as even a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Economic policies that were begun under President Carlos Salinas
de Gortari and continued by the current administration have driven
many small farmers to the door of desperation. Now, although many
rural families still fervently support the PRI, others are no
longer convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the PRI? Where is our government?'' asked Pedro
Palacios, who grows a few acres of sugar cane on a communal farm in
Tierra Blanca, a mostly rural township of 100,000 people in
southern Veracruz state. ``They like to say the peasants are with
them, and then they only visit the towns and the cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just need us for the vote,'' Palacios said. ``They just
use us.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, and today's presidential elections, were the hot topics
one recent evening as Palacios and four friends sat drinking beer
and watching the sunlight fade in front of a small house in La
Atalaya, a forlorn cluster of tiny concrete homes set among emerald
fields five miles south of Tierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   All five men owe their livelihoods to the PRI. Their fathers
received their land from President Lazaro Cardenas, Cuauhtemoc's
father, during a wave of redistribution in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, they enjoyed subsidized government prices for their
sugar cane and other crops. In one election after another, they
dutifully voted for PRI candidates. Now, at least for some of the
men, that marriage is over.
</P>
<P>
   The year's harvest had just ended, the sugar delivered to the
nearby mill. But the mill managers claimed to have no cash, the
farmers said. Most of them were not paid.
</P>
<P>
   As the caps came off one beer after another, the talk became
angrier, more heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lost out here, deserted,'' said Mario Barada, who farms
about 20 acres of cane in a neighboring village. ``How are we going
to maintain our families?''
</P>
<P>
   Farm prices have fallen so low in recent years that it barely
pays to cut the cane, the men said. The mangoes aren't worth taking
from the trees. Milk is better left in the cow.
</P>
<P>
   As in villages and towns across Mexico, most families in Tierra
Blanca have someone _ a father, aunt, brother or cousin _ working
in the United States. A young man from the town was one of two
Mexicans who drowned in the Rio Grande at Brownsville a few weeks
ago as television cameras rolled and police on both sides of the
river did little to save them.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tierra Blanca used to be solid PRI country, like most of
Veracruz state. But three years ago, the National Action Party won
the city hall. The opposition now controls half of the state's
townships. And the party is expected to win again in October
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The once monolithic PRI began to lose its grip on Mexican
politics 17 years ago, following an economic collapse brought on by
the government's overspending and overborrowing at the height of
the 1970s oil boom. National Action and other opposition parties
won a string of city halls along the U.S. border and across
northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas further damaged the ruling party in 1987,
when he led a group of disgruntled left-leaning politicians out of
the PRI in protest of its increasingly free-market and pro-U.S.
tilt.
</P>
<P>
   Although the PRI has since held on to the presidency _ claiming
a fraud-fueled victory over Cardenas in 1988 and winning a
relatively clean vote in 1994 _ it lost control of the lower house
of Congress three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the loss of Congress ended the presidency's near
total hold on national power, opening the way for real democratic
change.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties now govern 11 of Mexico's 31 states and most
important urban centers, including Mexico City. More than half of
Mexicans today live under opposition local or state governments.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when Mexican voters would turn against the PRI, the
party often resorted to electoral fraud to hold on to power .
</P>
<P>
   The clearest example of such maneuvering, critics say, was the
1988 election in which the PRI's candidate, Harvard-educated
economist Salinas, was declared president after vote-counting
computers inexplicably collapsed for three days.
</P>
<P>
   While the PRI has rarely been as brutal as an outright
dictatorship, some party leaders haven't shied from violence when
patronage, persuasion or vote-pilfering failed them, human rights
advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican army's 1968 massacre of hundreds of unarmed student
protesters stands as one stark example. The troops fired on the
orders of President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz, historians say. And
recently, troops, police and paramilitary organizations controlled
by the PRI in the southern states of Chiapas and Guerrero have
slaughtered scores of unarmed peasants in separate incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas' Democratic Revolution Party claims that nearly 650 of
its militants have been killed for political reasons in the past 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the PRI has also proved responsive, albeit sometimes very
slowly, to Mexican society's evolving political demands and social
values.
</P>
<P>
   Critics  &UR; s &LR; ay its willingness to mutate underscores the party's
soulless nature, proving that power rather than principles drives
the party's politics. But the PRI's defenders say its flexibility
has been its forte, allowing the party to stay relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a rigid party,'' said Javier Trevino, a top Labastida
campaign adviser who earned a master's degree in political science
at Harvard. ``The PRI has a great capacity for change.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, changing the PRI has meant trying to
remake it into a modern democratic party. Labastida won his
candidacy in an open primary last November. It was the first time
the PRI's candidate had not been personally selected by Mexico's
outgoing president, who was also the de facto leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Under most of the PRI's long reign, Mexican presidents have
ruled as near-emperors. PRI-controlled Congresses, government
bureaucracies, unions and peasant organizations rarely opposed a
president's will. Each president put his own ideological stamp on
the party and, in turn, on all of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many voices within the PRI, but there is only one
leader,'' is how Trevino puts it. Other have a harsher take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is a party that still doesn't have its own
personality,'' said Basave, who was once in charge of the PRI's
leading policy think tank. ``It was always remade in the image of
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's system provided opportunities for politicians with a
range of ideologies, because each new Mexican president brought his
own supporters into the bureaucracy every six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have very important mobility within the PRI,'' Trevino
said. ``The PRI has the capability of adjusting and evolving. If
the PRI were one person, one strongman, it would have died a long
time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If a Labastida victory extends the PRI's hold on the presidency
for another six years, he will have to govern Mexico in a far
different fashion than his 13 PRI predecessors, many analysts
agree. With a stronger political opposition in place, making deals
_ rather than decreeing policies _ almost certainly will be the
order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as so complicated,'' Labastida said during the
interview in Sonora state last month. ``Why can't we think in
formulas like those in Europe?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we think of agreements between parties? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises us as new,'' he said of the give-and-take of
democracy. ``It's new for us, but it's not new for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
