<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MOYNIHAN-FARM-ART-NYT     06-30 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOYNIHAN-FARM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHANS SELLING FARM IN AN EFFORT TO SIMPLIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There it was, tucked quietly in between the ads for the $4.5
million Greek Revival and the $2.5 million Colonial, announcing the
end of a political era: ``DeMulder Realty Better Homes and Gardens
is pleased to offer for sale: Derrymore, beloved country estate of
Elizabeth and Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan.''
</P>
<P>
   The price, $1.1 million, included two houses, two barns,
``bucolic views,'' pastures, woods, fields, ponds, a stream and
``8,000 feet of road frontage!''
</P>
<P>
   A phone call to Derrymore in upstate New York took the cheery
real estate language of Friday's advertisement in The Wall Street
Journal to a more human dimension. ``It's over 500 acres,'' sighed
Elizabeth Moynihan, the retiring senator's wife, who was cleaning
out the woodshed that serves as her office while she spoke. ``It's
a lot of work to maintain it, for me. Pat doesn't drive, and
everyone I know over 70 is doing the same thing. He's giving up the
Senate, and I'm giving up the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are farms, and then there is the Moynihan farm _ the
four-term senator's spiritual home, the site of the 19th-century
schoolhouse where he has written his 18 books, a political base
that tied the man born in Hells Kitchen to the history and hills of
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the political symbolism of the farm that Hillary Rodham
Clinton asked the Moynihans last summer if she could use it to open
her ``listening tour'' of New York state. The unforgettable sight
of that day was of Moynihan slowly walking the woman who was
seeking to replace him down the verdant road from his schoolhouse,
as if giving away a bride, to the gantlet of press assembled in his
hayfield. There were at least 200 reporters, 30 television cameras
and eight satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up this morning and went out on the front step and
saw the satellite trucks at the top of the hill,'' Moynihan said at
the time, ``I felt like a character in `The Invasion of' _ you
know, one of those space alien movies.''
</P>
<P>
   But that most photographed moment of the Moynihans' lives at the
farm _ in the one-traffic-light hamlet called Pindars Corners,
about 70 miles west of Albany, near Oneonta _ was also an odd one.
The couple bought the farm in 1964 (Elizabeth Moynihan refused to
say for how much) and over the next 36 years rarely if ever used it
for political events. Occasionally reporters would interview the
senator there, but mostly it was the place where the senator and
his wife spent their summers and raised their three children, Tim,
44; Maura, 42; and John, 40.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are over. ``It's called simplifying your life,''
Elizabeth Moynihan said Friday. ``Life has different cycles.
Listen, I've painted these walls, I've painted this woodwork, I've
planted these gardens. Who's going to do it? Who's going to take
care of it?''
</P>
<P>
   The senator, a scholar-farmer who never actually gardened,
concurred. ``When I see her out there farming the gardens,'' he
said Friday from Washington, ``I think it's time to say, `Liz, why
don't we go over and look at the Botanical Garden in the Bronx?'''
</P>
<P>
   The prospective sale, he added, ``breaks your heart a little,
but it's time.'' The senator is 73 and still recovering from major
back surgery last year. His wife, who is 70, said Moynihan's
``insides are fine, the head is great, the infrastructure is a
little rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moynihans said the sale of the farm did not necessarily mean
that the senator, whose fourth term is up at the end of this year,
would no longer be a resident of New York. The plan, they said, was
to buy a smaller country house. ``I don't need over 500 acres,''
Elizabeth Moynihan said. ``I don't need two houses, I don't need
three ponds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moynihans, who also own a condominium on Pennsylvania Avenue
in Washington, bought the farm in February 1964, three months after
John F. Kennedy's assassination, while Moynihan was assistant
secretary of labor. ``We always wanted a farm,'' Moynihan said.
``We'd put the dog and the children and so forth in the station
wagon and zigzag across Pennsylvania and look around. When Kennedy
was assassinated, we were pretty depleted. And one day Liz got in
the car with our daughter and just made the trip, got to Oneonta,
and went to a real estate agent, and they said, yeah, they had a
farm for sale. She saw it first thing and said, `That's it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, then, never actually saw the farm before he bought it?
``Nor did I ever do any of the gardening,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Moynihan said that her real estate agent had received
a few interested calls, and that she was planning to show the farm
to one prospective buyer on Monday. Now that the couple had reached
the decision to sell _ only last week, she said _ she was eager to
have it over with. ``I'd just like to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was also looking forward to her life post-gardening.
``People have been visiting me for 38 years,'' she said. ``And now
I'm going to start visiting them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
