<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT TO ENROLL NEW YORK CITY POOR IN HEALTH PLANS IS EXTENDED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After citing ``serious concerns'' about flaws in an
initiative by New York City to move one million poor residents on
Medicaid into managed care health plans, State Comptroller Carl
McCall approved a two-year extension of the program Friday, along
with a list of recommendations on how to improve the effort.
</P>
<P>
   McCall spent several months reviewing the request by the state
Department of Health for the $40 million extension and expansion of
a collaborative state and city program, raising a series of
questions about Maximus, the Virginia-based contractor hired to
help enroll the poor in their new insurance plans. The original $24
million contract expired Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to have serious concerns regarding the performance
and integrity of Maximus and your agency's oversight and
monitoring,'' McCall wrote in a letter Friday to Antonia C.
Novello, the state commissioner of health. ``This is not simply an
issue of contract compliance. The health and well-being of Medicaid
recipients is dependent upon the quality of these outreach
services.''
</P>
<P>
   By intention, the switch to managed care should cut government
cost and enhance health care, because Medicaid recipients would
have their own family doctors instead of relying, as many now do,
on emergency rooms. But the process of linking people with
managed-care doctors has proved complicated in New York and other
states, in part because so many Medicaid recipients do not speak
English.
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory switch to managed care is happening in phases
across New York City, with the effort so far limited to Staten
Island, Lower Manhattan and southwest Brooklyn. Medicaid recipients
are given 60 days to pick a health plan and doctor, after which
both are assigned. Maximus sets up neighborhood seminars and
operates a telephone center to answer questions about the plans.
</P>
<P>
   McCall urged the state and Maximus to improve the training and
monitoring of the call center staff. The state-maintained list of
health plan doctors also needs to be revised, he said, to remove
errors that at times result in patients being assigned to doctors
who do not speak their language or are not part of the managed-care
network. And the state needs to simplify the process of granting
mandatory enrollment waivers to people who have special conditions
or cannot find a doctor who speaks their language, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Signor, a spokesman for the State Department of Health,
said the department was pleased that the comptroller had approved
the two-year extension and the expansion of Maximus' services into
Nassau and Suffolk counties. But he added that the criticisms
McCall raised had in large part already been remedied or were in
the process of being so.
</P>
<P>
   Rachael A. Rowland, a Maximus spokeswoman, said the company was
prepared for the audit McCall said he planned to determine whether
his recommendations were being followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
