u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-SENATE-     06-30 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NICE TAKES HOLIDAY AS CANDIDATES HEAT UP EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senate campaign in New York already has an overheated
quality, like a machine that is revving at full throttle minutes
after a jump-start. Four months before Election Day, Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Rep. Rick Lazio are hammering each other with a
ferocity that usually does not surface until October. Their
intensity raises an intriguing question. What are they saving to
use after Labor Day?
</P>
<P>
   The problems for each are fairly obvious. Lazio's late start
means he must fix an image of himself in the public mind before she
does. Clinton, whose well-known liabilities turn up in virtually
every poll, must use advertising and speeches to add a negative to
Lazio's portfolio for every negative on her side. That way, come
November, people may be debating issues more than personalities.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Lazio and his advisers have to work on adding
gravitas and on sanding down any sharp ideological edges. So far,
the Clinton campaign may be ahead in this definitional contest. It
has successfully nailed Lazio's political inconsistencies and
missed congressional votes. Such tactics can easily backfire,
however, if Clinton can be accused of ginning up the mighty White
House machine in the interest of sacrificing a lone congressman to
her ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, by ferreting out the details of Lazio's votes on
abortion, patients' rights, hate crimes and gun control, Clinton
does more than raise questions about whether he talks like a New
York moderate but votes like a Washington conservative. The first
lady also raises questions about her own lack of a voting record
and, indeed, her lack of substantial political experience
independent of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton has so far had her share of luck. Just as the
independent counsel spared her any charges on the travel office
firings at the White House, Lazio began facing his own troubles
with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The SEC has been
investigating whether Lazio violated insider trading laws three
years ago by investing in a company controlled by some of his
largest contributors. Lazio has denied any impropriety, and his
supporters have angrily labeled the investigation a Democratic
dirty trick. Detailed scrutiny of a candidate's past, however, is
part of the campaign experience for everyone, as Clinton knows only
too well.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign is also running fairly smoothly, while
Lazio's effort, after a strong launching, has been showing signs of
stress. He has made the kinds of missteps that afflicted Clinton a
year ago. One mistake was for Lazio to skip a gay pride parade in
New York City in favor of a farm stop upstate. He missed a chance
to pick up votes he might not get otherwise in order to talk to a
crowd that already favors him. Lazio's assertions that he will have
an open campaign have worn thin as journalists have been blocked or
limited in their queries. A missed vote on heating oil and a vote
against disclosure of the new secret 527 slush funds have become
easy fodder for Clinton, although Lazio was able to strike back on
the heating-oil vote by pointing out that one of her Congressional
supporters skipped it in order to raise money with her. Lazio aides
admit their man has looked a little off balance. They argue that he
entered the campaign as if shot from a cannon and will soon settle
down.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans complaining about the stream of money coming to
Clinton are taking steps to compete, as they illustrated this week
with a Manhattan fund-raiser that took in $1.7 million. Almost
weekly a new poll shows that despite the lopsided appearance of a
contest between a celebrity first lady and a barely recognized
congressman, this contest remains so tantalizingly close that it is
worth _ and will require _ major expenditure of money and energy by
both parties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
