A0452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-LEGISLATURE-N     06-30 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LEGISLATURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A VERY BUSY LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   Albany is quiet this week after a frenzy of legislative activity
unlike any seen for many years. With a budget approved early and a
vital election a few months away, the Legislature squeezed in the
time to approve almost 700 bills to go to Gov. George Pataki for
signing.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes a strong gun control package, an important
hate crimes bill, a bill requiring fire-safe cigarettes and another
providing for public access to critical data about doctors and
hospitals, to name only a few. Still, legislators failed to reform
the campaign finance and ballot systems, revamp the antiquated
Rockefeller drug laws and restructure the state courts.
</P>
<P>
   What unblocked the usual petty stalemates at the end of this
year's legislative marathon remains a political mystery. But there
was a little more fresh air and good political will wafting through
the closed rooms where state laws are manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   After a bitter power struggle between Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver and rival Assemblyman Michael Bragman, Silver began trying
to keep members more informed, even soliciting their input at
various stages in the deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, shuddering at the
possibility that Democrats could take over his chamber after
November's election, began leading his flock toward normally
dormant political territory, finally approving a decent hate crimes
bill being pushed for more than a decade by the Democrats. Pataki
angled for environmental improvements and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The hope, of course, is that this dusting of moderation and
compromise will not blow away after the election. There are still
important bills to be passed. At the top of that list would be
reform of a campaign finance system that has few real limits on
contributions to individual candidates and no limits for donations
to political parties. This is a need so basic it should serve as
the rallying cry for any challengers in this year's election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
